WEBVTT

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:32.280
Jonathan Harker's Journal. 3 May. Bistritz.

00:00:32.660 --> 00:00:43.500
Left Munich at 8.35 p.m. on 1 May, arriving at Vienna early next morning. Should have arrived at 6.46, but train was an hour late.

00:00:44.640 --> 00:00:51.240
Budapest seems a wonderful place from the glimpse which I got of it from the train, and the little I could walk through the streets.

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:58.640
I feared to go very far from the station, as we had arrived late, and would start as near the correct time as possible.

00:01:00.420 --> 00:01:04.680
The impression I had was that we were leaving the west, and entering the east.

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:13.680
The most western of splendid bridges over the Danube, which is here of noble width and depth, took us among the traditions of Turkish rule.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:23.420
We left in pretty good time, and came after nightfall to Claussenburg. Here I stopped for the night at the Hotel Royale.

00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:30.600
I had for dinner, or rather supper, a chicken done up some way with red pepper, which was very good but thirsty.

00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:34.920
Memorandum. Get recipe for Mina.

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:46.160
I asked the waiter, and he said it was called Paprika Händel, and that, as it was a national dish, I should be able to get it anywhere along the Carpathians.

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:53.460
I found my smattering of German very useful here. Indeed, I don't know how I should be able to get on without it.

00:01:54.420 --> 00:02:04.260
Having had some time at my disposal when in London, I had visited the British Museum, and made search among the books and maps in the library regarding Transylvania.

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:12.320
It had struck me that some foreknowledge of the country could hardly fail to have some importance in dealing with a nobleman of that country.

00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:30.740
I find that the district he named is in the extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states—Transylvania, Moldavia, and Bukovina, in the midst of the Carpathian mountains, one of the wildest and least known portions of Europe.

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:49.880
I was not able to light on any map or work giving the exact locality of the Castle Dracula, as there are no maps of this country as yet to compare with our own ordnance survey maps, but I found that Bistritz, the post-town named by Count Dracula, is a fairly well-known place.

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:57.720
I shall enter here some of my notes, as they may refresh my memory when I talk over my travels with Mina.

00:02:58.760 --> 00:03:16.140
In the population of Transylvania there are four distinct nationalities—Saxons in the south, and mixed with them the Wallachs, who are the descendants of the Dacians, Magyars in the west, and Zekalys in the east and north.

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:28.860
I am going among the latter, who claim to be descended from Attila and the Huns. This may be so, for when the Magyars conquered the country in the eleventh century they found the Huns settled in it.

00:03:30.380 --> 00:03:42.440
I read that every known superstition in the world is gathered into the horseshoe of the Carpathians, as if it were the centre of some sort of imaginative whirlpool. If so, my stay may be very interesting.

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:47.280
Memorandum. I must ask the Count all about them.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:04:06.780
I did not sleep well, though my bed was comfortable enough, for I had all sorts of queer dreams. There was a dog howling all night under my window, which may have had something to do with it, or it may have been the paprika, for I had to drink up all the water in my carafe, and was still thirsty.

00:04:08.420 --> 00:04:16.140
Towards morning I slept, and was wakened by the continuous knocking at my door, so I guess I must have been sleeping soundly then.

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:34.620
I had for breakfast more paprika, and a sort of porridge of maize flour, which they said was mamaliga, and eggplant stuffed with force-meat, a very excellent dish, which they call impletata. Memorandum. Get recipe for this also.

00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:48.860
I had to hurry breakfast, for the train started a little before eight, or rather it ought to have done so, for after rushing to the station at seven thirty I had to sit in the carriage for more than an hour before we began to move.

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:56.760
It seems to me that the further east you go the more unpunctual are the trains. What ought they to be in China?

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:10.640
All day long we seemed to dawdle through a country which was full of beauty of every kind. Sometimes we saw little towns or castles on the top of steep hills, such as we see in old missiles.

00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:24.780
Sometimes we ran by rivers and streams, which seemed from the wide stony margin on each side of them to be subject to great floods. It takes a lot of water, and running strong, to sweep the outside edge of a river clear.

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:43.880
At every station there were groups of people, sometimes crowds, and in all sorts of attire. Some of them were just like the peasants at home, or those I saw coming through France and Germany, with short jackets and round hats and home-made trousers, but others were very picturesque.

00:05:45.060 --> 00:06:04.020
The women looked pretty, except when you got near them, but they were very clumsy about the waist. They had all full white sleeves of some kind or other, and most of them had big belts, with a lot of strips of something fluttering from them, like the dresses in a ballet, but of course there were petticoats under them.

00:06:04.780 --> 00:06:22.280
The strangest figures we saw were the Slovaks, who were more barbarian than the rest, with their big cowboy hats, great baggy, dirty white trousers, white linen shirts, and enormous heavy leather belts, nearly a foot wide, all studded over with brass nails.

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:46.140
They wore high boots with their trousers tucked into them, and had long black hair and heavy black mustaches. They are very picturesque, but do not look prepossessing. On the stage they would be set down at once as some old oriental band of brigands. They are, however, I am told, very harmless, and rather wanting in natural self-assertion.

00:06:46.820 --> 00:07:03.920
It was on the dark side of twilight when we got to Bistritz, which is a very interesting old place. Being practically on the frontier, for the Borgo Pass leads from it into Bukovina, it has had a very stormy existence, and it certainly shows marks of it.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:24.040
Fifty years ago a series of great fires took place, which made terrible havoc on five separate occasions. At the very beginning of the seventeenth century it underwent a siege of three weeks, and lost thirteen thousand people, the casualties of war proper being assisted by famine and disease.

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:37.540
Count Dracula had directed me to go to the Golden Crone Hotel, which I found, to my great delight, to be thoroughly old-fashioned, for, of course, I wanted to see all I could of the ways of the country.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:54.520
I was evidently expected, for, when I got near the door, I faced a cheery-looking elderly woman in the usual peasant dress, white undergarment, with a long double apron, front and back, of coloured stuff, fitting almost too tight for modesty.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:58.520
When I came close, she bowed, and said—

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:00.980
The Hare Englishman?

00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:05.760
Yes, I said. Jonathan Harker.

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:13.180
She smiled, and gave some message to an elderly man in white shirt-sleeves, who had followed her to the door.

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:17.680
He went, but immediately returned with a letter.

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:37.480
My friend, welcome to the Carpathians. I am anxiously expecting you. Sleep well to-night. At three to-morrow the diligence will start for Bukovina. A place on it is kept for you. At the Borgo Pass my carriage will await you, and will bring you to me.

00:08:37.480 --> 00:08:47.440
I trust that your journey from London has been a happy one, and that you will enjoy your stay in my beautiful land. Your friend, Dracula.

00:08:49.300 --> 00:08:50.400
4th of May.

00:08:51.540 --> 00:09:14.420
I found that my landlord had got a letter from the Count, directing him to secure the best place on the coach for me, but on making inquiries as to details he seemed somewhat reticent, and pretended that he could not understand my German. This could not be true, because up to then he had understood it perfectly. At least he answered my questions exactly as if he did.

00:09:16.120 --> 00:09:40.060
He and his wife, the old lady who had received me, looked at each other in a frightened sort of way. He mumbled out that the money had been sent in a letter, and that was all he knew. When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed themselves, and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused to speak further.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:49.980
It was so near the time of starting that I had no time to ask anyone else, for it was all very mysterious, and not by any means comforting.

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:57.320
Just before I was leaving, an old lady came up to my room, and said in a hysterical way,

00:09:58.100 --> 00:10:01.420
Must you go? Oh, young Herr, must you go?

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:12.420
She was in such an excited state that she seemed to have lost her grip of what German she knew, and mixed it all up with some other language which I did not know at all.

00:10:13.120 --> 00:10:23.320
I was just able to follow her by asking many questions. When I told her that I must go at once, and that I was engaged on important business, she asked again,

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:25.660
Do you know what day it is?

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:31.520
I answered that it was the fourth of May. She shook her head as she said again,

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:36.400
Oh yes, I know that, I know that, but do you know what day it is?

00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:41.220
On my saying that I did not understand, she went on,

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:51.740
It is the eve of St. George's Day. Do you not know that tonight, when the clock strikes midnight, all the evil things in the world will have full sway?

00:10:52.460 --> 00:10:56.060
Do you know where you are going, and what you are going to?

00:10:57.420 --> 00:11:02.780
She was in such evident distress that I tried to comfort her, but without effect.

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:10.200
Finally she went down on her knees and implored me not to go, at least to wait a day or two before starting.

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:20.420
It was all very ridiculous, but I did not feel comfortable. However, there was business to be done, and I could allow nothing to interfere with it.

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:29.860
I tried to raise her up, and said, as gravely as I could, that I thanked her, but my duty was imperative, and that I must go.

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:37.220
She then rose, and dried her eyes, and taking a crucifix from her neck, offered it to me.

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:46.180
I did not know what to do, for, as an English churchman, I have been taught to regard such things as in some measure idolatrous,

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:52.240
and yet it seemed so ungracious to refuse an old lady meaning so well, and in such a state of mind.

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:59.300
She saw, I suppose, the doubt in my face, for she put the rosary round my neck, and said,

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:03.760
For your mother's sake, and went out of the room.

00:12:04.860 --> 00:12:13.200
I am writing up this part of the diary whilst I am waiting for the coach, which is, of course, late, and the crucifix is still round my neck.

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:26.000
Whether it is the old lady's fear, or the many ghostly traditions of this place, or the crucifix itself, I do not know, but I am not feeling nearly as easy in my mind as usual.

00:12:27.940 --> 00:12:32.820
If this book should ever reach Mina before I do, let it bring my good-bye.

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:35.280
Here comes the coach.

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:39.740
5th of May. The Castle.

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:55.780
The grey of the morning has passed, and the sun is high over the distant horizon, which seems jagged, whether with trees or hills I know not, for it is so far off that big things and little are mixed.

00:12:56.940 --> 00:13:03.240
I am not sleepy, and, as I am not to be called till I awake, naturally I write till sleep comes.

00:13:04.520 --> 00:13:14.840
There are many odd things to put down, and, lest who reads them may fancy that I dined too well before I left Bistritz, let me put down my dinner exactly.

00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:28.720
I dined on what they called robber steak, bits of bacon, onion, and beef, seasoned with red pepper and strung on sticks, and roasted over the fire in simple style of the London cat's meat.

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:41.740
The wine was golden mediash, which produces a queer sting on the tongue, which is, however, not disagreeable. I had only a couple of glasses of this, and nothing else.

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:48.560
When I got on the coach, the driver had not taken his seat, and I saw him talking to the landlady.

00:13:49.180 --> 00:14:00.900
They were evidently talking of me, for every now and then they looked at me, and some of the people who were sitting on the bench outside the door came and listened, and then looked at me, most of them pityingly.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:13.360
I could hear a lot of words often repeated, queer words, for there were many nationalities in the crowd, so I quietly got my polyglot dictionary from my bag and looked them out.

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:39.200
I must say they were not cheering to me, for amongst them were Ordog, Satan, Pokol, Hell, Stregoyka, Witch, Vrolok, and Vlkoslak, both mean the same thing, one being Slovak, and the other Serbian, for something that is either werewolf or vampire.

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:45.100
Memorandum. I must ask the Count about these superstitions.

00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:57.880
When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross, and pointed two fingers towards me.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:12.140
With some difficulty I got a fellow passenger to tell me what they meant. He would not answer at first, but on learning that I was English, he explained that it was a charm, or guard, against the evil eye.

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:25.880
This was not very pleasant for me, just starting for an unknown place to meet an unknown man, but every one seemed so kind-hearted, and so sorrowful, and so sympathetic, that I could not but be touched.

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:45.940
I shall never forget the last glimpse which I had of the inn yard, and its crowd of picturesque figures, all crossing themselves, as they stood round the wide archway, with its background of rich foliage of oleander and orange trees in green tubs, clustered in the centre of the yard.

00:15:47.600 --> 00:16:02.640
Then our driver, whose wide linen drawers covered the whole front of the box-seat, Gotze, they call them, cracked his big quip over his four small horses, which ran abreast, and we set off on our journey.

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:19.240
I soon lost sight and recollection of ghostly fears in the beauty of the scene as we drove along, although had I known the language, or rather languages, which my fellow passengers were speaking, I might not have been able to throw them off so easily.

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:32.720
Before us lay a green sloping land full of forests and woods, with here and there steep hills, crowned with clumps of trees or with farmhouses, the blank gable end to the road.

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:40.380
There was everywhere a bewildering mass of fruit blossom, apple, plum, pear, cherry.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:47.680
And as we drove by I could see the green grass under the trees, spangled with the fallen petals.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:17:05.480
In and out amongst these green hills of what they call here the middle land, ran the road, losing itself as it swept round the grassy curve, or was shut out by the straggling ends of pine woods, which here and there ran down the hillsides like tongues of flame.

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:12.620
The road was rugged, but still we seemed to fly over it with a feverish haste.

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:21.220
I could not understand then what the haste meant, but the driver was evidently bent on losing no time in reaching Borgo Prund.

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:29.220
I was told that this road is in summertime excellent, but that it had not yet been put in order after the winter snows.

00:17:29.840 --> 00:17:38.280
In this respect it is different from the general run of roads in the Carpathians, for it is an old tradition that they are not to be kept in too good order.

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:49.640
Of old the hospidars would not repair them, lest the Turk should think that they were preparing to bring in foreign troops, and so hasten the war, which was always really at loading point.

00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:59.400
Beyond the green swelling hills of the middle land rose mighty slopes of forest up to the lofty steeps of the Carpathians themselves.

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:08.880
Right and left of us they towered, with the afternoon sun falling full upon them, and bringing out all the glorious colours of this beautiful range.

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:25.520
Deep blue and purple in the shadows of the peaks, green and brown where grass and rock mingled, and an endless perspective of jagged rock and pointed crags, till these were themselves lost in the distance where the snowy peaks rose grandly.

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:35.560
Here and there seemed mighty rifts in the mountains through which, as the sun began to sink, we saw now and again the white gleam of falling water.

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:49.960
One of my companions touched my arm as we swept round the base of a hill, and opened up the lofty snow-covered peak of a mountain, which seemed, as we wound on our serpentine way, to be right before us.

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:57.800
Look!—Istenzek!—God's seat!—and he crossed himself reverently.

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:08.020
As we wound on our endless way, and the sun sank lower and lower behind us, the shadows of the evening began to creep round us.

00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:16.540
This was emphasised by the fact that the snowy mountaintop still held the sunset, and seemed to glow out with a delicate cool pink.

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:25.640
Here and there we passed Czechs and Slovaks, all in picturesque attire, but I noticed that Goethe was painfully prevalent.

00:19:27.160 --> 00:19:32.840
By the roadside were many crosses, and as we swept by my companions all crossed themselves.

00:19:33.740 --> 00:19:45.740
Here and there was a peasant man or a woman, kneeling before a shrine, who did not even turn round as we approached, but seemed, in the self-surrender of devotion, to have neither eyes nor ears for the outer world.

00:19:46.900 --> 00:20:00.160
There were many things new to me, for instance hay-ricks in the trees, and here and there very beautiful masses of weeping birch, their white stems shining like silver through the delicate green of the leaves.

00:20:01.940 --> 00:20:11.200
Now and again we passed a Leiterwagen, the ordinary peasant's cart, with its long snake-like vertebra, calculated to suit the inequalities of the road.

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:25.440
On this were sure to be seated quite a group of homecoming peasants, the Czechs with their white, and the Slovaks with their collared sheepskins, the latter carrying lance fashion their long staves, with axe at end.

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:48.660
As the evening fell it began to get very cold, and the growing twilight seemed to merge into one dark mistiness with gloom of the trees, oak, beech, and pine, though in the valleys which ran deep between the spurs of the hills, as we ascended through the pass, the dark firs stood out here and there against the background of late-lying snow.

00:20:50.360 --> 00:21:17.680
Sometimes, as the road was cut through the pine woods that seemed in the darkness to be closing down upon us, great masses of greyness which here and there bestrewed the trees, produced a peculiarly weird and solemn effect, which carried on the thoughts and grim fancies engendered earlier in the evening, when the falling sunset threw into strange relief the ghost-like clouds, which amongst the Carpathians seemed to wind ceaselessly through the valleys.

00:21:19.420 --> 00:21:31.620
Sometimes the hills were so steep that, despite our driver's haste, the horses could only go slowly. I wished to get down and walk up them as we do at home, but the driver would not hear of it.

00:21:31.620 --> 00:21:36.460
No, no, he said, you must not walk here, the dogs are too fierce.

00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:45.660
And then he added, with what he evidently meant for grim pleasantry, for he looked round to catch the approving smile of the rest.

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:50.260
And you may have enough of such matters before you go to sleep.

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:56.220
The only stop he would make was a moment's pause to light his lamps.

00:21:57.940 --> 00:22:06.560
When it grew dark there seemed to be some excitement amongst the passengers, and they kept speaking to him, one after the other, as though urging him to further speed.

00:22:07.500 --> 00:22:15.180
He lashed the horses unmercifully with his long whip, and with wild cries of encouragement urged them on to further exertions.

00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:22.500
Then, through the darkness, I could see a sort of patch of grey light ahead of us, as though there were a cleft in the hills.

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:32.760
The excitement of the passengers grew greater. The crazy coach rocked on its great leather springs, and swayed like a boat tossed on a stormy sea.

00:22:34.180 --> 00:22:45.180
I had to hold on. The road grew more level, and we appeared to fly along. Then the mountains seemed to come nearer to us on each side, and to frown down upon us.

00:22:45.940 --> 00:22:48.120
We were entering on the Borgo Pass.

00:22:49.160 --> 00:22:56.840
One by one several of the passengers offered me gifts, which they pressed upon me with an earnestness which would take no denial.

00:22:57.980 --> 00:23:05.020
These were certainly of an odd and varied kind, but each was given in simple good faith, with a kindly word and a blessing,

00:23:05.560 --> 00:23:15.700
and that same strange mixture of fear-meaning movements which I had seen outside the hole at Bistritz, the sign of the cross, and the guard against the evil eye.

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:26.200
Then, as we flew along, the driver leaned forward, and on each side the passengers, craning over the edge of the coach, peered eagerly into the darkness.

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:36.900
It was evident that something very exciting was either happening or expected, but though I asked each passenger, no one would give me the slightest explanation.

00:23:36.900 --> 00:23:45.700
This state of excitement kept on for some little time, and at last we saw before us the pass opening out on the eastern side.

00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:52.360
There were dark rolling clouds overhead, and in the air the heavy oppressive sense of thunder.

00:23:54.040 --> 00:24:01.000
It seemed as though the mountain range had separated two atmospheres, and that now we had got into the thunderous one.

00:24:02.220 --> 00:24:07.040
I was now myself looking out for the conveyance which was to take me to the Count.

00:24:07.660 --> 00:24:12.780
Each moment I expected to see the glare of lamps through the blackness, but all was dark.

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:20.900
The only light was the flickering rays of our own lamps, in which the steam from our hard-driven horses rose in a white cloud.

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:27.560
We could see now the sandy road lying white before us, but there was on it no sign of a vehicle.

00:24:28.340 --> 00:24:34.060
The passengers drew back with a sigh of gladness, which seemed to mock my own disappointment.

00:24:35.580 --> 00:24:43.220
I was already thinking what I had best to do, when the driver, looking at his watch, said to the others something which I could hardly hear.

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:48.720
It was spoken so quietly, and in so low a tone. I thought it was—

00:24:48.720 --> 00:24:50.540
An hour less than the time.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:55.140
Then, turning to me, he spoke in German worse than my own.

00:24:56.380 --> 00:25:00.740
There is no carriage here. The hare is not expected after all.

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:07.160
He will now come on to Bukovina, and return to-morrow, or the next day, better the next day.

00:25:08.820 --> 00:25:15.680
Whilst he was speaking, the horses began to neigh, and snort, and plunge wildly, so that the driver had to hold them up.

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:27.520
Then, amongst a chorus of screams from the peasants, and a universal crossing of themselves, a kalish, with four horses, drove up behind us, overtook us, and drew up beside the coach.

00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:35.580
I could see from the flash of our lamps, as the rays fell on them, that the horses were coal-black, and splendid animals.

00:25:36.240 --> 00:25:44.100
They were driven by a tall man, with a long brown beard, and a great black hat, which seemed to hide his face from us.

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:53.680
I could only see the gleam of a pair of very bright eyes, which seemed red in the lamplight, as he turned to us.

00:25:54.560 --> 00:25:55.820
He said to the driver,

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:59.320
You are early to-night, my friend.

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:02.260
The man stammered in reply,

00:26:02.780 --> 00:26:04.860
The English hare was in a hurry.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:07.920
To which the stranger replied,

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:19.060
That is why, I suppose, you wished him to go on to Bukovina. You cannot deceive me, my friend. I know too much, and my horses are swift.

00:26:19.060 --> 00:26:31.400
As he spoke, he smiled, and the lamplight fell on a hard-looking mouth, with very red lips, and sharp-looking teeth, as white as ivory.

00:26:32.720 --> 00:26:37.500
One of my companions whispered to another the line from Berger's Lenore,

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:40.340
Denn die Toten reiten schnell,

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:43.140
For the dead travel fast.

00:26:44.520 --> 00:26:48.980
The strange driver evidently heard the words, for he looked up with a gleaming smile.

00:26:49.860 --> 00:26:55.340
The passenger turned his face away, at the same time putting out his two fingers, and crossing himself.

00:26:57.100 --> 00:27:04.840
Give me the hare's luggage, said the driver, and with exceeding alacrity my bags were handed out, and put in the kalesh.

00:27:04.840 --> 00:27:16.880
Then I descended from the side of the coach, as the kalesh was close alongside, the driver helping me with a hand which caught my arm in a grip of steel. His strength must have been prodigious.

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:25.480
Without a word he shook the reins, the horses turned, and we swept into the darkness of the pass.

00:27:26.220 --> 00:27:35.420
As I looked back I saw the steam from the horses of the coach by the light of the lamps, and projected against it the figures of my late companions crossing themselves.

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:42.620
Then the driver cracked his whip, and called to his horses, and off they swept on their way to Bukovina.

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:49.120
As they sank into the darkness I felt a strange chill, and a lonely feeling came over me.

00:27:49.120 --> 00:27:55.800
But a cloak was thrown over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and the driver said in excellent German.

00:27:56.840 --> 00:28:02.380
The night is chill, mine hare, and my master the Count bade me take all care of you.

00:28:02.820 --> 00:28:10.200
There is a flask of slivovits, the plum brandy of the country, underneath the seat, if you should require it.

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:15.120
I did not take any, but it was a comfort to know it was there all the same.

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:20.020
I felt a little strangely, and not a little frightened.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:27.280
I think had there been any alternative I should have taken it, instead of prosecuting that unknown night journey.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:35.460
The carriage went at a hard pace straight along, then we made a complete turn, and went along another straight road.

00:28:36.480 --> 00:28:46.140
It seemed to me that we were simply going over and over the same ground again, and so I took note of some salient point, and found that this was so.

00:28:47.120 --> 00:29:00.100
I would have liked to have asked the driver what this all meant, but I really feared to do so, for I thought that, placed as I was, any protest would have had no effect in case there had been an intention to delay.

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:09.260
By and by, however, as I was curious to know how time was passing, I struck a match, and by its flame looked at my watch.

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:20.460
It was within a few minutes of midnight. This gave me a sort of shock, for I suppose the general superstition about midnight was increased by my recent experiences.

00:29:21.280 --> 00:29:24.680
I waited, with a sick feeling of suspense.

00:29:26.460 --> 00:29:35.320
Then a dog began to howl somewhere in a farmhouse far down the road, a long, agonised wailing, as if from fear.

00:29:36.220 --> 00:29:53.460
The sound was taken up by another dog, and then another and another, till, borne on the wind, which now sighed softly through the pass, a wild howling began, which seemed to come from all over the country, as far as the imagination could grasp it, through the gloom of the night.

00:29:54.680 --> 00:30:06.320
At the first howl the horses began to strain and rear, but the driver spoke to them soothingly, and they quieted down, but shivered and sweated, as though after a runaway from sudden fright.

00:30:07.320 --> 00:30:29.960
Then far off in the distance, from the mountains on each side of us, began a louder and a sharper howling, that of wolves, which affected both the horses and myself in the same way, for I was minded to jump from the calèche and run, whilst they reared again and plunged madly, so that the driver had to use all his great strength to keep them from bolting.

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:41.780
In a few minutes, however, my own ears got accustomed to the sound, and the horses so far became quiet that the driver was able to descend, and to stand before them.

00:30:43.320 --> 00:30:56.820
He petted and soothed them, and whispered something in their ears, as I have heard of horse tamers doing, and with extraordinary effect, for under his caresses they became quite manageable again, though they still trembled.

00:30:58.240 --> 00:31:11.840
The driver again took his seat, and, shaking his reins, started off at a great pace. This time, after going to the far side of the pass, he suddenly turned down a narrow roadway, which ran sharply to the right.

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:24.940
Soon we were hemmed in with trees, which in places arched right over the roadway till we passed, as through a tunnel. And again great frowning rocks guarded us boldly on either side.

00:31:26.480 --> 00:31:36.040
Though we were in shelter, we could hear the rising wind, for it moaned and whistled through the rocks, and the branches of the trees crashed together as we swept along.

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:47.020
It grew colder and colder still, and fine, powdery snow began to fall, so that soon we and all around us were covered with a white blanket.

00:31:47.980 --> 00:31:54.440
The keen wind still carried the howling of the dogs, though this grew fainter as we went on our way.

00:31:55.860 --> 00:32:02.160
The baying of the wolves sounded nearer and nearer, as though they were closing round on us from every side.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:16.560
I grew dreadfully afraid, and the horses shared my fear. The driver, however, was not in the least disturbed. He kept turning his head to left and right, but I could not see anything through the darkness.

00:32:18.600 --> 00:32:31.260
Suddenly, away on our left, I saw a faint flickering blue flame. The driver saw it at the same moment. He at once checked the horses, and, jumping to the ground, disappeared into the darkness.

00:32:32.120 --> 00:32:45.560
I did not know what to do, the less as the howling of the wolves grew closer, but, while I wondered, the driver suddenly reappeared again, and without a word took his seat, and we resumed our journey.

00:32:47.180 --> 00:32:57.380
I think I must have fallen asleep and kept dreaming of the incident, for it seemed to be repeated endlessly, and now, looking back, it is like a sort of awful nightmare.

00:32:58.440 --> 00:33:17.100
Once the flame appeared so near the road that even in the darkness around us I could watch the driver's motions, he went rapidly to where the blue flame arose. It must have been very faint, for it did not seem to illumine the place around it at all, and, gathering a few stones, formed them into some device.

00:33:19.220 --> 00:33:36.420
Once there appeared a strange optical effect. When he stood between me and the flame, he did not obstruct it, for I could see its ghostly flicker all the same. This startled me, but as the effect was only momentary, I took it that my eyes deceived me, straining through the darkness.

00:33:37.260 --> 00:33:47.940
Then for a time there were no blue flames, and we sped onwards through the gloom, with the howling of the wolves around us, as though they were following in a moving circle.

00:33:50.120 --> 00:34:06.500
At last there came a time when the driver went further afield than he had yet gone, and during his absence the horses began to tremble worse than ever, and to snort and scream with fright. I could not see any cause for it, for the howling of the wolves had ceased altogether.

00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:25.900
But just then the moon, sailing through the black clouds, appeared behind the jagged crest of a beetling pine-clad rock, and by its light I saw around us a ring of wolves, with white teeth and lolling red tongues, with long sinewy limbs and shaggy hair.

00:34:26.660 --> 00:34:44.860
They were a hundred times more terrible in the grim silence which held them than even when they howled. For myself I felt a sort of paralysis of fear. It is only when a man feels himself face to face with such horrors that he can understand their true import.

00:34:46.860 --> 00:35:07.620
All at once the wolves began to howl as though the moonlight had had some peculiar effect on them. The horses jumped about and reared, and looked helplessly round with eyes that rolled in a way painful to see. But the living ring of terror encompassed them on every side, and they had perforced to remain within it.

00:35:07.620 --> 00:35:24.140
I called to the coachman to come, for it seemed to me that our only chance was to try to break out through the ring, and to aid his approach I shouted and beat the side of the kalesh, hoping by the noise to scare the wolves from the side so as to give him a chance of reaching the trap.

00:35:25.580 --> 00:35:35.360
How he came there I know not, but I heard his voice raised in a tone of imperious command, and, looking towards the sound, saw him stand in the roadway.

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:52.020
As he swept his long arms, as though brushing aside some impalpable obstacle, the wolves fell back, and back further still. Just then a heavy cloud passed across the face of the moon, so that we were again in darkness.

00:35:53.360 --> 00:36:15.960
When I could see again, the driver was climbing into the kalesh, and the wolves disappeared. This was all so strange and uncanny that a dreadful fear came upon me, and I was afraid to speak or move. The time seemed interminable as we swept on our way, now in almost complete darkness, for the rolling clouds obscured the moon.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:41.380
We kept on ascending, with occasional periods of quick descent, but in the main always ascending. Suddenly I became conscious of the fact that the driver was in the act of pulling up the horses in the courtyard of a vast ruined castle, from whose tall black windows came no ray of light, and whose broken battlements showed a jagged line against the sky.

00:36:46.060 --> 00:36:52.280
Recorded on November 2nd, 2005, in Oceanside, California.

00:37:22.016 --> 00:37:24.096
Jonathan Harker's Journal Continued.

00:37:27.136 --> 00:37:32.116
Fifth of May. I must have been asleep, for certainly if I had been fully awake I must

00:37:32.116 --> 00:37:37.456
have noticed the approach of such a remarkable place. In the gloom the courtyard looked of

00:37:37.456 --> 00:37:42.576
considerable size, and as several dark ways led from it under great round arches,

00:37:43.156 --> 00:37:48.056
it perhaps seemed bigger than it really is. I have not yet been able to see it by daylight.

00:37:49.756 --> 00:37:54.736
When the collage stopped the driver jumped down and held out his hand to assist me to a light.

00:37:55.456 --> 00:38:01.056
Again I could not but notice his prodigious strength. His hand actually seemed like a steel

00:38:01.056 --> 00:38:06.616
vice that could have crushed mine if he had chosen. Then he took my traps and placed them

00:38:06.616 --> 00:38:12.416
on the ground beside me as I stood close to a great door, old and studded with large iron nails,

00:38:12.416 --> 00:38:18.336
and set in a projecting doorway of massive stone. I could see even in the dim light that

00:38:18.336 --> 00:38:23.576
the stone was massively carved, but that the carving had been much worn by time and weather.

00:38:25.416 --> 00:38:29.036
As I stood the driver jumped again into his seat and shook the reins.

00:38:29.696 --> 00:38:34.196
The horses started forward, and Trapindal disappeared down one of the dark openings.

00:38:36.496 --> 00:38:40.156
I stood in silence where I was, for I did not know what to do.

00:38:40.156 --> 00:38:45.936
Of bell or knocker there was no sign. Through these frowning walls and dark window openings

00:38:45.936 --> 00:38:50.896
it was not likely that my voice could penetrate. The time I waited seemed endless,

00:38:51.396 --> 00:38:58.096
and I felt doubts and fears crowding upon me. What sort of place had I come to, and among what kind

00:38:58.096 --> 00:39:05.116
of people? What sort of grim adventure was it on which I had embarked? Was this a customary

00:39:05.116 --> 00:39:10.076
incident in the life of a solicitor's clerk, sent out to explain the purchase of a London estate

00:39:10.076 --> 00:39:17.556
to a foreigner? Ha, solicitor's clerk! Mina would not like that. Solicitor! For just before leaving

00:39:17.556 --> 00:39:22.136
London I got word that my examination was successful, and I am now a full-blown solicitor.

00:39:23.076 --> 00:39:28.936
I began to rub my eyes and pinch myself to see if I were awake. It all seemed like a horrible

00:39:28.936 --> 00:39:34.616
nightmare to me, and I expected that I should suddenly awake and find myself at home, with the

00:39:34.616 --> 00:39:39.176
lawns struggling in through the windows, as I had now and again felt in the morning after a day of

00:39:39.176 --> 00:39:46.036
overwork. But my flesh answered the pinching test, and my eyes were not to be deceived. I was indeed

00:39:46.036 --> 00:39:51.496
awake and among the Carpathians. All I could do now was to be patient and to wait the coming of

00:39:51.496 --> 00:39:58.436
morning. Just as I had come to this conclusion I heard a heavy step approaching behind the great

00:39:58.436 --> 00:40:04.316
door, and I saw through the chinks the gleam of a coming light. Then there was the sound of rattling

00:40:04.316 --> 00:40:10.336
chains and the clanking of massive bolts drawn back. A key was turned with the loud grating noise

00:40:10.336 --> 00:40:18.036
of long disuse, and the great door swung back. Within stood a tall old man, clean shaven,

00:40:18.116 --> 00:40:23.456
save for a long white moustache, and clad in black from head to foot without a single speck

00:40:23.456 --> 00:40:29.576
of colour about him anywhere. He held in his hand an antique silver lamp, in which the flame

00:40:29.576 --> 00:40:35.076
burned without a chimney or globe of any kind, throwing long quivering shadows as it flickered

00:40:35.076 --> 00:40:40.896
in the draught of the open door. The old man motioned me in with his right hand with a courtly

00:40:40.896 --> 00:40:45.196
gesture, saying in excellent English, but with a strange intonation,

00:40:46.036 --> 00:40:53.876
Welcome to my house. Enter freely, and of your own free will. He made no motion of stepping to

00:40:53.876 --> 00:40:59.076
meet me, but stood like a statue, as though his gesture of welcome had fixed him into stone.

00:40:59.576 --> 00:41:04.676
The instant, however, that I had stepped over the threshold, he moved impulsively forward,

00:41:05.276 --> 00:41:10.416
and holding out his hand, grasped mine with a strength which made me wince, an effect which

00:41:10.416 --> 00:41:15.816
was not lessened by the fact that it seemed cold as ice, more like the hand of a dead than a living

00:41:15.816 --> 00:41:27.616
man. Again he said, Welcome to my house. Enter freely, go safely, and leave something of the

00:41:27.616 --> 00:41:33.556
much akin to what I had noticed in the driver, whose face I had not seen, that for a moment I

00:41:33.556 --> 00:41:39.196
doubted if it were not the same person to whom I was speaking. So to make sure, I said interrogatively,

00:41:39.776 --> 00:41:46.856
Count Dracula? He bowed in a courtly way as he replied, I am Dracula, and I bid you welcome,

00:41:46.916 --> 00:41:52.896
Mr. Harker, to my house. Come in, the night air is chill, and you must need to eat and rest.

00:41:53.536 --> 00:41:58.336
As he was speaking, he put the lamp on a bracket on the wall, and stepping out, took my luggage.

00:41:58.976 --> 00:42:03.236
He had carried it in before I could forestall him. I protested, but he insisted,

00:42:04.036 --> 00:42:10.216
Nay, sir, you are my guest. It is late, and my people are not available. Let me see to your

00:42:10.216 --> 00:42:17.076
comfort myself. He insisted on carrying my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding

00:42:17.076 --> 00:42:21.796
stair, and along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang heavily.

00:42:22.356 --> 00:42:27.576
At the end of this, he threw open a heavy door, and I rejoiced to see within a well-lit room in

00:42:27.576 --> 00:42:32.416
which a table was spread for supper, and on whose mighty hearth a great fire of logs,

00:42:32.496 --> 00:42:38.936
freshly replenished, flamed and flared. The Count halted, putting down my bags, closed the door,

00:42:39.336 --> 00:42:44.296
and crossing the room, opened another door, which led into a small octagonal room, lit by a single

00:42:44.296 --> 00:42:50.316
lamp, and seemingly without a window of any sort. Passing through this, he opened another door,

00:42:50.316 --> 00:42:56.376
and motioned me to enter. It was a welcome sight, for here was a great bedroom well lighted and

00:42:56.376 --> 00:43:01.196
warmed by another log fire also added to it lately, for the top logs were fresh,

00:43:01.456 --> 00:43:06.776
which sent a hollow roar up the wide chimney. The Count himself left my luggage inside,

00:43:06.896 --> 00:43:12.096
and withdrew, saying, before he closed the door, You will need, after your journey,

00:43:12.256 --> 00:43:17.356
to refresh yourself by making your toilette. I trust you will find all you wish.

00:43:17.916 --> 00:43:22.536
When you are ready, come into the other room, where you will find your supper prepared.

00:43:24.096 --> 00:43:28.636
The light and warmth of the Count's courteous welcome seemed to have dissipated all my doubts

00:43:28.636 --> 00:43:33.616
and fears. Having then reached my normal state, I discovered that I was half famished with hunger,

00:43:33.996 --> 00:43:39.296
so, making a hasty toilette, I went into the other room. I found supper already laid out.

00:43:39.676 --> 00:43:44.016
My host, who stood on one side of the great fireplace, leaning against the stonework,

00:43:44.016 --> 00:43:47.096
made a graceful wave of his hand toward the table, and said,

00:43:47.756 --> 00:43:51.556
I pray you, be seated, and sup how you please. You will I trust.

00:43:51.776 --> 00:43:56.316
Excuse me that I do not join you, but I have dined already, and I do not sup.

00:43:57.916 --> 00:44:02.196
I handed to him the sealed letter which Mr. Hawkins had entrusted to me.

00:44:02.416 --> 00:44:07.356
He opened it, and read it gravely. Then, with a charming smile, he handed it to me to read.

00:44:08.076 --> 00:44:10.396
One passage, if it at least, gave me a thrill of pleasure.

00:44:10.856 --> 00:44:15.396
I must regret that an attack of gout from which malady I am a constant sufferer

00:44:15.396 --> 00:44:18.836
forbids absolutely any travelling on my part for some time to come.

00:44:19.276 --> 00:44:22.276
But I am happy to say I can send a sufficient substitute,

00:44:22.736 --> 00:44:27.776
one in whom I have every possible confidence. He is a young man, full of energy and talent

00:44:27.776 --> 00:44:32.776
in his own way, and of a very faithful disposition. He is discreet and silent,

00:44:33.016 --> 00:44:37.496
and has grown into manhood in my service. He shall be ready to attend on you when you

00:44:37.496 --> 00:44:40.796
will, during his stay, and shall take your instructions in all matters.

00:44:42.216 --> 00:44:45.536
The Count himself came forward, and took off the cover of a dish,

00:44:45.816 --> 00:44:50.116
and I felt who at once on an excellent roast chicken. This, with some cheese,

00:44:50.156 --> 00:44:54.356
and a salad, and a bottle of old tokay, of which I had two glasses, was my supper.

00:44:55.336 --> 00:44:58.936
During the time I was eating it, the Count asked me many questions as to my journey,

00:44:59.336 --> 00:45:04.636
and I told him by degrees all I had experienced. By this time I had finished my supper,

00:45:04.636 --> 00:45:09.636
and by my host's desire had drawn up a chair by the fire, and begun to smoke a cigar which he

00:45:09.636 --> 00:45:15.696
offered me, at the same time excusing himself that he did not smoke. I had now an opportunity

00:45:15.696 --> 00:45:21.216
of observing him, and found him of a very marked physiognomy. His face was a strong,

00:45:21.556 --> 00:45:27.576
a very strong aquiline, with high bridge of the thin nose, and peculiarly arched nostrils,

00:45:27.956 --> 00:45:33.136
and with lofty domed forehead, and hair growing scantily round the temples, but profusely elsewhere.

00:45:34.036 --> 00:45:39.196
His eyebrows were very massive, almost meeting over the nose, and with bushy hair that seemed

00:45:39.196 --> 00:45:44.656
to curl in its own profusion. The mouth, so far as I could see it under the heavy mustache,

00:45:45.056 --> 00:45:51.316
was fixed and rather cruel looking, with peculiarly sharp white teeth. These protruded over the lips,

00:45:51.616 --> 00:45:57.056
whose remarkable ruddiness showed astonishing vitality in a man of his years. For the rest,

00:45:57.256 --> 00:46:03.016
his ears were pale, and at the tops extremely pointed. The chin was broad and strong, and the

00:46:03.016 --> 00:46:09.736
cheeks firm though thin. The general effect was one of extraordinary pallor. Hitherto I had noticed

00:46:09.736 --> 00:46:14.456
the backs of his hands as they lay on his knees in the firelight, and they had seemed rather white

00:46:14.456 --> 00:46:20.096
and fine. But seeing them now close to me I could not but notice that they were rather coarse, broad

00:46:20.096 --> 00:46:26.776
with squat fingers. Strange to say they were hairs in the centre of the palm. The nails were long and

00:46:26.776 --> 00:46:32.516
fine, and cut to a sharp point. As the count leaned over me, and his hands touched me, I could

00:46:32.516 --> 00:46:39.196
repress a shudder. It may have been that his breath was rank, but a horrible feeling of nausea came

00:46:39.196 --> 00:46:46.036
over me, which, do what I would, I could not conceal. The count evidently noticing it drew back,

00:46:46.516 --> 00:46:51.316
and with a grim sort of smile, which showed more than he had yet done of his protuberant teeth,

00:46:51.876 --> 00:46:57.176
sat himself down again on his own side of the fireplace. We were both silent for a while,

00:46:57.436 --> 00:47:01.296
and as I looked towards the window I saw the first dim streak of the coming dawn.

00:47:01.836 --> 00:47:08.376
There seemed a strange stillness over everything, but as I listened I heard as if from down below

00:47:08.376 --> 00:47:13.476
in the valley the howling of many wolves. The count's eyes gleamed, and he said,

00:47:13.996 --> 00:47:18.416
Listen to them, the children of the night, what music they make.

00:47:19.976 --> 00:47:23.536
Seeing, I suppose, some expression in my face, strange to him, he added,

00:47:24.276 --> 00:47:28.236
Ah sir, you dwellers in the city cannot enter into the feelings of the hunter.

00:47:29.676 --> 00:47:35.436
Then he rose and said, But you must be tired. Your bedroom is all ready,

00:47:35.736 --> 00:47:40.156
and tomorrow you shall sleep as late as you will. I have to be away till the afternoon,

00:47:40.556 --> 00:47:46.136
so sleep well and dream well. With a courteous bow he opened for me himself the door of the

00:47:46.136 --> 00:47:54.696
octagonal room, and I entered my bedroom. I am all in a sea of wonders. I doubt. I fear.

00:47:55.496 --> 00:47:59.456
I think strange things which I dare not confess to my own soul.

00:48:00.636 --> 00:48:03.576
God keep me, if only for the sake of those dear to me.

00:48:07.736 --> 00:48:12.976
7th of May. It is again early morning, but I have rested and enjoyed the last twenty-four hours.

00:48:13.676 --> 00:48:18.176
I slept till late in the day, and awoke of my own accord. When I had dressed myself,

00:48:18.236 --> 00:48:21.776
I went into the room where we had supped, and found a cold breakfast laid out,

00:48:21.776 --> 00:48:26.576
with coffee kept hot by the pot being placed on the hearth. There was a card on the table,

00:48:26.696 --> 00:48:31.276
on which was written, I have to be absent for a while. Do not wait for me. D.

00:48:32.596 --> 00:48:36.796
I set to and enjoyed a hearty meal. When I had done I looked for a bell,

00:48:36.856 --> 00:48:40.636
so that I might let the servants know I had finished, but I could not find one.

00:48:41.516 --> 00:48:46.016
There are certainly odd deficiencies in the house, considering the extraordinary evidences

00:48:46.016 --> 00:48:51.056
of wealth which are round me. The table services of gold and so beautifully wrought that it must be

00:48:51.056 --> 00:48:56.816
of immense value. The curtains and upholstery of the chairs and sofas and the hangings of my bed

00:48:56.816 --> 00:49:01.616
are of the costliest and most beautiful fabrics, and must have been of fabulous value when they

00:49:01.616 --> 00:49:06.596
were made, for they are centuries old, though in excellent order. I saw something like them

00:49:06.596 --> 00:49:12.296
in Hampton Court, but they were worn and frayed in Malthedon. But still in none of the rooms is

00:49:12.296 --> 00:49:17.176
there a mirror. There is not even a toilette glass on my table, and I had to get the little

00:49:17.176 --> 00:49:22.516
glass from my bag before I could either shave or brush my hair. I have not yet seen a servant

00:49:22.516 --> 00:49:26.436
anywhere, or heard a sound near the castle, except the howling of wolves.

00:49:28.096 --> 00:49:32.676
Some time after I had finished my meal, I did not know whether to call it breakfast or dinner,

00:49:32.856 --> 00:49:37.736
for it was between five and six o'clock when I had it. I looked about for something to read,

00:49:37.816 --> 00:49:41.216
for I did not like to go about the castle until I had asked the Count's permission.

00:49:41.216 --> 00:49:47.276
There was absolutely nothing in the room, book, newspaper, or even writing materials,

00:49:47.276 --> 00:49:50.496
so I opened another door in the room and found a sort of library.

00:49:51.216 --> 00:49:57.076
The door opposite mine I tried, but found locked. In the library, I found to my great delight a

00:49:57.076 --> 00:50:02.316
vast number of English books, whole shelves full of them, and bound volumes of magazines and

00:50:02.316 --> 00:50:07.136
newspapers. A table in the centre was littered with English magazines and newspapers, though

00:50:07.136 --> 00:50:12.136
none of them were of very recent date. The books were of the most varied kind. History,

00:50:12.296 --> 00:50:18.556
geography, politics, political economy, botany, geology, law, all relating to England and the

00:50:18.556 --> 00:50:23.076
English life and customs and manners. There were even books of reference, such as the London

00:50:23.076 --> 00:50:28.596
Directory, the Red and Blue Books, Switikas Almanac, the Army and Navy Lists, and it somehow

00:50:28.596 --> 00:50:34.396
gladdened by heart to see it, the Law List. Whilst I was looking at the books, the door opened and

00:50:34.396 --> 00:50:39.156
Count entered. He saluted me in a hearty way and hoped that I had had a good night's rest.

00:50:39.756 --> 00:50:41.056
Then he went on.

00:51:04.396 --> 00:51:09.536
the crowded streets of your mighty London, to be in the midst of the whirl and rush of humanity,

00:51:10.136 --> 00:51:17.936
to share its life, its change, its death, and all that makes it what it is. But alas, as yet I only

00:51:17.936 --> 00:51:22.216
know your tongue through books. To you, my friend, I look that I know it to speak.

00:51:23.196 --> 00:51:27.996
But Count, I said, you know and speak English thoroughly. He bowed gravely.

00:51:28.456 --> 00:51:32.716
I thank you, my friend, for your all too flattering estimate, but yet I fear I am but

00:51:32.716 --> 00:51:37.476
a little way on the road I would travel. True, I know the grammar and the words,

00:51:37.676 --> 00:51:42.256
but yet I know not how to speak them. Indeed, I said, you speak excellently.

00:51:42.876 --> 00:51:47.896
Not so, he answered. Well, I know that. Did I move and speak in your London?

00:51:48.376 --> 00:51:52.396
None there are who would not know me for a stranger. That is not enough for me.

00:51:52.656 --> 00:52:02.696
Here I am noble. I am a boyar. The common people know me, and I am master. But a stranger in a

00:52:02.696 --> 00:52:08.996
not, and to know not is to care not for. I am content if I am like the rest, so that no man

00:52:08.996 --> 00:52:15.736
stops if he sees me, or pauses in his speaking if he hears my words. Ha, ha, stranger. I have been

00:52:15.736 --> 00:52:21.496
so long, master, that I would be master still, or at least that none other should be master of me.

00:52:21.976 --> 00:52:26.976
You come to me not alone as agent of my friend Peter Hawkins of Exeter, to tell me all about

00:52:26.976 --> 00:52:32.536
my new estate in London. You, shall I trust, rest here with me a while, so that by our talking I may

00:52:32.536 --> 00:52:37.436
learn the English in donation, and I would that you tell me when I make error even of the smallest

00:52:37.436 --> 00:52:43.316
in my speaking. I am sorry that I had to be away so long to-day, but you will, I know, forgive one

00:52:43.316 --> 00:52:49.716
who has so many important affairs in hand. Of course I said all I could about being willing,

00:52:50.176 --> 00:52:56.296
and asked if I might come into that room when I chose. He answered, yes, certainly, and added,

00:52:56.776 --> 00:53:01.096
you may go anywhere you wish in the castle, except where the doors are locked where, of course,

00:53:01.096 --> 00:53:06.216
you will not wish to go. There is reason that all things are as they are, and did you see with my

00:53:06.216 --> 00:53:12.536
eyes, and know with my knowledge, you would perhaps better understand. I said I was sure of this,

00:53:12.576 --> 00:53:18.696
and then he went on. We are in Transylvania, and Transylvania is not England. Our ways are

00:53:18.696 --> 00:53:24.176
not your ways, and there shall be to you many strange things. Nay, from what you have told me

00:53:24.176 --> 00:53:30.756
of your experiences already you know something of what strange things there may be. This led

00:53:30.756 --> 00:53:35.396
to much conversation, and as it was evident that he wanted to talk, if only for talking's sake,

00:53:35.776 --> 00:53:39.876
I asked him many questions regarding things that had already happened to me or come within my notice.

00:53:40.596 --> 00:53:44.876
Sometimes he sheered off the subject, or turned the conversation by pretending not to understand,

00:53:45.376 --> 00:53:50.496
but generally he answered all I asked most frankly. Then, as time went on, and I had got somewhat

00:53:50.496 --> 00:53:55.736
bolder, I asked him of some of the strange things of the preceding night, as, for instance, why the

00:53:56.056 --> 00:54:01.696
places where he had seen the blue flames. He then explained to me that it was commonly believed

00:54:01.696 --> 00:54:07.656
that on a certain night of the year, last night in fact, when all evil spirits are supposed to have

00:54:07.656 --> 00:54:12.216
unchecked sway, a blue flame is seen over any place where treasure has been concealed.

00:54:13.116 --> 00:54:18.056
That treasure has been hidden, he went on. In the region through which you came last night,

00:54:18.096 --> 00:54:22.936
there can be but little doubt, for it was the ground fought over for centuries by the Wallachian,

00:54:22.936 --> 00:54:28.156
the Saxon, and the Turk. Why, there is hardly a foot of soil in all this region that has not

00:54:28.156 --> 00:54:33.856
been enriched by the blood of men, patriots, or invaders. In the old days there were stirring

00:54:33.856 --> 00:54:39.196
times when the Austrians and the Hungarians came up in hordes, and the patriots went out to meet

00:54:39.196 --> 00:54:44.616
them, men and women, the aged and children too, and waited their coming on the rocks above the

00:54:44.616 --> 00:54:48.456
passes that they might sweep destruction on them with their artificial avalanches.

00:54:49.016 --> 00:54:54.616
When the invader was triumphant, he found but a little, for whatever there was had been sheltered

00:54:54.616 --> 00:55:00.196
in the friendly soil. But how, said I, can it have remained so long undiscovered,

00:55:00.276 --> 00:55:03.076
when there is a sure index to it if men will but take the trouble to look?

00:55:03.856 --> 00:55:09.256
The Count smiled, and as his lips ran back over the gums, the long sharp canine teeth

00:55:09.256 --> 00:55:14.776
showed out strangely. He answered, Because your peasant is at heart a coward and a fool.

00:55:15.336 --> 00:55:20.096
Those flames only appear on one night, and on that night no man of this land willed if he can

00:55:20.096 --> 00:55:25.736
help it stir without his doors. And, dear sir, even if he did, he would not know what to do.

00:55:26.176 --> 00:55:29.416
Why, even the peasant that you tell me of, who marked the place of the flame,

00:55:29.836 --> 00:55:32.516
would not know where to look in daylight even for his own work.

00:55:33.116 --> 00:55:36.976
Even you would not, I dare be sworn, be able to find these places again.

00:55:38.216 --> 00:55:42.436
There you are right, I said. I know no more than the dead were even to look for them.

00:55:42.956 --> 00:55:44.816
Then we drifted on to other matters.

00:55:46.036 --> 00:55:51.656
Come, he said at last, tell me of London, and of the house which you have procured for me.

00:55:52.536 --> 00:55:57.156
With an apology for my remissness, I went into my own room to get the papers from my bag.

00:55:58.236 --> 00:56:02.436
Whilst I was placing them in order, I heard a rattling of china and silver in the next room,

00:56:02.876 --> 00:56:06.716
and as I passed through, noticed that the table had been cleared and the lamp lit,

00:56:07.136 --> 00:56:09.136
for it was by this time deep into the dark.

00:56:09.856 --> 00:56:12.676
The lamps were also lit in the study or library,

00:56:13.236 --> 00:56:16.956
and I found the Count lying on the sofa reading, of all things in the world,

00:56:17.196 --> 00:56:22.336
an English Bradshaw's guide. When I came in, he cleared the books and papers from the table,

00:56:22.716 --> 00:56:28.056
and with him I went into plans and deeds and figures of all sorts. He was interested in

00:56:28.056 --> 00:56:32.056
everything, and asked me a myriad questions about the place and its surroundings.

00:56:32.736 --> 00:56:36.516
He clearly had studied beforehand all he could get on the subject of the neighborhood,

00:56:36.516 --> 00:56:42.136
for he evidently at the end knew very much more than I did. When I remarked this, he answered,

00:56:42.676 --> 00:56:47.996
Well, but my friend, is it not needful that I should? When I go there, I shall be all alone,

00:56:48.216 --> 00:56:53.956
and my friend Harker Jonathan, nay, pardon me, I fall into my country's habit of putting your

00:56:53.956 --> 00:57:00.296
patronymic first, my friend Jonathan Harker, will not be by my side to correct and aid me.

00:57:00.636 --> 00:57:05.776
He will be an exeter miles away, probably working at papers of the law with my other friend Peter

00:57:05.776 --> 00:57:11.476
Hawkins, soul. We went thoroughly into the business of the purchase of the estate at

00:57:11.996 --> 00:57:16.416
Perfleet. When I had told him the facts, and got his signature to the necessary papers,

00:57:16.976 --> 00:57:22.276
and had written a letter with them ready to post to Mr. Hawkins, he began to ask me how I had come

00:57:22.276 --> 00:57:27.696
across so suitable a place. I read to him the notes which I had made at the time, and which

00:57:27.696 --> 00:57:34.796
I inscribe here. At Perfleet, on a by-road, I came across just such a place as seemed to be required,

00:57:34.796 --> 00:57:38.956
and where there was displayed a dilapidated notice that the place was for sale.

00:57:39.576 --> 00:57:45.296
It was surrounded by a high wall of ancient structure, built of heavy stones, and has not

00:57:45.296 --> 00:57:50.696
been repaired for a large number of years. The closed gates are of heavy old oak and iron,

00:57:51.096 --> 00:57:57.736
all eaten with rust. The estate is called Carfax, no doubt a corruption of the old Cartreface,

00:57:57.916 --> 00:58:01.816
as the house is four-sided, agreeing with the cardinal points of the compass.

00:58:02.476 --> 00:58:07.976
It contains in all some twenty acres, quite surrounded by the solid stone wall above mentioned.

00:58:08.736 --> 00:58:14.156
There are many trees on it which make it in places gloomy, and there is a deep, dark-looking pond,

00:58:14.276 --> 00:58:20.216
a small lake, evidently fed by some springs, as the water is clear and flows away in a fair-sized

00:58:20.216 --> 00:58:26.496
stream. The house is very large, and of all periods back, I should say to medieval times,

00:58:26.496 --> 00:58:32.516
for one part is of stone immensely thick, with only a few windows high up and heavily barred

00:58:32.516 --> 00:58:38.016
with iron. It looks like part of a keep, and is close to an old chapel or church.

00:58:38.696 --> 00:58:42.676
I could not enter it, as I had not the key of the door leading to it from the house,

00:58:43.156 --> 00:58:46.256
but I have taken with my Kodak views of it from various points.

00:58:47.416 --> 00:58:52.216
The house had been added to, but in a very straggling way, and I can only guess at the

00:58:52.216 --> 00:58:58.196
amount of ground it covers, which must be very great. There are but few houses close at hand,

00:58:58.496 --> 00:59:03.316
one being a very large house only recently added to and formed into a private lunatic asylum.

00:59:03.916 --> 00:59:06.316
It is not, however, visible from the grounds.

00:59:07.656 --> 00:59:09.296
When I had finished, he said,

00:59:09.856 --> 00:59:17.216
I am glad that it is old and big. I myself am of an old family, and to live in a new house would

00:59:17.216 --> 00:59:23.896
kill me. A house cannot be made habitable in a day, and after all how few days go to make up a

00:59:23.896 --> 00:59:31.436
century. I rejoice also that there is a chapel of old times. We Transylvanian nobles love not to

00:59:31.436 --> 00:59:38.476
think that our bones may lie amongst the common dead. I seek not gaiety nor mirth, not the bright

00:59:38.476 --> 00:59:44.776
voluptuousness of much sunshine and sparkling waters which please the young and gay. I am no

00:59:44.776 --> 00:59:51.096
longer young, and my heart, through weary years of mourning over the dead, is attuned to mirth.

00:59:52.196 --> 00:59:58.976
Moreover, the walls of my castle are broken, the shadows are many, and the wind breathes cold

00:59:58.976 --> 01:00:05.496
through the broken battlements and casements. I love the shade and the shadow, and would be alone

01:00:05.496 --> 01:00:13.036
with my thoughts when I may. Somehow his words and his look did not seem to accord, or else it

01:00:13.036 --> 01:00:20.376
the cast of his face made his smile look malignant and satanine. Presently with an excuse he left me,

01:00:20.516 --> 01:00:26.056
asking me to pull my papers together. He was some little time away, and I began to look at

01:00:26.056 --> 01:00:31.736
some of the books around me. One was an atlas which I found open naturally to England, as if

01:00:31.736 --> 01:00:37.556
that map had been much used. On looking at it, I found in certain places little rings marked,

01:00:37.556 --> 01:00:42.716
and on examining these, I noticed that one was near London on the east side,

01:00:43.016 --> 01:00:48.576
manifestly where his new estate was situated. The other two were at Exeter, and would be on

01:00:48.576 --> 01:00:54.296
the Yorkshire coast. It was the better part of an hour when the Count returned.

01:00:55.176 --> 01:01:03.016
Aha! he said. Still at your books? Good. But you must not work always. Come, I am informed

01:01:03.016 --> 01:01:08.556
that your supper is ready. He took my arm, and we went into the next room, where I found an

01:01:08.556 --> 01:01:13.596
excellent supper ready on the table. The Count again excused himself, as he had dined out on

01:01:13.596 --> 01:01:19.556
his being away from home. But he sat as on the previous night, and chatted whilst I ate. After

01:01:19.556 --> 01:01:24.336
supper I smoked as on the last evening, and the Count stayed with me, chatting and asking questions

01:01:24.336 --> 01:01:30.216
on every conceivable subject, hour after hour. I felt that it was getting very late indeed,

01:01:30.216 --> 01:01:35.216
but I did not say anything, for I felt under obligation to meet my host's wishes in every way.

01:01:35.976 --> 01:01:41.976
I was not sleepy, as the long sleep yesterday had fortified me, but I could not help experiencing

01:01:41.976 --> 01:01:46.576
that chill which comes over one at the coming of the dawn, which is like, in its way, the turn of

01:01:46.576 --> 01:01:51.636
the tide. They say that people who are near death die generally at the change to dawn,

01:01:51.676 --> 01:01:56.576
or at the turn of the tide. Anyone who has when tired, and tied as it were to his post,

01:01:57.156 --> 01:02:00.096
experienced this change in the atmosphere, I can well believe it.

01:02:00.916 --> 01:02:04.516
All at once we heard the crow of the cock coming up with preternatural

01:02:04.516 --> 01:02:09.476
shrillness through the clear morning air. Count Dracula, jumping to his feet, said,

01:02:09.876 --> 01:02:15.976
Why, there is the morning again! How remiss I am to let you stay up so long! You must make

01:02:15.976 --> 01:02:21.656
your conversation regarding my dear new country of England less interesting, so that I may not

01:02:21.656 --> 01:02:27.136
forget how time flies by us. And with a courtly bow he quickly left me.

01:02:28.136 --> 01:02:31.556
I went into my room and drew the curtains, but there was little to notice.

01:02:32.256 --> 01:02:36.976
My window opened into the courtyard, all I could see was the warm grey of the quickening sky,

01:02:37.556 --> 01:02:40.816
so I pulled the curtains again, and have written of this day.

01:02:42.956 --> 01:02:47.976
8th of May. I began to fear as I wrote in this book that I was getting to diffuse,

01:02:47.976 --> 01:02:53.976
but now I am glad that I went into detail from the first, for there is something so strange about

01:02:53.976 --> 01:02:59.236
this place and all in it that I cannot but feel uneasy. I wish I was safe out of it,

01:02:59.336 --> 01:03:04.796
or that I had never come. It may be that this strange night existence is telling on me,

01:03:05.156 --> 01:03:10.616
but would that that were all. If there were anyone to talk to I could bear it, but there is no one.

01:03:11.136 --> 01:03:17.476
I have only the Count to speak with, and he—I fear I am myself the only living soul within the

01:03:17.476 --> 01:03:24.296
place. Let me be prosaic so far as facts can be. It will help me to bear up, and imagination must

01:03:24.296 --> 01:03:30.696
not run riot with me. If it does, I am lost. Let me say at once how I stand, or seem to.

01:03:31.916 --> 01:03:37.256
I only slept a few hours when I went to bed, and feeling that I could not sleep any more got up.

01:03:37.856 --> 01:03:41.516
I had hung my shaving-glass by the window, and was just beginning to shave.

01:03:42.256 --> 01:03:46.656
Suddenly I felt a hand on my shoulder, and heard the Count's voice saying to me,

01:03:47.036 --> 01:03:52.776
Good morning. I started, for it amazed me that I had not seen him since the reflection of

01:03:52.776 --> 01:03:57.276
the glass covered the whole room behind me. In starting I had cut myself slightly,

01:03:57.696 --> 01:04:01.736
but did not notice it at the moment. Having answered the Count's salutation,

01:04:02.176 --> 01:04:07.416
I turned to the glass again to see how I had been mistaken. This time there could be no error,

01:04:07.416 --> 01:04:12.356
for the man was close to me, and I could see him over my shoulder, but there was no reflection of

01:04:12.356 --> 01:04:18.156
him in the mirror. The whole room behind me was displayed, but there was no sign of a man in it,

01:04:18.296 --> 01:04:24.576
except myself. This was startling, and coming on top of so many strange things was beginning

01:04:24.576 --> 01:04:28.776
to increase that vague feeling of uneasiness which I always have when the Count is near.

01:04:29.556 --> 01:04:34.276
But at the instant I saw that the cut had bled a little, and the blood was trickling over my chin,

01:04:34.276 --> 01:04:39.376
I laid down the razor, turning as I did so half round to look for some sticking plaster.

01:04:40.096 --> 01:04:44.716
When the Count saw my face, his eyes blazed with a sort of demoniac fury,

01:04:45.076 --> 01:04:50.776
and he suddenly made a grab at my throat. I drew away, and his hand touched the string of beads

01:04:50.776 --> 01:04:56.356
which held the crucifix. It made an instant change in him, for the fury passed so quickly

01:04:56.356 --> 01:05:03.296
that I could hardly believe that it was ever there. Take care, he said. Take care how you cut

01:05:03.296 --> 01:05:09.896
yourself. It is more dangerous than you think in this country. Then, seizing the shaving glass,

01:05:09.916 --> 01:05:15.256
he went on, and this is the wretched thing that has done the mischief. It is a foul

01:05:15.256 --> 01:05:21.976
barbel of man's vanity. Away with it! And opening the window with one wrench of his terrible hand,

01:05:22.456 --> 01:05:33.276
he flung out the glass, which was shattered into a thousand pieces on the stones of the

01:05:33.276 --> 01:05:38.156
I did not see how I am to shave, unless in my watch case or the bottom of the shaving pot,

01:05:38.336 --> 01:05:43.356
which is fortunately of metal. When I went into the dining room, breakfast was prepared,

01:05:43.676 --> 01:05:48.976
but I could not find the Count anywhere, so I breakfasted alone. It is strange that as yet

01:05:48.976 --> 01:05:55.296
I have not seen the Count eat or drink. He must be a very peculiar man. After breakfast,

01:05:55.556 --> 01:06:00.356
I did a little exploring in the castle. I went out on the stairs, and found a room looking

01:06:00.356 --> 01:06:05.576
towards the south. The view was magnificent, and from where I stood there was every opportunity

01:06:05.576 --> 01:06:11.336
of seeing it. The castle is on the very edge of a terrific precipice. A stone falling from the

01:06:11.336 --> 01:06:16.596
window would fall a thousand feet without touching anything. As far as the eye can reach is a sea of

01:06:16.596 --> 01:06:21.916
green tree tops, with occasionally a deep rift where there is a chasm. Here and there are silver

01:06:21.916 --> 01:06:27.036
threads where the rivers wind in deep gorges through the forests. But I am not in heart to

01:06:27.036 --> 01:06:33.476
beauty, for when I had seen the view I explored further. Doors, doors, doors everywhere,

01:06:33.976 --> 01:06:39.556
and all locked and bolted. In no place save from the windows and the castle walls is there an

01:06:39.556 --> 01:06:45.336
available exit. The castle is a veritable prison, and I am a prisoner.

01:07:19.465 --> 01:07:24.425
III Jonathan Harker's Journal Continued

01:07:26.485 --> 01:07:33.185
When I found that I was a prisoner, a sort of wild feeling came over me. I rushed up and down

01:07:33.185 --> 01:07:39.765
the stairs, trying every door and peering out of every window I could find. But after a little,

01:07:40.285 --> 01:07:46.005
the conviction of my helplessness overpowered all other feelings. When I look back, after a

01:07:46.005 --> 01:07:52.985
few hours, I think I must have been mad for the time, for I behaved much as a rat does in a trap.

01:07:53.745 --> 01:08:00.405
When, however, the conviction had come to me that I was helpless, I sat down quietly,

01:08:00.885 --> 01:08:07.845
as quietly as I have ever done anything in my life, and began to think over what was best to

01:08:07.845 --> 01:08:16.735
be done. I am thinking still, and as yet have come to no definite conclusion. Of one thing only am I

01:08:16.735 --> 01:08:24.615
that it is no use making my ideas known to the count. He knows well that I am imprisoned,

01:08:24.995 --> 01:08:32.735
and as he has done it himself, and has doubtless his own motives for it, he would only deceive me

01:08:32.735 --> 01:08:41.035
if I trusted him fully with the facts. So far as I can see, my only plan will be to keep my

01:08:41.035 --> 01:08:49.375
knowledge and my fears to myself, and my eyes open. I am, I know, either being deceived,

01:08:49.795 --> 01:08:57.295
like a baby, by my own fears, or else I am in desperate straits, and if the latter be so,

01:08:57.755 --> 01:09:05.895
I need, and shall need, all my brains to get through. I had hardly come to this conclusion

01:09:05.895 --> 01:09:13.275
when I heard the great door below shut, and knew that the Count had returned. He did not

01:09:13.275 --> 01:09:19.395
come at once into the library, so I went cautiously to my own room and found him making the bed.

01:09:20.255 --> 01:09:27.375
This was odd, but only confirmed what I had all along thought, that there are no servants

01:09:27.375 --> 01:09:33.335
in the house. When later I saw him through the chink of the hinges of the door laying

01:09:33.335 --> 01:09:40.215
the table in the dining-room, I was assured of it. For if he does himself all these menial

01:09:40.215 --> 01:09:46.675
offices, surely it is proof that there is no one else in the castle. It must have been

01:09:46.675 --> 01:09:52.735
the Count himself who was the driver of the coach that brought me here. This is a terrible

01:09:52.735 --> 01:10:00.735
thought. For if so, what does it mean that he could control the wolves as he did, by

01:10:00.735 --> 01:10:08.635
only holding up his hand for silence? How was it that all the people at Bistritz and

01:10:08.635 --> 01:10:16.475
on the coach had some terrible fear for me? What meant the giving of the crucifix, of

01:10:16.475 --> 01:10:25.215
the garlic, of the wild rose, of the mountain ash? Bless that good, good woman who hung

01:10:25.215 --> 01:10:31.395
the crucifix round my neck! For it is a comfort and a strength to me whenever I touch it.

01:10:32.075 --> 01:10:39.035
It is odd that a thing which I have been taught to regard with disfavour and as idolatrous

01:10:39.035 --> 01:10:47.175
should in a time of loneliness and trouble be of help. Is it that there is something

01:10:47.175 --> 01:10:57.175
in the essence of the thing itself, or that it is a medium, a tangible help, in conveying

01:10:57.175 --> 01:11:04.495
memories of sympathy and comfort? Sometime, if it may be, I must examine this matter and

01:11:04.495 --> 01:11:11.075
try to make up my mind about it. In the meantime I must find out all I can about Count Dracula,

01:11:11.075 --> 01:11:18.795
as it may help me to understand. Tonight he may talk of himself, if I turn the conversation

01:11:18.795 --> 01:11:24.735
that way. I must be very careful, however, not to awake his suspicion.

01:11:26.395 --> 01:11:26.935
Midnight.

01:11:28.495 --> 01:11:33.935
I've had a long talk with the Count. I asked him a few questions on Transylvania history,

01:11:33.955 --> 01:11:39.855
and he warmed up to the subject wonderfully. In his speaking of things and people, and

01:11:39.855 --> 01:11:45.315
especially of battles, he spoke as if he had been present at them all. This he afterwards

01:11:45.315 --> 01:11:53.295
explained by saying that to a boyar the pride of his house and name is his own pride, that

01:11:53.295 --> 01:11:59.935
their glory is his glory, that their fate is his fate. Whenever he spoke of his house

01:11:59.935 --> 01:12:08.695
he always said we, and spoke almost in the plural, like a king speaking. I wish I could

01:12:08.695 --> 01:12:15.695
put down all he said exactly as he said it, for to me it was most fascinating. It seemed

01:12:15.695 --> 01:12:22.395
to have in it a whole history of the country. He grew excited as he spoke, and walked about

01:12:22.395 --> 01:12:27.635
the room pulling his great white moustache, and grasping anything on which he laid his

01:12:27.635 --> 01:12:34.195
hands as though he would crush it by main strength. One thing he said, which I shall

01:12:34.195 --> 01:12:40.275
put down as nearly as I can, for it tells in its way the story of his race.

01:12:41.935 --> 01:12:49.475
These Achilles have a right to be proud, for in our reigns flows the blood of many brave

01:12:49.475 --> 01:13:04.175
races who fought as the lion fights for lordship. Here, in the whirlpool of European races, the

01:13:04.175 --> 01:13:10.215
thunder and thunder gave them, which their berserkers displayed to such foul intent on

01:13:10.215 --> 01:13:19.455
the seaboard of Europe, and of Asia and Africa too, till the peoples thought that the wervels

01:13:19.455 --> 01:13:29.895
themselves had come. Here too, when they came, they found Sahans, whose warlike fury had

01:13:29.895 --> 01:13:36.795
swept the earth like a living flame, till the dying peoples held it in their veins,

01:13:37.275 --> 01:13:44.135
and the blood of those old witches who expelled from Scythia had mated with the devils in

01:13:44.135 --> 01:13:56.435
the desert. Fools! Fools! What devil or what witch was ever so great as Attila, whose blood

01:13:56.435 --> 01:14:06.295
is in these veins? He held up his arms. Is it a wonder that we were a conquering race?

01:14:07.055 --> 01:14:15.815
That we were proud that when the Magyar, the Lombard, the Avvar, the Bolgar, or the Turk

01:14:15.815 --> 01:14:25.255
poured his thousands on our frontiers that we drove them back? Is it strange that when

01:14:25.255 --> 01:14:33.475
our path and his legions swept through the Hungarian fatherland, he found us here when

01:14:33.475 --> 01:14:42.275
he reached the frontier, that the Honfoglalaz was completed there, and when the Hungarian

01:14:42.275 --> 01:14:51.635
flood swept eastward, the Zekales were claimed as kindred by the victorious Magyars, and

01:14:51.635 --> 01:14:59.815
who us for centuries was trusted to guarding of the frontier of Turkiland? Ay, and more

01:14:59.815 --> 01:15:08.835
than that, endless duty of the frontier guard, for as the Turks say, water sleeps and the

01:15:08.835 --> 01:15:17.995
enemy is sleepless. Who more gladly than we throughout the four nations received the bloody

01:15:17.995 --> 01:15:26.455
sword, or at its warlike call flocked quicker to the standard of the king? When was redeemed

01:15:26.455 --> 01:15:35.235
that great shame of my nation, the shame of Kosova, when the flags of the Valach and the

01:15:35.235 --> 01:15:44.395
Magyar went down beneath the crescent? Who was it but one of my own race who as Voivode

01:15:44.395 --> 01:15:54.395
crossed the Danube and beat the Turk on his own ground? This was a Dracula, indeed. Who

01:15:54.395 --> 01:16:02.095
was it that his own unworthy brother, when he had fallen, sold his people to the Turk

01:16:02.645 --> 01:16:12.235
and brought the shame of slavery on them? Was it not this Dracula, indeed, who inspired

01:16:12.235 --> 01:16:19.615
that other of his race, who in a later age again and again brought his forces over the

01:16:19.615 --> 01:16:28.075
great river into Turkiland, who when he was beaten back, came again and again, though

01:16:28.075 --> 01:16:34.555
he had to come alone from the bloody field where his troops were being slaughtered, since

01:16:34.555 --> 01:16:42.215
he knew that he alone could ultimately triumph? They said that he thought only of his own

01:16:42.235 --> 01:16:55.755
self. Bah! What good are peasants without a leader? Where ends the war without a brain

01:16:55.755 --> 01:17:07.355
and a heart to conduct it? Again, when after the battle of Mohaks they threw off the Hungarian

01:17:07.355 --> 01:17:19.775
yoke, we of the Dracula blood were amongst their leaders, for our spirit would not brook

01:17:19.775 --> 01:17:31.935
that we were not free. Ah, young sir, the Zechelis and the Dracula as their heart's

01:17:31.935 --> 01:17:42.095
blood, their brains and their swords, can boast a record that mushroom growths like

01:17:42.095 --> 01:17:53.195
the Habsburgs and the Romanovs could never reach. The warlike days are over. Blood is

01:17:53.195 --> 01:18:01.915
too precious a thing in these days of dishonorable peace, and the glories of the great race,

01:18:01.935 --> 01:18:05.555
the vices, are as a tale that is told.

01:18:07.075 --> 01:18:14.735
It was by this time close on morning, and we went to bed. Memorandum. This diary seems

01:18:14.735 --> 01:18:19.775
horribly like the beginning of the Arabian Nights, for everything has to break off at

01:18:19.775 --> 01:18:23.215
cock-crow or like the ghost of Hamlet's father.

01:18:24.815 --> 01:18:34.775
12th of May. Let me begin with facts. Bare, meager facts, verified by books and figures,

01:18:35.475 --> 01:18:42.555
and of which there can be no doubt. I must not confuse them with experiences which will

01:18:42.555 --> 01:18:48.115
have to rest on my own observation or my memory of them. Last evening, when the Count came

01:18:48.115 --> 01:18:54.255
from his room, he began by asking me questions on legal matters and on the doings of certain

01:18:54.255 --> 01:19:01.295
kinds of business. I had spent the day wearily over books, and, simply to keep my mind occupied,

01:19:01.695 --> 01:19:09.495
went over some of the matters I had been examined in at Lincoln's Inn. There was a certain method

01:19:09.495 --> 01:19:15.475
in the Count's inquiries, so I shall try to put them down in sequence. The knowledge may

01:19:15.475 --> 01:19:19.475
somehow, or some time, be useful to me.

01:19:20.615 --> 01:19:26.895
First, he asked if a man in England might have two solicitors or more. I told him he

01:19:26.895 --> 01:19:31.235
might have a dozen if he wished, but that it would not be wise to have more than one

01:19:31.235 --> 01:19:37.335
solicitor engaged in one transaction, as only one could act at a time, and that the change

01:19:37.335 --> 01:19:43.615
would be certain to militate against his interest. He seemed thoroughly to understand, and went

01:19:43.615 --> 01:19:48.715
on to ask if there would be any practical difficulty in having one man to attend, say,

01:19:48.775 --> 01:19:54.555
to banking, and another to look after shipping, in case local help were needed in a place

01:19:54.555 --> 01:20:00.215
far from home of the banking solicitor. I asked him to explain more fully, so that I

01:20:00.215 --> 01:20:04.335
might not by any chance mislead him. So he said,

01:20:05.095 --> 01:20:14.155
I shall illustrate. Your friend and mine, Mr. Peter Hawkins, from under the shadow of

01:20:14.155 --> 01:20:22.155
your beautiful cathedral at Exeter, which is far from London, buys for me through your

01:20:22.155 --> 01:20:30.115
good self my place at London. Now here let me say frankly, lest you should think it strange

01:20:30.115 --> 01:20:36.455
that I have sought the services of one so far off from London instead of some one resident

01:20:36.455 --> 01:20:44.735
there, that my motive was that no local interest might be served save my wish only, and as

01:20:44.735 --> 01:20:51.755
one of London residents might perhaps have some purpose of himself or friend to serve.

01:20:52.775 --> 01:20:59.335
I went thus afield to seek my agent, whose labor should be only to my interest.

01:21:00.995 --> 01:21:12.275
Now suppose I, who have much of affairs, wish to ship goods, say, to Newcastle or Durham

01:21:12.275 --> 01:21:21.135
or Harwich or Dover. Might it not be that it could be with more ease be done by consigning

01:21:21.135 --> 01:21:29.455
to one in these ports? I answered that certainly it would be most easy, but that we solicitors

01:21:29.455 --> 01:21:35.015
had a system of agency, one for the other, so that local work could be done locally on

01:21:35.015 --> 01:21:40.135
instruction from any solicitor, so that the client simply by placing himself in the hands

01:21:40.135 --> 01:21:44.315
of one man could have his wishes carried out by him without further trouble.

01:21:45.635 --> 01:21:52.655
But, said he, I could be at liberty to direct myself. Is it not so?

01:21:53.575 --> 01:22:00.855
Of course, I replied, and such is often done by men of business, who do not like the whole

01:22:00.855 --> 01:22:03.155
of their affairs to be known by any one person.

01:22:04.615 --> 01:22:10.075
Good, he said, and then went on to ask about the means of making consignments and the forms

01:22:10.075 --> 01:22:15.915
to be gone through, and of all sorts of difficulties which might arise, but by forethought could

01:22:15.915 --> 01:22:22.095
be guarded against. I explained all these things to him to the best of my ability, and

01:22:22.095 --> 01:22:26.795
he certainly left me under the impression that he would have made a wonderful solicitor.

01:22:27.815 --> 01:22:33.355
For there was nothing that he did not think of or foresee. For a man who was never in

01:22:33.355 --> 01:22:39.375
the country, and who did not evidently do much in the way of business, his knowledge

01:22:39.375 --> 01:22:44.235
and acumen were wonderful. When he had satisfied himself on these points

01:22:44.235 --> 01:22:49.655
on which he had spoken, and I had verified all as well as I could by the books available,

01:22:50.195 --> 01:22:51.995
he suddenly stood up and said,

01:22:53.115 --> 01:23:00.855
Have you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter Hawkins, or to any other?

01:23:01.675 --> 01:23:07.135
It was with some bitterness in my heart that I answered that I had not, that as yet I had

01:23:07.135 --> 01:23:09.895
not seen any opportunity of sending letters to anybody.

01:23:11.555 --> 01:23:19.635
Then right now, my young friend, he said, laying a heavy hand on my shoulder, write

01:23:19.655 --> 01:23:28.675
to our friend, and to any other, and say, if it will please you, that you shall stay

01:23:28.675 --> 01:23:31.755
with me until a month from now.

01:23:32.835 --> 01:23:38.895
Do you wish me to stay so long? I asked, for my heart grew cold at the thought.

01:23:40.135 --> 01:23:46.595
I desire it much. Nay, I will take no refusal.

01:23:47.395 --> 01:23:55.815
When your master, employer, what you will, engaged that someone should come on his behalf,

01:23:56.555 --> 01:24:00.555
it was understood that my needs only were to be consulted.

01:24:01.295 --> 01:24:04.975
I have not stinted. Is it not so?

01:24:05.935 --> 01:24:12.995
What could I do but bow acceptance? It was Mr. Hawkins' interest, not mine, and I had

01:24:12.995 --> 01:24:19.435
to think of him not myself and besides, while Count Dracula was speaking. There was that

01:24:19.435 --> 01:24:25.915
in his eyes and in his bearing, which made me remember that I was a prisoner, and that

01:24:25.915 --> 01:24:28.835
if I wished it, I could have no choice.

01:24:29.995 --> 01:24:36.155
The Count saw his victory in my bow, and his mastery in the trouble of my face, for he

01:24:36.155 --> 01:24:41.835
began at once to use them, but in his own smooth, resistless way.

01:24:42.915 --> 01:24:51.655
I pray you, my good young friend, that you will not discourse of things other than business

01:24:51.655 --> 01:24:58.335
in your letters. It will doubtless please your friends to know that you are well and

01:24:58.335 --> 01:25:06.135
that you look forward to getting home to them. Is it not so? As he spoke, he handed me three

01:25:06.155 --> 01:25:13.055
sheets of notepaper and three envelopes. They were all the thinnest foreign post, and looking

01:25:13.055 --> 01:25:21.795
at them, then at him, and noticing his quiet smile with the sharp canine teeth lying over

01:25:21.795 --> 01:25:28.875
the red underlip, I understood as well as if he had spoken that I should be more careful

01:25:28.875 --> 01:25:32.135
what I wrote, for he would be able to read it.

01:25:33.235 --> 01:25:38.655
So I determined to write only formal notes now, but to write fully to Mr. Hawkins in

01:25:38.655 --> 01:25:44.155
secret, and also to Mina, for to her I could write shorthand which would puzzle the Count,

01:25:44.795 --> 01:25:51.675
if he did see it. When I had written my two letters I sat quiet, reading a book, whilst

01:25:51.675 --> 01:25:56.795
the Count wrote several notes, referring, as he wrote them, to some books on his table.

01:25:56.795 --> 01:26:03.335
Then he took up my two and placed them with his own, and put by his writing materials,

01:26:03.935 --> 01:26:10.635
after which, the instant the door had closed behind him, I leaned over and looked at the

01:26:10.635 --> 01:26:16.375
letters, which were face down on the table. I felt no compunction in doing so, for under

01:26:16.375 --> 01:26:20.275
the circumstances I felt that I should protect myself in every way I could.

01:26:21.375 --> 01:26:27.835
One of the letters was directed to Samuel F. Billington, No. 7, the Crescent, Whitby.

01:26:28.495 --> 01:26:35.955
Another to Herr Lütner, Varna. The third was to Coots & Company, London, and the fourth

01:26:35.955 --> 01:26:50.255
to Herren Klopstock & Bilruth, Bankers, Budapest. The second and fourth were unsealed. I was

01:26:50.255 --> 01:26:55.535
having just had time to resume my book before the Count, holding still another letter in

01:26:55.535 --> 01:27:00.795
his hand, entered the room. He took up the letters on the table and stamped them carefully,

01:27:01.235 --> 01:27:03.215
and then turning to me, said,

01:27:04.515 --> 01:27:12.395
I trust you will forgive me, but I have much work to do in private this evening. You will,

01:27:12.395 --> 01:27:16.175
I hope, find all things as you wish.

01:27:17.135 --> 01:27:21.215
At the door he turned, and after a moment's pause said,

01:27:22.035 --> 01:27:35.495
Let me advise you, my dear young friend, Nay, let me warn you, with all seriousness, that

01:27:35.495 --> 01:27:43.955
should you leave these rooms, you will not by any chance go to sleep in any other part

01:27:43.955 --> 01:27:54.895
of the castle. It is old and has many memories, and there are bad dreams for those who sleep

01:27:54.895 --> 01:28:07.495
unwisely. Be warned. Should sleep now or ever overcome you, or be like to do, then haste

01:28:07.495 --> 01:28:15.515
to your own chamber or to these rooms, for your rest will then be safe. But if you be

01:28:15.515 --> 01:28:20.975
not careful in this respect, then...

01:28:21.205 --> 01:28:27.175
He finished his speech in a gruesome way, for he motioned with his hands as if he were

01:28:27.175 --> 01:28:35.995
washing them. I quite understood. My only doubt was as to whether any dream could be

01:28:35.995 --> 01:28:44.915
more terrible than the unnaturable, horrible net of gloom and mystery which seemed closing

01:28:44.915 --> 01:28:45.955
around me.

01:28:47.395 --> 01:28:54.675
Later, I endorsed the last words written, but this time there is no doubt in question.

01:28:55.975 --> 01:29:01.715
I shall not fear to sleep in any place where he is not. I have placed the crucifix over

01:29:01.715 --> 01:29:08.155
the head of my bed. I imagine that my rest is thus freer from dreams, and there it shall

01:29:08.155 --> 01:29:08.595
remain.

01:29:10.015 --> 01:29:16.515
When he left me I went to my room. After a little while, not hearing any sound, I came

01:29:16.515 --> 01:29:23.195
out and went up the stone stair to where I could look out towards the south. There was

01:29:23.195 --> 01:29:30.155
some sense of freedom in the vast expanse. Inaccessible though it was to me, as compared

01:29:30.155 --> 01:29:32.255
with the narrow darkness of the courtyard.

01:29:33.995 --> 01:29:40.895
Looking out on this, I felt that I was indeed in prison, and I seemed to want a breath of

01:29:40.895 --> 01:29:48.235
fresh air, though it were of the night. I am beginning to feel this nocturnal existence

01:29:48.235 --> 01:29:56.195
tell on me. It is destroying my nerve. I start at my own shadow and am full of all sorts

01:29:56.195 --> 01:30:04.595
of horrible imaginings. God knows that there is ground for my terrible fear in this accursed

01:30:04.595 --> 01:30:05.135
place.

01:30:06.315 --> 01:30:13.215
I looked out over the beautiful expanse, bathed in soft yellow moonlight till it was almost

01:30:13.215 --> 01:30:22.195
as light as day. In the soft light the distant hills became melted, and the shadows in the

01:30:22.195 --> 01:30:31.095
valleys and gorges of velvety blackness. The mere beauty seemed to cheer me. There was

01:30:31.095 --> 01:30:33.835
peace and comfort in every breath I drew.

01:30:34.775 --> 01:30:43.915
As I leaned from the window my eye was caught by something moving a story below me and somewhat

01:30:43.915 --> 01:30:51.355
to my left, where I imagined, from the order of the rooms, that the windows of the Count's

01:30:51.355 --> 01:30:59.375
Stone Room would look out. The window at which I stood was tall and deep, stone mullioned,

01:31:00.175 --> 01:31:06.895
and though weather-worn was still complete. But it was evidently many a day since the

01:31:06.895 --> 01:31:21.335
case had been there. I drew back behind the stonework and looked carefully out. What I

01:31:22.065 --> 01:31:28.835
knew the man by the neck and the movement of his back and arms. In any case I could

01:31:28.835 --> 01:31:35.655
not mistake the hands which I had some many opportunities of studying. I was at first

01:31:35.655 --> 01:31:42.215
interested and somewhat amused, or it is wonderful how small a matter will interest and amuse

01:31:42.215 --> 01:31:51.315
a man when he is a prisoner. But my very feelings changed to repulsion and terror. I was not

01:31:51.335 --> 01:32:00.255
when I saw the whole man slowly emerge from the window and begin to crawl down the castle

01:32:00.255 --> 01:32:08.395
wall over the dreadful abyss, face down with his cloak spreading out around him like great

01:32:08.395 --> 01:32:18.935
wings. At first I could not believe my eyes. I thought it was some trick of the moonlight,

01:32:18.935 --> 01:32:30.575
and some weird effect of shadow. But I kept looking, and it could be no delusion. I saw

01:32:30.575 --> 01:32:38.615
the fingers and toes grasp the corners of the stones, worn clear of the mortar by the

01:32:38.615 --> 01:32:46.475
stress of years, and by thus using every projection and inequality move downwards with considerable

01:32:46.475 --> 01:32:57.955
speed, just as a lizard moves along a wall. What manner of man is this, or what manner

01:32:57.955 --> 01:33:07.295
of creature is it in the semblance of man? I feel the dread of this horrible place overpowering

01:33:07.295 --> 01:33:16.075
me. I am in fear, in awful fear, and there is no escape for me.

01:33:17.175 --> 01:33:23.295
I am encompassed about with terrors that I dare not think of.

01:33:27.615 --> 01:33:36.175
Once more I have seen the Count go out in his lizard fashion. He moved downwards in

01:33:36.175 --> 01:33:42.915
a side-long way, some hundred feet down and a good deal to the left. He vanished into

01:33:42.915 --> 01:33:49.515
some hole or window. When his head had disappeared I leaned out to try and see more but without

01:33:49.515 --> 01:33:56.595
a veil. The distance was too great to allow a proper angle of sight. I knew he had left

01:33:56.595 --> 01:34:01.975
the castle now, and thought to use the opportunity to explore more than I had dared to do as

01:34:01.975 --> 01:34:09.975
yet. I went back to the room, and taking a lamp, tried all the doors. They were all locked,

01:34:09.975 --> 01:34:17.455
as I had expected, and the locks were comparatively new. But I went down the stone stairs to the

01:34:17.455 --> 01:34:24.295
hall where I had entered originally. I found I could pull back the bolts easily enough

01:34:24.295 --> 01:34:32.455
and unhook the great chains. But the door was locked, and the key was gone. That key

01:34:32.455 --> 01:34:39.415
must be in the Count's room. I must watch, should his door be unlocked, so that I may

01:34:39.415 --> 01:34:46.455
get it and escape. I went on to make a thorough examination of the various stairs and passages,

01:34:46.935 --> 01:34:53.495
and to try the doors that opened from them. One or two small rooms near the hall were

01:34:53.495 --> 01:34:59.515
open, but there was nothing to see in them except old furniture, dusty with age and moth-eaten.

01:35:00.655 --> 01:35:06.655
At last, however, I found one door at the top of the stairway which, though it seemed

01:35:06.655 --> 01:35:14.555
locked, gave a little under pressure. I tried it harder, and found that it was not really

01:35:14.555 --> 01:35:20.055
locked, but that the resistance came from the fact that the hinges had fallen somewhat,

01:35:20.615 --> 01:35:26.375
and the heavy door rested on the floor. Here was an opportunity which I might not have

01:35:26.375 --> 01:35:32.975
again, so I exerted myself, and with many efforts forced it back so that I could enter.

01:35:32.975 --> 01:35:39.875
I was now on a wing of the castle, further to the right than the rooms I knew, and a

01:35:39.875 --> 01:35:45.395
story lower down. From the windows I could see that the suite of rooms lay along to the

01:35:45.395 --> 01:35:51.755
south of the castle, the windows of the end-room looking out both west and south.

01:35:52.955 --> 01:35:59.275
On the latter side, as well as to the former, there was a great precipice. The castle was

01:35:59.275 --> 01:36:06.375
built on the corner of a great rock, so that on three sides it was quite impregnable. And

01:36:06.375 --> 01:36:13.975
great windows were placed here, where sling or bow or culverine could not reach, and consequently

01:36:13.975 --> 01:36:20.975
light and comfort, impossible to a position which had to be guarded, were secured. To

01:36:20.975 --> 01:36:27.915
the west was a great valley, and then rising far away great jagged mountain fastnesses

01:36:28.855 --> 01:36:37.175
rising peak on peak, the sheer rock studded with mountain ash and thorn, whose roots clung

01:36:37.175 --> 01:36:43.535
in cracks and crevices and crannies of the stone. This was evidently the portion of the

01:36:43.535 --> 01:36:49.715
castle occupied by the ladies in bygone days, for the furniture had more an air of comfort

01:36:49.715 --> 01:36:55.275
than any I had seen. The windows were curtainless, and the yellow

01:36:55.275 --> 01:37:02.975
moonlight, flooding in through the diamond panes, enabled one to see even colours, whilst

01:37:02.975 --> 01:37:09.755
it softened the wealth of dust which lay over all and disguised in some measure the ravages

01:37:09.755 --> 01:37:16.135
of time and moth. My lamp seemed to be of little effect in the brilliant moonlight,

01:37:16.855 --> 01:37:24.595
but I was glad to have it with me, for there was a dreadful loneliness in the place which

01:37:24.595 --> 01:37:33.255
chilled my heart and made my nerves tremble. Still, it was better than living alone in

01:37:33.255 --> 01:37:38.835
the rooms which I had come to hate from the presence of the Count, and after trying a

01:37:38.835 --> 01:37:43.795
little to school my nerves, I found a soft quietude come over me.

01:37:44.915 --> 01:37:52.075
Here I am, sitting at a little oak table, where in old times possibly some fair lady

01:37:52.075 --> 01:38:01.335
sat to pen, with much thought and many blushes, her ill-spelt love-letter, and writing in

01:38:01.335 --> 01:38:08.235
my diary in shorthand all that has happened since I closed it last. It is the nineteenth

01:38:08.235 --> 01:38:17.415
century, up to date with a vengeance, and yet, unless my senses deceive me, the old

01:38:17.415 --> 01:38:26.115
centuries had, and have, powers of their own which mere modernity cannot kill.

01:38:28.175 --> 01:38:38.675
Later, the morning of sixteenth May, God preserve my sanity, for to this I am reduced.

01:38:40.635 --> 01:38:48.095
Safety, and the assurance of safety, are things of the past. Whilst I live on here, there

01:38:48.095 --> 01:38:59.635
is but one thing to hope for, that I may not go mad, if indeed I be not mad already. If

01:38:59.635 --> 01:39:08.655
I be sane, and surely it is maddening to think that of all the foul things that lurk in this

01:39:08.675 --> 01:39:19.895
hateful place, the Count is the least dreadful to me, that to him alone I can look for safety,

01:39:21.015 --> 01:39:32.055
even though this be only whilst I can serve his purpose. Great God! Merciful God! Let

01:39:32.055 --> 01:39:37.655
me be calm, for out of that way lies madness indeed.

01:39:39.115 --> 01:39:46.535
I begin to get new lights on certain things which have puzzled me. Up to now I never quite

01:39:46.535 --> 01:39:55.915
knew what Shakespeare meant when he made Hamlet say, My tablets, quick, my tablets, tis meat

01:39:55.915 --> 01:40:05.495
that I put it down, etc. For now, feeling as though my own brain were unhinged, or

01:40:05.495 --> 01:40:13.635
as if the shock had come which must end in its undoing, I turn to my diary for repose.

01:40:14.535 --> 01:40:19.815
The habit of entering accurately must help to soothe me.

01:40:20.595 --> 01:40:27.135
The Count's mysterious warning frightened me at the time. It frightens me more now when

01:40:27.135 --> 01:40:33.815
I think of it, for in the future he has a fearful hold upon me. I shall fear to doubt

01:40:33.815 --> 01:40:35.255
what he may say.

01:40:37.215 --> 01:40:44.135
When I had written in my diary, and had fortunately replaced the book and pen in my pocket, I

01:40:44.135 --> 01:40:51.055
felt sleepy. The Count's warning came into my mind, but I took pleasure in disobeying

01:40:51.055 --> 01:40:59.495
it. The sense of sleep was upon me, and with it the obstinacy which sleep brings as outrider.

01:41:00.415 --> 01:41:08.615
The soft moonlight soothed, and the wide expanse without gave a sense of freedom which refreshed

01:41:08.615 --> 01:41:16.115
me. I determined not to return to-night to the gloom-haunted rooms, but to sleep here,

01:41:16.715 --> 01:41:24.835
where of old ladies had sat and sung and lived sweet lives whilst their gentle breasts were

01:41:24.835 --> 01:41:31.135
sad for their menfolk away in the midst of remorseless wars. I drew a great couch out

01:41:31.135 --> 01:41:38.115
of its place near the corner, so that as I lay I could look at the lovely view to east

01:41:38.115 --> 01:41:47.055
and south, and unthinking of and uncaring for the dust, compose myself for sleep. I

01:41:47.055 --> 01:41:56.615
suppose I must have fallen asleep. I hope so, but I fear, for all that followed was

01:41:56.615 --> 01:42:04.155
startlingly real, so real that now sitting here in the broad full sunlight of the morning

01:42:04.895 --> 01:42:14.835
I cannot in the least believe that it was all sleep. I was not alone. The room was the

01:42:14.835 --> 01:42:22.675
same, unchanged in any way since I came into it. I could see along the floor, in the brilliant

01:42:22.675 --> 01:42:29.035
moonlight, my own footsteps marked where I had disturbed the long accumulation of dust.

01:42:29.815 --> 01:42:39.175
In the moonlight opposite me were three young women, ladies by their dress and manner. I

01:42:39.175 --> 01:42:45.475
thought at the time that I must be dreaming when I saw them. They threw no shadow on the

01:42:45.475 --> 01:42:55.855
floor. They came close to me and looked at me for some time, and then whispered together.

01:42:55.855 --> 01:43:07.295
Two were dark, and had high aquiline noses, like the Count, and great, dark, piercing

01:43:07.295 --> 01:43:16.875
eyes that seemed to be almost red when contrasted with the pale yellow moon. The other was fair,

01:43:17.455 --> 01:43:25.835
as fair as can be, with great masses of golden hair and eyes like pale gold. I could not

01:43:25.855 --> 01:43:35.815
feel sapphires. I seemed somehow to know her face, and to know it in connection with some

01:43:35.815 --> 01:43:46.675
dreamy fear, but I could not recollect at the moment how or where. All three had brilliant

01:43:46.675 --> 01:43:55.415
white teeth that shone like pearls against the ruby of their voluptuous lips.

01:43:56.315 --> 01:44:08.755
There was something about them that made me uneasy, some longing, at the same time some

01:44:08.755 --> 01:44:21.135
deadly fear. I felt in my heart a wicked, burning desire that they would kiss me with

01:44:21.135 --> 01:44:29.575
those red lips. It is not good to note this down, lest some day it should meet Mina's

01:44:29.575 --> 01:44:38.615
eyes and cause her pain, but it is the truth. They whispered together, and then they all

01:44:38.615 --> 01:44:47.595
three laughed. Such a silvery musical laugh, but as hard as though the sound never could

01:44:47.595 --> 01:44:56.875
have come through the softness of human lips. It was like the intolerable, tingling sweetness

01:44:56.875 --> 01:45:05.975
of water-glasses when played on by a cunning hand. The fair girl shook her head coquettishly,

01:45:06.155 --> 01:45:10.815
and the other two urged her on. One said,

01:45:11.375 --> 01:45:18.755
Go on. You are the first. We shall follow. Yours is the right to begin.

01:45:19.835 --> 01:45:27.995
The other added, He is young and strong. There are kisses for us all.

01:45:29.555 --> 01:45:39.335
I lay quiet, looking out from under my eyelashes in an agony of delightful anticipation. The

01:45:39.335 --> 01:45:47.955
fair girl advanced and bent over me till I could feel the movement of her breath upon

01:45:47.955 --> 01:45:56.335
me. Sweet it was in one sense, honey sweet, and

01:45:56.335 --> 01:46:05.535
sent the same tingling through the nerves as her voice, but with a bitter underlying

01:46:05.535 --> 01:46:13.415
the sweet, a bitter offensiveness as one smells in blood.

01:46:14.935 --> 01:46:23.855
I was afraid to raise my eyelids, but looked out and saw perfectly under the lashes. The

01:46:23.855 --> 01:46:35.515
girl went on her knees and bent over me, simply gloating. There was a deliberate sense of

01:46:36.855 --> 01:46:48.175
voluptuousness which was both thrilling and repulsive, and as she arched her neck she

01:46:48.175 --> 01:46:56.935
actually licked her lips like an animal, till I could see in the moonlight the moisture

01:46:56.935 --> 01:47:05.515
shining on the scarlet lips and on the red tongue as it lapped the white lips.

01:47:05.535 --> 01:47:17.575
Sweet, sharp teeth. Lower and lower went her head as the lips went below the range of my

01:47:17.575 --> 01:47:24.195
mouth and chin and seemed to fasten on my throat.

01:47:26.675 --> 01:47:35.515
Then she paused, and I could hear the churning sound of her tongue as it licked her lips

01:47:36.395 --> 01:47:42.955
and teeth, and I could feel the hot breath on my neck.

01:47:44.555 --> 01:47:55.695
Then the skin of my throat began to tingle as one's flesh does when the hand that is

01:47:55.695 --> 01:48:05.515
to tickle it approaches nearer, nearer. I could feel the soft, shivering touch of her

01:48:06.175 --> 01:48:21.515
lips on the super-sensitive skin of my throat, and the hard dents of two sharp teeth just

01:48:21.515 --> 01:48:35.515
touching and pausing there. I closed my eyes in languorous ecstasy, and when I saw her

01:48:35.535 --> 01:48:47.655
I waited, waited with beating heart. But at that instant another sensation swept through

01:48:47.655 --> 01:48:56.175
me as quick as lightning. I was conscious of the presence of the Count and of his being

01:48:56.175 --> 01:49:05.515
as if I lapped in a storm of fury. As my eyes opened involuntarily I saw something

01:49:05.535 --> 01:49:14.935
his strong hand grasp the slender neck of the fair woman, and with giant's power drawed

01:49:14.935 --> 01:49:24.295
back, the blue eyes transformed with fury, the white teeth champing with rage, and the

01:49:24.295 --> 01:49:33.775
fair cheeks blazing red with passion. But the Count, never did I imagine such wrath

01:49:33.775 --> 01:49:43.755
and fury even to the demons of the pit. His eyes were positively blazing. The red light

01:49:43.755 --> 01:49:54.075
in them was lurid as if the flames of hell-fire blazed behind them. His face was deathly pale,

01:49:54.815 --> 01:50:03.535
and the lines of it were hard like drawn wires. The thick eyebrows that met over the nose

01:50:04.215 --> 01:50:13.275
now seemed like a heaving bar of white-hot metal. With a fierce sweep of his arm he hurled

01:50:13.275 --> 01:50:18.775
the woman from him, and then motioned to the others as though he were beating them back.

01:50:19.595 --> 01:50:27.475
It was the same imperious gesture that I had seen used to the wolves, in a voice which

01:50:27.475 --> 01:50:34.235
though low and almost in a whisper seemed to cut through the air and then ring in the

01:50:34.235 --> 01:50:48.375
room, he said, How dare you touch him, any of you! How dare you cast eyes on him when

01:50:48.375 --> 01:50:57.455
I have forbidden it! Back, I tell you all! This man is not a wolf. He is not a wolf.

01:50:57.475 --> 01:51:09.215
This man belongs to me. Beware how you meddle with him, or you'll have to deal with me.

01:51:10.355 --> 01:51:21.795
The fair girl, with a laugh of ribald coquetry, turned to answer him, You yourself never loved,

01:51:21.795 --> 01:51:31.595
you never love. On this the other women joined, and such a mirthless, hard, soulless laughter

01:51:31.595 --> 01:51:39.915
rang through the room that it almost made me faint to hear. It seemed like the pleasure

01:51:39.915 --> 01:51:48.815
of fiends. Then the count turned, after looking at my face attentively and said in a soft

01:51:48.815 --> 01:52:05.815
whisper, Yes, I too can love. You yourselves can tell it from the past. Is it not so? Well,

01:52:06.395 --> 01:52:15.255
now I promise you that when I am done with him, you shall kiss him at your will. Now

01:52:15.255 --> 01:52:23.575
go, go! I must have vacant him, for there is work to be done.

01:52:25.335 --> 01:52:33.895
Are we to have nothing tonight? said one of them, with a low laugh, as she pointed to

01:52:33.895 --> 01:52:40.815
the bag which he had thrown upon the floor, and which moved as though there were some

01:52:40.815 --> 01:52:48.735
living thing within it. For answer he nodded his head. One of the women jumped forward

01:52:48.735 --> 01:53:00.815
and opened it. If my ears did not deceive me, there was a gasp and a low wail as of

01:53:00.815 --> 01:53:09.815
a half-smothered child. The women closed round, whilst I was aghast with horror.

01:53:11.075 --> 01:53:21.035
But as I looked, they disappeared, and with them that dreadful bag. There was no door

01:53:21.035 --> 01:53:28.255
near them, and they could not have passed me without my noticing. They simply seemed

01:53:28.975 --> 01:53:36.195
to fade into the rays of the moonlight and pass out through the window, for I could see

01:53:36.195 --> 01:53:47.235
outside the dim, shadowy forms for a moment, before they entirely faded away. Then the

01:53:47.235 --> 01:53:53.115
horror overcame me, and I sank down, unconscious.

01:54:25.350 --> 01:54:27.830
Jonathan Harker's Journal Continued

01:55:46.790 --> 01:55:48.570
18th of May

01:56:15.910 --> 01:56:17.730
19th of May

01:57:58.050 --> 01:57:59.090
19th of May

01:58:10.590 --> 01:58:15.810
There is a chance of escape, or at any rate of being able to send word home.

01:58:16.550 --> 01:58:20.330
A band of Sagani have come to the castle and are encamped in the courtyard.

01:58:20.970 --> 01:58:24.930
These are gypsies. I have notes of them in my book.

01:58:25.910 --> 01:58:30.370
They are peculiar to this part of the world, though allied to the ordinary gypsies all the

01:58:30.370 --> 01:58:37.070
world over. There are thousands of them in Hungary and Transylvania who are almost outside all law.

01:58:38.170 --> 01:58:44.010
They attach themselves as a rule to some great noble or boyar and call themselves by his name.

01:58:44.810 --> 01:58:48.690
They are fearless and without religion, save superstition,

01:58:49.070 --> 01:58:52.190
and they talk only their own varieties of the Romani tongue.

01:58:53.750 --> 01:58:57.470
I shall write some letters home and shall try to get them to have them posted.

01:58:58.210 --> 01:59:01.450
I have already spoken to them through my window to begin acquaintanceship.

01:59:02.270 --> 01:59:06.070
They took their hats off and made obeisance and many signs,

01:59:06.450 --> 01:59:10.430
which however I could not understand any more than I could their spoken language.

01:59:12.670 --> 01:59:19.810
I have written the letters. Minas is in shorthand and I simply ask Mr. Hawkins to communicate with

01:59:19.810 --> 01:59:25.950
her. To her I have explained my situation, but without the horrors which I may only surmise.

01:59:27.070 --> 01:59:31.610
It would shock and frighten her to death were I to expose my heart to her.

01:59:32.690 --> 01:59:38.430
Should the letters not carry, then the Count shall not yet know my secret or the extent of my

01:59:38.430 --> 01:59:45.930
knowledge. I have given the letters. I threw them through the bars of my window with a gold

01:59:45.930 --> 01:59:51.010
piece and made what signs I could to have them posted. The man who took them pressed them to his

01:59:51.010 --> 01:59:58.190
heart and bowed and then put them in his cap. I could do no more. I stole back to the study

01:59:58.190 --> 02:00:03.230
and began to read. As the Count did not come in, I have written here,

02:00:04.670 --> 02:00:11.290
The Count has come. He sat down beside me and said in his smoothest voice as he opened two letters,

02:00:12.330 --> 02:00:19.150
The Sagani has given me these, of which though I know not whence they come, I shall of course

02:00:19.150 --> 02:00:27.470
take care. See, he must have looked at it. One is from you and to my friend Peter Hawkins.

02:00:28.310 --> 02:00:32.630
The other, here he caught sight of the strange symbols as he opened the envelope,

02:00:33.230 --> 02:00:37.310
and the dark look came into his face and his eyes blazed wickedly.

02:00:38.690 --> 02:00:46.610
The other is a vile thing, an outrage upon friendship and hospitality. It is not signed.

02:00:48.190 --> 02:00:54.310
Well, so it cannot matter to us. And he calmly held letter and envelope

02:00:54.310 --> 02:00:57.430
in the flame of the lamp till they were consumed.

02:00:58.630 --> 02:01:06.190
Then he went on. The letter to Hawkins that I shall, of course, send on since it is yours.

02:01:07.210 --> 02:01:13.890
Your letters are sacred to me. Your pardon, my friend, that unknowingly I did break the seal.

02:01:14.630 --> 02:01:21.550
Will you not cover it again? He held out the letter to me and with a courteous bow handed me

02:01:21.550 --> 02:01:27.070
a clean envelope. I could only redirect it and hand it to him in silence.

02:01:27.690 --> 02:01:31.070
When he went out of the room I could hear the key turn softly.

02:01:32.070 --> 02:01:35.510
A minute later I went over and tried it, and the door was locked.

02:01:37.290 --> 02:01:41.210
When, an hour or two after, the Count came quietly into the room,

02:01:41.690 --> 02:01:47.350
his coming awakened me, for I had gone to sleep on the sofa. He was very courteous and very

02:01:47.350 --> 02:01:50.810
cheery in his manner, and seeing that I had been sleeping he said,

02:01:51.370 --> 02:01:57.750
So, my friend, you are tired. Get to bed. There is the surest rest.

02:01:58.970 --> 02:02:04.150
I may not have the pleasure of talk tonight, since there are many labours to me.

02:02:04.930 --> 02:02:06.990
But you will sleep, I pray.

02:02:08.770 --> 02:02:14.270
I passed to my room and went to bed, and, strange to say, slept without dreaming.

02:02:15.630 --> 02:02:17.290
Despair has its own calms.

02:02:22.090 --> 02:02:26.230
This morning when I woke I thought I would provide myself with some papers and envelopes

02:02:26.230 --> 02:02:31.050
from my bag and keep them in my pocket, so that I might write in case I should get an opportunity.

02:02:31.830 --> 02:02:40.210
But again, a surprise. Again, a shock. Every scrap of paper was gone, and with it all my notes,

02:02:40.530 --> 02:02:45.390
my memoranda, relating to railways and travel, my letter of credit, in fact all that might be

02:02:45.390 --> 02:02:47.270
useful to me were I once outside the castle. I was in a hurry to go to bed, and I had been

02:02:47.270 --> 02:02:54.350
in the castle. I sat and pondered a while, and then some thought occurred to me, and I made

02:02:54.350 --> 02:03:00.610
search of my portmanteau and in the wardrobe where I had placed my clothes. The suit in which I had

02:03:00.610 --> 02:03:06.830
travelled was gone, and also my overcoat and rug. I could find no trace of them anywhere.

02:03:07.950 --> 02:03:10.790
This looked like some new scheme of villainy.

02:03:13.670 --> 02:03:14.750
17th of June

02:03:16.290 --> 02:03:22.170
This morning as I was sitting on the edge of my bed, cudgeling my brains, I heard without

02:03:22.170 --> 02:03:26.890
a crackling of whips and pounding and scraping of horses' feet up the rocky path beyond the

02:03:26.890 --> 02:03:33.470
courtyard. With joy I hurried to the window and saw drive into the yard two great lighter wagons,

02:03:33.830 --> 02:03:39.990
each drawn by eight sturdy horses, and at the head of each pair a Slovak, with his wide hat,

02:03:39.990 --> 02:03:46.790
great nail-studded belt, dirty sheepskin and high boots. They had also their long staves in hand.

02:03:48.010 --> 02:03:52.690
I ran to the door intending to descend and try to join them through the main hall,

02:03:53.090 --> 02:03:59.770
as I thought that way might be opened for them. Again a shock, my door was fastened on the outside.

02:04:02.010 --> 02:04:06.530
Then I ran to the window and cried to them. They looked up at me stupidly and pointed,

02:04:06.530 --> 02:04:11.930
but just then the hat man of the Tsigani came out and, seeing them pointing to my window,

02:04:12.250 --> 02:04:14.650
said something, at which they laughed.

02:04:16.850 --> 02:04:23.150
Henceforth no effort of mine, no piteous cry or agonized entreaty, would make them even look at

02:04:23.150 --> 02:04:30.010
me. They resolutely turned away. The lighter wagons contained great square boxes with handles of

02:04:30.010 --> 02:04:34.590
thick rope. These were evidently empty by the ease with which the Slovaks handled them,

02:04:34.590 --> 02:04:39.910
and by their resonance when they were roughly moved. When they were all unloaded and packed

02:04:39.910 --> 02:04:44.590
in a great heap in one corner of the yard, the Slovaks were given some money by the Tsigani,

02:04:45.150 --> 02:04:49.310
and, spitting on it for luck, lazily went each to his horse's head.

02:04:50.330 --> 02:04:54.110
Shortly afterwards I heard the crackling of their whips die away in the distance.

02:04:57.350 --> 02:05:03.210
24th of June. Last night the Count left me early and locked himself into his own room.

02:05:03.850 --> 02:05:08.490
As soon as I dared I ran up the winding stair and looked out of the window, which opened south.

02:05:09.230 --> 02:05:12.210
I thought I would watch for the Count, for there is something going on.

02:05:13.050 --> 02:05:17.170
The Tsigani are quartered somewhere in the castle and are doing work of some kind.

02:05:17.670 --> 02:05:23.890
I know it, for now and then I hear a far away muffled sound as of matic and spade,

02:05:24.170 --> 02:05:28.970
and whatever it is, it must be the end of some ruthless villainy.

02:05:29.510 --> 02:05:34.550
I had been at the window somewhat less than half an hour when I saw something coming out

02:05:34.550 --> 02:05:40.910
of the Count's window. I drew back and watched carefully, and saw the whole man emerge.

02:05:42.110 --> 02:05:47.130
It was a new shock to me to find that he had on the suit of clothes which I had worn whilst

02:05:47.130 --> 02:05:52.510
travelling here, and slung over his shoulder the terrible bag which I had seen the women take away.

02:05:53.330 --> 02:05:57.370
There could be no doubt as to his quest, and in my garb too.

02:05:58.150 --> 02:06:03.810
This then is his new scheme of evil, that he will allow others to see me as they think,

02:06:04.110 --> 02:06:07.970
so that he may both leave evidence that I have been seen in the towns or villages,

02:06:08.290 --> 02:06:13.810
posting my own letters, and that any wickedness which he may do shall by the local people be

02:06:13.810 --> 02:06:20.810
attributed to me. It makes me rage to think that this can go on, and whilst I am shut up here,

02:06:21.230 --> 02:06:27.350
a veritable prisoner, but without that protection of the law which is even a

02:06:28.030 --> 02:06:32.770
I thought I would watch for the Count's return, and for a long time sat doggedly at the window.

02:06:33.870 --> 02:06:37.770
Then I began to notice that there were some quaint little specks floating in the rays of

02:06:37.770 --> 02:06:43.990
the moonlight. They were like the tiniest grains of dust, and they whirled round and gathered in

02:06:43.990 --> 02:06:51.070
clusters in a nebulous sort of way. I watched them with a sense of soothing, and a sort of

02:06:51.070 --> 02:06:57.050
calm stole over me. I leaned back in the embrasure in a more comfortable position,

02:06:57.350 --> 02:07:00.510
so that I could enjoy more fully the aerial gambling.

02:07:03.190 --> 02:07:08.630
Something made me start up, a low, piteous howling of dogs somewhere far below in the valley,

02:07:09.150 --> 02:07:14.730
which was hidden from my sight. Louder it seemed to ring in my ears, and the floating motes of dust

02:07:14.730 --> 02:07:20.570
take new shapes to the sound as they danced in the moonlight. I felt myself struggling to awake to

02:07:20.570 --> 02:07:26.870
some call of my instincts. Nay, my very soul was struggling, and my half-remembered sensibilities

02:07:26.870 --> 02:07:34.610
were striving to answer the call. I was becoming hypnotized. Quicker and quicker danced the dust.

02:07:35.350 --> 02:07:39.270
The moonbeams seemed to quiver as they went by me into the mass of gloom beyond.

02:07:40.230 --> 02:07:43.430
More and more they gathered till they seemed to take dim phantom shapes.

02:07:44.070 --> 02:07:50.230
And then I started, broad awake, in full possession of my senses, and ran screaming from the place.

02:07:51.750 --> 02:07:56.130
The phantom shapes which were becoming gradually materialized from the moonbeams

02:07:56.130 --> 02:07:59.610
were those three ghostly women to whom I was doomed.

02:08:01.250 --> 02:08:05.030
I fled and felt somewhat safer in my own room where there was no moonlight

02:08:05.030 --> 02:08:07.090
and where the lamp was burning brightly.

02:08:09.370 --> 02:08:14.410
When a couple of hours had passed, I heard something stirring in the Count's room,

02:08:14.930 --> 02:08:22.850
something like a sharp wail quickly suppressed. And then there was silence, deep, awful silence,

02:08:22.850 --> 02:08:28.870
which chilled me. With a beating heart, I tried the door, but I was locked in my

02:08:28.870 --> 02:08:33.330
prison and could do nothing. I sat down and simply cried.

02:08:35.350 --> 02:08:40.210
As I sat, I heard a sound in the courtyard without, the agonized cry of a woman.

02:08:41.110 --> 02:08:44.590
I rushed to the window, and throwing it up, peered between the bars.

02:08:46.750 --> 02:08:51.010
There, indeed, was a woman with disheveled hair, holding her hands over her heart,

02:08:51.010 --> 02:08:56.030
as one distressed with running. She was leaning against the corner of the gateway.

02:08:57.210 --> 02:09:01.290
When she saw my face at the window, she threw herself forward and shouted in a voice

02:09:01.290 --> 02:09:07.690
laden with menace, Monster, give me my child. She threw herself on her knees,

02:09:08.050 --> 02:09:11.850
and raising up her hands, cried the same words in tones which rung my heart.

02:09:12.910 --> 02:09:17.130
Then she tore her hair and beat her breast and abandoned herself to all the violences

02:09:17.130 --> 02:09:22.990
of extravagant emotion. Finally she threw herself forward, and though I could not see her,

02:09:23.410 --> 02:09:26.310
I could hear the beating of her naked hands against the door.

02:09:27.930 --> 02:09:34.190
Somewhere high overhead, probably on the tower, I heard the voice of the count calling in his harsh

02:09:34.190 --> 02:09:40.590
metallic whisper. His call seemed to be answered from far and wide by the howling of wolves.

02:09:41.950 --> 02:09:46.890
Before many minutes had passed, a pack of them poured like a pent-up dam when liberated,

02:09:46.890 --> 02:09:52.850
through the wide entrance into the courtyard. There was no cry from the woman,

02:09:53.410 --> 02:10:00.690
and the howling of the wolves was but short. Before long they streamed away singly, licking their lips.

02:10:03.210 --> 02:10:09.770
I could not pity her, for I knew now what had become of her child, and she was better dead.

02:10:11.470 --> 02:10:20.290
What shall I do? What can I do? How can I escape from this dreadful thing of night, gloom, and fear?

02:10:23.210 --> 02:10:24.470
25th of June

02:10:26.090 --> 02:10:29.290
No man knows till he has suffered from the night

02:10:29.290 --> 02:10:33.130
how sweet and dear to his heart and eye the morning can be.

02:10:34.330 --> 02:10:39.010
When the sun grew so high this morning that it struck the top of the great gateway opposite my

02:10:39.010 --> 02:10:44.970
window, the high spot which it touched seemed to me as if the dove from the ark had lighted there.

02:10:46.170 --> 02:10:50.910
My fear fell from me as if it had been a vaporous garment which dissolved in the warmth.

02:10:52.490 --> 02:10:56.410
I must take action of some sort whilst the courage of the day is upon me.

02:10:56.790 --> 02:11:02.010
Last night one of my post-dated letters went to post, the first of that fatal series which is to

02:11:02.010 --> 02:11:08.510
blot out the very traces of my existence from the earth. Let me not think of it. Action.

02:11:09.910 --> 02:11:15.710
It has always been at night time that I've been molested or threatened or in some way in danger or in fear.

02:11:16.990 --> 02:11:22.630
I have not yet seen the count in the daylight. Can it be that he sleeps when others wake?

02:11:23.530 --> 02:11:28.970
That he may be awake whilst they sleep? If I could only get into his room.

02:11:30.150 --> 02:11:35.050
But there is no possible way. The door is always locked. No way for me.

02:11:36.690 --> 02:11:46.210
Yes, there is a way, if one dares to take it. Where his body has gone, why may not another body go?

02:11:47.190 --> 02:11:53.330
I have seen him myself crawl from his window. Why should not I imitate him and go in by his window?

02:11:54.930 --> 02:11:58.670
The chances are desperate, but my need is more desperate still.

02:11:59.310 --> 02:12:05.470
I shall risk it. At the worst, it can only be death. And a man's death is not a calf's.

02:12:06.270 --> 02:12:11.470
And the dreaded hereafter may still be open to me. God help me in my task.

02:12:12.950 --> 02:12:17.830
Goodbye, Mina, if I fail. Goodbye, my faithful friend and second father.

02:12:19.010 --> 02:12:22.970
Goodbye, all, and last of all, Mina.

02:12:25.410 --> 02:12:32.990
Same day, later. I have made the effort, and, God helping me, have come safely back to this room.

02:12:33.730 --> 02:12:45.150
I must put down every detail in order. I went whilst my courage was fresh, straight to the window on the south side, and at once got outside on this side.

02:12:45.910 --> 02:12:51.050
The stones are big and roughly cut, and the mortar has by process of time been washed away between them.

02:12:51.830 --> 02:12:55.210
I took off my boots and ventured out on the desperate way.

02:12:56.830 --> 02:13:06.270
I looked down once, so as to make sure that a sudden glimpse of the awful depth would not overcome me, but after that kept my eyes away from it.

02:13:07.150 --> 02:13:16.070
I know pretty well the direction and distance of the Count's window, and made for it as well as I could, having regard to the opportunities available.

02:13:16.850 --> 02:13:27.450
I did not feel dizzy, I suppose I was too excited, and the time seemed ridiculously short, till I found myself standing on the windowsill and trying to raise up the sash.

02:13:28.650 --> 02:13:33.690
I was filled with agitation, however, when I bent down and slid feet foremost in through the window.

02:13:34.530 --> 02:13:39.790
Then I looked around for the Count, but with surprise and gladness made a discovery.

02:13:40.790 --> 02:13:47.630
The room was empty. It was barely furnished with odd things which seemed to have never been used.

02:13:49.690 --> 02:13:54.090
The furniture was something the same style as that in the south rooms, and was covered with dust.

02:13:55.130 --> 02:13:59.030
I looked for the key, but it was not in the lock, and I could not find it anywhere.

02:14:00.350 --> 02:14:05.230
The only thing I found was a great heap of gold in one corner, gold of all kinds.

02:14:05.790 --> 02:14:13.910
Roman, and British, and Austrian, and Hungarian, and Greek, and Turkish money, covered with a film of dust as though it had lain long on the ground.

02:14:15.110 --> 02:14:18.090
None of it that I noticed was less than 300 years old.

02:14:19.010 --> 02:14:24.030
There were also chains and ornaments, some jeweled, but all of them old and stained.

02:14:25.550 --> 02:14:27.570
At one corner of the room was a heavy door.

02:14:28.190 --> 02:14:34.370
I tried it, for since I could not find the key of the room or the key of the outer door, which was the main object of my search,

02:14:34.370 --> 02:14:39.390
I must make further examination, or all my efforts would be in vain.

02:14:40.490 --> 02:14:46.430
It was open, and led through a stone passage to a circular stairway which went steeply down.

02:14:47.870 --> 02:14:54.910
I descended, minding carefully where I went, for the stairs were dark, being only lit by loopholes in the heavy masonry.

02:14:55.910 --> 02:15:01.050
At the bottom there was a dark, tunnel-like passage through which came a deathly,

02:15:01.050 --> 02:15:04.890
sickly odor, the odor of old earth newly turned.

02:15:06.190 --> 02:15:09.310
As I went through the passage the smell grew closer and heavier.

02:15:11.030 --> 02:15:19.550
At last I pulled open a heavy door which stood ajar, and found myself in an old ruined chapel, which had evidently been used as a graveyard.

02:15:21.070 --> 02:15:25.130
The roof was broken, and in two places were steps leading to vaults,

02:15:25.130 --> 02:15:29.470
but the ground had recently been dug over, and the earth placed in great wooden boxes.

02:15:30.310 --> 02:15:33.190
Manifestly those which had been brought by the Slovaks.

02:15:34.570 --> 02:15:39.670
There was nobody about, and I made a search over every inch of the ground so as not to lose a chance.

02:15:40.730 --> 02:15:46.970
I went down even into the vaults, where the dim light struggled, although to do so was a dread to my very soul.

02:15:48.370 --> 02:15:54.030
Into two of these I went, but saw nothing except fragments of old coffins and piles of dust.

02:15:54.990 --> 02:15:57.990
In the third, however, I made a discovery.

02:15:59.650 --> 02:16:07.770
There, in one of the great boxes, of which there were fifty in all, on a pile of newly dug earth, lay the Count.

02:16:08.790 --> 02:16:10.690
He was either dead or asleep.

02:16:11.450 --> 02:16:17.650
I could not say which, for eyes were open and stony, but without the glassiness of death,

02:16:18.250 --> 02:16:21.630
and the cheeks had the warmth of life through all their pallor.

02:16:22.430 --> 02:16:24.470
The lips were as red as ever,

02:16:25.130 --> 02:16:29.090
but there was no sign of movement, no pulse, no breath.

02:16:29.550 --> 02:16:31.010
No beating of the heart.

02:16:32.570 --> 02:16:35.750
I bent over him and tried to find any sign of life, but in vain.

02:16:36.970 --> 02:16:41.250
He could not have lain there long, for the earthy smell would have passed away in a few hours.

02:16:42.410 --> 02:16:46.430
By the side of the box was its cover, pierced with holes here and there.

02:16:47.690 --> 02:16:52.110
I thought he might have the keys on him, but when I went to search I saw the dead eyes,

02:16:52.570 --> 02:16:54.770
and in them dead, though they were,

02:16:55.470 --> 02:16:56.890
such look of hate.

02:16:57.590 --> 02:17:03.590
Though unconscious of me or my presence, that I fled from the place, and leaving the Count's room by the window,

02:17:04.270 --> 02:17:05.930
crawled again up the castle wall.

02:17:07.170 --> 02:17:10.870
Regaining my room, I threw myself panting upon the bed and tried to think.

02:17:13.850 --> 02:17:14.810
29th of June.

02:17:16.210 --> 02:17:20.690
Today is the date of my last letter, and the Count has taken steps to prove that it was genuine,

02:17:20.970 --> 02:17:24.810
for again I saw him leave the castle by the same window and in my clothes.

02:17:25.530 --> 02:17:32.650
As he went down the wall, lizard fashion, I wished I had a gun or some lethal weapon that I might destroy him.

02:17:33.970 --> 02:17:39.270
But I fear that no weapon wrought along by man's hand would have any effect upon him.

02:17:40.270 --> 02:17:44.210
I dared not wait to see him return, for I feared to see those weird sisters.

02:17:45.150 --> 02:17:49.190
I came back to the library and read there till I fell asleep.

02:17:51.430 --> 02:17:53.190
I was awakened by the Count,

02:17:53.910 --> 02:17:57.390
who looked at me as grimly as a man could look, as he said,

02:17:58.650 --> 02:18:01.590
Tomorrow, my friend, we must part.

02:18:02.810 --> 02:18:05.170
You return to your beautiful England,

02:18:05.910 --> 02:18:09.990
eye to some work which may have such an end that we may never meet.

02:18:11.090 --> 02:18:13.350
Your letter home has been dispatched.

02:18:14.190 --> 02:18:16.110
Tomorrow I shall not be here,

02:18:16.470 --> 02:18:18.670
but all shall be ready for your journey.

02:18:19.490 --> 02:18:23.910
In the morning come the Sagani, who have some labors of their own here,

02:18:24.190 --> 02:18:26.530
and also come some Slovaks.

02:18:27.190 --> 02:18:30.390
When they have gone, my carriage shall come for you,

02:18:30.530 --> 02:18:32.670
and shall bear you to the Borgo Pass

02:18:32.670 --> 02:18:36.110
to meet the diligence from Bokovena to Bistritz.

02:18:37.470 --> 02:18:41.530
But I am in hopes that I shall see more of you at Castle Dracula.

02:18:42.990 --> 02:18:46.530
I suspected him and determined to test his sincerity.

02:18:48.190 --> 02:18:52.290
Sincerity seems like a profanation of the word to write it in connection with such a monster,

02:18:52.330 --> 02:18:53.730
so I asked him point-blank.

02:18:55.110 --> 02:18:56.630
Why may I not go tonight?

02:18:58.270 --> 02:19:02.590
Because, dear sir, my coachmen and horses are away on a mission.

02:19:03.850 --> 02:19:06.990
But I would walk with pleasure. I want to get away at once.

02:19:08.210 --> 02:19:11.610
He smiled such a soft, smooth diabolical smile

02:19:11.610 --> 02:19:14.710
that I knew there was some trick behind his smoothness.

02:19:15.350 --> 02:19:16.050
He said,

02:19:16.790 --> 02:19:17.810
And your baggage?

02:19:18.690 --> 02:19:21.930
I do not care about it. I can send for it some other time.

02:19:23.170 --> 02:19:28.650
The Count stood up and said, with a sweet courtesy which made me rub my eyes, it seems so real,

02:19:30.110 --> 02:19:33.810
You English have a saying which is close to my heart,

02:19:34.210 --> 02:19:36.670
for its spirit is that which rules our boyars.

02:19:37.690 --> 02:19:40.810
Welcome the coming. Speed the parting guest.

02:19:42.490 --> 02:19:44.110
Come with me, my dear young friend.

02:19:44.110 --> 02:19:47.450
Not an hour shall you wait in my house against your will,

02:19:47.910 --> 02:19:51.730
though sad am I at your going, and that you so suddenly desire it.

02:19:52.410 --> 02:19:52.810
Come.

02:19:54.150 --> 02:19:58.710
With a stately gravity he, with the lamp, proceeded me down the stairs and along the hall.

02:19:59.970 --> 02:20:00.990
Suddenly he stopped.

02:20:02.050 --> 02:20:02.430
Hark!

02:20:04.530 --> 02:20:06.890
Close at hand came the howling of many wolves.

02:20:07.490 --> 02:20:10.670
It was almost as if the sounds sprang up at the rising of his hand,

02:20:10.670 --> 02:20:14.630
just as the music of a great orchestra seems to leap under the baton of the conductor.

02:20:16.070 --> 02:20:20.530
After a pause of a moment he proceeded in his stately way to the door,

02:20:21.110 --> 02:20:26.170
drew back the ponderous bolts, unhooked the heavy chains, and began to draw it open.

02:20:27.690 --> 02:20:31.030
To my intense astonishment I saw that it was unlocked.

02:20:32.350 --> 02:20:36.150
Suspiciously I looked all around, but could see no key of any kind.

02:20:37.730 --> 02:20:42.850
As the door began to open, the howling of the wolves without grew louder and angrier.

02:20:43.410 --> 02:20:48.050
Their red jaws with champing teeth, and their blunt clawed feet as they leaped,

02:20:48.370 --> 02:20:49.790
came in through the opening door.

02:20:50.790 --> 02:20:54.070
I knew then that to struggle at the moment against the Count was useless.

02:20:54.590 --> 02:20:57.850
With such allies as these at his command, I could do nothing.

02:20:58.650 --> 02:21:03.090
But still the door continued slowly to open, and only the Count's body stood in a gap.

02:21:04.230 --> 02:21:07.410
Suddenly it struck me that this might be the moment and means of my doom.

02:21:08.050 --> 02:21:11.570
I was to be given to the wolves, and at my own instigation.

02:21:13.050 --> 02:21:16.270
There was a diabolical wickedness in the idea great enough for the Count,

02:21:17.070 --> 02:21:18.630
and as the last chance I cried out,

02:21:19.390 --> 02:21:21.530
Shut the door! I shall wait till morning!

02:21:22.550 --> 02:21:26.350
And I covered my face with my hands to hide my tears of bitter disappointment.

02:21:28.230 --> 02:21:31.790
With one sweep of his powerful arm, the Count threw the door shut,

02:21:31.790 --> 02:21:36.510
and the great bolts clanged and echoed through the hall as they shot back into their places.

02:21:38.370 --> 02:21:42.610
In silence we returned to the library, and after a minute or two I went to my own room.

02:21:44.090 --> 02:21:48.630
The last I saw of Count Dracula was his kissing his hand to me,

02:21:48.950 --> 02:21:55.070
with a red light of triumph in his eyes, and with a smile that Judas in hell might be proud of.

02:21:56.990 --> 02:22:01.610
When I was in my room and about to lie down, I thought I heard a whispering at my door.

02:22:02.750 --> 02:22:09.090
I went to it softly and listened. Unless my ears deceived me, I heard the voice of the Count.

02:22:10.490 --> 02:22:16.550
Back, back to your own place. Your time has not yet come.

02:22:18.090 --> 02:22:24.590
Wait, have patience. Tonight is mine. Tomorrow night is yours.

02:22:26.090 --> 02:22:29.950
There was a low sweet ripple of laughter, and in a rage I threw open the door,

02:22:29.950 --> 02:22:33.530
and saw without the three terrible women licking their lips.

02:22:34.670 --> 02:22:38.130
As I appeared, they all joined in a horrible laugh and ran away.

02:22:39.670 --> 02:22:46.030
I came back to my room and threw myself on my knees. It is then so near the end.

02:22:48.290 --> 02:22:52.890
Tomorrow, tomorrow. Lord, help me and those to whom I am dear.

02:22:55.090 --> 02:23:02.850
30th of June. These may be the last words I ever write in this diary. I slept till just before the

02:23:02.850 --> 02:23:08.550
dawn, and when I woke, threw myself on my knees, for I determined that if death came, he should

02:23:08.550 --> 02:23:15.830
find me ready. At last I felt that subtle change in the air, and knew that the morning had come.

02:23:17.150 --> 02:23:20.830
Then came the welcome cock crow, and I felt that I was safe.

02:23:21.990 --> 02:23:28.350
With a glad heart, I opened the door and ran down the hall. I had seen that the door was unlocked,

02:23:28.870 --> 02:23:34.630
and now escape was before me. With hands that trembled with eagerness, I unhooked the chains

02:23:34.630 --> 02:23:42.130
and threw back the massive bolts. But the door would not move. Despair seized me. I pulled and

02:23:42.130 --> 02:23:50.810
pulled at the door, and shook it till, massive as it was, it rattled in its casement. I could see the

02:23:50.810 --> 02:23:57.910
count. Then a wild desire took me to obtain the key at any risk, and I determined then and there

02:23:57.910 --> 02:24:04.710
to scale the wall again and gain the count's room. He might kill me, but death now seemed the happier

02:24:04.710 --> 02:24:10.910
choice of evils. Without a pause, I rushed up to the east window and scrambled down the wall as

02:24:10.910 --> 02:24:18.050
before, into the count's room. It was empty, but that was as I expected. I could not see a key

02:24:18.050 --> 02:24:23.210
anywhere but the heap of gold remained. I went through the door in the corner and down the

02:24:23.210 --> 02:24:29.430
winding stair and along the dark passage to the old chapel. I knew now well enough where to find

02:24:29.430 --> 02:24:36.850
the monster I sought. The great box was in the same place, close against the wall, but the lid

02:24:36.850 --> 02:24:42.190
was laid on it, not fastened down, but with the nails ready in their places to be hammered home.

02:24:43.650 --> 02:24:49.170
I knew I must reach the body for the key, so I raised the lid and laid it back against the wall,

02:24:49.750 --> 02:24:55.910
and then I saw something which filled my very soul with horror. There lay the count,

02:24:56.790 --> 02:25:03.150
but looking as if his youth had been half restored, for the white hair and mustache were changed to

02:25:03.150 --> 02:25:10.870
dark iron gray, the cheeks were fuller, and the white skin seemed ruby red underneath. The mouth

02:25:10.870 --> 02:25:15.810
was redder than ever, for on the lips were gouts of fresh blood which trickled from the corners of

02:25:15.810 --> 02:25:21.690
the mouth and ran down over the chin and neck. Even the deep burning eyes seemed set amongst

02:25:21.690 --> 02:25:26.810
swollen flesh, for the lids and pouches underneath were bloated. It seemed as if the whole awful

02:25:26.810 --> 02:25:34.390
creature was simply gorged with blood. He lay like a filthy leech, exhausted with his repletion.

02:25:35.930 --> 02:25:40.710
I shuddered as I bent over to touch him, and every sense in me revolted at the contact,

02:25:41.310 --> 02:25:48.130
but I had to search, or I was lost. The coming night might see my own body a banquet in a

02:25:48.130 --> 02:25:55.470
similar war to those horrid three. I felt all over the body, but no sign could I find of the key.

02:25:56.830 --> 02:25:59.390
Then I stopped and looked at the count.

02:26:00.930 --> 02:26:07.390
There was a mocking smile on the bloated face which seemed to drive me mad. This was the being

02:26:07.390 --> 02:26:13.310
I was helping to transfer to London, where perhaps for centuries to come he might, amongst his

02:26:13.310 --> 02:26:19.210
teeming millions, satiate his lust for blood and create a new and ever-widening circle of semi-demons

02:26:19.210 --> 02:26:29.370
to batten on the helpless. The very thought drove me mad. A terrible desire came upon me to rid the

02:26:29.370 --> 02:26:35.130
shovel which the workmen had been using to fill the cases, and lifting it high, struck with the

02:26:35.130 --> 02:26:42.050
edge downward at the hateful face. But as I did so, the head turned and the eyes fell upon me with

02:26:42.050 --> 02:26:48.130
all their blaze of basilisk horror. The sight seemed to paralyze me, and the shovel turned in

02:26:48.130 --> 02:26:54.850
my hand and glanced from my face, merely making a deep gash above the forehead. The shovel fell

02:26:54.850 --> 02:26:59.350
from my hand across the box, and as I pulled it away, the flange of the blade caught the edge of

02:26:59.350 --> 02:27:05.910
the lid which fell over again and hid the horrid thing from my sight. The last glimpse I had was

02:27:05.910 --> 02:27:12.270
of the bloated face, blood-stained and fixed with a grin of malice which would have held its own in

02:27:12.270 --> 02:27:19.690
the nethermost hell. I thought and thought what should be my next move, but my brain seemed on

02:27:19.690 --> 02:27:28.150
fire, and I waited with a despairing feeling growing over me. As I waited, I heard in the

02:27:28.710 --> 02:27:32.010
through their song the rolling of heavy wheels and the cracking of whips.

02:27:33.430 --> 02:27:36.470
The sigarni and the slovaks of whom the Count had spoken were coming.

02:27:37.650 --> 02:27:42.150
With a last look around and at the box which contained the vile body, I ran from the place

02:27:42.150 --> 02:27:45.830
and gained the Count's room determined to rush out at the moment the door should be opened.

02:27:46.930 --> 02:27:51.870
With strained ears, I listened and heard downstairs the grinding of the key in the great lock

02:27:51.870 --> 02:27:57.490
and the falling back of the heavy door. There must have been some other means of entry,

02:27:57.490 --> 02:28:03.590
or someone had a key for one of the locked doors. Then there came the sound of many feet

02:28:03.590 --> 02:28:10.630
tramping and dying away in some passage which sent up a clanging echo. I turned to run down again

02:28:10.630 --> 02:28:15.310
towards the vault where I might find the new entrance, but at the moment there seemed to come

02:28:15.310 --> 02:28:20.530
a violent puff of wind and the door to the winding stair blew too with a shock that set the dust from

02:28:20.530 --> 02:28:25.910
the lintels flying. When I ran to push it open, I found that it was hopelessly fast.

02:28:26.490 --> 02:28:31.730
I was again a prisoner and the net of doom was closing around me more closely.

02:28:33.670 --> 02:28:38.530
As I write, there is in the passage below a sound of many tramping feet and the crash of

02:28:38.530 --> 02:28:43.050
weights being set down heavily, doubtless the boxes with their freight of earth.

02:28:44.150 --> 02:28:48.150
There was a sound of hammering. It is the box being nailed down.

02:28:49.290 --> 02:28:54.690
Now I can hear the heavy feet tramping again along the hall with many other idle feet coming

02:28:54.690 --> 02:29:01.990
behind them. The door is shut. The chains rattle. There is a grinding of the key in the lock.

02:29:03.130 --> 02:29:07.010
I can hear the key withdrawn, then another door opens and shuts.

02:29:07.830 --> 02:29:14.190
I hear the creaking of lock and bolt. Hark! In the courtyard and down the rocky way,

02:29:14.270 --> 02:29:19.050
the roll of heavy wheels, the crack of whips, and the chorus of the sagani as they pass into the

02:29:19.050 --> 02:29:25.610
distance. I am alone in the castle with those horrible women.

02:29:28.110 --> 02:29:32.610
Mina is a woman and there is not in common. They are devils of the pit.

02:29:34.190 --> 02:29:38.790
I shall not remain alone with them. I shall try to scale the castle wall farther than I have

02:29:38.790 --> 02:29:43.910
yet attempted. I shall take some of the gold with me lest I want it later. I may find a way from

02:29:43.910 --> 02:29:49.230
this dreadful place. And then a way for home. A way to the quickest and nearest train,

02:29:49.530 --> 02:29:54.490
away from the cursed spot, from this cursed land where the devil and his children still walk with

02:29:54.490 --> 02:30:00.470
earthly feet. At least God's mercy is better than that of those monsters and the precipice

02:30:00.470 --> 02:30:08.730
is steep and high. At its foot a man may sleep as a man. Goodbye all. Mina.

02:30:42.571 --> 02:30:47.071
LETTER FROM MISS MENA MURRAY TO MISS LUCY WESTONRAH

02:30:47.071 --> 02:30:48.271
9th of May

02:31:13.431 --> 02:31:26.651
When we are married, I shall be able to be useful to Jonathan, and if I can stenograph well enough, I can take down what he wants to say in this way, and write it out for him on the typewriter, at which also I am practicing very hard.

02:31:26.651 --> 02:31:45.011
He and I sometimes write letters in shorthand, and he is keeping a stenographic journal of his travels abroad. When I am with you, I shall keep a diary in the same way. I don't mean one of those two pages to the week with Sunday squeezed in a corner diaries, but a sort of journal which I can write in whenever I feel inclined.

02:31:45.531 --> 02:32:04.331
I do not suppose there will be much of interest to other people, but it is not intended for them. I may show it to Jonathan some day, if there is in it anything worth sharing, but it is really an exercise book. I shall try to do what I see lady journalists do, interviewing and writing descriptions, and trying to remember conversations.

02:32:04.331 --> 02:32:25.771
I am told that, with a little practice, one can remember all that goes on or that one hears said during a day. However, we shall see. I will tell you of my little plans when we meet. I have just had a few hurried lines from Jonathan from Transylvania. He is well, and will be returning in about a week. I am longing to hear all his news.

02:32:25.771 --> 02:32:46.151
It must be nice to see strange countries. I wonder if we—I mean Jonathan and I—shall ever see them together. There is the ten o'clock bell ringing. Good-bye, your loving Mina. Tell me all the news when you write. You have not told me anything for a long time. I hear rumours, and especially of a tall, handsome, curly-haired man.

02:32:48.071 --> 02:32:51.011
Letter Lucy Westenra to Mina Murray

02:32:51.011 --> 02:32:54.491
17 Chatham Street, Wednesday

02:33:21.011 --> 02:33:31.291
Someone has evidently been telling tales. That was Mr. Homewood. He often comes to see us, and he and Mama get on very well together. They have so many things to talk about in common.

02:33:31.291 --> 02:33:49.531
We met some time ago, a man that would just do for you if you were not already engaged to Jonathan. He is an excellent party, being handsome, well-off, and of good birth. He is a doctor, and really clever—just fancy. He is only nine and twenty, and he has an immense lunatic asylum all under his own care.

02:33:49.531 --> 02:34:18.491
Mr. Homewood introduced him to me, and he called here to see us, and often comes now. I think he is one of the most resolute men I ever saw, and yet the most calm. He seems absolutely imperturbable. I can fancy what a wonderful power he must have over his patience. He has a curious habit of looking one straight in the face, as if trying to read one's thoughts. He tries this on very much with me, but I flatter myself he has got a tough nut to crack. I know that from my glass.

02:34:18.491 --> 02:34:33.751
Do you ever try to read your own face? I do, and I can tell you it is not a bad study, and it gives you more trouble than you can well fancy if you have never tried it. He says that I afford him a curious psychological study, and I humbly think I do.

02:34:33.751 --> 02:34:44.631
I do not, as you know, take sufficient interest in dress to be able to describe the new fashions. Dress is a bore. That is slang again, but never mind. Arthur says that every day.

02:34:44.631 --> 02:35:09.471
There, it is all out, Mina. We have told all our secrets to each other since we were children. We have slept together and eaten together, and laughed and cried together, and now, though I have spoken, I would like to speak more. Oh, Mina, couldn't you guess? I love him. I am blushing as I write, for although I think he loves me, he has not told me so in words. But oh, Mina, I love him. I love him. There, that does me good.

02:35:09.471 --> 02:35:37.751
I wish I were with you, dear, sitting by the fire and dressing as we used to sit, and I would try to tell you what I feel. I do not know how I am writing this even to you. I am afraid to stop, or I should tear up the letter, and I don't want to stop, for I do so want to tell you all. Let me hear from you at once, and tell me all that you think about it. Mina, pray for my happiness. Lucy. P.S. I need not tell you this is a secret. Good night again, L.

02:35:39.671 --> 02:35:44.511
Letter, Lucy Westenra to Mina Murray. 24th of May.

02:35:45.851 --> 02:35:53.291
My dearest Mina, thanks and thanks and thanks again for your sweet letter. It was so nice to be able to tell you and to have your sympathy.

02:35:54.031 --> 02:36:15.771
My dear, it never rains, but it pours. How true the old Proverbs are! Here am I, who shall be twenty in September, and yet I never had a proposal till to-day, not a real proposal, and to-day I had three! Just fancy, three proposals in one day! Isn't it awful? I feel sorry, really and truly sorry, for two of the poor fellows.

02:36:15.771 --> 02:36:42.891
Oh Mina, I am so happy that I don't know what to do with myself, and three proposals! But for goodness sake, don't tell any of the girls, or they would be getting all sorts of extravagant ideas, and imagining themselves injured and slighted if in their very first day at home they did not get six at least. Some girls are so vain! You and I, Mina dear, who are engaged and are going to settle down soon soberly until old married women can despise vanity.

02:36:43.551 --> 02:37:06.991
Well, I must tell you about the three, but you must keep it a secret, dear, from everyone, except of course Jonathan. You will tell him, because I would, if I were in your place, certainly tell Arthur. A woman ought to tell her husband everything, don't you think so, dear? And I must be fair. Men like women, certainly their wives, to be quite as fair as they are, and women, I am afraid, are not always quite as fair as they should be.

02:37:07.791 --> 02:37:31.891
Well, my dear, number one came just before lunch. I told you of him, Dr. John Seward, the lunatic asylum man, with the strong jaw and the good forehead. He was very cool outwardly, but was nervous all the same. He had evidently been schooling himself as to all sorts of little things, and remembered them, but he almost managed to sit down on his silk hat, which men don't generally do when they are cool.

02:37:31.891 --> 02:37:56.171
And then when he wanted to appear at ease he kept playing with the lancet in a way that made me nearly scream. He spoke to me, Mina, very straightforwardly. He told me how dear I was to him, though he had known me so little, and what his life would be with me to help and cheer him. He was going to tell me how unhappy he would be if I did not care for him, but when he saw me cry he said he was a brute and would not add to my present trouble.

02:37:56.771 --> 02:38:15.271
Then he broke off and asked if I could love him in time, and when I shook my head his hands trembled, and then with some hesitation he asked me if I cared already for anyone else. He put it very nicely, saying that he did not want to wring my confidence from me, but only to know because if a woman's heart was free a man might have hope.

02:38:15.271 --> 02:38:32.991
And then, Mina, I felt a sort of duty to tell him that there was someone. I only told him that much. And then he stood up, and he looked very strong and very grave, as he took both my hands in his and said he hoped I would be happy, and that if I ever wanted a friend I must count him one of my best.

02:38:33.471 --> 02:38:59.331
Oh, Mina dear, I can't help crying, and you must excuse this letter being all blotted. Being proposed to is all very nice and all that sort of thing, but it isn't at all a happy thing when you have to see a poor fellow, whom you know loves you honestly, going away and looking all broken-hearted, and to know that, no matter what he may say at the moment, you are passing out of his life. My dear, I must stop here at present. I feel so miserable, though I am so happy.

02:39:27.891 --> 02:39:29.291
Evening.

02:39:43.691 --> 02:39:58.351
My dear, I am somewhat previous. Mr. Quincy P. Morris found me alone. It seems that a man always does find a girl alone. No, he doesn't, for Arthur tried twice to make a chance, and I helping him all I could, I am not ashamed to say it now.

02:39:59.331 --> 02:40:17.871
I must tell you beforehand that Mr. Morris doesn't always speak slang, that is to say, he never does so to strangers or before them, for he is really well educated and has exquisite manners, but he found out that it amused me to hear him talk American slang, and whenever I was present there was no one to be shocked, he said such funny things.

02:40:17.871 --> 02:40:33.551
I am afraid, my dear, he has to invent it all, for it fits exactly into whatever else he has to say. But this is the way slang has. I do not know myself if I shall ever speak slang. I do not know if Arthur likes it, as I have never heard him use any as yet.

02:40:34.671 --> 02:40:45.131
Well, Mr. Morris sat down beside me and looked as happy and jolly as he could, but I could see all the same that he was very nervous. He took my hand in his and said ever so sweetly.

02:40:46.291 --> 02:41:03.091
Miss Lucy, I know I ain't good enough to regulate the fixings of your little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is, you will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit. Won't you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road together, driving in double harness?

02:41:04.151 --> 02:41:17.631
Well, he did look so good-humored and so jolly that it didn't seem half so hard to refuse him as it did poor Dr. Seward. So I said, as lightly as I could, that I did not know anything of hitching, and that I wasn't broken to harness at all yet.

02:41:17.631 --> 02:41:34.711
Then he said that he had spoken in a light manner, and he hoped that if he had made a mistake in doing so on so grave, so momentous, and occasioned for him, I would forgive him. He really did look serious when he was saying it, and I couldn't help feeling a sort of exultation that he was number two in one day.

02:41:34.711 --> 02:41:59.951
And then, my dear, before I could say a word, he began pouring out a perfect torrent of love-making, laying his very heart and soul at my feet. He looked so earnest over it that I shall never again think that a man must be playful always and never earnest because he is merry at times. I suppose he saw something in my face which checked him, for he suddenly stopped and said with a sort of manly fervor that I could have loved him for if I had been free.

02:42:00.731 --> 02:42:22.091
Lucy, you are an honest-hearted girl, I know. I should not be here speaking to you as I am now if I did not believe you clean grit, right through to the very depths of your soul. Tell me, like one good fella to another, is there anyone else that you care for? And if there is, I'll never trouble you a hair's breadth again, but will be, if you will let me, a very faithful friend.

02:42:23.051 --> 02:42:47.231
My dear Mina, why are men so noble when we women are so little worthy of them? Here was I almost making fun of this great-hearted, true gentleman. I burst into tears, I am afraid, my dear, you will think this a very sloppy letter in more ways than one, and I really felt very badly. Why can't they let a girl marry three men, or as many as want her, and save all this trouble? But this is heresy, and I must not say it.

02:42:47.231 --> 02:42:59.351
I am glad to say that, though I was crying, I was able to look into Mr. Morris's brave eyes, and I told him out straight. Yes, there is someone I love, though he has not told me yet that he even loves me.

02:43:00.191 --> 02:43:09.971
I was right to speak to him so frankly, for quite a light came into his face, and he put out both his hands and took mine, I think I put them into his, and said in a hearty way,

02:43:10.671 --> 02:43:34.531
That's my brave girl. It's better worth being late for a chance of winning you than being in time for any other girl in the world. Don't cry, my dear. If it's for me, I'm a hard nut to crack, and I take it standing up. If that other fellow doesn't know his happiness, well, he'd better look for it soon, or he'll have to deal with me. Little girl, your honesty and pluck have made me a friend, and that's rarer than a lover. It's more selfish, anyhow.

02:43:34.531 --> 02:43:48.831
My dear, I'm going to have a pretty lonely walk between this and Kingdom Come. Won't you give me one kiss? It'll be something to keep off the darkness now and then. You can, you know, if you like, for that other good fellow, or you could not love him, hasn't spoken yet.

02:43:49.311 --> 02:44:14.271
That quite won me, Mina, for it was brave and sweet of him, and noble too, to a rival, wasn't it? And he so sad, so I leaned over and kissed him. He stood up with my two hands in his, and as he looked down into my face, I'm afraid I was blushing very much. He said, Little girl, I hold your hand, and you've kissed me, and if these things don't make us friends, nothing ever will. Thank you for your sweet honesty to me, and good-bye.

02:44:14.951 --> 02:44:35.531
He rung my hand, and taking up his hat, went straight out of the room without looking back, without a tear or a quiver or a pause, and I am crying like a baby. Why must a man like that be made unhappy when there are lots of girls about who would worship the very ground he trod on? I know I would if I were free, only I don't want to be free.

02:44:35.531 --> 02:44:46.951
My dear, this quite upset me, and I feel I cannot write of happiness just at once after telling you of it, and I don't wish to tell of the number three until it can be all happy. Ever your loving, Lucy.

02:44:48.031 --> 02:45:13.551
P.S. Oh, about number three, I needn't tell you of number three, need I? Besides, it was all so confused. It seemed only a moment from his coming into the room till both his arms were round me and he was kissing me. I am very, very happy, and I don't know what I have done to deserve it. I must only try in the future to show that I am not ungrateful to God for all his goodness to me in sending to me such a lover, such a husband, and such a friend. Good-bye.

02:45:15.131 --> 02:45:17.771
Dr. Seward's Diary, Captain Phonograph

02:45:17.771 --> 02:45:19.251
May 25

02:45:20.571 --> 02:45:42.471
Ebb tide and appetite today. Cannot eat, cannot rest, so diary instead. Since my rebuff of yesterday I have a sort of empty feeling. Nothing in the world seems of sufficient importance to be worth the doing. As I knew that the only cure for this sort of thing was work, I went amongst the patients. I picked out one who has afforded me a study of much interest.

02:45:42.471 --> 02:45:50.951
He is so quaint that I am determined to understand him as well as I can. Today I seem to get nearer than ever before to the heart of his mystery.

02:45:52.411 --> 02:46:09.271
I question him more fully than I had ever done, with a view to making myself master of the facts of his hallucination. In my manner of doing it there was, I now see, something of cruelty. I seem to wish to keep him to the point of his madness, a thing which I avoid with the patience as I would the mouth of hell.

02:46:11.431 --> 02:46:14.731
Memorandum. Under what circumstances would I not avoid the pit of hell?

02:46:16.171 --> 02:46:27.851
Omnia Romei Venalia sunt. Hell has its price. If there be anything behind this instinct, it would be valuable to trace it afterwards accurately, so I had better commence to do so, therefore...

02:46:27.851 --> 02:46:30.351
R. M. Renfield, age 59.

02:46:57.851 --> 02:47:12.711
When self is the fixed point, the centripetal force is balanced with the centrifugal. When duty, a cause, etc., is the fixed point, the latter force is paramount, and only accident or a series of accidents can balance it.

02:47:13.971 --> 02:47:18.871
Letter. Quincy P. Morris to Honorable Arthur Homewood. 25th of May.

02:47:19.471 --> 02:47:34.611
My dear Art, we've told yarns by the campfire and the prairies, and dressed one another's wounds after trying a landing at the Marquesas, and drunk healths on the shore of Titicaca. There are more yarns to be told, and other wounds to be healed, and other health to be drunk.

02:47:35.111 --> 02:47:44.851
Won't you let this be at my campfire tomorrow night? I have no hesitation in asking you, as I know a certain lady is engaged to a certain dinner party, and that you are free.

02:47:45.451 --> 02:48:01.811
There will only be one other, our old pal at the Correa, Jack Seward. He's coming too, and we both want to mingle our weeps over the wine cup, and to drink a health with all our hearts to the happiest man in all the wide world, who has won the noblest heart that God has made, and best worth winning.

02:48:02.331 --> 02:48:17.731
We promise you a hearty welcome, and a loving greeting, and a health as true as your own right hand. We shall both swear to leave you at home if you drink too deep to a certain pair of eyes. Come, yours as ever and always, Quincy P. Morris.

02:48:18.891 --> 02:48:23.531
Telegram from Arthur Holmwood to Quincy P. Morris. 26th of May.

02:48:24.511 --> 02:48:29.851
Count me in every time. I bear messages which will make both your ears tingle. Art.

02:49:05.891 --> 02:49:08.751
MENA MURRAY'S JOURNAL

02:49:09.751 --> 02:49:16.271
24th July. Whitby. Lucy met me at the station, looking sweeter and lovelier than ever, and

02:49:16.271 --> 02:49:21.591
we drove up to the house at the crescent in which they have rooms. This is a lovely place.

02:49:21.951 --> 02:49:26.791
The little river, the Esk, runs through a deep valley, which broadens out as it comes

02:49:26.791 --> 02:49:32.591
near the harbor. A great viaduct runs across, with high piers, through which the view seems

02:49:33.171 --> 02:49:39.391
away than it really is. The valley is beautifully green, and it is so steep that when you are

02:49:39.391 --> 02:49:44.271
on the high land on either side you look right across it, unless you are near enough to see

02:49:44.271 --> 02:49:50.291
down. The houses of the old town, the sight away from us, are all red-roofed, and seem

02:49:50.291 --> 02:49:56.531
piled up one over the other anyhow, like the pictures we see of Nuremberg. Right over the

02:49:56.531 --> 02:50:01.571
town is the ruin of Whitby Abbey, which was sacked by the Danes, and which is the scene

02:50:01.571 --> 02:50:07.331
of part of Marmion, where the girl was built up, in the wall. It is a most noble ruin,

02:50:07.471 --> 02:50:13.251
of immense size, and full of beautiful and romantic bits. There is a legend that a white

02:50:13.251 --> 02:50:18.671
lady is seen in one of the windows. Between it and the town there is another church, the

02:50:18.671 --> 02:50:24.151
parish one, round which is a big graveyard, all full of tombstones. This is, to my mind,

02:50:24.191 --> 02:50:29.451
the nicest spot in Whitby, for it lies right over the town, and has a full view of the

02:50:29.451 --> 02:50:35.251
harbour, and all up the bay to where the headland called Kettleness stretches out into the sea.

02:50:35.891 --> 02:50:41.271
It descends so steeply over the harbour that part of the bank has fallen away, and some

02:50:41.271 --> 02:50:46.831
of the graves have been destroyed. In one place part of the stonework of the graves

02:50:46.831 --> 02:50:52.911
stretches out over the sandy pathway far below. There are walks with seats beside them through

02:50:52.911 --> 02:50:57.711
the churchyard, and people go and sit there all day long, looking at the beautiful view

02:50:57.711 --> 02:51:04.331
and enjoying the breeze. I shall come and sit here often myself in work. Indeed, I am

02:51:04.331 --> 02:51:09.131
writing now, with my book on my knee, and listening to the talk of three old men who

02:51:09.131 --> 02:51:13.471
are sitting beside me. They seem to do nothing all day but sit here and talk.

02:51:14.431 --> 02:51:20.111
The harbour lies below me, with on the far side one long granite wall stretching out

02:51:20.111 --> 02:51:25.211
into the sea, with a curve outwards at the end of it, in the middle of which is a lighthouse.

02:51:25.211 --> 02:51:31.991
A heavy seawall runs along outside of it. On the near side the seawall makes an elbow

02:51:31.991 --> 02:51:38.111
crooked inversely, and its end too has a lighthouse. Between the two piers there is a narrow opening

02:51:38.111 --> 02:51:44.311
into the harbour, which then suddenly widens. It is nice at high water, but when the tide

02:51:44.311 --> 02:51:49.791
is out it shoals away to nothing, and there is merely the stream of the esk running between

02:51:49.791 --> 02:51:55.611
banks of sand with rocks here and there. Outside the harbour, on this side, there rises for

02:51:55.611 --> 02:52:00.591
about half a mile a great reef, the sharp of which runs straight out from behind the

02:52:00.591 --> 02:52:06.331
south lighthouse. At the end of it is a buoy with a bell, which swings in bad weather and

02:52:06.331 --> 02:52:11.851
sends in a mournful sound on the wind. They have a legend here that when a ship is lost

02:52:11.851 --> 02:52:17.471
bells are heard out at sea. I must ask the old man about this. He is coming this way.

02:52:18.311 --> 02:52:24.171
He is a funny old man. He must be awfully old, for his face is gnarled and twisted like

02:52:24.171 --> 02:52:29.691
the bark of a tree. He tells me that he is nearly a hundred, and that he was a sailor

02:52:29.691 --> 02:52:35.511
in the Greenland fishing fleet when Waterloo was fought. He is, I am afraid, a very sceptical

02:52:35.511 --> 02:52:40.211
person, for when I asked him about the bells at sea and the white lady at the abbey he

02:52:40.211 --> 02:52:45.951
said very brusquely, I wouldn't fash myself about them, miss. Them things we all wore

02:52:45.951 --> 02:52:51.391
out. Mind, I don't say that they never was, but I do say that they wasn't in my time.

02:52:52.191 --> 02:52:56.671
They be all very well for comers and trippers and the like, but not for a nice young lady

02:52:56.671 --> 02:53:02.591
like you. Them fit folks from York and Leeds that be always eatin' curd herons and drinkin'

02:53:02.711 --> 02:53:08.211
tea and lookin' out to buy cheap jut with creed art. I wonder myself who'll be bothered

02:53:08.211 --> 02:53:11.771
tellin' lies to them, even the newspapers, which is full of fool talk.

02:53:12.851 --> 02:53:17.511
I thought he would be a good person to learn interesting things from, so I asked him if

02:53:17.511 --> 02:53:22.351
he would mind telling me something about the whale fishing in the old days. He was just

02:53:22.351 --> 02:53:27.471
settling himself to begin when the clock struck six, whereupon he laboured to get up and

02:53:27.471 --> 02:53:27.731
said,

02:53:28.091 --> 02:53:33.031
I must be gang a greenwoods home now, miss. My grand-daughter doesn't like to be kept

02:53:33.031 --> 02:53:37.451
waitin' when the tea is ready, for it takes me time to cramble a boon the grease, for

02:53:37.451 --> 02:53:41.591
there be many of them, and miss a lack barely timbersairly by the clock.

02:53:43.091 --> 02:53:49.071
He hobbled away, and I could see him hurrying as well as he could down the steps. The steps

02:53:49.071 --> 02:53:53.751
are a great feature on the place. They lead from the town to the church. There are hundreds

02:53:53.751 --> 02:53:59.311
of them—I do not know how many—and they wind up in a delicate curve. The slope is

02:53:59.311 --> 02:54:04.811
so gentle that a horse could easily walk up and down them. I think they must originally

02:54:04.811 --> 02:54:07.031
have had something to do with the abbey.

02:54:07.531 --> 02:54:12.971
I shall go home too. Lucy went out, visiting with her mother, and as they were only duty

02:54:12.971 --> 02:54:14.531
calls I did not go.

02:54:18.551 --> 02:54:24.451
First of August. I came up here an hour ago with Lucy, and we had a most interesting talk

02:54:24.451 --> 02:54:29.331
with my old friend and the two others who always come and join him. He is evidently

02:54:29.331 --> 02:54:34.231
the Sir Oracle of them, and I should think must have been in his time a most dictatorial

02:54:34.231 --> 02:54:40.631
person. He would not admit anything and down faces everybody. If he can't out argue them

02:54:40.631 --> 02:54:44.391
he bullies them and then takes their silence for agreement with his views.

02:54:45.871 --> 02:54:50.571
Lucy was looking sweetly pretty in her white lawn frock. She has got a beautiful color

02:54:50.571 --> 02:54:51.791
since she has been here.

02:54:52.971 --> 02:54:57.591
I noticed that the old men did not lose any time in coming and sitting near her when we

02:54:57.591 --> 02:55:02.271
sat down. She is so sweet with old people. I think they all fell in love with her on

02:55:02.271 --> 02:55:08.531
spot. Even my old man succumbed and did not contradict her, but gave me double share instead.

02:55:09.111 --> 02:55:13.531
I got him on the subject of the legends, and he went off at once into a sort of sermon.

02:55:13.891 --> 02:55:16.151
I must try to remember it and put it down.

02:55:17.591 --> 02:55:23.271
It be all fool talk, luck, stock and metal, that's what it be and not else. These bans

02:55:23.271 --> 02:55:29.231
and laughs and bull-ghosts and bar-gasts and a-beldering, they be not but air-blibs. They

02:55:29.231 --> 02:55:34.791
not grins and signs and warnings, be all invented by partisans and ill-some berk-botties and

02:55:34.791 --> 02:55:39.431
railway-tartas to scare and scorn our halflings and to get folks to do something that they

02:55:39.431 --> 02:55:45.591
don't other incline to. It makes me ireful to think of them. Why, it's them that, not

02:55:45.591 --> 02:55:50.011
content with printing lies on paper and preaching them out of pulpits, does want to be cutting

02:55:50.011 --> 02:55:56.511
them on the tombstones. Look here, all around you, in that air-three-well. All them stains

02:55:56.511 --> 02:56:01.311
holding up their heads as well as the kind out of their pride is a kind simply tumbling

02:56:01.311 --> 02:56:06.611
down with the weight of the lies wrote on them. Here lies the body, or sacred to the

02:56:06.611 --> 02:56:11.051
memory wrote on all of them, and yet in thy half of them there beeth no bodies at all,

02:56:11.351 --> 02:56:16.771
and the memories of them beeth care to pinch your snuff about, much less sacred. Lies all

02:56:16.771 --> 02:56:22.091
of them, nothing but lies of one kind or another. My god, but it be a queer scoundrelment at

02:56:22.091 --> 02:56:26.411
the day of judgment when they come tumbling up in their death-socks, all drooped together,

02:56:26.611 --> 02:56:30.931
and trying to drag their tomb-stains with them to prove how good they was, some of them

02:56:30.931 --> 02:56:35.431
trembling and dithering, with their hands dozened and slippery from lying in the sea

02:56:35.431 --> 02:56:37.691
that they can't even keep their gurp of them.

02:56:38.691 --> 02:56:43.691
I could see from the old fellow's self-satisfied air, and the way in which he looked round

02:56:43.691 --> 02:56:48.571
for the approval of his cronies that he was showing off, so I put in a word to keep him

02:56:48.571 --> 02:56:56.071
Oh, Mr. Swales, you can't be serious. Certainly these tomb-stones are not all wrong. Gablons,

02:56:56.471 --> 02:57:01.031
there may be a poorest few not wrong, save in where they make out the people too good,

02:57:01.271 --> 02:57:06.431
for there be folk that do think a bonbon be like the sea, if only it be their own. The

02:57:06.431 --> 02:57:11.451
whole thing be only lies. Now look you here, you come here to a stranger, and you see this

02:57:11.451 --> 02:57:12.231
kick goth.

02:57:12.991 --> 02:57:17.851
I nodded, for I thought it better to assent, though I did not quite understand his dialect.

02:57:17.851 --> 02:57:20.371
I knew it had something to do with the church.

02:57:21.251 --> 02:57:22.231
He went on,

02:57:22.231 --> 02:57:27.111
And you can say it that all this stands be a boon folk that be a hept here, snort and

02:57:27.111 --> 02:57:27.551
snog.

02:57:28.051 --> 02:57:29.431
I assented again.

02:57:30.191 --> 02:57:34.391
Then that be just where the lie comes in. Why, there be scores of these lay-beds that

02:57:34.391 --> 02:57:39.351
be true as old Dunn's back-a-box on Friday night. He nudged one of his companions, and

02:57:39.351 --> 02:57:44.631
they all laughed. And, my God, how could there be otherwise? Look at that one, the athas

02:57:44.631 --> 02:57:46.231
above the beer-bank. Read it.

02:57:46.831 --> 02:57:48.631
I went over and read,

02:57:48.771 --> 02:57:55.311
Edward Spence-la, master mariner, murdered by pirates off the coast of Andres, April

02:57:55.911 --> 02:58:00.291
1854, age thirty. When I came back, Mr. Swills went on,

02:58:00.631 --> 02:58:06.211
Who brought him home, I wonder, to hap him here? Murdered off the coast of Andres, and

02:58:06.211 --> 02:58:11.791
you consented his body lay under. Why, I could name me a dozen whose bones lie in the Greenland

02:58:11.791 --> 02:58:17.851
He pointed northwards, or where the currents may have drifted them. There be the stains

02:58:17.851 --> 02:58:22.871
around ye. You can't with your young eyes read the small print of the lies from here.

02:58:23.391 --> 02:58:28.611
This breath-wet Lowry, I knew his father, lost in the lively off Greenland in twenty.

02:58:29.151 --> 02:58:36.971
Or Andrew Woodhouse, drowned in the same seas in 1777. Or John Paxton, drowned off Cape

02:58:36.971 --> 02:58:42.071
farewell a year later, or old John Rowlings, whose grandfather sailed with me, drowned

02:58:42.071 --> 02:58:47.671
in the Gulf of Finland in fifty. Do ye think that all these men will have to make a rush

02:58:47.671 --> 02:58:53.511
to Whitby when the trumpet sounds? I have me anthems about it. I tell ye that when they

02:58:53.511 --> 02:58:58.091
got here they be jumbling and jostling one another, the way that it would be like a fight

02:58:58.091 --> 02:59:03.211
upon the ice in the old days, when we be at one another from daylight to dark, and trying

02:59:03.211 --> 02:59:09.391
to tie up our cuts by the Arura Borealis. This was evidently local pleasantry, for the

02:59:09.391 --> 02:59:12.711
old man cackled over it, and his cronies joined in with gusto.

02:59:13.871 --> 02:59:19.071
But, I said, surely you are not quite correct, for you start on the assumption that all the

02:59:19.071 --> 02:59:23.091
poor people or their spirits will have to take their tombstones with them on the day

02:59:23.091 --> 02:59:26.591
of judgment. Do you think that that will be really necessary?

02:59:27.451 --> 02:59:31.071
Well what else be the tombstones for? Answer me that, miss.

02:59:31.611 --> 02:59:33.571
To please their relatives, I suppose.

02:59:34.071 --> 02:59:40.711
To please their relatives, you suppose? This he said with intense scorn. How will it pleasure

02:59:40.711 --> 02:59:45.631
their relatives to know that lies are wrote over them, and that everybody in the place

02:59:45.631 --> 02:59:47.071
know that they be lies?

02:59:48.031 --> 02:59:52.871
He pointed to a stone at our feet, which had been laid down as a slab, on which the seat

02:59:52.871 --> 02:59:58.591
was rested, close to the edge of the cliff. Read the lies on that thrift-stone, he said.

02:59:59.391 --> 03:00:04.411
The letters were upside down to me from where I sat, but Lucy was more opposite to them,

03:00:04.411 --> 03:00:06.231
so she leant over and read—

03:00:06.811 --> 03:00:11.311
Sacred to the memory of George Cannon, who died in the hope of glorious resurrection,

03:00:11.811 --> 03:00:19.171
on July 20, 1873, falling from the rocks at Kettles. This tomb was erected by his sorrowing

03:00:19.171 --> 03:00:24.691
mother to her dearly beloved son. He was the only son of his mother, and she was a widow.

03:00:24.691 --> 03:00:28.991
Really, Mr. Swales, I don't see anything very funny in that."

03:00:28.991 --> 03:00:32.171
She spoke her comment very gravely and somewhat severely.

03:00:32.671 --> 03:00:38.191
"'You don't see aunt funny, ha-ha! But that's because your grand-a-sarnin' mother was a

03:00:38.191 --> 03:00:44.051
hell-cat that hated him because he was a crooked, a regular lammeter he was, and he hated her

03:00:44.051 --> 03:00:49.051
so that he committed suicide in order that she mightn't get an insurance she put on his

03:00:49.051 --> 03:00:54.231
life. Blew neither top of his head off with an old musket that they had for scaring crows

03:00:54.231 --> 03:00:59.831
with. Point for crows then, for it brought the clags and the dowps to him. That's the

03:00:59.831 --> 03:01:05.031
way he fell off the rocks. And as to hopes of a glorious resurrection, I've often heard

03:01:05.031 --> 03:01:09.451
him say myself that he hoped he'd go to hell, for his mother was so fierce that she'd be

03:01:09.451 --> 03:01:15.391
sure to go to heaven, and he didn't want to idle where she was. Isn't that stunning at

03:01:15.391 --> 03:01:21.391
any rate he hammered it with his stick as he spoke? Apocalypse! And won't it make Gabriel

03:01:21.391 --> 03:01:27.291
when Geordi comes pantonutris with the tomb-stand balanced on his hump and asked to be took

03:01:27.291 --> 03:01:29.031
as evidence?'

03:01:29.031 --> 03:01:34.791
I did not know what to say, but Lucy turned the conversation as she said, rising up,

03:01:35.231 --> 03:01:40.471
"'Oh, why did you tell us of this? It is my favorite seat, and I cannot leave it, and

03:01:40.471 --> 03:01:43.991
now I find I must go on sitting over the grave of a suicide.'

03:01:45.231 --> 03:01:50.411
"'That won't harm you, my pretty, and it may make poor Geordi gladsome to have so trim a

03:01:50.411 --> 03:01:55.931
sitting on his lap. Ah, that won't hurt you. Why, I've sat here off and on for nigh twenty

03:01:55.931 --> 03:02:00.871
years past, and it hasn't done me no harm. Don't you fash about them as lies unto ye,

03:02:01.091 --> 03:02:05.451
or they doesn't lie there either. It'll be time for you to be getting scat when you see

03:02:05.451 --> 03:02:09.851
the tomb-stains all run away with, and the place is bare as a stubble field.'

03:02:10.651 --> 03:02:15.891
"'Ah, there's the clock, and I must go. I can serve as tea, ladies.' And off he hobbled.'

03:02:16.951 --> 03:02:22.731
Lucy and I sat awhile, and it was all so beautiful before us that we took hands as we sat, and

03:02:22.731 --> 03:02:28.211
she told me all over again about Arthur and their coming marriage. That made me just a

03:02:28.211 --> 03:02:31.751
little heartsick, for I haven't heard from Jonathan for a whole month.

03:02:34.291 --> 03:02:40.911
"'The same day. I came up here alone, for I am very sad. There was no letter for me.

03:02:40.911 --> 03:02:46.491
I hope there cannot be anything the matter with Jonathan. The clock has just struck nine.

03:02:46.951 --> 03:02:52.191
I see the lights scattered all over the town, sometimes in rows where the streets are, and

03:02:52.191 --> 03:02:58.311
sometimes singly. They run right up the esk and die away in the curve of the valley. To

03:02:58.311 --> 03:03:03.011
my left the view is cut off by a black line of roof of the old house next to the abbey.

03:03:03.371 --> 03:03:07.791
The sheep and lambs are bleating in the fields away behind me, and there is a clatter of

03:03:07.791 --> 03:03:13.511
donkeys' hooves up the paved road below. The band on the pier is playing a harsh waltz

03:03:13.511 --> 03:03:18.651
in good time, and farther along the quay there is a Salvation Army meeting in the back street.

03:03:19.371 --> 03:03:24.571
Neither of the bands hears the other, but up here I hear and see them both. I wonder

03:03:24.571 --> 03:03:31.471
where Jonathan is, and if he is thinking of me. Oh, I wish he were here.'

03:03:36.831 --> 03:03:37.911
5 June.

03:03:38.631 --> 03:03:44.231
The case of Renfield grows more interesting the more I get to understand the man. He has

03:03:44.231 --> 03:03:51.451
certain qualities very largely developed—selfishness, secrecy, and purpose. I wish I could get at

03:03:51.451 --> 03:03:56.371
what is the object of the latter. He seems to have some settled scheme of his own, but

03:03:56.371 --> 03:04:03.271
what it is I do not know. His redeeming quality is a love of animals, though, indeed, he has

03:04:03.271 --> 03:04:08.931
such curious turns in it that I sometimes imagine he is only abnormally cruel. His pets

03:04:08.931 --> 03:04:15.891
are of odd sorts. Just now his hobby is catching flies. He has at present such a quantity that

03:04:15.891 --> 03:04:22.851
I have had myself to expostulate. To my astonishment he did not break out into a fury, as I expected,

03:04:22.851 --> 03:04:27.871
but took the matter in simple seriousness. He thought for a moment and then said,

03:04:28.451 --> 03:04:34.391
"'May I have three days? I shall clear them away.' Of course I said that would do. I must

03:04:34.391 --> 03:04:36.091
watch him.'

03:04:37.191 --> 03:04:38.271
18 June.

03:04:38.811 --> 03:04:44.291
He has turned his mind now to spiders, and has got several very big fellows in a box.

03:04:44.751 --> 03:04:50.011
He keeps feeding them his flies, and the number of the latter is becoming sensibly diminished,

03:04:50.351 --> 03:04:54.991
although he has used half his food in attracting more flies from outside to his room.

03:04:57.311 --> 03:04:58.271
1 July.

03:04:59.131 --> 03:05:04.411
His spiders are now becoming as great a nuisance as his flies, and today I told him that he

03:05:04.411 --> 03:05:09.731
must get rid of them. He looked very sad at this, so I said that he must, some of them,

03:05:09.731 --> 03:05:15.111
at all events. He cheerfully acquiesced in this, and I gave him the same time as before

03:05:15.111 --> 03:05:21.051
for reduction. He disgusted me much while with him, for when a hoarded blow-fly, bloated

03:05:21.051 --> 03:05:26.431
with some carrion food, buzzed into the room, he caught it, held it exultantly for a few

03:05:26.431 --> 03:05:30.831
moments between his finger and thumb, and before I knew what he was going to do, put

03:05:30.831 --> 03:05:36.671
it in his mouth and ate it. I scolded him for it, but he argued quietly that it was

03:05:36.671 --> 03:05:42.551
very good and very wholesome, that it was life, strong life, and gave life to him. This

03:05:42.551 --> 03:05:47.791
gave me an idea, or the rudiment of one. I must watch how he gets rid of his spiders.

03:05:48.991 --> 03:05:54.131
He has evidently some deep problem in his mind, for he keeps a little notebook in which

03:05:54.131 --> 03:05:59.291
he is always jotting down something. Whole pages of it are filled with masses of figures,

03:05:59.731 --> 03:06:04.831
generally single numbers added up in batches, and then the totals added in batches again,

03:06:05.391 --> 03:06:08.571
as though he were focusing some account, as the auditors put it.

03:06:10.591 --> 03:06:11.511
8 July.

03:06:12.051 --> 03:06:17.751
There is a method in his madness, and the rudimentary idea in my mind is growing. It

03:06:17.751 --> 03:06:23.251
will be a whole idea soon, and then, oh unconscious cerebration, you will have to give the wall

03:06:23.251 --> 03:06:28.691
to your conscious brother. I kept away from my friend for a few days so that I might notice

03:06:28.691 --> 03:06:33.511
if there were any change. Things remain as they were, except that he has parted with

03:06:33.511 --> 03:06:39.851
some of his pets and got a new one. He has managed to get a sparrow, and has already

03:06:39.851 --> 03:06:45.691
partially tamed it. His means of taming is simple, for already the spiders have diminished.

03:06:46.531 --> 03:06:51.331
Those that do remain, however, are well fed, for he still brings in the flies by tempting

03:06:51.331 --> 03:06:52.431
them with his food.

03:06:55.511 --> 03:06:56.631
19 July.

03:06:57.191 --> 03:07:03.711
We are progressing. My friend has now a whole colony of sparrows, and his flies and spiders

03:07:03.711 --> 03:07:09.831
are almost obliterated. When I came in, he ran to me and said he wanted to ask me a great

03:07:09.831 --> 03:07:17.191
favor, a very, very great favor, and as he spoke, he fawned on me like a dog. I asked

03:07:17.191 --> 03:07:22.031
him what it was, and he said, with a sort of rapture in his voice and bearing, a kitten,

03:07:22.351 --> 03:07:28.011
a nice little sleek, playful kitten, that I can play with and teach and feed and feed

03:07:28.011 --> 03:07:35.091
and feed. I was not unprepared for this request, for I had noticed how his pets went on increasing

03:07:35.091 --> 03:07:40.531
in size and vivacity, but I did not care that his pretty family of tamed sparrows should

03:07:40.531 --> 03:07:46.531
be wiped out in the same manner as the flies and spiders. So I said I would see about it,

03:07:46.571 --> 03:07:51.711
and asked him if he would not rather have a cat than a kitten. His eagerness betrayed

03:07:51.711 --> 03:07:56.411
him as he answered, Oh, yes, I would like a cat. I only asked for a kitten lest you

03:07:56.411 --> 03:08:02.071
should refuse me a cat. No one would refuse me a kitten, would they? I shook my head,

03:08:02.071 --> 03:08:06.411
and said that at present I feared it would not be possible, but that I would see about

03:08:06.411 --> 03:08:11.691
it. His face fell, and I could see a warning of danger in it, for there was a sudden fierce

03:08:11.691 --> 03:08:17.771
sidelong look which meant killing. The man is an undeveloped homicidal maniac. I shall

03:08:17.771 --> 03:08:22.651
test him with his present craving and see how it will work out, and then I shall know

03:08:22.651 --> 03:08:23.151
more.

03:08:24.351 --> 03:08:29.891
10 p.m. I visited him again and found him sitting in a corner brooding. When I came

03:08:29.891 --> 03:08:34.391
again he threw himself on his knees before me and implored me to let him have a cat that

03:08:34.391 --> 03:08:39.691
his salvation depended upon it. I was firm, however, and told him that he could not have

03:08:39.691 --> 03:08:45.111
it, whereupon he went without a word and sat down gnawing his fingers in the corner where

03:08:45.111 --> 03:08:48.711
I had found him. I shall see him in the morning early.

03:08:50.391 --> 03:08:58.051
20 j. Visited Renfield very early before attendant went his rounds. Found him up and humming

03:08:58.051 --> 03:09:03.851
a tune. He was spreading out his sugar, which he had saved, in the window, and was manifestly

03:09:03.851 --> 03:09:09.531
beginning his fly-catching again, and beginning it cheerfully and with a good grace. I looked

03:09:09.531 --> 03:09:14.671
around for his birds, and not seeing them, asked him where they were. He replied without

03:09:14.671 --> 03:09:19.591
turning round that they had all flown away. There were a few feathers about the room,

03:09:19.671 --> 03:09:25.571
and on his pillow a drop of blood. I said nothing, but went and told the keeper to report

03:09:25.571 --> 03:09:28.631
to me if there were anything odd about him during the day.

03:09:29.731 --> 03:09:35.071
11 a.m. The attendant has just been to see me to say that Renfield has been very sick

03:09:35.071 --> 03:09:41.371
and has disgorged a whole lot of feathers. My belief is, doctor, he said, that he has

03:09:41.371 --> 03:09:44.451
eaten his birds and that he just took and ate them raw.

03:09:46.051 --> 03:09:52.411
11 p.m. I gave Renfield a strong opiate tonight, enough to make even him sleep, and took away

03:09:52.411 --> 03:09:57.011
his pocket-book to look at it. The thought that has been buzzing about my brain lately

03:09:57.011 --> 03:10:03.991
is complete, and the theory proved. My homicidal maniac is of a peculiar kind. I shall have

03:10:03.991 --> 03:10:10.251
to invent a new classification for him and call him a Zufagous Life-Eating Maniac.

03:10:11.211 --> 03:10:17.091
What he desires is to absorb as many lives as he can, and he has laid himself out to

03:10:17.091 --> 03:10:23.471
achieve it in a cumulative way. He gave many flies to one spider, and many spiders to one

03:10:23.471 --> 03:10:29.691
bird, and then wanted a cat to eat the many birds. What would have been his later steps?

03:10:30.711 --> 03:10:35.371
It would almost be worthwhile to complete the experiment. It might be done if there

03:10:35.371 --> 03:10:40.811
were only a sufficient cause. Men sneered at vivisection, and yet look at its results

03:10:40.811 --> 03:10:46.411
today. Why not advance science in its most difficult and vital aspect, the knowledge

03:10:46.411 --> 03:10:52.431
of the brain? Had I even the secret of one such mind, did I hold the key to the fancy

03:10:52.431 --> 03:10:57.471
of even one lunatic, I might advance my own branch of science to a pitch compared with

03:10:57.471 --> 03:11:03.851
which Burton Sanderson's physiology, or Faraday's brain knowledge, would be as nothing. If only

03:11:03.851 --> 03:11:08.711
there were a sufficient cause, I must not think too much of this, or I may be tempted.

03:11:09.191 --> 03:11:14.311
A good cause might turn the scale with me, for may not I too be of an exceptional brain

03:11:14.311 --> 03:11:20.691
congenitally? How well the man reasoned. Lunatics always do within their own scope.

03:11:21.291 --> 03:11:27.651
I wonder at how many lives he values a man, or if at only one. He has closed the account

03:11:27.651 --> 03:11:33.811
most accurately, and today begun a new record. How many of us begin a new record with each

03:11:33.811 --> 03:11:39.611
day of our lives? To me it seems only yesterday that my whole life ended with my new hope,

03:11:39.611 --> 03:11:45.011
and that truly I began a new record. So it shall be until the great recorder sums me

03:11:45.011 --> 03:11:49.371
up and closes my ledger account with a balance to profit or loss.

03:11:50.891 --> 03:11:56.351
Ah, Lucy, Lucy, I cannot be angry with you, nor can I be angry with my friend whose happiness

03:11:56.351 --> 03:12:04.591
is yours, but I must only wait on hopeless and work, work, work. If I could have as strong

03:12:04.591 --> 03:12:10.391
a cause as my poor mad friend there, a good unselfish cause to make me work, that would

03:12:10.391 --> 03:12:11.731
be indeed happiness.

03:12:14.491 --> 03:12:15.691
Mina Murray's Journal

03:12:17.471 --> 03:12:24.211
26th of July. I am anxious and it soothes me to express myself here. It is like whispering

03:12:24.211 --> 03:12:29.611
to oneself and listening at the same time. And there is also something about the shorthand

03:12:29.611 --> 03:12:31.731
symbols that makes it different from writing.

03:12:32.771 --> 03:12:38.651
I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan. I had not heard from Jonathan for some time

03:12:38.651 --> 03:12:44.211
and was very concerned, but yesterday dear Mr. Hawkins, who is always so kind, sent me

03:12:44.211 --> 03:12:49.131
a letter from him. I had written asking him if he had heard, and he said the enclosed

03:12:49.131 --> 03:12:55.371
had just been received. It is only a line dated from Castle Dracula and says that he

03:12:55.371 --> 03:13:01.531
is just starting for home. That is not like Jonathan. I do not understand it and it makes

03:13:01.531 --> 03:13:02.171
me uneasy.

03:13:03.751 --> 03:13:09.311
Then too Lucy, although she is so well, has lately taken to her old habit of walking in

03:13:09.311 --> 03:13:14.271
her sleep. Her mother has spoken to me about it, and we have decided that I am to lock

03:13:14.271 --> 03:13:20.711
the door of our room every night. Mrs. Westlenra has got an idea that sleepwalkers always go

03:13:20.711 --> 03:13:25.891
out on roofs of houses and along the edges of cliffs and then get suddenly wakened and

03:13:25.891 --> 03:13:31.831
fall over with a despairing cry that echoes all over the place. Poor dear! She is naturally

03:13:31.831 --> 03:13:36.851
anxious about Lucy and she tells me that her husband, Lucy's father, had the same habit,

03:13:37.071 --> 03:13:40.791
that he would get up in the night and dress himself and go out if he were not stopped.

03:13:42.211 --> 03:13:47.171
Lucy is to be married in the autumn, and she is already planning out her dresses and how

03:13:47.171 --> 03:13:53.191
house is to be arranged. I sympathize with her, for I do the same. Only Jonathan and

03:13:53.191 --> 03:13:58.031
I will start in life in a very simple way, and shall have to try to make both ends meet.

03:13:59.691 --> 03:14:06.331
Mr. Homewood, he is the honorable Arthur Homewood, only son of Lord Godalming, is coming up here

03:14:06.331 --> 03:14:11.471
very shortly, as soon as he can leave town, for his father is not very well, and I think

03:14:11.471 --> 03:14:16.611
dear Lucy is counting the moments till he comes. She wants to take him up in the seat

03:14:16.611 --> 03:14:21.811
of the churchyard cliff and show him the beauty of Whitby. I dare say it is the waiting which

03:14:21.811 --> 03:14:24.791
disturbs her. She will be all right when he arrives.

03:14:26.991 --> 03:14:33.211
27th of July. No news from Jonathan. I am getting quite uneasy about him, though why

03:14:33.211 --> 03:14:38.691
I should I do not know, but I do wish that he would write, if it were only a single line.

03:14:39.751 --> 03:14:44.731
Lucy walks more than ever, and each night I am awakened by her moving about the room.

03:14:45.451 --> 03:14:50.911
Fortunately, the weather is so hot that she cannot get cold. But still, the anxiety and

03:14:50.911 --> 03:14:55.151
the perpetually being awakened is beginning to tell on me, and I am getting nervous and

03:14:55.151 --> 03:15:01.071
wakeful myself. Thank God Lucy's health keeps up. Mr. Homewood has been suddenly called

03:15:01.071 --> 03:15:06.491
to ring to see his father, who has been taken seriously ill. Lucy frets at the postponement

03:15:06.491 --> 03:15:11.911
of seeing him, but it does not touch her looks. She is a trifle stouter, and her cheeks are

03:15:11.911 --> 03:15:17.491
lovely rose pink. She has lost the anemic look which she had. I pray it will all last.

03:15:19.191 --> 03:15:24.951
3rd of August. Another week gone by, and no news from Jonathan. Not even to Mr. Hawkins,

03:15:25.151 --> 03:15:30.631
from whom I have heard. Oh, I do hope he is not ill. He surely would have written. I look

03:15:30.631 --> 03:15:35.551
at that last letter of his, but somehow it does not satisfy me. It does not read like

03:15:35.551 --> 03:15:39.131
him, and yet it is his writing. There is no mistake of that.

03:15:40.311 --> 03:15:44.771
Lucy has not walked much in her sleep the last week, but there is an odd concentration

03:15:44.771 --> 03:15:49.811
about her which I do not understand. Even in her sleep she seems to be watching me.

03:15:50.211 --> 03:15:54.971
She tries the door, and finding it locked, goes about the room, searching for the key.

03:15:57.171 --> 03:16:03.531
6th of August. Another three days, and no news. The suspense is getting dreadful. If

03:16:03.531 --> 03:16:08.311
I only knew where to write to or where to go to, I should feel easier. But no one has

03:16:08.311 --> 03:16:13.011
heard a word of Jonathan since that last letter. I must only pray to God for patience.

03:16:14.111 --> 03:16:19.631
Lucy is more excitable than ever, but is otherwise well. Last night was very threatening, and

03:16:19.631 --> 03:16:23.971
the fishermen say that we are in for a storm. I must try to watch it, and learn the weather

03:16:23.971 --> 03:16:24.411
signs.

03:16:25.751 --> 03:16:30.951
Today is a gray day, and the sun as I write is hidden in thick clouds high over Kettleness.

03:16:31.751 --> 03:16:36.671
Everything is gray, except the green grass which seems like emerald amongst it, gray

03:16:36.671 --> 03:16:42.271
earthy rock, gray clouds, tinged with a sunburst at the far edge, hang over the gray sea in

03:16:42.271 --> 03:16:48.371
which the sand points stretch like gray figures. The sea is tumbling in over the shallows in

03:16:48.371 --> 03:16:54.071
the sandy flats with a roar, muffled in sea mists drifting inland. The horizon is lost

03:16:54.071 --> 03:16:59.891
in a gray mist. All vastness, the clouds are piled up like giant rocks, and there is a

03:16:59.891 --> 03:17:05.411
brule over the sea that sounds like some passage of doom. Dark figures are on the beach here

03:17:05.411 --> 03:17:34.971
and there, sometimes half-shrouded in the mist, and seem men-like trees walking. The fishing boats are racing for home, and rise and dip in the ground swell as they sweep into the harbor, bending to the scuppers. Here comes old Mr. Swales. He is making straight for me, and I can see by the way he lifts his hat that he wants to talk. I have been quite touched by the change in the poor old man. When he sat down beside me, he said in a very gentle way, I want to say something to you, miss.

03:17:35.491 --> 03:18:05.391
I could see that he was not at ease, so I took his poor old wrinkled hand in mine and asked him to speak fully. So he said, leaving his hand in mine, I am afraid, my dearie, that I must have shocked you by all the wicked things I have been saying about the dead and such-like for weeks past, but I didn't mean them, and I want you to remember that when I am gone. We old folks that be daffled, with one foot above the crock-hole, don't all together like to think of it, and we don't want to feel scared of it, and that's why I took to making light

03:18:05.391 --> 03:18:33.431
of it, so that I would cheer up my own heart a bit. But, Lord, love you, miss, I ain't afraid of dying, not a bit, only I don't want to die if I can help it. My time must be nigh at hand now, for I be old, and a hundred years is too much for any man to expect. And I am so nigh at that the old man has already witnessed life. You see, I can't get out of the habit of coughing about it all at once. The chaffs will wag as they be used to.

03:18:34.391 --> 03:18:55.651
Ah, some day soon the angel of death will sound his trumpet for me. But don't you dull and grate, my dearie, for he saw that I was crying. If he should come this very night, I'd not refuse to answer his call. For life be after all, only awaiting for something else than what we're doing, and death be all that we can rightly depend on.

03:18:56.051 --> 03:19:10.051
But I'm content, for it's coming to me, my dearie, and coming quick. It may be coming while we be looking and wondering. Maybe it's in that wind out over the sea that's pringing with it loss and wreck and sore distress and sad hearts.

03:19:10.551 --> 03:19:19.791
Look, look! he cried suddenly. There's something in that wind and in the host beyond that sound, and looks and tastes and smells like death.

03:19:20.331 --> 03:19:22.631
It's in the air. I feel it coming.

03:19:23.811 --> 03:19:26.771
Ah, Lord, make me answer cheerful when my call comes.

03:19:27.251 --> 03:19:32.371
He held up his arms devoutly and raised his hat. His mouth moved as though he were praying.

03:19:32.891 --> 03:19:42.291
After a few minutes' silence he got up, shook hands with me, and blessed me, and said good-bye, and hobbled off. It all touched me and upset me very much.

03:19:42.931 --> 03:19:52.011
I was glad when the Coast Guard came along with his spy-glass under his arm. He stopped to talk with me, as he always does, but all the time kept looking at a strange ship.

03:19:53.251 --> 03:19:55.991
I can't make her out, he said.

03:19:56.691 --> 03:20:01.871
She's a Russian by the look of her. Ah, but she's knocking about in the queerest way.

03:20:02.371 --> 03:20:11.071
She doesn't know her mind a bit. She seems to see the storm coming, but can't decide whether to run up north in the open or to put in here.

03:20:11.851 --> 03:20:19.471
Look there again. She's steered mighty strangely, for she doesn't mind the hand on the wheel, changes about with every puff of wind.

03:20:20.231 --> 03:20:23.171
Ah, we'll hear more of her before this time tomorrow.

03:20:56.627 --> 03:21:05.607
Cutting from The Daily Graph, 8th of August, pasted in Mina Murray's journal.

03:21:07.227 --> 03:21:10.067
From a Correspondent, Whitby.

03:21:11.307 --> 03:21:16.167
One of the greatest and suddenest storms on record has just been experienced here with

03:21:16.167 --> 03:21:18.687
results both strange and unique.

03:21:20.047 --> 03:21:25.647
The weather had been somewhat sultry, but not to any degree uncommon in the month of August.

03:21:26.627 --> 03:21:32.247
Saturday evening was as fine as was ever known, and the great body of holiday-makers laid

03:21:32.247 --> 03:21:39.567
out yesterday for visits to Mulgrave Woods, Robin Hood's Bay, Rig Mill, Runswick, States,

03:21:40.027 --> 03:21:42.447
and the various trips in the neighborhood of Whitby.

03:21:43.347 --> 03:21:50.247
The steamers Emma and Scarborough made trips up and down the coast, and there was an unusual

03:21:50.247 --> 03:21:53.387
amount of tripping both to and from Whitby.

03:21:54.667 --> 03:21:59.687
The day was unusually fine till the afternoon when some of the gossips who frequent the

03:21:59.687 --> 03:22:06.307
east cliff churchyard and from the commanding eminence watch the wide sweep of sea visible

03:22:06.307 --> 03:22:14.047
to the north and east, called attention to a sudden show of mare's tails high in the

03:22:14.047 --> 03:22:15.287
sky to the northwest.

03:22:16.407 --> 03:22:21.547
The wind was then blowing from the southwest in the mild degree which in barometrical

03:22:21.547 --> 03:22:26.127
language is ranked as number two light breeze.

03:22:27.727 --> 03:22:33.767
The Coast Guard on duty at once made report, and one old fisherman, who for more than half

03:22:33.767 --> 03:22:39.547
century has kept watch on weather signs from the east cliff, foretold in an emphatic manner

03:22:39.547 --> 03:22:41.447
the coming of a sudden storm.

03:22:42.407 --> 03:22:48.087
The approach of sunset was so very beautiful, so grand in its masses of splendidly colored

03:22:48.087 --> 03:22:53.427
clouds that there was quite an assemblage on the walk along the cliff in the old churchyard

03:22:53.427 --> 03:22:54.647
to enjoy the beauty.

03:22:55.267 --> 03:23:00.767
Before the sun dipped below the black mass of kettleness, standing boldly a thwart the

03:23:00.767 --> 03:23:08.067
western sky, its downward way was marked by myriad clouds of every sunset color, flame,

03:23:08.307 --> 03:23:16.247
purple, pink, green, violet, and all the tints of gold, with here and there masses not large,

03:23:16.627 --> 03:23:24.507
but of seemingly absolute blackness in all sorts of shapes, as well outlined as colossal

03:23:24.507 --> 03:23:25.307
silhouettes.

03:23:26.447 --> 03:23:32.367
The experience was not lost on the painters, and doubtless some of the sketches of the

03:23:32.367 --> 03:23:39.807
prelude to the great storm will grace the R.A. and R.I. walls in May next.

03:23:41.707 --> 03:23:48.267
More than one captain made up his mind then and there that his cobble, or his mule, as

03:23:48.267 --> 03:23:52.467
they term the different classes of boats, would remain in the harbor till the storm

03:23:52.467 --> 03:23:53.147
had passed.

03:23:53.147 --> 03:24:02.687
The wind fell away entirely during the evening, and at midnight there was a dead calm, a sultry

03:24:02.687 --> 03:24:10.007
heat, and that prevailing intensity which, on the approach of thunder, affects persons

03:24:10.007 --> 03:24:11.287
of a sensitive nature.

03:24:12.667 --> 03:24:18.547
There were but few lights in sight at sea, for even the coasting steamers, which usually

03:24:18.547 --> 03:24:24.707
the shore so closely, kept well to seaward, and but a few fishing boats were in sight.

03:24:25.567 --> 03:24:31.607
The only sail noticeable was a foreign schooner with all sails set, which was seemingly going

03:24:31.607 --> 03:24:32.447
westwards.

03:24:33.487 --> 03:24:40.007
The foolhardiness or ignorance of her officers was a prolific theme for comment whilst she

03:24:40.007 --> 03:24:45.467
remained in sight, and efforts were made to signal her to reduce sail in the face of her

03:24:45.467 --> 03:24:45.887
danger.

03:24:47.147 --> 03:24:54.067
Before the night shut down she was seen with sails idly flapping as she gently rolled on

03:24:54.067 --> 03:25:01.547
the undulating swell of the sea, as idle as a painted ship upon a painted ocean.

03:25:03.687 --> 03:25:09.507
Shortly before ten o'clock the stillness of the air grew quite oppressive, and the silence

03:25:09.507 --> 03:25:15.107
was so marked that the bleating of a sheep inland or the barking of a dog in the town

03:25:15.107 --> 03:25:23.067
was distinctly heard, and the band on the pier, with its lively French air, was like

03:25:23.067 --> 03:25:27.527
a discord in the great harmony of nature's silence.

03:25:29.387 --> 03:25:37.107
A little after midnight came a strange sound from over the sea, and high overhead the air

03:25:37.107 --> 03:25:41.587
began to carry a strange faint hollow booming.

03:25:43.047 --> 03:25:49.707
Then, without warning, the tempest broke, with a rapidity which at the time seemed incredible,

03:25:50.427 --> 03:25:56.847
and even afterwards is impossible to realize, the whole aspect of nature at once becoming

03:25:56.847 --> 03:25:57.847
convulsed.

03:25:58.527 --> 03:26:05.947
The waves rose in growing fury, each overtopping its fellow, till, in a very few minutes, the

03:26:06.677 --> 03:26:11.727
sea was like a roaring and devouring monster.

03:26:13.247 --> 03:26:19.427
White crested waves beat madly on the level sands and rushed up the shelving cliffs.

03:26:20.647 --> 03:26:25.807
Others broke over the piers, and with their spewms swept the lanthorns of the lighthouse,

03:26:26.347 --> 03:26:29.427
which rise from the end of either pier of Whitby Harbour.

03:26:30.207 --> 03:26:38.087
The wind roared like thunder, and blew with such force that it was with difficulty that

03:26:38.087 --> 03:26:44.987
even strong men kept their feet, or clung with grim clasp to the iron stanchions.

03:26:45.927 --> 03:26:52.407
It was found necessary to clear the entire pier from the mass of onlookers, or else the

03:26:52.407 --> 03:26:54.967
fatalities of the night would have increased manifold.

03:26:55.907 --> 03:27:02.667
To add to the difficulties and dangers of the time, masses of sea-fog came drifting

03:27:02.667 --> 03:27:03.367
inland.

03:27:04.227 --> 03:27:13.667
White, wet clouds, which swept by in ghostly fashion, so dank and damp and cold that it

03:27:13.667 --> 03:27:19.527
needed but a little effort of imagination to think that the spirits of those lost at

03:27:19.527 --> 03:27:27.707
were touching their living brethren with the clammy hands of death, and many a one shuddered

03:27:27.707 --> 03:27:31.407
as the wreaths of sea-mist swept by.

03:27:33.607 --> 03:27:39.927
At times the mist cleared, and the sea, for some distance, could be seen in the glare

03:27:39.927 --> 03:27:46.587
of the lightning, which came thick and fast, followed by such peals of thunder that the

03:27:46.587 --> 03:27:52.687
whole sky overhead seemed trembling under the shock of the footsteps of the storm.

03:27:54.007 --> 03:28:01.007
Some of the scenes thus revealed were of immeasurable grandeur and of absorbing interest.

03:28:01.887 --> 03:28:11.307
The sea, running mountains high, threw skywards with each wave mighty masses of white foam,

03:28:11.737 --> 03:28:17.207
which the tempest seemed to snatch at and whirl away into space.

03:28:18.227 --> 03:28:23.667
Here and there a fishing-boat with a rag of sail running madly for shelter before the

03:28:23.667 --> 03:28:29.227
blast, now and again the white wings of a storm-tossed sea-bird.

03:28:30.687 --> 03:28:36.367
On the summit of the east cliff the new search-light was ready for experiment, but had not yet

03:28:36.367 --> 03:28:37.147
been tried.

03:28:37.907 --> 03:28:44.407
The officers in charge of it got it into working order, and in the pauses of onrushing mist

03:28:44.407 --> 03:28:46.727
swept with it the surface of the sea.

03:28:47.847 --> 03:28:54.887
Once or twice its service was most effective, as when a fishing-boat with gunnel under water

03:28:54.887 --> 03:29:01.047
rushed into the harbor, able, by the guidance of the sheltering light, to avoid the danger

03:29:01.047 --> 03:29:02.827
of dashing against the piers.

03:29:03.727 --> 03:29:10.087
As each boat achieved the safety of the port there was a shout of joy from the mass of

03:29:10.087 --> 03:29:17.027
people on the shore, a shout which for a moment seemed to cleave the gale and was then swept

03:29:17.027 --> 03:29:18.647
away in its rush.

03:29:20.747 --> 03:29:26.907
Before long the search-light discovered some distance away a schooner, with all sails set,

03:29:27.487 --> 03:29:30.667
apparently the same vessel which had been noticed earlier in the evening.

03:29:31.427 --> 03:29:38.047
The wind had by this time backed to the east, and there was a shudder amongst the watchers

03:29:38.047 --> 03:29:43.107
on the cliff as they realized the terrible danger in which she now was.

03:29:44.927 --> 03:29:51.687
Between her and the port lay the great flat reef on which so many good ships have from

03:29:51.687 --> 03:29:58.307
time to time suffered, and with the wind blowing from its present quarter it would be quite

03:29:58.307 --> 03:30:01.887
impossible that she should fetch the entrance of the harbor.

03:30:03.757 --> 03:30:09.527
It was now nearly the hour of high tide, but the waves were so great that in their troughs

03:30:09.527 --> 03:30:16.487
the shallows of the shore were almost visible, and the schooner with all sails set was rushing

03:30:16.487 --> 03:30:23.847
with such speed that, in the words of one old salt, she must fetch up somewhere if it

03:30:23.847 --> 03:30:25.267
was only in hell.

03:30:26.267 --> 03:30:34.047
Then came another rush of sea-fog, greater than any hitherto, a mass of dank mist which

03:30:34.047 --> 03:30:41.167
seemed to close on all things like a gray pall, and left available to men only the organ

03:30:41.167 --> 03:30:46.907
of hearing, for the roar of the tempest and the crash of the thunder and the booming of

03:30:46.907 --> 03:30:52.687
the mighty billows came through the damp oblivion even louder than before.

03:30:53.527 --> 03:30:59.507
The rays of the search-light were kept fixed on the harbor mouth across the east pier,

03:31:00.127 --> 03:31:05.127
where the shock was expected, and the men waited breathless.

03:31:06.627 --> 03:31:12.547
The wind suddenly shifted to the northeast, and the remnant of the sea-fog melted in the

03:31:12.547 --> 03:31:22.667
blast, and then Mirebiel Dictu swept the strange schooner before the blast with all sails set

03:31:23.367 --> 03:31:25.627
and gained the safety of the harbor.

03:31:26.347 --> 03:31:32.847
The search-light followed her, and a shudder ran through all who saw her, for lashed to

03:31:32.847 --> 03:31:40.627
the helm was a corpse, with drooping head, which swung horribly to and fro at each motion

03:31:40.627 --> 03:31:41.287
of the ship.

03:31:42.307 --> 03:31:45.867
No other form could be seen on the deck at all.

03:31:47.087 --> 03:31:54.467
A great awe came on all as they realized that the ship as if by a miracle had found the

03:31:54.467 --> 03:31:59.027
harbor unsteered save by the hand of a dead man.

03:32:00.147 --> 03:32:05.107
However, all took place more quickly than it takes to write these words.

03:32:06.327 --> 03:32:12.767
The schooner paused not, but, rushing across the harbor, pitched herself on that accumulation

03:32:12.767 --> 03:32:18.987
of sand and gravel washed by many tides and many storms, into the southeast corner of

03:32:18.987 --> 03:32:23.547
the pier jutting under the east cliff, known locally as Tate Hill Pier.

03:32:24.727 --> 03:32:30.467
There was, of course, a considerable concussion as the vessel drove up on the sand-heap.

03:32:30.767 --> 03:32:38.087
Every spar, rope, and stay was strained, and some of the top-hammer came crashing down,

03:32:38.567 --> 03:32:47.607
but strangest of all, the very instant the shore was touched an immense dog sprang up

03:32:47.607 --> 03:32:54.727
on deck from below as if shot up by the concussion, and running forward jumped from the bow on

03:32:54.727 --> 03:33:01.187
the sand, making straight for the steep cliff where the churchyard hangs over the laneway

03:33:01.187 --> 03:33:07.867
to the east pier so steeply that some of the flat tombstones, thruff-steens or through-stones

03:33:07.867 --> 03:33:13.127
as they call them in the Whitby vernacular, actually project over where the sustaining

03:33:13.127 --> 03:33:14.507
cliff has fallen away.

03:33:15.527 --> 03:33:21.487
It disappeared in the darkness, which seemed intensified just beyond the focus of the search-light.

03:33:22.807 --> 03:33:28.047
It so happened that there was no one at the moment on Tate Hill Pier, as all those whose

03:33:28.047 --> 03:33:33.647
houses are in close proximity were either in bed or were out on the heights above.

03:33:34.447 --> 03:33:40.087
Thus the Coast Guard on duty on the eastern side of the harbor, who at once ran down to

03:33:40.087 --> 03:33:43.027
the little pier, was the first to climb aboard.

03:33:43.987 --> 03:33:48.347
The men working the search-light after scouring the entrance of the harbor without seeing

03:33:48.347 --> 03:33:52.807
anything, then turned the light on the derelict and kept it there.

03:33:53.387 --> 03:33:59.607
The Coast Guard ran aft, and when he came beside the wheel bent over to examine it,

03:34:00.047 --> 03:34:04.047
and recoiled at once as though under some sudden emotion.

03:34:05.567 --> 03:34:10.367
This seemed to pique general curiosity, and quite a number of people began to run.

03:34:11.147 --> 03:34:17.307
It was a good way round from the west cliff by the drawbridge to Tate Hill Pier, but your

03:34:17.307 --> 03:34:21.127
correspondent is a fairly good runner, and came well ahead of the crowd.

03:34:21.967 --> 03:34:27.727
When I arrived, however, I found already assembled on the pier a crowd, whom the Coast Guard

03:34:27.727 --> 03:34:30.807
and police refused to allow to come on board.

03:34:31.947 --> 03:34:37.867
By the courtesy of the Chief Boatman, I was, as your correspondent, permitted to climb

03:34:37.867 --> 03:34:44.387
on deck, and was one of a small group who saw the dead seaman whilst actually lashed

03:34:44.387 --> 03:34:45.327
to the wheel.

03:34:46.027 --> 03:34:54.007
It was no wonder that the Coast Guard was surprised, or even awed, for not often can

03:34:54.007 --> 03:34:56.107
such a sight have been seen.

03:34:56.967 --> 03:35:04.067
The man was simply fastened by his hands, tied one over the other, to a spoke of the

03:35:04.067 --> 03:35:04.427
wheel.

03:35:05.367 --> 03:35:12.387
Between the inner hand and the wood was a crucifix, the set of beads on which it was

03:35:12.387 --> 03:35:18.687
fastened being around both wrists and wheel, and all kept fast by the binding cords.

03:35:19.687 --> 03:35:25.967
The poor fellow may have been seated at one time, but the flapping and buffeting of the

03:35:25.967 --> 03:35:31.827
sails had worked through the rudder of the wheel, and had dragged him to and fro, so

03:35:31.827 --> 03:35:35.967
that the cords with which he was tied had cut the flesh to the bone.

03:35:37.527 --> 03:35:44.147
Accurate note was made of the state of things in a doctor, Surgeon J. M. Caffin of 33 East

03:35:44.147 --> 03:35:50.147
place, who came immediately after me, declared after making examination that the man must

03:35:50.147 --> 03:35:52.867
have been dead for quite two days.

03:35:54.267 --> 03:36:02.247
In his pocket was a bottle, carefully corked, empty save for a little roll of paper, which

03:36:02.247 --> 03:36:04.447
proved to be the addendum to the log.

03:36:05.707 --> 03:36:10.747
The Coast Guard said the man must have tied up his own hands, fastening the knots with

03:36:10.747 --> 03:36:11.427
his teeth.

03:36:12.267 --> 03:36:17.047
The fact that a Coast Guard was the first on board may save some complications later

03:36:17.047 --> 03:36:23.067
on in the Admiralty Court, for Coast Guards cannot claim the salvage which is the right

03:36:23.067 --> 03:36:25.467
of the first civilian entering on a derelict.

03:36:27.227 --> 03:36:32.767
Already however the legal tongues are wagging, and one young law student is loudly asserting

03:36:32.767 --> 03:36:39.667
that the rights of the owner are already completely sacrificed, his property being held in contravention

03:36:39.667 --> 03:36:46.227
of the statutes of Mort Main, since the tiller, as emblemship, if not proof, of delegated

03:36:46.227 --> 03:36:49.387
possession, is held in a dead hand.

03:36:50.217 --> 03:36:56.167
It is needless to say that the dead steersman has been reverently removed from the place

03:36:56.167 --> 03:37:03.827
where he held his honorable watch and ward till death, a steadfastness as noble as that

03:37:03.827 --> 03:37:09.667
of the young Casabianca, and placed in the mortuary to await inquest.

03:37:10.587 --> 03:37:17.207
Already the sudden storm is passing, and its fierceness is abating, crowds are scattering

03:37:17.207 --> 03:37:21.927
backward and the sky is beginning to redden over the Yorkshire wolds.

03:37:23.547 --> 03:37:29.667
I shall send, in time for your next issue, further details of the derelict ship which

03:37:29.667 --> 03:37:34.167
her way so miraculously into harbor in the storm.

03:37:38.667 --> 03:37:44.107
The sequel to the strange arrival of the derelict in the storm last night is almost more startling

03:37:44.107 --> 03:37:45.127
than the thing itself.

03:37:45.607 --> 03:37:51.227
It turns out that the schooner is Russian from Varna, and is called the Demeter.

03:37:52.107 --> 03:37:58.627
She is also entirely imbalanced of silver sand, with only a small amount of cargo, a

03:37:58.627 --> 03:38:02.467
number of great wooden box, filled with mold.

03:38:03.307 --> 03:38:11.327
This cargo was consigned to a Whitby solicitor, Mr. S. F. Billington, of Seven the Crescent,

03:38:11.747 --> 03:38:15.627
who this morning went aboard and took formal possession of the goods consigned to him.

03:38:16.527 --> 03:38:22.467
The Russian consul, too, acting for the Charter Party, took formal possession of the ship,

03:38:22.887 --> 03:38:25.027
and paid all harbor dues, etc.

03:38:25.767 --> 03:38:29.667
Nothing is talked about here today except the strange coincidence.

03:38:30.587 --> 03:38:35.487
The officials of the Board of Trade have been most exacting in seeing that every compliance

03:38:35.487 --> 03:38:37.787
has been made with existing regulations.

03:38:39.427 --> 03:38:45.507
As the matter is to be a nine days' wonder, they are evidently determined that there shall

03:38:45.507 --> 03:38:47.547
be no cause of other complaint.

03:38:48.747 --> 03:38:53.687
A good deal of interest was abroad concerning the dog which landed when the ship struck,

03:38:54.027 --> 03:38:59.487
and more than a few of the members of the SPCA, which is very strong in Whitby, have

03:38:59.487 --> 03:39:01.067
tried to befriend the animal.

03:39:01.687 --> 03:39:05.007
To the general disappointment, however, it was not to be found.

03:39:05.807 --> 03:39:08.687
It seems to have disappeared entirely from the town.

03:39:09.727 --> 03:39:15.087
It may be that it was frightened, and made its way on to the moors, where it is still

03:39:15.087 --> 03:39:16.467
hiding in terror.

03:39:17.067 --> 03:39:23.047
There are some who look with dread on such a possibility, lest later on it should in

03:39:23.047 --> 03:39:27.467
itself become a danger, for it is evidently a fierce brute.

03:39:28.887 --> 03:39:33.887
Early this morning a large dog, a half-bred mastiff belonging to a coal merchant close

03:39:33.887 --> 03:39:39.287
to Tate Hill Pier, was found dead in the roadway opposite its master's yard.

03:39:40.047 --> 03:39:48.007
It had been fighting, and manifestly had had a savage opponent, for its throat was torn

03:39:48.007 --> 03:39:52.627
away, and its belly was slit open as if with a savage claw.

03:39:53.667 --> 03:39:54.167
Later.

03:39:55.127 --> 03:40:00.187
By the kindness of the board of trade inspector I have been permitted to look over the logbook

03:40:00.187 --> 03:40:06.587
of the demeter, which was in order up to within three days, but contained nothing of special

03:40:06.587 --> 03:40:10.067
interest except as to facts of missing men.

03:40:10.927 --> 03:40:16.347
The greatest interest, however, is with regard to the paper found in the bottle which was

03:40:16.347 --> 03:40:22.227
today produced at the inquest, and a more strange narrative than the two between them

03:40:22.227 --> 03:40:25.787
unfold, and has not been my lot to come across.

03:40:26.607 --> 03:40:32.227
As there is no motive for concealment I am permitted to use them, and accordingly send

03:40:32.227 --> 03:40:37.527
you a transcript, simply omitting technical details of seamanship and supercargo.

03:40:38.067 --> 03:40:44.127
It almost seems as though the captain had been seized with some kind of mania before

03:40:44.127 --> 03:40:49.267
he had got well into blue water, and that this had developed persistently throughout

03:40:49.267 --> 03:40:49.907
the voyage.

03:40:51.207 --> 03:40:56.967
Of course, my statement must be taken cum grano, since I am writing from the dictation

03:40:56.967 --> 03:41:02.787
of a clerk of the Russian Council, who kindly translated for me, time being short.

03:41:03.547 --> 03:41:07.507
Log of the Demeter, Varna to Whitby.

03:41:07.787 --> 03:41:09.387
Written 18th of July.

03:41:10.327 --> 03:41:16.007
Things so strange happening that I shall keep accurate note henceforth till we land.

03:41:16.807 --> 03:41:23.027
On 6th July we finish taking in cargo, silver sand and boxes of earth.

03:41:24.147 --> 03:41:25.687
At noon set sail.

03:41:26.807 --> 03:41:33.407
East wind fresh, crew five hands, two mates cook, and myself captain.

03:41:34.147 --> 03:41:43.907
On 11th July, at dawn entered Bosphorus, boarded by Turkish customs officers, Bakshish, all

03:41:43.907 --> 03:41:46.927
correct, under way at 4 p.m.

03:41:47.127 --> 03:41:55.947
On 12th July, through Dardanelles, more customs officers and flag-boat of guarding squadron,

03:41:56.607 --> 03:42:02.607
Bakshish again, work of officers thorough but quick, want us off soon.

03:42:03.197 --> 03:42:05.967
At dark passed into Archipelago.

03:42:06.727 --> 03:42:10.067
On 13th July passed Cape Matapin.

03:42:10.407 --> 03:42:16.927
Crew dissatisfied about something, seemed scared, but would not speak out.

03:42:18.007 --> 03:42:21.807
On 14th July was somewhat anxious about crew.

03:42:22.827 --> 03:42:29.527
Men, all steady fellows who sailed with me before, mate could not make out what was wrong.

03:42:30.107 --> 03:42:35.167
They only told him there was something, and crossed themselves.

03:42:36.367 --> 03:42:39.167
Mate lost temper with one of them that day and struck him.

03:42:40.247 --> 03:42:43.607
Expected fierce quarrel, but all was quiet.

03:42:44.487 --> 03:42:51.127
On 16th July, mate reported in the morning that one of the crew, Petrovsky, was missing,

03:42:51.967 --> 03:42:53.727
could not account for it.

03:42:53.727 --> 03:43:00.247
Took-larbered watch eight bells last night, was relieved by Amramov, but did not go to

03:43:00.247 --> 03:43:00.467
bunk.

03:43:01.307 --> 03:43:09.307
Men, more downcast than ever, all said they expected something of the kind, but would

03:43:09.307 --> 03:43:13.527
not say more than there was something aboard.

03:43:15.047 --> 03:43:19.567
Mate getting very impatient with them, feared some trouble ahead.

03:43:21.027 --> 03:43:28.367
On 17th July, yesterday, one of the men, Olgaren, came to my cabin, and in an awe-struck way

03:43:28.367 --> 03:43:32.927
confided to me that he thought there was a strange man aboard the ship.

03:43:33.887 --> 03:43:39.947
He said that in his watch he had been sheltering behind the deck-house, as there was a rainstorm,

03:43:40.527 --> 03:43:47.507
when he saw a tall, thin man who was not like any of the crew come up the companion-way

03:43:47.787 --> 03:43:50.567
and go along the deck forward and disappear.

03:43:51.467 --> 03:43:57.107
He followed cautiously, but when he got to bows found no one, and the hatchways were

03:43:57.107 --> 03:43:57.867
all closed.

03:43:58.567 --> 03:44:03.147
He was in a panic of superstitious fear, and I am afraid the panic may spread.

03:44:04.227 --> 03:44:09.507
To allay it, I shall today search the entire ship carefully from stem to stern.

03:44:10.587 --> 03:44:14.847
Later in the day I got together the whole crew and told them, as they evidently thought

03:44:14.847 --> 03:44:19.767
there was some one in the ship, we would search from stem to stern.

03:44:20.867 --> 03:44:26.187
First mate angry said it was folly, and to yield to such foolish ideas would demoralize

03:44:26.187 --> 03:44:26.747
the men.

03:44:27.607 --> 03:44:31.047
Said he would engage to keep them out of trouble with the hand-spike.

03:44:32.627 --> 03:44:38.307
I let him take the helm, while the rest began a thorough search, all keeping abreast with

03:44:39.167 --> 03:44:39.727
lanterns.

03:44:39.767 --> 03:44:42.647
We left no corner unsearched.

03:44:43.057 --> 03:44:48.967
As there were only the big wooden boxes there were no odd corners where a man could hide.

03:44:50.127 --> 03:44:54.087
Men much relieved went search over, and went back to work cheerfully.

03:44:55.207 --> 03:44:57.527
First mate scowled, but said nothing.

03:44:58.547 --> 03:44:59.587
22 July.

03:45:00.887 --> 03:45:05.767
Rough weather lasts three days and all hands busy with sails, no time to be frightened.

03:45:07.007 --> 03:45:08.907
Men seem to have forgotten their dread.

03:45:09.627 --> 03:45:17.887
Mate cheerful again, and all on good terms, praised men for work and bad weather, past

03:45:17.887 --> 03:45:20.547
Gibraltar and out through Straits.

03:45:21.707 --> 03:45:22.587
All well.

03:45:23.667 --> 03:45:24.667
24 July.

03:45:25.707 --> 03:45:28.787
There seems some doom over this ship.

03:45:30.207 --> 03:45:36.107
Already a hand short and entering the Bay of Biscay with wild weather ahead, and yet

03:45:36.107 --> 03:45:41.967
Last night another man lost, disappeared, like the first.

03:45:42.667 --> 03:45:45.167
He came off his watch and was not seen again.

03:45:46.067 --> 03:45:52.847
Men all in a panic of fear, sent a round robin asking to have double watch, as they fear

03:45:52.847 --> 03:45:53.767
to be alone.

03:45:54.927 --> 03:46:00.767
Mate angry, fear there will be some trouble, as either he or the men will do some violence.

03:46:01.887 --> 03:46:03.047
28 July.

03:46:03.767 --> 03:46:11.867
Four days in hell, knocking about in a sort of maelstrom, and the wind a tempest, no sleep

03:46:11.867 --> 03:46:14.587
for anyone, men all worn out.

03:46:15.327 --> 03:46:18.707
Hardly know how to set a watch since no one fit to go on.

03:46:19.727 --> 03:46:25.007
Second mate volunteered to steer and watch, and let men snatch a few hours' sleep.

03:46:26.187 --> 03:46:31.067
Wind abating, seas still terrific, but feel them less.

03:46:31.467 --> 03:46:33.187
A ship is steadier.

03:46:34.007 --> 03:46:35.127
29 July.

03:46:36.927 --> 03:46:38.107
Another tragedy.

03:46:39.587 --> 03:46:42.727
Had single watch to-night as crew too tired to double.

03:46:43.927 --> 03:46:47.747
When morning watch came on deck could find no one except steersman.

03:46:49.167 --> 03:46:55.327
Raised outcry and all came on deck, thorough search, but no one was found.

03:46:56.687 --> 03:47:00.907
Are now without second mate, and crew in a panic.

03:47:02.127 --> 03:47:06.847
Mate and I agreed to go armed henceforth and wait for any sign of cause.

03:47:07.987 --> 03:47:08.907
30 July.

03:47:09.887 --> 03:47:10.647
Last night.

03:47:11.607 --> 03:47:15.687
Rejoiced we are nearing England, weather fine, all sails set.

03:47:16.967 --> 03:47:23.967
Retired, worn out, slept soundly, awakened by mate telling me that both men of watch

03:47:23.967 --> 03:47:26.167
and steersman missing.

03:47:27.347 --> 03:47:31.827
Only self and mate and two hands left to work ship.

03:47:32.787 --> 03:47:33.727
One August.

03:47:34.647 --> 03:47:37.867
Two days of fog, and not a sail sighted.

03:47:38.647 --> 03:47:42.867
Had hoped when in the English Channel to be able to signal for help or get in somewhere.

03:47:43.987 --> 03:47:47.927
Not having power to work sails, have to run before wind.

03:47:48.847 --> 03:47:52.007
Dare not lower, as could not raise them again.

03:47:52.707 --> 03:47:57.467
We seem to be drifting to some terrible doom.

03:47:58.987 --> 03:48:02.007
Mate now more demoralized than either of men.

03:48:02.787 --> 03:48:06.167
His stronger nature seems to have worked inwardly against himself.

03:48:07.467 --> 03:48:14.207
Men are beyond fear, working stolidly and patiently with minds made up to worst.

03:48:15.247 --> 03:48:16.647
They are Russian.

03:48:17.607 --> 03:48:18.467
Heave Romanian.

03:48:19.707 --> 03:48:20.907
Two August.

03:48:21.967 --> 03:48:22.567
Midnight.

03:48:23.407 --> 03:48:29.007
Woke up from few minutes' sleep by hearing a cry, seemingly outside my port.

03:48:30.027 --> 03:48:33.327
Could see nothing in fog, rushed on deck and ran against mate.

03:48:34.087 --> 03:48:38.987
Tells me he heard cry and ran, but no sign of man on watch.

03:48:40.227 --> 03:48:41.187
One more gone.

03:48:42.427 --> 03:48:44.127
Lord, help us.

03:48:44.847 --> 03:48:51.207
Mate says we must be past Straits of Dover, as in a moment of fog lifting we saw north

03:48:51.207 --> 03:48:54.867
foreland, just as he heard the man cry out.

03:48:55.947 --> 03:49:01.727
If so, we are now off in the North Sea, and only God can guide us in the fog, which seems

03:49:01.727 --> 03:49:06.687
to move with us, and God seems to have deserted us.

03:49:07.647 --> 03:49:08.687
Three August.

03:49:10.407 --> 03:49:16.867
At midnight I went to relieve the man at the wheel, and when I got to it found no one there.

03:49:18.247 --> 03:49:23.407
The wind was steady, and as we ran before it there was no yawing.

03:49:24.147 --> 03:49:27.507
I dared not leave it, so shouted for the mate.

03:49:29.287 --> 03:49:33.207
After a few seconds he rushed up on deck in his flannels.

03:49:33.947 --> 03:49:39.927
He looked wild-eyed and haggard, and I greatly fear his reason has given way.

03:49:41.147 --> 03:49:48.047
He came close to me, and he whispered hoarsely with his mouth to my ear, as though fearing

03:49:48.047 --> 03:49:49.607
the very air might hear.

03:49:50.507 --> 03:49:51.887
It is here.

03:49:52.627 --> 03:49:54.407
I know it now.

03:49:54.647 --> 03:49:58.047
On the watch last night I saw it.

03:49:58.047 --> 03:50:05.187
Like a man, tall and thin and ghastly pale, it was in the boughs and looking out.

03:50:05.907 --> 03:50:14.767
I crept behind it and gave it my knife, but the knife went through it, empty as the air.

03:50:15.847 --> 03:50:20.987
And as he spoke he took the knife and drove it savagely into space, then he went on.

03:50:21.927 --> 03:50:26.867
But it is here, and I'll find it.

03:50:26.927 --> 03:50:29.647
It is in the hold, perhaps in one of those boxes.

03:50:30.287 --> 03:50:34.527
I'll unscrew them one by one and see you work the helm.

03:50:35.607 --> 03:50:40.707
And with a warning look and his finger on his lip he went below.

03:50:41.807 --> 03:50:45.547
There was springing up a choppy wind, and I could not leave the helm.

03:50:46.367 --> 03:50:52.367
I saw him come out on deck again with a tool-chest and lantern, and go down the forward hatchway.

03:50:53.307 --> 03:51:00.267
He's mad, stark, raving, mad, and it's no use my trying to stop him.

03:51:00.867 --> 03:51:07.267
He can't hurt those big boxes, they are invoiced as clay, and to pull them about is as harmless

03:51:07.267 --> 03:51:08.547
a thing as he can do.

03:51:09.267 --> 03:51:15.047
So here I stay and mind the helm and write these notes.

03:51:16.287 --> 03:51:21.387
I can only trust in God and wait till the fog clears.

03:51:22.487 --> 03:51:29.567
Then, if I can't steer to any harbor with the wind that is, I shall cut down sails and

03:51:29.567 --> 03:51:31.907
lie by and signal for help.

03:51:32.487 --> 03:51:34.887
It is nearly all over now.

03:51:35.967 --> 03:51:42.507
Just as I was beginning to hope that the mate would come out calmer, for I heard him knocking

03:51:42.507 --> 03:51:49.707
away at something in the hold, and work is good for him, there came up the hatchway a

03:51:49.707 --> 03:51:59.587
sudden, startled scream which made my blood run cold, and up on the deck he came as if

03:51:59.587 --> 03:52:07.087
shot from a gun, a raging madman with his eyes rolling and his face convulsed with fear.

03:52:09.907 --> 03:52:17.147
Save me, save me, he cried, and then looked round on the blanket of fog.

03:52:17.787 --> 03:52:24.687
His horror turned to despair, and in a steady voice he said, You had better come too, captain,

03:52:25.507 --> 03:52:27.107
before it is too late.

03:52:28.227 --> 03:52:30.367
He is there.

03:52:31.167 --> 03:52:32.867
I know the secret now.

03:52:33.687 --> 03:52:39.327
The sea will save me from him, and it is all that is left.

03:52:41.007 --> 03:52:48.107
Before I could say a word or move forward to seize him, he sprang on the bulwark and

03:52:48.107 --> 03:52:50.807
deliberately threw himself into the sea.

03:52:51.787 --> 03:52:54.507
I suppose I know the secret too now.

03:52:54.507 --> 03:53:03.327
It was this madman who had got rid of the men one by one, and now he has followed them

03:53:03.327 --> 03:53:04.007
himself.

03:53:05.827 --> 03:53:07.407
God help me!

03:53:08.027 --> 03:53:12.287
How am I to account for all these horrors when I get to port?

03:53:13.687 --> 03:53:18.387
When I get to port, will that ever be?

03:53:19.087 --> 03:53:20.447
4 August.

03:53:21.447 --> 03:53:25.567
Still fog, which the sunrise cannot pierce.

03:53:26.287 --> 03:53:30.487
I know there is sunrise, because I am a sailor.

03:53:30.987 --> 03:53:32.467
Why else I know not?

03:53:33.327 --> 03:53:34.987
I dared not go below.

03:53:35.767 --> 03:53:43.567
I dared not leave the helm, so here all night I stayed, and in the dimness of night I saw

03:53:43.567 --> 03:53:43.807
it.

03:53:45.087 --> 03:53:45.667
Him.

03:53:48.347 --> 03:53:53.007
God forgive me, but the mate was right to jump overboard.

03:53:53.907 --> 03:54:01.147
It was better to die like a man, to die like a sailor in blue water no man can object.

03:54:02.587 --> 03:54:07.107
But I am captain, and I must not leave my ship.

03:54:08.027 --> 03:54:16.187
But I shall baffle this fiend or monster, for I shall tie my hands to the wheel when

03:54:16.187 --> 03:54:24.507
my strength begins to fail, and along with them I shall tie that which he, it, dare not

03:54:24.507 --> 03:54:24.947
touch.

03:54:26.107 --> 03:54:34.587
And then, come good wind or foul, I shall save my soul, and my honor as captain.

03:54:35.447 --> 03:54:40.027
I am growing weaker, and the night is coming on.

03:54:41.247 --> 03:54:46.527
If he can look me in the face again, I may not have time to act.

03:54:47.387 --> 03:54:55.927
If we are wrecked, mayhap this bottle may be found, and those who find it may understand.

03:54:57.227 --> 03:55:05.427
If not, well, then all men shall know that I have been true to my trust.

03:55:06.787 --> 03:55:15.827
God and the Blessed Virgin and the Saints help a poor ignorant soul trying to do his

03:55:15.827 --> 03:55:16.367
duty.

03:55:18.947 --> 03:55:21.087
Of course the verdict was an open one.

03:55:21.087 --> 03:55:25.727
There is no evidence to adduce, and whether or not the man himself committed the murders

03:55:25.727 --> 03:55:27.387
there is now none to say.

03:55:28.547 --> 03:55:34.367
The folk here hold almost universally that the captain is simply a hero, and he is to

03:55:34.367 --> 03:55:35.587
be given a public funeral.

03:55:37.027 --> 03:55:42.187
Already it is arranged that his body is to be taken with a train of boats up the Esk

03:55:42.187 --> 03:55:48.647
for a piece, and then brought back to Tate Hill Pier and up the Abbey Steps, for he is

03:55:48.647 --> 03:55:50.607
to be buried in the churchyard on the cliff.

03:55:51.527 --> 03:55:56.447
The owners of more than a hundred boats have already given in their names as wishing to

03:55:56.447 --> 03:55:57.707
follow him to the grave.

03:55:59.367 --> 03:56:05.467
No trace has ever been found of the great dog, at which there is much mourning, for,

03:56:06.047 --> 03:56:11.107
with public opinion in its present state, he would, I believe, be adopted by the town.

03:56:11.987 --> 03:56:20.667
Tomorrow we'll see the funeral, and so will end this one more Mystery of the Sea.

03:56:22.607 --> 03:56:26.707
Mina Murray's Journal 8 August

03:56:28.447 --> 03:56:33.147
Lucy was very restless all night, and I too could not sleep.

03:56:33.947 --> 03:56:42.387
The storm was fearful, and as it boomed loudly among the chimney-pots it made me shudder.

03:56:42.987 --> 03:56:47.707
When a sharp puff came it seemed to be like a distant gun.

03:56:48.927 --> 03:56:53.707
Strangely enough Lucy did not wake, but she got up twice and dressed herself.

03:56:54.867 --> 03:57:00.647
Fortunately each time I awoke in time and managed to undress her without waking her,

03:57:00.647 --> 03:57:02.167
got her back to bed.

03:57:03.147 --> 03:57:09.887
It is a very strange thing, this sleep-walking, for as soon as her will is thwarted in any

03:57:09.887 --> 03:57:16.967
physical way, her intention, if there be any, disappears, and she yields herself almost

03:57:16.967 --> 03:57:19.367
exactly to the routine of her life.

03:57:20.427 --> 03:57:25.887
Early in the morning we both got up and went down to the harbor to see if anything had

03:57:25.887 --> 03:57:26.887
happened in the night.

03:57:27.607 --> 03:57:32.827
There were very few people about, and though the sun was bright and the air clear and fresh,

03:57:33.447 --> 03:57:39.787
the big grim-looking waves that seemed dark themselves, because the foam that topped them

03:57:39.787 --> 03:57:46.487
was like snow, forced themselves in through the mouth of the harbor, like a bullying man

03:57:46.487 --> 03:57:47.527
going through a crowd.

03:57:48.627 --> 03:57:54.047
Somehow I felt glad that Jonathan was not on the sea last night, but on land.

03:57:54.867 --> 03:57:59.207
But, oh, is he on land or sea?

03:58:00.367 --> 03:58:01.927
Where is he?

03:58:02.427 --> 03:58:03.427
And how?

03:58:04.387 --> 03:58:11.587
I am getting fearfully anxious about him, if I only knew what to do, and could do anything.

03:58:12.567 --> 03:58:13.827
10 August

03:58:15.367 --> 03:58:19.507
The funeral of the poor sea-captain today was most touching.

03:58:20.027 --> 03:58:25.167
Every boat in the harbor seemed to be there, and the coffin was carried by captains all

03:58:25.167 --> 03:58:27.747
the way from Tate Hill Pier up to the churchyard.

03:58:28.967 --> 03:58:35.667
Lucy came with me, and we went early to our old seat, whilst the cortege of boats went

03:58:35.667 --> 03:58:38.827
up the river to the viaduct and came down again.

03:58:39.767 --> 03:58:43.687
We had a lovely view and saw the procession nearly all the way.

03:58:44.547 --> 03:58:49.907
The poor fellow was laid to rest near our seat, so that we stood on it when the time

03:58:49.907 --> 03:58:51.467
came and saw everything.

03:58:53.187 --> 03:58:55.167
Poor Lucy seemed much upset.

03:58:55.807 --> 03:59:02.467
She was restless and uneasy all the time, and I cannot but think that her dreaming at

03:59:02.467 --> 03:59:04.047
night is telling on her.

03:59:04.807 --> 03:59:07.627
She is quite odd in one thing.

03:59:08.507 --> 03:59:14.147
She will not admit to me that there is any cause for restlessness, or if there be, she

03:59:14.147 --> 03:59:16.107
does not understand it herself.

03:59:17.047 --> 03:59:23.707
There is an additional cause, in that poor Mr. Swales was found dead this morning on

03:59:23.707 --> 03:59:26.647
our seat, his neck being broken.

03:59:27.347 --> 03:59:33.327
He had evidently, as the doctor said, fallen back in the seat in some sort of fright, for

03:59:33.327 --> 03:59:39.727
there was a look of fear and horror on his face that the men said made them shudder.

03:59:40.287 --> 03:59:42.187
Poor dear old man.

03:59:43.587 --> 03:59:48.947
Lucy is so sweet and sensitive that she feels influences more acutely than other people

03:59:48.947 --> 03:59:49.487
do.

03:59:50.207 --> 03:59:57.287
Just now she was quite upset by a little thing which I did not much heed, though I am myself

03:59:57.287 --> 03:59:58.607
very fond of animals.

03:59:59.407 --> 04:00:05.107
One of the men who came up here often to look for the boats was followed by his dog.

04:00:05.907 --> 04:00:07.527
The dog is always with him.

04:00:07.947 --> 04:00:13.347
They are both quiet persons, and I never saw the man angry nor heard the dog bark.

04:00:14.407 --> 04:00:21.547
During the service the dog would not come to its master, who was on the seat with us,

04:00:22.047 --> 04:00:25.447
but kept a few yards off barking and howling.

04:00:26.327 --> 04:00:32.947
Its master spoke to it gently, and then harshly, and then angrily, but it would neither come

04:00:32.947 --> 04:00:34.867
nor cease to make a noise.

04:00:35.787 --> 04:00:42.547
It was in a fury, with its eyes savage and all its hair bristling out like a cat's tail

04:00:42.547 --> 04:00:44.767
when puss is on the war path.

04:00:45.967 --> 04:00:51.327
Finally the man, too, got angry, and jumped down and kicked the dog, and then took it

04:00:51.327 --> 04:00:55.787
by the strough of the neck, and half dragged and half threw it on the tombstone on which

04:00:55.787 --> 04:00:57.027
the seat is fixed.

04:00:57.787 --> 04:01:02.507
The moment it touched the stone the poor thing began to tremble.

04:01:02.987 --> 04:01:10.247
It did not try to get away, but crouched down, quivering and cowering, and was in such a

04:01:10.247 --> 04:01:15.987
pitiable state of terror that I tried, though without effect, to comfort it.

04:01:16.627 --> 04:01:23.687
Lucy was full of pity, too, but she did not attempt to touch the dog, but looked at it

04:01:23.687 --> 04:01:25.927
in an agonized sort of way.

04:01:26.647 --> 04:01:33.207
I greatly fear that she is of too supersensitive a nature to go through the world without trouble.

04:01:34.547 --> 04:01:37.487
She will be dreaming of this to-night, I am sure.

04:01:38.287 --> 04:01:45.347
The whole agglomeration of things, the ship steered into port by a dead man, his attitude

04:01:45.347 --> 04:01:53.147
tied to the wheel with a crucifix and beads, the touching funeral, the dog, now furious

04:01:53.147 --> 04:01:58.367
and now in terror, will all afford material for her dreams.

04:01:59.427 --> 04:02:05.707
I think it will be best for her to go to bed tired out physically, so I shall take her

04:02:05.707 --> 04:02:10.067
for a long walk by the cliffs to Robin Hood's Bay and back.

04:02:10.067 --> 04:02:13.967
She ought not to have much inclination for sleep-walking then.

04:02:38.156 --> 04:02:39.016
Same day.

04:02:39.016 --> 04:02:40.396
Eleven o'clock p.m.

04:02:40.696 --> 04:02:42.376
Oh, but I am tired.

04:02:42.976 --> 04:02:47.196
If it were not that I had made my diary a duty, I could not open it tonight.

04:02:48.216 --> 04:02:49.316
We had a lovely walk.

04:02:50.376 --> 04:02:56.556
Lucy, after a while, was in gay spirits, owing, I think, to some dear cows who came nosing

04:02:56.556 --> 04:03:00.696
towards us in a field close to the lighthouse, and frightened the wits out of us.

04:03:01.736 --> 04:03:05.876
I believe we forgot everything, except, of course, personal fear.

04:03:06.456 --> 04:03:09.916
And it seemed to wipe the slate clean and give us a fresh start.

04:03:10.936 --> 04:03:17.116
We had a capital severe tea at Robin Hood's Bay, in a sweet little old-fashioned inn,

04:03:17.716 --> 04:03:21.556
with a bow-window right over the seaweed-covered rocks of the Strand.

04:03:23.336 --> 04:03:26.876
I believe we should have shocked the new woman with our appetites.

04:03:27.936 --> 04:03:29.896
Men are more tolerant, bless them.

04:03:30.976 --> 04:03:35.156
Then we walked home with some, or rather many, stoppages to rest,

04:03:35.876 --> 04:03:39.276
and with our hearts full of constant dread of wild bulls.

04:03:41.376 --> 04:03:46.516
Lucy was really tired, and we intended to creep off to bed as soon as we could.

04:03:48.136 --> 04:03:53.036
The young curate came in, however, and Mrs. Westenra asked him to stay for supper.

04:03:54.976 --> 04:03:57.996
Lucy and I both had a fight for it with the dusty miller.

04:03:59.016 --> 04:04:02.476
I know it was a hard fight on my part, and I am quite heroic.

04:04:03.596 --> 04:04:06.916
I think that some day the bishops must get together,

04:04:07.456 --> 04:04:09.636
and see about breeding up a new class of curates,

04:04:10.076 --> 04:04:13.196
who don't take supper, no matter how hard they may be pressed to,

04:04:13.296 --> 04:04:15.576
and who will know when girls are tired.

04:04:17.416 --> 04:04:19.276
Lucy is asleep and breathing softly.

04:04:20.376 --> 04:04:24.296
She has more color in her cheeks than usual, and looks oh so sweet.

04:04:25.876 --> 04:04:29.476
If Mr. Homewood fell in love with her, seeing her only in the drawing-room,

04:04:29.476 --> 04:04:32.396
I wonder what he would say if he saw her now.

04:04:33.756 --> 04:04:36.816
Some of the new women writers will some day start an idea

04:04:36.816 --> 04:04:41.116
that men and women should be allowed to see each other asleep before proposing or accepting.

04:04:42.436 --> 04:04:45.996
But I suppose the new woman wouldn't condescend in future to accept.

04:04:46.776 --> 04:04:51.576
She will do the proposing herself, and a nice job she will make of it too.

04:04:52.236 --> 04:04:53.976
There's some consolation in that.

04:04:53.976 --> 04:04:58.976
I am happy tonight, because dear Lucy seems better.

04:05:00.376 --> 04:05:02.176
I really believe she has turned the corner,

04:05:02.876 --> 04:05:04.796
and that we are over her troubles with dreaming.

04:05:06.276 --> 04:05:08.756
I should be quite happy if only I knew of Jonathan.

04:05:09.716 --> 04:05:10.996
God bless and keep him.

04:05:13.336 --> 04:05:15.816
11th August. Diary again.

04:05:16.796 --> 04:05:18.976
No sleep now, so I may as well write.

04:05:19.396 --> 04:05:20.996
I am too agitated to sleep.

04:05:21.576 --> 04:05:25.196
We have had such an adventure, such an agonizing experience.

04:05:26.936 --> 04:05:29.136
I fell asleep as soon as I had closed my diary.

04:05:30.036 --> 04:05:35.936
Suddenly, I became broad awake and sat up, with a horrible sense of fear upon me,

04:05:36.176 --> 04:05:38.556
and of some feeling of emptiness around me.

04:05:39.396 --> 04:05:42.096
The room was dark, so I could not see Lucy's bed.

04:05:43.236 --> 04:05:46.856
I stole a cross and felt for her. The bed was empty.

04:05:48.616 --> 04:05:51.416
I lit a match and found that she was not in the room.

04:05:52.096 --> 04:05:54.916
The door was shut, but not locked as I had left it.

04:05:55.556 --> 04:05:59.136
I feared to wake her mother, who has been more than usually ill lately,

04:05:59.776 --> 04:06:02.276
so threw on some clothes and got ready to look for her.

04:06:03.556 --> 04:06:06.776
As I was leaving the room, it struck me that the clothes she wore

04:06:06.776 --> 04:06:09.176
might give me some clue to her dreaming intention.

04:06:10.476 --> 04:06:13.136
Dressing gown would mean house, dress outside.

04:06:14.496 --> 04:06:17.196
Dressing gown and dress were both in their places.

04:06:18.256 --> 04:06:23.456
Thank God, I said to myself, she cannot be far as she is only in her night dress.

04:06:25.916 --> 04:06:29.596
I ran downstairs and looked in the sitting room, not there.

04:06:30.596 --> 04:06:32.836
Then I looked in all the other rooms of the house,

04:06:33.196 --> 04:06:35.336
with an ever-growing fear chilling my heart.

04:06:36.436 --> 04:06:39.496
Finally, I came to the hall door and found it open.

04:06:39.496 --> 04:06:43.756
It was not wide open, but the catch of the lock had not caught.

04:06:45.236 --> 04:06:48.536
The people of the house are careful to lock the door every night,

04:06:48.956 --> 04:06:51.856
so I feared that Lucy must have gone out as she was.

04:06:52.916 --> 04:06:55.056
There was no time to think of what might happen.

04:06:55.936 --> 04:06:59.156
A vague, overmastering fear obscured all details.

04:07:01.656 --> 04:07:04.396
I took a big heavy shawl and ran out.

04:07:05.376 --> 04:07:08.256
The clock was striking one as I was in the crescent,

04:07:08.256 --> 04:07:10.496
and there was not a soul in sight.

04:07:11.776 --> 04:07:13.396
I ran along the north terrace,

04:07:13.976 --> 04:07:16.556
but could see no sign of the white figure which I expected.

04:07:18.416 --> 04:07:20.336
At the edge of the west cliff above the pier,

04:07:20.576 --> 04:07:22.536
I looked across the harbor to the east cliff,

04:07:23.176 --> 04:07:25.296
in the hope or fear, I don't know which,

04:07:25.876 --> 04:07:27.736
of seeing Lucy in our favorite seat.

04:07:30.196 --> 04:07:32.316
There was a bright, full moon,

04:07:32.956 --> 04:07:35.016
with heavy black, driving clouds,

04:07:35.016 --> 04:07:38.336
which threw the whole scene into a fleeting diorama

04:07:38.336 --> 04:07:40.716
of light and shade as they sailed across.

04:07:42.416 --> 04:07:44.476
For a moment or two, I could see nothing,

04:07:44.976 --> 04:07:49.416
as the shadow of a cloud obscured St. Mary's Church and all around it.

04:07:50.836 --> 04:07:52.256
Then, as the cloud passed,

04:07:52.616 --> 04:07:55.316
I could see the ruins of the abbey coming into view,

04:07:55.996 --> 04:07:58.196
and as the edge of a narrow band of light,

04:07:58.356 --> 04:08:00.396
as sharp as a sword cut moved along,

04:08:01.236 --> 04:08:04.416
the church and churchyard became gradually visible.

04:08:06.096 --> 04:08:08.916
Whatever my expectation was, it was not disappointed,

04:08:09.376 --> 04:08:10.856
for there, on our favorite seat,

04:08:11.356 --> 04:08:14.176
the silver light of the moon struck a half-reclining figure,

04:08:14.556 --> 04:08:15.196
snowy white.

04:08:17.156 --> 04:08:20.016
The coming of the cloud was too quick for me to see much,

04:08:20.656 --> 04:08:23.256
for the shadow shut down on the light almost immediately.

04:08:24.316 --> 04:08:27.256
But it seemed to me as if something dark stood behind the seat

04:08:27.256 --> 04:08:29.616
where the white figure shone and bent over it.

04:08:30.396 --> 04:08:34.036
What it was, whether man or beast, I could not tell.

04:08:36.796 --> 04:08:39.056
I did not wait to catch another glance,

04:08:39.736 --> 04:08:41.896
but flew down the steep steps to the pier

04:08:41.896 --> 04:08:44.436
and along by the fish market to the bridge,

04:08:45.056 --> 04:08:47.176
which was the only way to reach the east cliff.

04:08:48.516 --> 04:08:51.636
The town seemed as dead, for not a soul that I see.

04:08:52.816 --> 04:08:54.236
I rejoiced that it was so,

04:08:54.416 --> 04:08:57.076
for I wanted no witness of poor Lucy's condition.

04:08:58.396 --> 04:09:00.736
The time and distance seemed endless,

04:09:01.296 --> 04:09:04.016
and my knees trembled and my breath came labored

04:09:04.016 --> 04:09:06.856
as I toiled up the endless steps to the abbey.

04:09:07.876 --> 04:09:09.436
I must have gone fast,

04:09:09.716 --> 04:09:13.076
and yet it seemed to me as if my feet were weighted with lead,

04:09:13.776 --> 04:09:16.116
and as though every joint in my body were rusty.

04:09:18.476 --> 04:09:20.396
When I got almost to the top,

04:09:20.756 --> 04:09:22.736
I could see the seat and the white figure,

04:09:23.296 --> 04:09:25.616
for I was now close enough to distinguish it

04:09:25.616 --> 04:09:27.276
even through the spells of shadow.

04:09:28.756 --> 04:09:31.516
There was undoubtedly something, long and black,

04:09:31.516 --> 04:09:34.236
bending over the half-reclining white figure.

04:09:35.256 --> 04:09:36.196
I called in fright,

04:09:36.776 --> 04:09:38.036
Lucy, Lucy!

04:09:39.356 --> 04:09:40.976
and something raised ahead,

04:09:41.816 --> 04:09:44.376
and from where I was I could see a white face

04:09:44.376 --> 04:09:46.456
and red gleaming eyes.

04:09:48.596 --> 04:09:49.816
Lucy did not answer,

04:09:50.656 --> 04:09:52.716
and I ran onto the entrance of the churchyard.

04:09:53.776 --> 04:09:56.796
As I entered, the church was between me and the seat,

04:09:57.136 --> 04:09:59.476
and for a minute or so I lost sight of her.

04:10:00.956 --> 04:10:03.596
When I came in the view again, the cloud had passed,

04:10:04.156 --> 04:10:06.236
and the moonlight struck so brilliantly

04:10:06.236 --> 04:10:08.256
that I could see Lucy half-reclining

04:10:08.256 --> 04:10:10.336
with her head lying over the back of the seat.

04:10:11.516 --> 04:10:12.716
She was quite alone,

04:10:13.196 --> 04:10:15.596
and there was not a sign of any living thing about.

04:10:17.916 --> 04:10:19.396
When I bent over her,

04:10:19.556 --> 04:10:21.136
I could see that she was still asleep.

04:10:22.196 --> 04:10:23.696
Her lips were parted,

04:10:23.736 --> 04:10:24.776
and she was breathing,

04:10:25.196 --> 04:10:27.176
not softly as usual with her,

04:10:27.176 --> 04:10:29.276
but in long, heavy gasps,

04:10:30.156 --> 04:10:32.876
as though striving to get her lungs full at every breath.

04:10:34.676 --> 04:10:35.816
As I came close,

04:10:36.376 --> 04:10:37.876
she put up her hand in her sleep

04:10:37.876 --> 04:10:40.956
and pulled the collar of her nightdress close about her,

04:10:41.316 --> 04:10:42.536
as though she felt the cold.

04:10:44.076 --> 04:10:46.636
I flung the warm shawl over her,

04:10:46.956 --> 04:10:48.936
and drew the edges tight around her neck,

04:10:49.456 --> 04:10:52.296
for I dreaded lest she get some deadly chill from the night air,

04:10:52.456 --> 04:10:53.596
unclad as she was.

04:10:55.016 --> 04:10:56.856
I feared to wake her all at once,

04:10:56.996 --> 04:11:00.536
so, in order to have my hands free to help her,

04:11:00.856 --> 04:11:03.556
I fastened the shawl at her throat with a big safety pin.

04:11:04.656 --> 04:11:06.796
But I must have been clumsy in my anxiety

04:11:06.796 --> 04:11:09.056
and pinched or pricked her with it,

04:11:09.236 --> 04:11:12.076
for by and by, when her breathing became quieter,

04:11:12.816 --> 04:11:15.496
she put her hand to her throat again and moaned.

04:11:16.536 --> 04:11:18.096
When I had her carefully wrapped up,

04:11:18.196 --> 04:11:19.636
I put my shoes on her feet

04:11:19.636 --> 04:11:22.896
and then began very gently to wake her.

04:11:23.636 --> 04:11:26.496
At first, she did not respond,

04:11:27.036 --> 04:11:30.236
but gradually she became more and more uneasy in her sleep,

04:11:30.556 --> 04:11:32.016
moaning and sighing occasionally.

04:11:33.436 --> 04:11:35.696
At last, as time was passing fast,

04:11:35.776 --> 04:11:36.876
and for many other reasons,

04:11:37.316 --> 04:11:38.716
I wished to get her home at once,

04:11:39.156 --> 04:11:40.516
I shook her forcibly,

04:11:40.876 --> 04:11:43.216
till finally she opened her eyes and awoke.

04:11:44.436 --> 04:11:46.776
She did not seem surprised to see me,

04:11:46.936 --> 04:11:50.776
as, of course, she did not realize all at once where she was.

04:11:52.476 --> 04:11:54.176
Lucy always wakes pitifully,

04:11:54.776 --> 04:11:56.296
and even at such a time,

04:11:56.956 --> 04:11:59.096
when her body must have been chilled with cold

04:11:59.096 --> 04:12:03.356
and her mind somewhat appalled at waking unclad in a churchyard at night,

04:12:03.656 --> 04:12:04.856
she did not lose her grace.

04:12:05.836 --> 04:12:07.856
She trembled a little and clung to me.

04:12:08.756 --> 04:12:10.936
When I told her to come at once with me home,

04:12:11.236 --> 04:12:12.536
she rose without a word,

04:12:13.076 --> 04:12:14.696
with the obedience of a child.

04:12:15.736 --> 04:12:18.416
As we passed along, the gravel hurt my feet,

04:12:18.676 --> 04:12:20.116
and Lucy noticed me wince.

04:12:21.016 --> 04:12:24.696
She stopped and wanted to insist upon my taking my shoes,

04:12:24.936 --> 04:12:26.116
but I would not.

04:12:26.796 --> 04:12:30.216
However, when we got to the pathway outside the churchyard,

04:12:30.556 --> 04:12:32.956
where there was a puddle of water remaining from the storm,

04:12:33.496 --> 04:12:34.996
I daubed my feet with mud,

04:12:35.356 --> 04:12:37.436
using each foot in turn on the other,

04:12:37.756 --> 04:12:39.476
so that as we went home no one,

04:12:39.596 --> 04:12:41.036
in case we should meet anyone,

04:12:41.556 --> 04:12:43.056
should notice my bare feet.

04:12:45.536 --> 04:12:48.356
Fortune favored us, and we got home without meeting a soul.

04:12:49.236 --> 04:12:52.256
Once we saw a man, who seemed not quite sober,

04:12:52.916 --> 04:12:54.876
passing along a street in front of us.

04:12:55.536 --> 04:12:58.396
But we hid in a door till he had disappeared up an opening,

04:12:58.656 --> 04:13:01.176
such as there are here, steep little closes,

04:13:01.656 --> 04:13:03.716
or wines, as they call them in Scotland.

04:13:04.896 --> 04:13:06.836
My heart beat so loud all the time,

04:13:06.876 --> 04:13:08.336
sometimes I thought I should faint.

04:13:09.316 --> 04:13:11.356
I was filled with anxiety about Lucy,

04:13:12.196 --> 04:13:13.456
not only for her health,

04:13:13.876 --> 04:13:15.636
lest she should suffer from the exposure,

04:13:15.636 --> 04:13:19.276
but for her reputation, in case a story should get wind.

04:13:20.396 --> 04:13:22.376
When we got in, and had washed our feet,

04:13:22.736 --> 04:13:24.616
and had said a prayer of thankfulness together,

04:13:24.976 --> 04:13:26.216
I tucked her into bed.

04:13:27.096 --> 04:13:29.176
Before falling asleep, she asked,

04:13:29.436 --> 04:13:32.036
even implored me not to say a word to anyone,

04:13:32.216 --> 04:13:35.216
even her mother, about her sleepwalking adventure.

04:13:37.296 --> 04:13:39.336
I hesitated at first to promise,

04:13:39.936 --> 04:13:42.136
but on thinking of the state of her mother's health,

04:13:42.556 --> 04:13:44.736
and how the knowledge of such a thing would fret her,

04:13:44.736 --> 04:13:48.716
and think, too, of how such a story might become distorted,

04:13:49.076 --> 04:13:52.516
nay, infallibly would, in case it should leak out,

04:13:52.836 --> 04:13:54.576
I thought it wiser to do so.

04:13:55.196 --> 04:13:56.456
I hope I did right.

04:13:57.116 --> 04:14:00.056
I have locked the door, and the key is tied to my wrist,

04:14:00.356 --> 04:14:02.416
so perhaps I shall not again be disturbed.

04:14:03.616 --> 04:14:05.096
Lucy is sleeping soundly.

04:14:05.716 --> 04:14:08.816
The reflex of the dawn is high and far over the sea.

04:14:10.476 --> 04:14:12.056
Same day, noon.

04:14:12.956 --> 04:14:14.396
All goes well.

04:14:15.256 --> 04:14:16.356
Lucy slept till I woke her,

04:14:16.416 --> 04:14:18.476
and seemed not to have even changed her side.

04:14:19.876 --> 04:14:22.556
The adventure of the night does not seem to have harmed her.

04:14:22.736 --> 04:14:25.236
On the contrary, it has benefited her,

04:14:25.496 --> 04:14:28.036
for she looks better this morning than she has done for weeks.

04:14:29.336 --> 04:14:32.976
I was sorry to notice that my clumsiness with the safety pin hurt her.

04:14:33.576 --> 04:14:35.256
Indeed, it might have been serious,

04:14:35.756 --> 04:14:37.656
for the skin of her throat was pierced.

04:14:38.176 --> 04:14:40.516
I must have pinched up a piece of loose skin,

04:14:40.516 --> 04:14:42.296
and have transfixed it,

04:14:42.316 --> 04:14:45.076
for there are two little red points like pinpricks,

04:14:45.396 --> 04:14:47.676
and on the band of her nightdress was a drop of blood.

04:14:49.196 --> 04:14:51.296
When I apologized and was concerned about it,

04:14:51.356 --> 04:14:53.136
she laughed and petted me,

04:14:53.396 --> 04:14:55.156
and said she did not even feel it.

04:14:56.056 --> 04:14:59.136
Fortunately, it cannot leave a scar, as it is too tiny.

04:15:01.696 --> 04:15:03.516
Same day, night.

04:15:04.936 --> 04:15:06.156
We passed a happy day.

04:15:06.896 --> 04:15:09.036
The air was clear, and the sun bright,

04:15:09.036 --> 04:15:10.496
and there was a cool breeze.

04:15:11.536 --> 04:15:13.616
We took our lunch to Mulgrave Woods,

04:15:14.636 --> 04:15:16.516
Mrs. Westenra driving by the road,

04:15:17.036 --> 04:15:19.276
and Lucy and I walking by the cliff path,

04:15:19.556 --> 04:15:20.756
and joining her at the gate.

04:15:21.916 --> 04:15:23.656
I felt a little sad myself,

04:15:24.536 --> 04:15:27.656
for I could not but feel how absolutely happy I would have been

04:15:27.656 --> 04:15:29.036
had Jonathan been with me.

04:15:29.236 --> 04:15:31.576
But there, I must only be patient.

04:15:32.956 --> 04:15:35.176
In the evening we strolled in the casino terrace,

04:15:35.176 --> 04:15:37.596
and heard some good music by Svor and Mackenzie,

04:15:37.696 --> 04:15:38.576
and went to bed early.

04:15:39.656 --> 04:15:42.336
Lucy seems more restful than she has been for some time,

04:15:42.376 --> 04:15:43.396
and fell asleep once.

04:15:44.256 --> 04:15:47.196
I shall lock the door and secure the key the same as before,

04:15:47.456 --> 04:15:49.496
though I do not expect any trouble tonight.

04:15:53.256 --> 04:15:54.896
My expectations were wrong,

04:15:55.336 --> 04:15:58.496
for twice during the night I was wakened by Lucy trying to get out.

04:15:59.036 --> 04:16:00.976
She seemed, even in her sleep,

04:16:01.496 --> 04:16:04.096
to be a little impatient at finding the door shut,

04:16:04.096 --> 04:16:06.896
and went back to bed under a sort of protest.

04:16:08.316 --> 04:16:09.316
I woke with the dawn,

04:16:09.616 --> 04:16:11.516
and heard the birds chirping outside the window.

04:16:12.876 --> 04:16:15.076
Lucy woke too, and I was glad to see,

04:16:15.476 --> 04:16:17.456
was even better than on the previous morning.

04:16:18.636 --> 04:16:21.776
All her old gay day of manners seemed to have come back,

04:16:22.256 --> 04:16:24.516
and she came and snuggled in beside me,

04:16:24.736 --> 04:16:25.916
and told me all about Arthur.

04:16:27.156 --> 04:16:29.336
I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan,

04:16:29.736 --> 04:16:31.256
and then she tried to comfort me.

04:16:31.976 --> 04:16:33.816
Well, she succeeded somewhat,

04:16:34.336 --> 04:16:36.356
for though sympathy can't alter facts,

04:16:36.896 --> 04:16:38.576
it can make them more bearable.

04:16:40.996 --> 04:16:41.956
13th August

04:16:42.896 --> 04:16:44.476
Another quiet day,

04:16:45.056 --> 04:16:47.076
and to bed with the key on my wrist as before.

04:16:48.176 --> 04:16:49.416
Again I awoke in the night,

04:16:49.616 --> 04:16:51.956
and found Lucy sitting up in bed, still asleep,

04:16:52.096 --> 04:16:52.996
pointing to the window.

04:16:54.256 --> 04:16:55.336
I got up quietly,

04:16:56.036 --> 04:16:58.096
and pulling aside the blind, looked out.

04:16:58.976 --> 04:17:00.476
It was brilliant moonlight,

04:17:00.476 --> 04:17:04.116
and the soft effect of the light over the sea and sky,

04:17:04.556 --> 04:17:06.896
merged together in one great silent mystery,

04:17:07.596 --> 04:17:09.336
was beautiful beyond words.

04:17:11.156 --> 04:17:13.816
Between me and the moonlight flitted a great bat,

04:17:14.436 --> 04:17:16.776
coming and going in great whirling circles.

04:17:17.836 --> 04:17:19.656
Once or twice it came quite close,

04:17:20.056 --> 04:17:22.696
but was, I suppose, frightened at seeing me,

04:17:23.056 --> 04:17:25.656
and flitted away across the harbor towards the abbey.

04:17:26.756 --> 04:17:28.096
When I came back from the window,

04:17:28.096 --> 04:17:30.316
Lucy had laid down again and was sleeping peacefully.

04:17:31.336 --> 04:17:33.456
She did not stir again all night.

04:17:36.096 --> 04:17:36.896
14th August

04:17:37.996 --> 04:17:39.216
On the east cliff,

04:17:39.436 --> 04:17:40.916
reading and writing all day,

04:17:41.376 --> 04:17:44.456
Lucy seems to have become as much in love with the spot as I am,

04:17:44.896 --> 04:17:46.576
as it is hard to get her away from it

04:17:46.576 --> 04:17:49.056
when it is time to come home for lunch or tea or dinner.

04:17:49.976 --> 04:17:51.896
This afternoon she made a funny remark.

04:17:52.956 --> 04:17:54.376
We were coming home for dinner,

04:17:54.836 --> 04:17:56.376
and had come to the top of the steps,

04:17:56.376 --> 04:17:57.596
up from the west pier,

04:17:58.096 --> 04:18:00.676
and stopped to look at the view, as we generally do.

04:18:01.736 --> 04:18:04.236
The setting sun, low down in the sky,

04:18:04.736 --> 04:18:06.736
was just dropping behind Kettleness.

04:18:08.056 --> 04:18:11.416
The red light was thrown over the east cliff and the old abbey,

04:18:11.856 --> 04:18:14.576
and seemed to bathe everything in a beautiful rosy glow.

04:18:16.076 --> 04:18:17.496
We were silent for a while,

04:18:17.976 --> 04:18:20.436
and suddenly Lucy murmured as if to herself.

04:18:21.916 --> 04:18:23.376
His red eyes again,

04:18:23.376 --> 04:18:25.316
they are just the same.

04:18:26.716 --> 04:18:28.816
It was such an odd expression,

04:18:29.396 --> 04:18:30.676
coming apropos of nothing,

04:18:30.816 --> 04:18:32.356
that it quite startled me.

04:18:33.256 --> 04:18:34.756
I slewed round a little,

04:18:35.016 --> 04:18:37.576
so I asked to see Lucy well without seeming to stare at her,

04:18:38.416 --> 04:18:40.756
and saw that she was in a half dreamy state,

04:18:41.596 --> 04:18:44.476
with an odd look on her face that I could not quite make out,

04:18:44.656 --> 04:18:47.056
so I said nothing, but followed her eyes.

04:18:48.056 --> 04:18:50.696
She appeared to be looking over at our own seat,

04:18:51.316 --> 04:18:53.656
whereupon was a dark figure seated alone.

04:18:54.976 --> 04:18:57.016
I was quite a little startled myself,

04:18:57.796 --> 04:18:59.056
for it seemed for an instant

04:18:59.056 --> 04:19:01.976
as if the stranger had great eyes like burning flames,

04:19:02.596 --> 04:19:04.396
but a second look dispelled the illusion.

04:19:06.216 --> 04:19:08.096
The red sunlight was shining on the windows

04:19:08.096 --> 04:19:10.096
of St. Mary's Church behind our seat,

04:19:10.816 --> 04:19:13.456
and as the sun dipped there was just sufficient change

04:19:13.456 --> 04:19:15.176
in the reflection and refraction

04:19:15.696 --> 04:19:17.816
to make it appear as if the light moved.

04:19:19.556 --> 04:19:22.516
I called Lucy's attention to the peculiar effect,

04:19:22.976 --> 04:19:24.636
and she became herself with a start,

04:19:25.316 --> 04:19:27.356
but she looked sad all the same.

04:19:28.596 --> 04:19:29.916
It may have been that she was thinking

04:19:29.916 --> 04:19:31.456
of that terrible night up there.

04:19:31.996 --> 04:19:33.416
We never refer to it,

04:19:33.656 --> 04:19:36.216
so I said nothing, and we went home to dinner.

04:19:37.536 --> 04:19:39.316
Lucy had a headache and went early to bed.

04:19:39.916 --> 04:19:43.216
I saw her asleep and went out for a little stroll myself.

04:19:44.876 --> 04:19:46.996
I walked along the cliffs to the westward

04:19:46.996 --> 04:19:48.576
and was full of sweet sadness,

04:19:48.776 --> 04:19:50.096
for I was thinking of Jonathan.

04:19:51.356 --> 04:19:53.616
When coming home, it was then bright moonlight,

04:19:54.096 --> 04:19:56.556
so bright that, though the front of our part

04:19:56.556 --> 04:19:57.936
of the crescent was in shadow,

04:19:58.296 --> 04:19:59.556
everything could be well seen.

04:20:00.436 --> 04:20:01.996
I threw a glance up at our window

04:20:01.996 --> 04:20:03.916
and saw Lucy's head leaning out.

04:20:04.976 --> 04:20:07.116
I opened my handkerchief and waved it.

04:20:07.816 --> 04:20:10.176
She did not notice or make any movement whatever.

04:20:11.416 --> 04:20:14.356
Just then, the moonlight crept round an angle

04:20:14.356 --> 04:20:16.796
of the building, and the light fell on the window.

04:20:18.096 --> 04:20:19.816
There distinctly was Lucy with her head

04:20:19.816 --> 04:20:21.676
lying up against the side of the windowsill

04:20:21.676 --> 04:20:22.676
and her eyes shut.

04:20:23.756 --> 04:20:26.256
She was fast asleep, and by her,

04:20:26.596 --> 04:20:27.776
seated on the windowsill,

04:20:28.316 --> 04:20:30.196
was something that looked like a good-sized bird.

04:20:31.736 --> 04:20:33.296
I was afraid she might get a chill,

04:20:33.296 --> 04:20:36.216
so I ran upstairs, but as I came into the room,

04:20:36.236 --> 04:20:37.676
she was moving back to her bed,

04:20:37.976 --> 04:20:40.196
fast asleep and breathing heavily.

04:20:41.456 --> 04:20:43.396
She was holding her hand to her throat,

04:20:43.396 --> 04:20:45.616
as though to protect it from the cold.

04:20:47.796 --> 04:20:50.096
I did not wake her, but tucked her warmly.

04:20:50.876 --> 04:20:52.536
I had taken care that the door was locked

04:20:52.536 --> 04:20:54.516
and the window securely fastened.

04:20:56.556 --> 04:20:58.476
She looked so sweet as she sleeps,

04:20:58.956 --> 04:21:00.616
but she is paler than is her want,

04:21:01.416 --> 04:21:03.676
and there is a drawn, haggard look under her eyes,

04:21:03.696 --> 04:21:04.676
which I do not like.

04:21:05.616 --> 04:21:07.236
I fear she is fretting about something.

04:21:07.816 --> 04:21:09.836
I wish I could find out what it is.

04:21:12.876 --> 04:21:13.836
Fifteenth August.

04:21:14.916 --> 04:21:16.156
Rose later than usual.

04:21:17.056 --> 04:21:18.396
Lucy was languid and tired

04:21:18.396 --> 04:21:20.336
and slept on after we had been called.

04:21:21.156 --> 04:21:22.796
We had a happy surprise at breakfast.

04:21:23.776 --> 04:21:24.916
Arthur's father is better

04:21:24.916 --> 04:21:26.816
and wants the marriage to come off soon.

04:21:28.196 --> 04:21:29.596
Lucy is full of quiet joy,

04:21:29.996 --> 04:21:32.416
and her mother is glad and sorry at once.

04:21:33.976 --> 04:21:35.956
Later on in the day, she told me the cause.

04:21:36.756 --> 04:21:39.116
She is grieved to lose Lucy as her very own,

04:21:39.116 --> 04:21:41.116
but she is rejoiced that she is soon

04:21:41.116 --> 04:21:43.296
to have someone to protect her.

04:21:43.396 --> 04:21:44.896
Poor dear sweet lady.

04:21:46.416 --> 04:21:48.936
She confided to me that she has got her death warrant.

04:21:49.796 --> 04:21:51.016
She has not told Lucy

04:21:51.016 --> 04:21:52.896
and made me promise secrecy.

04:21:53.916 --> 04:21:55.936
Her doctor told her that within a few months,

04:21:56.096 --> 04:21:57.716
at most, she must die,

04:21:57.836 --> 04:21:59.196
for her heart is weakening.

04:22:00.016 --> 04:22:01.636
At any time, even now,

04:22:01.836 --> 04:22:04.236
a sudden shock would be almost sure to kill her.

04:22:05.176 --> 04:22:07.116
We were wise to keep the affair

04:22:07.116 --> 04:22:09.116
of the dreadful night of Lucy's sleepwalking.

04:22:12.136 --> 04:22:13.096
17th August

04:22:14.076 --> 04:22:16.196
No diary for two whole days.

04:22:16.656 --> 04:22:18.176
I have not had the heart to write.

04:22:19.156 --> 04:22:22.536
Some sort of shadowy pall seems to be coming over our happiness.

04:22:23.816 --> 04:22:24.876
No news from Jonathan,

04:22:25.656 --> 04:22:27.276
and Lucy seems to be growing weaker

04:22:27.276 --> 04:22:30.036
whilst her mother's hours are numbering to a close.

04:22:31.296 --> 04:22:34.256
I do not understand Lucy's fading away as she is doing.

04:22:34.916 --> 04:22:36.756
She eats well and sleeps well,

04:22:36.756 --> 04:22:38.156
and enjoys a fresh air,

04:22:38.676 --> 04:22:41.016
but all the time the roses in her cheeks are fading,

04:22:41.716 --> 04:22:44.056
and she gets weaker and more languid day by day.

04:22:45.236 --> 04:22:47.556
At night I hear her gasping as if for air.

04:22:49.536 --> 04:22:52.776
I keep the key of our door always fastened to my wrist at night,

04:22:52.916 --> 04:22:54.576
but she gets up and walks about the room

04:22:54.576 --> 04:22:55.876
and sits at the open window.

04:22:57.036 --> 04:22:59.276
Last night I found her leaning out when I woke up,

04:22:59.376 --> 04:23:00.936
and when I tried to wake her I could not.

04:23:01.916 --> 04:23:03.056
She was in a faint.

04:23:03.756 --> 04:23:05.236
When I managed to restore her,

04:23:05.236 --> 04:23:07.596
she was weak as water and cried silently

04:23:07.596 --> 04:23:09.876
between long, painful struggles for breath.

04:23:11.176 --> 04:23:12.996
When I asked her how she came to be at a window,

04:23:13.076 --> 04:23:14.736
she shook her head and turned away.

04:23:15.976 --> 04:23:20.216
I trust her feeling ill may not be from that unlucky prick of the safety pin.

04:23:21.476 --> 04:23:24.076
I looked at her throat just now as she lay asleep,

04:23:24.856 --> 04:23:27.296
and the tiny wounds seemed not to have healed.

04:23:28.256 --> 04:23:32.136
They are still open, and if anything, larger than before,

04:23:32.136 --> 04:23:34.816
and the edges of them are faintly white.

04:23:35.896 --> 04:23:38.276
They are like little white dots with red centers.

04:23:39.156 --> 04:23:40.816
Unless they heal within a day or two,

04:23:41.236 --> 04:23:44.156
I shall insist on the doctors saying about them.

04:23:47.516 --> 04:23:52.536
Letter, Samuel F. Billington & Son, Solicitors Whitby.

04:23:52.976 --> 04:23:56.356
To Mrs. Carter, Patterson & Co., London.

04:23:57.176 --> 04:23:58.236
17th August.

04:23:59.416 --> 04:24:03.216
Dear Sirs, Herewith please receive invoice of goods

04:24:03.216 --> 04:24:05.556
sent by Great Northern Railway.

04:24:06.236 --> 04:24:09.676
Same are to be delivered at Carfax, near Perfleet,

04:24:10.096 --> 04:24:12.996
immediately on receipt at Good Station Kings Cross.

04:24:14.016 --> 04:24:17.956
The house is at present empty, but enclosed please find all keys,

04:24:18.376 --> 04:24:19.316
all of which are labeled.

04:24:20.616 --> 04:24:23.736
You will please deposit the boxes, fifty in number,

04:24:24.196 --> 04:24:25.536
which form the consignment,

04:24:25.536 --> 04:24:28.776
in the partially ruined building forming part of the house

04:24:28.776 --> 04:24:31.716
and marked A on rough diagrams enclosed.

04:24:33.016 --> 04:24:35.796
Your agent will easily recognize the locality,

04:24:36.256 --> 04:24:38.216
as it is the ancient chapel of the mansion.

04:24:39.576 --> 04:24:42.416
The goods leave by the train at 9.30 tonight,

04:24:42.816 --> 04:24:46.396
and will be due at Kings Cross at 4.30 tomorrow afternoon.

04:24:47.916 --> 04:24:51.056
As our client wishes the delivery to be made as soon as possible,

04:24:51.676 --> 04:24:54.856
we shall be obliged by your having teams ready at Kings Cross

04:24:54.856 --> 04:24:58.396
at the time named and forwith conveying the goods to destination.

04:25:00.116 --> 04:25:03.816
In order to obviate any delays possible through any routine requirements

04:25:03.816 --> 04:25:05.496
as to payment in your departments,

04:25:06.056 --> 04:25:08.596
we enclose check Herewith for ten pounds,

04:25:09.116 --> 04:25:10.596
receipt of which please acknowledge.

04:25:11.436 --> 04:25:13.016
Should the charge be less than this amount,

04:25:13.096 --> 04:25:14.236
you can return the balance.

04:25:14.576 --> 04:25:18.316
If greater, we shall at once send check for difference upon hearing from you.

04:25:19.236 --> 04:25:22.476
You are to leave the keys on coming away in the main hall of the house,

04:25:22.476 --> 04:25:25.676
where the proprietor may get them on his entering the house

04:25:25.676 --> 04:25:27.356
by means of his duplicate key.

04:25:29.176 --> 04:25:32.096
Pray do not take us as exceeding the bounds of business courtesy

04:25:32.096 --> 04:25:34.896
in pressing you in all ways to use the utmost expedition.

04:25:35.996 --> 04:25:41.356
We are, dear sirs, faithfully yours, Samuel F. Billington and son.

04:25:45.096 --> 04:25:45.536
Letter.

04:25:45.536 --> 04:25:48.736
Missions Carter, Patterson, and Co., London.

04:25:49.396 --> 04:25:51.556
To Missions Billington and son, Whitby.

04:25:52.596 --> 04:25:53.716
21st August.

04:25:54.776 --> 04:25:58.516
Dear sirs, we beg to acknowledge ten pounds received

04:25:58.516 --> 04:26:02.956
and to return check of one pound seventeen shillings nine pence,

04:26:03.096 --> 04:26:06.696
amount of overplus, as shown in receded account Herewith.

04:26:07.516 --> 04:26:09.976
Goods are delivered in exact accordance with instructions,

04:26:10.556 --> 04:26:13.176
and keys left in parcel in main hall, as directed.

04:26:13.756 --> 04:26:16.216
We are, dear sirs, yours respectfully.

04:26:16.756 --> 04:26:18.496
Carter, Patterson, and Co.

04:26:20.936 --> 04:26:22.516
Mina Murray's Journal.

04:26:23.756 --> 04:26:24.616
18th August.

04:26:25.556 --> 04:26:28.696
I am happy today and write singing on the seat in the churchyard.

04:26:29.296 --> 04:26:30.536
Lucy is ever so much better.

04:26:31.196 --> 04:26:34.136
Last night she slept well all night and did not disturb me once.

04:26:35.676 --> 04:26:38.116
The roses seem to be coming back already to her cheeks,

04:26:38.536 --> 04:26:40.676
though she is still sadly pale and wan looking.

04:26:40.676 --> 04:26:44.596
If she were in any way anemic I can understand it, but she is not.

04:26:45.476 --> 04:26:48.276
She is in gay spirits and full of life and cheerfulness.

04:26:49.396 --> 04:26:52.056
All the morbid reticence seems to have passed from her,

04:26:52.316 --> 04:26:55.456
and she has just reminded me, as if I need any reminding,

04:26:55.616 --> 04:26:59.856
of that night and that it was here on this very seat I found her asleep.

04:27:01.536 --> 04:27:05.516
And she told me she tapped playfully with the heel of her boot on the stone slab inside.

04:27:06.756 --> 04:27:09.116
My poor little feet didn't make much noise then.

04:27:09.116 --> 04:27:15.436
I dare say poor old Mr. Swells would have told me that it was because I didn't want to wake up Geordie.

04:27:16.736 --> 04:27:21.136
As she was in such a communicative humour I asked her if she had dreamed it all that night.

04:27:23.496 --> 04:27:27.536
Before she answered, that sweet puckered look came into her forehead,

04:27:27.836 --> 04:27:31.556
which Arthur, I call him Arthur from her habit, says he loves,

04:27:31.876 --> 04:27:34.076
and indeed I don't wonder that he does.

04:27:35.216 --> 04:27:37.756
Then she went on in a half-dreaming kind of way,

04:27:37.756 --> 04:27:40.076
as if trying to recall it to herself.

04:27:41.976 --> 04:27:45.376
I didn't quite dream, but it all seemed to be real.

04:27:46.676 --> 04:27:48.996
I only wanted to be here, in this spot.

04:27:50.116 --> 04:27:53.996
I don't know why, for I was afraid of something, I don't know what.

04:27:55.896 --> 04:28:01.996
I remember, though, I suppose I was asleep, passing through the streets and over the bridge.

04:28:03.196 --> 04:28:07.816
A fish leaped as I went by, and I leaned over to look at it,

04:28:08.376 --> 04:28:10.516
and I heard a lot of dogs howling.

04:28:11.716 --> 04:28:15.556
The whole town seemed as it must be full of all dogs howling at once,

04:28:16.236 --> 04:28:17.656
as I went up the steps.

04:28:19.276 --> 04:28:23.616
Then I had a vague memory of something long and dark with red eyes,

04:28:24.456 --> 04:28:25.956
just as we saw in the sunset,

04:28:26.636 --> 04:28:30.876
and something very sweet and very bitter all around me at once.

04:28:32.636 --> 04:28:35.836
And then I seemed sinking into deep green water,

04:28:36.596 --> 04:28:40.856
and there was singing in my ears, as I have heard there is to drowning men,

04:28:41.476 --> 04:28:44.456
and then everything seemed passing away from me.

04:28:45.756 --> 04:28:49.216
My soul seemed to go out from my body and float about the air.

04:28:50.636 --> 04:28:55.316
I seemed to remember that once the west lighthouse was right under me,

04:28:55.316 --> 04:28:58.076
and then there was sort of an agonizing feeling,

04:28:58.956 --> 04:29:00.436
as if I were in an earthquake,

04:29:01.556 --> 04:29:03.956
and I came back and found you shaking my body.

04:29:05.136 --> 04:29:07.236
I saw you do it before I felt you.

04:29:09.316 --> 04:29:10.836
Then she began to laugh.

04:29:11.856 --> 04:29:14.976
It seemed a little uncanny to me, and I listened to her breathlessly.

04:29:15.416 --> 04:29:19.156
I did not quite like it, and thought it better not to keep her mind on the subject,

04:29:19.616 --> 04:29:23.036
so we drifted on to another subject, and Lucy was like her old self again.

04:29:23.536 --> 04:29:26.236
When we got home, the fresh breeze had braced her up,

04:29:26.456 --> 04:29:28.576
and her pale cheeks were really more rosy.

04:29:29.176 --> 04:29:33.636
Her mother rejoiced when she saw her, and we all spent a very happy evening together.

04:29:36.536 --> 04:29:39.576
Nineteenth August. Joy, joy, joy!

04:29:40.356 --> 04:29:43.536
Although not all joy. At last, news of Jonathan.

04:29:44.536 --> 04:29:47.436
The dear fellow has been ill, that is why he did not ride.

04:29:48.196 --> 04:29:51.456
I am not afraid to think it, or to say it, now that I know.

04:29:52.676 --> 04:29:57.076
Mr. Hawkins sent me on the letter, and wrote himself oh so kindly.

04:29:59.076 --> 04:30:01.416
I am to leave in the morning, and go over to Jonathan,

04:30:01.656 --> 04:30:04.376
and to help nurse him if necessary, and to bring him home.

04:30:05.316 --> 04:30:09.136
Mr. Hawkins says it would not be a bad thing if we were to be married out there.

04:30:10.236 --> 04:30:12.356
I have cried over the good sister's letter,

04:30:12.636 --> 04:30:15.116
so I can fill it wet against my bosom, where it lies.

04:30:16.016 --> 04:30:19.296
It is of Jonathan, and must be near my heart, for he is in my heart.

04:30:20.196 --> 04:30:22.696
My journey is all mapped out, and my luggage ready.

04:30:23.316 --> 04:30:25.276
I am only taking one change of dress.

04:30:26.296 --> 04:30:29.696
Lisa will bring my trunk to London, and keep it till I send for it.

04:30:30.236 --> 04:30:33.016
For it may be that I must write no more.

04:30:33.296 --> 04:30:35.716
I must keep it to say to Jonathan, my husband.

04:30:36.756 --> 04:30:39.956
The letter that he has seen and touched must comfort me till we meet.

04:30:43.096 --> 04:30:44.516
Letter. Sister Agatha.

04:30:45.176 --> 04:30:48.216
Hospital of St. Joseph and St. Mary Budapest.

04:30:48.796 --> 04:30:51.096
To Miss Wilhema Murray.

04:30:52.036 --> 04:30:54.356
12th August. Dear Madame.

04:30:55.976 --> 04:30:58.336
I write by desire of Mr. Jonathan Harker,

04:30:59.356 --> 04:31:01.336
who is himself not strong enough to write,

04:31:01.516 --> 04:31:04.916
though progressing well, thanks to God and St. Joseph and St. Mary.

04:31:06.516 --> 04:31:09.316
He has been under our care for nearly six weeks,

04:31:09.956 --> 04:31:11.656
suffering from a violent brain fever.

04:31:13.236 --> 04:31:15.456
He wishes me to convey his love,

04:31:16.076 --> 04:31:18.816
and to say that by this post I write for him

04:31:18.816 --> 04:31:21.296
to Mr. Peter Hawkins Exeter, to say,

04:31:21.656 --> 04:31:24.956
with his dutiful respects, that he is sorry for his delay,

04:31:25.336 --> 04:31:27.156
and that all of his work is completed.

04:31:28.456 --> 04:31:32.076
He'll require some few weeks' rest in our sanatorium in the hills,

04:31:32.076 --> 04:31:33.396
but will then return.

04:31:34.576 --> 04:31:38.596
He wishes me to say that he has not sufficient money with him,

04:31:39.096 --> 04:31:41.856
and that he would like to pay for his staying here,

04:31:41.856 --> 04:31:45.416
so that others who need shall not be wanting for help.

04:31:46.776 --> 04:31:47.816
Believe me.

04:31:48.076 --> 04:31:51.756
Yours, with sympathy and all blessings, Sister Agatha.

04:31:52.756 --> 04:31:53.796
P.S.

04:31:54.296 --> 04:31:55.876
My patient being asleep,

04:31:56.776 --> 04:31:58.796
I open this to let you know something more.

04:31:59.376 --> 04:32:02.656
He has told me all about you, and that you are shortly to be his wife.

04:32:03.096 --> 04:32:04.396
All blessings to you both.

04:32:04.936 --> 04:32:07.516
He has had some fearful shock, so says our doctor,

04:32:07.516 --> 04:32:10.516
and in his delirium his ravings have been dreadful,

04:32:10.636 --> 04:32:13.776
of wolves and poison and blood, of ghosts and demons,

04:32:14.156 --> 04:32:15.396
and I fear to say of what.

04:32:16.536 --> 04:32:19.556
Be careful of him always, that there may be nothing to excite him

04:32:19.556 --> 04:32:21.756
of this kind for a long time to come.

04:32:22.996 --> 04:32:26.156
The traces of such an illness as his do not lightly die away.

04:32:27.356 --> 04:32:29.936
We should have written long ago, but we knew nothing of his friends,

04:32:30.016 --> 04:32:31.396
and there was nothing on him,

04:32:31.716 --> 04:32:33.236
nothing that anyone could understand.

04:32:34.876 --> 04:32:37.116
He came in the train from Claussenburg,

04:32:37.756 --> 04:32:40.096
and the guard was told by the stationmaster there

04:32:40.096 --> 04:32:43.256
that he rushed into the station shouting for a ticket home.

04:32:44.516 --> 04:32:46.916
Seeing from his violent demeanor that he was English,

04:32:47.656 --> 04:32:50.336
they gave him a ticket for the furthest station on the way

04:32:50.336 --> 04:32:51.816
thither that the train reached.

04:32:53.196 --> 04:32:55.196
Be assured that he is well cared for.

04:32:56.156 --> 04:32:58.916
He has won all hearts by his sweetness and gentleness.

04:32:59.396 --> 04:33:01.016
He is truly getting on well,

04:33:01.016 --> 04:33:04.396
and I have no doubt will in a few weeks will all be himself.

04:33:05.956 --> 04:33:07.916
But be careful of him for safety's sake.

04:33:08.536 --> 04:33:11.896
There are, I pray, and St. Joseph and St. Mary,

04:33:12.356 --> 04:33:14.376
many, many happy years for you both.

04:33:16.256 --> 04:33:19.036
Dr. Seward's Diary, 19th August.

04:33:20.176 --> 04:33:22.636
Strange and sudden change in Renfield last night.

04:33:23.216 --> 04:33:25.216
About eight o'clock he began to get excited

04:33:25.216 --> 04:33:27.816
and sniff about as a dog does when setting.

04:33:29.216 --> 04:33:30.936
The attendant was struck by his manner.

04:33:30.936 --> 04:33:34.476
And knowing my interest in him, encouraged him to talk.

04:33:35.696 --> 04:33:37.616
He is usually respectful to the attendant

04:33:37.616 --> 04:33:40.716
and at times servile, but tonight the man tells me

04:33:40.716 --> 04:33:43.556
he was quite haughty, would not condescend

04:33:43.556 --> 04:33:45.356
to talk with him at all.

04:33:46.676 --> 04:33:49.296
All he would say was, I don't want to talk to you.

04:33:49.376 --> 04:33:51.916
You don't count now. The master is at hand.

04:33:53.936 --> 04:33:56.036
The attendant thinks it is some form

04:33:56.036 --> 04:33:58.196
of religious mania which has seized him.

04:33:58.196 --> 04:34:01.156
If so, we must look out for squalls,

04:34:01.596 --> 04:34:04.156
for a strong man with homicidal and religious mania

04:34:04.156 --> 04:34:05.656
at once might be dangerous.

04:34:06.196 --> 04:34:08.016
The combination is a dreadful one.

04:34:09.596 --> 04:34:11.516
At nine o'clock I visited him myself.

04:34:12.316 --> 04:34:15.156
His attitude to me was the same as that to the attendant.

04:34:16.516 --> 04:34:19.116
In his sublime self-feeling, the difference between

04:34:19.116 --> 04:34:21.436
myself and the attendant seemed to him as nothing.

04:34:22.536 --> 04:34:24.436
It looks like a religious mania,

04:34:24.436 --> 04:34:27.296
and he will soon think that he himself is God.

04:34:29.316 --> 04:34:31.076
These infinitesimal distinctions

04:34:31.076 --> 04:34:33.496
between man and man are too paltry

04:34:33.496 --> 04:34:34.816
for an omnipotent being.

04:34:35.756 --> 04:34:37.636
How these madmen give themselves away.

04:34:38.796 --> 04:34:41.216
The real God taketh heed lest a sparrow fall.

04:34:42.176 --> 04:34:44.196
But the God created from human vanity

04:34:44.196 --> 04:34:46.856
sees no difference between an eagle and a sparrow.

04:34:47.396 --> 04:34:48.676
Oh, if men only knew.

04:34:50.476 --> 04:34:52.896
For a half hour or more Renfield kept getting

04:34:52.896 --> 04:34:54.736
excited in greater and greater degree.

04:34:55.556 --> 04:34:57.356
I did not pretend to be watching him,

04:34:57.476 --> 04:35:00.176
but I kept strict observation all the same.

04:35:01.576 --> 04:35:04.396
All at once that shifty look came into his eyes,

04:35:04.676 --> 04:35:07.536
which we always see when a madman has seized an idea,

04:35:08.036 --> 04:35:10.876
and with it the shifty movements of the head and back

04:35:10.876 --> 04:35:13.156
which asylum attendants come to know so well.

04:35:14.256 --> 04:35:16.576
He became quiet, and went and sat

04:35:16.576 --> 04:35:18.196
on the edge of his bed resignedly,

04:35:18.896 --> 04:35:21.176
and looked into space with lackluster eyes.

04:35:22.556 --> 04:35:25.396
I thought I would find out if his apathy were real

04:35:25.396 --> 04:35:29.096
or only assumed, and tried to lead him to talk of his pets,

04:35:29.756 --> 04:35:31.696
a thing which never failed to excite his attention.

04:35:33.296 --> 04:35:34.656
At first he made no reply,

04:35:35.396 --> 04:35:36.956
but at length and testily.

04:35:37.736 --> 04:35:39.916
Bother them all. I don't care a pin about them.

04:35:41.216 --> 04:35:42.256
What? I said.

04:35:42.776 --> 04:35:45.176
You don't mean to tell me you don't care about spiders?

04:35:47.536 --> 04:35:49.056
Spiders at present are his hobby,

04:35:49.616 --> 04:35:52.196
and the notebook is filling up with columns of small figures.

04:35:53.756 --> 04:35:55.516
To this he answered enigmatically.

04:35:56.416 --> 04:35:58.356
The bride-maiden rejoiced the eyes

04:35:58.356 --> 04:35:59.876
that wait the coming of the bride,

04:36:00.576 --> 04:36:02.416
but when the bride draweth nigh,

04:36:02.856 --> 04:36:05.536
then the maidens shine not to the eyes that are filled.

04:36:07.376 --> 04:36:08.956
He would not explain himself,

04:36:08.956 --> 04:36:11.876
but remained obstinately seated on his bed

04:36:11.876 --> 04:36:13.436
all the time I remained with him.

04:36:14.656 --> 04:36:16.936
I am weary tonight, and low in spirits.

04:36:18.016 --> 04:36:19.176
I cannot but think of Lucy,

04:36:19.536 --> 04:36:21.116
and how different things might have been.

04:36:21.756 --> 04:36:23.156
If I don't sleep at once,

04:36:23.996 --> 04:36:25.756
Chloral, the modern Morpheus,

04:36:26.876 --> 04:36:29.196
I must be careful not to let it grow into a habit.

04:36:29.796 --> 04:36:31.456
No, I shall take none tonight.

04:36:31.976 --> 04:36:33.476
I have thought of Lucy,

04:36:33.796 --> 04:36:36.016
and I shall not dishonour her by mixing the two.

04:36:37.116 --> 04:36:38.896
If need be, tonight shall be sleepless.

04:36:40.856 --> 04:36:41.296
Later.

04:36:42.656 --> 04:36:45.756
Glad I made the resolution, gladder that I kept it.

04:36:46.076 --> 04:36:47.516
I had lain tossing about,

04:36:48.056 --> 04:36:50.016
and had heard the clock strike only twice,

04:36:50.676 --> 04:36:52.796
when the night watchman came to see me,

04:36:53.056 --> 04:36:55.836
sent up from the ward to say that Renfield had escaped.

04:36:56.476 --> 04:36:58.716
I threw on my clothes and ran down at once.

04:36:59.896 --> 04:37:02.536
My patient is too dangerous a person to be roaming about.

04:37:03.476 --> 04:37:05.616
Those ideas of his might work out dangerously

04:37:05.616 --> 04:37:06.276
with strangers.

04:37:08.196 --> 04:37:09.916
The attendant was waiting for me.

04:37:10.616 --> 04:37:12.896
He said he had not seen him at ten minutes before,

04:37:13.776 --> 04:37:15.296
seemingly asleep in his bed,

04:37:15.776 --> 04:37:18.116
when he looked through the observation trap in the door.

04:37:19.276 --> 04:37:22.236
His attention was called by the sound of the window being wretched out.

04:37:23.316 --> 04:37:26.216
He ran back and saw his feet disappear through the window,

04:37:26.676 --> 04:37:27.936
and had it once sent for me.

04:37:28.736 --> 04:37:31.476
He was only in his night gear and could not be far off.

04:37:33.336 --> 04:37:35.596
The attendant thought it would be more useful to watch

04:37:35.596 --> 04:37:37.596
where he should go than follow him,

04:37:37.796 --> 04:37:40.516
as he might lose sight of him while skidding out of the building by the door.

04:37:41.296 --> 04:37:43.656
He is a bulky man and couldn't get through the window.

04:37:44.996 --> 04:37:47.796
I am thin, so with his aid I got out,

04:37:48.136 --> 04:37:49.076
but feet foremost,

04:37:49.076 --> 04:37:52.116
as we were only a few feet above the ground, landed unhurt.

04:37:54.596 --> 04:37:56.956
The attendant told me the patient had gone to the left

04:37:56.956 --> 04:37:58.736
and had taken a straight line,

04:37:58.956 --> 04:38:00.696
so I ran as quickly as I could.

04:38:02.336 --> 04:38:03.996
As I got through the belt of trees,

04:38:04.436 --> 04:38:06.616
I saw a white figure scale the high wall

04:38:06.616 --> 04:38:09.576
which separates our grounds from those of the deserted house.

04:38:11.456 --> 04:38:12.916
I ran back at once,

04:38:13.216 --> 04:38:15.556
told the watchman to get three or four men immediately

04:38:15.556 --> 04:38:18.196
and follow me into the grounds of Carfax

04:38:18.196 --> 04:38:19.996
in case our friend might be dangerous.

04:38:21.076 --> 04:38:22.336
I got a ladder myself,

04:38:23.096 --> 04:38:25.476
and crossing the wall, dropped down to the other side.

04:38:27.516 --> 04:38:29.696
I could see Renfield's figure just disappearing

04:38:29.696 --> 04:38:32.076
behind the angle of the house, so I ran after him.

04:38:33.096 --> 04:38:35.856
On the far side of the house, I found him pressed close

04:38:35.856 --> 04:38:38.256
against the old iron-bound oak door of the chapel.

04:38:39.676 --> 04:38:41.736
He was talking, apparently to someone,

04:38:41.736 --> 04:38:44.576
but I was afraid to go near enough to hear what he was saying

04:38:44.576 --> 04:38:46.936
lest I might frighten him, and he should run off.

04:38:48.896 --> 04:38:51.056
Chasing an errant swarm of bees is nothing

04:38:51.056 --> 04:38:54.676
to following a naked lunatic when a fit of escaping is upon him.

04:38:55.856 --> 04:38:57.216
After a few minutes, however,

04:38:57.676 --> 04:39:00.736
I could see that he did not take note of anything around him

04:39:00.736 --> 04:39:03.156
and so ventured to draw near to him,

04:39:03.696 --> 04:39:05.836
the more so as my men had now crossed the wall

04:39:05.836 --> 04:39:08.536
and were closing him in. I heard him say,

04:39:09.436 --> 04:39:11.356
I am here to do your bidding, master.

04:39:11.656 --> 04:39:14.956
I am your slave, and you will reward me, so I shall be faithful.

04:39:16.236 --> 04:39:18.596
I have worshipped you long and afar off.

04:39:19.396 --> 04:39:21.416
Now that you are near, I await your commands,

04:39:21.976 --> 04:39:24.316
and you will not pass me by, will you, dear master,

04:39:25.216 --> 04:39:26.976
in your distribution of good things?

04:39:28.476 --> 04:39:30.336
He is a selfish old beggar, anyhow.

04:39:30.976 --> 04:39:32.456
He thinks of the loaves and fishes,

04:39:32.796 --> 04:39:35.216
even when he believes he is in the real presence.

04:39:36.076 --> 04:39:38.376
His manias make a startling combination.

04:39:40.196 --> 04:39:42.496
When we closed in on him, he fought like a tiger.

04:39:43.176 --> 04:39:44.576
He is immensely strong,

04:39:45.056 --> 04:39:47.156
for he was more like a wild beast than a man.

04:39:48.416 --> 04:39:51.896
I never saw a lunatic in such a paroxysm of rage before,

04:39:52.056 --> 04:39:53.496
and I hope I shall not again.

04:39:54.776 --> 04:39:56.756
It is mercy that we have found out his strength

04:39:56.756 --> 04:39:58.156
and danger in good time.

04:39:59.096 --> 04:40:00.796
With strength and determination like his,

04:40:00.796 --> 04:40:04.096
he might have done wild work before he was caged.

04:40:05.476 --> 04:40:06.796
He is safe now, at any rate.

04:40:08.076 --> 04:40:09.616
Jack Shepherd himself couldn't get free

04:40:09.616 --> 04:40:12.156
from the straight waistcoat that keeps him restrained,

04:40:12.476 --> 04:40:14.316
and he is chained to the wall in the padded room.

04:40:15.596 --> 04:40:17.196
His cries are at times awful,

04:40:17.876 --> 04:40:20.236
but the silences that follow are more deadly still,

04:40:20.896 --> 04:40:23.036
for he means murder in every turn and movement.

04:40:24.516 --> 04:40:27.116
Just now he spoke coherent words for the first time.

04:40:27.776 --> 04:40:29.356
I shall be patient, Master.

04:40:29.716 --> 04:40:31.976
It is coming, coming, coming.

04:40:33.696 --> 04:40:35.636
So I took the hint and came to.

04:40:36.476 --> 04:40:37.896
I was too excited to sleep,

04:40:38.816 --> 04:40:40.776
but this diary has quieted me,

04:40:40.896 --> 04:40:42.876
and I feel I shall get some sleep tonight.

04:41:18.898 --> 04:41:22.478
DRACULA by Bram Stoker

04:41:29.638 --> 04:41:30.238
Letter

04:41:30.878 --> 04:41:36.558
Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra, Budapest, 24 August

04:41:36.558 --> 04:41:44.658
My dearest Lucy, I know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we parted at the railway station at Whitby.

04:41:45.258 --> 04:41:51.358
Well, my dear, I got to Hull all right and caught the boat to Hamburg and then the train on here.

04:41:51.858 --> 04:42:02.658
I feel that I can hardly recall anything of the journey, except that I knew I was coming to Jonathan, and that as I should have to do some nursing, I had better get all the sleep I could.

04:42:03.638 --> 04:42:08.238
I found my dear one, oh so thin and pale and weak looking.

04:42:09.378 --> 04:42:16.258
All the resolution has gone out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in his face has vanished.

04:42:16.258 --> 04:42:23.558
He is only a wreck of himself, and he does not remember anything that has happened to him for a long time past.

04:42:24.358 --> 04:42:28.098
At least he wants me to believe so, and I shall never ask.

04:42:28.758 --> 04:42:35.978
He has had some terrible shock, and I fear it might tax his poor brain if he were to try to recall it.

04:42:36.938 --> 04:42:43.578
Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born nurse, tells me that he wanted her to tell me what they were.

04:42:43.578 --> 04:42:56.018
She would only cross herself and say she would never tell, that the ravings of the sick were the secrets of God, and that if a nurse through her vocation should hear them, she should respect her trust.

04:42:56.798 --> 04:43:05.898
She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject my poor dear raved about, added,

04:43:05.898 --> 04:43:15.598
I can tell you this much my dear, that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself, and you as his wife-to-be have no cause to be concerned.

04:43:16.238 --> 04:43:23.558
He has not forgotten you, or what he owes to you. His fear was of great and terrible things which no mortal can treat of.

04:43:24.218 --> 04:43:30.618
I do believe the dear soul thought I might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any other girl.

04:43:30.618 --> 04:43:41.498
The idea of my being jealous about Jonathan, and yet my dear let me whisper I felt a thrill of joy through me when I knew that no other woman was cause for trouble.

04:43:42.398 --> 04:43:48.278
I am now sitting by his bedside where I can see his face while he sleeps. He is waking.

04:43:49.638 --> 04:43:57.958
When he woke he asked me for his coat as he wanted to get me something from the pocket. I asked Sister Agatha and she brought all his things.

04:43:58.578 --> 04:44:06.358
I saw amongst them was his notebook. I was going to ask him to let me look at it, for I knew that I might find some clue to his trouble.

04:44:06.898 --> 04:44:14.658
But I suppose he must have seen my wish in my eyes, for he sent me over to the window, saying he wanted to be quite alone for a moment.

04:44:15.358 --> 04:44:20.018
Then he called me back and he said to me very solemnly, Wilhelmina.

04:44:21.478 --> 04:44:27.258
I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him.

04:44:27.858 --> 04:44:34.978
You know dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife, there should be no secret, no concealment.

04:44:35.538 --> 04:44:43.918
I have had a great shock and when I try to think of what it is I feel my head spin round and I do not know if it was real or the dreaming of the madman.

04:44:44.478 --> 04:44:50.958
You know I had brain fever and that is to be mad. The secret is here and I do not want to know it.

04:44:50.958 --> 04:45:00.198
I want to take up my life here, with our marriage. For, my dear, we had decided to be married as soon as the formalities are complete.

04:45:01.298 --> 04:45:19.578
Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance? Here is the book. Take it and keep it. Read it if you will, but never let me know unless, indeed, some solemn duty should come upon me to go back to the bitter hours, asleep or awake, sane or mad, recorded here.

04:45:20.418 --> 04:45:32.618
He fell back exhausted and I put the book under his pillow and kissed him. I have asked sister Agatha to beg the superior to let our wedding be this afternoon and am waiting her reply.

04:45:33.658 --> 04:45:43.738
She has come and told me that the chaplain of the English mission church has been sent for. We are to be married in an hour or as soon after as Jonathan awakes.

04:45:44.678 --> 04:45:51.038
Lucy, the time has come and gone. I feel very solemn but very, very happy.

04:45:51.778 --> 04:45:57.958
Jonathan woke a little after the hour and all was ready and he sat up in bed propped up with pillows.

04:45:58.758 --> 04:46:07.678
He answered his I will firmly and strong. I could hardly speak. My heart was so full that even those words seemed to choke me.

04:46:07.678 --> 04:46:18.918
The dear sisters were so kind. Please, God, I shall never, never forget them, nor the grave and sweet responsibilities I have taken upon me.

04:46:19.538 --> 04:46:26.058
I must tell you of my wedding present when the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband.

04:46:26.838 --> 04:46:33.758
Oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words my husband left me alone with my husband.

04:46:33.758 --> 04:46:42.458
I took the book from under his pillow and wrapped it up in white paper and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck

04:46:43.058 --> 04:46:48.998
and sealed it over the knot with sealing wax and for my seal I used my wedding ring.

04:46:49.758 --> 04:46:54.698
Then I kissed it and showed it to my husband and told him that I would keep it so

04:46:54.698 --> 04:47:00.458
and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our lives that we trusted each other

04:47:00.458 --> 04:47:06.418
that I would never open it unless it were for his own dear's sake or for the sake of some stern duty.

04:47:07.298 --> 04:47:13.498
Then he took my hand in his and, oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife's hand

04:47:14.138 --> 04:47:22.078
and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world and that he would go through all the past again to win it if need be.

04:47:22.078 --> 04:47:27.478
The poor dear meant to have set a part of the past but he cannot think of time yet

04:47:27.478 --> 04:47:32.538
and I shall not wonder if at first he mixes up not only the month but the year.

04:47:33.618 --> 04:47:40.478
Well, my dear, what could I say? I could only tell him that I was the happiest woman in all the wide world

04:47:40.478 --> 04:47:47.898
and that I had nothing to give him except myself, my life, and my trust

04:47:47.898 --> 04:47:52.058
and that with these went my love and duty for all the days of my life.

04:47:52.998 --> 04:48:00.378
And, my dear, when he kissed me and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a solemn pledge between us.

04:48:01.498 --> 04:48:07.998
Lucy, dear, do you know why I tell you all this? It is not only because it is all sweet to me

04:48:07.998 --> 04:48:11.238
but because you have been and are very dear to me.

04:48:11.238 --> 04:48:18.638
It was my privilege to be your friend and guide you when you came from the schoolroom to prepare for the world of life.

04:48:19.498 --> 04:48:24.578
I want you to see now, and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whether duty has led me

04:48:24.578 --> 04:48:29.018
so that in your own married life you too may be all happy as I am.

04:48:29.918 --> 04:48:34.978
My dear, please, Almighty God, your life, may it be all it promises.

04:48:34.978 --> 04:48:41.458
A long day of sunshine with no harsh wind, no forgetting duty, no distrust.

04:48:42.498 --> 04:48:49.318
I must not wish you no pain, for that can never be, but I do hope you will always be as happy as I am now.

04:48:49.938 --> 04:48:55.208
Good-bye, my dear. I shall post this at once and perhaps write you very soon again.

04:48:56.098 --> 04:49:00.478
I must stop, for Jonathan is waking. I must attend my husband.

04:49:01.018 --> 04:49:04.738
Your ever-loving, Mina Harker

04:49:04.738 --> 04:49:05.658
Letter

04:49:06.518 --> 04:49:09.298
Lucy Westenra to Mina Harker

04:49:09.298 --> 04:49:10.898
Whitby, 30 August

04:49:11.358 --> 04:49:17.078
My dearest Mina, oceans of love and millions of kisses, and may you soon be in your own home with your husband.

04:49:17.358 --> 04:49:20.118
I wish you were coming home soon enough to stay with us here.

04:49:20.378 --> 04:49:24.078
The strong air would soon restore Jonathan. It has quite restored me.

04:49:24.278 --> 04:49:28.738
I have an appetite like a cormorant. I am full of life and sleep well.

04:49:28.738 --> 04:49:34.818
You'll be glad to know that I have quite given up walking in my sleep. I think I have not stirred out of my bed for a week.

04:49:35.418 --> 04:49:37.378
That is when I once get into it at night.

04:49:38.258 --> 04:49:39.698
Arthur says I am getting fat.

04:49:40.238 --> 04:49:42.738
By the way, I forgot to tell you that Arthur is here.

04:49:43.098 --> 04:49:49.418
We have such walks and drives and rides and rowing and tennis and fishing together, and I love him more than ever.

04:49:49.818 --> 04:49:55.558
He tells me that he loves me more, but I doubt that, for at first he told me that he couldn't love me more than he did then.

04:49:56.058 --> 04:49:57.438
But this is nonsense.

04:49:57.438 --> 04:50:02.938
There he is calling to me, so no more just at present, from your loving Lucy.

04:50:03.978 --> 04:50:08.278
P.S. Mother sends her love. She seems better, poor dear.

04:50:09.258 --> 04:50:12.618
P.P.S. We are to be married on 28 September.

04:50:13.778 --> 04:50:15.438
Dr. Seward's Diary

04:50:16.418 --> 04:50:17.618
20 August

04:50:18.258 --> 04:50:21.638
The case of Renfield grows even more interesting.

04:50:22.718 --> 04:50:27.018
He is now so far quiet that there are spells of cessation from his passion.

04:50:27.018 --> 04:50:31.158
For the first week after his attack he was perpetually violent.

04:50:31.738 --> 04:50:36.598
Then one night, just as the moon rose, he grew quiet and kept murmuring to himself.

04:50:37.338 --> 04:50:39.598
Now I can wait. Now I can wait.

04:50:40.438 --> 04:50:44.338
The attendant came to tell me, so I ran down at once to have a look at him.

04:50:45.058 --> 04:50:48.278
He was still in the straight waistcoat and in the padded room,

04:50:48.618 --> 04:50:53.878
but the suffused look has gone from his face and his eyes had something of their old pleading.

04:50:54.678 --> 04:50:57.798
I might almost say cringing softness.

04:50:58.358 --> 04:51:02.258
I was satisfied with his present condition and directed him to be relieved.

04:51:02.958 --> 04:51:06.878
The attendants hesitated, but finally carried out my wishes without protest.

04:51:07.738 --> 04:51:11.538
It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust,

04:51:11.618 --> 04:51:16.578
for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them,

04:51:17.218 --> 04:51:20.938
they think I could hurt you, fancy me hurting you, the fools.

04:51:21.578 --> 04:51:26.258
It was soothing somehow to the feelings to find myself disassociated

04:51:26.258 --> 04:51:29.298
even in the mind of this poor madman from the others.

04:51:29.878 --> 04:51:32.238
But all the same I could not follow his thought.

04:51:32.998 --> 04:51:38.158
Am I to take it that I have anything in common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together?

04:51:39.178 --> 04:51:44.278
Or has he to gain from me some good so stupendous that my well-being is needful to him?

04:51:44.838 --> 04:51:46.698
I must find out later on.

04:51:47.458 --> 04:51:48.998
Tonight he will not speak.

04:51:49.498 --> 04:51:53.118
Even the offer of a kitten or even a full-grown cat will not tempt him.

04:51:53.598 --> 04:51:56.838
He will only say, I don't take any stock in cats.

04:51:57.398 --> 04:52:00.738
I have more to think of now, and I can wait, I can wait.

04:52:01.618 --> 04:52:03.298
After a while I left him.

04:52:03.598 --> 04:52:06.958
The attendant tells me that he was quiet until just before dawn,

04:52:07.418 --> 04:52:10.958
and that then he began to get uneasy, and at length violent,

04:52:10.958 --> 04:52:15.358
until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted him,

04:52:15.378 --> 04:52:17.318
so that he swooned into a sort of coma.

04:52:18.238 --> 04:52:20.598
Three nights has the same thing happened.

04:52:20.958 --> 04:52:24.598
Violent all day, then quiet from moonrise to sunrise.

04:52:25.358 --> 04:52:27.678
I wish I could get some clue to the cause.

04:52:28.058 --> 04:52:31.758
It would almost seem as if there was some influence which came and went.

04:52:32.198 --> 04:52:32.978
Happy thought.

04:52:34.078 --> 04:52:37.598
We shall tonight play sane wits against mad ones.

04:52:38.258 --> 04:52:40.298
He escaped before without our help.

04:52:40.298 --> 04:52:42.418
Tonight he shall escape with it.

04:52:42.978 --> 04:52:47.218
We shall give him a chance and have the men ready to follow in case they are required.

04:52:49.078 --> 04:52:50.058
23rd August

04:52:50.898 --> 04:52:53.238
The expected always happens.

04:52:54.198 --> 04:52:56.678
How well does Rayleigh knew life.

04:52:57.618 --> 04:53:00.298
Our bird when he found the cage open would not fly,

04:53:00.538 --> 04:53:02.738
so all our subtle arrangements were for naught.

04:53:03.358 --> 04:53:05.358
At any rate we have proved one thing,

04:53:05.538 --> 04:53:08.458
that the spells of quietness last a reasonable time.

04:53:08.458 --> 04:53:13.358
We shall in future be able to ease his bonds for a few hours each day.

04:53:13.918 --> 04:53:17.618
I have given orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room

04:53:17.618 --> 04:53:20.998
and once he is quiet, until the hour before sunrise.

04:53:21.798 --> 04:53:26.778
The poor soul's body will enjoy the relief even if his mind cannot appreciate it.

04:53:27.258 --> 04:53:30.258
Hark! the unexpected again, I am called.

04:53:30.858 --> 04:53:32.718
Patient has once more escaped.

04:53:34.098 --> 04:53:34.618
Later.

04:53:35.638 --> 04:53:37.038
Another night adventure.

04:53:37.798 --> 04:53:41.638
Renfield artfully waited until the attendant was entering the room to inspect.

04:53:42.198 --> 04:53:44.898
Then he dashed out past him and flew down the passage.

04:53:45.478 --> 04:53:47.538
I sent word for the attendants to follow.

04:53:48.238 --> 04:53:50.678
Again he went into the grounds of the deserted house

04:53:50.678 --> 04:53:54.438
and we found him in the same place pressed against the old chapel door.

04:53:55.258 --> 04:53:57.178
When he saw me he became furious

04:53:57.178 --> 04:54:00.978
and had not the attendant seized him in time he would have tried to kill me.

04:54:01.318 --> 04:54:03.798
As we were holding him a strange thing happened.

04:54:04.198 --> 04:54:06.118
He suddenly redoubled his efforts

04:54:06.118 --> 04:54:08.498
and then as suddenly grew calm.

04:54:09.438 --> 04:54:12.018
I looked round instinctively but could see nothing.

04:54:12.798 --> 04:54:15.238
Then I caught the patient's eye and followed it

04:54:15.238 --> 04:54:18.418
but could trace nothing as it looked into the moonlight sky

04:54:18.418 --> 04:54:23.538
except a big bat which was flapping its silent and ghostly way to the west.

04:54:24.718 --> 04:54:28.558
Bats usually wheel about but this one seemed to go straight on

04:54:28.558 --> 04:54:32.378
as if it knew where it was bound for or had some intention of its own.

04:54:33.118 --> 04:54:36.958
The patient grew calmer every instant and presently said,

04:54:37.538 --> 04:54:39.998
You needn't tie me. I shall go quietly.

04:54:40.998 --> 04:54:43.018
Without trouble we came back to the house.

04:54:43.538 --> 04:54:47.538
I feel that there is something ominous in his calm and shall not forget this night.

04:54:49.638 --> 04:54:51.838
Lucy with Stenra's Diary.

04:54:52.038 --> 04:54:53.698
Hillingham 24 August.

04:54:54.178 --> 04:54:57.138
I must imitate Mina and keep writing things down.

04:54:57.438 --> 04:54:59.518
Then we can have long talks when we do meet.

04:54:59.958 --> 04:55:01.218
I wonder when it will be.

04:55:01.218 --> 04:55:04.178
I wish she were with me again for I feel so unhappy.

04:55:04.698 --> 04:55:08.198
Last night I seemed to be dreaming again just as I was at Whitby.

04:55:08.318 --> 04:55:10.998
Perhaps it is the change of air or getting home again.

04:55:11.278 --> 04:55:14.458
It is all dark and horrid to me for I can remember nothing

04:55:14.458 --> 04:55:19.698
but I am full of vague fear and I feel so weak and worn out.

04:55:20.138 --> 04:55:23.458
When Arthur came to lunch he looked quite grieved when he saw me

04:55:23.458 --> 04:55:25.598
and I had in the spirit to try to be cheerful.

04:55:26.018 --> 04:55:28.238
I wonder if I could sleep in mother's room tonight.

04:55:28.338 --> 04:55:30.318
I shall make an excuse to try.

04:55:32.978 --> 04:55:33.938
25 August.

04:55:34.518 --> 04:55:35.858
Another bad night.

04:55:36.618 --> 04:55:38.478
Mother Nut seemed to take to my proposal.

04:55:38.778 --> 04:55:42.118
She seems not too well herself and doubtless she fears to worry me.

04:55:42.498 --> 04:55:44.998
I tried to keep awake and succeeded for a while

04:55:44.998 --> 04:55:47.938
but when the clock struck twelve it waked me from a doze

04:55:47.938 --> 04:55:49.578
so I must have been falling asleep.

04:55:50.298 --> 04:55:52.918
There was a sort of scratching or flapping at the window

04:55:52.918 --> 04:55:56.078
but I did not mind it and as I remember no more

04:55:56.078 --> 04:55:57.838
I suppose I must have fallen asleep.

04:55:58.398 --> 04:55:59.498
More bad dreams.

04:55:59.498 --> 04:56:01.378
I wish I could remember them.

04:56:01.638 --> 04:56:03.478
This morning I am horribly weak.

04:56:03.758 --> 04:56:06.838
My face is ghastly pale and my throat pains me.

04:56:07.498 --> 04:56:09.318
It must be something wrong with my lungs

04:56:09.318 --> 04:56:11.218
for I don't seem to be getting air enough.

04:56:11.758 --> 04:56:13.778
I shall try to cheer up when Arthur comes

04:56:13.778 --> 04:56:16.418
or else I know he will be miserable to see me so.

04:56:19.558 --> 04:56:20.038
Letter.

04:56:21.118 --> 04:56:22.818
Arthur to Dr. Seward.

04:56:23.558 --> 04:56:24.598
Albemarle Hotel.

04:56:25.558 --> 04:56:26.598
31 August.

04:56:27.078 --> 04:56:30.198
My dear Jack, I want you to do me a favour.

04:56:30.978 --> 04:56:31.858
Lucy is ill.

04:56:32.218 --> 04:56:33.978
That is she has no special disease

04:56:33.978 --> 04:56:36.518
but she looks awful and is getting worse every day.

04:56:37.138 --> 04:56:38.938
I have asked her if there is any cause.

04:56:39.898 --> 04:56:41.578
I do not dare to ask her mother

04:56:41.578 --> 04:56:43.998
for to disturb the poor lady's mind about her daughter

04:56:43.998 --> 04:56:46.018
and her present state of health would be fatal.

04:56:47.038 --> 04:56:49.978
Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her doom is spoken.

04:56:50.558 --> 04:56:51.578
Disease of the heart.

04:56:51.898 --> 04:56:53.558
The poor Lucy does not know it yet.

04:56:54.038 --> 04:56:56.178
I am sure that there is something praying

04:56:56.178 --> 04:56:57.578
on my dear girl's mind.

04:56:57.678 --> 04:57:00.038
I am almost distracted when I think of her.

04:57:00.658 --> 04:57:02.338
To look at her gives me a pang.

04:57:02.958 --> 04:57:04.778
I told her I should ask you to see her

04:57:04.778 --> 04:57:06.138
and though she demurred at first

04:57:06.138 --> 04:57:08.478
I know why, old fellow, she finally consented.

04:57:09.718 --> 04:57:12.518
It will be a painful task for you, I know, old friend,

04:57:12.618 --> 04:57:15.398
but it is for her sake and I must not hesitate to ask

04:57:15.398 --> 04:57:16.278
or you to act.

04:57:16.638 --> 04:57:18.678
You are to come at lunch at Hilling tomorrow.

04:57:19.718 --> 04:57:22.358
Two o'clock, so as not to arouse any suspicion

04:57:22.358 --> 04:57:23.418
of Mrs. Westenra.

04:57:23.878 --> 04:57:26.058
And after lunch Lucy will take an opportunity

04:57:26.058 --> 04:57:27.298
of being alone with you.

04:57:27.798 --> 04:57:30.278
I am filled with anxiety and I want to consult with you

04:57:30.278 --> 04:57:32.578
alone as soon as I can after you have seen her.

04:57:32.918 --> 04:57:33.978
Do not fail.

04:57:35.758 --> 04:57:36.278
Arthur

04:57:39.258 --> 04:57:39.778
TELEGRAM

04:57:40.338 --> 04:57:41.958
Arthur Holmwood to Seward

04:57:43.078 --> 04:57:44.118
1 September

04:57:44.118 --> 04:57:46.258
I am summoned to see my father,

04:57:46.318 --> 04:57:47.118
who is worse.

04:57:47.578 --> 04:57:50.358
I am writing. Write me fully by tonight's post

04:57:50.358 --> 04:57:50.898
to ring.

04:57:51.798 --> 04:57:53.298
Wire me if necessary.

04:57:55.478 --> 04:57:55.998
Letter

04:57:55.998 --> 04:57:58.458
from Dr. Seward to Arthur Holmwood

04:57:59.738 --> 04:58:00.778
2 September

04:58:01.678 --> 04:58:03.278
My dear old fellow,

04:58:03.798 --> 04:58:05.698
with regard to Mrs. Westenra's health

04:58:05.698 --> 04:58:07.358
I hasten to let you know at once

04:58:07.358 --> 04:58:10.178
that in my opinion there is not any functional disturbance

04:58:10.178 --> 04:58:12.138
or any malady that I know of.

04:58:12.458 --> 04:58:15.038
At the same time I am not by any means satisfied

04:58:15.038 --> 04:58:15.898
with her appearance.

04:58:16.298 --> 04:58:18.358
She is woefully different from what she was

04:58:18.358 --> 04:58:19.498
when I saw her last.

04:58:19.498 --> 04:58:21.478
Of course you must bear in mind

04:58:21.478 --> 04:58:23.758
that I have not had the full opportunity of examination

04:58:23.758 --> 04:58:24.878
such as I should wish.

04:58:25.418 --> 04:58:27.378
Our very friendship makes a little difficulty

04:58:27.378 --> 04:58:29.678
which not even medicinal science or custom

04:58:29.678 --> 04:58:30.518
can bridge over.

04:58:31.038 --> 04:58:32.998
I had better tell you exactly what happened,

04:58:33.078 --> 04:58:35.758
leaving you to draw, in a measure, your own conclusions.

04:58:36.158 --> 04:58:37.738
I shall then say what I have done

04:58:37.738 --> 04:58:38.698
and propose doing.

04:58:39.618 --> 04:58:42.318
I found Mrs. Westenra in seemingly gay spirits.

04:58:42.498 --> 04:58:43.578
Her mother was present

04:58:43.578 --> 04:58:45.358
and in a few seconds I made up my mind

04:58:45.358 --> 04:58:47.598
that she was trying all she knew to mislead her mother

04:58:47.598 --> 04:58:49.098
and prevent her from being anxious.

04:58:49.598 --> 04:58:51.938
I have no doubt she guesses if she does not know

04:58:51.938 --> 04:58:53.618
what need of caution there is.

04:58:54.418 --> 04:58:55.598
We lunched alone

04:58:55.598 --> 04:58:57.558
and as we all exerted ourselves to be

04:58:57.558 --> 04:58:59.658
cheerful we got, as some kind of reward

04:58:59.658 --> 04:59:01.738
for our labors, some real cheerfulness

04:59:01.738 --> 04:59:02.698
amongst us.

04:59:03.518 --> 04:59:05.538
Then Mrs. Westenra went to lie down

04:59:05.538 --> 04:59:06.998
and Lucy was left with me.

04:59:07.418 --> 04:59:08.678
We went into her boudoir.

04:59:09.458 --> 04:59:11.318
Until we got there her gaiety remained

04:59:11.318 --> 04:59:13.038
for the servants were coming and going.

04:59:13.778 --> 04:59:15.478
As soon as the door was closed however

04:59:15.478 --> 04:59:17.218
the mask fell from her face

04:59:17.218 --> 04:59:19.938
and she sunk down into a chair with a great sigh

04:59:19.938 --> 04:59:21.538
and hid her eyes with her hand.

04:59:22.078 --> 04:59:23.798
When I saw that her high spirits had

04:59:23.798 --> 04:59:25.558
failed I at once took advantage of her

04:59:25.558 --> 04:59:27.038
reaction to make a diagnosis.

04:59:27.858 --> 04:59:29.618
She said to me very sweetly,

04:59:29.798 --> 04:59:31.478
I cannot tell you how I loathe

04:59:31.478 --> 04:59:32.698
talking about myself.

04:59:33.238 --> 04:59:35.878
I reminded her that a doctor's confidence was sacred

04:59:35.878 --> 04:59:37.618
but that you were grievously anxious

04:59:37.618 --> 04:59:39.518
about her. She caught on

04:59:39.518 --> 04:59:41.658
to my meaning at once and settled that matter

04:59:41.658 --> 04:59:43.578
in a word. Tell author

04:59:43.578 --> 04:59:46.098
everything you choose. I do not care

04:59:46.098 --> 04:59:47.578
for myself but for him

04:59:47.578 --> 04:59:49.018
so I am quite free.

04:59:49.718 --> 04:59:51.678
I could easily see that she was somewhat

04:59:51.678 --> 04:59:53.578
bloodless but I could not see the usual

04:59:53.578 --> 04:59:56.058
anemic signs and by the chance

04:59:56.058 --> 04:59:57.898
I was able to test the actual quality

04:59:57.898 --> 04:59:59.738
of her blood. For an opening

04:59:59.738 --> 05:00:01.578
of the window which was stiff a cord

05:00:01.578 --> 05:00:03.778
gave way and she cut her hands

05:00:03.778 --> 05:00:05.278
slightly with broken glass.

05:00:05.758 --> 05:00:07.718
It was a slight matter in itself but it

05:00:07.718 --> 05:00:09.618
gave me an evident chance and I secured

05:00:09.618 --> 05:00:11.698
a few drops of the blood and have analyzed

05:00:11.698 --> 05:00:13.948
them. The qualitative analysis

05:00:14.438 --> 05:00:16.358
gave a quite normal condition

05:00:16.358 --> 05:00:17.998
and shows I should infer

05:00:17.998 --> 05:00:19.998
in itself a vigorous state of health.

05:00:20.598 --> 05:00:21.798
In other physical matters

05:00:21.798 --> 05:00:23.938
I was quite satisfied that there is no need

05:00:23.938 --> 05:00:25.898
for anxiety but as there must be

05:00:25.898 --> 05:00:27.938
a cause somewhere I have come to the conclusion

05:00:27.938 --> 05:00:29.538
that it must be something mental.

05:00:30.718 --> 05:00:32.118
She complains of difficulty

05:00:32.118 --> 05:00:34.278
breathing satisfactorily at times

05:00:34.278 --> 05:00:36.158
and of heavy lethargic

05:00:36.158 --> 05:00:38.078
sleep with dreams that frighten

05:00:38.078 --> 05:00:39.938
her but regarding which

05:00:39.938 --> 05:00:42.158
she can remember nothing. She says

05:00:42.158 --> 05:00:44.278
that as a child she used to walk in her sleep

05:00:44.278 --> 05:00:46.118
and that when in Whitby the habit came back

05:00:47.058 --> 05:00:48.138
and that once she

05:00:48.138 --> 05:00:50.138
walked out in the night and went out to Eastcliff

05:00:50.138 --> 05:00:51.998
where Miss Murray found her. But

05:00:51.998 --> 05:00:54.058
she assures me that of late that habit has not

05:00:54.058 --> 05:00:54.638
returned.

05:00:55.838 --> 05:00:57.918
I am in doubt and so have done the best

05:00:57.918 --> 05:00:59.978
thing I know of. I have written to

05:00:59.978 --> 05:01:01.918
my old friend and master, Professor

05:01:01.918 --> 05:01:03.898
Van Helsing of Amsterdam

05:01:03.898 --> 05:01:05.998
who knows as much about obscure diseases

05:01:05.998 --> 05:01:08.118
as anyone in the world. I have asked

05:01:08.118 --> 05:01:10.278
him to come over and as you told me that

05:01:10.278 --> 05:01:12.238
all things were to be at your charge I have mentioned

05:01:12.238 --> 05:01:14.078
to him who you are and your relation to

05:01:14.078 --> 05:01:16.258
Miss Westenra. This my dear

05:01:16.258 --> 05:01:18.218
fellow is an obedience to your wishes for I

05:01:18.218 --> 05:01:20.118
am only too proud and happy to do anything

05:01:20.118 --> 05:01:21.158
I can for her.

05:01:23.158 --> 05:01:24.478
Van Helsing would I know

05:01:24.478 --> 05:01:26.138
do anything for me for a personal

05:01:26.138 --> 05:01:28.138
reason so no matter on what ground he

05:01:28.138 --> 05:01:29.818
comes we must accept his wishes.

05:01:30.458 --> 05:01:32.458
He is a seemingly arbitrary man

05:01:32.458 --> 05:01:34.218
this is because he knows what he is talking

05:01:34.218 --> 05:01:35.738
about better than anyone else.

05:01:35.738 --> 05:01:37.738
He is a philosopher and a metaphysician

05:01:38.358 --> 05:01:40.038
and one of the most advanced scientists

05:01:40.038 --> 05:01:42.198
of its day and he has I believe

05:01:42.198 --> 05:01:43.758
an absolutely open mind.

05:01:44.158 --> 05:01:46.038
This with an iron nerve a temper

05:01:46.038 --> 05:01:48.138
of the ice brook and indomitable

05:01:48.138 --> 05:01:49.958
resolution, self command and

05:01:49.958 --> 05:01:52.058
toleration exalted from virtues to

05:01:52.058 --> 05:01:54.278
blessings and the kindliest

05:01:54.278 --> 05:01:55.878
and truest heart that beats.

05:01:56.698 --> 05:01:58.358
He is from his equipment for the noble

05:01:58.358 --> 05:02:00.138
work that he is doing for mankind

05:02:00.138 --> 05:02:02.418
work both in theory and practice

05:02:02.418 --> 05:02:04.078
for his views are as wide as his

05:02:04.078 --> 05:02:05.238
all embracing sympathy.

05:02:05.918 --> 05:02:07.938
I tell you these facts that you may know why

05:02:07.938 --> 05:02:09.458
I have such confidence in him.

05:02:09.858 --> 05:02:11.498
I have asked him to come at once.

05:02:11.878 --> 05:02:14.298
I shall see Miss Westenra tomorrow again.

05:02:14.658 --> 05:02:16.158
She is to meet me at the stores

05:02:16.158 --> 05:02:18.218
so that I may not alarm her mother by too early

05:02:18.218 --> 05:02:19.858
a repetition of my call.

05:02:21.198 --> 05:02:22.078
Yours always

05:02:22.078 --> 05:02:23.078
John Seward

05:02:25.478 --> 05:02:25.918
Letter

05:02:26.838 --> 05:02:28.078
Abraham Van Helsing

05:02:28.918 --> 05:02:30.858
M.D. D.P.H.

05:02:31.078 --> 05:02:32.218
D.L.I.T. etc.

05:02:32.798 --> 05:02:34.278
To Dr. Seward

05:02:35.318 --> 05:02:36.278
2. September

05:02:36.918 --> 05:02:38.278
My good friend,

05:02:38.418 --> 05:02:40.358
when I received your letter I am already

05:02:40.358 --> 05:02:42.398
coming to you. By good fortune I can

05:02:42.398 --> 05:02:44.318
leave just as once without wrong to

05:02:44.318 --> 05:02:45.878
any of those who have trusted me.

05:02:46.618 --> 05:02:48.298
Were fortune other, then it were bad

05:02:48.298 --> 05:02:50.358
for those who have trusted, for I come to my

05:02:50.358 --> 05:02:52.418
friend when he call me to aid those he holds

05:02:52.418 --> 05:02:54.238
dear. Tell your friend that

05:02:54.238 --> 05:02:56.378
when time you suck from my wound so swiftly

05:02:56.378 --> 05:02:58.458
the poison of the gangrene from that knife

05:02:58.458 --> 05:03:00.598
that our other friend too nervous let slip

05:03:00.598 --> 05:03:03.058
you did more for him when he wants my aids

05:03:03.058 --> 05:03:04.838
and you call for them than all his great

05:03:04.838 --> 05:03:06.978
fortune could do. But it is pleasure

05:03:06.978 --> 05:03:08.538
added to do for him, your friend,

05:03:08.578 --> 05:03:09.898
it is you that I come.

05:03:11.278 --> 05:03:12.738
Have near at hand and please

05:03:12.738 --> 05:03:14.758
it so arranged that we see the young lady

05:03:14.758 --> 05:03:16.938
not too late on tomorrow, for it is likely

05:03:16.938 --> 05:03:18.738
that I may have to return here that night.

05:03:19.158 --> 05:03:20.738
But if need be I shall come again

05:03:20.738 --> 05:03:22.978
in three days and stay longer if it must.

05:03:23.438 --> 05:03:25.018
Till then, good-bye,

05:03:25.238 --> 05:03:26.558
my friend John.

05:03:28.518 --> 05:03:29.398
Van Helsing

05:03:32.278 --> 05:03:32.758
Letters

05:03:32.758 --> 05:03:33.098
Letter

05:03:33.098 --> 05:03:35.398
Dr. Stuart to Hon. Arthur Holmwood

05:03:36.978 --> 05:03:37.938
3. September

05:03:38.618 --> 05:03:39.938
My dear Art,

05:03:40.318 --> 05:03:41.718
Van Helsing is come and gone.

05:03:41.858 --> 05:03:43.438
He came on with me to Hillingham and

05:03:43.438 --> 05:03:45.438
found that by Lucy's discretion her mother

05:03:45.438 --> 05:03:47.858
was lunching out so that we were alone with her.

05:03:48.758 --> 05:03:50.278
Van Helsing made a very careful

05:03:50.278 --> 05:03:51.658
examination of the patient.

05:03:51.818 --> 05:03:53.378
He is to report to me and I shall

05:03:53.378 --> 05:03:55.698
advise you, for of course I was not

05:03:55.698 --> 05:03:56.798
present all the time.

05:03:56.798 --> 05:03:59.078
He is, I fear, much concerned,

05:03:59.158 --> 05:04:01.018
but says he must think. When I told

05:04:01.018 --> 05:04:02.918
him of our friendship and how you trust me

05:04:02.918 --> 05:04:04.918
in the matter, he said, you must tell him

05:04:04.918 --> 05:04:07.078
all you think. Tell him, him,

05:04:07.078 --> 05:04:09.198
what I think, if you can guess it, if you will.

05:04:09.698 --> 05:04:10.978
Nay, I am not jesting.

05:04:11.018 --> 05:04:12.758
There is no jest, but life and death,

05:04:12.798 --> 05:04:13.578
perhaps more.

05:04:14.438 --> 05:04:16.718
I asked what he meant by that, for he was very

05:04:16.718 --> 05:04:18.758
serious. This was when we had come back

05:04:18.758 --> 05:04:20.658
to town and he was having a cup of tea

05:04:20.658 --> 05:04:22.898
before starting on his return to Amsterdam.

05:04:23.378 --> 05:04:24.858
He would not give me any further

05:04:24.858 --> 05:04:27.238
clue. You must not be angry with me,

05:04:27.438 --> 05:04:28.998
Art, because his very reticence

05:04:28.998 --> 05:04:31.098
means that all his brains are working for her

05:04:31.098 --> 05:04:33.098
good. He will speak plainly enough

05:04:33.098 --> 05:04:34.618
when the time comes, be sure.

05:04:35.098 --> 05:04:37.018
So I told him I would simply write an account

05:04:37.018 --> 05:04:38.958
of our visit, just as if I were doing

05:04:38.958 --> 05:04:41.058
a descriptive special article for the Daily

05:04:41.058 --> 05:04:43.038
Telegraph. He seemed not to

05:04:43.038 --> 05:04:44.998
notice, but remarked that the smuts of London

05:04:44.998 --> 05:04:46.878
were not quite so bad as they used to be when he

05:04:46.878 --> 05:04:48.958
was a student here. I am to

05:04:48.958 --> 05:04:50.858
get his report tomorrow if he can possibly

05:04:50.858 --> 05:04:52.898
make it. In any case, I am to have

05:04:52.898 --> 05:04:53.258
a letter.

05:04:54.458 --> 05:04:56.958
Well, as to the visit, Lucy

05:04:56.958 --> 05:04:58.898
was more cheerful than on the day I first

05:04:58.898 --> 05:05:00.638
saw her, and certainly looked better.

05:05:00.978 --> 05:05:02.778
She had lost something of the ghastly look

05:05:02.778 --> 05:05:04.958
that so upset you, and her breathing was normal.

05:05:05.298 --> 05:05:06.958
She was very sweet to the Professor,

05:05:07.178 --> 05:05:09.018
as she always is, and tried

05:05:09.018 --> 05:05:10.778
to make him feel at ease, though I could see

05:05:10.778 --> 05:05:13.178
the poor girl was making a hard struggle for it.

05:05:13.658 --> 05:05:15.018
I believe Van Helsing

05:05:15.018 --> 05:05:17.078
saw it too, for I saw the quick

05:05:17.078 --> 05:05:18.818
look under his bushy brows that I knew

05:05:18.818 --> 05:05:20.938
of old. Then he began to chat of

05:05:20.938 --> 05:05:23.078
all things except ourselves and diseases,

05:05:23.158 --> 05:05:25.258
and with such an infinite geniality

05:05:25.258 --> 05:05:27.118
that I could see poor Lucy's pretense

05:05:27.118 --> 05:05:29.018
of animation merge into reality.

05:05:29.518 --> 05:05:31.138
Then, without any seeming change,

05:05:31.158 --> 05:05:32.978
he brought the conversation gently round

05:05:32.978 --> 05:05:34.738
to his visit, and suavely said,

05:05:36.558 --> 05:05:39.078
My dear young Miss, I have the so

05:05:39.078 --> 05:05:40.818
great pleasure because you are so much

05:05:40.818 --> 05:05:43.018
beloved. That is much, my dear.

05:05:43.518 --> 05:05:45.338
Even there, that which I did not

05:05:45.338 --> 05:05:47.038
see. They told me you were down

05:05:47.038 --> 05:05:48.938
in the spirit, and that you were of a ghastly

05:05:48.938 --> 05:05:51.198
tale. To them I say poof,

05:05:51.518 --> 05:05:53.058
and he snapped his fingers at me

05:05:53.058 --> 05:05:55.078
and went on. But you and I shall

05:05:55.078 --> 05:05:56.938
show them how wrong they are. How

05:05:56.938 --> 05:05:58.998
can he, and he pointed at me with the same

05:05:58.998 --> 05:06:00.978
look and gesture as that which he pointed me

05:06:00.978 --> 05:06:03.158
out in his class, on and rather

05:06:03.158 --> 05:06:05.118
after a particular occasion which he never

05:06:05.118 --> 05:06:06.958
fails to remind me of, know

05:06:06.958 --> 05:06:08.518
anything of a young lady's.

05:06:08.838 --> 05:06:10.958
He had his mad men to play with and to bring

05:06:10.958 --> 05:06:12.998
them back to happiness, and to those

05:06:12.998 --> 05:06:14.898
that love them. It is much to do,

05:06:14.938 --> 05:06:17.038
and oh, but there are rewards in that we can bestow

05:06:17.038 --> 05:06:19.038
such happiness. But the young ladies,

05:06:19.378 --> 05:06:21.018
he has no wife nor daughter,

05:06:21.078 --> 05:06:22.958
and the young do not tell themselves to the young,

05:06:23.238 --> 05:06:25.158
but to the old, like me, who have known

05:06:25.158 --> 05:06:27.158
so many sorrows and the causes of them.

05:06:27.438 --> 05:06:29.178
So, my dear, we will send him away

05:06:29.178 --> 05:06:31.038
to smoke the cigarette in the garden, whilst

05:06:31.038 --> 05:06:33.378
you and I have a little talk all to ourselves.

05:06:34.038 --> 05:06:34.998
I took the hint

05:06:34.998 --> 05:06:37.158
and strolled about, and presently the professor

05:06:37.158 --> 05:06:39.098
came to the window and called me in.

05:06:39.438 --> 05:06:40.898
He looked grave, but said,

05:06:41.098 --> 05:06:43.018
I have made careful examination, but

05:06:43.018 --> 05:06:45.098
there is no functional cause. With

05:06:45.098 --> 05:06:47.358
you I agree that there has been much blood

05:06:47.358 --> 05:06:49.318
lost. It has been,

05:06:49.338 --> 05:06:51.298
but is not. But the conditions of her

05:06:51.298 --> 05:06:53.218
are in no way anemic. I have asked

05:06:53.218 --> 05:06:55.258
her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one

05:06:55.258 --> 05:06:57.338
or two questions, that so I may not chance

05:06:57.338 --> 05:06:59.138
to miss nothing. I know well

05:06:59.138 --> 05:07:01.518
what she will say, and yet there is cause.

05:07:01.918 --> 05:07:03.138
There is always cause for

05:07:03.138 --> 05:07:05.338
everything. I must go back home and think.

05:07:05.618 --> 05:07:07.258
You must send me the telegram every

05:07:07.258 --> 05:07:09.238
day, and if there is nothing because, I shall come

05:07:09.238 --> 05:07:11.238
again. The disease, for not to be

05:07:11.238 --> 05:07:13.138
well as the disease, interests me,

05:07:13.138 --> 05:07:15.378
and the sweet, young dear, she interests

05:07:15.378 --> 05:07:17.358
me too. She charmed me,

05:07:17.398 --> 05:07:18.138
and for her?

05:07:19.138 --> 05:07:21.358
It is not for you or disease, I come.

05:07:22.278 --> 05:07:23.178
As I tell you,

05:07:23.178 --> 05:07:25.198
he would not say a word more, even when we

05:07:25.198 --> 05:07:27.218
were alone, and so now, Art, you

05:07:27.218 --> 05:07:29.398
know all I know. I shall keep stern

05:07:29.398 --> 05:07:31.158
watch. I trust your poor

05:07:31.158 --> 05:07:33.318
father is rallying. It must be a

05:07:33.318 --> 05:07:35.318
terrible thing to you, my dear fellow, to be

05:07:35.318 --> 05:07:37.338
placed in such a position between two people

05:07:37.338 --> 05:07:38.718
who are both so dear to you.

05:07:39.078 --> 05:07:41.198
I know your idea of duty to your father, and

05:07:41.198 --> 05:07:43.458
you are right to stick to it. But if need be,

05:07:43.518 --> 05:07:45.538
I shall send you word to come at once to Lucy,

05:07:45.658 --> 05:07:47.298
so not be overanxious unless you

05:07:47.298 --> 05:07:48.618
hear from me.

05:07:50.798 --> 05:07:51.898
Dr. Seward's

05:07:52.338 --> 05:07:52.778
Diary

05:07:52.778 --> 05:07:54.398
4 September

05:07:55.398 --> 05:07:57.598
Zufiga's patient still keeps up our interest

05:07:57.598 --> 05:07:59.498
in him. He had only one outburst,

05:07:59.518 --> 05:08:01.198
and that was yesterday, at an unusual

05:08:01.198 --> 05:08:03.638
time. Just before the stroke of noon,

05:08:03.678 --> 05:08:04.938
he began to grow restless.

05:08:05.198 --> 05:08:07.218
The attendant knew the symptoms, and at once

05:08:07.218 --> 05:08:09.218
summoned aid. Fortunately,

05:08:09.218 --> 05:08:11.498
the men came at a run, and were just in time,

05:08:11.578 --> 05:08:13.438
for at the stroke of noon he became so

05:08:13.438 --> 05:08:15.338
violent that it took all their strength to hold

05:08:15.338 --> 05:08:17.518
him. In about five minutes, however,

05:08:17.558 --> 05:08:19.478
he began to get more quiet, and finally

05:08:19.478 --> 05:08:21.398
sank into a sort of melancholy, in

05:08:21.398 --> 05:08:23.278
which state he has remained up to now.

05:08:23.858 --> 05:08:25.578
The attendant tells me that his

05:08:25.578 --> 05:08:27.278
screams while in the paroxysm

05:08:27.278 --> 05:08:29.518
were really appalling. I found

05:08:29.518 --> 05:08:31.418
my hands full when I got in, attending

05:08:31.418 --> 05:08:33.298
to some of the other patients who were frightened

05:08:33.298 --> 05:08:35.618
by him. Indeed, I can quite understand

05:08:35.618 --> 05:08:37.398
the effect, for the sounds disturbed

05:08:37.398 --> 05:08:39.898
even me, though I was some distance away.

05:08:40.278 --> 05:08:41.758
It is now after the dinner hour

05:08:41.758 --> 05:08:43.638
of the asylum, and as yet my patient

05:08:43.638 --> 05:08:45.518
sits in a corner brooding with a

05:08:45.518 --> 05:08:47.378
dull, sullen, woe-begone look

05:08:47.378 --> 05:08:49.558
in his face, which seems rather to

05:08:49.558 --> 05:08:51.438
indicate than to show something directly.

05:08:51.778 --> 05:08:53.638
I cannot quite understand it.

05:08:54.918 --> 05:08:55.378
Later.

05:08:56.178 --> 05:08:57.658
Another change in my patient.

05:08:57.758 --> 05:08:59.478
At five o'clock I looked in on him

05:08:59.478 --> 05:09:01.738
and found him seemingly as happy and contented

05:09:01.738 --> 05:09:03.398
as he used to be. He was

05:09:03.398 --> 05:09:05.598
catching flies and eating them, and was keeping

05:09:05.598 --> 05:09:07.638
note of his capture by making nail marks

05:09:07.638 --> 05:09:09.718
on the edge of the door between the ridges of

05:09:09.718 --> 05:09:11.598
padding. When he saw me he

05:09:11.598 --> 05:09:13.658
came over and apologized for his bad

05:09:13.658 --> 05:09:15.538
conduct and asked me in a very humble,

05:09:15.778 --> 05:09:17.958
cringing way to be led back to his own room

05:09:17.958 --> 05:09:19.738
and to have his notebook again.

05:09:20.178 --> 05:09:21.638
I thought it well to humor him,

05:09:21.638 --> 05:09:23.858
so he is back in his room with the window open.

05:09:24.358 --> 05:09:25.838
He has the sugar of his tea

05:09:25.838 --> 05:09:27.618
spread out on the windowsill and is

05:09:27.618 --> 05:09:29.438
reaping quite a harvest of flies.

05:09:29.918 --> 05:09:31.518
He is not now eating them, but

05:09:31.518 --> 05:09:33.458
putting them into a box as of old,

05:09:33.458 --> 05:09:36.058
and is already examining the corners of his room

05:09:36.058 --> 05:09:37.018
to find a spider.

05:09:37.638 --> 05:09:39.498
I tried to get him to talk about the past

05:09:39.498 --> 05:09:41.598
few days, for any clue to his thoughts would be

05:09:41.598 --> 05:09:43.678
of an immense help to me, but he would not

05:09:43.678 --> 05:09:45.558
rise. For a moment or two

05:09:45.558 --> 05:09:47.578
he looked very sad and said in a sort

05:09:47.578 --> 05:09:49.558
of far away voice as though saying it

05:09:49.558 --> 05:09:51.218
rather to himself than to me.

05:09:51.938 --> 05:09:53.978
All over, all over,

05:09:54.198 --> 05:09:55.498
he has deserted me.

05:09:55.738 --> 05:09:57.638
No hope for me now unless I do it

05:09:57.638 --> 05:09:59.578
myself. Then suddenly

05:09:59.578 --> 05:10:01.578
turning to me in a resolute way he

05:10:01.578 --> 05:10:03.918
said, Doctor, won't you be

05:10:03.918 --> 05:10:05.618
very good to me and let me have a little

05:10:05.618 --> 05:10:07.658
more sugar? I think it would be very

05:10:07.658 --> 05:10:09.638
good for me. And the

05:10:09.638 --> 05:10:10.558
flies, I said.

05:10:11.758 --> 05:10:13.698
Yes, the flies like it too,

05:10:13.938 --> 05:10:15.698
and I like the flies, therefore

05:10:15.698 --> 05:10:17.598
I like it. And there are

05:10:17.598 --> 05:10:19.558
people who know so little as to think

05:10:19.558 --> 05:10:21.118
that madmen do not argue.

05:10:21.618 --> 05:10:23.558
I procured him a double supply and

05:10:23.558 --> 05:10:25.678
left him as happy as a man, I suppose,

05:10:25.898 --> 05:10:26.778
any in the world.

05:10:28.198 --> 05:10:29.678
I wish I could fathom his

05:10:29.678 --> 05:10:32.038
mind. Midnight,

05:10:32.578 --> 05:10:33.698
another change in him,

05:10:34.058 --> 05:10:35.218
I have been to see Miss

05:10:35.218 --> 05:10:37.218
Westernera whom I found much better

05:10:37.218 --> 05:10:39.438
and has just returned, and was standing

05:10:39.438 --> 05:10:41.518
at our own gate looking at the sunset

05:10:41.518 --> 05:10:43.198
when once more I heard him yelling.

05:10:43.698 --> 05:10:45.538
As his room is on the other side of the

05:10:45.538 --> 05:10:47.458
house I could bear it better in the morning.

05:10:48.038 --> 05:10:49.618
It was a shock to me to turn from

05:10:49.618 --> 05:10:51.538
the wonderful smoky beauty of a

05:10:51.538 --> 05:10:53.398
sunset over London with its lurid

05:10:53.398 --> 05:10:55.298
lights and inky shadows and all the

05:10:55.298 --> 05:10:57.178
marvellous tints that come on foul

05:10:57.178 --> 05:10:59.078
clouds, even as on foul water,

05:10:59.558 --> 05:11:01.138
and to realise all the grim

05:11:01.138 --> 05:11:03.078
sternness of my own cold stone

05:11:03.078 --> 05:11:05.138
building with its wealth of

05:11:05.138 --> 05:11:07.258
breathing misery and my own

05:11:07.258 --> 05:11:09.058
desolate heart to endure it all.

05:11:09.518 --> 05:11:11.258
I reached him just as the sun was

05:11:11.258 --> 05:11:13.178
going down and from his window saw

05:11:13.178 --> 05:11:14.598
the red disc sink.

05:11:15.198 --> 05:11:17.418
As it sank he became less and less

05:11:17.418 --> 05:11:19.138
frenzied and just as it dipped he

05:11:19.138 --> 05:11:20.738
slid from the hands that held him

05:11:20.738 --> 05:11:22.878
an inert mass on the floor.

05:11:23.798 --> 05:11:25.258
It is wonderful, however,

05:11:25.258 --> 05:11:27.198
with intellectual recubative power

05:11:27.198 --> 05:11:29.358
lunatics have for within a few

05:11:29.358 --> 05:11:31.118
minutes he stood up quite calmly and

05:11:31.118 --> 05:11:33.378
looked around him. I signalled to

05:11:33.378 --> 05:11:35.278
the attendants not to hold him for I was

05:11:35.278 --> 05:11:36.818
anxious to see what he would do.

05:11:37.238 --> 05:11:39.078
He went straight over to the window and

05:11:39.078 --> 05:11:40.538
brushed out the crumbs of sugar.

05:11:41.098 --> 05:11:43.018
Then he took his fly box and emptied it

05:11:43.018 --> 05:11:44.938
outside and threw away the box.

05:11:45.458 --> 05:11:47.138
Then he shut the window and crossing

05:11:47.138 --> 05:11:48.738
over sat down on his bed.

05:11:49.358 --> 05:11:51.538
All this surprised me so I asked him

05:11:51.538 --> 05:11:53.378
Are you going to keep

05:11:53.378 --> 05:11:54.418
flies anymore?

05:11:55.638 --> 05:11:57.118
No, said he.

05:11:57.358 --> 05:11:59.278
I am sick of all that rubbish.

05:12:00.158 --> 05:12:01.698
He certainly is a wonderfully

05:12:01.698 --> 05:12:02.798
interesting study.

05:12:03.338 --> 05:12:05.498
I wish I could get some glimpse of his mind

05:12:05.498 --> 05:12:07.318
or of the cause of his sudden passion.

05:12:08.018 --> 05:12:09.618
Stop. There may be a clue

05:12:09.618 --> 05:12:11.698
after all if we can find why today

05:12:11.698 --> 05:12:13.438
his paroxysms came on at

05:12:13.438 --> 05:12:14.818
high noon and at sunset.

05:12:15.698 --> 05:12:17.618
Can it be that there is a malign influence

05:12:17.618 --> 05:12:19.458
of the sun at periods which affect

05:12:19.458 --> 05:12:21.638
certain natures as at times

05:12:21.638 --> 05:12:22.798
the moon does others?

05:12:23.438 --> 05:12:25.438
We shall see.

05:12:52.818 --> 05:12:53.858
TELEGRAM SEWARD

05:12:53.858 --> 05:12:54.658
LONDON

05:12:54.658 --> 05:12:56.738
to Van Helsing, Amsterdam

05:12:56.738 --> 05:12:58.178
6 September

05:12:58.738 --> 05:13:00.358
Terrible change for the worse.

05:13:00.818 --> 05:13:02.838
Come at once. Do not lose an hour.

05:13:03.358 --> 05:13:05.738
I hold over Telegram to Holmwood till I've seen you.

05:13:22.638 --> 05:13:24.178
PISKED WEST

05:13:24.178 --> 05:13:25.538
PRINCE SEWARD ISLAND

05:13:52.282 --> 05:13:57.262
LETTER, Dr. Seward, to Hon. Arthur Homewood, 6th of September.

05:13:58.522 --> 05:14:01.502
My dear Art, my news to-day is not so good.

05:14:02.162 --> 05:14:04.122
Lucy this morning had gone back a bit.

05:14:04.382 --> 05:14:07.462
There is, however, one good thing which has arisen from it.

05:14:07.922 --> 05:14:13.122
Mrs. Westernra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally

05:14:13.122 --> 05:14:13.922
about her.

05:14:14.322 --> 05:14:19.942
I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsink, the great

05:14:20.242 --> 05:14:24.922
specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly

05:14:24.922 --> 05:14:25.662
with myself.

05:14:26.442 --> 05:14:31.442
So now we can come and go without alarming her unduly, for a shock to her would mean

05:14:31.442 --> 05:14:36.082
sudden death, and this, in Lucy's weak condition, might be disastrous to her.

05:14:36.482 --> 05:14:41.642
We are hedged in with difficulties, all of us, my poor fellow, but, please God, we shall

05:14:41.642 --> 05:14:42.902
come through them all right.

05:14:43.682 --> 05:14:49.082
If any need, I shall write, so that, if you do not hear from me, take it for granted that

05:14:49.082 --> 05:14:54.322
I am simply waiting for news, in haste, yours ever, John Seward.

05:14:56.222 --> 05:14:57.402
Dr. Seward's Diary

05:14:59.202 --> 05:15:00.462
7th of September.

05:15:01.102 --> 05:15:05.942
The first thing Van Helsink said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was, Have you

05:15:05.942 --> 05:15:08.782
said anything to a young friend to love of her?

05:15:09.262 --> 05:15:10.242
No, I said.

05:15:10.762 --> 05:15:13.822
I waited till I had seen you, as I said in my telegram.

05:15:14.122 --> 05:15:18.882
I wrote him a letter, simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westernra was not

05:15:18.882 --> 05:15:21.962
so well, and that I should let him know if need be.

05:15:22.462 --> 05:15:24.382
Right, my friend, he said.

05:15:24.902 --> 05:15:27.482
Quite right, better he not know as yet.

05:15:27.722 --> 05:15:29.142
Perhaps he will never know.

05:15:29.682 --> 05:15:32.962
I pray so, but if it be needed, then he shall know all.

05:15:33.502 --> 05:15:36.242
And my good friend John, let me caution you.

05:15:36.642 --> 05:15:38.222
You deal with the madmen.

05:15:38.622 --> 05:15:43.622
All men are mad in some way or the other, and inasmuch as you deal discreetly with your

05:15:43.622 --> 05:15:47.482
madmen, so deal with God's madmen too, the rest of the world.

05:15:48.042 --> 05:15:51.942
You tell not your madmen what you do, nor why you do it.

05:15:52.262 --> 05:15:53.922
You tell them not what you think.

05:15:54.822 --> 05:15:59.562
So you shall keep knowledge in its place, where it may rest, where it may gather its

05:15:59.562 --> 05:16:00.962
kind around it and breed.

05:16:01.622 --> 05:16:05.482
You and I shall keep as yet what we know here and here.

05:16:06.102 --> 05:16:10.622
He touched me on the heart and on the forehead, and then touched himself the same way.

05:16:11.182 --> 05:16:13.622
I have for myself thoughts at the pleasant.

05:16:13.962 --> 05:16:15.822
Later I shall unfold to you.

05:16:15.822 --> 05:16:17.302
Why not now?

05:16:17.322 --> 05:16:17.942
I asked.

05:16:18.322 --> 05:16:19.502
It may do some good.

05:16:19.602 --> 05:16:21.322
We may arrive at some decision.

05:16:22.022 --> 05:16:23.382
He looked at me and said,

05:16:23.642 --> 05:16:29.262
My friend John, while the corn is grown, even before it has ripened, while the milk of its

05:16:29.262 --> 05:16:34.222
mother earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold,

05:16:34.582 --> 05:16:39.462
the husbandman, he pull the air and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the

05:16:39.462 --> 05:16:42.662
green chaff, and say to you, Look, he's good corn.

05:16:42.662 --> 05:16:45.182
He will make a good crop when the time comes.

05:16:46.002 --> 05:16:49.162
I did not see the application, and told him so.

05:16:49.862 --> 05:16:54.162
For reply he reached over and took my ear in his hand and pulled it playfully, as he

05:16:54.162 --> 05:16:59.942
used long ago to do at lectures, and said, The good husbandman tell you so then because

05:16:59.942 --> 05:17:01.982
he knows, but not till then.

05:17:02.682 --> 05:17:07.042
But you do not find the good husbandman dig up his planted corn to see if he grow.

05:17:07.602 --> 05:17:12.422
That is for the children who play a husbandry, and not for those who take it as of other

05:17:12.422 --> 05:17:13.462
work of their life.

05:17:13.922 --> 05:17:15.282
See you now, friend John.

05:17:15.522 --> 05:17:20.042
I have sown my corn, and Nature has her work to do in making it sprout.

05:17:20.182 --> 05:17:25.002
If he sprout at all, there is some promise, and I wait till the ear begins to swell.

05:17:25.562 --> 05:17:29.102
He broke off, for he evidently saw that I understood.

05:17:29.482 --> 05:17:34.762
Then he went on gravely, You were always a careful student, and your case book was ever

05:17:34.762 --> 05:17:38.582
more full than the rest, and I trust that good habit hath not failed.

05:17:39.182 --> 05:17:44.242
Remember, my friend, that knowledge is stronger than memory, and we should not trust the weaker.

05:17:44.902 --> 05:17:49.982
Even if you have not kept a good practice, let me tell you that this case of our dear

05:17:49.982 --> 05:17:56.562
miss is one that may be, mind I say may be, of such interest to us and others that all

05:17:56.562 --> 05:17:59.902
the rest may not make him kick the beam, as your people say.

05:18:00.402 --> 05:18:02.002
Take then good note of it.

05:18:02.182 --> 05:18:03.622
Nothing is too small.

05:18:04.162 --> 05:18:07.942
I counsel you put down in record even your doubts and surmises.

05:18:08.582 --> 05:18:12.282
Hereafter it may be of interest to you to see how true you guess.

05:18:12.642 --> 05:18:15.142
We learn from failure, not from success.

05:18:16.462 --> 05:18:22.002
When I described Lucy's symptoms, the same as before, but infinitely more marked, he

05:18:22.002 --> 05:18:23.942
looked very grave, but said nothing.

05:18:24.462 --> 05:18:29.662
He took with him a bag in which were many instruments and drugs, the ghastly paraphernalia

05:18:29.662 --> 05:18:34.842
of our beneficial trade, as he once called, in one of his lectures, the equipment of a

05:18:34.842 --> 05:18:36.442
of the healing craft.

05:18:37.702 --> 05:18:40.862
When we were shown in, Mrs. Westlandra met us.

05:18:41.102 --> 05:18:44.982
She was alarmed, but not nearly so much as I expected to find her.

05:18:45.662 --> 05:18:50.602
Nature in one of her beneficent moods has ordained that even death has some antidote

05:18:50.602 --> 05:18:51.822
to its own terrors.

05:18:52.482 --> 05:18:57.782
Here in a case where any shock may prove fatal, matters are so ordered that, from some cause

05:18:57.782 --> 05:19:03.142
or other, the things not personal, even the terrible change in her daughter to whom she

05:19:03.142 --> 05:19:05.662
is so attached, do not seem to reach her.

05:19:06.322 --> 05:19:10.982
It is something like the way damed nature gathers round a foreign body an envelope of

05:19:10.982 --> 05:19:15.862
some insensitive tissue which can protect from evil that which it would otherwise harm

05:19:15.862 --> 05:19:16.702
by contact.

05:19:17.462 --> 05:19:22.122
If this be an ordered selfishness, then we should pause before we condemn anyone for

05:19:22.122 --> 05:19:26.902
the vice of egoism, for there may be deeper root for its causes than we have knowledge

05:19:26.902 --> 05:19:27.422
of.

05:19:28.102 --> 05:19:33.802
I used my knowledge of this phase of spiritual pathology and set down a rule that she should

05:19:33.802 --> 05:19:38.802
not be present with Lucy, or think of her illness more than was absolutely required.

05:19:39.442 --> 05:19:44.522
She ascended readily, so readily that I saw again the hand of nature fighting for life.

05:19:45.182 --> 05:19:47.562
Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy's room.

05:19:47.922 --> 05:19:52.502
If I was shocked when I saw her yesterday, I was horrified when I saw her today.

05:19:53.082 --> 05:19:55.662
She was ghastly, chalkily pale.

05:19:56.162 --> 05:20:01.222
The red seemed to have gone even from her lips and gums, and the bones of her face stood

05:20:01.222 --> 05:20:02.242
out prominently.

05:20:02.682 --> 05:20:04.982
Her breathing was painful to see or hear.

05:20:05.922 --> 05:20:10.662
Van Helsing's face grew set as marble, and his eyebrows converged till they almost touched

05:20:10.662 --> 05:20:11.602
over his nose.

05:20:12.482 --> 05:20:17.842
Lucy lay motionless, and did not seem to have strength to speak, so for a while we were

05:20:17.842 --> 05:20:18.502
all silent.

05:20:19.462 --> 05:20:23.062
Then Van Helsing beckoned me, and we went gently out of the room.

05:20:23.662 --> 05:20:28.282
The instant we had closed the door, he stepped quickly along the passage to the next door,

05:20:28.282 --> 05:20:29.122
which was open.

05:20:29.462 --> 05:20:32.182
Then he pulled me quickly in with him and closed the door.

05:20:32.482 --> 05:20:35.182
My God! he said, this is dreadful.

05:20:35.402 --> 05:20:37.062
There is not time to be lost.

05:20:37.422 --> 05:20:41.642
She will die for sheer want of blood to keep the hut's action as it should be.

05:20:41.922 --> 05:20:44.442
There must be a transfusion of blood at once.

05:20:44.882 --> 05:20:46.162
Is it you or me?

05:20:46.862 --> 05:20:48.602
I am younger and stronger, Professor.

05:20:48.702 --> 05:20:49.882
It must be me.

05:20:50.202 --> 05:20:51.542
Then get ready at once.

05:20:51.542 --> 05:20:52.842
I will bring up my bag.

05:20:53.102 --> 05:20:53.842
I am prepared.

05:20:54.862 --> 05:20:59.122
I went downstairs with him, and as we were going there was a knock at the hall door.

05:20:59.562 --> 05:21:03.902
When we reached the hall, the maid had just opened the door, and Arthur was stepping quickly

05:21:03.902 --> 05:21:04.402
in.

05:21:04.782 --> 05:21:08.762
He rushed up to me, saying in an eager whisper, Jack, I was so anxious.

05:21:09.262 --> 05:21:12.942
I read between the lines of your letter, and I have been in an agony.

05:21:13.462 --> 05:21:16.502
The dad was better, so I ran down here to see for myself.

05:21:16.922 --> 05:21:19.042
Is not that gentleman Dr. Van Helsing?

05:21:19.042 --> 05:21:21.582
I am so thankful to you, sir, for coming.

05:21:22.442 --> 05:21:26.782
When first the Professor's eyes had lit upon him, he had been angry at his interruption

05:21:26.782 --> 05:21:32.082
at such a time, but now, as he took in his stalwart proportions and recognized the strong

05:21:32.082 --> 05:21:35.722
young manhood which seemed to emanate from him, his eyes gleamed.

05:21:36.202 --> 05:21:40.862
Without a pause he said to him as he held out his hand, Sir, you have come in time.

05:21:41.162 --> 05:21:42.942
You are the lover of our dear Miss.

05:21:43.082 --> 05:21:45.162
She is bad, very, very bad.

05:21:45.162 --> 05:21:50.002
Nay, my child, do not go like that, for he suddenly grew pale and sat down in a chair

05:21:50.002 --> 05:21:51.062
almost fainting.

05:21:51.542 --> 05:21:53.042
You ought to help her.

05:21:53.282 --> 05:21:56.882
You can do more than any that live, and your courage is your best help.

05:21:57.982 --> 05:21:59.042
What can I do?

05:21:59.162 --> 05:22:00.142
asked Arthur hoarsely.

05:22:00.742 --> 05:22:02.322
Tell me, and I shall do it.

05:22:02.682 --> 05:22:07.462
My life is hers, and I would give the last drop of my blood in my body for her.

05:22:07.902 --> 05:22:12.902
The Professor has a strongly humorous side, and I could from old knowledge detect a trace

05:22:12.902 --> 05:22:14.482
of its origin in his answer.

05:22:14.982 --> 05:22:19.362
My young Sir, I do not ask so much as that, not the last.

05:22:20.462 --> 05:22:21.702
What shall I do?

05:22:21.902 --> 05:22:25.122
There was fire in his eyes, and his open nostrils quivered with intent.

05:22:25.722 --> 05:22:27.362
Van Helsing slapped him on the shoulder.

05:22:27.682 --> 05:22:31.342
Come, he said, you are a man, and it is a man we want.

05:22:31.642 --> 05:22:34.082
You are better than me, better than my friend John.

05:22:34.482 --> 05:22:38.922
Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way.

05:22:39.542 --> 05:22:41.502
Young Miss is bad, very bad.

05:22:41.862 --> 05:22:44.682
She wants blood, and blood she must have or die.

05:22:45.322 --> 05:22:50.162
My friend John and I have consulted, and we are about to perform what we call transfusion

05:22:50.162 --> 05:22:55.242
of blood, to transfer from full veins of one to the empty veins which pine for him.

05:22:55.882 --> 05:22:59.602
John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me.

05:22:59.822 --> 05:23:02.642
Here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence.

05:23:03.062 --> 05:23:08.142
But now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world

05:23:08.142 --> 05:23:08.582
of thought.

05:23:09.002 --> 05:23:12.562
Our nerves are not so calm and our blood so bright than yours.

05:23:13.762 --> 05:23:15.182
Arthur turned to him and said,

05:23:15.682 --> 05:23:19.402
If you only knew how gladly I would die for her you would understand.

05:23:20.082 --> 05:23:22.182
He stopped with a sort of choke in his voice.

05:23:23.182 --> 05:23:24.922
Good boy, said Van Helsing.

05:23:25.402 --> 05:23:29.262
In the not so far off you will be happy that you have done all for her you love.

05:23:29.702 --> 05:23:30.962
Come now and be silent.

05:23:31.422 --> 05:23:36.222
You shall kiss her once before it is done, but then you must go and you must leave at

05:23:36.222 --> 05:23:36.802
my sign.

05:23:36.802 --> 05:23:38.482
Say no word to madam.

05:23:39.382 --> 05:23:40.842
You know how it is with her.

05:23:41.262 --> 05:23:42.262
There must be no shock.

05:23:42.562 --> 05:23:44.182
Any knowledge of this would be one.

05:23:45.222 --> 05:23:45.702
Come."

05:23:45.702 --> 05:23:47.582
We all went up to Lucy's room.

05:23:48.302 --> 05:23:50.282
Arthur by direction remained outside.

05:23:50.762 --> 05:23:53.422
Lucy turned her head and looked at us, but said nothing.

05:23:54.082 --> 05:23:57.662
She was not asleep, but she was simply too weak to make the effort.

05:23:58.262 --> 05:23:59.622
Her eyes spoke to us.

05:23:59.682 --> 05:24:00.642
That was all.

05:24:02.002 --> 05:24:06.082
Van Helsing took some things from his bag and laid them on a little table out of sight.

05:24:06.082 --> 05:24:10.382
Then he mixed a narcotic, and coming over to the bed said cheerily,

05:24:10.762 --> 05:24:12.942
Now, little miss, here is your medicine.

05:24:13.582 --> 05:24:15.062
Drink it off like a good child.

05:24:15.322 --> 05:24:18.162
See I lift you so that to swallow is easy yet.

05:24:18.842 --> 05:24:20.882
She had made the effort with success.

05:24:21.842 --> 05:24:24.582
It astonished me how long the drug took to act.

05:24:24.882 --> 05:24:27.582
This in fact marked the extent of her weakness.

05:24:28.282 --> 05:24:31.842
The time seemed endless until sleep began to flicker in her eyelids.

05:24:31.842 --> 05:24:38.182
At last, however, the narcotic began to manifest its potency, and she fell into a deep sleep.

05:24:39.122 --> 05:24:43.922
When the professor was satisfied, he called Arthur into the room and bade him strip off

05:24:43.922 --> 05:24:44.442
his coat.

05:24:45.042 --> 05:24:49.622
Then he added, You may take that one little kiss whilst I bring over the table.

05:24:50.062 --> 05:24:51.242
Finchon, help to me.

05:24:51.882 --> 05:24:54.582
So neither of us looked while he bent over her.

05:24:55.482 --> 05:25:00.842
Van Helsing turning to me said, He is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need

05:25:00.842 --> 05:25:02.242
not defibrinate it.

05:25:03.082 --> 05:25:07.662
Then with swiftness, but with absolute method, Van Helsing performed the operation.

05:25:08.142 --> 05:25:13.062
As the transfusion went on, something like life seemed to come back to poor Lucy's cheeks,

05:25:13.462 --> 05:25:18.022
and through Arthur's growing power the joy of his face seemed absolutely to shine.

05:25:18.742 --> 05:25:23.982
After a bit I began to grow anxious, for the loss of blood was telling on Arthur, strong

05:25:23.982 --> 05:25:25.062
man as he was.

05:25:25.422 --> 05:25:30.362
It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy's system must have undergone that what

05:25:30.362 --> 05:25:33.462
weakened Arthur only partially restored her.

05:25:34.522 --> 05:25:39.282
But the professor's face was set, and he stood watch in hand, and with his eyes fixed now

05:25:39.282 --> 05:25:40.862
on the patient and now on Arthur.

05:25:41.402 --> 05:25:42.902
I could hear my own heartbeat.

05:25:43.542 --> 05:25:47.322
Presently he said in a soft voice, Do not stir an instant.

05:25:47.602 --> 05:25:48.282
It is enough.

05:25:48.862 --> 05:25:51.002
You will attend him, I will look to her.

05:25:51.902 --> 05:25:55.222
When all was over, I could see how much Arthur was weakened.

05:25:55.652 --> 05:25:58.462
I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away.

05:25:58.662 --> 05:26:03.302
When Van Helsing spoke, without turning round, the man seems to have eyes in the back of

05:26:03.302 --> 05:26:08.802
his head, the brave lover, I think, that serve another kiss which he shall have presently.

05:26:08.922 --> 05:26:13.722
And as he had now finished his operation, he adjusted the pillow to the patient's head.

05:26:14.382 --> 05:26:19.302
As he did so, the narrow black velvet band, which she seems always to wear around her

05:26:19.302 --> 05:26:24.282
throat, buckled with an old diamond buckle which her lover had given her, was dragged

05:26:24.282 --> 05:26:27.242
a little up, and showed a red mark on her throat.

05:26:28.542 --> 05:26:30.042
Arthur did not notice it.

05:26:30.242 --> 05:26:34.742
But I could hear the deep hiss of in-drawn breath, which is one of Van Helsing's ways

05:26:34.742 --> 05:26:36.042
of betraying emotion.

05:26:36.622 --> 05:26:41.402
He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying, Now take him down, our brave

05:26:41.402 --> 05:26:45.162
young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down awhile.

05:26:45.522 --> 05:26:51.042
He must then go home and rest, sleep much, and eat much, that he may be recruited of

05:26:51.042 --> 05:26:52.782
what he has so given to his love.

05:26:52.782 --> 05:26:54.842
He must not stay here.

05:26:55.162 --> 05:26:55.862
Hold a moment.

05:26:56.042 --> 05:26:58.802
I may take it, sir, that you are anxious of result.

05:26:59.282 --> 05:27:03.502
Then bring it with you that in all ways the operation is successful.

05:27:03.922 --> 05:27:09.102
You have saved her life this time, and you can go home and rest easy in mind that all

05:27:09.102 --> 05:27:10.342
that can be is.

05:27:10.802 --> 05:27:13.162
I shall tell her all when she is well.

05:27:13.462 --> 05:27:16.382
She shall love you none the less for what you have done.

05:27:16.702 --> 05:27:18.262
Good-bye."

05:27:18.262 --> 05:27:20.562
When Arthur had gone, I went back to the room.

05:27:21.242 --> 05:27:24.122
Lucy was sleeping gently, but her breathing was stronger.

05:27:24.622 --> 05:27:27.682
I could see the counter-pain move as her breast heaved.

05:27:27.802 --> 05:27:30.862
By the bedside sat Van Helsing, looking at her intently.

05:27:31.522 --> 05:27:33.982
The velvet band again covered the red mark.

05:27:34.502 --> 05:27:38.862
I asked the professor in a whisper, What do you make of that mark on her throat?

05:27:39.302 --> 05:27:40.882
What do you make of it?

05:27:41.302 --> 05:27:45.842
I have not examined it yet, I answered, and then and there proceeded to loose the band.

05:27:45.842 --> 05:27:52.322
Just over the external jugular vein there were two punctures, not large, but not wholesome

05:27:52.322 --> 05:27:52.802
looking.

05:27:53.482 --> 05:27:59.082
There was no sign of disease, but the edges were white and worn-looking, as if by some

05:27:59.082 --> 05:27:59.822
trituration.

05:28:00.822 --> 05:28:06.182
It at once occurred to me that this wound, or whatever it was, might be the means of

05:28:06.182 --> 05:28:07.882
that manifest loss of blood.

05:28:08.362 --> 05:28:12.882
But I abandoned the idea as soon as it formed, for such a thing could not be.

05:28:13.342 --> 05:28:17.562
The whole bed would have been drenched to a scarlet with the blood which the girl must

05:28:17.562 --> 05:28:21.002
have lost to leave such a pallor as she had before the transfusion.

05:28:22.042 --> 05:28:23.482
Well? said Van Helsing.

05:28:24.582 --> 05:28:27.362
Well, said I, I can make nothing of it.

05:28:27.882 --> 05:28:29.182
The professor stood up.

05:28:29.562 --> 05:28:32.602
I must go back to Amsterdam to-night, he said.

05:28:33.202 --> 05:28:35.602
There are books and things there which I want.

05:28:36.042 --> 05:28:40.742
You must remain here all night, and you must not let your sight pass from her.

05:28:41.422 --> 05:28:43.502
Shall I have a nurse? I asked.

05:28:44.202 --> 05:28:48.742
We are the best nurses, you and I. You keep watch all night.

05:28:49.102 --> 05:28:52.182
See that she is well fed, and that nothing disturbs her.

05:28:52.742 --> 05:28:55.062
You must not sleep all the night.

05:28:55.442 --> 05:28:57.722
Later on we can sleep, you and I.

05:28:58.362 --> 05:29:01.822
I shall be back as soon as possible, and then we may begin.

05:29:02.442 --> 05:29:03.162
May begin?

05:29:03.162 --> 05:29:03.722
I said.

05:29:03.962 --> 05:29:05.422
What on earth do you mean?

05:29:05.802 --> 05:29:08.702
We shall see, he answered, as he hurried out.

05:29:08.962 --> 05:29:13.602
He came back a moment later, and put his head inside the door, and said, with a warning

05:29:13.602 --> 05:29:17.122
finger held up, Remember, she is your charge.

05:29:17.442 --> 05:29:21.762
If you leave her, and harm befall, you shall not sleep easy hereafter.

05:29:24.082 --> 05:29:26.642
Dr. Seward's diary, continued.

05:29:27.602 --> 05:29:28.582
8th of September.

05:29:29.602 --> 05:29:31.122
I sat up all night with Lucy.

05:29:31.662 --> 05:29:35.542
The opiate worked itself off towards dusk, and she waked naturally.

05:29:36.182 --> 05:29:39.722
She looked a different being from what she had been before the operation.

05:29:40.162 --> 05:29:45.862
Her spirits even were good, and she was full of a happy vivacity, but I could see evidences

05:29:45.862 --> 05:29:48.822
of the absolute prostration which she had undergone.

05:29:49.242 --> 05:29:54.262
When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her,

05:29:54.462 --> 05:29:59.002
she almost poo-pooed the idea, pointing out her daughter's renewed strength and excellent

05:29:59.002 --> 05:29:59.462
spirits.

05:30:00.002 --> 05:30:03.842
I was firm, however, and made preparations for my long vigil.

05:30:04.362 --> 05:30:09.742
When her maid had prepared her for the night, I came in, having in the meantime had supper,

05:30:09.922 --> 05:30:11.522
and took a seat by the bedside.

05:30:12.262 --> 05:30:16.942
She did not in any way make objection, but she looked at me gratefully whenever I caught

05:30:16.942 --> 05:30:17.562
her eye.

05:30:18.162 --> 05:30:22.902
After a long spell she seemed sinking off to sleep, but with an effort seemed to pull

05:30:22.902 --> 05:30:24.662
herself together and shook it off.

05:30:25.262 --> 05:30:29.902
It was apparent that she did not want to sleep, so I tackled the subject at once.

05:30:30.422 --> 05:30:31.822
You do not want to sleep?

05:30:32.882 --> 05:30:34.562
No, I am afraid.

05:30:35.282 --> 05:30:36.362
Afraid to go to sleep?

05:30:36.582 --> 05:30:37.222
Why so?

05:30:37.342 --> 05:30:39.242
It is the boon we all crave for.

05:30:39.722 --> 05:30:43.822
Oh, not if you were like me, if sleep was to you a presage of horror.

05:30:44.562 --> 05:30:45.862
A presage of horror?

05:30:45.962 --> 05:30:47.302
What on earth do you mean?

05:30:48.002 --> 05:30:49.042
I don't know.

05:30:49.222 --> 05:30:50.662
Oh, I don't know.

05:30:51.042 --> 05:30:52.622
And that is what is so terrible.

05:30:53.042 --> 05:30:56.982
All this weakness comes to me in sleep until I dread the very thought.

05:30:57.702 --> 05:31:00.462
But, my dear girl, you may sleep tonight.

05:31:00.662 --> 05:31:04.922
I am here watching you, and I can promise that nothing will happen.

05:31:05.502 --> 05:31:07.582
I can trust you, she said.

05:31:08.082 --> 05:31:13.182
I seized the opportunity and said, I promise that if I see any evidence of bad dreams I

05:31:13.182 --> 05:31:14.382
will wake you at once.

05:31:14.842 --> 05:31:15.442
You will?

05:31:15.742 --> 05:31:16.762
Will you really?

05:31:17.062 --> 05:31:18.622
How good you are to me.

05:31:18.642 --> 05:31:19.822
Then I will sleep.

05:31:20.162 --> 05:31:24.282
And almost at the word she gave a deep sigh of relief and sank back asleep.

05:31:25.102 --> 05:31:27.382
All night long I watched by her.

05:31:27.542 --> 05:31:32.722
She never stirred, but slept on and on in a deep, tranquil, life-giving, health-giving

05:31:32.722 --> 05:31:33.122
sleep.

05:31:33.862 --> 05:31:38.682
Her lips were slightly parted, and her breast rose and fell with the regularity of a pendulum.

05:31:39.502 --> 05:31:44.302
There was a smile on her face, and it was evident that no bad dreams had come to disturb

05:31:44.302 --> 05:31:45.402
her peace of mind.

05:31:46.022 --> 05:31:50.922
In the early morning her maid came, and I left her in her care and took myself back

05:31:50.922 --> 05:31:53.682
home, for I was anxious about many things.

05:31:53.682 --> 05:31:59.022
I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result

05:31:59.022 --> 05:31:59.962
of the operation.

05:32:00.602 --> 05:32:04.562
My own work, with its manifold arrears, took me all day to clear off.

05:32:05.002 --> 05:32:08.642
It was dark when I was able to inquire about my oophages patient.

05:32:09.262 --> 05:32:10.402
The report was good.

05:32:10.622 --> 05:32:13.362
He had been quite quiet for the past day and night.

05:32:13.962 --> 05:32:18.982
A telegram came from Van Helsing at Amsterdam whilst I was at dinner, suggesting that I

05:32:18.982 --> 05:32:24.202
be at Hillingham tonight, as it might be well to be at hand, and stating that he was leaving

05:32:24.202 --> 05:32:27.102
by the night mail and would join me early in the morning.

05:32:28.782 --> 05:32:29.702
9 September.

05:32:30.202 --> 05:32:33.362
I was pretty tired and worn out when I got to Hillingham.

05:32:33.902 --> 05:32:38.262
For the two nights I had hardly had a wink of sleep, and my brain was beginning to feel

05:32:38.262 --> 05:32:40.662
that numbness which marks cerebral exhaustion.

05:32:41.522 --> 05:32:43.542
Lucy was up and in cheerful spirits.

05:32:43.942 --> 05:32:47.222
When she shook hands with me she looked sharply in my face and said,

05:32:59.162 --> 05:33:02.682
I would not argue the point, but went and had my supper.

05:33:03.422 --> 05:33:08.762
Lucy came with me, and, enlivened by her charming presence, I made an excellent meal and had

05:33:08.762 --> 05:33:11.222
a couple of glasses of the more than excellent port.

05:33:11.922 --> 05:33:16.522
Then Lucy took me upstairs and showed me a room next to her own where a cozy fire was

05:33:16.522 --> 05:33:16.882
burning.

05:33:17.682 --> 05:33:20.442
Now, she said, you must stay here.

05:33:20.762 --> 05:33:23.422
I shall leave this door open and my door too.

05:33:23.782 --> 05:33:29.082
You can lie on the sofa, for I know that nothing would induce any of you doctors to go to bed

05:33:29.082 --> 05:33:31.242
whilst there is a patient above the horizon.

05:33:32.002 --> 05:33:36.082
If I want anything I shall call out, and you can come to me at once.

05:33:36.982 --> 05:33:42.562
I could not but acquiesce, for I was dog-tired, and could not have sat up had I tried.

05:33:43.202 --> 05:33:48.242
So, on her renewing her promise to call me if she should want anything, I lay on the

05:33:48.242 --> 05:33:51.122
sofa and forgot all about everything.

05:33:53.702 --> 05:33:55.202
Lucy Westenra's Diary

05:33:56.922 --> 05:33:58.142
9th of September.

05:33:58.582 --> 05:34:00.202
I feel so happy to-night.

05:34:00.302 --> 05:34:05.602
I have been so miserably weak that to be able to think and move about is like feeling sunshine

05:34:05.602 --> 05:34:09.002
after a long spell of east wind out of a steel sky.

05:34:09.822 --> 05:34:12.802
Somehow Arthur feels very, very close to me.

05:34:13.082 --> 05:34:15.842
I seem to feel his presence warm about me.

05:34:16.362 --> 05:34:21.382
I suppose it is that sickness and weakness are selfish things and turn our inner eyes

05:34:21.382 --> 05:34:26.722
and sympathy on ourselves, whilst health and strength give love rein, and in thought and

05:34:26.722 --> 05:34:28.822
feeling he can wander where he wills.

05:34:29.102 --> 05:34:32.582
I know where my thoughts are, if only Arthur knew.

05:34:33.062 --> 05:34:37.122
My dear, my dear, your ears must tingle as you sleep as mine do waking.

05:34:37.122 --> 05:34:39.882
Oh, the blissful rest of last night!

05:34:40.182 --> 05:34:40.982
How I slept!

05:34:41.302 --> 05:34:43.702
Were that dear, good Dr. Seward watching me?

05:34:44.022 --> 05:34:48.262
And to-night I shall not fear to sleep, since he is close at hand and within call.

05:34:48.862 --> 05:34:51.242
Thank everybody for being so good to me.

05:34:51.402 --> 05:34:52.162
Thank God!

05:34:52.722 --> 05:34:53.722
Good night, Arthur.

05:34:55.402 --> 05:34:57.142
Dr. Seward's Diary

05:34:57.142 --> 05:34:58.602
10th of September.

05:34:58.822 --> 05:35:03.802
I was conscious of the Professor's hand on my head and started to wake all in a second.

05:35:03.802 --> 05:35:07.682
That is one of the things that we learn in an asylum at any rate.

05:35:08.922 --> 05:35:10.482
And how is our patient?

05:35:11.222 --> 05:35:14.882
Well, when I left her, or rather when she left me, I answered.

05:35:15.822 --> 05:35:19.642
Come, let us see, he said, and together we went into the room.

05:35:20.262 --> 05:35:24.902
The blind was down, and I went over to raise it gently, whilst Van Helsing stepped with

05:35:24.902 --> 05:35:27.362
his soft cat-like tread over to the bed.

05:35:28.082 --> 05:35:32.782
As I raised the blind and the morning sunlight flooded the room, I heard the Professor's

05:35:32.782 --> 05:35:37.262
slow hiss of inspiration, and knowing its rarity, a deadly fear shot through my heart.

05:35:37.822 --> 05:35:43.102
As I passed over, he moved back, and his exclamation of horror, caught in the himmel, needed no

05:35:43.102 --> 05:35:45.122
enforcement from his agonized face.

05:35:45.522 --> 05:35:50.342
He raised his hand and pointed to the bed, and his ironed face was drawn and ash-and-white.

05:35:50.842 --> 05:35:52.702
I felt my knees begin to tremble.

05:35:53.302 --> 05:35:58.382
There on the bed, seemingly in a swoon, lay poor Lucy, more horribly white and bland-looking

05:35:58.382 --> 05:35:59.002
than ever.

05:35:59.582 --> 05:36:03.722
Even the lips were white, and the gums seemed to have shrunken back from the teeth, as

05:36:03.722 --> 05:36:06.802
we sometimes see in a corpse after a prolonged illness.

05:36:07.782 --> 05:36:12.282
Van Helsing raised his foot to stamp in anger, but the instinct of his life and all the long

05:36:12.282 --> 05:36:15.362
years of habit stood to him, and he put it down again softly.

05:36:15.942 --> 05:36:17.922
Quick, he said, bring the brandy.

05:36:18.282 --> 05:36:20.922
I flew to the dining-room and returned with a decanter.

05:36:21.342 --> 05:36:25.542
He wedded the poor white lits with it, and together we rubbed palm and wrist and heart.

05:36:26.242 --> 05:36:29.862
He felt her heart, and after a few moments of agonizing suspense said,

05:36:30.422 --> 05:36:31.662
It is not too late.

05:36:32.042 --> 05:36:34.122
It beats, though but feebly.

05:36:34.642 --> 05:36:36.102
All our work is undone.

05:36:36.222 --> 05:36:37.822
We must begin again.

05:36:38.282 --> 05:36:39.942
There is no young author here now.

05:36:40.102 --> 05:36:42.882
I have to call on you yourself this time, friend John.

05:36:43.462 --> 05:36:48.162
As he spoke, he was dipping into his bag and producing the instruments of transfusion.

05:36:48.662 --> 05:36:51.442
I had taken off my coat and rolled up my shirt-sleeve.

05:36:51.442 --> 05:36:56.542
There was no possibility of an opiate just at present, and no need of one, and so without

05:36:56.542 --> 05:36:58.862
a moment's delay we began the operation.

05:36:59.742 --> 05:37:04.202
After a time, it did not seem a short time either, for the draining away of one's blood,

05:37:04.402 --> 05:37:07.522
no matter how willingly it be given, is a terrible feeling.

05:37:07.982 --> 05:37:09.862
Van Helsing held up a warning finger.

05:37:10.682 --> 05:37:16.362
Do not stir, he said, but I fear that with growing strength she may wake, and that would

05:37:16.362 --> 05:37:18.522
make danger oh so much danger.

05:37:18.522 --> 05:37:23.522
But I shall precaution take, I shall give hypodemic injection of morphia.

05:37:24.282 --> 05:37:27.722
He proceeded then swiftly and deftly to carry out his intent.

05:37:28.622 --> 05:37:34.122
The effect on Lucy was not bad, for the faint seemed to merge subtly into the narcotic sleep.

05:37:34.682 --> 05:37:39.402
It was with a feeling of personal pride that I could see a faint tinge of color steal back

05:37:39.402 --> 05:37:41.102
into the pallid cheeks and lips.

05:37:41.702 --> 05:37:47.742
No man knows till he experiences it what it is to feel his own life-blood drawn away into

05:37:47.742 --> 05:37:49.502
the veins of the woman he loves.

05:37:50.242 --> 05:37:52.162
The Professor watched me critically.

05:37:52.622 --> 05:37:54.062
That will do, he said.

05:37:54.462 --> 05:37:59.802
Already, I remonstrated, you took a great deal more from Art, to which he smiled a sad

05:37:59.802 --> 05:38:03.962
sort of smile as he replied, He is her lover, her fiancé.

05:38:04.622 --> 05:38:10.202
You have work, much work to do for her and for others, and the present will suffice.

05:38:11.062 --> 05:38:15.762
When we stopped the operation he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure

05:38:16.442 --> 05:38:16.922
incision.

05:38:17.322 --> 05:38:22.662
I lay down while I waited his leisure to attend to me, for I felt faint and a little sick.

05:38:23.222 --> 05:38:28.422
By and by he bound up my wound and sent me downstairs to get a glass of wine for myself.

05:38:29.062 --> 05:38:34.202
As I was leaving the room he came after me and half whispered, Mind, nothing must be

05:38:34.202 --> 05:38:39.302
said of this, for young lovers should turn up unexpected as before, no word to him.

05:38:39.762 --> 05:38:44.262
It would at once frighten him and enjealous him too, there must be none, so.

05:38:45.082 --> 05:38:49.822
When I came back he looked at me carefully and then said, You are not much to the West,

05:38:50.302 --> 05:38:55.642
go into the room and lie on your sofa and rest awhile, then have much breakfast and

05:38:55.642 --> 05:38:56.482
come here to me.

05:38:57.782 --> 05:39:01.702
I followed out his orders, for I knew how right and wise they were.

05:39:02.042 --> 05:39:05.922
I had done my part, and now my next duty was to keep up my strength.

05:39:06.302 --> 05:39:11.042
I felt very weak, and in the weakness lost something of the amazement at what had occurred.

05:39:11.622 --> 05:39:16.762
I fell asleep on the sofa, however, wondering over and over again how Lucy had made such

05:39:16.762 --> 05:39:21.522
a retrograde movement and how she could have been drained of so much blood with no sign

05:39:21.522 --> 05:39:22.942
anywhere to show for it.

05:39:23.402 --> 05:39:28.482
I think I must have continued my wonder in my dreams, for sleeping and waking my thoughts

05:39:28.482 --> 05:39:33.642
always came back to the little punctures in her throat and the ragged, exhausted appearance

05:39:33.642 --> 05:39:35.882
of their edges, tiny though they were.

05:39:37.102 --> 05:39:42.122
Lucy slept well into the day, and when she woke she was fairly well and strong, though

05:39:42.122 --> 05:39:44.322
not nearly so much so as the day before.

05:39:45.082 --> 05:39:50.042
When Van Helsing had seen her, he went out for a walk, leaving me in charge, with strict

05:39:50.042 --> 05:39:52.722
injunctions that I was not to leave her for a moment.

05:39:53.402 --> 05:39:57.542
I could hear his voice in the hall, asking the way to the nearest telegraph office.

05:39:59.042 --> 05:40:03.542
Lucy chatted with me freely, and seemed quite unconscious that anything had happened.

05:40:04.022 --> 05:40:06.222
I tried to keep her amused and interested.

05:40:06.742 --> 05:40:11.442
When her mother came up to see her, she did not seem to notice any change whatever, but

05:40:11.442 --> 05:40:12.502
said to me gratefully,

05:40:12.782 --> 05:40:17.362
"'We owe you so much, Dr. Seward, for all you have done, but you really must now take

05:40:17.362 --> 05:40:19.062
care not to overwork yourself.

05:40:19.522 --> 05:40:21.322
You are looking pale yourself.

05:40:21.682 --> 05:40:25.602
You want a wife to nurse and look after you a bit, that you do.'

05:40:25.602 --> 05:40:30.842
As she spoke, Lucy turned crimson, though it was only momentarily, for her poor, wasted

05:40:30.842 --> 05:40:34.142
could not stand for long an unwanted drain to the head.

05:40:34.642 --> 05:40:38.782
The reaction came in excessive pallor as she turned imploring eyes on me.

05:40:39.382 --> 05:40:42.062
I smiled and nodded, and laid my finger on my lips.

05:40:42.302 --> 05:40:44.682
With a sigh she sank back amid her pillows.

05:40:45.962 --> 05:40:49.462
Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me,

05:40:49.682 --> 05:40:52.562
"'Now you go home, and eat much and drink enough.

05:40:52.902 --> 05:40:54.242
Make yourself strong.

05:40:54.542 --> 05:40:57.882
I stay here tonight, and I shall sit up with Little Miss myself.

05:40:58.612 --> 05:41:02.602
You and I must watch the case, and we must have none other to know.

05:41:02.922 --> 05:41:04.182
I have grave reasons.

05:41:04.682 --> 05:41:05.962
No, do not ask me.

05:41:06.262 --> 05:41:07.262
Think what you will.

05:41:07.582 --> 05:41:10.842
Do not fear to think even the most not improbable.

05:41:11.322 --> 05:41:12.442
Good night.'

05:41:13.062 --> 05:41:18.082
In the hall two of the maids came to me, and asked if they or either of them might not

05:41:18.082 --> 05:41:19.102
sit up with Miss Lucy.

05:41:19.702 --> 05:41:24.382
They implored me to let them, and when I said it was Dr. Van Helsing's wish that either

05:41:24.382 --> 05:41:30.222
he or I should sit up, they asked me quite piteously to intercede with the foreign gentleman.

05:41:30.842 --> 05:41:33.082
I was much touched by their kindness.

05:41:33.262 --> 05:41:38.222
Perhaps it is because I am weak at present, and perhaps because it was on Lucy's account

05:41:38.222 --> 05:41:40.102
that their devotion was manifested.

05:41:40.782 --> 05:41:45.402
For over and over again have I seen similar instances of woman's kindness.

05:41:45.862 --> 05:41:51.302
I got back here in time for a late dinner, went my rounds all well, and set this down

05:41:51.302 --> 05:41:52.402
whilst waiting for sleep.

05:41:52.402 --> 05:41:53.622
It is coming.

05:41:55.402 --> 05:41:56.482
11th of September.

05:41:56.902 --> 05:41:59.242
This afternoon I went over to Hillingham.

05:41:59.682 --> 05:42:03.382
Found Van Helsing in excellent spirits, and Lucy much better.

05:42:04.182 --> 05:42:08.782
Shortly after I had arrived, a big parcel from abroad came for the professor.

05:42:09.422 --> 05:42:14.302
He opened it with much impressment, assumed, of course, and showed a great bundle of white

05:42:14.302 --> 05:42:14.782
flowers.

05:42:15.602 --> 05:42:18.202
"'These are for you, Miss Lucy,' he said.

05:42:18.842 --> 05:42:19.882
"'For me?

05:42:20.122 --> 05:42:21.502
Oh, Dr. Van Helsing!

05:42:22.002 --> 05:42:24.482
Yes, my dear, but not for you to play with.

05:42:24.602 --> 05:42:26.302
These are medicines.'

05:42:26.302 --> 05:42:28.002
Here Lucy made a wry face.

05:42:28.542 --> 05:42:33.562
"'Nate, but they are not to take in a decoction or in nauseous form, so you need not snub

05:42:33.562 --> 05:42:38.542
that so charming nose, or I shall point out to my friend Arthur what woes he may have

05:42:38.542 --> 05:42:42.862
to endure in seeing so much beauty that he so loves so much distort.'

05:42:43.782 --> 05:42:47.902
"'Aha, my pretty miss, that brings the so nice nose all straight again.

05:42:47.902 --> 05:42:51.242
This is medicinal, but you do not know how.

05:42:51.522 --> 05:42:52.922
I put him in your window.

05:42:53.262 --> 05:42:56.962
I make pretty wreath and hang him round your neck so you sleep well.

05:42:57.722 --> 05:43:01.322
Oh, yes, they, like the lotus flower, make your trouble forgotten.

05:43:01.882 --> 05:43:07.042
It smells so like the waters of Lethe and of that fountain of use that the conquistador

05:43:07.042 --> 05:43:10.142
sought for in the Florida's and find him all too late.'

05:43:11.142 --> 05:43:15.402
Whilst he was speaking, Lucy had been examining the flowers and smelling them.

05:43:15.742 --> 05:43:19.182
Now she threw them down, saying, with half laughter and half disgust,

05:43:19.382 --> 05:43:23.342
"'Oh, Professor, I believe you are only putting up a joke on me.

05:43:23.442 --> 05:43:26.922
Why, these flowers are only common garlic.'

05:43:26.922 --> 05:43:33.342
To my surprise Van Helsing rose up and said with all his sternness, his iron-jaw set and

05:43:33.342 --> 05:43:34.882
his bushy eyebrows meeting,

05:43:35.362 --> 05:43:38.682
"'No trifling with me, I never jest.

05:43:39.162 --> 05:43:44.462
There is grim purpose in what I do, and I warn you that you do not thwart me.

05:43:44.982 --> 05:43:49.062
Take care for the sake of others, if not for your own.'

05:43:49.062 --> 05:43:53.542
Then seeing poor Lucy scared, as she might well be, he went on more gently,

05:43:54.282 --> 05:43:57.222
"'Oh, little miss, my dear, do not fear me.

05:43:57.342 --> 05:44:02.562
I only do for your good, but there is much virtue to you in those so common flowers.

05:44:03.422 --> 05:44:05.962
See I place them myself in your room.

05:44:06.362 --> 05:44:09.062
I make myself the wreath that you are to wear.

05:44:09.442 --> 05:44:13.802
But hush, no telling to others that make so inquisitive questions.

05:44:13.802 --> 05:44:20.762
We must obey, and silence is a part of obedience, and obedience is to bring your strong and

05:44:20.762 --> 05:44:23.062
well into loving arms that wait for you.

05:44:23.602 --> 05:44:25.042
Now sit still a while.

05:44:25.642 --> 05:44:30.262
Come with me, friend John, and you shall help me deck the room with my garlic, which is

05:44:30.262 --> 05:44:34.982
all the way from Haarlem, where my friend Van der Poel raise herb in his glass houses

05:44:34.982 --> 05:44:35.962
all the year.

05:44:36.202 --> 05:44:39.732
I had to telegraph yesterday, or they would not have been here.'

05:44:40.572 --> 05:44:43.652
We went into the room, taking the flowers with us.

05:44:44.092 --> 05:44:48.892
The professor's actions were certainly odd, and not to be found in any pharmacopoeia that

05:44:48.892 --> 05:44:49.972
I ever heard of.

05:44:50.692 --> 05:44:53.652
First he fastened up the windows and latched them securely.

05:44:54.172 --> 05:44:58.992
Next, taking a handful of the flowers, he rubbed them all over the sashes, as though

05:44:58.992 --> 05:45:03.692
to ensure that every whiff of air that might get in would be laden with a garlic smell.

05:45:04.312 --> 05:45:09.892
Then with a wisp he rubbed all over the jamb of the door, above, below, and at each side,

05:45:10.072 --> 05:45:12.052
and round the fireplace in the same way.

05:45:12.572 --> 05:45:14.312
It all seemed grotesque to me.

05:45:14.532 --> 05:45:15.792
And presently I said,

05:45:16.232 --> 05:45:20.592
"'Well, professor, I know you always have a reason for what you do, but this certainly

05:45:20.592 --> 05:45:21.512
puzzles me.

05:45:21.752 --> 05:45:26.532
It is well we have no skeptic here, or he would say that you were working some spell

05:45:26.532 --> 05:45:28.612
to keep out an evil spirit.'

05:45:29.212 --> 05:45:34.272
"'Perhaps I am,' he answered quietly, as he began to make the wreath which Lucy was

05:45:34.272 --> 05:45:35.412
to wear round her neck.

05:45:36.492 --> 05:45:40.892
We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he

05:45:40.892 --> 05:45:43.952
came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.

05:45:44.332 --> 05:45:46.172
The last words he said to her were,

05:45:46.452 --> 05:45:51.492
"'Take care you do not disturb it, and even if the room feel close, do not tonight open

05:45:51.492 --> 05:45:53.272
the window or the door.'

05:45:53.272 --> 05:45:54.912
"'I promise,' said Lucy,

05:45:55.272 --> 05:45:58.912
"'and thank you both a thousand times for all your kindness to me.

05:45:59.272 --> 05:46:02.612
Oh, what have I done to be blessed with such friends?'

05:46:02.612 --> 05:46:06.332
As we left the house in my fly, which was waiting, Van Helsing said,

05:46:06.632 --> 05:46:09.752
"'Tonight I can sleep in peace, and sleep I want.

05:46:09.952 --> 05:46:15.032
Two nights of travel, much reading in the day between, and much anxiety on the day to

05:46:15.032 --> 05:46:17.532
follow, and a night to sit up without to wink.

05:46:18.112 --> 05:46:23.052
"'Tomorrow in the morning early you call for me, and we come together to see a pretty

05:46:23.052 --> 05:46:26.892
miss, so much stronger from my spell which I have worked.

05:46:26.952 --> 05:46:28.072
Ho, ho!'

05:46:28.072 --> 05:46:33.032
He seemed so confident, that I, remembering my own confidence two nights before, and with

05:46:33.032 --> 05:46:36.012
the baneful result, felt awe and vague terror.

05:46:36.652 --> 05:46:40.772
It must have been my weakness that made me hesitate to tell it to my friend, but I felt

05:46:40.772 --> 05:46:43.412
it all the more like unshed tears."

05:47:06.112 --> 05:47:08.292
Dracula by Bram Stoker.

05:47:10.492 --> 05:47:14.592
Lucy Wisterna's Diary.

05:47:15.592 --> 05:47:16.552
12 September.

05:47:18.732 --> 05:47:20.872
How good they all are to me.

05:47:21.592 --> 05:47:23.872
I quite love that dear Dr. Van Helsing.

05:47:26.272 --> 05:47:28.692
I wonder why he was so anxious about these flowers.

05:47:29.612 --> 05:47:32.332
He positively frightened me he was so fierce.

05:47:33.372 --> 05:47:36.612
And yet he must have been right, for I feel comfort from them already.

05:47:38.092 --> 05:47:41.312
Somehow, I do not dread being alone tonight.

05:47:42.512 --> 05:47:44.292
And I can go to sleep without fear.

05:47:47.172 --> 05:47:49.812
I shall not mind any flapping outside the window.

05:47:51.212 --> 05:47:55.052
Oh, the terrible struggle that I have had against sleep so often of late.

05:47:55.452 --> 05:47:57.412
The pain of sleeplessness.

05:47:57.992 --> 05:48:00.072
Or the pain of the fear of sleep.

05:48:00.412 --> 05:48:03.492
And with such unknown horrors as it has for me.

05:48:04.472 --> 05:48:09.652
How blessed are some people whose lives have no fears, no dreads.

05:48:09.692 --> 05:48:13.032
To whom sleep is a blessing that comes on nightly.

05:48:13.592 --> 05:48:15.432
And brings nothing but sweet dreams.

05:48:16.632 --> 05:48:20.012
Well, here I am tonight, hoping for sleep.

05:48:21.072 --> 05:48:23.432
And lying like Ophelia in the play.

05:48:23.852 --> 05:48:26.852
With virgin crants and maiden struments.

05:48:28.792 --> 05:48:33.272
I never liked garlic before, but tonight it is delightful.

05:48:35.072 --> 05:48:36.512
There is peace in its smell.

05:48:38.072 --> 05:48:39.632
I feel sleep coming already.

05:48:40.652 --> 05:48:42.292
Good night, everybody.

05:48:46.532 --> 05:48:49.952
Dr. Seward's Diary, 13 September.

05:48:52.852 --> 05:48:55.312
Called at the Berkeley and found Van Helsing.

05:48:56.412 --> 05:48:58.572
As usual, up to time.

05:48:59.732 --> 05:49:01.792
The carriage ordered from the hotel was waiting.

05:49:02.512 --> 05:49:06.372
The professor took his bag, which he always brings with him now.

05:49:08.272 --> 05:49:10.292
Let all be put down exactly.

05:49:11.392 --> 05:49:15.132
Van Helsing and I arrived at Hillingham at eight o'clock.

05:49:15.692 --> 05:49:17.252
It was a lovely morning.

05:49:19.312 --> 05:49:22.192
The bright sunshine and all the fresh feeling of early autumn

05:49:22.192 --> 05:49:24.792
seemed like the completion of nature's annual work.

05:49:26.172 --> 05:49:28.952
The leaves were turning to all kinds of beautiful colours.

05:49:29.612 --> 05:49:32.672
But had not yet begun to drop from the trees.

05:49:34.752 --> 05:49:37.552
When we entered we met Mrs. Westerna.

05:49:38.112 --> 05:49:39.292
Coming out of the morning room.

05:49:40.792 --> 05:49:42.432
She is always an early riser.

05:49:43.712 --> 05:49:45.432
She greeted us warmly and said,

05:49:46.352 --> 05:49:48.392
You will be glad to know that Lucy is better.

05:49:48.732 --> 05:49:50.472
The dear child is still asleep.

05:49:50.472 --> 05:49:52.632
I looked into her room and saw her,

05:49:52.632 --> 05:49:55.272
but did not go in lest I should disturb her.

05:49:55.972 --> 05:49:58.192
The professor smiled and looked quite jubilant.

05:49:58.592 --> 05:50:00.432
He rubbed his hands together and said,

05:50:01.212 --> 05:50:04.312
Aha! I thought I had diagnosed the case.

05:50:04.712 --> 05:50:05.952
My treatment is working.

05:50:08.372 --> 05:50:09.732
To which she replied,

05:50:10.172 --> 05:50:13.272
You must not take all the credit to yourself, doctor.

05:50:14.672 --> 05:50:17.472
Lucy's state this morning is due in part to me.

05:50:18.492 --> 05:50:20.612
How do you mean, ma'am? asked the professor.

05:50:22.472 --> 05:50:25.172
Well, I was anxious about the dear child in the night

05:50:25.172 --> 05:50:26.412
and went into her room.

05:50:27.132 --> 05:50:28.912
She was sleeping soundly.

05:50:29.252 --> 05:50:31.912
So soundly that even my coming did not wake her.

05:50:32.212 --> 05:50:33.552
But the room was awfully stuffy.

05:50:34.512 --> 05:50:37.012
There were a lot of those horrible strong-smelling flowers

05:50:37.012 --> 05:50:38.992
about everywhere and she had actually

05:50:39.592 --> 05:50:41.312
a bunch of them round her neck.

05:50:41.992 --> 05:50:44.052
I feared that the heavy odour would be too much

05:50:44.052 --> 05:50:45.872
for the dear child in her weak state

05:50:45.872 --> 05:50:48.452
so I took them all away and opened a bit of the window

05:50:49.092 --> 05:50:51.272
to let in a little fresh air.

05:50:52.712 --> 05:50:54.852
You will be pleased with her, I am sure.

05:50:56.832 --> 05:50:58.712
She moved off into her boudoir

05:50:58.712 --> 05:51:00.692
where she usually breakfasted early.

05:51:02.052 --> 05:51:04.712
As she had spoken I watched the professor's face

05:51:04.712 --> 05:51:06.532
and saw it turn ash and grey.

05:51:08.332 --> 05:51:10.552
He had been able to retain his self-command

05:51:10.552 --> 05:51:12.412
whilst the poor lady was present

05:51:12.412 --> 05:51:15.092
for he knew her state and how mischievous

05:51:15.092 --> 05:51:16.612
a shock would be.

05:51:17.372 --> 05:51:19.112
He actually smiled on her

05:51:19.112 --> 05:51:21.912
as he held open the door for her to pass into her room.

05:51:22.892 --> 05:51:24.412
But the instant she disappeared

05:51:24.712 --> 05:51:26.932
he pulled me suddenly and forcibly

05:51:26.932 --> 05:51:30.272
into the dining room and closed the door.

05:51:33.752 --> 05:51:36.312
Then, for the first time in my life

05:51:36.312 --> 05:51:39.332
I saw Van Helsing break down.

05:51:40.692 --> 05:51:43.432
He raised his hands over his head

05:51:43.432 --> 05:51:45.532
in a sort of mute despair

05:51:45.532 --> 05:51:49.492
and then beat his palms together in a helpless way.

05:51:51.132 --> 05:51:53.092
Finally he sat down on a chair

05:51:53.092 --> 05:51:55.072
and putting his hands before his face

05:51:55.072 --> 05:51:57.572
began to sob with loud dry sobs

05:51:57.572 --> 05:52:00.312
that seemed to come from the very racking of his heart.

05:52:02.112 --> 05:52:03.912
Then he raised his arms again

05:52:03.912 --> 05:52:06.352
as though appealing to the whole universe.

05:52:06.852 --> 05:52:09.212
God, God, God, he said.

05:52:09.932 --> 05:52:11.012
What have we done?

05:52:11.072 --> 05:52:13.312
What has this poor thing done?

05:52:13.312 --> 05:52:16.652
That we are so sore beset.

05:52:17.232 --> 05:52:19.252
Is there fate amongst us still?

05:52:21.212 --> 05:52:23.592
Send down from the pagan world of old

05:52:23.592 --> 05:52:27.052
that such things must be in such a way.

05:52:27.672 --> 05:52:30.552
This poor mother, all unknowing

05:52:30.552 --> 05:52:33.212
and all for the best as she think

05:52:33.212 --> 05:52:36.912
does such thing as lose her daughter, body and soul.

05:52:37.352 --> 05:52:38.932
And we must not tell her.

05:52:38.952 --> 05:52:40.712
We must not even warn her

05:52:40.712 --> 05:52:43.052
before she die, then both die.

05:52:43.732 --> 05:52:45.792
Oh, how we are beset.

05:52:47.412 --> 05:52:50.532
How are all the powers of devils against us?

05:52:52.472 --> 05:52:54.072
Suddenly he jumped to his feet.

05:52:54.152 --> 05:52:55.432
Come, he said, come!

05:52:56.492 --> 05:52:57.872
We must see an act.

05:52:58.472 --> 05:53:00.092
Devils are no devils.

05:53:01.272 --> 05:53:03.392
Or all the devils at once, it matters not.

05:53:04.272 --> 05:53:06.052
We must fight him all the same.

05:53:07.572 --> 05:53:09.992
He went to the hall door for his bag

05:53:09.992 --> 05:53:12.332
and together we went up to Lucy's room.

05:53:14.072 --> 05:53:15.892
Once again I drew the blind

05:53:15.892 --> 05:53:19.572
whilst Van Helsing went towards the bed.

05:53:20.592 --> 05:53:23.292
This time he did not start as he looked on the poor face

05:53:23.292 --> 05:53:26.452
with the same awful waxen pallor as before.

05:53:27.492 --> 05:53:30.412
He wore a look of stern sadness and infinite pity.

05:53:31.572 --> 05:53:34.352
As I expected, he murmured

05:53:34.872 --> 05:53:38.532
with that hissing inspiration of his which meant so much.

05:53:39.492 --> 05:53:41.832
Without a word he went and locked the door

05:53:41.832 --> 05:53:44.412
and then began to set out on a little table

05:53:44.412 --> 05:53:46.472
the instruments for yet another operation

05:53:46.472 --> 05:53:47.832
of transfusion of blood.

05:53:49.332 --> 05:53:51.332
I had long ago recognized the necessity

05:53:51.332 --> 05:53:53.612
and begun to take off my coat

05:53:53.612 --> 05:53:55.712
but he stopped me with a warning hand.

05:53:56.012 --> 05:53:57.152
No, he said.

05:53:58.092 --> 05:53:59.852
Today you must operate.

05:54:00.352 --> 05:54:01.212
I shall provide.

05:54:02.032 --> 05:54:03.312
You were weakened already.

05:54:05.532 --> 05:54:07.252
As he spoke he took off his coat

05:54:07.252 --> 05:54:08.892
and rolled up his shirt sleeve.

05:54:10.712 --> 05:54:12.252
Again the operation.

05:54:12.972 --> 05:54:14.612
Again the narcotic.

05:54:15.632 --> 05:54:18.552
Again some return of colour to the ashy cheeks

05:54:18.552 --> 05:54:21.312
and the regular breathing of healthy sleep.

05:54:22.652 --> 05:54:24.672
This time I watched whilst

05:54:24.672 --> 05:54:28.292
Van Helsing recruited himself and rested.

05:54:30.252 --> 05:54:31.692
Presently he took an opportunity

05:54:31.692 --> 05:54:33.312
of telling Mrs. Westernra

05:54:34.212 --> 05:54:36.712
that she must not remove anything from Lucy's room

05:54:36.712 --> 05:54:38.212
without consulting him.

05:54:39.692 --> 05:54:42.152
That the flowers were of medicinal value

05:54:42.592 --> 05:54:44.312
and that the breathing of their order

05:54:44.312 --> 05:54:46.352
was part of the system of the cure.

05:54:47.972 --> 05:54:50.792
Then he took over the care of the case himself

05:54:50.792 --> 05:54:54.092
saying that he would watch this night and the next

05:54:54.092 --> 05:54:56.632
and would send me word when to come.

05:54:58.552 --> 05:55:01.492
After another hour Lucy waked from her sleep

05:55:01.492 --> 05:55:04.752
fresh and bright and seemingly not much the worse

05:55:04.752 --> 05:55:07.012
for her terrible ordeal.

05:55:10.772 --> 05:55:11.812
What does it all mean?

05:55:12.632 --> 05:55:15.632
I'm beginning to wonder if my long habit of life

05:55:15.632 --> 05:55:17.012
amongst the insane

05:55:17.872 --> 05:55:20.852
is beginning to tell upon my own brain.

05:55:24.772 --> 05:55:26.752
Lucy Westernra's Diary

05:55:27.712 --> 05:55:28.992
17 September

05:55:30.812 --> 05:55:32.932
Four days and nights of peace.

05:55:32.932 --> 05:55:37.392
I'm getting so strong again that I hardly know myself.

05:55:38.672 --> 05:55:42.392
It is as if I had passed through some long nightmare

05:55:42.392 --> 05:55:45.792
and had just awakened to see the beautiful sunshine

05:55:45.792 --> 05:55:49.032
and feel the fresh air of the morning around me.

05:55:51.292 --> 05:55:55.312
I have a dim half-remembrance of long anxious times

05:55:55.312 --> 05:55:57.012
of waiting and fearing.

05:55:57.732 --> 05:56:00.312
Darkness in which there was not even the pain of hope

05:56:00.312 --> 05:56:02.512
to make the present distress more poignant.

05:56:03.572 --> 05:56:05.912
And then long spells of oblivion

05:56:06.752 --> 05:56:09.632
and the rising back to life as a diver

05:56:09.632 --> 05:56:12.472
coming up through a great press of water.

05:56:14.792 --> 05:56:17.592
Since, however, Dr Van Helsing has been with me

05:56:17.592 --> 05:56:20.212
all this bad dreaming seems to have passed away.

05:56:21.252 --> 05:56:24.112
The noises that used to so frighten me

05:56:24.112 --> 05:56:26.712
out of my wits, the flapping against the windows,

05:56:26.712 --> 05:56:30.312
the distant voices which seemed so close to me,

05:56:30.992 --> 05:56:33.632
the harsh sounds that came from I know not where

05:56:33.632 --> 05:56:36.572
and commanded me to do I know not what

05:56:36.572 --> 05:56:37.892
have all ceased.

05:56:39.512 --> 05:56:41.872
I go to bed now without any fear of sleep.

05:56:42.752 --> 05:56:44.752
I do not even try to keep awake.

05:56:45.552 --> 05:56:47.852
I have grown quite fond of the garlic

05:56:47.852 --> 05:56:50.932
and a boxful arrives for me every day from Harlem.

05:56:53.152 --> 05:56:56.072
Tonight Van Helsing is going away.

05:56:57.312 --> 05:57:00.052
And he has to be for a day in Amsterdam.

05:57:01.992 --> 05:57:03.332
But I need not be watched.

05:57:03.572 --> 05:57:05.332
I am well enough to be left alone.

05:57:06.992 --> 05:57:10.212
Thank God for Mother's sake and dear Arthur's,

05:57:10.392 --> 05:57:12.592
for all our friends have been so kind.

05:57:13.452 --> 05:57:15.232
I shall not even feel the change,

05:57:15.332 --> 05:57:18.312
for last night Dr Van Helsing slept in his chair

05:57:18.312 --> 05:57:19.512
a lot of the time.

05:57:20.612 --> 05:57:23.272
I found him asleep twice when I awoke.

05:57:23.272 --> 05:57:26.332
But I did not fear to go to sleep again,

05:57:26.812 --> 05:57:28.712
although the boughs or bats or something

05:57:28.712 --> 05:57:32.272
flapped almost angrily against the window panes.

05:57:34.992 --> 05:57:37.352
The Pall Mall Gazette, 18 September.

05:57:38.492 --> 05:57:40.512
The escaped wolf, perilous adventure

05:57:40.512 --> 05:57:42.912
of our interviewer, interview with the keeper

05:57:42.912 --> 05:57:44.792
in the zoological gardens.

05:57:46.552 --> 05:57:49.772
After many inquiries and almost as many refusals

05:57:49.772 --> 05:57:52.692
and perpetually using the words Pall Mall Gazette

05:57:52.692 --> 05:57:55.672
as a sort of talisman, I managed to find

05:57:55.672 --> 05:57:58.052
the keeper of the section of the zoological gardens

05:57:58.052 --> 05:58:00.692
in which the wolf department is included.

05:58:01.812 --> 05:58:03.952
Thomas Builder lives in one of the cottages

05:58:03.952 --> 05:58:06.112
in the enclosure behind the elephant house

05:58:06.112 --> 05:58:08.932
and was just sitting down to his tea when I found him.

05:58:09.652 --> 05:58:11.772
Thomas and his wife are hospitable folk,

05:58:12.012 --> 05:58:14.152
elderly and without children.

05:58:14.612 --> 05:58:17.892
And if the specimen I enjoyed of their hospitality

05:58:17.892 --> 05:58:20.312
be of the average kind, their lives must be

05:58:20.312 --> 05:58:23.392
pretty comfortable. The keeper would not enter

05:58:23.392 --> 05:58:26.532
on what he called business until the supper was over

05:58:26.532 --> 05:58:28.112
and we were all satisfied.

05:58:29.712 --> 05:58:32.732
Then when the table was cleared and he had lit his pipe

05:58:32.732 --> 05:58:36.032
he said, Now sir, you can go on

05:58:36.032 --> 05:58:38.892
and ask me what you want. You'll excuse me

05:58:38.892 --> 05:58:42.172
for refusing to talk of professional subjects

05:58:42.172 --> 05:58:45.452
of four meals. I gives the wolves and the jackals

05:58:45.452 --> 05:58:47.752
and the hyenas in all our section their tea

05:58:47.752 --> 05:58:50.372
before I begins to ask them questions.

05:58:53.392 --> 05:58:54.752
How do you mean ask them questions?

05:58:54.972 --> 05:58:57.672
I queried, wishful to get him into a talkative humour.

05:59:00.272 --> 05:59:01.292
Itn of them over the head

05:59:01.292 --> 05:59:02.772
with a pole is one way,

05:59:03.452 --> 05:59:04.932
scratching of their ears is another,

05:59:05.452 --> 05:59:09.132
when Jens's flush wants a bit of shore for their gals.

05:59:10.192 --> 05:59:11.972
I don't so much mind the fuss.

05:59:11.972 --> 05:59:15.972
The itn of the pole part before I chucks in their dinner

05:59:15.972 --> 05:59:18.172
but I awaits till they've had

05:59:18.172 --> 05:59:21.232
their sherry and quaffy, so to speak,

05:59:21.652 --> 05:59:23.952
before I tries on with the ears scratching.

05:59:25.532 --> 05:59:27.992
Mind you, he added philosophically,

05:59:28.532 --> 05:59:30.612
there's a deal of the same nature in us

05:59:30.612 --> 05:59:31.972
as in them dear animals.

05:59:33.012 --> 05:59:36.192
Here's you a common and arskin of me questions about my business

05:59:36.192 --> 05:59:39.752
and I, the grump-like, that only for your

05:59:41.412 --> 05:59:44.452
I'd have seen you bloat fuss before I'd answer.

05:59:45.172 --> 05:59:47.952
Now even when you asked me me sarcastic-like,

05:59:48.572 --> 05:59:50.552
if I'd like you to ask the superintendent

05:59:50.552 --> 05:59:52.612
if you might ask me questions.

05:59:54.412 --> 05:59:56.392
Without offence, did I tell you to go to hell?

05:59:57.912 --> 05:59:58.912
You did.

05:59:59.672 --> 06:00:02.792
And when you said you'd report me for using obscene language

06:00:02.792 --> 06:00:04.532
that was itn me over the head.

06:00:05.772 --> 06:00:07.712
But the arf quid made that all right.

06:00:08.572 --> 06:00:10.212
I weren't going to fight

06:00:10.212 --> 06:00:12.292
so I waited for the food

06:00:12.292 --> 06:00:16.512
and did with my all as the wolves and lions and tigers does.

06:00:17.772 --> 06:00:19.612
But, Lord, love your art.

06:00:21.512 --> 06:00:23.672
Now that the old woman has stuck

06:00:23.672 --> 06:00:25.792
a chunk of her tea cake in me

06:00:25.792 --> 06:00:28.252
and rinsed me out with her bloomin' old teapot

06:00:28.252 --> 06:00:29.952
and I've lit a hop,

06:00:30.732 --> 06:00:33.012
you may scratch my ears for all your worth

06:00:33.012 --> 06:00:35.432
and won't even get a growl out of me.

06:00:35.872 --> 06:00:37.212
Drive along with your questions.

06:00:37.772 --> 06:00:39.392
I know what you're coming at.

06:00:39.932 --> 06:00:41.172
That ear escaped wolf.

06:00:43.332 --> 06:00:45.852
Exactly, I want you to give me your view of it.

06:00:46.512 --> 06:00:47.892
Just tell me how it happened

06:00:47.892 --> 06:00:50.872
and when I know the facts, I'll get you to say

06:00:50.872 --> 06:00:52.732
what you consider was the cause of it

06:00:52.732 --> 06:00:54.852
and how you think the whole affair will end.

06:00:56.452 --> 06:00:57.792
All right, Governor,

06:00:58.852 --> 06:01:00.872
this ear's about the old story.

06:01:01.992 --> 06:01:05.012
That ear wolf, what we call Bersiker,

06:01:05.892 --> 06:01:08.492
was one of three grey ones that come from Norway

06:01:09.532 --> 06:01:10.652
to Jamrocks,

06:01:11.472 --> 06:01:13.672
which we bought off him four years ago.

06:01:14.912 --> 06:01:16.972
He was a nice, well-behaved wolf

06:01:16.972 --> 06:01:19.732
that never gave no trouble to talk of.

06:01:20.852 --> 06:01:22.532
I'm more surprised at him

06:01:22.532 --> 06:01:23.972
for one to get out

06:01:23.972 --> 06:01:26.872
or any other animile in the place,

06:01:27.192 --> 06:01:29.972
but there you can't trust wolves no more

06:01:29.972 --> 06:01:31.212
nor women.

06:01:32.492 --> 06:01:33.972
Don't you mind him, sir,

06:01:34.112 --> 06:01:36.472
broke in Mrs. Tom with a cheery laugh.

06:01:37.212 --> 06:01:38.952
He's got mind in the animiles

06:01:39.572 --> 06:01:42.512
so long that blessed he ain't like an old wolf himself,

06:01:43.492 --> 06:01:45.532
but there ain't no harm in him.

06:01:48.552 --> 06:01:50.432
Well, sir, it was about

06:01:50.432 --> 06:01:52.212
two hours after feeding yesterday

06:01:52.212 --> 06:01:54.132
when I first ear my disturbance.

06:01:54.932 --> 06:01:57.192
I was making up a litter with the monkey-house

06:01:57.192 --> 06:01:59.192
for young Puma, which was ill,

06:01:59.812 --> 06:02:01.932
but when I heard the yelping and howling,

06:02:02.172 --> 06:02:03.812
I came way straight.

06:02:05.312 --> 06:02:08.612
There was Bersiker, a tearing like a mad thing

06:02:08.612 --> 06:02:11.132
at the bars if he wanted to get out.

06:02:11.932 --> 06:02:14.252
There wasn't much people about that day,

06:02:14.612 --> 06:02:16.872
and close at hand was only one man,

06:02:17.132 --> 06:02:19.452
a tall, thin chap with a nook nose

06:02:19.452 --> 06:02:22.532
and a pointed beard with a few white hairs

06:02:22.532 --> 06:02:23.772
running through it.

06:02:24.492 --> 06:02:27.412
He had a hard, cold look and red eyes,

06:02:28.172 --> 06:02:30.592
and I took a sort of mislike to him,

06:02:30.952 --> 06:02:32.912
for it seemed as if it was him

06:02:32.912 --> 06:02:34.712
that was irritating that.

06:02:34.712 --> 06:02:38.992
He had white kid gloves on, his hands,

06:02:39.552 --> 06:02:41.392
and he pointed out to the animiles,

06:02:42.052 --> 06:02:43.572
to me, and says, Keeper,

06:02:44.252 --> 06:02:46.152
these wolves seem upset at something.

06:02:47.652 --> 06:02:49.472
Maybe it's you, says I,

06:02:49.932 --> 06:02:52.172
for I did not like the hairs as he'd give himself.

06:02:52.972 --> 06:02:55.612
He didn't get angry, as I hoped he would,

06:02:55.892 --> 06:02:58.412
but he smiled a kind of insolent smile

06:02:58.412 --> 06:03:01.672
with a mouth full of white, sharp teeth.

06:03:02.612 --> 06:03:05.612
Oh, no, they wouldn't like me, says.

06:03:07.132 --> 06:03:09.372
Oh, yes, they would, says I,

06:03:09.512 --> 06:03:10.692
imitating of him.

06:03:11.352 --> 06:03:13.812
They always like a bone or two to clean their teeth

06:03:13.812 --> 06:03:15.592
on about tea-time,

06:03:16.732 --> 06:03:18.112
which you is a bagful.

06:03:19.712 --> 06:03:21.232
Well, it was an odd thing,

06:03:21.792 --> 06:03:25.132
but when the animiles sees us a-talking,

06:03:25.432 --> 06:03:26.552
they lay down.

06:03:27.232 --> 06:03:29.352
And when I went over to Bersicker,

06:03:30.072 --> 06:03:32.032
he let me stroke his ears same as ever.

06:03:32.892 --> 06:03:34.572
That there man came over and blessed,

06:03:34.792 --> 06:03:35.912
but if he didn't put his hand in,

06:03:35.972 --> 06:03:37.552
then stroke the old wolf's ears, too.

06:03:38.452 --> 06:03:41.872
I care, says I, Bersicker is quick.

06:03:43.752 --> 06:03:46.152
Never mind, he says, I'm used to him.

06:03:46.852 --> 06:03:49.192
Are you in the business yourself, I says,

06:03:49.512 --> 06:03:50.612
taking off my hat,

06:03:51.132 --> 06:03:53.272
for a man what trades in wolves

06:03:54.432 --> 06:03:56.732
and setterer is a good friend to keepers.

06:03:58.392 --> 06:03:59.672
Norm, says he,

06:04:00.092 --> 06:04:01.652
not exactly in the business,

06:04:02.252 --> 06:04:03.852
but I have made pets of several.

06:04:04.692 --> 06:04:06.352
And with that he lifts his hat,

06:04:06.852 --> 06:04:08.872
as polite as a lord, and walks away.

06:04:09.632 --> 06:04:11.372
Old Bersicker kept a-looking after him

06:04:11.372 --> 06:04:12.732
till he was out of sight,

06:04:12.732 --> 06:04:15.372
and then went and lay down in a corner,

06:04:15.712 --> 06:04:17.872
and wouldn't come out the whole evening.

06:04:18.852 --> 06:04:22.412
Well, last night, so soon as the moon was up,

06:04:22.892 --> 06:04:24.892
the wolves here began all a-howling.

06:04:25.872 --> 06:04:27.892
There warn't nothing for them to howl at.

06:04:29.432 --> 06:04:30.592
There warn't no one near,

06:04:30.772 --> 06:04:33.152
except someone that was evidently a-calling a dog

06:04:33.152 --> 06:04:36.352
somewheres out back of the gardenings in the park road.

06:04:37.132 --> 06:04:39.852
Once or twice I went out to see that all was all right,

06:04:39.852 --> 06:04:40.652
and it was.

06:04:41.212 --> 06:04:42.992
And then the owlin' stopped.

06:04:44.032 --> 06:04:46.852
Just before twelve o'clock I just took a look round

06:04:46.852 --> 06:04:48.692
before it turned in and bust me,

06:04:48.812 --> 06:04:51.532
but when I came opposite the old Bersicker's cage,

06:04:52.032 --> 06:04:55.292
I see the rails broken and twisted about the cage and empty.

06:04:56.292 --> 06:04:57.952
And that's all I know for certain.

06:04:59.932 --> 06:05:01.472
Did anyone else see anything?

06:05:03.512 --> 06:05:05.632
One of our gardeners was a-coming home

06:05:05.632 --> 06:05:07.632
about that time from Harmony,

06:05:09.092 --> 06:05:10.832
when he sees a big grey dog

06:05:10.832 --> 06:05:12.612
a-coming out through the gardening edges.

06:05:13.172 --> 06:05:16.952
At least so he says, I don't give much for it myself.

06:05:18.312 --> 06:05:21.072
For if he did, he never said a word about it

06:05:21.072 --> 06:05:23.292
to his missus when he got home.

06:05:24.632 --> 06:05:26.672
And it was only after the escape of the wolf

06:05:26.672 --> 06:05:29.712
that was made known, and we'd been up all night

06:05:29.712 --> 06:05:32.192
a-hunting of the park for Bersicker,

06:05:32.192 --> 06:05:34.832
that he remembered seeing anything.

06:05:36.632 --> 06:05:38.292
My own belief was that the Harmony

06:05:38.292 --> 06:05:39.432
got in his head.

06:05:41.952 --> 06:05:45.292
Now, Mr. Builder, can you account in any way

06:05:45.292 --> 06:05:46.932
for the escape of the wolf?

06:05:49.552 --> 06:05:50.422
Well, sir,

06:05:51.192 --> 06:05:53.442
he said with a suspicious sort of modesty,

06:05:55.352 --> 06:05:56.852
I think I can,

06:05:57.272 --> 06:05:59.532
but I don't know as how you'd be satisfied

06:05:59.532 --> 06:06:02.532
with the theory. Certainly I shall.

06:06:02.652 --> 06:06:05.712
If a man like you, who knows the animals

06:06:05.712 --> 06:06:08.112
from experience, can't hazard a good guess

06:06:08.112 --> 06:06:10.332
at any rate, who is even to try?

06:06:12.772 --> 06:06:14.272
Well then, sir,

06:06:15.272 --> 06:06:17.392
I accounts for it this way.

06:06:18.432 --> 06:06:20.832
It seems to me that

06:06:20.832 --> 06:06:22.452
that there wolf escaped

06:06:23.652 --> 06:06:26.592
simply because he wanted to get out.

06:06:26.592 --> 06:06:29.712
From the hearty way that both Thomas

06:06:29.712 --> 06:06:31.492
and his wife laughed at the joke,

06:06:31.592 --> 06:06:34.692
I could see that it had done some service before,

06:06:34.772 --> 06:06:37.432
and that the whole explanation was simply

06:06:37.432 --> 06:06:38.952
an elaborate sell.

06:06:40.272 --> 06:06:43.272
I couldn't cope in badnage with the worthy Thomas,

06:06:43.812 --> 06:06:46.472
but I thought I knew a sure way to his heart.

06:06:47.172 --> 06:06:50.372
So I said, now Mr. Builder will consider

06:06:50.372 --> 06:06:52.912
that first half-sovereign worked off,

06:06:52.912 --> 06:06:55.932
and this brother of his is waiting

06:06:55.932 --> 06:06:58.792
to be claimed when you've told me what you think will happen.

06:06:59.512 --> 06:07:02.272
Right you are, sir, he said briskly,

06:07:02.552 --> 06:07:04.672
you'll excuse me, I know,

06:07:04.932 --> 06:07:07.912
for a chaffin of ye, but the old woman here

06:07:07.912 --> 06:07:11.112
winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.

06:07:12.612 --> 06:07:13.812
Well, I never,

06:07:14.212 --> 06:07:15.232
said the old lady.

06:07:16.772 --> 06:07:19.392
My opinion is this, that there wolf

06:07:19.392 --> 06:07:21.032
was hiding of somewheres.

06:07:22.272 --> 06:07:25.312
The gardener, what, didn't remember, said he was a galloping

06:07:25.312 --> 06:07:28.632
northward faster than a horse could go, but I don't believe him.

06:07:28.892 --> 06:07:31.672
For ye see, sir, wolves don't gallop no more

06:07:31.672 --> 06:07:32.832
and no dogs does.

06:07:33.472 --> 06:07:35.092
They not being built that way.

06:07:36.232 --> 06:07:38.312
Wolves just find things in a storybook,

06:07:39.112 --> 06:07:42.332
and I dare say when they gets in packs and does be chivy

06:07:42.332 --> 06:07:45.392
and something that's more of feared than they is,

06:07:45.392 --> 06:07:49.892
they can make a devil of a noise and chop it up whatever it is.

06:07:50.172 --> 06:07:51.892
But, Lord bless ye,

06:07:52.252 --> 06:07:54.812
in real life a wolf is only a low creature,

06:07:55.192 --> 06:07:57.532
not half so clever or bold as a good dog,

06:07:58.112 --> 06:08:01.212
and not half a quarter so much fight in him.

06:08:02.432 --> 06:08:04.012
This one ain't been used to fighting,

06:08:04.732 --> 06:08:06.632
or even providing for his self.

06:08:07.972 --> 06:08:10.092
More like he's somewhere round the park of hiding

06:08:10.092 --> 06:08:13.432
and the shivering of, and if he thinks it all

06:08:13.432 --> 06:08:15.612
he's still wondering where he's to get his breakfast from.

06:08:17.112 --> 06:08:19.232
Or maybe he's got down some area

06:08:19.232 --> 06:08:21.312
and is in a coal cellar.

06:08:22.312 --> 06:08:25.412
My eye won't some cook get a rum start

06:08:25.412 --> 06:08:28.832
when she sees his green eyes shining at her out of the dark.

06:08:29.812 --> 06:08:32.272
If he can't get food he's bound to look for it,

06:08:32.492 --> 06:08:34.392
and may have he made chance to light

06:08:34.392 --> 06:08:36.092
on a butcher's shop in time.

06:08:36.592 --> 06:08:39.752
If he doesn't, then some nursemaid goes out a walkin'

06:08:39.752 --> 06:08:42.942
with a soldier leaving the infant in the purambulator.

06:08:44.772 --> 06:08:46.912
Well, then I shouldn't be surprised

06:08:46.912 --> 06:08:49.132
if the census is one baby the less.

06:08:50.152 --> 06:08:51.212
That's all.

06:08:52.652 --> 06:08:54.612
I was handing him the half-sovereign

06:08:54.612 --> 06:08:57.072
when something came bobbing up against the window,

06:08:57.612 --> 06:09:00.812
and Mr. Builder's face doubled its natural length with surprise.

06:09:01.172 --> 06:09:03.612
God bless me, he said,

06:09:04.152 --> 06:09:07.352
if there ain't old Bersicker come back by his self.

06:09:08.472 --> 06:09:10.852
He went to the door and opened it,

06:09:10.892 --> 06:09:13.832
a most unnecessary proceeding, it seemed to me.

06:09:14.972 --> 06:09:17.452
I have always thought a wild animal

06:09:17.452 --> 06:09:19.952
never looks so well as when some obstacle

06:09:19.952 --> 06:09:22.832
of profound durability is between us.

06:09:24.032 --> 06:09:26.312
A personal experience has intensified

06:09:26.312 --> 06:09:27.912
rather than diminish that idea.

06:09:29.312 --> 06:09:31.712
After all, however, there is nothing like custom,

06:09:32.092 --> 06:09:35.412
for neither Builder nor his wife thought any more

06:09:35.412 --> 06:09:37.152
of the wolf than I should of a dog.

06:09:38.172 --> 06:09:40.832
The animal itself was as peaceful and well-behaved

06:09:40.832 --> 06:09:43.432
as that father of all picture wolves,

06:09:43.612 --> 06:09:46.172
Red Riding Hood's quantum friend,

06:09:46.652 --> 06:09:49.072
whilst moving her confidence in masquerade.

06:09:50.952 --> 06:09:53.712
The whole scene was an unutterable mixture

06:09:53.712 --> 06:09:55.412
of comedy and pathos.

06:09:55.872 --> 06:09:58.332
The wicked wolf that for a half day

06:09:58.332 --> 06:10:01.572
had paralyzed London and set all the children in town

06:10:01.572 --> 06:10:03.132
with a shivering in their shoes

06:10:03.132 --> 06:10:05.872
was there in a sort of pentanent mood

06:10:05.872 --> 06:10:07.752
and was received and petted

06:10:07.752 --> 06:10:10.632
like a sort of vulpine prodigal son.

06:10:11.912 --> 06:10:13.672
Old Builder examined him all over

06:10:13.672 --> 06:10:15.512
with most tender solicitude,

06:10:16.112 --> 06:10:19.172
and when he had finished with his pentanent said,

06:10:20.792 --> 06:10:22.892
There, I knew the poor old chap

06:10:22.892 --> 06:10:24.892
would get back into some kind of trouble.

06:10:24.892 --> 06:10:26.872
Didn't I say it all along?

06:10:27.352 --> 06:10:30.192
Here's his head all cut and full of broken glass.

06:10:30.412 --> 06:10:32.972
He's been a-getting over some blooming wall or other.

06:10:34.112 --> 06:10:36.492
It's a shame that people are allowed

06:10:36.492 --> 06:10:38.572
to top their walls with broken bottles.

06:10:39.372 --> 06:10:41.012
This here's what comes of it.

06:10:43.652 --> 06:10:46.992
He took the wolf and locked him up in a cage

06:10:46.992 --> 06:10:49.352
with a piece of meat that satisfied,

06:10:49.492 --> 06:10:50.852
in quantity at any rate,

06:10:50.852 --> 06:10:53.892
the elementary conditions of the fatted calf

06:10:53.892 --> 06:10:55.572
and went off to report.

06:10:57.072 --> 06:11:00.232
I came off, too, to report the only exclusive information

06:11:00.232 --> 06:11:03.632
that is given today regarding the strange escapade at the zoo.

06:11:11.132 --> 06:11:14.632
I was engaged after dinner in my study,

06:11:15.172 --> 06:11:16.812
posting up my books which,

06:11:16.812 --> 06:11:18.892
through press of other works,

06:11:20.032 --> 06:11:21.312
and the many visits to Lucy

06:11:21.312 --> 06:11:24.072
had fallen sadly into a rear.

06:11:25.572 --> 06:11:27.332
Suddenly the door was burst open,

06:11:27.732 --> 06:11:29.032
and in rushed my patient,

06:11:29.392 --> 06:11:31.312
with his face distorted with passion.

06:11:32.872 --> 06:11:34.732
I was thunderstruck for such a thing

06:11:34.732 --> 06:11:36.532
as a patient getting of his own accord

06:11:36.532 --> 06:11:40.312
into the superintendent's study is almost unknown.

06:11:42.072 --> 06:11:45.092
Without an instant's notice he made straight at me.

06:11:45.732 --> 06:11:47.512
He had a dinner knife in his hand,

06:11:47.632 --> 06:11:49.512
and as I saw he was dangerous

06:11:49.512 --> 06:11:51.752
I tried to keep the table between us.

06:11:52.892 --> 06:11:55.892
He was too quick and too strong for me, however,

06:11:56.512 --> 06:11:58.172
for before I could get my balance

06:11:58.172 --> 06:12:01.272
he had struck at me and cut my left wrist rather severely.

06:12:02.852 --> 06:12:04.892
Before he could strike again, however,

06:12:05.052 --> 06:12:06.492
I got in my right hand,

06:12:06.492 --> 06:12:09.092
and he was sprawling on his back on the floor.

06:12:10.412 --> 06:12:11.992
My wrist bled freely,

06:12:12.532 --> 06:12:14.832
and quite a little pool trickled onto the carpet.

06:12:16.312 --> 06:12:19.172
I saw that my friend was not intent on further effort,

06:12:19.452 --> 06:12:21.992
and occupied myself binding up my wrist,

06:12:22.572 --> 06:12:25.912
keeping a wary eye on the prostrate figure all the time.

06:12:26.812 --> 06:12:28.492
When the attendants rushed in,

06:12:28.592 --> 06:12:30.292
and we turned our attention to him,

06:12:31.112 --> 06:12:33.552
his employment positively sickened me.

06:12:33.552 --> 06:12:36.132
He was lying on his belly on the floor,

06:12:36.432 --> 06:12:37.932
licking up, like a dog,

06:12:38.192 --> 06:12:40.732
the blood which had fallen from my wounded wrist.

06:12:42.572 --> 06:12:44.192
He was easily secured,

06:12:44.732 --> 06:12:48.452
and to my surprise went with the attendants quite placidly,

06:12:48.612 --> 06:12:50.632
simply repeating over and over again,

06:12:51.512 --> 06:12:55.312
the blood is the life, the blood is the life.

06:12:57.532 --> 06:13:00.312
I cannot afford to lose blood just at present.

06:13:00.312 --> 06:13:03.292
I have lost too much of late for my physical good,

06:13:03.372 --> 06:13:06.812
and then the prolonged strain of Lucy's illness

06:13:06.812 --> 06:13:09.132
and its horrible phases is telling on me.

06:13:10.232 --> 06:13:12.132
I am overexcited and weary,

06:13:12.532 --> 06:13:15.872
and I need rest, rest, rest.

06:13:18.032 --> 06:13:21.052
Happily, Van Helsing has not summoned me,

06:13:21.052 --> 06:13:22.652
so I need not forgo my sleep.

06:13:23.652 --> 06:13:26.432
Tonight, I could not well do without it.

06:13:28.072 --> 06:13:32.652
Telegram, Van Helsing, Antwerp to Seward, Carfax.

06:13:33.072 --> 06:13:34.772
Sent to Carfax, Sussex,

06:13:35.012 --> 06:13:38.552
as no county given, delivered late by twenty-two hours.

06:13:39.712 --> 06:13:41.252
Seventeen September, stop.

06:13:42.432 --> 06:13:44.852
Do not fail to be at Hillingham tonight, stop.

06:13:45.852 --> 06:13:48.472
If not watching all the time, frequently visit,

06:13:48.752 --> 06:13:50.992
and see that flowers are as placed.

06:13:51.312 --> 06:13:53.632
Very important, do not fail, stop.

06:13:54.312 --> 06:13:58.052
Shall be with you as soon as possible after arrival, stop.

06:13:59.992 --> 06:14:02.732
Dr. Seward's Diary, 18 September.

06:14:03.672 --> 06:14:04.912
Just off train to London.

06:14:05.552 --> 06:14:08.792
The arrival of Van Helsing's Telegram filled me with dismay.

06:14:09.272 --> 06:14:12.312
A whole night lost, and I know by bitter experience

06:14:12.312 --> 06:14:13.972
what may happen in a night.

06:14:15.292 --> 06:14:17.832
Of course it is possible that all may be well,

06:14:18.112 --> 06:14:19.332
but what may have happened?

06:14:19.332 --> 06:14:22.912
Surely there is some horrible doom hanging over us

06:14:22.912 --> 06:14:25.752
that every possible accident should thwart us

06:14:25.752 --> 06:14:27.192
in all we try to do.

06:14:28.572 --> 06:14:30.332
I shall take the cylinder with me,

06:14:30.392 --> 06:14:33.612
and then I can complete my entry on Lucy's phonograph.

06:14:35.632 --> 06:14:37.572
Memorandum left by Lucy Wisterner.

06:14:38.812 --> 06:14:40.372
Seventeen September, night.

06:14:40.992 --> 06:14:43.372
I write this and leave it to be seen,

06:14:43.612 --> 06:14:47.152
so that no one may by any chance get into trouble through me.

06:14:47.772 --> 06:14:50.792
This is an exact record of what took place tonight.

06:14:51.552 --> 06:14:53.272
I feel I am dying of weakness

06:14:53.272 --> 06:14:55.772
and of barely enough strength to write,

06:14:56.472 --> 06:14:58.892
but it must be done if I die in the doing.

06:15:00.492 --> 06:15:02.012
I went to bed as usual,

06:15:02.472 --> 06:15:04.312
taking care that the flowers were placed

06:15:04.312 --> 06:15:08.032
as Dr. Van Helsing directed, and soon fell asleep.

06:15:09.252 --> 06:15:11.532
I was waked by the flapping at the window,

06:15:11.692 --> 06:15:13.672
which had begun after that sleepwalking

06:15:13.672 --> 06:15:16.672
off the cliff at Whitby when Mina saved me,

06:15:17.432 --> 06:15:19.112
and which now I know so well.

06:15:19.932 --> 06:15:21.212
I was not afraid,

06:15:21.392 --> 06:15:24.472
but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room,

06:15:24.832 --> 06:15:27.532
as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be,

06:15:27.852 --> 06:15:29.432
so that I might have called him.

06:15:29.712 --> 06:15:31.812
I tried to sleep, but I could not.

06:15:32.512 --> 06:15:34.992
Then there came to me the old fear of sleep,

06:15:35.112 --> 06:15:37.372
and I determined to keep awake.

06:15:39.252 --> 06:15:41.152
Perversely, sleep would try to come then

06:15:41.152 --> 06:15:42.752
when I did not want it.

06:15:43.632 --> 06:15:46.152
So, as I feared to be alone, I opened my door

06:15:46.152 --> 06:15:48.812
and called out, Is there anybody there?

06:15:49.732 --> 06:15:51.032
There was no answer.

06:15:51.912 --> 06:15:54.952
I was afraid to wake Mother, and so closed my door again.

06:15:55.792 --> 06:15:58.472
Then outside in the shrubbery I heard a sort of howl

06:15:58.472 --> 06:16:01.292
like a dog's, but more fierce and deeper.

06:16:03.012 --> 06:16:05.112
I went to the window and looked out,

06:16:05.112 --> 06:16:07.812
but could see nothing, except a big bat,

06:16:08.832 --> 06:16:10.992
which had evidently been buffering its wings

06:16:10.992 --> 06:16:11.912
against the window.

06:16:14.292 --> 06:16:17.112
So I went back to bed again, but determined

06:16:17.112 --> 06:16:18.232
not to go to sleep.

06:16:19.532 --> 06:16:22.172
Presently the door opened and my Mother looked in.

06:16:23.512 --> 06:16:25.752
Seeing by my moving that I was not asleep,

06:16:25.792 --> 06:16:27.712
she came in and sat by me.

06:16:28.172 --> 06:16:31.492
She said to me, even more sweetly and softly than her want,

06:16:33.212 --> 06:16:35.092
I was uneasy about you, darling,

06:16:35.092 --> 06:16:37.512
and came in to see that you were all right.

06:16:40.032 --> 06:16:42.572
I feared she might catch cold sitting there

06:16:42.572 --> 06:16:44.952
and asked her to come in and sleep with me,

06:16:45.372 --> 06:16:48.472
so she came into bed and lay down beside me.

06:16:49.272 --> 06:16:51.112
She did not take off her dressing gown,

06:16:51.152 --> 06:16:52.912
for she said she would only stay a while

06:16:52.912 --> 06:16:54.492
and then go back to her own bed.

06:16:55.872 --> 06:16:58.552
As she lay there in my arms, and I in hers,

06:16:58.552 --> 06:17:01.392
the flapping and buffeting came to the window again.

06:17:02.212 --> 06:17:04.052
She was startled and a little frightened

06:17:04.052 --> 06:17:06.332
and cried out, what is that?

06:17:08.012 --> 06:17:10.752
I tried to pacify her and at last succeeded

06:17:10.752 --> 06:17:13.612
and she lay quiet, but I could hear

06:17:13.612 --> 06:17:15.832
her poor heart still beating terribly.

06:17:17.172 --> 06:17:20.172
After a while there was a howl again out in the shrubbery,

06:17:21.132 --> 06:17:23.652
and shortly after there was a crash at the window,

06:17:24.132 --> 06:17:26.752
and a lot of broken glass was hurled on the floor.

06:17:27.332 --> 06:17:30.412
The window blind blew back with the wind

06:17:30.412 --> 06:17:33.892
that rushed in, and in the aperture of the broken panes

06:17:33.892 --> 06:17:36.872
there was the head of a great, gaunt gray wolf.

06:17:38.932 --> 06:17:40.512
Mother cried out in a fright

06:17:40.512 --> 06:17:42.812
and struggled up into a sitting posture

06:17:42.812 --> 06:17:46.552
and clutched wildly at anything that would help her.

06:17:47.032 --> 06:17:49.552
Amongst other things she clutched the wreath of flowers

06:17:49.552 --> 06:17:51.832
that Dr. Van Helsing insisted on my wearing

06:17:51.832 --> 06:17:55.072
around my neck and tore it away from me.

06:17:56.232 --> 06:17:59.092
For a second or two she sat up pointing at the wolf

06:17:59.092 --> 06:18:02.052
and there was a strange and horrible gurgling in her throat.

06:18:03.232 --> 06:18:05.512
Then she fell over as if struck with lightning

06:18:05.512 --> 06:18:07.772
and her head hit my forehead and made me dizzy

06:18:07.772 --> 06:18:09.072
for a moment or two.

06:18:10.812 --> 06:18:13.832
The room and all around seemed to spin

06:18:14.852 --> 06:18:15.332
around.

06:18:16.212 --> 06:18:19.772
I kept my eyes fixed on the window, but the wolf drew his head back

06:18:19.772 --> 06:18:22.632
and a whole myriad of little specks seems to come

06:18:22.632 --> 06:18:25.512
blowing in through the broken window and wheeling

06:18:25.512 --> 06:18:28.392
and circling round like the pillar of dust that the travelers

06:18:28.392 --> 06:18:31.652
describe when there is a simoon in the desert.

06:18:32.972 --> 06:18:35.532
I tried to stir, but there was some spell upon me

06:18:35.532 --> 06:18:38.692
and dear mother's poor body, which seemed to grow cold

06:18:38.692 --> 06:18:42.152
already, for her dear heart had ceased to beat,

06:18:42.592 --> 06:18:43.652
weighed me down,

06:18:44.292 --> 06:18:46.692
and I remembered no more for a while.

06:18:51.552 --> 06:18:54.252
The time did not seem long,

06:18:54.292 --> 06:18:56.452
but very, very awful,

06:18:57.332 --> 06:18:59.972
till I recovered consciousness again.

06:19:01.132 --> 06:19:03.612
Somewhere near a passing bell was tolling.

06:19:04.932 --> 06:19:07.712
The dogs all around the neighborhood were howling

06:19:07.712 --> 06:19:10.392
and in our shrubbery seeming just outside

06:19:10.392 --> 06:19:12.492
a nightingale was singing.

06:19:13.552 --> 06:19:16.552
I was dazed and stupid with pain and terror

06:19:16.552 --> 06:19:16.672
and I could not speak.

06:19:16.672 --> 06:19:17.292
I could not find weakness,

06:19:18.532 --> 06:19:21.112
but the sound of the nightingale seemed like the voice

06:19:21.112 --> 06:19:24.212
of my dead mother come back to comfort me.

06:19:26.052 --> 06:19:28.912
The sound seemed to have awakened the maids too,

06:19:29.112 --> 06:19:32.012
for I could hear their bare feet pattering outside my door.

06:19:32.952 --> 06:19:34.892
I called to them and they came in,

06:19:34.992 --> 06:19:37.172
and when they saw what had happened and what it was

06:19:37.172 --> 06:19:39.272
that lay over me in the bed, they screamed.

06:19:40.272 --> 06:19:42.472
The wind rushed in through the broken window

06:19:42.472 --> 06:19:44.032
and the door slammed too.

06:19:44.652 --> 06:19:47.012
They lifted off the body of my dear mother

06:19:47.012 --> 06:19:49.792
and laid her, covered up with a sheet

06:19:50.812 --> 06:19:52.932
on the bed after I had got up.

06:19:53.892 --> 06:19:55.852
They were all so frightened and nervous

06:19:55.852 --> 06:19:57.792
that I directed them to go to the dining room

06:19:57.792 --> 06:19:59.192
and each have a glass of wine.

06:19:59.892 --> 06:20:02.772
The door flew open for an instant and closed again.

06:20:03.532 --> 06:20:06.232
The maids shrieked and then went in a body

06:20:06.232 --> 06:20:08.972
to the dining room and I laid what flowers I had

06:20:08.972 --> 06:20:10.712
on my dear mother's breast.

06:20:12.232 --> 06:20:15.012
When they were there, I remembered what Dr. Van Helsing

06:20:15.012 --> 06:20:17.972
had told me, but I didn't like to remove them.

06:20:18.992 --> 06:20:22.032
And besides, I would have some of the servants

06:20:22.032 --> 06:20:23.532
to sit up with me now.

06:20:24.992 --> 06:20:27.432
I was surprised that the maids did not come back.

06:20:27.472 --> 06:20:30.152
I called them, but got no answer.

06:20:31.632 --> 06:20:33.772
So I went to the dining room to look for them.

06:20:35.512 --> 06:20:38.012
My heart sank when I saw what happened.

06:20:38.992 --> 06:20:41.332
They all four lay helpless on the floor,

06:20:41.712 --> 06:20:42.432
breathing heavily.

06:20:43.092 --> 06:20:46.032
The decanter of Sherry was on the table half full,

06:20:46.352 --> 06:20:48.452
but there was a queer, acrid smell about.

06:20:49.332 --> 06:20:51.692
I was suspicious and examined the decanter.

06:20:53.012 --> 06:20:54.372
It smelt of laudanum.

06:20:55.072 --> 06:20:57.572
And looking on the sideboard, I found that the bottle,

06:20:58.052 --> 06:20:59.912
which mother's doctor uses for her,

06:20:59.912 --> 06:21:02.452
oh, did use, was empty.

06:21:03.172 --> 06:21:05.832
What am I to do? What am I to do?

06:21:06.112 --> 06:21:08.712
I am back in the room with mother. I cannot leave her.

06:21:08.852 --> 06:21:11.332
I am alone, save for the sleeping servants

06:21:11.332 --> 06:21:14.712
whom someone has drugged, alone with the dead.

06:21:15.732 --> 06:21:18.972
I dare not go out, for I can hear the low howl

06:21:18.972 --> 06:21:21.652
of the wolf through the broken window.

06:21:23.072 --> 06:21:25.692
The air seems full of specks

06:21:25.692 --> 06:21:28.452
floating and circling in the draft from the window.

06:21:28.452 --> 06:21:31.252
And the lights burn blue and dim.

06:21:32.492 --> 06:21:33.872
What am I to do?

06:21:36.212 --> 06:21:38.772
God shield me from harm this night.

06:21:41.272 --> 06:21:43.372
I shall hide this paper in my breast,

06:21:43.772 --> 06:21:45.972
where they shall find it when they come to lay me out.

06:21:46.292 --> 06:21:49.612
My dear mother gone, it is time I go too.

06:21:51.332 --> 06:21:52.412
Goodbye, dear Arthur,

06:21:53.732 --> 06:21:55.732
if I should not survive this night.

06:21:56.732 --> 06:21:58.512
God keep you dear,

06:21:59.912 --> 06:22:02.032
and God help me.

06:22:31.308 --> 06:22:35.448
XII Dr. Seward's Diary

06:22:38.728 --> 06:22:46.988
18 September. I drove at once to Hillingham and arrived early. Keeping my cab at the gate,

06:22:47.508 --> 06:22:53.268
I went up the avenue alone. I knocked gently and rang as quietly as possible,

06:22:53.728 --> 06:22:59.468
for I feared to disturb Lucy or her mother, and hoped to only bring a servant to the door.

06:23:01.368 --> 06:23:07.468
After a while, finding no response, I knocked and rang again, still no answer.

06:23:09.328 --> 06:23:13.908
I cursed the laziness of the servants that they should lie a bed at such an hour,

06:23:14.108 --> 06:23:19.308
for it was now ten o'clock, and so rang and knocked again, but more impatiently,

06:23:20.508 --> 06:23:25.908
but still without response. Hitherto I had blamed only the servants,

06:23:25.908 --> 06:23:34.128
but now a terrible fear began to assail me. Was this desolation but another link in the

06:23:34.128 --> 06:23:42.728
chain of doom which seemed drawing tight around us? Was it indeed a house of death to which I had

06:23:42.728 --> 06:23:50.288
come too late? I know that minutes, even seconds of delay, might mean hours of danger to Lucy,

06:23:50.288 --> 06:23:58.028
if she had had again one of those frightful relapses, and I went round the house to try

06:23:58.028 --> 06:24:04.868
if I could find by chance an entry anywhere. I could find no means of ingress. Every window

06:24:04.868 --> 06:24:10.688
and door was fastened and locked, and I returned baffled to the porch. As I did so,

06:24:10.708 --> 06:24:17.068
I heard the rapid pit pat of a swiftly driven horse's feet. They stopped at the gate,

06:24:17.068 --> 06:24:23.228
and a few seconds later I met Van Helsing running up the avenue. When he saw me,

06:24:23.328 --> 06:24:30.608
he gasped out. Then it was you, and just arrived. How is she? Are we too late? Did you not get my

06:24:30.608 --> 06:24:37.028
telegram? I answered as quickly and coherently as I could that I had only got his telegram early

06:24:37.028 --> 06:24:42.828
in the morning, and had not a minute in coming here, and that I could not make anyone in the

06:24:42.828 --> 06:24:49.248
house hear me. He paused and raised his hat as he said solemnly, then I fear we are too late.

06:24:50.088 --> 06:24:55.888
God's will be done. With his usual recuperative energy, he went on,

06:24:55.908 --> 06:25:03.308
Come, if there be no way open to get in, we must make one. Time is all in all to us now.

06:25:04.928 --> 06:25:10.308
We went round to the back of the house, where there was a kitchen window. The professor took

06:25:10.308 --> 06:25:15.608
a small surgical saw from his case, and handing it to me, pointed to the iron bars which guarded

06:25:15.608 --> 06:25:22.448
the window. I attacked them at once, and had very soon cut through three of them. Then,

06:25:22.448 --> 06:25:27.128
with a long thin knife, we pushed back the fastening of the sashes, and opened the window.

06:25:28.568 --> 06:25:34.488
I helped the professor in, and followed him. There was no one in the kitchen or in the servants' rooms,

06:25:34.588 --> 06:25:39.708
which were close at hand. We tried all the rooms as we went along, and in the dining room,

06:25:39.708 --> 06:25:44.888
dimly lit by rays of light through the shutters, found four servant women lying on the floor.

06:25:46.808 --> 06:25:53.908
There was no need to think them dead, for their stertuous breathing and the acrid smell of laudanum

06:25:53.908 --> 06:26:01.648
in the room left no doubt as to their condition. Van Helsing and I looked at each other, and as we

06:26:01.648 --> 06:26:08.848
moved away, he said, we can attend to them later. Then we ascended to Lucy's room. For an instant or

06:26:08.848 --> 06:26:14.828
two, we paused at the door to listen, but there was no sound that we could hear. With white faces

06:26:14.828 --> 06:26:23.388
and trembling hands, we opened the door gently, and entered the room. How shall I describe what

06:26:23.388 --> 06:26:31.828
we saw? On the bed lay two women, Lucy and her mother. The latter lay farthest in, and she was

06:26:31.828 --> 06:26:37.948
covered with a white sheet, the edge of which had been blown back by the draught through the broken

06:26:37.948 --> 06:26:45.508
window, showing the drawn white face with a look of terror fixed upon it. By her side lay Lucy with

06:26:45.508 --> 06:26:51.468
a face white and still more drawn. The flowers which had been round her neck we found upon her

06:26:51.468 --> 06:26:57.328
mother's bosom, and her throat was bare, showing the two little wounds which we had noticed before,

06:26:58.088 --> 06:27:04.888
but looking horribly white and mangled. Without a word, the professor bent over the bed, his head

06:27:04.888 --> 06:27:11.068
almost touching poor Lucy's breast. Then he gave a quick turn of his head, as of one who listens,

06:27:11.628 --> 06:27:17.828
and leaping to his feet, he cried out to me, it's not yet too late. Quick, quick, bring the brandy.

06:27:18.928 --> 06:27:25.628
I flew downstairs and returned with it, taking care to smell and taste it lest it too were drugged,

06:27:25.628 --> 06:27:30.968
like the decanter of Sherry which I had found on the table. The maids were still breathing,

06:27:30.968 --> 06:27:36.468
but more restlessly, and I fancied that the narcotic was wearing off. I did not stay to make

06:27:36.468 --> 06:27:43.548
sure, but returned to Van Helsing. He rubbed the brandy, as on another occasion, on her lips and

06:27:43.548 --> 06:27:51.428
gums, and on her wrists and the palms of her hands. He said to me, I can do this, all that can be at

06:27:51.428 --> 06:27:57.308
the present. You go wake those maids, flick them in the face with a wet towel, and flick them hard,

06:27:57.308 --> 06:28:06.608
make them get heat and fire and a warm bath. This poor soul is nearly as cold as that cider. She will

06:28:06.608 --> 06:28:12.168
need be heated before we can do anything more. I went at once and found little difficulty in

06:28:12.168 --> 06:28:18.088
waking three of the women. The fourth was only a young girl, and the drug had evidently affected

06:28:18.088 --> 06:28:24.368
her more strongly, so I lifted her on the sofa and let her sleep. The others were dazed at first,

06:28:24.368 --> 06:28:29.408
but as remembrance came back to them, they cried and sobbed in a hysterical manner.

06:28:31.088 --> 06:28:36.708
I was stern with them, however, and would not let them talk. I told them that one life was bad enough

06:28:36.708 --> 06:28:43.928
to lose, and if they delayed, they would sacrifice Miss Lucy. So, sobbing and crying, they went about

06:28:43.928 --> 06:28:51.728
their way, half-clad as they were, and prepared fire and water. Fortunately, the kitchen and boiler

06:28:51.728 --> 06:28:59.028
were still alive, and there was no lack of hot water. We got a bath and carried Lucy out, as she

06:28:59.028 --> 06:29:04.788
was, and placed her in it. Whilst we were busy chafing her limbs, there was a knock at the hall

06:29:04.788 --> 06:29:12.728
door. One of the maids ran off, hurried, on some more clothes, and opened it. Then she returned and

06:29:12.728 --> 06:29:16.768
whispered to us that there was a gentleman who had come with a message from Mr. Holmwood.

06:29:18.708 --> 06:29:23.168
I bade her simply tell him that he must wait, for we could see no one now.

06:29:24.028 --> 06:29:28.868
She went away with a message, and engrossed with her work, I clean forgot all about him.

06:29:29.988 --> 06:29:36.208
I never saw in all my experience the professor work in such deadly earnest. I knew, as he knew,

06:29:36.688 --> 06:29:43.288
that it was a stand-up fight with death, and in a pause told him so. He answered me in a way that

06:29:43.288 --> 06:29:50.448
I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear. If that were all,

06:29:50.548 --> 06:29:58.528
I would stop here, where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life

06:29:58.528 --> 06:30:07.468
over her horizon. He went on with his work with, if possible, renewed and more frenzied vigor.

06:30:09.768 --> 06:30:14.628
Presently, we both began to be conscious that the heat was beginning to be of some effect.

06:30:16.008 --> 06:30:20.908
Lucy's heart beat a trifle more audibly to the stethoscope, and her lungs had a perceptible

06:30:20.908 --> 06:30:27.028
movement. Van Helsing's face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a

06:30:27.028 --> 06:30:35.908
hot sheet dryer, he said to me, the first gain is ours. Check to the king. We took Lucy into

06:30:35.908 --> 06:30:40.748
another room, which had by now been prepared, and laid her in bed and forced a few drops of

06:30:40.748 --> 06:30:47.608
brandy down her throat. I noticed that Van Helsing tied a soft, silk handkerchief round her throat.

06:30:48.508 --> 06:30:53.648
She was still unconscious, and was quite as bad as, if not worse than, we had ever seen her.

06:30:55.248 --> 06:30:59.428
Van Helsing called in one of the women and told her to stay with her and not take her eyes off

06:30:59.428 --> 06:31:05.888
her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room. We must consult as to what is to be done.

06:31:05.908 --> 06:31:13.028
He said as we descended the stairs. In the hall he opened the dining room door. As we passed in,

06:31:14.088 --> 06:31:19.968
he closing the door carefully behind him. The shutters had been opened, but the blinds were

06:31:19.968 --> 06:31:24.908
already down, with that obedience to the etiquette of death, which the British woman of the lower

06:31:24.908 --> 06:31:32.548
classes always rigidly observes. The room was, therefore, dimly dark. It was, however, light

06:31:32.548 --> 06:31:39.528
enough for our purposes. Van Helsing's sternness was somewhat relieved by a look of perplexity.

06:31:40.428 --> 06:31:45.808
He was evidently torturing his mind about something, so I waited for an instant, and he spoke.

06:31:47.408 --> 06:31:53.088
What are we to do now? Where are we to turn for help? We must have another transfusion of blood,

06:31:53.348 --> 06:31:57.748
and that's soon, or that poor girl's life won't be worth an hour's purchase.

06:31:57.748 --> 06:32:04.928
You are exhausted already. I am exhausted, too. I fear to trust those women, even if they would

06:32:04.928 --> 06:32:10.768
have courage to submit. What are we to do for someone who will open his veins for her?

06:32:11.788 --> 06:32:17.028
What's the matter with me, anyhow? The voice came from the sofa across the room, and its tones

06:32:17.028 --> 06:32:22.028
brought relief and joy to my heart, for they were those of Quincy Morris.

06:32:23.448 --> 06:32:28.668
Van Helsing started angrily at the first stound, but his face softened, and a glad look came into

06:32:28.668 --> 06:32:33.948
his eyes as I cried out, Quincy Morris, and rushed towards him with outstretched hands.

06:32:35.028 --> 06:32:40.128
What brought you here? I cried as our hands met. I guess art is the cause.

06:32:41.628 --> 06:32:48.088
He handed me a telegram. Have not heard from Seward for three days. Am terribly anxious. Stop.

06:32:48.088 --> 06:32:52.748
Cannot leave. Stop. Father's still in same condition. Stop.

06:32:53.888 --> 06:32:59.788
Send me word. How loose he is. Stop. Do not delay. Stop. Homeward.

06:33:00.968 --> 06:33:05.368
I think I came just in the nick of time. You know you have only to tell me what to do.

06:33:06.468 --> 06:33:10.608
Van Helsing strode forward and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes, and he said,

06:33:11.748 --> 06:33:15.588
A brave man's blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.

06:33:15.588 --> 06:33:20.808
You are a man and no mistake. Well, the devil may work against us for all he's worth,

06:33:20.968 --> 06:33:27.308
but God sends us men when we want them. Once again we went through that ghastly operation.

06:33:28.368 --> 06:33:34.028
I have not the heart to go through with the details. Lucy had got a terrible shock and

06:33:34.028 --> 06:33:38.748
had told on her more than before, for though plenty of blood went into her veins, her body

06:33:38.748 --> 06:33:44.948
did not respond to the treatment as well as on the other occasions. Her struggle back into life was

06:33:44.948 --> 06:33:50.688
something frightful to see and hear, however the action of both heat and lungs improved,

06:33:51.528 --> 06:33:57.308
and Van Helsing made a subcutaneous injection of Morphea as before and with good effect.

06:33:58.788 --> 06:34:04.148
Her faint became a profound slumber. The professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincy

06:34:04.148 --> 06:34:08.988
Morris and set one of the maids to pay off one of the cabin who were waiting.

06:34:10.748 --> 06:34:15.648
I left Quincy lying down after having a glass of wine and told the cook to get ready a good

06:34:15.648 --> 06:34:20.688
breakfast. Then a thought struck me, and I went back to the room where Lucy was now.

06:34:21.488 --> 06:34:26.868
When I came softly in, I found Van Helsing with a sheet or two of no paper in his hand.

06:34:27.448 --> 06:34:31.548
He had evidently read it and was thinking it over as he sat with his hand to his brow.

06:34:32.608 --> 06:34:37.588
There was a look of grim satisfaction in his face as of one who has had a doubt solved.

06:34:39.108 --> 06:34:44.928
He handed me the paper, saying only it dropped from Lucy's breast when we carried her to the bath.

06:34:48.188 --> 06:34:52.268
When I had read it, I stood looking at the professor, and after a pause,

06:34:52.268 --> 06:34:58.848
I asked him, in God's name, what does it all mean? Was she or is she mad? What sort of horrible

06:34:58.848 --> 06:35:04.488
danger is it? I was so bewildered that I did not know what to say any more.

06:35:05.688 --> 06:35:08.528
Van Helsing put out his hand and took the paper, saying,

06:35:09.628 --> 06:35:14.488
Do not trouble about it now. Forget it for the present. You shall know and understand in all

06:35:14.488 --> 06:35:20.528
good time, but it will be later. And now, what is it that you came to me to say?

06:35:22.788 --> 06:35:26.268
This brought me back to fact, and I was all myself again.

06:35:29.228 --> 06:35:33.928
I came to speak about the certificate of death. If we do not act properly and wisely,

06:35:33.928 --> 06:35:39.548
there may be an inquest, and that paper would have to be produced. I am in hopes that we need

06:35:39.548 --> 06:35:44.928
have no inquest, for if we had it, it would surely kill poor Lucy if nothing else did.

06:35:45.668 --> 06:35:51.188
I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westernra

06:35:51.188 --> 06:35:55.008
had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.

06:35:56.308 --> 06:36:00.328
Let us fill up the certificate at once, and I shall take it myself to the registrar,

06:36:00.328 --> 06:36:01.768
and go on to the undertaker.

06:36:04.768 --> 06:36:11.028
Good, oh, my friend John, well thought of. Truly Miss Lucy, if she be sad in the foes of that

06:36:11.028 --> 06:36:17.468
besetter, is at least very happy in the friends that love her. One, two, three, all open their

06:36:17.468 --> 06:36:24.408
veins for her, besides one old man. Ah, yes, I know, friend John, I am not blind.

06:36:25.208 --> 06:36:28.008
I love you all the more for it. Now go.

06:36:30.688 --> 06:36:34.328
In the hall, I met Quincy Morris with a telegram from Arthur,

06:36:34.588 --> 06:36:41.308
telling him that Mrs. Westernra was dead, that Lucy also had been ill, was now going on better,

06:36:41.508 --> 06:36:48.588
and that Van Helsing and I were with her. I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out.

06:36:49.248 --> 06:36:54.888
But as I was going, said, When you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you,

06:36:55.048 --> 06:36:59.068
all to ourselves? I nodded in reply, and went out.

06:37:00.328 --> 06:37:04.728
I found no difficulty about the registration, and arranged with the local undertaker to come

06:37:04.728 --> 06:37:07.768
up in the evening to measure for the coffin, and to make arrangements.

06:37:09.948 --> 06:37:12.868
When I got back, Quincy was waiting for me.

06:37:14.608 --> 06:37:18.268
I told him I would see him as soon as I knew about Lucy, and went up to her room.

06:37:19.408 --> 06:37:24.188
She was still sleeping, and the professor seemingly had not moved from his seat at her side.

06:37:26.188 --> 06:37:29.448
From his putting his finger to his lips, I gathered that he expected her to wake

06:37:29.448 --> 06:37:32.828
up before long, and was afraid of forestalling nature.

06:37:34.768 --> 06:37:39.228
So I went down to Quincy, and took him into the breakfast room, where the blinds were not drawn

06:37:39.228 --> 06:37:45.008
down, and which was a little more cheerful, or rather less cheerless than the other rooms.

06:37:46.068 --> 06:37:53.888
When we were alone, he said to me, Jack Seward, I don't want to shove myself in anywhere where

06:37:53.888 --> 06:38:01.188
I have no right to be, but this is no ordinary case. You know I love that girl, and wanted to marry her.

06:38:04.108 --> 06:38:08.648
But although that's all past and gone, I can't help feeling anxious about her all the same.

06:38:10.408 --> 06:38:15.808
What is it that's wrong with her? The Dutchman, and a fine old fellow he is, I can see that.

06:38:16.728 --> 06:38:20.768
Said that time you two came into the room, that you must have another transfusion of blood,

06:38:21.488 --> 06:38:27.128
and that both you and he were exhausted. Now I know well that you medical men speak in camera,

06:38:27.888 --> 06:38:31.128
and that a man must not expect to know what they consult about in private.

06:38:31.768 --> 06:38:36.128
But this is no common matter, and whatever it is, I have done my part. Is that not so?

06:38:37.928 --> 06:38:40.388
That is so, I said, and he went on.

06:38:42.188 --> 06:38:46.928
I take it that both you and Van Helsing have done already what I did today. Is that not so?

06:38:48.448 --> 06:38:56.168
That's so. And I guess Art was in it too. When I saw him four days ago down at his place, he looked

06:38:56.168 --> 06:39:02.928
queer. I've not seen anything pulled down so quick since I was on the pompous, and had a mare that I

06:39:02.928 --> 06:39:09.328
was fond of go to grass all in the night. One of those big bats that they call vampires had got her

06:39:09.328 --> 06:39:14.628
in the night, and what with his gorge and the vein left open, there wasn't enough blood in her to let

06:39:14.628 --> 06:39:21.488
her stand up, and I had to put a bullet through her as she lay. Jack, if you may tell me, without

06:39:21.488 --> 06:39:30.508
betraying confidence, Arthur was the first. Is not that so? As he spoke, the poor fellow looked

06:39:30.508 --> 06:39:36.088
terribly anxious. He was in a torture of suspense regarding the woman he loved, and his utter

06:39:36.088 --> 06:39:42.648
ignorance of the terrible mystery which seemed to surround her intensified his pain. His very heart

06:39:42.648 --> 06:39:49.148
was bleeding, and it took all the manhood of him, but there was a royal lot of it too to keep him

06:39:49.148 --> 06:39:56.528
from breaking down. I paused before answering, for I felt that I must not betray anything which the

06:39:56.528 --> 06:40:04.028
professor wished kept secret. But already he knew so much, and guessed so much, that there could be

06:40:04.028 --> 06:40:12.868
no reason for not answering. So I answered in the same phrase. That's so. And how long has this been

06:40:12.868 --> 06:40:25.668
going on? About ten days. Ten days? Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we

06:40:25.668 --> 06:40:32.208
all love has put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men. Man alive, her whole

06:40:32.208 --> 06:40:40.308
body wouldn't hold it. Then coming close to me, he spoke in a fierce half whisper. What took it out?

06:40:42.068 --> 06:40:51.168
I shook my head. That, I said, is the crux. Van Helsing is simply frantic about it, and I'm at my

06:40:51.168 --> 06:40:57.268
wit's end. I can't even hazard a guess. There's been a series of little circumstances which have

06:40:57.268 --> 06:41:03.208
thrown out all our calculations as to Lucy being properly watched. But these shall not occur again.

06:41:03.568 --> 06:41:06.488
Here we stay until all be well, or ill.

06:41:09.568 --> 06:41:15.268
Quincy held out his hand. Count me in, he said. You and the Dutchman will tell me what to do,

06:41:15.468 --> 06:41:22.648
and I'll do it. When she woke late in the afternoon, Lucy's first movement was to feel in her

06:41:22.648 --> 06:41:29.128
breast, and to my surprise produced the paper which Van Helsing had given me to read. The careful

06:41:29.128 --> 06:41:33.788
professor had replaced it where it had come from, lest on waking she should be alarmed.

06:41:34.688 --> 06:41:40.648
Her eyes then lit on Van Helsing, and on me too, and gladdened. Then she looked round the room,

06:41:40.988 --> 06:41:47.368
and seeing where she was, shuddered. She gave a loud cry, and put her poor thin hands before her

06:41:47.368 --> 06:41:54.368
pale face. We both understood what was meant, that she had realized to the full her mother's death.

06:41:56.208 --> 06:42:02.128
So we tried what we could to comfort her. Doubtless, sympathy eased her somewhat,

06:42:02.488 --> 06:42:07.848
but she was very low in thought and spirit, and wept silently and weakly for a long time.

06:42:08.888 --> 06:42:15.068
We told her that either or both of us would now remain with her all the time,

06:42:15.068 --> 06:42:19.568
and that seemed to comfort her. Towards dusk she fell into a doze.

06:42:21.368 --> 06:42:26.168
Here a very odd thing occurred. While still asleep she took the paper from her breast and

06:42:26.168 --> 06:42:32.548
tore it in two. Van Helsing stepped over and took the pieces from her. All the same, however,

06:42:32.888 --> 06:42:38.208
she went on with the action of tearing, as though the material were still in her hands.

06:42:39.648 --> 06:42:44.008
Finally she lifted her hands and opened them, as though scattering the fragments.

06:42:45.448 --> 06:42:51.748
Van Helsing seemed surprised, and his brows gathered as if in thought. But he said nothing.

06:42:53.108 --> 06:42:59.408
19 September. All last night she slept fitfully, being always afraid to sleep,

06:42:59.548 --> 06:43:06.008
and something weaker when she woke from it. The professor and I took turns to watch,

06:43:06.248 --> 06:43:11.448
and we never left her for a moment unattended. Quincy Morris said nothing about his intention,

06:43:11.448 --> 06:43:15.468
but I knew that all night long he patrolled round and round the house.

06:43:16.928 --> 06:43:21.128
When the day came, its searching light showed the ravages in poor Lucy's strength.

06:43:22.068 --> 06:43:25.988
She was hardly able to turn her head, and the little nourishment which she could take

06:43:25.988 --> 06:43:32.308
seemed to do her no good. At times she slept, and both Van Helsing and I noticed a difference in her

06:43:32.688 --> 06:43:39.728
between sleeping and waking. Whilst asleep she looked stronger, although more haggard,

06:43:39.728 --> 06:43:45.308
and her breathing was softer. Her open mouth showed pale gums drawn back from the teeth,

06:43:45.708 --> 06:43:48.588
which looked positively longer and sharper than usual.

06:43:50.048 --> 06:43:53.568
When she woke, the softness of her eyes evidently changed the expression,

06:43:54.828 --> 06:43:57.628
for she looked her own self, although a dying one.

06:43:59.828 --> 06:44:02.728
In the afternoon she asked for Arthur, and we telegraphed for him.

06:44:03.988 --> 06:44:05.648
Quincy went off to meet him at the station.

06:44:08.608 --> 06:44:13.288
When he arrived, it was nearly six o'clock, and the sun was setting full and warm,

06:44:13.648 --> 06:44:18.008
and the red light streamed in through the window, and gave more colour to the pale cheeks.

06:44:19.188 --> 06:44:23.748
When he saw her, Arthur was simply choking with emotion, and none of us could speak.

06:44:24.788 --> 06:44:29.428
In the hours that had passed, the fits of sleep, or the comatose condition that passed for it,

06:44:29.908 --> 06:44:35.008
had grown more and more frequent, so that the pauses when the conversation was possible

06:44:35.008 --> 06:44:39.508
were shortened. Arthur's presence, however, seemed to act as a stimulant.

06:44:39.928 --> 06:44:44.568
She rallied a little, and spoke to him more brightly than she had done since we arrived.

06:44:45.728 --> 06:44:49.368
He too pulled himself together, and spoke as cheerily as he could,

06:44:49.968 --> 06:44:51.688
so that the best was made of everything.

06:44:54.668 --> 06:44:58.108
It is now nearly one o'clock, and he and Van Helsing are sitting with her.

06:45:00.028 --> 06:45:04.688
I am to relieve them in a quarter of an hour, and I am entering this on Lucy's phonograph.

06:45:05.468 --> 06:45:09.548
Until six o'clock, they are to try to rest. I fear that tomorrow

06:45:10.208 --> 06:45:19.848
will end our watching, for the shock has been too great. The poor child cannot rally. God help us all.

06:45:22.748 --> 06:45:29.068
Letter, Mina Harker to Lucy Resternra. Unopened by her. 17 September.

06:45:30.208 --> 06:45:33.668
My dearest Lucy, it seems an age since I had heard from you,

06:45:33.668 --> 06:45:39.308
or indeed since I wrote. You will pardon me, I know, for all my faults when you have read

06:45:39.308 --> 06:45:43.888
all my budget of news. Well, I got my husband back all right.

06:45:44.628 --> 06:45:48.108
When we arrived at Exeter, there was a carriage waiting for us, and in it,

06:45:48.108 --> 06:45:52.748
though he had an attack of gout, Mr. Hawkins. He took us to his house,

06:45:53.408 --> 06:45:57.328
where there were rooms for us all nice and comfortable, and we dined together.

06:45:59.088 --> 06:46:01.068
After dinner, Mr. Hawkins said,

06:46:01.708 --> 06:46:04.908
My dears, I want to drink to your health and prosperity,

06:46:06.008 --> 06:46:11.068
and may every blessing attend you both. I know you both from children and have,

06:46:11.068 --> 06:46:16.188
with love and pride, seen you grow up. Now I want you to make your home here with me.

06:46:17.408 --> 06:46:24.428
I have left me neither chick nor child, all are gone, and in my will I have left you everything.

06:46:26.488 --> 06:46:32.888
I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands. Our evening was a very, very happy

06:46:32.888 --> 06:46:40.648
one. So here we are, installed in this beautiful old house, and from both my bedroom and the

06:46:40.648 --> 06:46:46.268
drawing room, I can see the great elms of the cathedral close, with their great black stems

06:46:46.268 --> 06:46:52.728
standing out against the old yellow stone of the cathedral, and I can hear the rooks overhead,

06:46:52.728 --> 06:46:56.748
calling and calling and chattering and chattering and gossiping all day,

06:46:57.448 --> 06:47:03.128
after the manner of rooks and humans. I am busy, I need not tell you,

06:47:03.188 --> 06:47:07.628
arranging things and housekeeping. Jonathan and Mr. Hawkins are busy all day.

06:47:07.988 --> 06:47:12.628
For now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.

06:47:15.288 --> 06:47:20.488
How is your dear mother getting on? I wish I could run up to town for a day or two to see you, dear,

06:47:20.488 --> 06:47:26.048
but I dare not go yet, with so much on my shoulders, and Jonathan wants looking after still.

06:47:27.328 --> 06:47:31.668
He's beginning to put some flesh on his bones again, but he was terribly weakened by the long

06:47:31.668 --> 06:47:37.888
illness. Even now he sometimes starts out of his sleep in a sudden way and awakens all trembling

06:47:37.888 --> 06:47:45.788
until I can coax him back to his usual placidity. However, thank God these occasions grow less

06:47:45.788 --> 06:47:51.768
frequent as the days go on, and they will in time pass away altogether, I trust.

06:47:52.768 --> 06:47:58.048
And now I have told you my news, let me ask yours. When are you to be married and where,

06:47:58.448 --> 06:48:02.988
and who is to perform the ceremony, and what are you to wear, and is it to be a public or

06:48:02.988 --> 06:48:08.008
private wedding? Tell me all about it, dear, tell me about everything, for there's nothing

06:48:08.008 --> 06:48:14.688
which interests you which will not be dear to me. Jonathan asked me to send his respectful duty,

06:48:14.688 --> 06:48:19.028
but I do not think that is good enough for the junior partner of the important firm Hawkins and

06:48:19.768 --> 06:48:25.868
Harker. And so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of

06:48:25.868 --> 06:48:33.128
the verb, I send you simply his love instead. Goodbye, my dearest Lucy, and blessings on you.

06:48:34.508 --> 06:48:35.888
Yours, Mina Harker.

06:48:44.688 --> 06:48:50.108
Et cetera, et cetera. To John Seward, M.D. 20 September.

06:48:52.588 --> 06:48:57.588
My dear sir, in accordance with your wishes, I enclose report of the conditions of everything

06:48:57.588 --> 06:49:03.448
left in my charge. With regard to the patient Renfield, there's more to say. He's had another

06:49:03.448 --> 06:49:10.088
outbreak, which might have had a dreadful ending, but which, as fortunately happened, was unattended

06:49:10.088 --> 06:49:15.548
with any unhappy results. This afternoon, a carrier's cart with two men made a call at

06:49:15.548 --> 06:49:20.608
the empty house whose grounds abut on ours, the house to which, you will remember, the patient

06:49:20.608 --> 06:49:27.048
twice ran away. The men stopped at our gate to ask the porter their way, as they were strangers.

06:49:29.988 --> 06:49:34.868
I was myself looking out of the study window, having a smoke after dinner, and saw one of them

06:49:34.868 --> 06:49:40.108
come up to the house. As he passed the window of Renfield's room, the patient began to rate

06:49:40.108 --> 06:49:44.688
him from the within, and called him all the foul names he could lay his tongue to.

06:49:45.628 --> 06:49:50.368
The man, who seemed a decent fellow enough, contented himself by telling him to shut up

06:49:50.368 --> 06:49:55.948
for a foul-mouthed beggar, whereupon our man accused him of robbing him and wanting to murder

06:49:55.948 --> 06:50:01.628
him, and said that he would hinder him if he were to swing for it. I opened the window and signed

06:50:01.628 --> 06:50:06.108
the man not to notice, so he contented himself, after looking the place over and making up his

06:50:06.108 --> 06:50:09.588
mind as to what kind of place he had got to, by saying,

06:50:09.648 --> 06:50:13.968
Lord bless you, sir, I wouldn't mind what was said to me in a blooming madhouse.

06:50:14.448 --> 06:50:18.428
I pity ye in the governor for having to live in the house with a wild beast like that.

06:50:20.068 --> 06:50:24.368
Then he asked his way civilly enough, and I told him where the gate of the empty house was.

06:50:24.748 --> 06:50:28.848
He went away, followed by threats and curses and revilings from our man.

06:50:29.808 --> 06:50:34.328
I went down to see if I could make out any cause for his anger, since he is usually such a well

06:50:34.328 --> 06:50:38.468
behaved man, and except his violent fits nothing of the kind had ever occurred.

06:50:39.268 --> 06:50:43.408
I found him, to my astonishment, quite composed and most genial in his manner.

06:50:44.428 --> 06:50:48.568
I tried to get him to talk of the incident, but he blandly asked me questions as to what I meant,

06:50:49.148 --> 06:50:52.128
and led me to believe that he was completely oblivious of the affair.

06:50:53.908 --> 06:50:59.908
It was, I am sorry to say, however, only another instance of his cunning, for within half an hour

06:50:59.908 --> 06:51:05.048
I heard of him again. This time he had broken out through the window of his room and was running

06:51:05.048 --> 06:51:10.888
down the avenue. I called for the attendants to follow me and ran after him, for I feared he was

06:51:10.888 --> 06:51:17.168
intent on some mischief. My fear was justified when I saw the same cart which had passed before

06:51:17.168 --> 06:51:22.108
coming down the road, having on it some great wooden boxes. The men were wiping their feet

06:51:22.108 --> 06:51:28.128
foreheads and were flushed in the face as if with violent exercise. Before I could get up to him,

06:51:28.208 --> 06:51:32.488
the patient rushed at them, and pulling one of them off the cart began to knock his head against

06:51:32.488 --> 06:51:37.168
the ground. If I had not seized him just at the moment, I believe he would have killed the man

06:51:37.168 --> 06:51:41.768
then and there. The other fellow jumped down and struck him over the head with the butt end of his

06:51:41.768 --> 06:51:47.968
heavy whip. It was a horrible blow, but he did not seem to mind it, but seized him also and struggled

06:51:47.968 --> 06:51:53.868
with the three of us, pulling us to and fro as if we were kittens. You know I am no lightweight,

06:51:54.308 --> 06:52:00.108
and the others were both burly men. At first he was silent in his fighting, but as we began to master

06:52:00.108 --> 06:52:06.008
him and the attendants were putting a straight waistcoat on him, he began to shout, I'll frustrate

06:52:06.008 --> 06:52:12.988
them. They shan't rob me. They shan't rob and murder me by inches. I'll fight for my lord and master.

06:52:13.888 --> 06:52:20.348
And all sorts of similar incoherent ravings. It was with very considerable difficulty that they

06:52:20.348 --> 06:52:25.948
got him back to the house and put him in a padded room. One of the attendants, Hardy,

06:52:26.208 --> 06:52:30.768
had a finger broken. However, I said it all right, and he is going well.

06:52:32.828 --> 06:52:37.248
The two carriers were at first loud in their threats of actions for damages and promised to

06:52:37.248 --> 06:52:42.088
rain down all the penalties of the law on us. Their threats were, however, mingled with some

06:52:42.088 --> 06:52:50.348
indirect apology for the defeat of the two of them by a feeble madman. They said that it had not been

06:52:50.348 --> 06:52:54.648
for the way their strength had been spent in carrying and raising the heavy boxes.

06:52:55.048 --> 06:53:00.248
To the cart they would have made a short work of him. They gave as another reason for their defeat

06:53:00.248 --> 06:53:04.828
the extraordinary state of drought to which they had been reduced by the dusty nature of their

06:53:04.828 --> 06:53:10.128
occupation and the reprehensible distance from the scene of their labors of any place of public

06:53:10.128 --> 06:53:17.008
entertainment. I quite understood their drift, and after a stiff glass of strong grog,

06:53:18.168 --> 06:53:24.208
or rather more of the same, and with each a sovereign in their hand, they made light of

06:53:24.208 --> 06:53:28.588
the attack and swore that they would encounter worse madmen any day for the pleasure of meeting

06:53:28.588 --> 06:53:34.108
so gloom and a good bloke as your correspondent. I took their names and addresses in case they

06:53:34.108 --> 06:53:41.148
be needed. They are as follows. Jack Smollett of Deadling's Rent, King George's Road, Great

06:53:41.148 --> 06:53:48.428
Walworth, and Thomas Snelling, Peter Farley's Row, Guide Court, Bethnal Green. They are both

06:53:48.428 --> 06:53:54.348
in the employment of Harrison Sons, Moving and Shipment Company, Orange Master's Yard, Soho.

06:53:55.368 --> 06:54:00.408
I shall report to you any matter of interest occurring here, and shall wire you at once if

06:54:00.408 --> 06:54:06.408
there is anything of importance. Believe me, dear sir. Yours faithfully, Patrick Hennessey.

06:54:08.768 --> 06:54:14.448
Letter, Mina Harkner to Lucy Wisternera. Unopened by her. 18 September.

06:54:15.868 --> 06:54:23.428
My dearest Lucy, such a sad blow has befallen us. Mr. Hawkins has died very suddenly. Some may not

06:54:23.428 --> 06:54:27.528
think it so sad for us, but we had both come to so love him that it really seems as though we had

06:54:27.528 --> 06:54:32.388
lost a father. I never knew either father or mother, so that the dear old man's death is a

06:54:32.388 --> 06:54:39.368
real blow to me. Jonathan is greatly distressed. It is not only that he feels sorrow, deep sorrow,

06:54:39.568 --> 06:54:45.008
for the dear, good man who has befriended him all his life, and now at the end has treated him like

06:54:45.008 --> 06:54:49.748
his own son and left him a fortune to which people of our modest bringing up his wealth beyond a

06:54:49.748 --> 06:54:56.008
dream of avarice, but Jonathan feels it on another account. He says the amount of responsibility which

06:54:56.008 --> 06:55:01.288
puts upon him makes him nervous. He begins to doubt himself. I try to cheer him up, but my

06:55:01.288 --> 06:55:06.388
belief in him helps him to have a belief in himself. But it is here that the grave shock

06:55:06.388 --> 06:55:12.268
that he experienced tells upon him the most. Oh, it is too hard that a sweet, simple, noble,

06:55:12.428 --> 06:55:18.428
strong nature such as his, a nature which enabled him by our dear good friend's aid to rise from

06:55:18.428 --> 06:55:24.108
clerk to master in a few years, should be so injured that the very essence of his strength is gone.

06:55:24.948 --> 06:55:28.708
Forgive me, dear, if I worry you with my troubles in the midst of your own happiness,

06:55:28.848 --> 06:55:33.088
but, Lucy dear, I must tell someone, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful

06:55:33.088 --> 06:55:39.448
appearance to Jonathan tires me, and I have no one here that I can confide in. I dread coming

06:55:39.448 --> 06:55:45.168
up to London, as we must do the day after tomorrow, for poor Mr. Hawkins left in his will that he was

06:55:45.168 --> 06:55:50.748
to be buried in the grave with his father. As there are no relations at all, Jonathan will

06:55:50.748 --> 06:55:56.568
have to be chief mourner. I shall try to run over to see you, dearest, if only for a few minutes.

06:55:57.908 --> 06:56:01.948
Forgive me for troubling you. With all blessings, your loving, Mina Harker.

06:56:05.188 --> 06:56:13.448
Dr. Seward's Diary, 20 September. Only resolution and habit can let me make an entry tonight.

06:56:14.008 --> 06:56:21.148
I am too miserable, too low-spirited, too sick of the world and all in it, including life itself,

06:56:21.408 --> 06:56:25.528
that I would not care if I heard this moment the flapping of the wings of the angel of death.

06:56:26.668 --> 06:56:33.128
And he has been flapping those grim wings to some purpose of late, Lucy's mother and Arthur's

06:56:33.128 --> 06:56:42.388
father, and now let me get on with my work. I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.

06:56:43.028 --> 06:56:48.528
We wanted Arthur to go and to rest also, but he refused at first. It was only when I told him

06:56:48.528 --> 06:56:53.048
that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of

06:56:53.048 --> 06:57:00.188
rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go. Van Helsing was very kind to him. Come,

06:57:00.248 --> 06:57:05.948
my child, he said. Come with me. You are sick and weak, and have had such sorrow and much mental

06:57:05.948 --> 06:57:12.028
pain, as well as that tax on your strength that we know of. You must not be alone, for to be alone

06:57:12.028 --> 06:57:17.148
is to be full of fears and alarms. Come to the drawing room, where there is a big fire,

06:57:17.248 --> 06:57:22.448
and there are two sofas. You shall lie on one, and I on the other, and our sympathy will be

06:57:22.448 --> 06:57:30.148
comfort to each other, even though we do not speak, even if we sleep. Arthur went off with

06:57:30.148 --> 06:57:35.428
him casting back a longing look on Lucy's face, which lay in her pillow, almost wider than the

06:57:35.428 --> 06:57:41.428
lawn. She lay quiet and still, and I looked round the room to see that all was as it should be.

06:57:42.028 --> 06:57:46.868
I could see that the Professor had carried out in this room, as in others, his purpose of using

06:57:46.868 --> 06:57:53.048
the garlic. The whole of the window sashes reeked with it, and round Lucy's neck over the silk

06:57:53.048 --> 06:57:59.448
handkerchief in which Van Helsing made her keep on was a rough chaplet of the same odorous flowers.

06:58:01.308 --> 06:58:07.048
Lucy was breathing somewhat stirtuously, and her face was at its worst, for the open mouth showed

06:58:07.048 --> 06:58:12.908
pale gums. Her teeth in the dim, uncertain light seemed longer and sharper than they had been in

06:58:12.908 --> 06:58:18.108
the morning. In particular, by some trick of the light, the canine teeth looked longer and sharper

06:58:18.108 --> 06:58:25.448
than the rest. I sat down beside her, and presently she moved uneasily. At the same moment, there came

06:58:25.448 --> 06:58:31.428
a sort of dull flapping or buffeting at the window. I went over to it softly and peeped out

06:58:31.428 --> 06:58:36.228
by the corner of the blind. There was full moonlight, and I could see that the noise was

06:58:36.228 --> 06:58:42.408
made by a great bat which wheeled round, doubtless attracted by the light, although so dim, and every

06:58:42.408 --> 06:58:48.308
now and again struck the window with its wings. When I came back to my seat, I found that Lucy had

06:58:48.308 --> 06:58:54.108
moved slightly, and had torn away the garlic flowers from her throat. I replaced them as well

06:58:54.108 --> 06:59:06.208
as I could, and sat watching her. Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had

06:59:06.208 --> 06:59:10.888
the unconscious struggle for life, and the strength that had hitherto marked her illness.

06:59:13.128 --> 06:59:17.148
It struck me as curious that the moment she became conscious, she pressed the garlic flowers

06:59:17.148 --> 06:59:23.388
close to her. It was certainly odd that whatever she got into that lethargic state, with this

06:59:23.388 --> 06:59:29.488
dirtuous breathing, she put the flowers from her, but that when she waked, she clutched them close.

06:59:30.468 --> 06:59:34.868
There was no possibility of making any mistake about this, for in the long hours that followed,

06:59:34.868 --> 06:59:40.048
she had many spells of sleeping and waking, and repeated both actions many times.

06:59:41.628 --> 06:59:47.728
At six o'clock, Van Helsing came to relieve me. Arthur had then fallen into a doze, and

06:59:47.728 --> 06:59:53.448
immersively let him sleep on. When he saw Lucy's face, I could hear the hissing indraw of breath,

06:59:53.628 --> 07:00:00.168
and he said to me in a sharp whisper, Drop the blind, I want light. Then he bent down,

07:00:00.168 --> 07:00:05.508
with his face almost touching Lucy's, examined her carefully. He removed the flowers and lifted

07:00:05.508 --> 07:00:10.408
the silk handkerchief from her throat. As he did so, he started back, and I could hear his

07:00:10.408 --> 07:00:18.028
ejaculation. My God! It was smothered in his throat. I bent over and looked too, and as I noticed some

07:00:18.028 --> 07:00:23.068
queer chill came over me. The wounds on her throat had absolutely disappeared.

07:00:25.168 --> 07:00:30.928
For fully five minutes, Van Helsing stood looking at her, with his face at its sternest.

07:00:33.048 --> 07:00:39.848
Then he turned to me and said calmly, She is dying. It will not be long now. It will be much

07:00:39.848 --> 07:00:46.208
difference, mark me, whether she dies, conscious or in her sleep. Wake that poor boy, and let him

07:00:46.208 --> 07:00:52.888
come to see the last. He trusts us, and we have promised him. I went to the dining room, and

07:00:53.528 --> 07:00:57.828
he was dazed for a moment, but when he saw the sunlight streaming in through the edges of the

07:00:57.828 --> 07:01:03.568
shutters, he thought he was late and expressed his fear. I assured him that Lucy was still asleep,

07:01:03.928 --> 07:01:08.048
but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.

07:01:09.408 --> 07:01:14.368
He covered his face with his hands and slid down on his knees by the sofa, where he remained,

07:01:14.588 --> 07:01:20.168
perhaps a minute, with his head buried, praying, whilst his shoulders shook with grief.

07:01:21.248 --> 07:01:27.948
I took him by the hand and raised him up. Come, I said, my dear old fellow, summon all your

07:01:27.948 --> 07:01:34.448
fortitude. It will be best and easiest for her. When we came into Lucy's room, I could see that

07:01:34.448 --> 07:01:39.008
Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything

07:01:39.008 --> 07:01:44.968
look as pleasing as possible. He had even brushed Lucy's hair so that it lay on the pillow in its

07:01:44.968 --> 07:01:51.068
usual, sunny ripples. When we came into the room, she opened her eyes, and seeing him,

07:01:51.088 --> 07:01:59.028
she whispered softly, Arthur, oh, my love, I am so glad you have come. He was stooping to kiss her

07:01:59.028 --> 07:02:05.248
when Van Helsing motioned him back. No, he whispered, not yet. Hold her hand, it will comfort

07:02:05.248 --> 07:02:11.448
her more. So Arthur took her hand and knelt beside her, and she looked her best, with all the soft

07:02:11.448 --> 07:02:17.048
lines matching the angelic beauty of her eyes. Then gradually her eyes closed, and she sank to

07:02:17.048 --> 07:02:24.008
sleep. For a little bit, her breast heaved softly, and her breath came and went like a tired child's.

07:02:25.388 --> 07:02:29.788
And then, insensibly, there came the strange change which I had noticed in the night.

07:02:30.748 --> 07:02:36.648
Her breathing grew sturtuous. The mouth opened, and the pale gums drawn back made the teeth look

07:02:36.648 --> 07:02:42.088
longer and sharper than ever. In a sort of sleep-waking, vague, unconscious way, she opened

07:02:42.088 --> 07:02:48.148
her eyes, which were now dull and hard at once, and she said in a soft, voluptuous voice such as

07:02:48.148 --> 07:02:57.328
I had never heard from her lips, Arthur, oh, my love, I am so glad you have come. Kiss me.

07:02:58.568 --> 07:03:04.448
Arthur bent eagerly over to kiss her, but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been

07:03:04.448 --> 07:03:09.268
startled by her voice, swooped upon him and, catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged

07:03:09.268 --> 07:03:14.048
him back with a fury of strength which I had never thought he could have possessed, and actually

07:03:14.048 --> 07:03:21.368
hurled him almost across the room. Not on your life, he said, not for your living soul and hers,

07:03:21.708 --> 07:03:27.908
and he stood between them like a lion at bay. Arthur was so taken aback that he did not for a

07:03:27.908 --> 07:03:34.128
moment know what to do or say, and before any impulse of violence could seize him, he realized

07:03:34.128 --> 07:03:40.588
the place and the occasion and stood silent, waiting. I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy as did Van

07:03:40.588 --> 07:03:47.708
Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face. The sharp teeth clamped

07:03:47.708 --> 07:03:54.148
together. Her eyes closed, and she breathed heavily. Very shortly after, she opened her

07:03:54.148 --> 07:03:59.508
eyes in all their softness, and putting out her poor, pale, thin hand, took Van Helsing's great

07:03:59.508 --> 07:04:06.668
brown one, drawing it close to her. She kissed it. My true friend, she said in a faint voice,

07:04:06.728 --> 07:04:16.408
but with untellable pathos. My true friend and his. Oh, guard him, and give me peace.

07:04:18.468 --> 07:04:24.768
I swear it, he said solemnly, kneeling beside her and holding up his hand as one who registers

07:04:24.768 --> 07:04:31.128
an oath. Then he turned to Arthur and said to him, come, my child, take her hand in yours

07:04:31.128 --> 07:04:38.928
and kiss her on the forehead. And only once. Their eyes met instead of their lips, and so they parted.

07:04:39.868 --> 07:04:44.888
Lucy's eyes closed, and Van Helsing, who had been watching closely, took Arthur's arm and

07:04:44.888 --> 07:04:53.068
drew him away. And then Lucy's breathing became stertuous again, and all at once it ceased.

07:04:54.348 --> 07:05:01.348
It's all over, said Van Helsing. She's dead. I took Arthur by the arm and led him to the drawing

07:05:01.348 --> 07:05:06.768
room, where he sat down and covered his face with his hands, sobbing in a way that nearly broke me

07:05:06.768 --> 07:05:13.788
down to see. I went back to the room and found Van Helsing, looking at poor Lucy, and his face was

07:05:13.788 --> 07:05:20.308
sterner than ever. Some change had come over her body. Death had given back part of her beauty for

07:05:20.308 --> 07:05:26.068
brow and cheeks had recovered some of their flowing lines. Even the lips had lost their

07:05:26.068 --> 07:05:32.388
deadly pallor. It was as if the blood, no longer needed for the working of the heart, had gone to

07:05:32.388 --> 07:05:38.548
make the harshness of death as little rude as might be. We thought her dying while she slept,

07:05:39.488 --> 07:05:46.328
and sleeping while she died. I stood beside Van Helsing and said, ah well, poor girl,

07:05:46.328 --> 07:05:54.288
there's peace for her at last. It is the end. He turned to me and said with a grave solemnity,

07:05:55.648 --> 07:06:02.268
not so, alas, not so. It is only the beginning. When I asked him what he meant, he only shook

07:06:02.268 --> 07:06:12.728
his head and answered, we can do nothing as yet. Wait and see.

07:06:44.756 --> 07:06:48.256
BY BRAM STOKER

07:06:52.336 --> 07:06:55.256
Dr. Seward's Diary

07:06:56.396 --> 07:06:56.716
CONTINUED

07:06:57.296 --> 07:07:02.796
The funeral was arranged for the next succeeding day, so that Lucy and her mother might be

07:07:02.796 --> 07:07:03.696
buried together.

07:07:03.856 --> 07:07:09.556
I attended to all the ghastly formalities, and the urbane undertaker proved that his

07:07:09.556 --> 07:07:15.316
staff was afflicted or blessed with something of his own ubiquitous suavity.

07:07:17.076 --> 07:07:22.856
Even the woman who performed the last offices for the dead remarked to me in a confidential,

07:07:23.356 --> 07:07:26.996
brother-professional way when she had come out from the death chamber.

07:07:27.976 --> 07:07:30.636
She makes a very beautiful corpse, sir.

07:07:31.016 --> 07:07:33.476
It's quite a privilege to attend on her.

07:07:33.876 --> 07:07:37.856
It's not too much to say that she will do credit to our establishment.

07:07:39.756 --> 07:07:43.336
I noticed that Van Helsing never kept far away.

07:07:43.916 --> 07:07:47.596
This was possible from the disordered state of things in the household.

07:07:48.316 --> 07:07:53.716
There were no relatives at hand, and as Arthur had to be back the next day to attend at his

07:07:53.716 --> 07:07:58.056
father's funeral, we were unable to notify anyone who should have been bitten.

07:07:58.696 --> 07:08:05.136
Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers—except.

07:08:06.176 --> 07:08:09.736
He insisted upon looking over Lucy's papers himself.

07:08:10.316 --> 07:08:16.656
I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English

07:08:16.656 --> 07:08:21.316
legal requirements, and so might an ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.

07:08:22.076 --> 07:08:24.836
He answered me, I know, I know.

07:08:25.136 --> 07:08:30.536
You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor, but this is not altogether for the law.

07:08:31.116 --> 07:08:33.536
You knew that when you avoided the coroner.

07:08:33.816 --> 07:08:35.636
I have more than him to avoid.

07:08:36.136 --> 07:08:39.076
There may be papers more, such as this.

07:08:39.636 --> 07:08:44.696
As he spoke, he took from his pocket-book the memorandum which had been in Lucy's breast

07:08:44.696 --> 07:08:47.056
and which she had torn in her sleep.

07:08:47.056 --> 07:08:54.196
When you find anything of the solicitors for the late Mrs. Westerna, seal all her papers

07:08:54.196 --> 07:08:56.036
and write him to-night.

07:08:56.636 --> 07:09:02.756
For me I watch here in the room and in Miss Lucy's old room all night, and I myself search

07:09:02.756 --> 07:09:03.856
for what may be.

07:09:04.136 --> 07:09:08.396
It is not well that her very thoughts go into the hands of strangers.

07:09:09.856 --> 07:09:15.356
I went on with my part of the work, and in another half-hour had found the name and address

07:09:15.356 --> 07:09:18.616
of Mrs. Westerna's solicitor I had written to him.

07:09:19.216 --> 07:09:21.776
All the poor lady's papers were in order.

07:09:22.316 --> 07:09:25.876
Explicit directions regarding the place of the burial were given.

07:09:26.396 --> 07:09:32.416
I had hardly sealed the letter when, to my surprise, Van Helsing walked into the room

07:09:32.416 --> 07:09:32.956
saying,

07:09:33.516 --> 07:09:35.396
Can I help you, friend John?

07:09:35.676 --> 07:09:38.836
I am free, and if I may, my service is to you.

07:09:39.736 --> 07:09:41.656
Have you got what you looked for?

07:09:41.876 --> 07:09:42.756
I asked.

07:09:42.756 --> 07:09:44.356
To which he replied,

07:09:44.396 --> 07:09:47.216
I did not look for any specific thing.

07:09:47.456 --> 07:09:51.456
I only hope to find, and find I have, all that there was.

07:09:51.836 --> 07:09:56.136
Only some letters, and a few memoranda, and a diary, new begun.

07:09:56.576 --> 07:10:00.356
But I have them here, and we shall for the present say nothing of them.

07:10:00.716 --> 07:10:06.656
I shall see that poor lad to-morrow evening, and, with his sanction, I shall use some.

07:10:06.656 --> 07:10:10.976
When we had finished the work in hand he said to me,

07:10:11.096 --> 07:10:14.156
And now, friend John, I think we may to bed.

07:10:14.596 --> 07:10:18.976
We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.

07:10:19.336 --> 07:10:24.776
To-morrow we shall have much to do, but for to-night there is no need of us, alas.

07:10:26.636 --> 07:10:29.676
Before turning in we went to look at poor Lucy.

07:10:30.416 --> 07:10:35.816
The undertaker had certainly done his work well, for the room was turned into a small

07:10:35.816 --> 07:10:36.976
chapela d'ante.

07:10:37.596 --> 07:10:42.836
There was a wilderness of beautiful white flowers, and death was made as little repulsive

07:10:42.836 --> 07:10:43.976
as might be.

07:10:44.496 --> 07:10:47.916
The end of the winding sheet was laid over the face.

07:10:48.396 --> 07:10:53.416
When the professor bent over and turned it gently back we both started at the beauty

07:10:53.416 --> 07:10:59.096
before us, the tall wax candle showing a sufficient light to note it well.

07:10:59.736 --> 07:11:05.636
All Lucy's loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead

07:11:05.636 --> 07:11:12.456
of leaving traces of decays of facing fingers, had but restored the beauty of life, till

07:11:12.456 --> 07:11:16.376
positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.

07:11:16.976 --> 07:11:19.336
The professor looked sternly grave.

07:11:19.716 --> 07:11:24.356
He had not loved her as I had, and there was no need for tears in his eyes.

07:11:24.736 --> 07:11:29.316
He said to me, Remain till I return, and left the room.

07:11:29.756 --> 07:11:35.196
He came back with a handful of wild garlic from the box waiting in the hall, but which

07:11:35.196 --> 07:11:40.596
had not been opened, and placed the flowers amongst the others on and around the bed.

07:11:41.156 --> 07:11:47.276
Then he took from his neck, inside his collar, a little gold crucifix, and placed it over

07:11:47.276 --> 07:11:47.876
the mouth.

07:11:48.436 --> 07:11:51.876
He restored the sheet to its place, and we came away.

07:11:53.236 --> 07:12:00.016
I was undressing in my own room when, with a prementory tap at the door, he entered,

07:12:00.376 --> 07:12:02.176
and at once began to speak.

07:12:02.876 --> 07:12:07.876
Tomorrow I want you to bring me, before night, a set of post-mortem knives.

07:12:09.216 --> 07:12:11.876
Must we make an autopsy? I asked.

07:12:12.776 --> 07:12:20.036
Yes, and no. I want to operate, but not what you think. Let me tell you now, but not a

07:12:20.036 --> 07:12:24.196
word to another. I want to cut off her head and take out her heart.

07:12:25.416 --> 07:12:31.696
Ah, you are a surgeon so shocked. You whom I have seen with no tremble of hand or heart,

07:12:31.696 --> 07:12:35.676
do operations of life and death that make the rest shudder.

07:12:36.476 --> 07:12:41.756
Oh, but I must not forget, my dear friend John, that you loved her, and have not forgotten

07:12:41.756 --> 07:12:46.856
it for his eye that shall operate, and you must not help. I would like to do it to-night,

07:12:47.096 --> 07:12:52.916
but for Arthur I must not. He will be free after his father's funeral tomorrow, and he

07:12:52.916 --> 07:12:59.196
will want to see her, to see it. Then when she is coffined ready for the next day, you

07:12:59.196 --> 07:13:04.896
and I shall come when all asleep. We shall unscrew the coffin lid and shall do our operation

07:13:04.896 --> 07:13:09.616
and then replace all, so that none know, save we alone.

07:13:11.056 --> 07:13:17.996
But why do it at all? The girl is dead. Why mutilate her poor body without need? If there

07:13:17.996 --> 07:13:24.236
is no necessity for a post-mortem and nothing to gain by it, no good to her, to us, to science,

07:13:24.236 --> 07:13:29.636
to human knowledge, why do it? Without such it is monstrous.

07:13:30.956 --> 07:13:37.416
For answer he put his hand on my shoulder and said, with infinite tenderness, Friend

07:13:37.416 --> 07:13:43.116
John, I pity your poor bleeding heart, and I love you the more because it does so bleed.

07:13:43.596 --> 07:13:48.656
If I could I would take on myself the burden that you do bear. But there are things that

07:13:48.656 --> 07:13:53.836
you know not, but that you shall know, and bless me for knowing, though they are not

07:13:53.836 --> 07:13:58.016
pleasant things. John, my child, you have been my friend now

07:13:58.016 --> 07:14:05.016
how many years, and yet did you ever know me to do any without good cause? I may err,

07:14:05.196 --> 07:14:11.256
I am but a man, but I believe in all I do. Was it not for these causes that you sent

07:14:11.256 --> 07:14:17.636
for me when the great trouble came? Yes, were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would

07:14:17.636 --> 07:14:23.476
not let Arthur kiss his love, though she was dying, and snatched him away by all my strength?

07:14:23.936 --> 07:14:31.196
Yes, and yet you saw how she thanked me with her so beautiful dying eyes, her voice, too,

07:14:31.236 --> 07:14:37.276
so weak, and she kissed my rough old hand and blessed me? Yes, and did you not hear

07:14:37.276 --> 07:14:42.136
me swear a promise to her that so she closed her eyes grateful? Yes.

07:14:43.416 --> 07:14:50.056
Well, I have good reason now for all I want to do. You have for many years, trust me.

07:14:50.576 --> 07:14:55.536
You have, believe me, weeks past, when there be things so strange that you might have welled

07:14:55.536 --> 07:15:01.256
out. Believe me yet a little, friend John, if you trust me not that I must think what

07:15:01.256 --> 07:15:07.356
I think, and that is not perhaps well, and if I work as work I shall, no matter trust

07:15:07.356 --> 07:15:13.996
or no trust, without my friend trust in me I work with heavy heart, and feel oh so lonely

07:15:13.996 --> 07:15:17.196
when I want all help and courage that may be.

07:15:17.796 --> 07:15:24.156
He paused a moment and went on solemnly, friend John, there are strange and terrible

07:15:24.156 --> 07:15:32.216
days before us, let us not be two but one, that so we work to a good end, will you not

07:15:32.216 --> 07:15:33.596
have faith in me?

07:15:34.136 --> 07:15:40.016
I took his hand and promised him, I held my door open as I went away and watched him go

07:15:40.016 --> 07:15:45.756
to his room and close the door, as I stood without moving I saw one of the maids pass

07:15:45.756 --> 07:15:51.556
silently along the passage, she had her back to me, so did not see me, and go into the

07:15:51.556 --> 07:15:58.296
room where Lucy lay. The sight touched me, devotion is so rare, and we are so grateful

07:15:58.296 --> 07:16:04.516
to those who show it unasked to those we love, here was a poor girl putting aside the terrors

07:16:04.516 --> 07:16:09.596
which she naturally had of death, to go watch alone by the beer of the mistress whom she

07:16:09.596 --> 07:16:14.936
had loved, so that the poor clay might not be lonely till laid to eternal rest.

07:16:15.696 --> 07:16:21.116
I must have slept long and soundly, for it was broad daylight when Van Helsing waked

07:16:21.116 --> 07:16:27.676
me by coming into my room, he came over to my bedside and said, you need not trouble

07:16:27.676 --> 07:16:30.436
about the knives, we shall not do it.

07:16:31.156 --> 07:16:37.656
Why not, I asked, for his solemnity of the night before had greatly impressed me, because,

07:16:37.716 --> 07:16:45.976
he said sternly, it is too late, or too early, see, here he held up the little golden crucifix,

07:16:46.256 --> 07:16:47.876
this was stolen in the night.

07:16:48.736 --> 07:16:55.216
How stolen, I asked in wonder, since you have it now, because I get it back from the worthless

07:16:55.216 --> 07:17:00.616
wretch who stole it, from the woman who robbed the dead in the living, her punishment will

07:17:00.616 --> 07:17:06.516
surely come but not through me, she knew not altogether what she did, and thus unknowing

07:17:06.516 --> 07:17:09.636
she only stole, now we must wait.

07:17:10.456 --> 07:17:16.236
He went away on the word, leaving me with a new mystery to think of, a new puzzle to

07:17:16.236 --> 07:17:24.656
grapple with, the forenoon was a dreary time, but at noon the solicitor came, Mr. Markand,

07:17:24.656 --> 07:17:27.796
of Holman's sons Markand and Litterdale.

07:17:28.556 --> 07:17:34.536
He was very genial and very appreciative of what we had done, and took off our hands all

07:17:34.536 --> 07:17:41.456
cares as to details, during lunch he told us that Mrs. Westenra had for some time expected

07:17:41.456 --> 07:17:47.656
sudden death from her heart, and had put her affairs in absolute order, he informed us

07:17:47.656 --> 07:17:53.296
that with the exception of a certain entailed property of Lucy's father, which now in default

07:17:53.296 --> 07:18:00.096
of direct issue went back to a distant branch of the family, the whole estate, real and

07:18:00.096 --> 07:18:09.676
personal, was left absolutely to Arthur Homewood, when he had told us so much he went on, frankly

07:18:09.676 --> 07:18:15.796
we did our best to prevent such a testamentary disposition, and pointed out certain contingencies

07:18:15.796 --> 07:18:21.536
that might leave her daughter, either penniless or not so free as she should be to act regarding

07:18:21.536 --> 07:18:27.376
a matrimonial alliance, indeed we pressed the matter so far that we almost came into

07:18:27.376 --> 07:18:32.636
collision, for she asked us if we were or were not prepared to carry out her wishes,

07:18:33.076 --> 07:18:39.476
of course we had then no alternative but to accept, we were right in principle, and ninety

07:18:39.476 --> 07:18:44.956
nine times out of a hundred we should have proved, by the logic of events, the accuracy

07:18:44.956 --> 07:18:51.356
of our judgment, frankly however, I must admit that in this case any other form of

07:18:51.356 --> 07:18:56.816
dispossession would have rendered impossible the carrying out of her wishes, for by her

07:18:56.816 --> 07:19:00.916
predeceasing her daughter, the latter would have come into possession of the property,

07:19:01.416 --> 07:19:07.856
and even if she had only survived her mother by five minutes, her property would, in case

07:19:07.856 --> 07:19:13.336
there were no will, and a will was a practical impossibility in this case, have been treated

07:19:13.336 --> 07:19:19.936
at her decease as underintessency, in which case Lord Galdeming, though so dear a friend,

07:19:19.936 --> 07:19:25.296
would have had no claim in the world, and the inheritors being remote would not be likely

07:19:25.296 --> 07:19:31.816
to abandon their just rights, for sentimental reasons regarding an entire stranger, I assure

07:19:31.816 --> 07:19:36.836
you my dear sirs, I am rejoiced at the result, perfectly rejoiced.

07:19:37.776 --> 07:19:43.456
He was a good fellow, but his rejoicing at the one little part, in which he was so officially

07:19:43.456 --> 07:19:50.116
interested, of so great a tragedy, was an object lesson in the limitations of sympathetic

07:19:50.116 --> 07:19:56.196
understanding. He did not remain long, but said he would look in later in the day and

07:19:56.196 --> 07:20:02.616
see Lord Galdeming. His coming, however, had been a certain comfort to us, since it assured

07:20:02.616 --> 07:20:09.056
us that we should not have to dread hostile criticism as to any of our acts. Arthur was

07:20:09.056 --> 07:20:15.016
expected to arrive at five o'clock, so a little before that time we visited the great chamber.

07:20:15.436 --> 07:20:22.876
It was so in very truth, for now both mother and daughter lay in it. The undertaker, true

07:20:22.876 --> 07:20:28.876
to his craft, had made the best display he could of his goods, and there was a mortuary

07:20:28.876 --> 07:20:32.416
air about the place that lowered our spirits at once.

07:20:33.336 --> 07:20:39.696
Van Helsing ordered the former arrangement to be adhered to, explaining that, as Lord

07:20:39.696 --> 07:20:45.056
Galdeming was coming very soon, it would be less harrowing to his feelings to see all

07:20:45.056 --> 07:20:51.996
that was left of his fiancée quite alone. The undertaker seemed shocked at his own stupidity,

07:20:52.416 --> 07:20:56.916
and exerted himself to restore things to the condition in which we left them the night

07:20:56.916 --> 07:21:03.416
before, so that, when Arthur came, such shocks to his feelings that we could avoid were saved.

07:21:04.656 --> 07:21:11.576
Poor fellow! He looked desperately sad and broken. Even his stalwart manhood seemed to

07:21:11.576 --> 07:21:18.316
have shrunk somewhat under the strain of his much-tried emotions. He had, I knew, been

07:21:18.316 --> 07:21:23.996
very genuinely and devotedly attached to his father, and to lose him, and at such a

07:21:23.996 --> 07:21:29.736
time, was a bitter blow to him. With me he was as warm as ever, and to Van Helsing he

07:21:29.736 --> 07:21:34.596
was sweetly courteous, but I could not help seeing that there was some constraint with

07:21:34.596 --> 07:21:41.356
him. The professor noticed it too, and mentioned me to bring him upstairs. I did so, and left

07:21:41.356 --> 07:21:45.976
him at the door of the room, so I felt he would like to be quite alone with her, but

07:21:45.976 --> 07:21:49.716
he took my arm, and led me in, saying huskily,

07:21:50.456 --> 07:21:56.356
You loved her too, old fellow. She told me all about it, and there was no friend had

07:21:56.356 --> 07:22:02.216
a closer place in her heart than you. I don't know how to thank you for all you had done

07:22:02.216 --> 07:22:04.756
for her. I can't think yet.

07:22:06.336 --> 07:22:12.296
Here, he suddenly broke down, and threw his arms round my shoulders, and laid his head

07:22:12.296 --> 07:22:19.916
on my breast, crying, Oh, Jack, Jack, what shall I do? The whole of life seems gone

07:22:19.916 --> 07:22:25.276
from me all at once, and there is nothing in the wide world for me to live for.

07:22:26.376 --> 07:22:33.436
I comforted him as well as I could. In such cases men do not need much expression. A grip

07:22:33.436 --> 07:22:39.136
of the hand, the tightening of an arm over the shoulder, the sob in unison, are expressions

07:22:39.136 --> 07:22:45.916
of sympathy dear to a man's heart. I stood still and silent till his sobs died away,

07:22:46.236 --> 07:22:51.216
and then I said softly to him, Come and look at her.

07:22:52.396 --> 07:22:59.396
Together we moved over to the bed, and I lifted the lawn from her face. God, how beautiful

07:22:59.396 --> 07:23:06.136
she was! Every hour seemed to be enhancing her loveliness. It frightened and amazed me

07:23:06.136 --> 07:23:12.876
somewhat, and as for Arthur, he felt a trembling, and finally was shaken with doubt as with

07:23:12.876 --> 07:23:22.256
an egu. At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper, Jack, is she really

07:23:22.256 --> 07:23:22.836
dead?

07:23:24.176 --> 07:23:30.836
I assured him sadly that it was so, and went on to suggest, for I felt that such a horrible

07:23:30.836 --> 07:23:36.356
doubt should not have life for a moment longer than I could help, that it often happened

07:23:36.356 --> 07:23:42.496
that after death faces become softened and even resolved into their youthful beauty,

07:23:42.936 --> 07:23:49.456
that this was especially so when death had been preceded by any acute or prolonged suffering.

07:23:49.976 --> 07:23:55.576
I seemed to quite do away with any doubt, and after kneeling beside the couch for a

07:23:55.576 --> 07:24:01.876
while, and looking at her lovingly and long, he turned aside. I told him that this must

07:24:01.876 --> 07:24:08.456
be good-bye, as the coffin had to be prepared, so he went back and took her dead hand and

07:24:08.456 --> 07:24:15.096
his and kissed it, and bent over and kissed her forehead. He came away, fondly looking

07:24:15.096 --> 07:24:21.596
back over his shoulder at her as he came. I left him in the drawing room, and told Van

07:24:21.596 --> 07:24:27.236
Helsing that he had said good-bye, so the later went to the kitchen to tell the undertaker's

07:24:27.236 --> 07:24:33.656
men to proceed with the preparations and to screw up the coffin. When he came out of the

07:24:33.656 --> 07:24:40.996
room again, I told him of Arthur's question, and he replied, I am not surprised. Just now

07:24:40.996 --> 07:24:47.716
I doubted for a moment myself. We all dined together, and I could see that poor Art was

07:24:47.716 --> 07:24:53.896
trying to make the best of things. Van Helsing had been silent all dinner time, but when

07:24:53.896 --> 07:25:02.816
we had lit our cigars, he said, Lord. But Arthur interrupted him. No, no, not that for

07:25:02.816 --> 07:25:08.896
God's sake, not yet at any rate. Forgive me, sir. I did not mean to speak offensively.

07:25:09.856 --> 07:25:17.696
It is only because my loss is so recent. The professor answered very sweetly, I said, I

07:25:17.716 --> 07:25:23.336
only use that name because I was in doubt. I must not call you Mr., and I have grown

07:25:23.336 --> 07:25:27.416
to love you. Yes, my dear boy, to love you as Arthur.

07:25:28.936 --> 07:25:33.116
Arthur held out his hand and took the old man's warmly.

07:25:33.836 --> 07:25:40.376
Call me what you will, he said. I hope I may always have the title of a friend, and let

07:25:40.376 --> 07:25:46.616
me say that I am at a loss for words to thank you for your goodness to my poor dear. He

07:25:46.616 --> 07:25:52.356
paused a moment and went on. I know that she understood your goodness even better than

07:25:52.356 --> 07:25:58.396
I do, and if I was rude, or in any way wanting at the time you acted so, you remember.

07:25:59.136 --> 07:26:07.276
The professor nodded. You must forgive me. He answered with a grave kindness. I know

07:26:07.276 --> 07:26:12.616
it was hard for you to quite trust me then, for to trust such violence needs to understand,

07:26:12.896 --> 07:26:18.896
and I take it that you do not, that you cannot trust me now, for you do not yet understand,

07:26:19.316 --> 07:26:24.236
and there may be more times when I shall want you to trust when you cannot, and may not,

07:26:24.536 --> 07:26:29.556
and must not yet understand, but the time will come when your trust shall be whole and

07:26:29.556 --> 07:26:34.736
complete in me, and when you shall understand as though the sunlight himself shone through.

07:26:35.396 --> 07:26:40.756
Then you shall bless me from the first to last for your own sake, and for the sake of

07:26:40.756 --> 07:26:44.636
others, and for her dear sake to whom I swore to protect.

07:26:46.336 --> 07:26:53.756
And indeed, indeed, sir, said Arthur warmly, I shall in all ways trust you. I know and

07:26:53.756 --> 07:26:59.556
believe you have a very noble heart, and you are Jack's friend, and you were hers. You

07:26:59.556 --> 07:27:00.936
shall do what you like.

07:27:02.476 --> 07:27:08.416
The professor cleared his throat a couple of times, as though about to speak, and finally

07:27:08.416 --> 07:27:11.316
said, May I ask you something now?

07:27:12.436 --> 07:27:12.956
Certainly.

07:27:14.356 --> 07:27:17.436
You know that Mrs. Westenra left you all her property.

07:27:18.856 --> 07:27:22.056
No, poor dear, I never thought of it.

07:27:22.796 --> 07:27:28.096
And as it is all yours, you have a right to deal with it as you will. I want you to give

07:27:28.096 --> 07:27:34.256
me the permission to read all Mrs. Lucy's papers and letters. Believe me, it is no idle

07:27:34.786 --> 07:27:40.656
curiosity. I have a motive of which, be sure, she would have approved. I have them all here.

07:27:40.936 --> 07:27:46.116
I took them before we knew that all was yours, so that no strange hand might touch them,

07:27:46.276 --> 07:27:53.016
no strange eye look through words into her soul. I shall keep them, if I may. Even you

07:27:53.016 --> 07:27:58.476
may not see them yet, but I shall keep you safe. No word shall be lost, and in good time

07:27:58.476 --> 07:28:03.936
I shall give them back to you. It is not a hard thing that I ask, but you will do it,

07:28:03.936 --> 07:28:06.016
will you not, for Lucy's sake?

07:28:07.356 --> 07:28:10.916
Arthur spoke out heartily, like his old self.

07:28:11.596 --> 07:28:17.636
Dr. Van Helsing, you may do what you will. I feel that in saying this I am doing what

07:28:17.636 --> 07:28:23.776
my dear one would have approved. I shall not trouble you with questions till the time comes.

07:28:24.676 --> 07:28:31.156
The old professor stood up as he said solemnly, and you are right. There will be pain for

07:28:31.156 --> 07:28:37.536
us all, but it will not be all pain, nor will this pain be the last. We, and you too,

07:28:37.596 --> 07:28:42.516
you most of all, dear boy, will have to pass through the bitter water before we reach the

07:28:42.516 --> 07:28:48.996
suite. But we must be brave of heart and unselfish, and do our duty, and all will be well.

07:28:50.156 --> 07:28:57.116
I slept on a sofa in Arthur's room that night. Van Helsing did not go to bed at all. He went

07:28:57.116 --> 07:29:02.016
to and fro as if patrolling the house, and was never out of sight of the room where Lucy

07:29:02.016 --> 07:29:09.256
lay in her coffin, strewn with the wild garlic flowers, which sent through the order of lily

07:29:09.256 --> 07:29:14.176
and rose a heavy overpowering smell into the night.

07:29:17.016 --> 07:29:26.636
Nina Harker's Journal, 22 September. In the tray into Exeter, Jonathan, sleeping,

07:29:27.116 --> 07:29:34.816
it seems only yesterday that the last entry was made, and yet how much between then. In

07:29:34.816 --> 07:29:42.436
Whitby and all the world before me, Jonathan away, and no news of him, and now married

07:29:42.436 --> 07:29:51.576
to Jonathan, Jonathan a solicitor, a partner, rich, master of his business, Mr. Hawkins,

07:29:51.576 --> 07:29:59.636
dead and buried, and Jonathan with another attack that may harm him. Someday he may ask

07:29:59.636 --> 07:30:08.336
me about it. Down it all goes. I am rusty in my short hand. See what unexpected prosperity

07:30:08.336 --> 07:30:14.636
does for us. So it may be as well to freshen it up again, with an exercise, anyhow.

07:30:15.336 --> 07:30:22.336
This service was very simple, and very solemn. There were only ourselves and the servants

07:30:22.336 --> 07:30:29.836
there, one or two old friends of his from Exeter, his London agent, and a gentleman

07:30:29.836 --> 07:30:37.136
representing Sir John Paxton, the president of the Incorporated Law Society. Jonathan

07:30:37.136 --> 07:30:43.056
and I stood hand in hand, and we felt that our best and dearest friend was gone from

07:30:43.056 --> 07:30:51.556
us. We came back to town quietly, taking a bus to Hyde Park Corner. Jonathan thought

07:30:51.556 --> 07:30:58.196
it would interest me to go into the row for a while, so we sat down. But there were very

07:30:58.196 --> 07:31:06.236
few people there, and it was sad looking and desolate to see so many empty chairs. It made

07:31:06.236 --> 07:31:14.056
us think of the empty chair at home. So we got up and walked down Piccadilly. Jonathan

07:31:14.056 --> 07:31:20.516
was holding me by the arm, the way he used to, in the old days, before I went to school.

07:31:21.616 --> 07:31:28.496
I felt it very improper, for you can go on for some years teaching etiquette and decorum

07:31:28.496 --> 07:31:35.536
to other girls, without the pedantry of it biting into yourself a bit. But it was Jonathan,

07:31:35.536 --> 07:31:41.416
and he was my husband, and we didn't know anybody who saw us, and we didn't care if

07:31:41.416 --> 07:31:49.316
they did. So on we walked. I was looking at a very beautiful girl, in a big cartwheel

07:31:49.316 --> 07:31:58.316
hat, sitting in a Victoria, outside Galenios, and I felt Jonathan clutch my arm so tight

07:31:58.316 --> 07:32:05.516
that he hurt me, and he said, under his breath, my God, I am all alone, and I don't know

07:32:05.536 --> 07:32:12.476
always anxious about Jonathan, for I fear that some nervous fit may upset him again.

07:32:13.076 --> 07:32:21.356
So I turned to him quickly and asked him what it was that disturbed him. He was very pale,

07:32:21.716 --> 07:32:29.176
and his eyes seemed bulging out as, half in terror and half in amazement, he gazed at

07:32:29.176 --> 07:32:37.756
a tall, thin man, with a beaky nose and black mustache and pointing beard, who was also

07:32:37.756 --> 07:32:44.256
observing the pretty girl. He was looking at her so hard that he did not see either

07:32:44.256 --> 07:32:53.316
of us, and so I had a good view of him. His face was not a good face. It was hard and

07:32:53.316 --> 07:33:01.096
cruel and sensual, and big white teeth that looked all the whiter because his lips were

07:33:01.096 --> 07:33:09.696
so red, were pointed like an animal's. Jonathan kept staring at him, till I was afraid he

07:33:09.696 --> 07:33:17.916
would notice. I feared he might take it ill. He looked so fierce and nasty. I asked Jonathan

07:33:17.916 --> 07:33:24.756
why he was disturbed, and he answered, evidently thinking I knew as much about it as he did.

07:33:25.516 --> 07:33:35.996
Do you see who it is? No, dear, I said. I don't know him. Who is it? His answer seemed

07:33:35.996 --> 07:33:42.736
a shock and thrill me, for it was said as if he did not know that it was me, Mina, to

07:33:42.736 --> 07:33:51.896
whom we were speaking. It is the man himself. The poor dear was evidently terrified at something,

07:33:52.556 --> 07:33:59.096
very greatly terrified. I do believe that if he had not had me to lean on and to support

07:33:59.096 --> 07:34:06.996
him he would have sunk down. He kept staring. A man came out of the shop with a small parcel

07:34:06.996 --> 07:34:15.096
and gave it to the lady, who then drove off. The dark man kept his eyes fixed on her, and

07:34:15.096 --> 07:34:21.676
when the carriage moved up Piccadilly he followed in the same direction and hailed a handsome.

07:34:23.636 --> 07:34:31.616
Jonathan kept looking after him and said, as if to himself, I believe it is the Count,

07:34:31.616 --> 07:34:40.636
but he has grown young. My God, if this be so! Oh, my God, my God! If only I knew! If

07:34:40.636 --> 07:34:48.176
only I knew! He was distressing himself so much that I feared to keep his mind on the

07:34:48.176 --> 07:34:55.456
subject by asking him any questions, so I remained silent. I drew away quietly, and

07:34:55.456 --> 07:35:02.836
he, holding my arm, came easily. We walked a little further, and then went in and sat

07:35:02.836 --> 07:35:09.076
for a while in the green park. It was a hot day for autumn, and there was a comfortable

07:35:09.076 --> 07:35:16.156
seat in a shady place. After a few minutes staring at nothing, Jonathan's eyes closed,

07:35:16.976 --> 07:35:23.936
and he went quickly into his sleep with his head on my shoulder. I thought it was the

07:35:23.936 --> 07:35:31.256
best thing for him, so did not disturb him. In about twenty minutes he woke up and said

07:35:31.256 --> 07:35:38.916
to me quite cheerfully, Why, Mina, have I been asleep? Oh, do forgive me for being so

07:35:38.916 --> 07:35:46.336
rude. Come, and we'll have a cup of tea somewhere. He had evidently forgotten all about the dark

07:35:46.336 --> 07:35:53.016
stranger, as in his illness he had forgotten all that this episode had reminded him of.

07:35:53.936 --> 07:36:01.136
I don't like this lapsing into forgetfulness. It may make or continue some injury to the

07:36:01.136 --> 07:36:08.856
brain. I must not ask him, for fear I shall do more harm than good, but I must somehow

07:36:08.856 --> 07:36:14.796
learn the facts of his journey abroad. The time has come, I fear, when I must open the

07:36:14.796 --> 07:36:21.996
parcel and know what is written. Oh, Jonathan, you will, I know, forgive me if I do wrong,

07:36:21.996 --> 07:36:24.956
but it is for your own dear sake.

07:36:27.376 --> 07:36:35.256
Later, a sad homecoming in every way, the house empty of the dear soul who was so good

07:36:35.256 --> 07:36:44.056
to us, Jonathan still pale and dizzy under a slight relapse of his malady, and now a telegram

07:36:44.056 --> 07:36:48.076
from Van Helsing, whoever he may be.

07:36:49.156 --> 07:36:56.436
You will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the

07:36:56.436 --> 07:37:00.456
day before yesterday. They were both buried today.

07:37:01.956 --> 07:37:12.716
Oh, what a wealth of sorrow in a few words! Poor Mrs. Westenra! Poor Lucy! Gone! Gone!

07:37:12.716 --> 07:37:20.236
Never to return to us! And poor, poor Arthur, to have lost such a sweetness out of his life!

07:37:21.216 --> 07:37:24.116
God help us all to bear our troubles!

07:37:26.836 --> 07:37:30.456
Dr. Seward's Diary, continued.

07:37:32.376 --> 07:37:39.596
22 September. It is all over. Arthur has gone back to Ring, and has taken Quincy Morris

07:37:39.596 --> 07:37:45.796
with him. What a fine fellow is Quincy! I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered

07:37:45.796 --> 07:37:51.356
as much about Lucy's death as any of us, but he bore himself through it like a moral liking.

07:37:52.116 --> 07:37:58.016
If America can go on breeding men like that, she will be a power in the world indeed.

07:37:58.896 --> 07:38:06.836
Van Helsing is lying down, having a rest preparatory to his journey. He goes to Amsterdam tonight,

07:38:06.836 --> 07:38:12.936
but says he will return tomorrow night, that he only wants to make some arrangements, which

07:38:12.936 --> 07:38:19.956
can only be made personally. He is to stop with me then, if he can. He says he has work

07:38:19.956 --> 07:38:26.896
to do in London which may take him some time. Poor old fellow! I fear that the strain of

07:38:26.896 --> 07:38:33.856
the past week has broken down even his iron strength. All the time of the burial he was,

07:38:33.856 --> 07:38:40.756
I could see, putting some terrible restraint on himself. When it was all over, we were

07:38:40.756 --> 07:38:47.376
standing besides Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation

07:38:47.376 --> 07:38:54.656
where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy's veins. I could see Van Helsing's face

07:38:54.656 --> 07:39:01.736
grow white and purple by turns. Arthur was saying he felt since then as if they too had

07:39:01.736 --> 07:39:07.996
been really married, and that she was his wife in the sight of God. None of us said

07:39:07.996 --> 07:39:15.016
a word of the other two operations, and none of us ever shall. Arthur and Quincy went away

07:39:15.016 --> 07:39:21.516
together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here. The moment we were alone in

07:39:21.516 --> 07:39:28.476
the carriage, he gave way to a regular fit of hysterics. He has denied to me since that

07:39:28.476 --> 07:39:34.316
it was hysterics, and insisted that it was only a sense of humour asserting itself under

07:39:34.316 --> 07:39:41.396
very terrible conditions. He laughed till he cried, and I had to draw down the blinds,

07:39:41.556 --> 07:39:48.056
lest anyone should see us and misjudge. And then he cried till he laughed again, and laughed

07:39:48.056 --> 07:39:54.836
and cried together, just as a woman does. I tried to be stern with him, as one is to

07:39:54.836 --> 07:40:00.676
a woman under the circumstances, but it had no effect. Men and women are so different

07:40:00.676 --> 07:40:07.136
in manifestations of nervous strength or weakness. Then when his face grew grave and

07:40:07.136 --> 07:40:14.656
stern again, I asked him why his mirth, and why at such a time. His reply was in a way

07:40:14.656 --> 07:40:22.616
characteristic of him, for it was logical and forceful and mysterious. He said, Ah,

07:40:22.616 --> 07:40:29.876
you don't comprehend, friend John. Do not think that I am not sad, though I laugh. See,

07:40:29.876 --> 07:40:35.056
I have cried even when the laugh did choke me. But no more think that I am sorry when

07:40:35.056 --> 07:40:41.876
I cry, for the laugh he come just the same. Keep it always with you, that laughter who

07:40:41.876 --> 07:40:49.196
knock at your door and say, May I come in? It is not true laughter. No, he is a king,

07:40:49.196 --> 07:40:55.616
and he come when and how he like. He ask no person, he choose no time of suitability.

07:40:56.116 --> 07:41:03.536
He say I am here. Behold an example I grieve my heart out, for that so young sweet girl.

07:41:04.096 --> 07:41:11.116
I give my blood for her, though I am old and worn. I give my time, my skill, my sleep.

07:41:11.576 --> 07:41:18.936
I let my other sufferers want that she may have it all. And yet I can laugh at her very

07:41:18.936 --> 07:41:25.136
grave, laugh when the clay from the spade of the sexton drop upon her coffin and say,

07:41:25.276 --> 07:41:33.596
Thud, thud, to my heart, till it send back the blood from my cheek. My heart bleed for

07:41:33.596 --> 07:41:40.376
that poor boy, that dear boy, so of an age of mine own boy had I been so blessed that

07:41:40.376 --> 07:41:48.916
he live, and with his hair and eyes the same. There, you know now why I love you, friend.

07:41:48.936 --> 07:41:54.016
I love him so. And yet when he say things that touch my husband heart to the quick,

07:41:54.556 --> 07:42:01.196
and make my father heart yearn to him as to no other man, not even you, friend John, for

07:42:01.196 --> 07:42:07.796
we are more level in experiences than father and son. Yet even at such a moment, king laugh,

07:42:07.836 --> 07:42:14.156
he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, Here I am, here I am, till the blood come

07:42:14.156 --> 07:42:20.276
dance back and bring some of the sunshine that he carry with him to my cheek. Oh friend

07:42:20.276 --> 07:42:26.616
John, it is a strange world, a sad world, a world full of miseries and woes and troubles.

07:42:27.196 --> 07:42:33.996
And yet when king laugh come, he make them all dance to the tune he play. Bleeding hearts

07:42:33.996 --> 07:42:39.676
and dry bones of the churchyard and tears that burn as they fall, all dance together

07:42:39.676 --> 07:42:45.576
to the music that he make with his smileless mouth of him. And believe me friend John,

07:42:45.756 --> 07:42:52.716
that he is good to come and kind. Ah, we men and women are like ropes drawn tight with

07:42:52.716 --> 07:42:59.096
strain that pull us different ways. Then tears come and like the rain on the ropes they brace

07:42:59.096 --> 07:43:06.436
us up, until perhaps the strain become too great and we break. But king laugh he come

07:43:06.436 --> 07:43:11.796
like the sunshine and he ease off the strain again and we bear to go on with our labor,

07:43:12.276 --> 07:43:19.816
what it may be. I did not like to wound him by pretending not to see his idea. But as

07:43:19.816 --> 07:43:25.296
I did not yet understand the cause of his laughter, I asked him. As he answered me his

07:43:25.296 --> 07:43:33.636
face grew stern and he said in quite a different tone, Oh, it was the grim irony of it all,

07:43:33.636 --> 07:43:40.916
this so lovely lady, garlanded with flowers that looked so fair as life, till one by one

07:43:40.916 --> 07:43:47.556
we wondered if she were truly dead. She laid in that so fine marble house, in that lonely

07:43:47.556 --> 07:43:54.016
churchyard where rests so many of her kin, lay there with the mother who loved her and

07:43:54.016 --> 07:44:02.316
whom she loved, and that sacred bell going toll, toll, toll, so sad and slow, and those

07:44:02.316 --> 07:44:08.476
holy men with the white garments of the angel, pretending to read books, and yet all the

07:44:08.476 --> 07:44:16.096
time their eyes never on the page, and all of us with the bowed head, and for what? She

07:44:16.096 --> 07:44:25.016
is dead, so is it not? Well, for the life of me, professor, I said, I can't see anything

07:44:25.016 --> 07:44:31.796
to laugh at and all that. Why, your expression makes it a harder puzzle than before. But

07:44:31.796 --> 07:44:38.716
even if the burial service was comic, what about poor art and his trouble? Why, his heart

07:44:38.716 --> 07:44:46.436
was simply breaking. Just so, said he not that the transfusion of his blood to her veins

07:44:46.436 --> 07:44:55.776
had made her truly his bride. Yes, and it was a sweet and comforting idea for him. Quite

07:44:55.776 --> 07:45:04.036
so. But there was a difficulty, friend John. If so that, then what about the others? Ho,

07:45:04.056 --> 07:45:12.516
ho. Then this so sweet maid is a polyandrist, and me, with my poor wife dead to me, but

07:45:12.516 --> 07:45:19.556
alive by church's law, though no wits, all gone, even I, who am faithful husband to his

07:45:19.556 --> 07:45:28.636
now no wife, am bigamist. I don't see where the joke comes in there either, I said, and

07:45:28.636 --> 07:45:34.216
I did not feel particularly pleased with him for saying such things. He laid his hand on

07:45:34.216 --> 07:45:41.856
my arm and said, Friend John, forgive me if I pain. I showed not my feelings to others

07:45:41.856 --> 07:45:47.936
when it would wound, but only to you, my old friend, whom I can trust. If you could have

07:45:47.936 --> 07:45:53.156
looked into my heart, then when I want to laugh, if you could have done so when the

07:45:53.156 --> 07:45:59.456
laughed arrived, if you could do so now, when King Laugh have packed up his crown and all

07:45:59.456 --> 07:46:06.476
that is to him, for he go far, far from me, and for a long, long time, maybe you would,

07:46:06.696 --> 07:46:15.756
perhaps, pity me the most of all. I was touched by the tenderness of his tone and asked why.

07:46:16.646 --> 07:46:26.456
Because I know. And now we are all scattered, and for many a long day loneliness will sit

07:46:26.456 --> 07:46:35.496
over our roofs with brooding wings. Lucy lies in the tomb of her kin, a lordly death house

07:46:35.496 --> 07:46:42.756
in a lonely churchyard, away from teeming London, where the air is fresh and the sun

07:46:42.756 --> 07:46:51.856
rises over Hampstead Hill, and where wildflowers grow of their own accord. So I can finish

07:46:51.856 --> 07:47:00.496
this diary, and God only knows if I shall ever begin another. If I do, or if I even

07:47:00.496 --> 07:47:07.636
open this again, it will be to deal with different people and different themes, for here at the

07:47:07.636 --> 07:47:13.516
end, where the romance of my life is told, ere I go back to take up the thread of my

07:47:13.516 --> 07:47:19.416
life work, I say sadly and without hope, fini.

07:47:21.916 --> 07:47:30.856
The Westminster Gazette. 25 September. A Hampstead Mystery. The neighborhood of Hampstead is

07:47:30.856 --> 07:47:36.556
just at present, exercised with a series of events which seem to run on lines parallel

07:47:36.556 --> 07:47:43.696
to those of what was known to the writers of headlines as The Kensington Horror, or

07:47:43.696 --> 07:47:51.816
The Stabbing Woman, or The Woman in Black. During the past two or three days, several

07:47:51.816 --> 07:47:57.736
cases have occurred of young children straying from home or neglecting to return from their

07:47:57.736 --> 07:48:03.336
playing on the heath. In all these cases the children were too young to give any properly

07:48:03.336 --> 07:48:09.036
intelligible account of themselves, but the consensus of their excuses is that they had

07:48:09.036 --> 07:48:14.516
been with a blooper lady. It has always been late in the evening when they have been missed,

07:48:14.896 --> 07:48:20.136
and on two occasions the children had not been found until early in the following morning.

07:48:20.636 --> 07:48:26.376
It is generally supposed in the neighborhood that, as the first child missed gave his reason

07:48:26.376 --> 07:48:32.096
for being away that a blooper lady had asked him to come for a walk, the others had picked

07:48:32.096 --> 07:48:38.276
up the phrase and used it as occasion served. This is the more natural as the favorite game

07:48:38.276 --> 07:48:44.696
of the little ones at present is luring each other away by wiles. A correspondent writes

07:48:44.696 --> 07:48:50.736
us that to see some of the tiny tots pretending to be the blooper lady is supremely funny.

07:48:51.276 --> 07:48:56.636
Some of our characteristics might, he says, take a lesson in the irony of grotesque by

07:48:56.636 --> 07:49:01.736
comparing the reality in the picture. It is only in accordance with general principles

07:49:01.736 --> 07:49:07.896
of human nature that the blooper lady should be the popular role at these alfresco performances.

07:49:08.616 --> 07:49:14.556
Our correspondent naively says that even Ellen Terry could not be so winningly attractive as

07:49:14.556 --> 07:49:20.576
some of these grubby-faced little children pretend and even imagine themselves to be.

07:49:21.276 --> 07:49:26.516
There is, however, possibly a serious side to the question, for some of the children,

07:49:26.516 --> 07:49:31.636
indeed all who have been missed at night, have been slightly torn or wounded in the

07:49:31.636 --> 07:49:38.296
throat. The wounds seem such as might be made by a rat or a small dog, and although of not

07:49:38.296 --> 07:49:43.216
much importance individually, would tend to show that whatever animal inflicts them has

07:49:43.216 --> 07:49:47.876
a system or method of its own. The police of the division have been instructed to keep

07:49:47.876 --> 07:49:54.576
a sharp lookout for straying children, especially when very young, in and around Hampstead Heath,

07:49:54.576 --> 07:49:57.936
and for any stray dog which may be about.

07:50:00.616 --> 07:50:09.536
The Westminster Gazette, 25 September. Extra Special. The Hampstead Horror. Another child

07:50:09.536 --> 07:50:16.496
injured. The blooper lady. We have just received intelligence that another child missed last

07:50:16.496 --> 07:50:22.176
night was only discovered late in the morning under a firs bush at the Shooter's Hill side

07:50:22.176 --> 07:50:28.096
of Hampstead Heath, which is perhaps less frequented than the other parts. It has the

07:50:28.096 --> 07:50:34.176
same tiny wound in the throat as has been noticed in other cases. It was terribly weak

07:50:34.176 --> 07:50:40.976
and looked quite emaciated, yet too impartially restored had the common story to tell of being

07:50:40.976 --> 07:50:43.616
lured away by the blooper lady.

07:50:52.176 --> 07:51:04.416
Recorded by Marlo Diane. April 21-26, 2006. Piscid West, Prince Edward Island.

07:51:37.204 --> 07:51:45.364
23 September. Jonathan is better after a bad night. I am so glad that he has plenty of work to do,

07:51:45.404 --> 07:51:51.824
for that keeps his mind off the terrible things, and oh, I am rejoiced that he is not now weighed

07:51:51.824 --> 07:51:58.724
down with the responsibility of his new position. I knew he would be true to himself, and now,

07:51:58.924 --> 07:52:04.764
how proud I am to see my Jonathan rising to the height of his advancement, and keeping pace in

07:52:04.764 --> 07:52:11.444
ways with the duties that come upon him. He will be away all day till late, for he said he could

07:52:11.444 --> 07:52:20.724
not lunch at home. My household work is done, so I shall take his foreign journal and lock myself

07:52:20.724 --> 07:52:30.644
up in my room and read it. 24 September. I hadn't the heart to write last night that

07:52:30.644 --> 07:52:39.124
terrible record of Jonathan's upset me so. Poor dear, how he must have suffered, whether it be

07:52:39.124 --> 07:52:47.304
true or only imagination. I wonder if there is any truth in it at all. Did he get his brain fever

07:52:47.304 --> 07:52:54.484
and then write all those terrible things, or had he some cause for it all? I suppose I shall never

07:52:54.484 --> 07:53:01.284
know, for I dare not open the subject to him. And yet, that man we saw yesterday,

07:53:01.724 --> 07:53:09.024
he seemed quite certain of him. Poor fellow. I suppose it was a funeral upset him and sent

07:53:09.024 --> 07:53:16.364
his mind back on some train of thought. He believes it all himself. I remember how on our

07:53:16.364 --> 07:53:23.204
wedding day he said, unless some solemn duty come upon me to go back to the bitter hours,

07:53:23.204 --> 07:53:30.264
asleep or awake, mad or sane. There seems to be through it all some thread of continuity.

07:53:30.924 --> 07:53:37.744
That fearful count was coming to London. If it should be, and he came to London with its

07:53:37.744 --> 07:53:44.844
teeming millions, there may be a solemn duty, and if it come, we must not shrink from it.

07:53:45.304 --> 07:53:52.464
I shall be prepared. I shall get my typewriter this very hour and begin transcribing. Then we

07:53:52.464 --> 07:54:00.864
shall be ready for other eyes, if required. And if it be wanted then, perhaps, if I am ready,

07:54:01.104 --> 07:54:06.324
poor Jonathan may not be upset, for I can speak for him and never let him be troubled or worried

07:54:06.324 --> 07:54:12.684
with it at all. If ever Jonathan quite gets over the nervousness he may want to tell me of it all,

07:54:13.204 --> 07:54:18.684
and I can ask him questions and find out things, and see how I may comfort him.

07:54:19.844 --> 07:54:26.484
Letter, Van Helsing to Mrs. Harker. 24 September. Confidence.

07:54:27.344 --> 07:54:33.684
Dear Madam, I pray you to pardon my writing, in that I am so far friend as that I sent you

07:54:33.684 --> 07:54:40.724
sad news of Miss Lucy Westenra's death. By the kindness of Lord Godalming, I am empowered to

07:54:40.724 --> 07:54:46.644
read her letters and papers, for I am deeply concerned about certain matters vitally important.

07:54:47.324 --> 07:54:52.884
In them I find some letters from you, which show how great friends you were and how you love her.

07:54:53.424 --> 07:55:01.264
Oh, Madam Mina, by that love, I implore you, help me. It is for others good that I ask

07:55:01.264 --> 07:55:07.764
to redress great wrong and to lift much trouble and terrible troubles that may be more great than

07:55:07.764 --> 07:55:14.464
you can know. May it be that I see you? You can trust me. I am friend of Dr. John Seward

07:55:14.464 --> 07:55:21.624
and of Lord Godalming, that was Arthur of Miss Lucy. I must keep it private for the present from

07:55:21.624 --> 07:55:26.684
all. I should come to Exeter to see you at once if you tell me I am privileged to come,

07:55:26.884 --> 07:55:32.904
and where and when. I implore your pardon, Madam. I have read your letters to poor Lucy

07:55:32.904 --> 07:55:39.104
and know how good you are and how your husband suffer. So I pray you, if it may be,

07:55:39.104 --> 07:55:46.384
enlighten him not, lest it may harm. Again your pardon and forgive me. Van Helsing.

07:55:48.904 --> 07:55:55.884
Telegram Mrs. Harker to Van Helsing. 25 September. Come today by quarter past 10 train,

07:55:55.984 --> 07:56:03.964
if you can catch it. Can see you any time you call. Wilhelmina Harker. Mina Harker's Journal.

07:56:03.964 --> 07:56:09.964
25 September. I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit

07:56:09.964 --> 07:56:16.344
of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan's sad experience

07:56:16.884 --> 07:56:21.584
and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness he can tell me all about her.

07:56:22.224 --> 07:56:26.964
That is the reason of his coming. It is concerning Lucy and her sleepwalking

07:56:26.964 --> 07:56:33.704
and not about Jonathan. Then I shall never know the real truth now. How silly I am.

07:56:33.964 --> 07:56:39.124
That awful journal gets hold of my imagination and tinges everything with something of its own

07:56:39.124 --> 07:56:45.984
colour. Of course it is about Lucy. That habit came back to the poor dear and that awful night

07:56:45.984 --> 07:56:51.204
on the cliff must have made her ill. I had almost forgotten in my own affairs how ill she was

07:56:51.204 --> 07:56:56.124
afterwards. She must have told him of her sleepwalking adventure on the cliff and that

07:56:56.124 --> 07:57:02.084
I knew all about it and now he wants me to tell him what I know so that he may understand.

07:57:02.784 --> 07:57:07.124
I hope I did right in not saying anything of it to Mrs. Westenra.

07:57:07.824 --> 07:57:12.564
I should never forgive myself if any act of mine were it even a negative one

07:57:12.564 --> 07:57:19.184
brought harm on poor dear Lucy. I hope too Dr. Van Helsing will not blame me.

07:57:20.004 --> 07:57:25.684
I have had so much trouble and anxiety of late that I feel I cannot bear more just at present.

07:57:27.504 --> 07:57:32.984
I suppose a cry does us all good at times. It clears the air as other rain does.

07:57:33.904 --> 07:57:38.284
Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me and then Jonathan went away this

07:57:38.284 --> 07:57:43.104
morning to stay away from me a whole day and night, the first time we have been parted since

07:57:43.104 --> 07:57:49.044
our marriage. I do hope the dear fellow will take care of himself and that nothing will occur to

07:57:49.044 --> 07:57:55.564
him. It is two o'clock and the doctor will be here soon now. I shall say nothing of

07:57:55.564 --> 07:58:01.264
Jonathan's journal unless he asks me. I am so glad I have typewritten out my own journal

07:58:01.264 --> 07:58:05.644
so that in case he asks about Lucy I can hand it to him. It will save much questioning.

07:58:08.044 --> 07:58:15.024
Later he has come and gone. Oh what a strange meeting and how it all makes my head whirl round.

07:58:15.024 --> 07:58:23.324
I feel like one in a dream. Can it be all possible or even a part of it? If I had not read

07:58:23.324 --> 07:58:31.564
Jonathan's journal first I should never have accepted even a possibility. Poor poor dear

07:58:31.564 --> 07:58:39.424
Jonathan. How he must have suffered. Please the good God all this may not upset him again.

07:58:39.424 --> 07:58:45.904
I shall try to save him from it but it may be even a consolation and a help to him terrible

07:58:45.904 --> 07:58:53.624
though it be and awful in its consequences to know for certain that his eyes and ears and brain did

07:58:53.624 --> 07:59:00.464
not deceive him and that it is all true. It may be that it is the doubt which haunts him

07:59:00.824 --> 07:59:06.064
and that when the doubt is removed no matter which waking or dreaming may prove the truth

07:59:06.064 --> 07:59:09.924
he will be more satisfied and better able to bear the shock.

07:59:10.784 --> 07:59:15.684
Dr. Van Helsing must be a good man as well as a clever one if he is Arthur's friend and Dr.

07:59:16.264 --> 07:59:21.784
Seward's and if they brought him all the way from Holland to look after Lucy. I feel from having

07:59:21.784 --> 07:59:29.904
seen him that he is good and kind and of a noble nature. When he comes tomorrow I shall ask him

07:59:29.904 --> 07:59:36.124
Jonathan and then please God all this sorrow and anxiety may lead to a good end.

07:59:37.924 --> 07:59:41.904
I used to think I would like to practice interviewing. Jonathan's friend on the

07:59:41.904 --> 07:59:46.824
Exeter News told him that memory is everything in such work that you must be able to put down

07:59:46.824 --> 07:59:51.904
exactly almost every word spoken even if you had to refine some of it afterwards.

07:59:52.624 --> 07:59:57.504
Here was a rare interview. I shall try to record it verbatim.

07:59:58.984 --> 08:00:06.004
It was half past two o'clock when the knock came. I took my courage and waited. In a few minutes

08:00:06.004 --> 08:00:14.124
Mary opened the door and announced Dr. Van Helsing. I rose and bowed and he came towards me, a man of

08:00:14.124 --> 08:00:20.004
medium weight, strongly built, with his shoulders set back over a broad deep chest and a neck well

08:00:20.004 --> 08:00:25.744
advanced on the trunk as the head is on the neck. The poise of the head strikes me at once as

08:00:25.744 --> 08:00:33.244
indicative of thought and power. The head is noble, well-sized, broad and large behind the ears.

08:00:33.964 --> 08:00:40.684
The face clean-shaven shows a hard square chin, a large resolute mobile mouth, a good-sized nose

08:00:40.684 --> 08:00:46.544
rather straight but with quick sensitive nostrils that seem to broaden as the big bushy brows come

08:00:46.544 --> 08:00:53.424
down and the mouth tightens. The forehead is broad and fine, rising at first almost straight

08:00:53.424 --> 08:00:58.844
and then sloping back over two bumps or ridges wide apart, such a forehead that the reddish hair

08:00:58.844 --> 08:01:06.744
cannot possibly tumble over it but falls naturally back and to the sides. Big dark blue eyes were set

08:01:06.744 --> 08:01:14.924
widely apart and are quick and tender or stern with the man's moods. He said to me, Mrs. Harker is it

08:01:14.924 --> 08:01:23.764
not? I bowed ascent. That was Miss Mina Murray? Again I assented. It is Mina Murray that I came

08:01:23.764 --> 08:01:30.724
to see that was friend of that poor dear child Lucy Westenra. Madam Mina, it is on account of

08:01:30.724 --> 08:01:38.624
the dead that I come. Sir, I said, you could have no better claim on me than that you were a friend

08:01:38.624 --> 08:01:44.744
and helper of Lucy Westenra and I held out my hand. He took it and said tenderly,

08:01:45.984 --> 08:01:53.644
oh Madam Mina, I knew that the friend of that poor little girl must be good but I had yet to learn.

08:01:54.684 --> 08:02:00.864
He finished his speech with a courtly bow. I asked him what it was that he wanted to see me about

08:02:00.864 --> 08:02:07.564
so he at once began, I have read your letters to Miss Lucy, forgive me but I had to begin to inquire

08:02:07.564 --> 08:02:14.784
somewhere and there was none to ask. I know that you were with her at Whitby. She sometimes kept a

08:02:14.784 --> 08:02:21.104
diary, you need not look surprised Madam Mina. It was begun after you had left and was an imitation

08:02:21.104 --> 08:02:27.564
of you and in that diary she traces by inference certain things to a sleepwalking in which she

08:02:27.564 --> 08:02:35.704
puts down that you saved her. In great perplexity then I come to you and ask you out of your so much

08:02:35.704 --> 08:02:42.904
kindness to tell me all of it that you can remember. I can tell you, I think, Dr. Van Helsing, all about

08:02:42.904 --> 08:02:50.144
it. Ah, then you have good memory for facts, for details. It is not always so with young ladies.

08:02:51.144 --> 08:02:57.764
No, doctor, but I wrote it all down at the time. I can show it to you if you like. Oh Madam Mina,

08:02:57.804 --> 08:03:04.004
I will be grateful. You will do me much favor. I could not resist the temptation of mystifying him

08:03:04.004 --> 08:03:10.584
a bit. I suppose it is some taste of the original apple that remains still in our mouths. So I handed

08:03:10.584 --> 08:03:19.184
him the shorthand diary. He took it with a grateful bow and said, may I read it? If you wish. I answered

08:03:19.184 --> 08:03:26.164
as demurely as I could. He opened it and for an instant his face fell. Then he stood up and bowed.

08:03:27.024 --> 08:03:34.724
Oh, you so clever woman, he said. I knew long that Mr. Jonathan was a man of much thankfulness,

08:03:34.784 --> 08:03:41.804
but see, his wife have all the good things. And will you not so much honor me, and so help me,

08:03:42.104 --> 08:03:47.744
as to read it for me, alas, I know not the shorthand. By this time my little joke was over

08:03:47.744 --> 08:03:53.624
and I was almost ashamed, so I took the typewritten copy from my work basket and handed it to him.

08:03:54.284 --> 08:03:59.844
Forgive me, I said. I could not help it, but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you

08:03:59.844 --> 08:04:04.984
wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait. Not on my account, but because I know your

08:04:04.984 --> 08:04:11.944
time must be precious. I have written it out on the typewriter for you. He took it and his eyes

08:04:11.944 --> 08:04:19.324
glistened. You are so good, he said. And may I read it now? I may want to ask you some things when

08:04:19.324 --> 08:04:26.204
I have read. By all means, I said. Read it over whilst I order lunch, and then you can ask me

08:04:26.204 --> 08:04:31.884
questions whilst we eat. He bowed, and settled himself in a chair with his back to the light,

08:04:32.384 --> 08:04:37.404
and became so absorbed in the papers whilst I went to see after lunch chiefly in order that he might

08:04:37.404 --> 08:04:43.624
not be disturbed. When I came back I found him walking hurriedly up and down the room, his face

08:04:43.624 --> 08:04:49.444
all ablaze with excitement. He rushed up to me and took me by both hands. Oh, Madam Mina, he said.

08:04:49.444 --> 08:04:56.804
How can I say what I owe you? This paper is as sunshine. It opens the gate to me. I am dazed,

08:04:57.124 --> 08:05:04.444
I am dazzled with so much light, and yet clouds roll in behind the light every time. But that you

08:05:04.444 --> 08:05:12.564
do not, cannot comprehend. Oh, but I am grateful to you, you so clever woman. Madam, he said this

08:05:12.564 --> 08:05:19.464
very solemnly. If ever Abraham Van Helsing can do anything for you or yours, I trust you will let me

08:05:19.464 --> 08:05:25.704
know. It will be pleasure and delight if I may serve you as a friend, as a friend. But all I have

08:05:25.704 --> 08:05:33.464
ever learned, all I can ever do, shall be for you and those you love. There are darknesses in life,

08:05:33.704 --> 08:05:40.644
and there are lights. You are one of the lights. You will have a happy life and a good life,

08:05:40.644 --> 08:05:47.904
and your husband will be blessed in you. But Doctor, you praise me too much. You do not know me,

08:05:48.304 --> 08:05:54.944
not know you, I who am old and who have studied all my life men and women. I who have made my

08:05:54.944 --> 08:06:00.644
specialty the brain and all that belongs to him and all that follow from him. And I have read your

08:06:00.644 --> 08:06:06.124
diary that you have so goodly written for me and which breathes out truth in every line.

08:06:06.924 --> 08:06:14.464
I who have read your so sweet letter to poor Lucy of your marriage and your trust, not know you.

08:06:15.124 --> 08:06:23.404
Oh, Madam Mina, good women tell all their lives, and by day and by hour and by minute,

08:06:24.004 --> 08:06:30.904
such things that angels can read. And we men who wish to know have in us something of angel's eyes.

08:06:30.904 --> 08:06:37.784
Your husband is noble nature, and you are noble too, for you trust. And trust cannot be where

08:06:37.784 --> 08:06:47.204
there is mean nature. And your husband? Tell me of him. Is he quite well? Is all that fever gone,

08:06:47.364 --> 08:06:54.924
and is he strong and hearty? I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said,

08:06:55.524 --> 08:07:02.924
He was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins' death. He interrupted,

08:07:03.044 --> 08:07:10.944
Oh, yes, I know, I know. I have read your last two letters. I went on, I suppose this upset him,

08:07:11.084 --> 08:07:18.504
for when we were in town on Thursday last, he had a sort of shock. A shock? And after brain fever

08:07:18.504 --> 08:07:23.664
so soon, that is not good. What kind of shock was it? He thought he saw someone who recalled

08:07:23.664 --> 08:07:29.084
something terrible, something which led to his brain fever. And here the whole thing seemed to

08:07:29.084 --> 08:07:34.764
overwhelm me in a rush, the pity for Jonathan, the horror which he experienced, the whole fearful

08:07:34.764 --> 08:07:41.704
mystery of his diary, and the fear that has been brooding over me ever since all came in a tumult.

08:07:42.384 --> 08:07:48.204
I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him and implored

08:07:48.204 --> 08:07:55.424
him to make my husband well again. He took my hands and raised me up and made me sit on the sofa

08:07:55.424 --> 08:08:02.944
and sat by me. He held my hand in his and said to me with, Oh, such infinite sweetness.

08:08:04.604 --> 08:08:11.944
My life is a barren and lonely one, so full of work that I have not had much time for friendships.

08:08:12.464 --> 08:08:19.064
But since I have been summoned to here by my friend John Seward, I have known so many good people

08:08:19.064 --> 08:08:26.624
and seen such nobility that I feel more than ever. And it has grown with my advancing years

08:08:27.144 --> 08:08:34.004
the loneliness of my life. Believe me then that I come here full of respect for you

08:08:34.324 --> 08:08:41.624
and you have given me hope. Hope not in what I am seeking of, but that there are good women

08:08:41.624 --> 08:08:49.144
still left to make life happy. Good women whose lives and whose truths may make good lesson for

08:08:49.144 --> 08:08:57.284
the children that are to be. I am glad, glad that I may be of some use to you. For if your husband

08:08:57.284 --> 08:09:05.764
suffer, he suffer within the range of my study and experience. I promise you that I will gladly do

08:09:05.764 --> 08:09:13.624
all for him that I can, all to make his life strong and manly and your life a happy one.

08:09:14.024 --> 08:09:20.764
Now you must eat. You are overwrought and perhaps overanxious. Husband Jonathan would not like to

08:09:20.764 --> 08:09:28.704
see you so pale and what he like not where he love is not to his good. Therefore for his sake

08:09:28.704 --> 08:09:36.564
you must eat and smile. You have told me about Lucy and so now we shall not speak of it

08:09:36.564 --> 08:09:43.164
lest it distress. I shall stay in Exeter tonight for I want to think much over what you have told me

08:09:43.664 --> 08:09:51.484
and when I have thought I will ask you questions if I may. And then too you will tell me of husband

08:09:51.484 --> 08:09:59.104
Jonathan's trouble so far as you can but not yet. You must eat now. Afterwards you shall tell me

08:09:59.104 --> 08:10:07.744
all. After lunch when we went back to the drawing room he said to me, at now tell me all about him.

08:10:09.164 --> 08:10:15.484
When it came to speaking to this great learned man I began to fear that he would think me a weak

08:10:15.484 --> 08:10:25.464
fool and Jonathan a madman. That journal is all so strange and I hesitated to go on but he was so

08:10:25.464 --> 08:10:35.224
sweet and kind and he had promised to help and I trusted him. So I said, Dr Van Helsing what I have

08:10:35.224 --> 08:10:41.184
to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband. I have been since yesterday

08:10:41.184 --> 08:10:48.064
in a sort of fever of doubt. You must be kind to me and not think me foolish that I have even half

08:10:48.064 --> 08:10:54.884
believed some very strange things. He reassured me by his manner as well as his words when he said,

08:10:54.964 --> 08:11:01.224
oh my dear if you only know how strange is the matter regarding which I am here it is you who

08:11:01.224 --> 08:11:07.464
would laugh. I have learned not to think little of anyone's belief no matter how strange it may be.

08:11:07.464 --> 08:11:14.064
I have tried to keep an open mind and it is not the ordinary things of life that could close it

08:11:14.064 --> 08:11:20.864
but the strange things the extraordinary things the things that make one doubt if they be mad or

08:11:20.864 --> 08:11:29.904
sane. Thank you thank you a thousand times you have taken a weight off my mind. If you will let me

08:11:29.904 --> 08:11:35.424
I shall give you a paper to read. It is long but I have typewritten it out. It will tell you my

08:11:35.424 --> 08:11:41.424
and Jonathan's. It is the copy of his journal when abroad and all that happened. I dare not

08:11:41.424 --> 08:11:47.724
say anything of it. You will read it for yourself and judge and then when I see you perhaps you will

08:11:47.724 --> 08:11:55.464
be very kind and tell me what you think. I promise he said as I gave him the papers I shall in the

08:11:55.464 --> 08:12:01.764
morning as soon as I can come to see you and your husband if I may. Jonathan will be here at half

08:12:01.764 --> 08:12:06.484
past eleven and you must come to lunch with us and see him then. You could catch the quick

08:12:06.484 --> 08:12:11.224
three thirty four train which will leave you at Paddington before eight. He was surprised

08:12:11.224 --> 08:12:16.024
at my knowledge of the trains off hand but he does not know that I have made up all the trains

08:12:16.024 --> 08:12:21.844
to and from Exeter so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry. So he took the papers with

08:12:21.844 --> 08:12:28.884
him and went away and I sit here thinking, thinking I don't know what.

08:12:30.724 --> 08:12:36.704
Letter by hand, Van Helsing to Mrs. Harker. 25 September, six o'clock. Dear Madame Mina,

08:12:36.904 --> 08:12:42.624
I have read your husband's so wonderful diary. You may sleep without doubt. Strange and terrible

08:12:42.624 --> 08:12:49.504
as it is, it is true. I will pledge my life on it. It may be worse for others but for him and you

08:12:49.504 --> 08:12:55.464
there is no dread. He is a noble fellow and let me tell you from experience of men that one who

08:12:55.464 --> 08:13:00.884
would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room, I and going a second time,

08:13:01.164 --> 08:13:07.584
is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock. His brain and his heart are all right. This I

08:13:07.584 --> 08:13:12.844
swear before I have even seen him so be at rest. I shall have much to ask him of other things.

08:13:13.404 --> 08:13:19.384
I am blessed that today I come to see you for I have learned all at once so much that again I

08:13:19.384 --> 08:13:26.664
dazzled, dazzled more than ever and I must think. Yours the most faithful, Abraham Van Helsing.

08:13:29.264 --> 08:13:36.844
Letter, Mrs. Harker to Van Helsing. 25 September, 6.30 p.m. My dear Dr. Van Helsing,

08:13:37.364 --> 08:13:41.924
a thousand thanks for your kind letter which has taken a great weight off my mind.

08:13:41.924 --> 08:13:49.984
And yet if it be true what terrible things there are in the world and what an awful thing if that

08:13:49.984 --> 08:14:00.104
man, that monster be really in London, I fear to think. I have this moment whilst writing had a

08:14:00.104 --> 08:14:05.824
letter from Jonathan saying that he leaves by the 6.25 tonight from Launston and will be here at

08:14:05.824 --> 08:14:12.444
10.18 so that I shall have no fear tonight. Will you therefore instead of lunching with us

08:14:12.444 --> 08:14:16.224
please come to breakfast at eight o'clock if this be not too early for you?

08:14:16.744 --> 08:14:22.284
You can get away if you are in a hurry by the 10.30 train which will bring you to Paddington by 2.35.

08:14:22.724 --> 08:14:27.564
Do not answer this as I shall take it that if I do not hear you will come to breakfast.

08:14:27.944 --> 08:14:32.624
Believe me, your faithful and grateful friend, Mina Harker.

08:14:33.504 --> 08:14:34.024
26 September.

08:14:34.484 --> 08:14:40.184
Jonathan Harker's Journal. 26 September. I thought never to write in this diary again,

08:14:40.324 --> 08:14:46.164
but the time has come. When I got home last night Mina had supper ready, and when we had supped she

08:14:46.164 --> 08:14:51.504
told me of Van Helsing's visit and of her having given him the two diaries copied out, and of how

08:14:51.504 --> 08:14:57.784
anxious she has been about me. She showed me in the doctor's letter that all I wrote down was true.

08:14:58.574 --> 08:15:04.124
It seems to have made a new man of me. It was the doubt as to the reality of the whole thing

08:15:04.124 --> 08:15:10.784
that knocked me over. I felt impotent and in the dark and distrustful. But now that I know,

08:15:11.324 --> 08:15:17.844
I am not afraid, even of the count. He has succeeded after all then in his design in

08:15:17.844 --> 08:15:25.844
getting to London, and it was he I saw. He has got younger, and how? Van Helsing is the man to

08:15:25.844 --> 08:15:32.044
mask him and hunt him out if he is anything like what Mina says. We sat late and talked it over.

08:15:32.424 --> 08:15:36.444
Mina is dressing, and I shall call at the hotel in a few minutes and bring him over.

08:15:37.564 --> 08:15:43.324
He was, I think, surprised to see me when I came into the room where he was and introduced myself.

08:15:43.664 --> 08:15:49.264
He took me by the shoulder and turned my face round to the light and said, after a sharp scrutiny,

08:15:49.904 --> 08:15:56.564
but Madame Mina told me you were ill, that you had had a shock. It was so funny to hear my wife

08:15:56.564 --> 08:16:04.964
called Madame Mina by this kindly strong-faced old man. I smiled and said, I was ill, I have had a

08:16:04.964 --> 08:16:12.584
shock, but you have cured me already. And how? By your letter to Mina last night. I was in doubt,

08:16:12.644 --> 08:16:18.144
and then everything took a hue of unreality, and I did not know what to trust, even the evidence of

08:16:18.144 --> 08:16:25.104
my own senses. Not knowing what to trust, I did not know what to do, and so had only to keep on

08:16:25.104 --> 08:16:30.924
working in what had hitherto been the groove of my life. The groove ceased to avail me, and I

08:16:30.924 --> 08:16:37.904
mistrusted myself. Doctor, you do not know what it is to doubt everything, even yourself. No,

08:16:38.024 --> 08:16:43.884
you do not. You could not with eyebrows like yours. He seemed pleased and laughed, as he said,

08:16:43.884 --> 08:16:50.884
so you are a physiognomist. I learn more here with each hour. I am with so much pleasure

08:16:50.884 --> 08:16:56.284
coming to you to breakfast, and, oh, sir, you will pardon praise from an old man,

08:16:56.524 --> 08:17:02.884
but you are blessed in your wife. I would listen to him go on praising Mina for a day,

08:17:02.904 --> 08:17:10.224
so I simply nodded and stood silent. She is one of God's women, fashioned by his own hand

08:17:10.224 --> 08:17:16.064
to show us men and other women that there is a heaven where we can enter, and that its light

08:17:16.064 --> 08:17:25.864
can be here on earth. So true, so sweet, so noble, so little an egoist, and that, let me tell you,

08:17:25.864 --> 08:17:33.624
is much in this age so sceptical and selfish. And you, sir, I have read all the letters to poor

08:17:33.624 --> 08:17:38.904
Miss Lucy, and some of them speak of you, so I know you since some days from the knowing of others,

08:17:39.464 --> 08:17:44.924
but I have seen your true self since last night. You will give me your hand, will you not,

08:17:45.284 --> 08:17:52.824
and let us be friends for all our lives. We shook hands, and he was so earnest and so kind

08:17:52.824 --> 08:18:00.084
that it made me quite chokey. And now, he said, may I ask you for some more help? I have a great

08:18:00.084 --> 08:18:06.524
task to do, and at the beginning it is to know. You can help me here. Can you tell me what went

08:18:06.524 --> 08:18:11.864
before your going to Transylvania? Later on I may ask for more help, and of a different kind,

08:18:11.904 --> 08:18:18.184
but at first this will do. Look here, sir, I said, does what you have to do concern the count?

08:18:18.704 --> 08:18:26.244
It does, he said solemnly. Then I am with you heart and soul. As you go by the 10.30 train,

08:18:26.564 --> 08:18:31.344
you will not have time to read them, but I shall get the bundle of papers. You can take them with

08:18:31.344 --> 08:18:36.124
you and read them in the train. After breakfast I saw him to the station. When we were parting,

08:18:36.124 --> 08:18:41.244
he said, perhaps you will come to town if I send for you, and take Madame Mina, too.

08:18:41.644 --> 08:18:47.424
We shall both come, when you will, I said. I had got him the morning papers and the London papers

08:18:47.424 --> 08:18:51.844
of the previous night, and while we were talking at the carriage window waiting for the train to

08:18:51.844 --> 08:18:56.824
start, he was turning them over. His eyes suddenly seemed to catch something in one of them, the

08:18:56.824 --> 08:19:02.744
Westminster Gazette, I knew by the colour, and he grew quite white. He read something intently,

08:19:02.744 --> 08:19:13.424
groaning to himself, my God, my God, so soon, so soon. I do not think he remembered me at the

08:19:13.424 --> 08:19:17.884
moment. Just then the whistle blew and the train moved off. This recalled him to himself,

08:19:17.944 --> 08:19:20.684
and he leaned out of the window and waved his hand, calling out,

08:19:20.804 --> 08:19:25.004
Love to Madame Mina, I shall write so soon as ever I can.

08:19:26.924 --> 08:19:27.364
26 September.

08:19:27.364 --> 08:19:30.224
Dr. Seward's Diary. 26 September.

08:19:30.884 --> 08:19:36.824
Truly there is no such thing as finality. Not a week since I said fini, and yet here I am starting

08:19:36.824 --> 08:19:42.264
fresh again, or rather going on with the record. Until this afternoon I had no cause to think of

08:19:42.264 --> 08:19:48.704
what is done. Renfield had become, to all intents, as sane as he ever was. He was already well ahead

08:19:48.704 --> 08:19:54.284
with his fly business, and he had just started in the spider line also, so he had not been of any

08:19:54.284 --> 08:20:00.104
trouble to me. I had a letter from Arthur, written on Sunday, and from it I gather that he is bearing

08:20:00.104 --> 08:20:05.284
up wonderfully well. Quincy Morris is with him, and that is of much help, for he himself is a

08:20:05.284 --> 08:20:10.524
bubbling well of good spirits. Quincy wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that Arthur is

08:20:10.524 --> 08:20:16.944
beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy. So as to them, all my mind is at rest. As for

08:20:16.944 --> 08:20:22.364
myself, I was settling down to my work with the enthusiasm which I used to have for it,

08:20:22.364 --> 08:20:27.404
so that I might fairly have said that the wound which poor Lucy left on me was becoming

08:20:27.944 --> 08:20:33.964
cicatrized. Everything is, however, now reopened, and what is to be the end God only knows.

08:20:34.804 --> 08:20:40.304
I have an idea that Van Helsing thinks he knows too, but he will only let out enough at a time

08:20:40.304 --> 08:20:46.344
to whet curiosity. He went to Exeter yesterday and stayed there all night. Today he came back

08:20:46.344 --> 08:20:51.984
and almost bounded into the room at about half past five o'clock, and thrust last night's

08:20:51.984 --> 08:20:54.044
Minster Gazette into my hand.

08:20:54.264 --> 08:20:58.584
What do you think of that? he asked as he stood back and folded his arms.

08:20:59.364 --> 08:21:03.664
I looked over the paper, for I really did not know what he meant, but he took it from me and

08:21:03.664 --> 08:21:09.964
pointed out a paragraph about children being decoyed away at Hampstead. It did not convey much to me

08:21:09.964 --> 08:21:14.944
until I reached a passage where it described small puncture wounds on their throats.

08:21:15.644 --> 08:21:18.124
An idea struck me, and I looked up.

08:21:18.884 --> 08:21:22.064
Well, he said, it's like poor Lucy's.

08:21:22.844 --> 08:21:24.204
And what do you make of it?

08:21:25.224 --> 08:21:30.764
Simply that there is some cause in common. Whatever it was that injured her has injured them.

08:21:31.344 --> 08:21:33.924
I did not quite understand his answer.

08:21:34.624 --> 08:21:37.664
That is true indirectly, but not directly.

08:21:38.324 --> 08:21:40.724
How do you mean, Professor? I asked.

08:21:40.724 --> 08:21:44.524
I was a little inclined to take his seriousness lightly, for,

08:21:44.744 --> 08:21:51.124
after all, four days of rest and freedom from burning, harrowing anxiety does help to restore

08:21:51.124 --> 08:21:57.704
one's spirits. But when I saw his face, it sobered me. Never, even in the midst of our

08:21:57.704 --> 08:22:01.044
despair about poor Lucy, had he looked more stern.

08:22:02.324 --> 08:22:03.884
Tell me, I said.

08:22:04.484 --> 08:22:09.184
I can hazard no opinion. I do not know what to think, and I have no data on which to

08:22:09.184 --> 08:22:10.344
conjecture.

08:22:11.124 --> 08:22:17.204
Do you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to what poor Lucy died of,

08:22:17.464 --> 08:22:22.404
not after all the hints given, not only by events, but by me,

08:22:23.244 --> 08:22:27.504
of nervous prostration following a great loss or waste of blood?

08:22:28.024 --> 08:22:30.804
And how was the blood lost or wasted?

08:22:31.604 --> 08:22:33.184
I shook my head.

08:22:33.704 --> 08:22:36.704
He stepped over and sat down beside me, and went on,

08:22:36.704 --> 08:22:41.564
You are a clever man, friend John. You reason well, and your wit is bold,

08:22:41.724 --> 08:22:46.864
but you are too prejudiced. You do not let your eyes see nor your ears hear,

08:22:47.024 --> 08:22:51.024
and that which is outside your daily life is not of account to you.

08:22:51.704 --> 08:22:56.804
Do you not think that there are things which you cannot understand, and yet which are,

08:22:57.284 --> 08:23:00.144
that some people see things that others cannot?

08:23:00.784 --> 08:23:05.264
But these are things old and new which must not be contemplated by men's eyes,

08:23:05.264 --> 08:23:11.004
because they know, or think they know, some things which other men have told them.

08:23:12.004 --> 08:23:18.504
It is the fault of our science that it wants to explain all, and if it explained not,

08:23:18.884 --> 08:23:21.284
then it says there is nothing to explain.

08:23:22.124 --> 08:23:28.444
But yet we see around us every day the growth of new beliefs which think themselves new,

08:23:29.064 --> 08:23:32.444
and which are yet but the old which pretend to be young,

08:23:32.444 --> 08:23:34.824
like the fine ladies at the opera.

08:23:35.244 --> 08:23:38.944
I suppose now you do not believe in corporeal transference?

08:23:39.404 --> 08:23:39.884
No.

08:23:40.844 --> 08:23:42.244
Nor in materialization?

08:23:42.864 --> 08:23:43.384
No.

08:23:44.484 --> 08:23:45.904
Nor in astral bodies?

08:23:46.324 --> 08:23:47.004
No.

08:23:47.404 --> 08:23:48.944
Nor in the reading of thought?

08:23:49.884 --> 08:23:50.564
No.

08:23:51.064 --> 08:23:52.244
Nor in hypnotism?

08:23:52.524 --> 08:23:55.284
Yes, I said. Charcot has proved that pretty well.

08:23:55.904 --> 08:23:57.424
He smiled as he went on.

08:23:57.564 --> 08:24:00.704
Then you are satisfied as to it?

08:24:00.764 --> 08:24:01.384
Yes.

08:24:01.384 --> 08:24:07.764
And of course then you understand how it act, and how can follow the mind of the great Charcot,

08:24:08.084 --> 08:24:12.904
alas that he is no more, into the very soul of the patient that he influenced?

08:24:14.424 --> 08:24:14.824
No.

08:24:15.984 --> 08:24:19.824
Then, friend John, am I to take it that you simply accept fact,

08:24:20.264 --> 08:24:25.204
that you are satisfied to let from premise to conclusion be a blank?

08:24:26.424 --> 08:24:26.824
No.

08:24:27.724 --> 08:24:33.744
Tell me, for I am a student of the brain, how you accept hypnotism and reject the thought reading.

08:24:34.504 --> 08:24:39.424
Let me tell you, my friend, that there are things done today in electrical science

08:24:39.424 --> 08:24:44.644
which would have been deemed unholy by the very man who discovered electricity,

08:24:44.784 --> 08:24:49.824
and who would themselves not so long before been burned as wizards.

08:24:50.644 --> 08:24:53.144
There are always mysteries in life.

08:24:53.484 --> 08:24:56.764
Why was it that Methuselah lived nine hundred years old?

08:24:56.824 --> 08:25:00.184
And old Parr, one hundred and sixty-nine.

08:25:00.824 --> 08:25:06.564
And yet that poor Lucy, with four men's blood in her poor veins, could not live even one day.

08:25:07.284 --> 08:25:10.924
For had she lived one more day, we could save her.

08:25:11.444 --> 08:25:13.944
Do you know all the mystery of life and death?

08:25:14.364 --> 08:25:17.504
Do you know the altogether of comparative anatomy,

08:25:17.624 --> 08:25:21.884
and can say wherefore the qualities of brutes are in some men and not in others?

08:25:22.584 --> 08:25:23.844
Can you tell me why?

08:25:23.844 --> 08:25:27.224
When other spiders die small and soon,

08:25:27.644 --> 08:25:32.784
that one great spider lived for centuries in the tower of the old Spanish church,

08:25:32.984 --> 08:25:38.784
and grew and grew, till on descending he could drink the oil of all the church lamps?

08:25:39.344 --> 08:25:42.684
Can you tell me why, in the Pompous, I, and elsewhere,

08:25:43.264 --> 08:25:47.564
there are bats that come out at night and open the veins of cattle and horses,

08:25:47.824 --> 08:25:49.504
and suck dry their veins?

08:25:50.044 --> 08:25:52.224
How in some islands of the western seas,

08:25:52.224 --> 08:25:55.304
there are bats which hang on the trees all day,

08:25:55.844 --> 08:25:59.644
and those who have seen describe as like giant nuts or pods,

08:26:00.084 --> 08:26:03.544
and that when the sailors sleep on the deck, because that it is hot,

08:26:04.004 --> 08:26:07.524
flit down on them, and then, and then, in the morning,

08:26:07.724 --> 08:26:11.364
are found dead men, white as even Miss Lucy was?

08:26:11.984 --> 08:26:14.804
Good God, Professor, I said, starting up.

08:26:14.824 --> 08:26:17.344
Do you mean to tell me that Lucy was bitten by such a bat,

08:26:17.644 --> 08:26:21.444
and that such a thing is here, in London, in the nineteenth century?

08:26:22.004 --> 08:26:24.304
He waved his hand for silence and went on.

08:26:25.044 --> 08:26:29.344
Can you tell me why the tortoise lives more long than generations of men,

08:26:29.524 --> 08:26:33.244
why the elephant goes on and on till he sees dynasties,

08:26:33.584 --> 08:26:37.884
and why the parrot never die only of bite of cat or dog or other complaint?

08:26:38.244 --> 08:26:41.544
Can you tell me why men believe in all ages and places

08:26:41.544 --> 08:26:44.084
that there are men and women who cannot die?

08:26:44.644 --> 08:26:47.384
We all know, because science has vouched for the fact,

08:26:47.384 --> 08:26:52.664
that there have been toads shut up in rocks for thousands of years,

08:26:53.044 --> 08:26:57.904
shut in one so small hole that only hold him since the youth of the world.

08:26:58.904 --> 08:27:02.884
Can you tell me how the Indian fakir can make himself to die

08:27:02.884 --> 08:27:07.244
and have been buried and his grave sealed and corn sowed on it,

08:27:07.664 --> 08:27:11.884
and the corn reaped and be cut and sown and reaped and cut again,

08:27:12.404 --> 08:27:15.024
and then men come and take away the unbroken seal,

08:27:15.024 --> 08:27:18.104
and that there lie the Indian fakir, not dead,

08:27:18.384 --> 08:27:20.584
but that rise up and walk amongst them as before?

08:27:21.364 --> 08:27:24.344
Here I interrupted him. I was getting bewildered.

08:27:24.664 --> 08:27:28.904
He so crowded on my mind his list of nature's eccentricities and

08:27:28.904 --> 08:27:32.464
possible impossibilities that my imagination was getting fired.

08:27:33.184 --> 08:27:36.264
I had a dim idea that he was teaching me some lesson,

08:27:36.424 --> 08:27:38.904
as long ago he used to do in his study at Amsterdam.

08:27:39.384 --> 08:27:44.084
But he used to tell me the thing so that I could have the object of thought in mind all the time,

08:27:44.084 --> 08:27:48.644
but now I was without his help, yet I wanted to follow him, so I said,

08:27:49.044 --> 08:27:51.644
Professor, let me be your pet student again.

08:27:52.064 --> 08:27:56.464
Tell me the thesis so that I may apply your knowledge as you go on.

08:27:56.744 --> 08:28:00.824
At present I am only going in my mind from point to point as a madman,

08:28:00.964 --> 08:28:02.944
and not a sane one, follows an idea.

08:28:03.184 --> 08:28:06.324
I feel like a novice lumbering through a bog in a mist,

08:28:06.624 --> 08:28:11.044
jumping from one tussock to another in the mere blind effort to move on,

08:28:11.364 --> 08:28:13.044
without knowing where I am going.

08:28:14.084 --> 08:28:16.044
That is a good image, he said.

08:28:16.584 --> 08:28:19.824
Well, I shall tell you. My thesis is this.

08:28:20.744 --> 08:28:24.864
I want you to believe. To believe what?

08:28:26.364 --> 08:28:29.284
To believe in things that you cannot.

08:28:30.924 --> 08:28:31.904
Let me illustrate.

08:28:32.484 --> 08:28:35.164
I heard once of an American who so defined faith,

08:28:36.264 --> 08:28:42.024
that faculty which enables us to believe things which we know to be untrue.

08:28:42.684 --> 08:28:44.884
For one, I follow that man.

08:28:45.244 --> 08:28:48.364
He meant that we shall have an open mind,

08:28:48.524 --> 08:28:54.124
and not let a little bit of truth check the rush of the big truth,

08:28:54.464 --> 08:28:57.144
like a small rock does a railway truck.

08:28:58.184 --> 08:29:00.844
We get the small truth first, good.

08:29:01.324 --> 08:29:03.544
We keep him, and we value him.

08:29:03.744 --> 08:29:09.484
But all the same, we must not let him think himself all the truth in the universe.

08:29:12.024 --> 08:29:15.544
Then you want me not to let some previous conviction

08:29:15.544 --> 08:29:19.864
inure the receptivity of my mind with regard to some strange matter.

08:29:20.104 --> 08:29:21.764
Do I read your lesson all right?

08:29:22.304 --> 08:29:24.564
Ah, you are my favourite pupil still.

08:29:24.924 --> 08:29:26.564
It is worth to teach you.

08:29:26.784 --> 08:29:30.704
Now that you are willing to understand, you have taken the first step to understand.

08:29:31.664 --> 08:29:36.344
You think, then, that those so small holes in the children's throats

08:29:36.344 --> 08:29:39.504
were made by the same that made the holes in Miss Lucy?

08:29:40.304 --> 08:29:41.984
I suppose so.

08:29:42.464 --> 08:29:44.284
He stood up and said solemnly,

08:29:45.364 --> 08:29:47.564
Then you are wrong.

08:29:48.264 --> 08:29:51.804
Oh, would it were so, but alas, no.

08:29:52.544 --> 08:29:55.524
It is worse, far, far worse.

08:29:56.244 --> 08:30:01.184
In God's name, Professor Helsing, what do you mean?

08:30:01.364 --> 08:30:01.984
I cried.

08:30:02.844 --> 08:30:06.184
He threw himself with a despairing gesture into a chair,

08:30:06.184 --> 08:30:10.824
and placed his elbows on the table, covering his face with his hands as he spoke.

08:30:12.244 --> 08:30:14.624
They were made by Miss Lucy.

08:30:41.772 --> 08:30:48.492
15. Dr. Seward's Diary, Continued.

08:30:50.072 --> 08:30:56.492
For a while sheer anger mastered me. It was as if he had, during her life, struck Lucy

08:30:56.492 --> 08:31:01.272
on the face. I smote the table hard and rose up as I said to him,

08:31:01.432 --> 08:31:08.052
"'Dr. Van Helsing, are you mad?' He raised his head and looked at me, and somehow the

08:31:08.052 --> 08:31:15.612
tenderness of his face calmed me at once. "'Would I were,' he said. Madness were

08:31:15.612 --> 08:31:22.352
easy to bear compared with truth like this. "'Oh, my friend, why, think you, did I go

08:31:22.352 --> 08:31:29.632
so far around? Why take so long to tell so simple a thing? Was it because I hate you

08:31:29.632 --> 08:31:36.372
and have hated you all my life? Was it because I wished to give you pain? Was it that I wanted,

08:31:36.452 --> 08:31:44.332
now so late, revenge for that time when you saved my life, and from a fearful death? Ah,

08:31:45.452 --> 08:31:52.832
no.' "'Forgive me,' I said. He went on, "'My friend, it was because I wished to be

08:31:52.832 --> 08:31:59.772
gentle in the breaking to you, for I know you have loved that so sweet lady. But even

08:31:59.772 --> 08:32:06.212
yet I do not expect you to believe. It is so hard to accept at once any abstract truth

08:32:06.212 --> 08:32:12.292
that we may doubt such to be possible when we have always believed the know of it. It

08:32:12.292 --> 08:32:20.552
is more hard still to accept so sad a concrete truth, and of such a one as Miss Lucy. Tonight

08:32:20.552 --> 08:32:28.912
I go to prove it. Dare you come with me?' "'This staggered me. A man does not like

08:32:28.912 --> 08:32:36.432
to prove such a truth,' Byron accepted from the category, Jealousy, and proved the very

08:32:36.432 --> 08:32:45.292
truth he most abhorred. He saw my hesitation and spoke. The logic is simple. No madman's

08:32:45.292 --> 08:32:51.832
logic this time, jumping from tussock to tussock in a misty bog. If it not be true, then proof

08:32:51.832 --> 08:33:00.992
will be relief. At worst it will not harm. If it be true, ah, there is the dread. Yet

08:33:00.992 --> 08:33:08.412
every dread should help my cause, for in it is some need of belief. Come, I tell you what

08:33:08.412 --> 08:33:15.412
I propose. First that we go off now and see that child in the hospital. Doctor Vincent

08:33:15.412 --> 08:33:20.792
of the North Hospital, where the papers say the child is, is a friend of mine, and I think

08:33:20.792 --> 08:33:27.332
of yours since you were in class at Amsterdam. He will let two scientists see his case, if

08:33:27.332 --> 08:33:32.512
he will not let two friends. We shall tell him nothing, but only that we wish to learn.

08:33:33.872 --> 08:33:41.892
And then...' And then?' He took a key from his pocket and held it up. And then we spend

08:33:41.892 --> 08:33:49.252
the night, you and I, in the churchyard where Lucy lies. This is the key that locked the

08:33:49.252 --> 08:33:56.972
tomb. I had it from the coffin man to give to Arthur. My heart sank within me, for I

08:33:56.972 --> 08:34:03.732
felt that there was some fearful ordeal before us. I could do nothing, however, so I plucked

08:34:03.732 --> 08:34:09.172
up what heart I could and said that we had better hasten, as the afternoon was passing.

08:34:11.592 --> 08:34:18.192
We found the child awake. It had had a sleep and taken some food, and altogether was going

08:34:18.192 --> 08:34:24.992
on well. Doctor Vincent took the bandage from its throat and showed us the punctures. There

08:34:24.992 --> 08:34:30.372
was no mistaking the similarity to those which had been on Lucy's throat. They were smaller

08:34:30.372 --> 08:34:37.252
and the edges looked fresher, that was all. We asked Vincent to what he attributed them,

08:34:37.572 --> 08:34:43.772
and he replied that it must have been a bite of some animal, perhaps a rat, but for his

08:34:43.772 --> 08:34:48.932
own part he was inclined to think it was one of the bats which are so numerous on the northern

08:34:48.932 --> 08:34:56.212
heights of London. Out of so many harmless ones, he said, there may be some wild specimen

08:34:56.212 --> 08:35:02.472
from the south of a more malignant species. Some sailor may have brought one home, and

08:35:02.472 --> 08:35:09.112
it managed to escape, or even from the zoological gardens a young one may have got loose, or

08:35:09.112 --> 08:35:16.392
one be bred there from a vampire. These things do occur, you know. Only ten days ago a wolf

08:35:16.392 --> 08:35:21.972
got out and was, I believe, traced up in this direction. For a week after the children

08:35:21.972 --> 08:35:26.412
were playing nothing but Red Riding Hood on the heath, and in every alley in the place,

08:35:26.652 --> 08:35:32.652
until this Blufa Lady scare came along. Since then it has been quite a gala time with them.

08:35:33.252 --> 08:35:38.572
Even this poor little mite, when he woke up today, asked the nurse if he might go away.

08:35:39.252 --> 08:35:44.272
When she asked him why he wanted to go, he said he wanted to play with the Blufa Lady.

08:35:45.552 --> 08:35:50.812
"'I hope,' said Van Helsing, "'that when you are sending the child home you will caution

08:35:50.812 --> 08:35:56.752
its parents to keep strict watch over it. These fancies to stray are most dangerous,

08:35:57.312 --> 08:36:03.152
and if the child were to remain out another night it would probably be fatal. But in any

08:36:03.152 --> 08:36:08.912
case I suppose you will not let it away for some days.' Certainly not, not for a week

08:36:08.912 --> 08:36:11.672
at least, longer if the wound is not healed.

08:36:13.552 --> 08:36:18.912
"'Our visit to the hospital took more time than we had reckoned on, and the sun had dipped

08:36:18.912 --> 08:36:25.732
before we came out. When Van Helsing saw how dark it was he said, "'There is not hurry.

08:36:26.352 --> 08:36:31.872
It is more late than I thought. Come, let us seek somewhere that we may eat, and then

08:36:31.872 --> 08:36:34.232
we shall go on our way.'

08:36:34.732 --> 08:36:40.832
We dined at Jack Straw's castle along with a little crowd of bicyclists and others who

08:36:40.832 --> 08:36:48.112
were genially noisy. About ten o'clock we started from the inn. It was then very dark,

08:36:48.492 --> 08:36:53.832
and the scattered lamps made the darkness greater when we were once outside their individual

08:36:53.832 --> 08:37:01.252
radius. The Professor had evidently noted the road we were to go, for he went on unhesitatingly,

08:37:01.252 --> 08:37:08.992
but as for me I was in quite a mix-up as to locality. As we went further we met fewer

08:37:08.992 --> 08:37:14.912
and fewer people, till at last we were somewhat surprised when we met even the patrol of horse

08:37:14.912 --> 08:37:21.312
police going their usual suburban round. At last we reached the wall of the churchyard

08:37:21.312 --> 08:37:28.112
which we climbed over. With some little difficulty, for it was very dark and the whole place seemed

08:37:28.112 --> 08:37:36.152
so strange to us, we found the Western Ratoum. The Professor took the key, opened the creaky

08:37:36.152 --> 08:37:43.272
door, and standing back, politely but quite unconsciously, motioned me to precede him.

08:37:44.072 --> 08:37:49.072
There was a delicious irony in the offer, in the courtliness of giving preference on

08:37:49.072 --> 08:37:56.832
such a ghastly occasion. My companion followed me quickly, and cautiously drew the door too,

08:37:57.352 --> 08:38:02.852
after carefully ascertaining that the lock was a falling and not a spring one, in the

08:38:02.852 --> 08:38:09.652
latter case we should have been in a bad plight. Then he fumbled in his bag and took out a

08:38:09.652 --> 08:38:16.312
match box and a piece of candle, proceeded to make a light. The tomb in the daytime,

08:38:16.952 --> 08:38:23.052
and when wreathed with fresh flowers, had looked grim and gruesome enough, but now,

08:38:23.052 --> 08:38:30.072
some days afterwards, when the flowers hung lank and dead, their whites turning to rust,

08:38:30.732 --> 08:38:36.572
and their greens to browns, when the spider and the beetle had resumed their accustomed

08:38:36.572 --> 08:38:45.252
dominance, when the thyme discoloured stone and dust encrusted mortar and rusty dank iron,

08:38:45.252 --> 08:38:52.232
and tarnished brass and clouded silver plating, gave back the feeble glimmer of a candle.

08:38:53.312 --> 08:39:00.572
The effect was more miserable and sordid than could have been imagined. It conveyed irresistibly

08:39:00.572 --> 08:39:06.832
the idea that life, animal life, was not the only thing which could pass away.

08:39:08.952 --> 08:39:14.932
Van Helsing went about his work systematically, holding his candle so that he could read the

08:39:14.932 --> 08:39:20.852
coffin plates, and so holding it that the sperm dropped in white patches which congealed

08:39:20.852 --> 08:39:28.392
as they touched the metal, he made assurance of Lucy's coffin. Another search in his bag,

08:39:28.752 --> 08:39:30.512
and he took out a turn screw.

08:39:31.692 --> 08:39:34.072
What are you going to do? I asked.

08:39:35.012 --> 08:39:38.172
To open the coffin you shall yet be convinced.

08:39:40.112 --> 08:39:45.652
Straightway he began taking out the screws, and finally lifted off the lid showing the

08:39:45.652 --> 08:39:52.632
casing of lead beneath. The sight was almost too much for me. It seemed to be as much an

08:39:52.632 --> 08:39:57.032
affront to the dead as it would have been to have stripped off her clothing in her sleep

08:39:57.032 --> 08:40:04.012
whilst living. I actually took hold of his hand to stop him. He only said, You shall

08:40:04.012 --> 08:40:11.532
see. And again fumbling in his bag took out a tiny fretsaw. Striking the turn screw through

08:40:11.532 --> 08:40:18.172
the lead with a swift downward stab, which made me wince, he made a small hole, which

08:40:18.172 --> 08:40:24.452
was, however, big enough to admit the point of the saw. I had expected a rush of gas from

08:40:24.452 --> 08:40:31.252
the weak old corpse. We doctors, who have had to study our dangers, have to become accustomed

08:40:31.252 --> 08:40:36.772
to such things, and I drew back towards the door. But the Professor never stopped for

08:40:36.772 --> 08:40:43.252
a moment. He sawed down a couple of feet along one side of the lead coffin, and then across

08:40:43.252 --> 08:40:49.752
and down the other side. Taking the edge of the loose flange, he bent it back towards

08:40:49.752 --> 08:40:55.932
the foot of the coffin, and holding up the candle into the aperture, motioned me to look.

08:40:57.232 --> 08:41:05.972
I drew near and looked. The coffin was empty. It was certainly a surprise to me and gave me a

08:41:05.972 --> 08:41:12.912
considerable shock, but Van Helsing was unmoved. He was now more sure than ever off his ground,

08:41:13.432 --> 08:41:22.172
and so emboldened to proceed in his work. Are you satisfied now, friend John? he asked. I felt all

08:41:22.172 --> 08:41:29.272
the dogged argumentativeness of my nature awake within me as I answered him. I am satisfied

08:41:29.272 --> 08:41:36.032
that Lucy's body is not in that coffin, but that only proves one thing. And what is that,

08:41:36.112 --> 08:41:43.792
friend John? That it is not there. That is good logic, he said, so far as it goes. But

08:41:43.792 --> 08:41:52.912
how can you account for it not being there? Perhaps a body snatcher, I suggested. Some

08:41:52.912 --> 08:41:58.872
of the undertaker's people may have stolen it. I felt that I was speaking folly, and

08:41:58.872 --> 08:42:01.632
yet it was the only real cause which I could suggest.

08:42:02.992 --> 08:42:11.312
The Professor sighed. Ah, well, he said, we must have more proof. Come with me. He put

08:42:11.312 --> 08:42:17.072
on the coffin lid again, gathered up all his things and placed them in the bag, blew out

08:42:17.072 --> 08:42:24.072
the light, and placed the candle also in the bag. We opened the door and went out. Behind

08:42:24.072 --> 08:42:30.732
us he closed the door and locked it. He handed me the key, saying, Will you keep it? You

08:42:30.732 --> 08:42:36.472
had better be assured. I laughed. It was not a very cheerful laugh, I am bound to say,

08:42:36.472 --> 08:42:43.352
as I motioned him to keep it. A key is nothing, I said. There are many duplicates, and anyhow

08:42:43.352 --> 08:42:48.732
it is not difficult to pick a lock of this kind. He said nothing, but put the key in

08:42:48.732 --> 08:42:55.052
his pocket. Then he told me to watch at one side of the churchyard, whilst he would watch

08:42:55.052 --> 08:43:02.872
at the other. I took up my place behind a yew tree, and I saw his dark figure move until

08:43:02.872 --> 08:43:06.972
the intervening headstones and trees hid it from my sight.

08:43:09.232 --> 08:43:16.412
It was a lonely vigil. Just after I had taken my place I heard a distant clock strike twelve,

08:43:16.992 --> 08:43:24.692
and in time came one and two. I was chilled and unnerved, and angry with the Professor

08:43:24.692 --> 08:43:30.992
for taking me on such an errand, and with myself for coming. I was too cold and too

08:43:30.992 --> 08:43:38.172
sleepy to be keenly observant, and not sleepy enough to betray my trust, so altogether I

08:43:38.172 --> 08:43:45.552
had a dreary, miserable time. Suddenly, as I turned round, I thought I saw

08:43:45.552 --> 08:43:52.192
something like a white streak moving between two dark yew trees at the side of the churchyard

08:43:52.192 --> 08:43:58.132
farthest from the tomb. At the same time a dark mass moved from the Professor's side

08:43:58.132 --> 08:44:04.472
of the ground, and hurriedly went towards it. Then I too moved, but I had to go round

08:44:04.472 --> 08:44:12.072
headstones and railed off tombs, and I stumbled over graves. The sky was overcast, and somewhere

08:44:12.072 --> 08:44:14.212
far off an early cock crew.

08:44:16.152 --> 08:44:21.372
A little ways off, beyond a line of scattered juniper trees which marked the pathway to

08:44:21.372 --> 08:44:28.032
the church, a white, dim figure flitted in the direction of the tomb. The tomb itself

08:44:28.032 --> 08:44:32.932
was hidden by trees, and I could not see where the figure had disappeared. I heard

08:44:32.932 --> 08:44:38.332
the rustle of actual movement where I had first seen the white figure, and coming over

08:44:38.332 --> 08:44:44.352
found the Professor holding in his arms a tiny child. When he saw me he held it out

08:44:44.352 --> 08:44:47.532
to me, and said, Are you satisfied now?

08:44:48.532 --> 08:44:56.572
No, I said, in a way that I felt was aggressive. Do you not see the child? Yes, it is a child,

08:44:56.572 --> 08:44:59.912
but who brought it here, and is it wounded?

08:45:01.052 --> 08:45:07.092
We shall see, said the Professor, and with one impulse we took our way out of the churchyard,

08:45:07.532 --> 08:45:14.412
he carrying the sleeping child. When we had got some little distance away we went into

08:45:14.412 --> 08:45:20.792
a clump of trees, and struck a match, and looked at the child's throat. It was without

08:45:20.792 --> 08:45:22.952
a scratch or scar of any kind.

08:45:24.032 --> 08:45:27.012
Was I right? I asked triumphantly.

08:45:28.112 --> 08:45:31.972
We were just in time, said the Professor, thankfully.

08:45:33.732 --> 08:45:40.332
We had now to decide what we were to do with the child, and so consulted about it. If we

08:45:40.332 --> 08:45:44.672
were to take it to a police station we should have to give some account of our movements

08:45:44.672 --> 08:45:49.912
during the night. At least we should have to make some statement as to how we had come

08:45:49.912 --> 08:45:56.512
to find the child. So finally we decided that we would take it to the Heath, and when

08:45:56.512 --> 08:46:02.192
we heard a policeman coming would leave it where he could not fail to find it. We would

08:46:02.192 --> 08:46:04.912
then seek our way home as quickly as we could.

08:46:06.172 --> 08:46:11.572
All fell out well, yet the edge of Hampstead Heath we heard a policeman's heavy tramp,

08:46:12.192 --> 08:46:18.512
and laying the child on the pathway we waited and watched until he saw it as he flashed

08:46:18.512 --> 08:46:25.552
his lantern to and fro. We heard his exclamation of astonishment, and then we went away silently.

08:46:26.512 --> 08:46:31.292
By good chance we got a cab near the Spaniards and drove to town.

08:46:32.572 --> 08:46:40.512
I cannot sleep, so I make this entry, but I must try to get a few hours sleep, as Van

08:46:40.512 --> 08:46:47.032
Helsing is to call for me at noon. He insists that I go with him on another expedition.

08:46:50.072 --> 08:46:51.192
27th September.

08:46:52.872 --> 08:46:58.832
It was two o'clock before we found a suitable opportunity for our attempt. The funeral held

08:46:58.832 --> 08:47:05.012
at noon was all completed, and the last stragglers of the mourners had taken themselves lazily

08:47:05.012 --> 08:47:11.572
away when, looking carefully from behind a clump of alder trees, we saw the sexton lock

08:47:11.572 --> 08:47:18.432
the gate after him. We knew that we were safe till the morning, did we desire it, but the

08:47:18.432 --> 08:47:24.832
professor told me that we should not want more than an hour at most. Again I felt that

08:47:24.832 --> 08:47:31.052
horrid sense of the reality of things in which any effort of imagination seemed out of place,

08:47:31.652 --> 08:47:37.932
and I realized distinctly the perils of the law which we were incurring in our unhallowed

08:47:37.932 --> 08:47:45.572
work. Besides, I felt it was all so useless, outrageous as it was to open a leaden coffin

08:47:45.572 --> 08:47:52.032
to see if a woman dead nearly a week were really dead. It now seemed the height of folly

08:47:52.032 --> 08:47:57.312
to open the tomb again when we knew from the evidence of our own eyesight that the coffin

08:47:57.312 --> 08:48:05.072
was empty. I shrugged my shoulders, however, and rested silent, for Van Helsing had a way

08:48:05.072 --> 08:48:14.212
of going on his own road no matter who remonstrated. He took the key, opened the vault, and again

08:48:14.212 --> 08:48:22.312
courteously motioned me to proceed. The place was not so gruesome as last night, but oh,

08:48:22.312 --> 08:48:30.192
how unutterably mean looking when the sunshine streamed in. Van Helsing walked over to Lucy's

08:48:30.192 --> 08:48:38.752
coffin and I followed. He bent over and again forced back the leaden flange, and a shock

08:48:38.752 --> 08:48:46.972
of surprise and dismay shot through me. There lay Lucy, seemingly just as we had seen her

08:48:46.972 --> 08:48:54.152
the night before her funeral. She was, if possible, more radiantly beautiful than ever,

08:48:54.702 --> 08:49:01.192
and I could not believe that she was dead. The lips were red, nay redder than before,

08:49:01.192 --> 08:49:04.092
and on the cheeks was a delicate bloom.

08:49:05.452 --> 08:49:08.432
"'Is this a juggle?' I said to him.

08:49:09.172 --> 08:49:15.532
"'Are you convinced now?' said the professor in response, and as he spoke he put over his

08:49:15.532 --> 08:49:22.832
hand, and in a way that made me shudder, pulled back the dead lips and showed the white teeth.

08:49:23.732 --> 08:49:30.432
"'See,' he went on, "'they are even sharper than before.' With this and this,' and he

08:49:30.432 --> 08:49:37.292
touched one of the canine teeth and that below it, the little children can be bitten. Are

08:49:37.292 --> 08:49:40.812
you of belief now, friend John?'

08:49:40.812 --> 08:49:47.552
Once more argumentative hostility woke within me. I could not accept such an overwhelming

08:49:47.552 --> 08:49:54.372
idea as he suggested, so with an attempt to argue, of which I was even at the moment ashamed,

08:49:54.372 --> 08:50:02.912
I said, she may have been placed here since last night. Indeed, that is so, and by whom?

08:50:04.072 --> 08:50:11.792
I do not know. Someone has done it. And yet she has been dead one week. Most peoples in

08:50:11.792 --> 08:50:20.112
that time would not look so. I had no answer for this, so was silent. Van Helsing did

08:50:20.112 --> 08:50:26.692
not seem to notice my silence. At any rate he showed neither chagrin nor triumph. He

08:50:26.692 --> 08:50:32.872
was looking intently at the face of the dead woman, raising the eyelids and looking at

08:50:32.872 --> 08:50:39.972
the eyes, and once more opening the lips and examining the teeth. Then he turned to me

08:50:39.972 --> 08:50:46.912
and said, "'Here there is one thing which is different from all recorded. Here is some

08:50:46.912 --> 08:50:53.712
dual life that is not as the common. She was bitten by the vampire when she was in a trance,

08:50:54.132 --> 08:51:00.132
sleep-walking. Oh, you start. You do not know that, friend John, but you shall know it later.

08:51:00.652 --> 08:51:08.072
And in trance could he best come to take more blood. In trance she dies, and in trance she

08:51:08.072 --> 08:51:15.892
is undead too. So it is that she differ from all other. Usually when the undead sleep at

08:51:15.892 --> 08:51:21.512
home, as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of his arm to designate what to a vampire

08:51:21.512 --> 08:51:29.492
was home, their face show what they are. But this so sweet that was when she not undead,

08:51:29.732 --> 08:51:36.552
she go back to the nothings of the common dead. There is no malign there, see, and so

08:51:36.552 --> 08:51:45.872
it make hard that I must kill her in her sleep.' This turned my blood cold, and it began to

08:51:45.872 --> 08:51:52.092
upon me that I was accepting Van Helsing's theories. But if she were really dead, what

08:51:52.092 --> 08:51:58.872
was there of terror in the idea of killing her? He looked up at me, and evidently saw

08:51:58.872 --> 08:52:06.072
the change in my face, for he said almost joyously, "'Ah, you believe now?' I answered,

08:52:06.212 --> 08:52:13.032
"'Do not press me too hard all at once. I am willing to accept. How will you do this

08:52:13.032 --> 08:52:19.812
bloody work?' I shall cut off her head and fill her mouth with garlic, and I shall drive

08:52:19.812 --> 08:52:26.132
a stake through her body.' It made me shudder to think of so mutilating the body of the

08:52:26.132 --> 08:52:33.752
woman whom I had loved, and yet the feeling was not so strong as I had expected. I was

08:52:33.752 --> 08:52:39.792
in fact beginning to shudder at the presence of this being, this undead as Van Helsing

08:52:39.792 --> 08:52:48.732
called it, and to loathe it. Is it possible that love is all subjective, or all objective?'

08:52:48.732 --> 08:52:55.452
I waited a considerable time for Van Helsing to begin, but he stood as if wrapped in thought.

08:52:56.552 --> 08:53:02.412
Presently he closed the catch of his bag with a snap, and said, "'I have been thinking,

08:53:02.532 --> 08:53:08.272
and have made up my mind as to what is best. If I did simply follow my inclining, I would

08:53:08.272 --> 08:53:13.952
do now at this moment what is to be done. But there are other things to follow, and

08:53:13.952 --> 08:53:20.272
things that are a thousand times more difficult, in that them we do not know. This is simple.

08:53:20.572 --> 08:53:26.132
She have yet no life taken, though that is of time, and to act an hour would be to take

08:53:26.132 --> 08:53:32.072
danger from her for ever. But then we may have to want Arthur, and how shall we tell

08:53:32.072 --> 08:53:39.332
him of this? If you, who saw the wounds on Lucy's throat, and saw the wounds so similar

08:53:39.332 --> 08:53:45.572
on the child's at the hospital, if you, who saw the coffin empty last night, and fall

08:53:45.572 --> 08:53:51.152
to-day with a woman who have not changed, only to be more rose and more beautiful in

08:53:51.152 --> 08:53:57.492
a whole week after she die, if you know of this, and know of the white figure last night

08:53:57.492 --> 08:54:03.052
that brought the child to the churchyard, and yet of your own senses you did not believe,

08:54:03.612 --> 08:54:11.692
how then can I expect Arthur, who know none of those things, to believe? He doubted me

08:54:11.692 --> 08:54:17.052
when I took him from her kiss when she was dying. I know he has forgiven me because in

08:54:17.052 --> 08:54:23.492
some mistaken idea I have done things that prevent him say good-bye as he ought. And

08:54:23.492 --> 08:54:29.932
he may think that in some more mistaken idea this woman was buried alive, and that in most

08:54:29.932 --> 08:54:36.512
mistake of all we have killed her. He will then argue back that it is we mistaken ones

08:54:36.512 --> 08:54:43.112
that have killed her by our own ideas, and so he will be much unhappy always. Yet he

08:54:43.112 --> 08:54:49.892
never can be sure, and that is the worst of all. And he will sometimes think that she

08:54:49.892 --> 08:54:55.832
he loved was buried alive, and that will paint his dreams with horrors of what she

08:54:55.832 --> 08:55:01.452
must have suffered, and again he will think that we may be right, and that his so beloved

08:55:01.452 --> 08:55:10.372
was after all an undead. No, I told him once, and since then I learn much. Now since I know

08:55:10.372 --> 08:55:16.412
it is all true, a hundred thousand times more do I know that he must pass through the bitter

08:55:16.412 --> 08:55:23.052
waters to reach the sweet. He, poor fellow, must have one hour that will make the very

08:55:23.052 --> 08:55:28.632
face of heaven grow black to him. Then we can act for good all round and send him peace.

08:55:29.452 --> 08:55:35.412
My mind is made up. Let us go. You return home for tonight to your asylum, and see that

08:55:35.412 --> 08:55:41.612
all be well. As for me, I shall spend the night here in this churchyard in my own way.

08:55:42.532 --> 08:55:48.052
Tomorrow night you shall come to me to the Barkey Hotel at ten o'clock. I shall send

08:55:48.052 --> 08:55:53.332
for Arthur to come too, and also that so fine young man of America that gave his blood.

08:55:54.232 --> 08:56:00.212
Later we shall all have work to do. I come with you so far as Piccadilly and there Dine,

08:56:00.332 --> 08:56:07.872
for I must be back here before the sun set. So we locked the tomb and came away, and got

08:56:07.872 --> 08:56:14.432
over the wall of the churchyard, which was not much of a task, and drove back to Piccadilly.

08:56:16.712 --> 08:56:24.192
Note left by Van Helsing in his portmanteau, Barkey Hotel, directed to John Seward, MD,

08:56:24.912 --> 08:56:34.332
not delivered. 27th September. Friend John, I write this in case anything should happen.

08:56:34.892 --> 08:56:42.432
I go alone to watch in that churchyard. It pleases me that the undead, Miss Lucy, shall

08:56:42.432 --> 08:56:49.532
not leave tonight, so that on the morrow night she may be more eager. Therefore I shall fix

08:56:49.532 --> 08:56:57.132
some things she like not, garlic and a crucifix, and so seal up the door of the tomb. She is

08:56:57.132 --> 08:57:04.312
young as undead and will heed. Moreover, these are only to prevent her coming out. They will

08:57:04.332 --> 08:57:11.272
not prevail on her wanting to get in, for then the undead is desperate, and must find

08:57:11.272 --> 08:57:17.252
the line of least resistance whatsoever it may be. I shall be at hand all the night from

08:57:17.252 --> 08:57:23.852
sunset till after sunrise, and if there be aught that may be learned, I shall learn it.

08:57:24.872 --> 08:57:31.932
For Miss Lucy, or from her, I have no fear. But that other, to whom is there that she

08:57:31.932 --> 08:57:38.912
is undead, he have not the power to seek her tomb and find shelter. He is cunning,

08:57:39.252 --> 08:57:45.032
as I know from Mr Jonathan, and from the way that all along he have fooled us when he played

08:57:45.032 --> 08:57:52.552
with us for Miss Lucy's life, and we lost, and in many ways the undead are strong. He

08:57:52.552 --> 08:57:58.072
have always the strength in his hand of twenty men, even we four who gave our strength to

08:57:58.072 --> 08:58:05.272
Miss Lucy, it also is all to him. Besides, he can summon his wolf, and I know not what.

08:58:06.252 --> 08:58:13.052
So if it be that he come hither on this night, he shall find me, but none other shall until

08:58:13.052 --> 08:58:19.332
it be too late. But it may be that he will not attempt the place. There is no reason

08:58:19.332 --> 08:58:25.172
why he should. His hunting ground is more full of game than the churchyard where the

08:58:25.172 --> 08:58:36.192
undead woman sleeps, and the one old man watch. Therefore I write this in case. Take the papers

08:58:36.192 --> 08:58:41.372
that are with this, the diaries of Harker and the rest, and read them, and then find

08:58:41.372 --> 08:58:47.492
this great undead, and cut off his head, and burn his heart, or drive a stake through it,

08:58:47.632 --> 08:58:55.032
so that the world may rest from him. If it be so, farewell, Van Helsing.

08:58:58.072 --> 08:59:01.552
Dr. Seward's Diary. 28th September.

08:59:03.672 --> 08:59:09.372
It is wonderful what a good night's sleep will do for one. Yesterday I was almost willing

08:59:09.372 --> 08:59:15.812
to accept Van Helsing's monstrous ideas, but now they seem to start out lurid before me,

08:59:16.092 --> 08:59:22.832
as outrage is on common sense. I have no doubt that he believes it all. I wonder if his mind

08:59:22.832 --> 08:59:28.972
can have become in any way unhinged. Surely there must be some rational explanation of

08:59:28.972 --> 08:59:34.912
all these mysterious things. Is it possible that the Professor can have done it himself?

08:59:36.012 --> 08:59:42.012
He is so abnormally clever that if he went off his head he would carry out his intent

08:59:42.012 --> 08:59:49.212
with regard to some fixed idea in a wonderful way. I am loath to think it, and indeed it

08:59:49.212 --> 08:59:53.932
would be almost as great a marvel as the other, to find that Van Helsing was mad.

08:59:54.872 --> 09:00:00.832
But anyhow, I shall watch him carefully. I may get some light on the mystery.

09:00:03.772 --> 09:00:09.512
29th September. Last night, at a little before ten o'clock,

09:00:10.012 --> 09:00:15.632
Arthur and Quincy came into Van Helsing's room. He told us all what he wanted us to

09:00:15.632 --> 09:00:23.252
do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all our wills were centred in his. He

09:00:23.252 --> 09:00:29.672
began by saying that he hoped we would all come with him too, for, he said, there is

09:00:29.672 --> 09:00:36.952
a grave duty to be done there. You were doubtless surprised at my letter. This query was directly

09:00:36.952 --> 09:00:43.432
addressed to Lord Godelming. I was. It rather upset me for a bit. There has been so much

09:00:43.432 --> 09:00:48.932
trouble around my house of late that I could do without any more. I have been curious too

09:00:48.932 --> 09:00:54.592
as to what you mean. Quincy and I talked it over, but the more we talked the more puzzled

09:00:54.592 --> 09:00:59.912
we got. Till now I can say for myself that I am about up a tree as to any meaning about

09:00:59.912 --> 09:01:04.252
anything. Me too, said Quincy Morris, laconicly.

09:01:05.172 --> 09:01:10.372
Oh, said the Professor, then you are nearer the beginning, both of you, than friend John

09:01:10.372 --> 09:01:17.712
here, who has to go a long way back before he can ever get so far as to begin. It was

09:01:17.712 --> 09:01:23.612
evident that he recognized my return to my old doubting frame of mind without my saying

09:01:23.612 --> 09:01:31.692
a word. Then, turning to the other two, he said with intense gravity, I want your permission

09:01:31.692 --> 09:01:38.592
to do what I think good this night. It is I know much to ask, and when you know what

09:01:38.592 --> 09:01:46.272
it is I propose to do you will know, and only then how much. Therefore may I ask that

09:01:46.272 --> 09:01:52.272
you promise me in the dark, so that afterwards, though you may be angry with me for a time,

09:01:53.032 --> 09:01:59.392
I must not disguise from myself the possibility that such may be. You shall not blame yourselves

09:01:59.392 --> 09:02:06.572
for anything. That's Frank anyhow, broke in Quincy. I'll answer for the Professor. I don't

09:02:06.572 --> 09:02:10.612
quite see his drift, but I swear he's honest, and that's good enough for me.

09:02:11.772 --> 09:02:18.092
I thank you, sir, said Van Helsing proudly. I have done myself the honor of counting you

09:02:18.092 --> 09:02:25.092
one trusting friend, and such endorsement is dear to me. He held out a hand which Quincy

09:02:25.092 --> 09:02:32.912
took. Then Arthur spoke out. Dr. Van Helsing, I don't quite like to buy a pig in a poke,

09:02:32.912 --> 09:02:38.632
as they say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honor as a gentleman or my faith

09:02:38.632 --> 09:02:45.232
as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a promise. If you can assure me that

09:02:45.232 --> 09:02:50.872
what you intend does not violate either of these two, then I give my consent at once,

09:02:51.312 --> 09:02:57.832
though for the life of me I cannot understand what you're driving at. I accept your limitation,

09:02:57.832 --> 09:03:03.672
said Van Helsing, and all I ask of you is that if you feel it necessary to condemn any

09:03:03.672 --> 09:03:09.792
act of mine, you will first consider it well and be satisfied that it does not violate

09:03:09.792 --> 09:03:10.692
your reservations.

09:03:12.612 --> 09:03:18.812
Agreed, said Arthur. That is only fair, and now that the poor parlors are over, may I

09:03:18.812 --> 09:03:27.812
ask what it is we are to do? I want you to come with me and to come in secret to the

09:03:28.812 --> 09:03:29.452
tomb.

09:03:29.452 --> 09:03:36.892
Arthur's face fell, as he said in an amazed sort of way, where poor Lucy is buried. The

09:03:36.892 --> 09:03:46.892
professor bowed. Arthur went on. And when there? To enter the tomb. Arthur stood up.

09:03:47.172 --> 09:03:54.612
Professor, are you in earnest, or is it some monstrous joke? Pardon me, I see that you

09:03:54.612 --> 09:04:00.612
are in earnest. He sat down again, but I could see that he sat firmly and proudly,

09:04:01.012 --> 09:04:08.552
as one who is on his dignity. There was silence until he asked again. And when in the tomb?

09:04:09.872 --> 09:04:17.492
To open the coffin. This is too much, he said, angrily rising again. I am willing to be patient

09:04:17.492 --> 09:04:23.452
in all things that are reasonable, but in this, this desecration of the grave, of one

09:04:23.452 --> 09:04:24.212
who—

09:04:24.212 --> 09:04:29.432
He fairly choked with indignation. The professor looked pityingly at him.

09:04:30.172 --> 09:04:37.552
If I could spare you one pang, my dear friend, he said, God knows I would. But this night

09:04:37.552 --> 09:04:45.452
our feet must tread on thorny paths, or later, and for ever, the feet you love must walk

09:04:45.452 --> 09:04:46.892
in paths of flame.

09:04:48.032 --> 09:04:53.532
Arthur looked up with set white face and said, Take care, sir, take care.

09:04:54.732 --> 09:04:59.652
Would it not be well to hear what I have to say? said Van Helsing. And then you will at

09:04:59.652 --> 09:05:01.752
least know the limit of my purpose.

09:05:03.012 --> 09:05:04.012
Shall I go on?

09:05:05.412 --> 09:05:07.592
That's fair enough, broken Morris.

09:05:08.992 --> 09:05:13.372
After a pause Van Helsing went on, evidently with an effort.

09:05:14.792 --> 09:05:24.192
Miss Lucy is dead. Is it not so? Yes. Then there can be no wrong to her. But if she is

09:05:24.192 --> 09:05:26.032
not dead—

09:05:26.032 --> 09:05:32.812
Arthur jumped to his feet. Good God! he cried. What do you mean? Has there been any mistake?

09:05:32.992 --> 09:05:39.112
Has she been buried alive? He groaned in anguish that not even hope could soften.

09:05:39.912 --> 09:05:47.312
I did not say she was alive, my child. I did not think it. I go no further than to say

09:05:47.312 --> 09:05:49.552
that she might be undead.

09:05:50.612 --> 09:05:56.712
Undead? Not alive? What do you mean? Is this all a nightmare, or what is it?

09:05:57.672 --> 09:06:04.412
There are mysteries which men can only guess at, which age by age they may solve only in

09:06:04.412 --> 09:06:08.792
part. Believe me, we are now on the verge of one.

09:06:09.852 --> 09:06:14.992
But I have not done. May I cut off the head of dead Miss Lucy?

09:06:16.092 --> 09:06:22.392
Heavens and earth, no! cried Arthur in a storm of passion. Not for the wide world will I

09:06:22.392 --> 09:06:25.592
consent to any mutilation of her dead body.

09:06:26.352 --> 09:06:33.252
Dr Van Helsing, you try me too far. What have I done to you that you should torture me so?

09:06:33.612 --> 09:06:40.212
What did that poor sweet girl do that you should want to cast such dishonour on her

09:06:40.212 --> 09:06:47.592
grave? Are you mad that you speak such things, or am I mad to listen to them? Don't dare

09:06:47.592 --> 09:06:53.872
think more of such a desecration. I shall not give my consent to anything you do. I

09:06:53.872 --> 09:07:00.172
have a duty to do in protecting her grave from outrage, and by God I shall do it.

09:07:02.032 --> 09:07:08.612
Van Helsing rose up from where he had all the time been seated, and said gravely and

09:07:08.612 --> 09:07:16.812
sternly, My Lord Godelming, I, too, have a duty to do, a duty to others, a duty to you,

09:07:17.172 --> 09:07:24.712
a duty to the dead, and by God I shall do it. All I ask you now is that you come with

09:07:24.712 --> 09:07:32.192
me, that you look and listen, and if, when later I make the same request, you do not

09:07:32.192 --> 09:07:39.492
be more eager for its fulfilment even than I am, then I shall do my duty, whatever it

09:07:39.672 --> 09:07:47.492
may seem to me. And then, to follow your Lordship's wishes, I shall hold myself at your disposal

09:07:47.492 --> 09:07:52.172
to render an account to you when and where you will.

09:07:53.292 --> 09:08:01.352
His voice broke a little, and he went on with a voice full of pity, But I beseech you, do

09:08:01.352 --> 09:08:08.832
not go forth in anger with me. In a long life of acts which were often not pleasant to do,

09:08:09.472 --> 09:08:17.132
and which sometimes did ring my heart, I have never had so heavy a task as now. Believe

09:08:17.132 --> 09:08:23.532
me, that if the time come for you to change your mind towards me, one look from you will

09:08:23.532 --> 09:08:30.912
wipe away all this so sad hour, for I would do what a man can to save you from sorrow.

09:08:31.872 --> 09:08:40.452
Just think, for why should I give myself so much labour and so much of sorrow? I have

09:08:40.452 --> 09:08:46.992
come here from my own land to do what I can of good, at the first to please my friend

09:08:46.992 --> 09:08:56.572
John, and then to help a sweet young lady whom too I come to love. For her, I am ashamed

09:08:56.572 --> 09:09:03.132
to say so much, but I say it in kindness, I gave what you gave, the blood of my veins.

09:09:03.622 --> 09:09:12.152
I gave it, I who was not like you her lover, but only her physician and her friend. I gave

09:09:12.152 --> 09:09:19.832
her my nights and days, before death, after death, and if my death can do her good even

09:09:19.832 --> 09:09:24.852
now when she is the dead undead, she shall have it freely.

09:09:26.232 --> 09:09:34.712
He said this with a very grave, sweet pride, and Arthur was much affected by it. He took

09:09:34.712 --> 09:09:41.792
the old man's hand and said in a broken voice, Oh, it is hard to think of it, and I cannot

09:09:41.792 --> 09:09:46.292
understand, but at least I shall go with you and wait.

09:10:14.208 --> 09:10:19.088
16. Dr. Seward's Diary.

09:10:19.148 --> 09:10:20.148
CONTINUED

09:10:20.868 --> 09:10:26.208
It was just a quarter before twelve o'clock when we got into the churchyard over the low wall.

09:10:27.308 --> 09:10:32.708
The night was dark with occasional gleams of moonlight between the dents of the heavy clouds

09:10:32.708 --> 09:10:39.208
that scutted across the sky. We all kept somehow close together with Van Helsing

09:10:39.208 --> 09:10:46.348
slightly in front as he led the way. When we had come close to the tomb I looked well at Arthur,

09:10:46.348 --> 09:10:51.778
for I feared the proximity to a place laden with so sorrowful a memory would upset him,

09:10:52.328 --> 09:10:59.148
but he bore himself well. I took it that the very mystery of the proceeding was in some way

09:10:59.148 --> 09:11:04.688
a counteractant to his grief. The Professor unlocked the door and, seeing a natural hesitation

09:11:04.688 --> 09:11:10.308
amongst us for various reasons, solved the difficulty by entering first himself.

09:11:11.028 --> 09:11:17.368
The rest of us followed and he closed the door. He then lit a dark lantern and pointed to a coffin.

09:11:18.188 --> 09:11:22.508
Arthur stepped forward, hesitantly. Van Helsing said to me,

09:11:23.028 --> 09:11:27.688
You were with me here yesterday. Was the body of Miss Lucy in that coffin?

09:11:28.488 --> 09:11:32.548
It was. The Professor turned to the rest saying,

09:11:32.748 --> 09:11:37.368
You here? And yet there is no one who does not believe with me.

09:11:37.948 --> 09:11:44.868
He took his screwdriver and again took off the lid of the coffin. Arthur looked on, very pale and

09:11:44.868 --> 09:11:52.208
silent. When the lid was removed he stepped forward. He evidently did not know there was

09:11:52.208 --> 09:11:58.488
a laden coffin, or at any rate had not thought of it. When he saw the rent in the lid the blood

09:11:58.488 --> 09:12:04.088
rushed to his face for an instant, but as quickly fell away again so that he remained of a ghastly

09:12:04.088 --> 09:12:12.528
whiteness. He was still silent. Van Helsing forced back the laden flange and we all looked in

09:12:12.528 --> 09:12:21.028
and recoiled. The coffin was empty. For several minutes no one spoke a word.

09:12:21.508 --> 09:12:27.588
The silence was broken by Quincy Morris. Professor, I answered for you. Your word is all I want.

09:12:28.028 --> 09:12:32.248
I wouldn't ask such a thing ordinarily. I wouldn't so dishonour you as to imply a doubt,

09:12:32.248 --> 09:12:37.368
but this is a mystery that goes beyond all honour or dishonour. Is this your doing?

09:12:38.948 --> 09:12:46.208
I swear to you by all that I hold sacred that I have not removed or touched her. What happened

09:12:46.208 --> 09:12:52.068
was this. Two nights ago my friend Seward and I came here with good purpose, believe me.

09:12:52.348 --> 09:12:58.608
I opened that coffin which was then sealed up and we found it as now empty. We then waited

09:12:58.608 --> 09:13:05.988
and saw something white come through the trees. The next day we came here in daytime and she lay

09:13:05.988 --> 09:13:12.788
there. Did she not, friend John? Yes. That night we were just in time.

09:13:13.508 --> 09:13:19.508
One more so small child was missing and we find it, thank God, unharmed amongst the graves.

09:13:20.488 --> 09:13:27.468
Yesterday I came here before sundown, for at sundown the undead can move. I waited here

09:13:27.468 --> 09:13:34.488
all night till the sun rose, but I saw nothing. It was most probable that it was because I had

09:13:34.488 --> 09:13:40.188
lain over the clamps of those doors garlic which the undead cannot bear, and other things which

09:13:40.188 --> 09:13:47.608
they shun. Last night there was no exodus, so tonight before sundown I took away my garlic

09:13:47.608 --> 09:13:57.388
and other things, and so it is we find this coffin empty. But bear with me. So far there is much

09:13:57.388 --> 09:14:05.668
strange. Wait you with me outside, unseen and unheard, and things much stranger are yet to be.

09:14:06.368 --> 09:14:14.488
So here he shut the dark slide of his lantern. Now to the outside. He opened the door and we

09:14:14.488 --> 09:14:26.328
filed out, he coming last and locking the door behind him. Oh, but it seemed fresh and pure in

09:14:26.328 --> 09:14:32.308
it was to see the clouds race by and the passing gleams of the moonlight between the scudding

09:14:32.308 --> 09:14:40.188
crowds crossing and passing, like the gladness and sorrow of a man's life. How sweet it was to

09:14:40.188 --> 09:14:46.908
breathe the fresh air that had no taint of death and decay, how humanizing to see the red lighting

09:14:46.908 --> 09:14:53.668
of the sky beyond the hill, and to hear far away the muffled roar that marks the life of a great

09:14:53.668 --> 09:15:01.748
city. Each in his own way was solemn and overcome. Arthur was silent and was, I could see,

09:15:02.168 --> 09:15:09.368
striving to grasp the purpose and inner meaning of the mystery. I was myself tolerably patient and

09:15:09.368 --> 09:15:16.448
half inclined again to throw aside doubt and to accept Van Helsing's conclusions. Quincy Morris

09:15:16.448 --> 09:15:22.648
was phlegmatic in the way of a man who accepts all things and accepts them in the spirit of cool

09:15:22.648 --> 09:15:30.348
bravery with hazard of all he has at stake. Not being able to smoke, he cut himself a good size

09:15:30.348 --> 09:15:38.628
plug of tobacco and began to chew. As to Van Helsing, he was employed in a definite way.

09:15:39.028 --> 09:15:45.888
First, he took from his bag a mass of what looked like thin wafer-like biscuit, which was carefully

09:15:45.888 --> 09:15:52.188
rolled up in a white napkin. Next, he took out a double handful of some whitish stuff,

09:15:52.548 --> 09:15:58.588
like dough or putty. He crumbled the wafer up fine and worked it into the mass between his hands.

09:15:58.848 --> 09:16:05.028
This he then took, and rolling it into thin strips, began to lay them into the crevices

09:16:05.028 --> 09:16:11.488
between the door and its setting in the tomb. I was somewhat puzzled by this, and being close,

09:16:11.488 --> 09:16:16.628
asked him what it was that he was doing. Arthur and Quincy drew near also,

09:16:16.948 --> 09:16:20.008
as they too were curious. He answered,

09:16:20.648 --> 09:16:24.588
I am closing the tomb so that the undead may not enter.

09:16:25.668 --> 09:16:28.128
And is that stuff you have there going to do it?

09:16:28.288 --> 09:16:29.048
It is.

09:16:31.008 --> 09:16:35.548
What is that which you are using? This time the question came by Arthur.

09:16:36.108 --> 09:16:39.328
Van Helsing reverently lifted his hat as he answered,

09:16:39.628 --> 09:16:45.928
The host, I brought it from Amsterdam. I have an indulgence.

09:16:47.268 --> 09:16:53.068
It was an answer that appalled the most sceptical of us, and we felt individually that in the

09:16:53.068 --> 09:16:59.928
presence of such earnest purpose as the Professor's, a purpose which could thus use the, to him,

09:16:59.928 --> 09:17:06.728
most sacred of things, it was impossible to distrust. In respectful silence,

09:17:06.948 --> 09:17:12.028
we took the places assigned to us close round the tomb, but hidden from sight of anyone approaching.

09:17:12.788 --> 09:17:18.528
I pitied the others, especially Arthur. I had myself been apprenticed by my former

09:17:18.528 --> 09:17:24.868
visits to this watching horror, and yet I, who had up to an hour ago repudiated the proofs,

09:17:24.868 --> 09:17:31.568
felt my heart sink within me. Never did tombs look so ghastly white.

09:17:32.068 --> 09:17:37.028
Never did cypress or yew or juniper seem the embodiment of funeral gloom.

09:17:37.748 --> 09:17:41.948
Never did tree or grass wave or rustle so ominously.

09:17:42.748 --> 09:17:48.728
Never did bow creak so mysteriously, and never did the faraway howling of dogs

09:17:48.728 --> 09:17:51.848
send such a woeful presage through the night.

09:17:52.488 --> 09:18:00.228
There was a long spell of silence, big, aching, void, and then from the Professor Rakeen,

09:18:02.708 --> 09:18:09.368
he pointed, and far down the avenue of yews we saw a white figure advance, a dim white figure,

09:18:09.768 --> 09:18:16.788
which held something dark at its breast. The figure stopped, and at the moment a startling

09:18:16.788 --> 09:18:23.888
prominence, a dark-haired woman dressed in the seriments of the grave. We could not see

09:18:23.888 --> 09:18:30.028
the face, for it was bent down over what we saw to be a fair-haired child. There was a pause,

09:18:30.408 --> 09:18:38.268
and a sharp little cry such as a child gives in sleep, or a dog as it lies before the fire in

09:18:38.268 --> 09:18:44.288
dreams. We were starting forward, but the Professor's warning hand, seen by us as he

09:18:44.288 --> 09:18:51.268
stood behind the yew tree, kept us back, and then as we looked the white figure moved forwards again.

09:18:51.748 --> 09:18:58.868
It was now near enough for us to see clearly, and the moonlight still held. My own heart grew

09:18:58.868 --> 09:19:05.948
cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur as we recognized the features of Lucy Westenra.

09:19:07.188 --> 09:19:17.988
Lucy Westenra, but yet how changed! The sweetness was turned to adamantine, heartless cruelty,

09:19:18.348 --> 09:19:25.148
and the purity to voluptuous wantonness. Van Helsing stepped out, and obedient to his gesture

09:19:25.148 --> 09:19:31.168
we all advanced to. The four of us ranged in a line before the door of the tomb. Van Helsing

09:19:31.168 --> 09:19:33.868
raised his lantern and drew the slide.

09:19:35.608 --> 09:19:41.468
By the concentrated light that fell on Lucy's face we could see that lips were crimson with

09:19:41.468 --> 09:19:47.448
fresh blood, and that the stream had trickled over her chin and stained the purity of her long death

09:19:47.448 --> 09:19:54.788
robe. We shuddered with horror. I could see by the tremulous light that even Van Helsing's iron

09:19:54.788 --> 09:20:00.468
nerve had failed. Arthur was next to me, and if I had not seized his arm and held him up

09:20:00.468 --> 09:20:08.468
he would have fallen. When Lucy, I call the thing that was before us Lucy because it bore her shape,

09:20:09.268 --> 09:20:14.088
saw us she drew back with an angry snarl such as a cat gives when taken unawares,

09:20:14.808 --> 09:20:21.048
then her eyes ranged over us. Lucy's eyes in form and color, but Lucy's eyes

09:20:21.048 --> 09:20:28.428
unclean and full of hellfire instead of the pure gentle orbs we knew. At that moment

09:20:28.428 --> 09:20:35.588
the remnant of my love passed into hate and loathing. Had she then to be killed I could have

09:20:35.588 --> 09:20:41.348
done it with savage delight. As she looked her eyes blazed with unholy light and the

09:20:41.348 --> 09:20:48.028
face became wreathed with a voluptuous smile. Oh God how it made me shudder to see it!

09:20:48.728 --> 09:20:53.808
With a careless motion she flung to the ground, callous as a devil, the child that up to now

09:20:53.808 --> 09:20:59.028
she had clutched strenuously to her breast, growling over it as a dog growls over a bone.

09:21:00.288 --> 09:21:07.588
The child gave a sharp cry and lay there moaning. There was a cold bloodedness in the act which

09:21:07.588 --> 09:21:13.628
wrung a groan from Arthur. When she advanced to him with outstretched arms and a wanton smile he

09:21:13.628 --> 09:21:19.488
fell back and hid his face in his hands. She still advanced however with a languorous,

09:21:19.488 --> 09:21:25.928
voluptuous grace said, come to me Arthur, leave these others and come to me.

09:21:26.528 --> 09:21:33.368
My arms are hungry for you, come and we can rest together, come my husband, come.

09:21:34.568 --> 09:21:41.688
There was something diabolically sweet in her tones, something of the tinkling of glass once

09:21:41.688 --> 09:21:47.208
struck which rang through the brains even of us who heard the words addressed to another.

09:21:47.208 --> 09:21:54.888
As for Arthur he seemed under a spell. Moving his hands from his face he opened wide his arms.

09:21:55.128 --> 09:22:01.028
She was leaping for them when Van Helsing sprang forward and held between them his little golden

09:22:01.028 --> 09:22:08.408
crucifix. She recoiled from it and with a suddenly distorted face full of rage dashed past him as if

09:22:08.408 --> 09:22:15.128
to enter the tomb. When within a foot or two of the door however she stopped, as if arrested by

09:22:15.128 --> 09:22:21.488
some irresistible force, then she turned and her face was shown in a clear burst of moonlight and

09:22:21.488 --> 09:22:28.188
by the lamp which had now no quiver from Van Helsing's nerves. Never did I see such baffled

09:22:28.188 --> 09:22:34.308
malice on a face and never, I trust, shall such ever be seen again by my mortal eyes.

09:22:35.448 --> 09:22:41.248
The beautiful colour became livid, the eyes seemed to throw out sparks of hellfire,

09:22:41.248 --> 09:22:47.468
the brows were wrinkled as though the folds of flesh were the coils of Medusa's snakes and the

09:22:47.468 --> 09:22:55.928
lovely blood-stained mouth grew to an open square as in the passion masks of the Greeks and Japanese.

09:22:56.608 --> 09:23:02.688
If ever a face meant death, if looks could kill, we saw it at that moment.

09:23:03.448 --> 09:23:09.168
And so for full half a minute, which seemed in eternity, she remained between the lifted

09:23:09.168 --> 09:23:16.168
crucifix and the sacred closing of her means of entry. Van Helsing broke the silence by asking

09:23:16.168 --> 09:23:24.908
Arthur. Answer me, oh my friend, am I to proceed in my work? Do as you will, friend, do as you will,

09:23:24.928 --> 09:23:29.828
there can be no horror like this ever any more, and he groaned in spirit.

09:23:31.308 --> 09:23:37.368
Quincy and I simultaneously moved towards him and took his arms. We could hear the click of

09:23:37.368 --> 09:23:44.828
the closing lantern as Van Helsing held it down. Coming close to the tomb, he began to remove from

09:23:44.828 --> 09:23:50.888
the chink some of the sacred emblem which he had placed there. We all looked on with horrified

09:23:50.888 --> 09:23:57.388
amazement as we saw when he stood back, the woman, with a corporeal body as real at that moment as

09:23:57.388 --> 09:24:04.548
our own, pass through the interstice where a scarce knife-blade could have gone. We all felt

09:24:04.548 --> 09:24:10.028
glad sense of relief when we saw the Professor calmly restoring the strings of putty to the edges

09:24:10.028 --> 09:24:16.848
of the door. When this was done, he lifted the child and said, Come now, my friends,

09:24:17.488 --> 09:24:24.228
we can do no more till tomorrow. There is a funeral at noon, so here we shall all come before long

09:24:24.228 --> 09:24:30.528
after that. The friends of the dead will all be gone by two, and when the sexton locks the gate

09:24:30.528 --> 09:24:37.248
we shall remain. Then there is more to do, but not like this of tonight. As for this little one,

09:24:37.748 --> 09:24:42.908
he is not much harmed, and by tomorrow night he shall be well. We shall leave him where the police

09:24:42.908 --> 09:24:48.528
will find him, as on the other night, and then to home. Coming close to Arthur, he said,

09:24:49.148 --> 09:24:54.068
My friend Arthur, you have had a sore trial, but after, when you look back,

09:24:54.408 --> 09:24:59.228
you will see how it was necessary. You are now in the bitter waters, my child.

09:24:59.228 --> 09:25:05.628
By this time tomorrow you will, please God, have passed them, and have drunk of the sweet water,

09:25:05.848 --> 09:25:13.548
so do not mourn over much. Till then, I shall not ask you to forgive me. Arthur and Quincy came home

09:25:13.548 --> 09:25:19.788
with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way. We had left behind the child in safety and

09:25:19.788 --> 09:25:25.868
tired, so we all slept with more or less reality of sleep.

09:25:26.868 --> 09:25:29.328
29 September Night

09:25:29.988 --> 09:25:35.788
A little before twelve o'clock we three, Arthur, Quincy Morris, and myself, called for the

09:25:35.788 --> 09:25:42.568
Professor. It was odd to notice that, by common consent, we had all put on black clothes.

09:25:42.948 --> 09:25:49.068
Of course Arthur wore black, for he was in deep mourning, but the rest of us wore it by instinct.

09:25:49.788 --> 09:25:55.148
We got to the graveyard by half past one and strolled about, keeping out of official observation,

09:25:55.368 --> 09:25:58.728
so that when the gravediggers had completed their task and the sexton,

09:25:59.088 --> 09:26:05.088
under the belief that everyone had gone, had locked the gate, we had the place all to ourselves.

09:26:07.408 --> 09:26:14.388
Van Helsing, instead of his little black bag, had with him a long leather one, something like a

09:26:14.388 --> 09:26:21.548
cricketing bag. It was manifestly of fair weight. When we were alone and had heard the last of the

09:26:21.548 --> 09:26:29.388
footsteps die out up the road, we silently, as if by ordered intention, followed the Professor to the

09:26:29.388 --> 09:26:36.608
tomb. He unlocked the door and we entered, closing it behind us. Then he took from his bag the lantern

09:26:36.608 --> 09:26:43.888
which he lit, and also two wax candles which, when lighted, he stuck by melting their own ends on

09:26:43.888 --> 09:26:50.908
other coffins, so that they might give light sufficient to work by. When he again lifted the

09:26:50.908 --> 09:26:57.468
lid off Lucy's coffin, we all looked, Arthur trembling like an aspen, and saw that the corpse

09:26:57.468 --> 09:27:04.648
lay there in all its deadly beauty. But there was no love in my own heart, nothing but loathing for

09:27:04.648 --> 09:27:10.868
the foul thing which had taken Lucy's shape without her soul. I could see even Arthur's face grow hard

09:27:10.868 --> 09:27:18.288
as he looked. Presently, he said to Van Helsing, is this really Lucy's body, or only a demon in her

09:27:18.288 --> 09:27:27.928
shape? It is her body, and yet not it. But wait a while, and you shall see her as she was, and is.

09:27:29.408 --> 09:27:36.168
She seemed like a nightmare of Lucy as she lay there, the pointed teeth, the blood-stained,

09:27:36.168 --> 09:27:42.848
voluptuous mouth, which made one shudder to see the whole carnal and unspirited appearance,

09:27:43.328 --> 09:27:51.768
seeming like a devilish mockery of Lucy's sweet purity. Van Helsing, with his usual methodicalness,

09:27:52.248 --> 09:27:58.688
began taking the various contents from his bag and placing them ready for use. First he took out

09:27:58.688 --> 09:28:05.828
a soldering iron, and some plumbing solder, and then a small oil lamp which gave out when lit in

09:28:05.828 --> 09:28:12.228
the corner of the tomb, gas which burned at a fierce heat with a blue flame, then his operating

09:28:12.228 --> 09:28:21.108
knives which he placed to hand, and last a round wooden stake, some two and a half or three inches

09:28:21.108 --> 09:28:28.388
thick and about three feet long. One end of it was hardened by charring in the fire and was sharpened

09:28:28.388 --> 09:28:35.288
to a fine point. With this stake came a heavy hammer, such as in households as used in the coal

09:28:35.288 --> 09:28:42.388
for breaking the lumps. To me, a doctor's preparations for work of any kind of stimulating,

09:28:42.728 --> 09:28:48.828
embracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincy was to cause them a sort of

09:28:48.828 --> 09:28:53.848
consternation. They both, however, kept their courage and remained silent and quiet.

09:28:54.748 --> 09:28:57.208
When all was ready, Van Helsing said,

09:28:58.008 --> 09:29:00.968
Before we do anything, let me tell you this.

09:29:02.628 --> 09:29:08.228
It is out of the lore and experience of the ancients and of all those who have studied the

09:29:08.228 --> 09:29:15.908
powers of the undead. When they become such, there comes with the chance the curse of immortality.

09:29:15.908 --> 09:29:23.548
They cannot die, but must go on, age after age, adding new victims and multiplying the evils of

09:29:23.548 --> 09:29:30.908
the world. For all that die from the praying of the undead become themselves undead and pray on

09:29:30.908 --> 09:29:37.748
their kind. And so the circle goes on, ever widening, like as the ripples from a stone thrown in the

09:29:37.748 --> 09:29:47.898
water. Friend Arthur, if you had met that kiss which you know of before poor Lucy die, or again,

09:29:48.458 --> 09:29:55.278
last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become

09:29:55.278 --> 09:30:03.598
Nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would for all time make many more of those undeads

09:30:03.598 --> 09:30:10.458
that so have filled us with horror. The career of this so unhappy dear lady has but just begun.

09:30:11.318 --> 09:30:16.978
Those children whose blood she sucked are not as yet so much the worst, but if she lives on,

09:30:17.738 --> 09:30:25.358
more and more they lose their blood, and by her power over them they come to her, and so she draw

09:30:25.358 --> 09:30:34.018
their blood with that so wicked mouth. But if she die in truth, then all cease. The tiny wounds of

09:30:34.018 --> 09:30:39.698
the throats disappear, and they go back to their play, unknowing ever of what has been.

09:30:40.418 --> 09:30:47.138
But of the most blessed of all, when this now undead be made to rest as true dead,

09:30:47.698 --> 09:30:55.298
then the soul of the poor lady whom we love shall again be free. Instead of working wickedness by

09:30:55.298 --> 09:31:02.498
night, and growing more debased in the assimilating of it by day, she shall take her place with the

09:31:02.498 --> 09:31:09.198
other angels, so that, my friend, it will be a blessed hand for her that shall strike the blow

09:31:09.198 --> 09:31:17.478
that sets her free. To this I am willing. But is the nun amongst us who has a better right?

09:31:18.718 --> 09:31:24.658
Will it be no joy to think of hereafter in the silence of the night when sleep is not?

09:31:25.518 --> 09:31:32.198
It was my hand that sent her to the stars. It was the hand of him that loved her best.

09:31:33.158 --> 09:31:39.898
The hand that of all she would herself have chosen had it been to her to choose.

09:31:41.358 --> 09:31:45.458
Tell me if there is one such amongst us.

09:31:47.118 --> 09:31:55.478
We all looked at Arthur. He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his

09:31:55.478 --> 09:32:02.538
should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy and not unholy memory.

09:32:03.558 --> 09:32:08.418
He stepped forward and said bravely, though his hand trembled and his face was pale as snow,

09:32:09.438 --> 09:32:13.738
My true friend, from the bottom of my broken heart I thank you.

09:32:14.658 --> 09:32:17.498
Tell me what I am to do and I shall not falter.

09:32:18.478 --> 09:32:25.078
Van Helsing laid a hand on his shoulder and said, Brave lad, a moment's courage and it is done.

09:32:25.478 --> 09:32:33.318
This stake must be driven through her. It will be a fearful ordeal. Be not deceived in that.

09:32:34.058 --> 09:32:39.718
But it will only be a short time, and you will then rejoice more than your pain was great.

09:32:40.178 --> 09:32:46.598
From this grim tomb you will emerge as though you tread on air, but you must not falter

09:32:47.258 --> 09:32:52.778
when once you have begun. Only think that we, your true friends, are round you,

09:32:52.778 --> 09:32:55.858
and that we pray for you all the time.

09:32:57.338 --> 09:33:00.798
Go on, said Arthur hoarsely. Tell me what I am to do.

09:33:02.618 --> 09:33:07.078
Take this stake in your left hand, ready to place the point over the heart and then the

09:33:07.078 --> 09:33:12.618
hammer in your right. Then when we begin our prayer for the dead I shall read him.

09:33:13.178 --> 09:33:20.478
I have here the book, and the others shall follow. Strike in God's name, that so all may be well with

09:33:20.478 --> 09:33:28.478
dead that we love, and that the undead pass away. Arthur took the stake in the hammer,

09:33:29.238 --> 09:33:34.798
and when once his mind was set on action his hands never trembled nor even quivered.

09:33:35.658 --> 09:33:41.398
Van Helsing opened his missile and began to read, and Quincy and I followed as well we could.

09:33:42.498 --> 09:33:49.638
Arthur placed the point over the heart, and as I looked I could see its dint in the white flesh.

09:33:51.358 --> 09:33:55.298
Then he struck with all his might.

09:33:56.338 --> 09:34:02.058
The thing in the coffin writhed, and a hideous blood-curdling screech came from the open red

09:34:02.058 --> 09:34:08.438
lips. The body shook and quivered and twisted in wild contortions. The sharp teeth champed

09:34:08.438 --> 09:34:13.598
together till the lips were cut, and the mouth was smeared with a crimson foam. But Arthur

09:34:15.078 --> 09:34:20.918
never faltered. He looked like a figure of Thor as his untumbling arm rose and fell,

09:34:20.998 --> 09:34:25.798
driving deeper and deeper the mercy-bearing stake whilst the blood from the pierced heart

09:34:25.798 --> 09:34:31.798
welled and spurted up around it. His face was set, and high duty seemed to shine through it.

09:34:32.018 --> 09:34:36.718
The sight of it gave us courage so that our voices seemed to ring through the little vault,

09:34:36.718 --> 09:34:43.858
and then the writhing and quivering of the body became less, and the teeth seemed to champ,

09:34:44.718 --> 09:34:50.778
and the face to quiver. Finally it lay still.

09:34:52.178 --> 09:34:55.338
The terrible task was over.

09:34:57.598 --> 09:35:03.278
The hammer fell from Arthur's hand. He reeled and would have fallen had we not caught him.

09:35:03.918 --> 09:35:09.238
The great drops of sweat sprang from his forehead, and his breath came in broken gasps.

09:35:09.638 --> 09:35:15.598
It had indeed been an awful strain on him, and had he not been forced to his task by more than

09:35:15.598 --> 09:35:22.318
human considerations, he could never have gone through with it. For a few minutes we were so

09:35:22.318 --> 09:35:28.798
taken up with him that we did not look toward the coffin. When we did, however, a murmur of

09:35:28.798 --> 09:35:34.638
startled surprise ran from one to the other of us. We gazed so eagerly that Arthur rose,

09:35:35.078 --> 09:35:42.258
for he had been seated on the ground, and came and looked too, and then a glad strange light

09:35:42.258 --> 09:35:50.218
broke over his face and dispelled altogether the gloom of horror that lay upon it. There,

09:35:50.478 --> 09:35:56.078
in the coffin, lay no longer the foul thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate

09:35:56.078 --> 09:36:02.358
that the work of her destruction was yield as a privilege, the one best entitled to it,

09:36:02.378 --> 09:36:09.518
but Lucy, as we had seen her in life with her face of unequal sweetness and purity.

09:36:10.818 --> 09:36:17.138
True that there were there, as we had seen them in life, the traces of care and pain and waste,

09:36:17.958 --> 09:36:22.638
but these were all dear to us, for they marked her truth to what we knew.

09:36:23.358 --> 09:36:30.558
One and all we felt that the holy calm that lay like sunshine over the wasted face and

09:36:30.558 --> 09:36:36.218
form was only an earthly token and symbol of the calm that was to reign forever.

09:36:37.478 --> 09:36:41.758
Van Helsing came and laid his hand on Arthur's shoulder and said to him,

09:36:42.598 --> 09:36:48.138
And now, Arthur, my friend dear lad, am I not forgiven?

09:36:49.698 --> 09:36:55.418
The reaction of terrible strain came as he took the old man's hand in his,

09:36:56.258 --> 09:37:03.418
raised it to his lips, pressed it and said, Forgiven! God bless you,

09:37:03.718 --> 09:37:07.978
that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.

09:37:09.458 --> 09:37:15.478
He put his hands on the professor's shoulders and, laying his head on his breast, cried

09:37:15.478 --> 09:37:25.678
for a while, silently, whilst we stood, unmoving. When he raised his head, Van Helsing said to him,

09:37:26.098 --> 09:37:34.178
And now, my child, you may kiss her, kiss her dead lips, if you will, as she would have you to,

09:37:34.178 --> 09:37:42.878
if for her to choose, for she is not a grinning devil now, not any more a foul thing for all

09:37:42.878 --> 09:37:52.358
eternity, no longer. She is the devil's undead, she is God's true dead, whose soul is with him.

09:37:53.658 --> 09:37:59.658
Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincy out of the tomb.

09:38:00.258 --> 09:38:05.358
The professor and I saw the top off the stake, leaving the point of it in the body.

09:38:06.518 --> 09:38:12.298
Then we cut off the head and filled the mouth with garlic. We started up the leaden coffin,

09:38:13.118 --> 09:38:17.358
screwed on the coffin lid, and gathered up our belongings, came away.

09:38:18.118 --> 09:38:21.858
When the professor locked the door, he gave the key to Arthur.

09:38:23.378 --> 09:38:31.838
Outside, the air was sweet, the sun shone and the birds sang, and it seemed as if all nature were

09:38:31.838 --> 09:38:39.178
tuned to a different pitch. There was gladness and mirth and peace everywhere, for we were at

09:38:39.178 --> 09:38:45.398
rest ourselves on one account, and we were glad, though it was with a tempered joy.

09:38:46.298 --> 09:38:54.598
Before we moved away, Van Helsing said, Now, my friends, one step of our work is done,

09:38:55.298 --> 09:39:02.558
one the most harrowing to ourselves, but there remains a greater task, to find out the author

09:39:02.898 --> 09:39:13.718
of all this our sorrow, and to stamp him out. I have clues which we can follow, but it is a

09:39:13.718 --> 09:39:21.338
danger in it, and pain. Shall you not all help me? We have learned to believe, all of us.

09:39:22.198 --> 09:39:31.958
Is it not so? And since so, do we not see our duty? Yes, and do we not promise to go on to the bitter

09:39:31.958 --> 09:39:42.158
end? Each in turn we took his hand, and the promise was made. Then said the professor as

09:39:42.158 --> 09:39:48.078
we moved off. Two nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven o'clock with

09:39:48.078 --> 09:39:56.238
friend John. I shall entreat two others, two that you know not as yet, and I shall be ready to all

09:39:56.238 --> 09:40:04.918
our work show and our plans unfold. Friend John, you come with me home, for I have much to consult

09:40:04.918 --> 09:40:12.118
you about, and you can help. Tonight I leave for Amsterdam, but shall return to-morrow night.

09:40:13.618 --> 09:40:22.078
And then begins our great quest. But first I shall have much to say, so that you may know what to do

09:40:22.078 --> 09:40:28.718
and what to dread. Then our promise shall be made to each other anew, but there is a terrible task

09:40:28.718 --> 09:40:35.898
before us, and once our feet are on the plowshare, we must not draw back.

09:41:02.092 --> 09:41:07.032
Doctor Seward's diary continued.

09:41:08.032 --> 09:41:13.752
When we arrived at the Berkeley Hotel, Van Helsing found a telegram waiting for him.

09:41:14.432 --> 09:41:23.432
I'm coming up by train. Jonathan at Whitby. Important news. Mina Harker. The Professor was delighted.

09:41:24.452 --> 09:41:31.752
Ah, that wonderful Madame Mina, he said. Pearl among women. She arrive, but I cannot stay.

09:41:31.752 --> 09:41:36.432
She must go to your house, friend John. You must meet her at the station.

09:41:37.252 --> 09:41:40.052
Telegraph her en route, so that she may be prepared.

09:41:41.032 --> 09:41:43.772
When the wire was dispatched, he had a cup of tea.

09:41:44.712 --> 09:41:54.652
Over it, he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs Harker's diary at Whitby.

09:41:54.652 --> 09:42:05.812
Take these, he said, and study them well. When I have returned, you will be master of all the facts, and we can then better enter on our inquisition.

09:42:06.452 --> 09:42:10.532
Keep them safe, for there is in them much of treasure.

09:42:11.472 --> 09:42:16.632
You will need all your faith, even you who have had such an experience as that of today.

09:42:17.272 --> 09:42:23.292
What is here told? He laid his hand heavily and gravely on the packet of papers as he spoke.

09:42:23.932 --> 09:42:31.812
May be the beginning of the end to you and me and many another, or it may sound the knell of the undead who walk the earth.

09:42:32.512 --> 09:42:41.932
Read all, I pray you, with the open mind, and if you can add in any way to the story here told, do so, for it is all important.

09:42:42.272 --> 09:42:45.892
You have kept a diary of all these so strange things, is it not so?

09:42:45.892 --> 09:42:50.212
Yes, then we shall go through all these together when we meet.

09:42:50.872 --> 09:42:55.272
He then made ready for his departure, and shortly drove off to Liverpool Street.

09:42:56.172 --> 09:43:01.592
I took my way to Paddington, where I arrived about fifteen minutes before the train came in.

09:43:02.272 --> 09:43:10.932
The crowd melted away after the bustling fashion common to arrival platforms, and I was beginning to feel uneasy lest I might miss my guest,

09:43:10.932 --> 09:43:16.592
when a sweet-faced dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and after a quick glance said,

09:43:17.152 --> 09:43:18.772
Doctor Seward, is it not?

09:43:19.192 --> 09:43:24.372
And you are Mrs Harker, I answered at once, whereupon she held out her hand.

09:43:25.012 --> 09:43:32.692
I knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy, but she stopped suddenly, and a quick blush overspread her face.

09:43:33.792 --> 09:43:40.192
The blush that rose to my own cheeks somehow set us both at ease, for it was a tacit answer to her own.

09:43:40.192 --> 09:43:46.712
I got her luggage, which included a typewriter, and we took the underground to Fenchurch Street,

09:43:47.212 --> 09:43:54.172
after I had sent a wire to my housekeeper to have a sitting-room and a bedroom prepared at once for Mrs Harker.

09:43:55.032 --> 09:43:59.652
In due time we arrived. She knew, of course, that the place was a lunatic asylum,

09:44:00.072 --> 09:44:03.812
but I could see that she was unable to repress her shudder when we entered.

09:44:03.812 --> 09:44:10.272
She told me that, if she might, she would come presently to my study, and she had much to say.

09:44:10.732 --> 09:44:16.112
So, here I am, finishing my entry in my phonograph diary, whilst I await her.

09:44:16.852 --> 09:44:23.452
As yet, I have not had the chance of looking at the papers which Van Helsing left with me, though they lie open before me.

09:44:23.692 --> 09:44:28.352
I must get her interested in something, so that I may have an opportunity of reading them.

09:44:28.352 --> 09:44:33.572
She does not know how precious time is, or what a task we have in hand.

09:44:34.252 --> 09:44:37.872
I must be careful not to frighten her. Here she is.

09:44:38.672 --> 09:44:41.692
Mina Harker's Journal. 29th September.

09:44:42.552 --> 09:44:46.512
After I had tidied myself, I went down to Dr Seward's study.

09:44:47.512 --> 09:44:51.592
At the door I paused a moment, for I thought I heard him talking with someone.

09:44:51.592 --> 09:45:00.252
As, however, he had pressed me to be quick, I knocked at the door, and, on his calling out, come in, I entered.

09:45:00.712 --> 09:45:03.792
To my intense surprise, there was no one with him.

09:45:04.132 --> 09:45:11.172
He was quite alone, and on the table opposite him was what I knew at once from the description to be a phonograph.

09:45:11.892 --> 09:45:14.632
I had never seen one, and was much interested.

09:45:14.632 --> 09:45:17.712
I hope I did not keep you waiting, I said.

09:45:18.192 --> 09:45:23.072
But I stayed at the door, as I heard you talking, and thought there was someone with you.

09:45:23.452 --> 09:45:26.792
Oh, he replied with a smile. I was only entering my diary.

09:45:27.452 --> 09:45:29.992
Your diary? I asked him in surprise.

09:45:30.832 --> 09:45:33.492
Yes, he answered. I keep it in this.

09:45:34.152 --> 09:45:36.992
As he spoke, he laid his hand on the phonograph.

09:45:37.652 --> 09:45:43.292
I felt quite excited over it, and blurted out, Why, this beats even shorthand.

09:45:43.292 --> 09:45:45.212
May I hear it say something?

09:45:46.092 --> 09:45:50.572
Certainly, he replied with alacrity, and stood up to put it in train for speaking.

09:45:51.472 --> 09:45:55.132
Then he paused, and a troubled look overspread his face.

09:45:55.652 --> 09:46:05.472
The fact is, he began awkwardly, I only keep my diary in it, and as it is entirely, almost entirely, about my cases, it may be awkward.

09:46:06.792 --> 09:46:11.552
That is, I mean, he stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment.

09:46:12.212 --> 09:46:19.612
You helped to attend dear Lucy at the end. Let me hear how she died. For all that I know of her, I shall be very grateful.

09:46:20.252 --> 09:46:22.692
She was very, very dear to me.

09:46:23.512 --> 09:46:31.112
To my surprise, he answered, with a horostruck look in his face, Tell you of her death, not for the wide world.

09:46:31.692 --> 09:46:36.032
Why not? I asked, for some grave terrible feeling was coming over me.

09:46:36.552 --> 09:46:40.992
Again he paused, and I could see that he was trying to invent an excuse.

09:46:40.992 --> 09:46:49.272
At length, he stammered out, You see, I do not know how to pick out any particular part of the diary.

09:46:49.752 --> 09:46:52.972
Even while he was speaking, an idea dawned upon him.

09:46:53.132 --> 09:46:59.952
And, he said, with an unconscious simplicity, in a quite different voice, and with the naivety of a child,

09:47:00.572 --> 09:47:04.172
That's quite true. Upon my honour. Honest Indian.

09:47:04.692 --> 09:47:07.432
I could not but smile, at which he grimaced.

09:47:07.432 --> 09:47:10.252
I gave myself away that time, he said.

09:47:10.792 --> 09:47:14.512
But do you know that although I have kept the diary for months past,

09:47:14.992 --> 09:47:20.372
It never once struck me how I was going to find any particular part of it, in case I wanted to look it up.

09:47:20.952 --> 09:47:25.572
By this time, my mind was made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy

09:47:25.572 --> 09:47:30.112
Might have something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible being.

09:47:30.112 --> 09:47:36.772
And I said, boldly, Then, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you, on my typewriter.

09:47:37.652 --> 09:47:46.732
He grew to a positively deftly pallor, as he said, No, no, no, for all the world, I wouldn't let you know that terrible story.

09:47:47.412 --> 09:47:50.192
Then it was terrible. My intuition was right.

09:47:50.792 --> 09:47:57.892
For a moment I thought, and as my eyes ranged the room, unconsciously looking for something, or some opportunity to aid me,

09:47:57.892 --> 09:48:01.192
They lit on the great batch of typewriting on the table.

09:48:01.672 --> 09:48:06.652
His eyes caught the look in mine, and without his thinking followed their direction.

09:48:07.432 --> 09:48:10.172
As he saw the parcel, he realized my meaning.

09:48:10.772 --> 09:48:12.612
You do not know me, I said.

09:48:13.332 --> 09:48:19.792
When you have read these papers, my own diary, and my husband's also, which I have typed, you will know me better.

09:48:20.412 --> 09:48:24.772
I have not faltered in giving every thought of my own heart in this cause.

09:48:24.772 --> 09:48:30.812
But, of course, you do not know me yet, and I must not expect you to trust me so far.

09:48:31.592 --> 09:48:36.152
He is certainly a man of noble nature. Poor dear Lucy was right about him.

09:48:36.552 --> 09:48:46.432
He stood up and opened a large drawer, in which were arranged, in order, a number of hollow cylinders of metal, covered with dark wax, and said,

09:48:46.432 --> 09:48:55.932
You are quite right. I did not trust you, because I did not know you, but I know you now, and let me say that I should have known you long ago.

09:48:56.612 --> 09:49:00.112
I know that Lucy told you of me. She told me of you, too.

09:49:00.792 --> 09:49:02.892
May I make the only atonement in my power?

09:49:03.752 --> 09:49:10.432
Take the cylinders, and hear them. The first half-dozen of them are personal to me, and they will not horrify you.

09:49:11.232 --> 09:49:12.932
Then you will know me better.

09:49:13.532 --> 09:49:22.452
Dinner will by then be ready. In the meantime, I shall read over some of these documents, and shall be better able to understand certain things.

09:49:23.712 --> 09:49:28.212
He carried the phonograph himself up to my sitting-room, and adjusted it for me.

09:49:28.792 --> 09:49:37.752
Now I shall learn something pleasant, I am sure, for it will tell me the other side of a true love episode of which I know one side already.

09:49:38.912 --> 09:49:41.752
Dr. Seward's Diary, 29th September

09:49:42.432 --> 09:49:50.472
I was so absorbed in that wonderful diary of Jonathan Harker, and that of his wife, that I let the time run on without thinking.

09:49:51.612 --> 09:50:01.412
Mrs. Harker was not down when the maid came to announce dinner, so I said, She is possibly tired, let dinner wait an hour, and I went on with my work.

09:50:02.372 --> 09:50:05.752
I had just finished Mrs. Harker's diary, when she came in.

09:50:05.752 --> 09:50:14.432
She looked sweetly pretty, but very sad, and her eyes were flushed with crying. This somehow moved me much.

09:50:15.292 --> 09:50:26.352
Of late I have had cause for tears, God knows, but the relief of them was denied me, and now the sight of those sweet eyes, brightened by recent tears, went straight to my heart.

09:50:27.192 --> 09:50:32.732
So, I said as gently as I could, I greatly fear I have distressed you.

09:50:32.732 --> 09:50:42.692
Oh no, not distressed me, she replied, but I have been more touched than I can say by your grief. That is a wonderful machine, but it is cruelly true.

09:50:43.392 --> 09:50:53.992
It told me, in its very tones, the anguish of your heart. It was like a soul crying out to Almighty God. No one must hear them spoken ever again.

09:50:54.732 --> 09:51:03.912
See, I have tried to be useful. I have copied out the words on my typewriter, and none of her need now hear your heartbeat as I did.

09:51:04.812 --> 09:51:08.972
No one need ever know, shall ever know, I said in a low voice.

09:51:10.492 --> 09:51:15.972
She laid her hand on mine, and said, very gravely, Ah, but they must.

09:51:17.172 --> 09:51:19.932
Must? But why? I asked.

09:51:20.872 --> 09:51:26.992
Because it is a part of the terrible story, a part of poor Lucy's death, and all that led to it.

09:51:27.492 --> 09:51:36.692
Because, in the struggle which we have before us, to rid the earth of this terrible monster, we must have all the knowledge, and all the help, which we can get.

09:51:37.292 --> 09:51:47.352
I think that the cylinders which you gave me contained more than you intended me to know, but I can see that there are, in your record, many lights to this dark mystery.

09:51:48.072 --> 09:52:02.552
You will let me help, will you not? I know all up to a certain point, and I see already that your diary only took me to the 7th of September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being wrought out.

09:52:02.552 --> 09:52:08.292
Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.

09:52:08.692 --> 09:52:13.632
He has gone to Whitby to get more information, and he will be here tomorrow to help us.

09:52:14.372 --> 09:52:23.252
We need to have no secrets amongst us. Working together, and with absolute trust, we can surely be stronger than if some of us were in the dark.

09:52:23.752 --> 09:52:32.572
She looked at me so appealingly, and at the same time manifested such courage and resolution in her bearing, that I gave in at once to her wishes.

09:52:33.572 --> 09:52:39.512
You shall, I said, do as you like in the matter. God forgive me if I do wrong.

09:52:40.032 --> 09:52:50.612
There are terrible things yet to learn of, but if you have so far travelled on the road to poor Lucy's death, you will not be content, I know, to remain in the dark.

09:52:50.612 --> 09:52:55.852
Nay, the end, the very end, may give you a gleam of peace.

09:52:56.532 --> 09:53:03.732
Come, there is dinner. We must keep one another strong for what is before us. We have a cruel and dreadful task.

09:53:04.372 --> 09:53:14.812
When you have eaten, you shall learn the rest, and I shall answer any questions you ask, if there be anything which you do not understand, though it was apparent to us who were present.

09:53:14.812 --> 09:53:18.252
Mina Harker's Journal, 29th September

09:53:18.992 --> 09:53:22.312
After dinner, I came with Dr Seward to his study.

09:53:23.532 --> 09:53:35.072
He brought back the phonograph from my room, and I took a chair and arranged the phonograph so that I could touch it without getting up, and showed me how to stop it in case I should want to pause.

09:53:35.692 --> 09:53:43.712
Then he very thoughtfully took a chair with his back to me, so that I might be as free as possible, and began to read.

09:53:43.712 --> 09:53:47.352
I put the forked metal to my ears and listened.

09:53:48.472 --> 09:53:55.232
When the terrible story of Lucy's death and all that followed was done, I lay back in my chair, powerless.

09:53:56.792 --> 09:53:59.672
Fortunately, I am not of a fainting disposition.

09:54:00.372 --> 09:54:14.352
When Dr Seward saw me, he jumped up with a horrified exclamation, and, hurriedly taking a case bottle from the cupboard, gave me some brandy, which, in a few minutes, somewhat restored me.

09:54:14.652 --> 09:54:27.752
My brain was all in a whirl, and only that there came, through all the multitude of horrors, the holy ray of light that my dear Lucy was at last at peace, I do not think that I could have borne it without making a scene.

09:54:27.752 --> 09:54:37.232
It is all so wild and mysterious, and strange, that if I had not known Jonathan's experience in Transylvania, I could not have believed.

09:54:38.112 --> 09:54:44.712
As it was, I didn't know what to believe, and so got out of my difficulty by attending to something else.

09:54:45.632 --> 09:54:49.232
I took the cover off my typewriter, and said to Dr Seward,

09:54:49.232 --> 09:54:54.652
Let me write this all out now. We must be ready for Dr Van Helsing when he comes.

09:54:55.312 --> 09:55:00.092
I have sent a telegram to Jonathan to come on here when he arrives in London from Whitby.

09:55:00.932 --> 09:55:10.912
In this matter, dates are everything, and I think that if we get all of our material ready, and to have every item put in chronological order, we shall have done much.

09:55:10.912 --> 09:55:18.232
You tell me that Lord Goodalming and Mr Morris are coming too. Let us be able to tell them when they come.

09:55:19.412 --> 09:55:26.472
He accordingly set the phonograph at a slow pace, and I began to type-write from the beginning of the seventeenth cylinder.

09:55:27.512 --> 09:55:33.792
I used manifold, and so took three copies of the diary, just as I had done with the rest.

09:55:34.432 --> 09:55:39.812
It was late when I got through, but Dr Seward went about his work of going his round of the patients.

09:55:40.372 --> 09:55:48.352
When he had finished, he came back and sat near me, reading, so that I did not feel too lonely whilst I worked.

09:55:48.932 --> 09:55:54.972
How good and thoughtful he is! The world seems full of good men, even if there are monsters in it.

09:55:56.052 --> 09:56:04.132
Before I left him, I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the professor's perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter.

09:56:05.172 --> 09:56:13.992
So, seeing that Dr Seward keeps his newspapers, I borrowed the files of the Westminster Gazette and the Pall Mall Gazette, and took them to my room.

09:56:14.692 --> 09:56:24.172
I remember how much the Daily Graph and the Whitby Gazette, of which I had made cuttings, had helped us to understand the terrible events at Whitby when Count Dracula landed.

09:56:24.812 --> 09:56:33.252
So I shall look through the evening papers since then, and perhaps I shall get some new light. I am not sleepy, and the work will help to keep me quiet.

09:56:34.552 --> 09:56:36.512
Dr Seward's Diary

09:56:36.512 --> 09:56:37.852
30th September

09:56:38.412 --> 09:56:49.012
Mr Harker arrived at nine o'clock. He got his wife's wire just before starting. He is uncommonly clever, if one can judge from his face, and full of energy.

09:56:49.912 --> 09:56:57.292
If this journal be true, and judging by one's own wonderful experiences it must be, he is also a man of great nerve.

09:56:57.292 --> 09:57:11.952
That going down to the vault a second time was a remarkable piece of daring. After reading his account of it, I was prepared to meet a good specimen of manhood, but hardly the quiet businesslike gentleman who came here today.

09:57:12.992 --> 09:57:13.372
Later

09:57:13.372 --> 09:57:24.392
After lunch, Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and as I passed a while ago, I heard the click of the typewriter. They are hard at it.

09:57:24.392 --> 09:57:30.892
Mrs Harker says that they are knitting together, in chronological order, every scrap of evidence they have.

09:57:32.012 --> 09:57:44.492
Harker has got the letters between the consignee of the boxes at Whitby, and the carriers in London who took charge of them. He is now reading his wife's transcript of my diary. I wonder what they will make out of it.

09:57:45.452 --> 09:57:56.432
Here it is. Strange that it never struck me that the very next house might be the Count's hiding place. Goodness knows that we had enough clues from the conduct of the patient Renfield.

09:57:57.612 --> 09:58:09.332
The bundle of letters relating to the purchase of the house were with the transcript. Oh, if we had only had them earlier, we might have saved poor Lucy. Stop! That way madness lies.

09:58:11.072 --> 09:58:31.032
Harker has gone back, and is again collecting material. He says that by dinnertime they will be able to show a whole connected narrative. He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.

09:58:31.732 --> 09:58:43.372
I hardly see this yet, but when I get at the dates I suppose I shall. What a good thing that Mrs Harker put my cylinders into type. We never could have found the dates otherwise.

09:58:43.372 --> 09:59:00.972
I found Renfield sitting placidly in his room, with his hands folded, smiling benignly. At the moment he seemed as sane as anyone I ever saw. I sat down and talked with him on a lot of subjects, all of which he treated naturally.

09:59:00.972 --> 09:59:15.572
He then, of his own accord, spoke of going home, a subject he has never mentioned to my knowledge during his sojourn here. In fact he spoke quite confidently of getting his discharge at once.

09:59:16.292 --> 09:59:26.712
I believe that had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.

09:59:26.712 --> 09:59:43.292
As it is, I am darkly suspicious. All those outbreaks were in some way linked with the proximity of the Count. What then does this absolute content mean? Can it be that his instinct is satisfied as to the Vampire's ultimate triumph?

09:59:43.292 --> 09:59:58.572
Stay. He is himself Zufagus, and in his wild ravings outside the chapel door of the deserted house, he always spoke of Master. This all seems confirmation of our idea.

09:59:58.572 --> 10:00:10.572
However, after a while I came away. My friend is just a little too sane at present to make it safe to probe him too deep with questions. He might begin to think, and then...

10:00:11.572 --> 10:00:23.552
So I came away. I mistrust these quiet moods of his, so I have given the attendant a hint to look closely after him and to have a straight waistcoat ready in case of need.

10:00:23.552 --> 10:00:29.292
Jonathan Harker's Journal. 29th September. In train to London.

10:00:30.672 --> 10:00:42.292
When I received Mr. Billington's courteous message that he would give me any information in his power, I thought it best to go down to Whitby and make, on the spot, such inquiries as I wanted.

10:00:42.292 --> 10:00:52.192
It was now my object to trace that horrid cargo of the Count's to its place in London. Later we may be able to deal with it.

10:00:52.572 --> 10:01:05.012
Billington Jr., a nice lad, met me at the station and brought me to his father's house, where they had decided that I must spend the night. They are hospitable, with true Yorkshire hospitality.

10:01:05.012 --> 10:01:18.892
Give a guest everything and leave him to do as he likes. They all knew that I was busy and that my stay was short, and Mr. Billington had ready, in his office, all the papers concerning the consignment of boxes.

10:01:19.572 --> 10:01:26.832
It gave me almost a turn to see again one of the letters which I had seen at the Count's table, before I knew of his diabolical plans.

10:01:26.832 --> 10:01:40.632
Everything had been carefully thought out and done systematically and with precision. He seems to have been prepared for every obstacle which might be placed by accident in the way of his intentions being carried out.

10:01:41.292 --> 10:01:52.372
To use an Americanism, he had taken no chances, and the absolute accuracy with which his instructions were fulfilled was simply the logical result of his care.

10:01:52.372 --> 10:02:08.792
I saw the invoice and took note of it. 50 cases of Common Earth to be used for experimental purposes. Also the copy of the letter to Carter Paterson, and their reply. Of both these I got copies.

10:02:08.792 --> 10:02:24.992
This was all the information Mr. Billington could give me, so I went down to the port and saw the Coast Guards, the Customs Officers and the Harbour Master, who kindly put me in communication with the men who had actually received the boxes.

10:02:25.652 --> 10:02:40.392
Their tally was exact with the list, and they had nothing to add to the simple description, 50 cases of Common Earth, except that the boxes were main and mortal heavy, and that shifting them was dry work.

10:02:40.392 --> 10:02:52.392
One of them added that it was hard lines that there wasn't any gentleman such like as like yourself, Squire, to show some sort of appreciation of their efforts in a liquid form.

10:02:52.392 --> 10:03:02.232
Another put in a rider that the first then generated was such that even the time which had elapsed had not completely elated.

10:03:02.712 --> 10:03:11.292
Needless to add, I took care before leaving to lift, forever and adequately, this source of reproach.

10:03:12.132 --> 10:03:26.712
30th September. The Station Master was good enough to give me a line to his old companion, the Station Master at King's Cross, so that when I arrived there in the morning, I was able to ask him about the arrival of the boxes.

10:03:27.372 --> 10:03:35.392
He, too, put me at once in communication with the proper officials, and I saw that their tally was correct with the original invoice.

10:03:35.392 --> 10:03:49.592
The opportunities of acquiring an abnormal first had been, here, limited. A noble use of them had, however, been made, and again I was compelled to deal with the result in ex post facto manner.

10:03:50.972 --> 10:04:05.392
From thence I went to Carter Paterson's central office, where I met with the utmost courtesy. They looked up the transaction in their day book and letter book, and at once telephoned to their King's Cross office for more details.

10:04:05.392 --> 10:04:20.572
By good fortune, the men who did the teaming were waiting for work, and the official at once sent them over, sending also, by one of them, the way bill and all the papers connected with the delivery of the boxes at Carfax.

10:04:20.572 --> 10:04:24.332
Here, again, I found the tally agreeing exactly.

10:04:25.532 --> 10:04:40.952
The carrier's men were able to supplement the paucity of the written words with a few more details. These were, I shortly found, connected almost solely with the dusty nature of the job, and the consequent first engendered in the operators.

10:04:41.552 --> 10:04:51.952
On my affording an opportunity, through the medium of the currency of the realm, of the allaying at a later period this beneficial evil, one of the men remarked,

10:04:52.572 --> 10:05:05.132
That airhouse, Governor, is the rummiest I ever was in. Blimey, but it ain't been touched since a hundred years. There was just that thick in the place that you might have slept on it without hurting of your bones.

10:05:05.832 --> 10:05:21.492
And the place was that neglected that you might have smelled old Jerusalem in it. But the old chapel, that took the sight that did. Me and my mate, we thought we wouldn't never get out quick enough, or I wouldn't take less nor a quid a moment to stay there out of dark.

10:05:21.492 --> 10:05:29.832
Having been in the house, I could well believe him. But if he knew what I know, he would, I think, have raised his terms.

10:05:30.732 --> 10:05:40.752
Of one thing I am now satisfied, that all those boxes which arrived at Whitby from Varna in the Demeter were safely deposited in the old chapel at Carfax.

10:05:41.512 --> 10:05:47.672
There should be fifty of them there, unless any have since been removed, as from Dr. Seward's diary, I fear.

10:05:48.332 --> 10:05:54.792
Later, Mina and I have worked all day, and we have put all the papers into order.

10:05:55.432 --> 10:06:03.312
Mina Harker's Journal. 30th September. I am so glad that I hardly know how to contain myself.

10:06:04.252 --> 10:06:13.672
It is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act detrimentally on Jonathan.

10:06:13.672 --> 10:06:19.592
I saw him leave for Whitby with as brave a face as could, but I was sick with apprehension.

10:06:20.472 --> 10:06:30.192
The effort has, however, done him good. He was never so resolute, never so strong, never so full of volcanic energy as at present.

10:06:30.672 --> 10:06:39.032
It is just as that good, dear Professor Van Helsing said. He is true grit, and he improves under strain that would kill a weaker nature.

10:06:39.032 --> 10:06:46.552
He came back full of life and hope and determination. We have got everything in order for tonight.

10:06:47.392 --> 10:06:53.472
I feel myself quite wild of excitement. I suppose one ought to pity anything so hunted as the Count.

10:06:54.372 --> 10:06:58.892
That is just it. This thing is not human, not even a beast.

10:06:59.792 --> 10:07:06.932
To read Dr. Seward's diary of poor Lucy's death and what followed is enough to dry up the springs of pity in one's heart.

10:07:08.092 --> 10:07:13.152
Later, Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris arrived earlier than we expected.

10:07:14.252 --> 10:07:19.712
Dr. Seward was out on business and had taken Jonathan with him, so I had to see them.

10:07:20.172 --> 10:07:26.672
It was, to me, a painful meeting, for it brought back all poor dear Lucy's hopes of only a few months ago.

10:07:27.312 --> 10:07:36.572
Of course, they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, had been quite blowing my trumpet, as Mr. Morris expressed it.

10:07:36.572 --> 10:07:42.112
Poor fellows, neither of them is aware that I know all about the proposals they made to Lucy.

10:07:43.072 --> 10:07:51.332
They did not quite know what to say or do, as they were ignorant of the amount of my knowledge, so they had to keep on neutral subjects.

10:07:52.432 --> 10:08:00.672
However, I thought the matter over and came to the conclusion that the best thing I could do would be to post them on affairs right up to date.

10:08:01.232 --> 10:08:09.872
I knew from Dr. Seward's diary that they had been at Lucy's death, a real death, and that I need not fear to betray any secret before the time.

10:08:10.412 --> 10:08:20.452
So I told them, as well as I could, that I had read all the papers and diaries and that my husband and I, having typewritten them, had just finished putting them into order.

10:08:20.972 --> 10:08:28.192
I gave them each a copy to read in the library. When Lord Godalming got it and turned it over, it does make a pretty good pile.

10:08:28.192 --> 10:08:34.572
He said, Did you write all this, Mrs. Harker? I nodded, and he went on.

10:08:34.912 --> 10:08:48.332
I don't quite see the drift of it, but you people are all so good and kind and have been working so earnestly and so energetically that all I can do is to accept your ideas blindfold and try to help you.

10:08:48.792 --> 10:08:55.012
I have had one lesson already in accepting facts that should make a man humble to the last hour of his life.

10:08:55.012 --> 10:08:58.052
Besides, I know you loved my Lucy.

10:08:59.292 --> 10:09:06.312
Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands. I could hear the tears in his voice.

10:09:07.112 --> 10:09:15.812
Mr. Morris, with instinctive delicacy, just laid a hand for a moment on his shoulder and then walked quietly out of the room.

10:09:15.812 --> 10:09:29.092
I suppose there is something in a woman's nature that makes a man free to break down before her and express his feelings on the tender or emotional side without feeling it derogatory to his manhood.

10:09:29.172 --> 10:09:36.752
For, when Lord Godalming found himself alone with me, he sat down on the sofa and gave way utterly and openly.

10:09:37.472 --> 10:09:40.312
I sat down beside him and took his hand.

10:09:41.092 --> 10:09:48.132
I hope he didn't think it forward of me, and that if he ever thinks of it afterwards he will never have such a thought.

10:09:48.912 --> 10:09:53.472
There I rang him. I know he never will. He is too true a gentleman.

10:09:54.492 --> 10:09:57.852
I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking.

10:09:58.432 --> 10:10:03.712
I loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you and what you were to her.

10:10:03.712 --> 10:10:07.332
She and I were like sisters, and now she is gone.

10:10:08.412 --> 10:10:11.752
Will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?

10:10:12.292 --> 10:10:16.792
I know what sorrows you have had, though I cannot measure the depth of them.

10:10:17.512 --> 10:10:24.492
If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won't you let me be of some little service for Lucy's sake?

10:10:25.352 --> 10:10:30.032
In an instant the poor dear fellow was overwhelmed with grief.

10:10:30.032 --> 10:10:36.812
It seemed to me that all that he had of late been suffering in silence found a vent at once.

10:10:37.412 --> 10:10:45.512
He grew quite hysterical, and, raising his open hands, beat his palms together in a perfect agony of grief.

10:10:45.892 --> 10:10:51.132
He stood up, and then sat down again, and the tears rained down his cheeks.

10:10:52.072 --> 10:10:56.492
I felt an infinite pity for him, and opened my arms unthinkingly.

10:10:56.492 --> 10:11:05.012
With a sob, he laid his head on my shoulder, and cried like a weary child, whilst he shook with emotion.

10:11:05.652 --> 10:11:12.432
We women have something of the mother in us that makes us rise above smaller matters when the mother spirit is invoked.

10:11:13.132 --> 10:11:21.572
I felt this big, sorrowing man's head resting on me, as though it were that of a baby that some day may lie on my bosom,

10:11:21.572 --> 10:11:25.532
and I stroked his hair as though he were my own child.

10:11:26.972 --> 10:11:29.772
I never thought at the time how strange it all was.

10:11:30.472 --> 10:11:38.272
After a little bit, his sob ceased, and he raised himself with an apology, though he made no disguise of his emotion.

10:11:39.132 --> 10:11:50.812
He told me that for days and nights past, weary days and sleepless nights, he had been unable to speak with anyone as a man must speak in his time of sorrow.

10:11:50.812 --> 10:12:00.772
There was no woman whose sympathy could be given to him, or with whom, owing to the terrible circumstances with which his sorrow was surrounded, he could speak freely.

10:12:01.472 --> 10:12:05.672
I know now how I suffered, he said, as he dried his eyes.

10:12:06.312 --> 10:12:13.592
But I do not know even yet, and none other can ever know, how much your sweet sympathy has been to me today.

10:12:13.592 --> 10:12:21.992
I shall know better in time, and believe me that though I am not ungrateful now, my gratitude will grow with my understanding.

10:12:22.832 --> 10:12:28.112
You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives, for dear Lucy's sake?

10:12:28.592 --> 10:12:32.372
For dear Lucy's sake, I said, as we clasped hands.

10:12:33.212 --> 10:12:43.012
I, and for your own sake, he added, for, if a man's esteem and gratitude are ever worth the winning, you have won mine today.

10:12:44.812 --> 10:12:51.672
If ever the future should bring to you a time when you need a man's help, believe me, you will not call in vain.

10:12:52.352 --> 10:13:00.992
God grant that no such time may ever come to you to break the sunshine of your life, but if it should ever come, promise me that you will let me know.

10:13:00.992 --> 10:13:06.652
He was so earnest, and his sorrow was so fresh, that I felt it would comfort him.

10:13:07.112 --> 10:13:13.632
So I said, I promise. As I came along the corridor, I saw Mr. Morris looking out of a window.

10:13:14.552 --> 10:13:16.412
He turned as he heard my footsteps.

10:13:17.092 --> 10:13:18.552
How is Art? he said.

10:13:19.172 --> 10:13:22.992
Then, noticing my red eyes, he went on.

10:13:23.152 --> 10:13:26.172
Ah, I see you have been comforting him.

10:13:27.032 --> 10:13:29.352
Poor old fellow, he needs it.

10:13:29.732 --> 10:13:35.852
No one but a woman can help a man when he is in trouble of the heart, and he had no one to comfort him.

10:13:36.572 --> 10:13:40.652
He bore his own trouble so bravely that my heart bled for him.

10:13:41.252 --> 10:13:46.932
I saw the manuscript in his hand, and I knew that when he read it, he would realize how much I knew.

10:13:47.572 --> 10:13:51.912
So I said to him, I wish I could comfort all who suffer from the heart.

10:13:51.912 --> 10:13:57.092
Will you let me be your friend, and will you come to me for comfort if you need it?

10:13:57.612 --> 10:13:59.452
You will know later why I speak.

10:14:00.312 --> 10:14:08.152
He saw that I was in earnest, and stooping, took my hand, and, raising it to his lips, kissed it.

10:14:08.692 --> 10:14:16.792
It seemed poor comfort to so brave an unselfish a soul, and impulsively, I bent over and kissed him.

10:14:16.792 --> 10:14:21.412
The tears rose in his eyes, and there was a momentary choking in his throat.

10:14:22.132 --> 10:14:23.992
He said, quite calmly,

10:14:24.852 --> 10:14:30.292
Little girl, you will never forget that true-hearted kindness so long as ever you live.

10:14:30.732 --> 10:14:34.032
Then he went into the study to his friend.

10:14:34.972 --> 10:14:42.152
Little girl, the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend.

10:15:06.829 --> 10:15:12.429
Dr C. Wood's Diary, 30th September. I got home at five o'clock, and found that

10:15:12.429 --> 10:15:16.689
Godelming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of

10:15:16.689 --> 10:15:20.649
various diaries and letters, which Harker had not yet returned from his visit to the

10:15:20.649 --> 10:15:26.249
Carrier's Men, of whom Dr Hennessy had written to me. Mrs Harker gave us a cup of tea, and

10:15:26.249 --> 10:15:30.269
I can honestly say that, for the first time since I have lived in it, this old house seemed

10:15:30.269 --> 10:15:33.709
like home. When we had finished tea, Mrs Harker said,

10:15:34.089 --> 10:15:40.129
Dr C. Wood, may I ask a favour? I want to see your patient, Mr Renfield. Do let me see

10:15:40.129 --> 10:15:43.909
him. What you have said of him in your diary interests me so much.

10:15:44.249 --> 10:15:49.329
She looked so appealing and so pretty that I could not refuse her, and there was no possible

10:15:49.329 --> 10:15:53.969
reason why I should, so I took her with me. When I went into the room, I told the man

10:15:53.969 --> 10:15:59.509
that a lady would like to see him, to which he simply answered, Why? She is going through

10:15:59.509 --> 10:16:05.269
the house and wants to see everyone in it, I said. Oh, very well, he said. Let her come

10:16:05.269 --> 10:16:08.449
in by all means, but just wait a minute till I tidy up the place.

10:16:09.109 --> 10:16:14.309
His method of tidying was peculiar. He simply swallowed all of the flies and spiders in

10:16:14.309 --> 10:16:19.029
the boxes before I could stop him. It was quite evident that he feared, or was jealous

10:16:19.029 --> 10:16:24.489
of, some interference. When he had got through his disgusting task, he said cheerfully, Let

10:16:24.489 --> 10:16:28.769
the lady come in, and sat down on the edge of his bed with his head down, but with his

10:16:28.769 --> 10:16:32.869
eyelids raised so that he could see her as she entered. For a moment I thought he might

10:16:32.869 --> 10:16:37.229
have some homicidal intent. I remembered how quiet he had been just before he attacked

10:16:37.229 --> 10:16:41.829
me in my own study, and I took care to stand where I could seize him at once, if he attempted

10:16:41.829 --> 10:16:46.749
to make a spring at her. She came into the room with an easy gracefulness, which would

10:16:46.749 --> 10:16:51.029
at once command the respect of any lunatic, for reasonness is one of the qualities mad

10:16:51.029 --> 10:16:56.169
people most respect. She walked over to him smiling pleasantly, and held out her hand.

10:16:56.669 --> 10:17:01.929
Good evening, Mr. Renfield, said she. You see, I know you, for Dr. Seaworth has told

10:17:01.929 --> 10:17:06.969
me of you. He made no immediate reply, but eyed her all over intently, with a set frown

10:17:06.969 --> 10:17:12.229
on his face. This look gave away to one of wonder, which merged in doubt. Then to my

10:17:12.229 --> 10:17:16.289
intense astonishment he said, You're not the girl the doctor wanted to marry, are you?

10:17:16.529 --> 10:17:22.569
You can't be, you know, for she's dead. Mrs. Harker smiled sweetly as she replied, Oh no,

10:17:22.809 --> 10:17:27.209
I have a husband of my own, to whom I was married before I ever saw Dr. Seaworth, or

10:17:27.209 --> 10:17:33.229
he me, I and Mrs. Harker. Then what are you doing here? My husband and I are staying on

10:17:33.229 --> 10:17:39.089
a visit with Dr. Seaworth. Then don't stay. But why not? I thought that this style of

10:17:39.089 --> 10:17:43.729
conversation might not be pleasant to Mrs. Harker any more than it was to me, so I joined

10:17:43.729 --> 10:17:50.229
in. How did you know I wanted to marry anyone? His reply was simply contemptuous, given in

10:17:50.229 --> 10:17:54.549
a pause in which he turned his eyes from Mrs. Harker to me, instantly turning them back

10:17:54.549 --> 10:18:00.689
again. What an asinine question! I don't see that at all, Mr. Renfield, said Mrs. Harker,

10:18:00.689 --> 10:18:06.789
at once championing me. He replied to her with as much courtesy and respect as he had

10:18:06.789 --> 10:18:12.469
shown contempt to me. You will of course understand, Mrs. Harker, that when a man is so loved and

10:18:12.469 --> 10:18:16.729
honoured as our host is, everything regarding him is of interest in our little community.

10:18:17.369 --> 10:18:21.789
Dr. Seaworth is loved not only by his household and his friends, but even by his patients,

10:18:22.189 --> 10:18:28.009
who, being some of them hardly in mental equilibrium, are apt to distort causes and effects. Since

10:18:28.009 --> 10:18:32.849
I myself have been an inmate of a lunatic asylum, I cannot but notice that the sophisticated

10:18:32.849 --> 10:18:38.329
tendencies of some of his inmates lean towards the errors of non-causer and ignoratio elench.

10:18:39.369 --> 10:18:45.489
I positively opened my eyes at this new development. Here was my own pet lunatic, the most pronounced

10:18:45.489 --> 10:18:49.969
of his type that I had ever met with, talking elemental philosophy, and with the manner

10:18:49.969 --> 10:18:54.649
of a polished gentleman. I wonder if it was Mrs. Harker's presence which had touched some

10:18:54.649 --> 10:18:59.989
memory. If this new phase was spontaneous, or in any way due to her unconscious influence,

10:19:00.369 --> 10:19:02.389
she must have some rare gift or power.

10:19:02.709 --> 10:19:07.549
We continued to talk for some time, and seeing that he was seemingly quite reasonable, she

10:19:07.549 --> 10:19:11.349
ventured, looking at me questioningly as she began to lead him to his favourite topic.

10:19:11.849 --> 10:19:16.709
I was again astonished, for he addressed himself to the question with the impartiality of the

10:19:16.709 --> 10:19:21.649
completest sanity. He even took himself as an example when he mentioned certain things.

10:19:21.649 --> 10:19:26.769
Why I myself am an instance of a man who had a strange belief. Indeed, it was no wonder

10:19:26.769 --> 10:19:31.309
that my friends were alarmed and insisted on my being put under control. I used to fancy

10:19:31.309 --> 10:19:36.129
that life was a positive and perpetual entity, and that by consuming a multitude of living

10:19:36.129 --> 10:19:40.509
things, no matter how low in the scale of creation, one might indefinitely prolong

10:19:40.509 --> 10:19:44.989
life. At times I held the belief so strongly that I had actually tried to take a human

10:19:44.989 --> 10:19:49.349
life. The doctor here will bear me out that on one occasion I tried to kill him for the

10:19:49.349 --> 10:19:53.489
purpose of strengthening my vital powers by the assimilation with my own body of his

10:19:53.489 --> 10:19:57.649
life through the medium of his blood, relying of course upon the scriptural phrase, for

10:19:57.649 --> 10:20:03.009
the blood is the life. Though indeed the vendor of a certain nostrum has vulgarised the truism

10:20:03.009 --> 10:20:05.869
to the very point of contempt. Isn't that true, doctor?

10:20:06.449 --> 10:20:11.609
I nodded assent, for I was so amazed that I hardly knew what to either think or say,

10:20:11.969 --> 10:20:15.969
it was hard to imagine that I had seen him eat up his spiders and flies not five minutes

10:20:15.969 --> 10:20:20.709
before. Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing,

10:20:20.889 --> 10:20:26.009
and I told Mrs Harker that it was time to leave. She came at once, after saying pleasantly

10:20:26.009 --> 10:20:30.929
to Mr Renfield, good-bye, and I hope that I may see you often under auspices pleasanter

10:20:30.929 --> 10:20:36.389
to yourself. To which, to my astonishment, he replied, good-bye, my dear, I pray God I

10:20:36.389 --> 10:20:39.829
may never see your sweet face again. May he bless and keep you.

10:20:40.909 --> 10:20:44.769
When I went to the station to meet Van Helsing, I left the boys behind me.

10:20:44.769 --> 10:20:49.649
Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first took ill, and Quincy is more

10:20:49.649 --> 10:20:54.169
like his own bright self than he has been for many a long day. Van Helsing stepped from the

10:20:54.169 --> 10:20:58.409
carriage with the eager nimbleness of a boy. He saw me at once and rushed up to me, saying,

10:20:58.589 --> 10:21:05.529
Ah, friends John, how goes all? Well, so, I have been busy, for I come here to stay if need be.

10:21:06.129 --> 10:21:08.909
All affairs are settled with me, and I have much to tell.

10:21:09.589 --> 10:21:15.169
Madam Mina is with you? Yes. And her so fine husband? And Arthur and my friend Quincy,

10:21:15.449 --> 10:21:20.649
they are with you too? Good. As I drove to the house, I told him of what had passed,

10:21:21.029 --> 10:21:24.929
and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs Harker's suggestion,

10:21:25.449 --> 10:21:31.049
at which the Professor interrupted me. Ah, that wonderful Madam Mina! She has a man's brain,

10:21:31.309 --> 10:21:34.989
a brain that a man should have were he much gifted, and a woman's heart.

10:21:34.989 --> 10:21:40.409
The good God fashioned her for a purpose, believe me, when he made that so good combination.

10:21:41.109 --> 10:21:46.369
Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us, after tonight she must not

10:21:46.369 --> 10:21:52.489
have to do with this so terrible affair. It is not good that she run a risk so great. We men are

10:21:52.489 --> 10:21:57.789
determined, nay, are we not pledged to destroy this monster? But it is no part for a woman.

10:21:58.149 --> 10:22:02.649
Even if she be not harmed, her heart may fail her in so much and so many horrors,

10:22:02.649 --> 10:22:07.829
and hereafter she may suffer, both in walking from her nerves, and in sleep from her dreams.

10:22:08.469 --> 10:22:13.729
And besides, she is young woman, and not so long married. There may be other things to think of

10:22:13.729 --> 10:22:19.009
some time, if not now. You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us,

10:22:19.209 --> 10:22:24.509
but to-morrow we say good-bye to this work, and we go alone. I agreed heartily with him,

10:22:24.589 --> 10:22:28.949
and then I told him what we had found in his absence, that the house which Dracula had bought

10:22:28.949 --> 10:22:34.369
was the very next one to my own. He was amazed, and a great concern seemed to come on him.

10:22:34.909 --> 10:22:39.129
Oh, that we had known it before, he said, for then we might have reached him in time to save

10:22:39.129 --> 10:22:45.949
poor Lucy. However, the milk that is spilt cries not out afterwards, as you say. We shall not think

10:22:45.949 --> 10:22:51.229
of that, but go on our way to the end. Then he fell into silence that lasted till we entered

10:22:51.229 --> 10:22:56.749
my own gateway. Before we went to prepare for dinner, he said to Mrs Harker, I am told,

10:22:57.189 --> 10:23:02.369
by my friend John, that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been

10:23:02.369 --> 10:23:07.189
up to this moment. Not up to this moment, Professor, she said impulsively, but up to

10:23:07.189 --> 10:23:12.409
this morning. But why not up till now? We have seen hitherto how good light all of the little

10:23:12.409 --> 10:23:17.529
things have made. We have told our secrets, and yet no one who was told is the worst for it.

10:23:18.169 --> 10:23:22.029
Mrs Harker began to blush, and taking a paper from her pocket, she said,

10:23:22.029 --> 10:23:27.609
Dr Van Helsing, will you read this and tell me if it must go in? It is my record of today.

10:23:28.049 --> 10:23:31.869
I too have seen the need of putting down at present everything, however trivial,

10:23:32.249 --> 10:23:35.909
but there is little in this, except what is personal. Must it go in?

10:23:36.249 --> 10:23:39.569
The Professor read it over gravely, and handed it back, saying,

10:23:39.869 --> 10:23:44.789
It need not go in if you do not wish it, but I pray that it may. It can but make your husband

10:23:44.789 --> 10:23:49.389
love you the more, and all us your friends more honour you, as well as more esteem and love.

10:23:49.389 --> 10:23:55.049
She took it back with another blush and a bright smile. And so now, up to this very hour,

10:23:55.289 --> 10:24:00.729
all the records we have are complete and in order. The Professor took away one copy to study after

10:24:00.729 --> 10:24:05.549
dinner, and before our meeting, which is fixed for nine o'clock. The rest of us have already

10:24:05.549 --> 10:24:10.509
read everything, so when we meet in the study, we shall all be informed as to facts, and can

10:24:10.509 --> 10:24:13.989
arrange our plan of battle with this terrible and mysterious enemy.

10:24:14.869 --> 10:24:17.729
Mina Harker's Journal 30th September

10:24:18.309 --> 10:24:23.189
When we met in Dr Seawood's study two hours after dinner, which had been at six o'clock,

10:24:23.469 --> 10:24:27.869
we unconsciously formed a sort of board or committee. Professor Van Helsing took the

10:24:27.869 --> 10:24:32.849
head of the table, to which Dr Seawood motioned him as he came into the room. He made me sit

10:24:32.849 --> 10:24:38.469
next to him on his right, and asked me to act as secretary. Jonathan sat next to me. Oppositors

10:24:38.469 --> 10:24:43.849
were Lord Godelming, Dr Seawood and Mr Morris, Lord Godelming being next to the Professor,

10:24:44.269 --> 10:24:47.329
and Dr Seawood in the centre. The Professor said,

10:24:47.649 --> 10:24:52.289
I may, I suppose, take it that we are all acquainted with the facts that are in these papers.

10:24:52.849 --> 10:24:58.009
We all expressed assent, and he went on. Then it were, I think, good that I tell you something of

10:24:58.009 --> 10:25:02.289
the kind of enemy with which we have to deal. I shall then make known to you something of the

10:25:02.289 --> 10:25:07.009
history of this man, which has been ascertained for me, so we can then discuss how we shall act,

10:25:07.009 --> 10:25:08.829
and can take our measure according.

10:25:10.069 --> 10:25:14.189
There are such beings as vampires. Some of us have evidence that they exist.

10:25:14.969 --> 10:25:19.669
Even had we not the proof of our own unhappy experience, the teachings and the records of

10:25:19.669 --> 10:25:25.989
the past give proof enough for sane peoples. I admit that at the first I was sceptic. Were it

10:25:25.989 --> 10:25:30.789
not that through long years I have trained myself to keep an open mind, I could not have believed

10:25:30.789 --> 10:25:38.569
until such time as that fact thunder on my ear. See, see, I prove, I prove. Alas, had I known at

10:25:38.569 --> 10:25:44.269
first what now I know, nay, had I even guessed at him, one so precious life had been spared to many

10:25:44.269 --> 10:25:50.409
of us who did love her. But that is gone, and we must so work that other poor souls perish not,

10:25:50.809 --> 10:25:56.709
whilst we can save. The Nosferatu do not die like the bee when he sting once. He is only stronger,

10:25:56.709 --> 10:26:02.929
and being stronger have yet more power to work evil. This vampire which is amongst us of himself

10:26:02.929 --> 10:26:08.929
is so strong in person as twenty men. He is of cunning more than mortal, for his cunning be the

10:26:08.929 --> 10:26:14.789
growth of ages, and have still the aids of necromancy, which is, as his etymology imply,

10:26:15.189 --> 10:26:21.269
the divination of the dead, and all the dead that he can come nigh to are for him at command. He is

10:26:21.989 --> 10:26:28.789
more than brute, he is devil in callous, and the heart of him is not. He can, within his range,

10:26:29.249 --> 10:26:34.389
direct the elements, the storm, the fog, the thunder, he can command all the meaner things,

10:26:34.589 --> 10:26:41.149
the rat, and the owl, and the bat, the moth, and the fox, and the wolf, and he can grow and

10:26:41.149 --> 10:26:47.629
become small, and he can at times vanish and come unknown. How then are we to begin our strike to

10:26:47.629 --> 10:26:54.009
destroy him? How shall we find his where, and having found it, how can we destroy? My friends,

10:26:54.349 --> 10:26:59.549
this is much. It is a terrible task that we undertake, and there may be consequence to make

10:26:59.549 --> 10:27:06.429
the brave shudder. For if we fail in this, our fight. He must surely win, and then where end we?

10:27:07.029 --> 10:27:13.449
Life is nothing's, I heed him not. But to fail here is not mere life or death. It is that we

10:27:13.449 --> 10:27:18.969
come as him, that we henceforward become foul things of the night like him, without heart or

10:27:18.969 --> 10:27:24.949
conscience, praying on the bodies and the souls of those we love best. To us forever are the gates

10:27:24.949 --> 10:27:30.509
of heaven shut, for who shall open them to us again? We go on for all time abhorred by all,

10:27:30.849 --> 10:27:35.449
a blot on the face of God's sunshine, an arrow in the side of him who died for man.

10:27:36.509 --> 10:27:42.989
But we are face to face with duty, and in such case we must shrink. For me, I say no, but then I am

10:27:42.989 --> 10:27:49.629
old, and life, with his sunshine, his fair places, his songs of birds, his music and his love, lie

10:27:49.629 --> 10:27:55.469
far behind. You others are young, some have seen sorrow, but there are fair days yet in store.

10:27:55.969 --> 10:28:03.229
What say you? Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand. I feared, oh so much, that the

10:28:03.229 --> 10:28:08.329
appalling nature of our danger was overcoming him when I saw his hand stretch out. But it was life

10:28:08.329 --> 10:28:15.089
to me to feel its touch, so strong, so self-reliant, so resolute. A brave man's hand can speak for

10:28:15.089 --> 10:28:20.809
itself. It does not even need a woman's love to hear its music. When the Professor had done

10:28:20.809 --> 10:28:26.749
speaking, my husband looked into my eyes, and I in his. There was no need for speaking between us.

10:28:27.269 --> 10:28:33.249
I answer for Mina and myself, he said. Count me in, Professor, said Mr Quincy Morris,

10:28:33.249 --> 10:28:39.769
laconically as usual. I am with you, said Lord Godelming, for Lucy's sake, if for no other reason.

10:28:40.349 --> 10:28:47.469
Dr Seawood simply nodded. The Professor stood up, and, after laying his golden crucifix on the table,

10:28:47.809 --> 10:28:52.869
held out his hand on either side. I took his right hand, and Lord Godelming his left.

10:28:53.349 --> 10:28:57.049
Jonathan held my right, with his left, and stretched across to Mr Morris.

10:28:57.689 --> 10:29:04.329
So as we all took hands, our solemn compact was made. I felt my heart icy cold, but it did not

10:29:04.329 --> 10:29:10.089
even occur to me to draw back. We resumed our places, and Dr Van Helsing went on with a sort

10:29:10.089 --> 10:29:15.829
of cheerfulness which showed that the serious work had begun. It was to be taken as gravely,

10:29:15.969 --> 10:29:19.589
and in as businesslike a way, as any other transaction of life.

10:29:20.489 --> 10:29:25.209
Well, you know what we have to contend against, but we too are not without strength.

10:29:25.769 --> 10:29:31.749
We have on our side power of combination, a power denied to the vampire kind. We have sources of

10:29:31.749 --> 10:29:36.749
science. We are free to act and think, and the hours of the day and the night are ours equally.

10:29:37.209 --> 10:29:42.229
In fact, so far as our powers extend, they are unfettered, and we are free to use them.

10:29:42.989 --> 10:29:49.049
We have self-devotion in a cause, and an end to achieve, which is not a selfish one. These

10:29:49.049 --> 10:29:54.729
things are much. Now, let us see how far the general powers arrayed against us are restrict,

10:29:54.729 --> 10:30:00.869
and how the individual cannot. In fine, let us consider the limitations of the vampire in general,

10:30:01.209 --> 10:30:07.349
and this one in particular. All we have to go upon are traditions and superstitions.

10:30:08.289 --> 10:30:12.229
These do not at the first appear much, when the matter is one of life and death,

10:30:12.509 --> 10:30:17.769
nay of more than life and death. Yet must we be satisfied, in the first place because we have to

10:30:17.769 --> 10:30:24.209
be, no other means is at our control. And secondly, because after all these things, tradition and

10:30:24.209 --> 10:30:29.749
superstition are everything. Does not the belief in vampires rest for others, though not, alas,

10:30:29.829 --> 10:30:35.809
for us on them? A year ago, which of us would have received such a possibility in the midst of our

10:30:35.809 --> 10:30:42.389
scientific, sceptical, matter-of-fact 19th century? We even scouted a belief that we saw justified

10:30:42.389 --> 10:30:47.449
under our very eyes. Take it, then, that the vampire, and the belief in his limitations and

10:30:47.449 --> 10:30:53.369
his cure, rest for the moment on some base. For, let me tell you, he is known everywhere

10:30:53.369 --> 10:31:00.309
that men have been. In old Greece, in old Rome, he flourished in Germany all over, in France,

10:31:00.529 --> 10:31:06.969
in India, even in the Germanies, and in China, so far from us in all ways. There even is he,

10:31:07.229 --> 10:31:13.189
and the people's for him at this day. He have followed the wake of the berserker Icelander,

10:31:13.269 --> 10:31:21.329
the devil-begotten Hun, the Slav, the Saxon, the Magyar. So far, then, we have all we may act upon,

10:31:21.329 --> 10:31:27.029
and let me tell you that very much of the beliefs are justified by what we have seen in our own so

10:31:27.029 --> 10:31:33.669
unhappy experience. The vampire live on, and cannot die by mere passing of the time. He can

10:31:33.669 --> 10:31:39.309
flourish when that he can fatten on the blood of the living. Even more, we have seen amongst us that

10:31:39.309 --> 10:31:44.949
he can grow younger, that his vital faculties grow strenuous, and seem as though they refresh

10:31:44.949 --> 10:31:52.189
themselves when his special pabulum is plenty. But he cannot flourish without this diet. He eat

10:31:52.189 --> 10:31:58.649
not as others. Even friend Jonathan, who lived with him for weeks, did never see him eat, never.

10:31:59.449 --> 10:32:05.569
He throws no shadow, he make in the mirror no reflect, as again Jonathan observe. He has the

10:32:05.569 --> 10:32:10.789
strength of many of his hand, witness again Jonathan when he shut the door against the wolves,

10:32:10.789 --> 10:32:16.869
and when he help him from the diligence too. He can transform himself to wolf, as we gather from

10:32:16.869 --> 10:32:23.709
the ship arrival in Whitby, when he tear open the dog. He can be as a bat, as Madame Mina saw him on

10:32:23.709 --> 10:32:29.569
the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend

10:32:29.569 --> 10:32:35.889
Quincy saw him in the window of Miss Lucy. He can come in mist which he create, that noble ships

10:32:35.889 --> 10:32:40.909
kept improved him of this, but from what we know the distance he can make this mist is limited,

10:32:41.169 --> 10:32:47.009
and it can only be round himself. He come on moonlight rays as elemental dust, as again

10:32:47.009 --> 10:32:52.369
Jonathan saw those sisters in the castle of Dracula. He becomes so small, we ourselves saw

10:32:52.369 --> 10:32:57.969
Miss Lucy, as she was at peace, slip through a hair breadth space at the tomb door. He can,

10:32:58.389 --> 10:33:04.069
when once he find his way, come out from anything or into anything, no matter how close it be bound,

10:33:04.069 --> 10:33:10.769
or even fused up with fire, soldier you call it. He can see in the dark, no small power this,

10:33:11.209 --> 10:33:17.669
in a world which is one half shut from the light. Ah, but hear me through, he can do all these things,

10:33:17.829 --> 10:33:25.009
yet he is not free. Nay, he is even more prisoner than the slave of the galley, than the madman in

10:33:25.009 --> 10:33:31.189
his cell. He cannot go where he lists. He who is not of nature has yet to obey some nature's laws.

10:33:31.189 --> 10:33:37.349
Why, we know not. He may not enter anywhere at the first, unless there be some one of the household

10:33:37.349 --> 10:33:43.089
who bid him to come, though afterwards he can come as he please. His power ceases, as does that of

10:33:43.089 --> 10:33:49.329
all evil things, at the coming of the day. Only at certain times can he have limited freedom.

10:33:49.769 --> 10:33:55.589
If he be not at the place whether he is bound, he can only change himself at noon, or exact sunrise,

10:33:55.589 --> 10:34:02.369
or sunset. These things we are told, and in this record of ours we have proof by inference. Thus,

10:34:02.849 --> 10:34:08.029
whereas he can do as he will within his limit, when he have his earth home, his coffin home,

10:34:08.329 --> 10:34:13.549
his hell home, the place unhallowed, as we saw when he went to the grave of the suicide at Whitby,

10:34:13.989 --> 10:34:18.569
still at other time he can only change when the time come. It is said, too,

10:34:18.689 --> 10:34:23.929
that he can only pass running water at the slack or the flood of the tide. Then there are things

10:34:23.929 --> 10:34:29.429
which so afflict him that he has no power, as the garlic that we know of, and as for things sacred,

10:34:29.729 --> 10:34:35.789
as this symbol, my crucifix. That was amongst us even now when we resolve. To them he is nothing,

10:34:36.249 --> 10:34:41.609
but in their presence he take his place far off and silent with respect. There are others, too,

10:34:41.829 --> 10:34:47.849
which I shall tell you of, lest in our seeking we may need them. The branch of wild rose on his

10:34:47.849 --> 10:34:53.429
coffin keep him that he may not move from it. A sacred bullet fired into the coffin kill him so

10:34:53.429 --> 10:34:58.169
that he be true dead. And as for the stake through him, we know already of its peace,

10:34:58.569 --> 10:35:04.809
or the cut-off head that giveth rest. We have seen it with our own eyes. Thus, when we find the

10:35:04.809 --> 10:35:11.169
habitation of this man that was, we can confine him to his coffin and destroy him if we obey what

10:35:11.169 --> 10:35:17.949
we know. But he is clever. I have asked my friend Arminius of Budapest University to make his record,

10:35:17.949 --> 10:35:23.669
and from all the means that are, he tell me of what he has been. He must indeed have been

10:35:23.669 --> 10:35:28.989
that Vierveau de Dracula, who won his name against the Turk over the great river on the

10:35:28.989 --> 10:35:34.989
very frontier of Turkeyland. If it be so, then was he no common man, for in that time and for

10:35:34.989 --> 10:35:40.509
centuries after, he was spoken of as the cleverest and the most cunning, as well as the bravest of

10:35:40.509 --> 10:35:46.049
the sons of the land beyond the forest. That mighty brain and that iron resolution went with

10:35:46.049 --> 10:35:51.749
him to his grave, and are even now arrayed against us. The Draculas were, says Arminius,

10:35:51.949 --> 10:35:58.349
a great and noble race, though now and again were Scions who held by their Kovels to have had

10:35:58.349 --> 10:36:03.909
dealings with the evil one. They learned his secrets in the Scholomans, amongst the mountains

10:36:03.909 --> 10:36:10.149
over Lake Hermonstadt, where the devil claims the tenth scholar as his due. In the records are such

10:36:10.149 --> 10:36:17.889
words as Stragochica, Witch, Ordog, and Pocol, Satan and Hell, and in one manuscript this very

10:36:17.889 --> 10:36:24.529
Dracula is spoken of as Vampire, which we all understand too well. There have been from the

10:36:24.529 --> 10:36:30.489
loins of this very one great man and good women, and their graves make sacred the earth, where alone

10:36:30.489 --> 10:36:36.309
this foulness can dwell. For it is not the least of its terrors that this evil thing is rooted deep

10:36:36.309 --> 10:36:42.309
in all good. In soil barren of holy memories it cannot rest. Whilst they were talking,

10:36:42.609 --> 10:36:47.629
Mr Morris was looking steadily at the window, and he now got up quietly and went out of the room.

10:36:48.149 --> 10:36:53.329
There was a little pause, and then the professor went on. And now we must settle what we do.

10:36:53.729 --> 10:36:59.589
We have here much data, and we must proceed to lay out our campaign. We know from the inquiry

10:36:59.589 --> 10:37:05.169
of Jonathan that from the castle to Whitby came fifty boxes of earth, all of which were delivered

10:37:05.169 --> 10:37:11.889
at Carfax. We also know that at least some of these boxes have been removed. It seems to me

10:37:11.889 --> 10:37:16.969
that our first step should be to ascertain whether all the rest remain in the house beyond that wall

10:37:16.969 --> 10:37:22.689
where we look today, or whether any more have been removed. If the latter, we must trace.

10:37:23.429 --> 10:37:29.249
Here we were interrupted in a very startling way. Outside the house came the sound of a pistol shot.

10:37:29.569 --> 10:37:34.949
The glass of the window was shattered with a bullet, which ricocheting from the top of

10:37:34.949 --> 10:37:40.209
the room. I am afraid I am at heart a coward, for I shrieked out. The men all jumped to their

10:37:40.209 --> 10:37:45.909
feet. Lord Godelming flew over to the window and threw up the sash. As he did so, we heard Mr

10:37:45.909 --> 10:37:51.289
Morris' voice without, Sorry, I fear I have alarmed you. I shall come in and tell you about it.

10:37:52.009 --> 10:37:56.089
A minute later, he came in and said, It was an idiotic thing of me to do,

10:37:56.169 --> 10:38:01.229
and I ask your pardon, Mrs Harker, most sincerely. I fear I must have frightened you terribly.

10:38:01.229 --> 10:38:06.549
But the fact is that whilst the Professor was talking, there came a big bat and sat on the

10:38:06.549 --> 10:38:11.409
windowsill. I have got such a horror of the damned brutes from recent events that I cannot

10:38:11.409 --> 10:38:16.069
stand them, and I went out to have a shot, as I have been doing late of evenings, whenever I

10:38:16.069 --> 10:38:22.409
have seen one. You used to laugh at me for it then, Art. Did you hit it? asked Dr Van Helsing.

10:38:22.989 --> 10:38:28.289
I don't know. I fancy not, for it flew away into the wood. Without saying any more, he took his

10:38:28.289 --> 10:38:34.169
seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement. We must trace each of these boxes,

10:38:34.509 --> 10:38:39.189
and when we are ready, we must either capture or kill this monster in his lair, or we must,

10:38:39.189 --> 10:38:45.209
so to speak, sterilise the earth, so that no more he can seek safely in it. Thus, in the end,

10:38:45.449 --> 10:38:50.849
we may find him in his form of man between the hours of noon and sunset, and so engage with him

10:38:50.849 --> 10:38:57.269
when he is at his most weak. And now for you, Madame Mina, this night is end, until all be well.

10:38:57.269 --> 10:39:04.289
You are too precious to us to have such risk. When we part tonight, you no more must question.

10:39:05.289 --> 10:39:10.969
We are men and are able to bear, but you must be our star and our hope, and we shall act all the

10:39:10.969 --> 10:39:16.949
more free that you are not in danger, such as we are. All the men, even Jonathan, seemed relieved,

10:39:17.329 --> 10:39:21.949
but it did not seem to me good that they should brave danger and perhaps lessen their safety,

10:39:21.949 --> 10:39:26.589
strength being the best safety, through care of me. But their minds were made up,

10:39:27.069 --> 10:39:30.169
and though it was a bitter pill for me to swallow, I could say nothing,

10:39:30.589 --> 10:39:35.449
save to accept their chivalrous care of me. Mr Morris resumed the discussion.

10:39:35.849 --> 10:39:40.669
As there is no time to lose, I vote we have a look at his house right now. Time is everything

10:39:40.669 --> 10:39:47.249
with him, and swift action on our part may save another victim. I own that my heart began to fail

10:39:47.249 --> 10:39:52.589
me when the time fraction came so close, but I did not say anything, for I had a greater fear

10:39:52.589 --> 10:39:57.029
that if I appeared as a drag or a hindrance to their work, they might even leave me out of their

10:39:57.029 --> 10:40:01.709
counsels altogether. They have now gone off to Carthax with means to get into the house.

10:40:02.689 --> 10:40:07.529
Manlike, they had told me to go to bed and sleep, as if a woman can sleep when those she loves are

10:40:07.529 --> 10:40:14.049
in danger. I shall lie down and pretend to sleep, lest Jonathan have added anxiety about me when he

10:40:14.049 --> 10:40:21.329
returns. Dr Seward's diary, 1st October 4am. Just as we were about to leave the house,

10:40:21.609 --> 10:40:25.429
an urgent message was brought to me from Renfield to know if I would see him at once,

10:40:25.609 --> 10:40:29.909
as he had something of the utmost importance to say to me. I told the messenger to say that I

10:40:29.909 --> 10:40:34.649
would attend to his wishes in the morning. I was busy just at the moment. The attendant added,

10:40:34.909 --> 10:40:40.169
He seems very importunate, sir. I have never seen him so eager. I don't know but what,

10:40:40.169 --> 10:40:43.449
if you don't see him soon, he will have one of his violent fits.

10:40:44.569 --> 10:40:47.769
I knew the man would not have said this without some cause, so I said,

10:40:48.249 --> 10:40:52.049
All right, I'll go now, and I asked the others to wait a few minutes for me,

10:40:52.129 --> 10:40:53.729
as I had to go and see my patient.

10:40:54.769 --> 10:40:59.529
Take me with you, friends John, said the professor. His case in your diary interests me much,

10:40:59.789 --> 10:41:03.689
and it had bearing too now and again on our case. I should much like to see him,

10:41:03.909 --> 10:41:08.609
and especially when his mind is disturbed. May I come along also? asked Lord Godalming.

10:41:08.609 --> 10:41:14.409
Me too, said Quincy Morris. May I come, said Harker. I nodded, and we all went down the

10:41:14.409 --> 10:41:19.629
passage together. We found him in a state of considerable excitement, but far more rational

10:41:19.629 --> 10:41:24.709
in his speech and manner than I had ever seen him. There was an unusual understanding of himself,

10:41:25.009 --> 10:41:29.309
which was unlike anything I had ever seen in a lunatic, and he took it for granted that his

10:41:29.309 --> 10:41:35.229
reasons would prevail, with others entirely sane. We all five went into the room, but none of the

10:41:35.229 --> 10:41:39.909
first said anything. His request was that I would at once release him from the asylum

10:41:39.909 --> 10:41:44.429
and send him home. This he backed up with arguments regarding his complete recovery,

10:41:44.809 --> 10:41:50.029
and deducing his own existing sanity. I appealed to your friends, he said. They will perhaps not

10:41:50.029 --> 10:41:54.169
mind sitting in judgment on my case. By the way, you have not introduced me.

10:41:54.909 --> 10:42:00.269
I was so much astonished that the oddness of introducing a madman in an asylum did not strike

10:42:00.269 --> 10:42:04.889
me at the moment, and besides, there was a certain dignity in the man's manner, so much

10:42:04.889 --> 10:42:10.009
of the habit of equality, that I at once made the introduction, Lord Godelming, Professor Van

10:42:10.009 --> 10:42:17.829
Helsing, Mr Quincy Morris of Texas, Mr Jonathan Harker, Mr Renfield. He shook hands with each of

10:42:17.829 --> 10:42:22.769
them, saying in turn, Lord Godelming, I had the honour of seconding your father at the Wyndham.

10:42:23.029 --> 10:42:28.469
I grieve to know, by your holding the title, that he is no more. He was a man loved and honoured

10:42:28.469 --> 10:42:33.709
by all who knew him, and in his youth was, I have heard, the inventor of a burnt rum punch,

10:42:34.049 --> 10:42:38.689
much patronised on Derby night. Mr Morris, you should be proud of your great state.

10:42:39.229 --> 10:42:44.089
Its reception into the Union was a precedent which may have far-reaching effects hereafter,

10:42:44.329 --> 10:42:49.429
when the Pole and the Tropic may hold alliance for the Stars and Stripes. The power of treaty may

10:42:49.429 --> 10:42:54.509
yet prove a vast engine of enlargement, when the Monroe Doctrine takes its true place in the

10:42:54.509 --> 10:43:01.229
fable. What shall any man say of his pleasure at meeting Van Helsing? Sir, I make no apology for

10:43:01.229 --> 10:43:06.689
dropping all forms of conventional prefix. When an individual has revolutionised therapeutics by his

10:43:06.689 --> 10:43:11.229
discovery of the continuous evolution of brain-matter, conventional forms are unfitting,

10:43:11.529 --> 10:43:17.929
since they would seem to limit him to one of a class. You, gentlemen, who by nationality,

10:43:18.249 --> 10:43:24.489
by heredity, or by the possession of natural gifts, are fitted to hold your respective places in the

10:43:24.489 --> 10:43:27.889
world. I do not need to witness that I am sane, as at least the majority of men are in full

10:43:27.889 --> 10:43:33.369
possession of their liberties. And I am sure that you, Dr Seward, humanitarian and medico-jurist,

10:43:33.609 --> 10:43:38.769
as well as scientist, will deem it a moral duty to deal with me as one to be considered

10:43:38.769 --> 10:43:44.389
as under exceptional circumstances. He made this last appeal with a courtly air of conviction,

10:43:44.749 --> 10:43:50.449
which was not without its own charm. I think we were all staggered. For my own part,

10:43:50.449 --> 10:43:54.249
I was under the conviction, despite my knowledge of the man's character and history,

10:43:54.549 --> 10:43:59.469
that his reason had been restored, and I felt under a strong impulse to tell him that I was

10:43:59.469 --> 10:44:04.269
satisfied as to his sanity, and would see about the necessary formalities for his release in the

10:44:04.269 --> 10:44:09.109
morning. I thought it better to wait, however, before making so grave a statement, for of old

10:44:09.109 --> 10:44:14.149
I knew the sudden changes to which this particular patient was liable. So I contented myself with

10:44:14.149 --> 10:44:18.829
making a general statement that he appeared to be improving very rapidly, that I would have a longer

10:44:18.829 --> 10:44:22.769
chat with him in the morning, and would then see what I could do in the direction of meeting his

10:44:22.769 --> 10:44:29.249
wishes. This did not at all satisfy him, for he said quickly, But I fear, Dr Seward, that you

10:44:29.249 --> 10:44:35.609
hardly apprehend my wish. I desire to go at once, here, now, this very hour, this very moment, if I

10:44:35.609 --> 10:44:40.869
may. Time presses, and in our implied agreement with the old Seidman, it is of the essence of

10:44:40.869 --> 10:44:46.849
the contract. I am sure it is only necessary to put before so admirable a practitioner as Dr Seward,

10:44:46.849 --> 10:44:53.249
so simple, yet so momentous a wish, to ensure its fulfilment. He looked at me keenly, and seeing the

10:44:53.249 --> 10:44:58.029
negative in my face, turned to the others, and scrutinised them closely. Not meeting any

10:44:58.029 --> 10:45:04.209
sufficient response, he went on, Is it possible I have erred in my supposition? You have, I said

10:45:04.209 --> 10:45:11.469
frankly, but at the same time, as I felt, brutally. There was a considerable pause, and then he said

10:45:11.469 --> 10:45:18.129
Then I suppose I must only shift my ground of request. Let me ask for this concession, boon,

10:45:18.369 --> 10:45:23.889
privilege, whatever you will. I am content to implore in such a case, not on personal grounds,

10:45:24.169 --> 10:45:28.849
but for the sake of others. I am not at liberty to give you the whole of my reasons, but you may,

10:45:28.849 --> 10:45:34.629
I assure you, take it from me that they are good ones, unsound and unselfish, and spring from the

10:45:34.629 --> 10:45:40.149
highest sense of duty. Could you look, sir, into my heart, you would approve to the full the

10:45:40.149 --> 10:45:46.449
animate me. Nay, more, you would count me amongst the best and truest of your friends.

10:45:47.369 --> 10:45:52.469
Again he looked at us all keenly. I had a growing conviction that this sudden change of his entire

10:45:52.469 --> 10:45:57.689
intellectual method was but yet another phase of his madness, and so determined to let him go on

10:45:57.689 --> 10:46:02.309
a little longer, knowing from experience that he would, like all lunatics, give himself away

10:46:02.309 --> 10:46:07.829
in the end. Van Helsing was gazing at him with a look of utmost intensity, his bushy eyebrows

10:46:07.829 --> 10:46:12.589
almost meeting with the fixed concentration of his look. He said to Renfield, in a tone which

10:46:12.589 --> 10:46:17.069
did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards, for it was as of one

10:46:17.069 --> 10:46:21.709
addressing an equal, Can you not tell, frankly, your real reason for wishing to be free tonight?

10:46:22.149 --> 10:46:27.509
I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me, a stranger without prejudice, and with a habit

10:46:27.509 --> 10:46:32.109
of keeping an open mind, Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and his own responsibility,

10:46:32.109 --> 10:46:38.129
the privilege you seek. He shook his head sadly, and with a look of poignant regret on his face,

10:46:38.529 --> 10:46:43.909
the professor went on, Come sir, bethink yourself. You claim the privilege of reason in the highest

10:46:43.909 --> 10:46:49.169
degree, since you seek to impress us with your complete reasonableness. You do this, whose sanity

10:46:49.169 --> 10:46:53.709
we have reason to doubt, since you are not yet released from medical treatment for this very

10:46:53.709 --> 10:46:58.769
defect. If you will not help us in our effort to choose the wisest course, how can we perform the

10:46:58.769 --> 10:47:04.769
duty which you yourself put upon us? Be wise and help us, and if we can we shall aid you to

10:47:04.769 --> 10:47:10.549
achieve your wish. He still shook his head, as he said, Dr. Van Helsing, I have nothing to say.

10:47:10.929 --> 10:47:16.089
Your argument is complete, and if I were free to speak, I should not hesitate a moment, but I am

10:47:16.089 --> 10:47:21.829
not my own master in the matter. I can only ask you to trust me. If I am refused, the responsibility

10:47:21.829 --> 10:47:27.229
does not rest with me. I thought it was now time to end the scene, which was becoming too comically

10:47:27.229 --> 10:47:33.189
grave, so I went towards the door, simply saying, Come my friends, we have work to do. Good night.

10:47:34.429 --> 10:47:40.009
As, however, I got near the door, a new change came over the patient. He moved towards me so

10:47:40.009 --> 10:47:43.569
quickly that for the moment I feared he was about to make another homicidal attack.

10:47:44.229 --> 10:47:49.249
My fears, however, were groundless, for he held up his two hands imploringly and made his petition

10:47:49.249 --> 10:47:54.809
in a moving manner. As he saw that the very excess of his emotion was mitigating against him,

10:47:54.809 --> 10:48:00.609
by storing us more to our old relations, he became still more demonstrative. I glanced at Van Helsing

10:48:00.609 --> 10:48:05.329
and saw my conviction reflected in his eyes, so it became a little more fixed in my manner,

10:48:05.589 --> 10:48:08.789
if not more stern, and motioned to him that his efforts were unavailing.

10:48:09.469 --> 10:48:13.969
I had previously seen something of the same constantly growing excitement in him when he

10:48:13.969 --> 10:48:18.749
had to make some request of which at the time he had thought much, such for instance as when he

10:48:18.749 --> 10:48:23.129
wanted a cat, and I was prepared to see the collapse into the same sullen acquiescence

10:48:23.129 --> 10:48:28.789
on this occasion. My expectation was not realized, for when he found that his appeal would not be

10:48:28.789 --> 10:48:34.209
successful, he got into quite a frantic condition. He threw himself onto his knees and held up his

10:48:34.209 --> 10:48:39.689
hands, wringing them in plaintive supplication, and poured forth a torrent of entreaty with the

10:48:39.689 --> 10:48:44.389
tears rolling down his cheeks and his whole face and form expressive of the deepest emotion.

10:48:44.829 --> 10:48:49.689
Let me entreat you, Dr. Seward. Oh, let me implore you to let me out of this house at once.

10:48:49.689 --> 10:48:55.629
Send me away, how you will and where you will. Send keepers with me, with whips and chains.

10:48:55.929 --> 10:49:01.549
Let them take me in a straight waistcoat, manacled and leg-ind, even to jail. But let me go out of

10:49:01.549 --> 10:49:06.989
this. You don't know what you do by keeping me here. I'm speaking from the depths of my heart,

10:49:07.029 --> 10:49:13.929
of my very soul. You don't know whom you wrong, or how, and I may not tell. Woe is me, I may not tell.

10:49:13.929 --> 10:49:19.969
By all you hold sacred, by all you hold dear, by your love that is lost, by your hope that lives,

10:49:20.189 --> 10:49:25.429
for the sake of the Almighty, take me out of this and save my soul from guilt. Can't you hear me,

10:49:25.549 --> 10:49:30.789
man? Can't you understand? Will you never learn? Don't you know that I am sane and earnest now,

10:49:30.889 --> 10:49:37.229
that I am no lunatic in a mad fit, but a sane man fighting for his soul? Oh, hear me! Hear me!

10:49:37.489 --> 10:49:43.909
Let me go! Let me go! Let me go! I thought that the longer this went on, the wilder he would get.

10:49:43.929 --> 10:49:47.569
And so would bring on a fit. So I took him by the hand and raised him up.

10:49:48.089 --> 10:49:52.269
Come, I said sternly, no more of this. We have had quite enough already.

10:49:52.589 --> 10:49:58.189
Get to your bed and try to behave more discreetly. He suddenly stopped and looked at me intently for

10:49:58.189 --> 10:50:03.949
several moments. Then, without a word, he rose and, moving over, sat down on the side of the bed.

10:50:04.509 --> 10:50:10.089
The collapse had come, as on former occasions, just as I had expected. When I was leaving the

10:50:10.089 --> 10:50:14.409
room, last of our party, he said to me, in a quiet, well-bred voice,

10:50:15.209 --> 10:50:19.049
You will, I trust, Dr. Seward, do me the justice to bear in mind,

10:50:19.129 --> 10:50:22.769
later on, that I did what I could to convince you to night.

10:50:44.841 --> 10:50:48.341
Dracula by Bram Stoker

10:50:51.941 --> 10:50:53.801
Jonathan Harker's Journal

10:50:55.581 --> 10:50:57.661
1st October, 5am

10:50:58.841 --> 10:51:05.401
I went with the party to the search with an easy mind, for I think I never saw Mina so absolutely strong and well.

10:51:05.941 --> 10:51:09.321
I'm so glad that she consented to hold back and let us men do the work.

10:51:09.861 --> 10:51:12.901
Somehow it was a dread to me that she was in this fearful business at all,

10:51:13.201 --> 10:51:21.021
but now that her work is done and that it is due to her energy and brains and foresight that the whole story is put together in such a way that every point tells,

10:51:21.021 --> 10:51:25.781
she may well feel that her part is finished and she can henceforth leave the rest to us.

10:51:26.761 --> 10:51:30.181
We were, I think, all a little upset by the scene with Mr. Renfield.

10:51:30.861 --> 10:51:34.361
When we came away from his room we were silent till we got back to the study.

10:51:35.581 --> 10:51:37.341
Then Mr. Morrie said to Dr. Seward,

10:51:38.141 --> 10:51:42.661
Say Jack, if that man wasn't attempting a bluff he is about the sanest lunatic I ever saw.

10:51:43.361 --> 10:51:49.901
I'm not sure, but I believe he had some serious purpose, and if he had it was pretty rough on him not to get a chance.

10:51:51.301 --> 10:51:54.801
Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added,

10:51:54.961 --> 10:51:58.401
Friend John, you know more about lunatics than I do, and I'm glad of it,

10:51:58.541 --> 10:52:04.041
for I fear that if it had been me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.

10:52:04.641 --> 10:52:10.461
But we live and learn, and in our present task we must take no chance, as my friend Quincy would say.

10:52:11.221 --> 10:52:12.861
All is best as they are.

10:52:14.361 --> 10:52:17.161
Dr. Seward seemed to answer them both in a dreamy kind of way,

10:52:17.161 --> 10:52:19.401
I don't know but that I agree with you.

10:52:19.721 --> 10:52:23.341
If that man had been an ordinary lunatic I would have taken my chance of trusting him,

10:52:23.641 --> 10:52:30.021
but he seemed so mixed up with the Count in an indexy kind of way that I'm afraid of doing anything wrong by helping his fads.

10:52:31.101 --> 10:52:34.301
I can't forget how he prayed with almost equal fervour for a cat,

10:52:35.261 --> 10:52:37.501
then tried to tear my throat out with his teeth.

10:52:38.281 --> 10:52:43.901
Besides, he called the Count Lord and Master, and he may want to get out and help him in some diabolical way.

10:52:43.901 --> 10:52:47.941
That horrid thing has the wolves and rats in his own kind to help him,

10:52:48.041 --> 10:52:50.881
so I suppose he isn't above trying to use a respectable lunatic.

10:52:51.681 --> 10:52:53.261
He certainly did seem earnest though.

10:52:53.741 --> 10:52:55.421
I only hope we have done what is best.

10:52:56.001 --> 10:53:00.501
These things, in conjunction with the wild work we have in hand, help to unnerve a man.

10:53:01.661 --> 10:53:06.821
The Professor stepped over, and laying his hand on his shoulder, said in his grave kindly way,

10:53:07.361 --> 10:53:08.821
Friend John, have no fear.

10:53:09.281 --> 10:53:12.521
We are trying to do our duty in a very sad and terrible case.

10:53:12.521 --> 10:53:14.601
We can only do as we deem best.

10:53:15.081 --> 10:53:17.921
What else have we to hope for, except the pity of the good God?

10:53:19.861 --> 10:53:23.321
Lord Godolming had slipped away for a few minutes, but now he returned.

10:53:24.181 --> 10:53:26.441
He held up a little silver whistle, as he remarked.

10:53:26.661 --> 10:53:30.621
That old place may be full of rats, and if so, I've got an antidote on call.

10:53:32.201 --> 10:53:34.821
Having passed the wall, we took our way to the house,

10:53:35.181 --> 10:53:38.841
taking care to keep in the shadows of the trees on the lawn when the moonlight shone out.

10:53:39.321 --> 10:53:42.041
When we got to the porch, the Professor opened his bag,

10:53:42.481 --> 10:53:44.881
and took out a lot of things which he laid on the step,

10:53:45.341 --> 10:53:48.421
sorting them into four little groups, evidently one for each.

10:53:49.121 --> 10:53:49.841
Then he spoke.

10:53:50.981 --> 10:53:56.221
My friends, we are going into a terrible danger, and we need arms of many kinds.

10:53:57.241 --> 10:53:59.081
Our enemy is not merely spiritual.

10:53:59.861 --> 10:54:02.021
Remember that he has the strengths of twenty men,

10:54:02.381 --> 10:54:05.561
and that though our necks or our windpipes are of the common kind,

10:54:05.561 --> 10:54:10.921
and therefore breakable or crushable, his are not amenable to mere strength.

10:54:11.741 --> 10:54:14.941
A stronger man or a body of men, more strong in all than him,

10:54:15.141 --> 10:54:20.101
can at certain times hold him, but they cannot hurt him as we can be hurt by him.

10:54:20.901 --> 10:54:23.381
We must therefore guard ourselves from his touch.

10:54:24.281 --> 10:54:25.741
Keep this near your heart.

10:54:26.561 --> 10:54:29.461
As he spoke, he lifted a small silver crucifix,

10:54:29.881 --> 10:54:32.141
and held it out to me, I being nearest to him.

10:54:32.721 --> 10:54:34.801
Put these flowers round your neck.

10:54:35.301 --> 10:54:37.961
Here he handed me a wreath of withered garlic blossoms.

10:54:38.961 --> 10:54:42.661
For other enemies more mundane, this revolver and this knife,

10:54:42.861 --> 10:54:47.601
and for aiding all these so small electrical lamps which you can fasten to your breast,

10:54:47.961 --> 10:54:52.481
and for all and above all at the last, this which we must not desecrate needless.

10:54:53.701 --> 10:54:58.601
This was a portion of sacred wafer which he put in an envelope and handed to me.

10:54:58.601 --> 10:55:01.321
Each of the others were similarly equipped.

10:55:02.821 --> 10:55:06.001
Now, he said, friend John, where are the skeleton keys?

10:55:07.001 --> 10:55:12.581
If we can open the door, we need not break into the house by the window as before at Miss Lucy's.

10:55:13.521 --> 10:55:17.721
Dr. Seward tried one or two skeleton keys, his mechanical dexterity as a surgeon,

10:55:18.061 --> 10:55:19.261
standing him in good stead.

10:55:20.321 --> 10:55:21.581
Presently he got one to suit.

10:55:21.961 --> 10:55:26.541
After a little play back and forward the bolt yielded, and with a rusty clang shot back.

10:55:26.541 --> 10:55:31.141
We pressed on the door, the rusty hinges creaked, and it slowly opened.

10:55:32.181 --> 10:55:37.621
It was startling like the image conveyed to me in Dr. Seward's diary of the opening of Miss Westenra's tomb.

10:55:38.541 --> 10:55:43.121
I fancied that the same idea appeared to strike the others, for with one accord they shrank back.

10:55:44.161 --> 10:55:48.161
The professor was the first to move forward, and he stepped into the open door.

10:55:49.381 --> 10:55:53.841
In manus tuas domine, he said, crossing himself as we passed over the threshold.

10:55:55.101 --> 10:56:01.481
We closed the door behind us, lest when we should have lit our lamps we should possibly attract attention from the road.

10:56:02.341 --> 10:56:08.601
The professor carefully tried the lock, lest we might not be able to open it from within should we be in a hurry making our exit.

10:56:09.881 --> 10:56:12.661
Then we all lit our lamps and proceeded on our search.

10:56:15.121 --> 10:56:20.301
The light from the tiny lamps fell in all sorts of odd forms as the rays crossed each other,

10:56:20.561 --> 10:56:22.861
or the opacity of our bodies through great shadows.

10:56:23.401 --> 10:56:27.841
I could not for my life get away from the feeling that there was someone else amongst us.

10:56:28.621 --> 10:56:35.621
I suppose it was the recollection so powerfully brought home to me by the grim surroundings of that terrible experience in Transylvania.

10:56:36.681 --> 10:56:45.041
I think the feeling was common to us all, for I noticed that the others kept looking over their shoulders at every sound and every new shadow, just as I felt myself doing.

10:56:47.021 --> 10:56:48.901
The whole place was thick with dust.

10:56:49.521 --> 10:56:53.901
The floor was seemingly inches deep, except where there were recent footsteps,

10:56:54.341 --> 10:56:58.321
in which on holding down my lamp I could see marks of hobnails where the dust was cracked.

10:56:59.201 --> 10:57:03.781
The walls were fluffy and heavy with dust, and in the corners were masses of spider's webs,

10:57:04.141 --> 10:57:09.361
whereon the dust had gathered till they looked like old tattered rags as the weight had torn them partly down.

10:57:10.321 --> 10:57:14.761
On a table in the hall was a great bunch of keys with a time-yellowed label on each.

10:57:14.761 --> 10:57:23.721
They had been used several times, for on the table were several similar rents in the blanket of dust, similar to that exposed when the professor lifted them.

10:57:25.181 --> 10:57:31.461
He turned to me and said, You know this place, Jonathan. You have copied maps of it, and you know it at least more than we do.

10:57:32.281 --> 10:57:33.521
Which is the way to the chapel?

10:57:35.241 --> 10:57:40.661
I had an idea of its direction, though on my former visit I had not been able to get admission to it,

10:57:40.661 --> 10:57:48.061
so I led the way, and after a few wrong turnings found myself opposite a low arched oaken door, ribbed with iron bands.

10:57:49.481 --> 10:57:53.881
This is the spot, said the professor as he turned his lamp on a small map of the house,

10:57:54.241 --> 10:57:57.281
copied from the file of my original correspondence regarding the purchase.

10:57:58.581 --> 10:58:01.581
With a little trouble we found the key on the bunch and opened the door.

10:58:02.761 --> 10:58:09.361
We were prepared for some unpleasantness, for as we were opening the door a faint, malodorous air seemed to exhale through the gaps.

10:58:10.161 --> 10:58:13.761
But none of us ever expected such an odour as we encountered.

10:58:14.861 --> 10:58:21.921
None of the others had met the Count at all at the close quarters, and when I had seen him he was either in the fasting stage of his existence in his rooms,

10:58:22.301 --> 10:58:26.301
or when he was bloated with fresh blood in a ruined building open to the air.

10:58:27.041 --> 10:58:32.981
But here the place was small and close, and the long disuse had made the air stagnant and foul.

10:58:33.681 --> 10:58:38.281
There was an earthy smell as of some dry miasma which came through the foul air.

10:58:38.881 --> 10:58:42.761
But as to the odour itself, how shall I describe it?

10:58:43.601 --> 10:58:49.621
It was not alone that it was composed of all the ills and mortality, and with the pungent, acrid smell of blood,

10:58:49.981 --> 10:58:53.401
but it seemed as though corruption had become itself corrupt.

10:58:53.981 --> 10:58:56.881
Ugh, it sickens me to think of it.

10:58:57.341 --> 10:59:03.281
Every breath exhaled by that monster seemed to have clung to the place and intensified its loathsomeness.

10:59:05.121 --> 10:59:09.681
Under ordinary circumstances, such a stench would have brought our enterprise to an end.

10:59:10.261 --> 10:59:14.841
But this was no ordinary case, and the high and terrible purpose in which we were involved

10:59:14.841 --> 10:59:18.161
gave us a strength which rose above merely physical considerations.

10:59:19.401 --> 10:59:23.101
After the involuntary shrinking consequent on the first nauseous whiff,

10:59:23.601 --> 10:59:27.561
we one and all set about our work as though that loathsome place were a garden of roses.

10:59:30.041 --> 10:59:34.741
We made an accurate examination of the place, the professor saying as we began,

10:59:35.201 --> 10:59:37.841
the first thing is to see how many of the boxes are left.

10:59:38.421 --> 10:59:41.241
We must then examine every hole and corner and cranny,

10:59:41.701 --> 10:59:44.781
and see if we cannot get some clue as to what has become of the rest.

10:59:46.341 --> 10:59:48.761
A glance was sufficient to show how many remained,

10:59:49.121 --> 10:59:52.081
for the great earth chests were bulky and there was no mistaking them.

10:59:52.921 --> 10:59:55.541
There were only 29 left out of the 50.

10:59:56.641 --> 11:00:01.261
Once I got a fright, for seeing Lord Godalning suddenly turn and look out of the vaulted door

11:00:01.261 --> 11:00:06.501
into the dark passage beyond, I looked too, and for an instant my heart stood still.

11:00:07.641 --> 11:00:12.101
Somewhere, looking out from the shadow, I seemed to see the highlights of the Count's evil face,

11:00:12.621 --> 11:00:16.701
the ridge of the nose, the red eyes, the red lips, the awful pallor.

11:00:17.241 --> 11:00:20.021
It was only for a moment, for as Lord Godalning said,

11:00:20.681 --> 11:00:22.861
I thought I saw a face, but it was only the shadows,

11:00:22.861 --> 11:00:27.721
and resumed his inquiry, I turned my lamp in the direction and stepped into the passage.

11:00:28.741 --> 11:00:32.741
There was no sign of anyone, and as there were no corners, no doors,

11:00:33.141 --> 11:00:36.161
no aperture of any kind but only the solid walls of the passage,

11:00:36.781 --> 11:00:38.741
there could be no hiding place even for him.

11:00:39.761 --> 11:00:43.201
I took it that fear had helped imagination and said nothing.

11:00:46.001 --> 11:00:49.901
A few moments later I saw Morris step suddenly back from a corner which he was examining.

11:00:50.481 --> 11:00:55.561
We all followed his movements with our eyes, for undoubtedly some nervousness was growing on us,

11:00:55.941 --> 11:00:59.121
and we saw a whole mass of phosphorescence which twinkled like stars.

11:00:59.881 --> 11:01:04.481
We all instinctively drew back. The whole place was becoming alive with rats.

11:01:06.441 --> 11:01:09.601
For a moment or two we stood appalled, all save Lord Godalning,

11:01:10.061 --> 11:01:12.221
who was seemingly prepared for such an emergency.

11:01:13.121 --> 11:01:17.381
Rushing over to the great iron-bound oaken door which Dr. Seward had described from the outside,

11:01:17.381 --> 11:01:21.141
and which I had seen myself, he turned the key in the lock,

11:01:21.461 --> 11:01:23.521
drew the huge bolts and swung the door open.

11:01:24.161 --> 11:01:28.321
Then, taking his little silver whistle from his pocket, he blew a low shrill call.

11:01:29.201 --> 11:01:32.181
It was answered from behind Dr. Seward's house by the yelping of dogs,

11:01:32.661 --> 11:01:36.721
and after about a minute three terriers came dashing round the corner of the house.

11:01:37.981 --> 11:01:39.841
Unconsciously we had all moved towards the door,

11:01:40.201 --> 11:01:42.921
and as we moved I noticed that the dust had been much disturbed.

11:01:43.721 --> 11:01:46.561
The boxes which had been taken out had been brought this way.

11:01:46.561 --> 11:01:50.761
But even in the minute that had elapsed the number of the rats had vastly increased.

11:01:51.661 --> 11:01:54.181
They seemed to swarm over the place all at once,

11:01:54.601 --> 11:01:58.861
till the lamplight shining on their moving dark bodies and glittering baleful eyes

11:01:58.861 --> 11:02:02.061
made the place look like a bank of earth set with fireflies.

11:02:03.341 --> 11:02:06.841
The dogs dashed on but at the threshold suddenly stopped and snarled,

11:02:07.221 --> 11:02:12.061
and then, simultaneously lifting their noses, began to howl in most lugubrious fashion.

11:02:12.701 --> 11:02:16.541
The rats were multiplying in thousands, and we moved out.

11:02:17.921 --> 11:02:21.781
Lord Godalming lifted one of the dogs and, carrying him in, placed him on the floor.

11:02:22.861 --> 11:02:27.301
The instant his feet touched the ground he seemed to recover his courage and rushed at his natural enemies.

11:02:28.321 --> 11:02:31.961
They fled before him so fast that before he had shaken the life out of a score,

11:02:32.501 --> 11:02:35.261
the other dogs, who had by now been lifted in the same manner,

11:02:35.861 --> 11:02:38.101
had but small prey ere the whole mass had vanished.

11:02:40.701 --> 11:02:44.161
With their going it seemed as if some evil presence had departed,

11:02:44.541 --> 11:02:49.061
for the dogs frisked about and barked merrily as they made sudden darts at their prostrate foes,

11:02:49.221 --> 11:02:52.341
and turned them over and over and tossed them in the air with vicious shakes.

11:02:53.221 --> 11:02:55.201
We all seemed to find our spirits rise.

11:02:56.001 --> 11:02:59.781
Whether it was the purifying of the deadly atmosphere by the opening of the chapel door,

11:03:00.321 --> 11:03:03.721
or the relief we experienced by finding ourselves in the open, I know not,

11:03:04.101 --> 11:03:07.441
but most certainly the shadow of dread seemed to slip from us like a robe,

11:03:07.441 --> 11:03:10.941
and the occasion of our coming lost something of its grim significance,

11:03:11.581 --> 11:03:13.801
though we did not slacken the wit in our resolution.

11:03:15.021 --> 11:03:17.581
We closed the outer door and barred and locked it,

11:03:17.841 --> 11:03:20.481
and bringing the dogs with us began our search of the house.

11:03:21.701 --> 11:03:25.081
We found nothing throughout except dust in extraordinary proportions,

11:03:25.801 --> 11:03:29.641
and all untouched save for my own footsteps when I had made my first visit.

11:03:30.901 --> 11:03:34.001
Never once did the dogs exhibit any symptom of uneasiness,

11:03:34.001 --> 11:03:37.001
and even when we returned to the chapel they frisked about

11:03:37.001 --> 11:03:39.641
as though they had been rabbit hunting in a summer wood.

11:03:41.181 --> 11:03:44.521
The morning was quickening in the east when we emerged from the front.

11:03:45.421 --> 11:03:48.101
Dr Van Helsing had taken the key of the hall door from the bunch

11:03:48.101 --> 11:03:53.101
and locked the door in orthodox fashion, putting the key into his pocket when he had done.

11:03:54.381 --> 11:03:57.981
So far, he said, our night has been eminently successful.

11:03:58.621 --> 11:04:00.961
No harm has come to us such as I feared might be,

11:04:00.961 --> 11:04:03.581
and yet we have ascertained how many boxes are missing.

11:04:04.241 --> 11:04:07.861
More than all do I rejoice that this, our first and perhaps our most difficult

11:04:07.861 --> 11:04:09.641
and dangerous step has been accomplished,

11:04:10.061 --> 11:04:12.601
without bringing there into our most sweet madame Mina,

11:04:13.181 --> 11:04:16.281
or troubling her waking or sleeping thoughts with sights and sounds

11:04:16.281 --> 11:04:18.461
and smells of horror which she might never forget.

11:04:20.121 --> 11:04:25.221
One lesson, too, we have learned, if it be allowable to argue a particularity,

11:04:25.641 --> 11:04:28.181
that the brute beasts which are at the Count's command

11:04:28.181 --> 11:04:31.141
are yet themselves not amenable to his spiritual power,

11:04:31.541 --> 11:04:35.561
for look, these rats that would come to his call just as from his castle top

11:04:35.561 --> 11:04:38.901
he summoned the wolves to your going and to that poor mother's cry,

11:04:39.321 --> 11:04:43.401
though they come to him, they run pell-mell from the so little dogs my friend Arthur.

11:04:44.541 --> 11:04:49.501
We have other matters before us, other dangers, other fears, and that monster.

11:04:50.461 --> 11:04:55.261
He has not used his power over the brute world for the only or the last time tonight,

11:04:55.261 --> 11:04:57.241
so be it that he has gone elsewhere.

11:04:57.821 --> 11:05:03.221
Good, it has given us opportunity to cry check in some ways in this check game

11:05:03.221 --> 11:05:05.421
which we play for the sake of human souls.

11:05:06.521 --> 11:05:09.141
Now let us go home, the dawn is close at hand

11:05:09.141 --> 11:05:12.201
and we have reason to be content with our first night's work.

11:05:12.801 --> 11:05:16.741
It may be ordained that we have many nights and days to follow, if full of peril,

11:05:17.341 --> 11:05:20.621
but we must go on and from no danger shall we shrink.

11:05:23.561 --> 11:05:26.161
The house was silent when we got back,

11:05:26.481 --> 11:05:30.081
save for some poor creature who was screaming away in one of the distant wards

11:05:30.081 --> 11:05:33.001
and a low moaning sound from Renfield's room.

11:05:34.441 --> 11:05:37.781
The poor wretch was doubtless torturing himself after the manner of the insane

11:05:37.781 --> 11:05:39.581
with needless thoughts of pain.

11:05:42.181 --> 11:05:45.641
I came tiptoe into our own room and found Mina asleep,

11:05:46.101 --> 11:05:49.481
breathing so softly that I had to put my ear down to hear it.

11:05:49.481 --> 11:05:51.581
She looks paler than usual.

11:05:52.201 --> 11:05:54.441
I hope the meeting tonight has not upset her.

11:05:55.101 --> 11:05:58.221
I am truly thankful that she is to be left out of our future work

11:05:58.221 --> 11:05:59.941
and even of our deliberations.

11:06:00.881 --> 11:06:03.321
It is too great a strain for a woman to bear.

11:06:04.561 --> 11:06:07.541
I did not think so at first but I know better now.

11:06:08.241 --> 11:06:10.041
Therefore I am glad that it is settled.

11:06:10.761 --> 11:06:12.921
There may be things which would frighten her to hear

11:06:12.921 --> 11:06:15.861
and yet to conceal them from her might be worse than to tell her

11:06:15.861 --> 11:06:18.201
if once she suspected that there was any concealment.

11:06:19.281 --> 11:06:21.881
Henceforth our work is to be a sealed book to her

11:06:21.881 --> 11:06:24.601
till at least such time as we can tell her that all is finished

11:06:24.601 --> 11:06:27.201
and the earth free from a monster of the netherworld.

11:06:28.461 --> 11:06:32.341
I dare say it would be difficult to begin to keep silence after such confidence as ours

11:06:32.341 --> 11:06:37.481
but I must be resolute and tomorrow I shall keep dark over tonight's doings

11:06:37.481 --> 11:06:39.661
and shall refuse to speak of anything that has happened.

11:06:40.921 --> 11:06:43.621
I rest on the sofa so as not to disturb her.

11:06:46.921 --> 11:06:48.781
First of October, later.

11:06:49.681 --> 11:06:52.301
I suppose it was natural that we should all have overslept ourselves

11:06:52.301 --> 11:06:55.621
for the day was a busy one and the night had no rest at all.

11:06:56.281 --> 11:06:57.961
Even Mina must have felt his exhaustion

11:06:57.961 --> 11:07:01.421
for though I slept till the sun was high I was awake before her

11:07:01.421 --> 11:07:03.821
and had to call two or three times before she awoke.

11:07:05.401 --> 11:07:09.401
Indeed she was so sound asleep that for a few seconds she did not recognise me

11:07:09.401 --> 11:07:11.761
but looked at me with a sort of blank terror

11:07:11.761 --> 11:07:14.641
as one looks who has been waked out of a bad dream.

11:07:15.721 --> 11:07:19.741
She complained a little of being tired and I let her rest till later in the day.

11:07:20.601 --> 11:07:23.221
We now know of 21 boxes having been removed

11:07:23.701 --> 11:07:26.521
and if it be that several were taken in any of these removals

11:07:26.521 --> 11:07:28.581
we may be able to trace them all.

11:07:29.181 --> 11:07:31.641
Such will of course immensely simplify our labour

11:07:32.181 --> 11:07:34.521
and the sooner the matter is attended to the better.

11:07:35.361 --> 11:07:37.561
I shall look up Thomas Snelling today.

11:07:39.481 --> 11:07:40.701
Dr. Seward's diary

11:07:41.241 --> 11:07:43.921
1st of October. It was towards noon

11:07:43.921 --> 11:07:46.741
when I was awakened by the professor walking into my room.

11:07:47.301 --> 11:07:49.201
He was more jolly and cheerful than usual

11:07:49.201 --> 11:07:51.701
and it is quite evident that last night's work

11:07:51.701 --> 11:07:54.081
has helped take some of the brooding weight off his mind.

11:07:55.481 --> 11:07:57.741
After going over the adventure of the night he suddenly said

11:07:57.741 --> 11:07:59.701
your patient interests me much.

11:08:00.161 --> 11:08:02.381
May it be that with you I visit him this morning

11:08:02.381 --> 11:08:05.841
or if that you are too occupied I can go alone if it may be.

11:08:06.061 --> 11:08:08.741
It is a new experience to me to find a lunatic

11:08:08.741 --> 11:08:10.801
who talks philosophy and reason so sound.

11:08:12.021 --> 11:08:13.721
I had some work to do which pressed

11:08:13.721 --> 11:08:16.561
so I told him that if he would go alone I would be glad

11:08:16.561 --> 11:08:18.501
as then I should not have to keep him waiting.

11:08:19.001 --> 11:08:21.621
So I called an attendant and gave him the necessary instructions.

11:08:23.181 --> 11:08:24.741
Before the professor left the room

11:08:24.741 --> 11:08:28.161
I cautioned him against getting any false impression from my patient.

11:08:29.281 --> 11:08:32.281
But, he answered, I want to talk to him of himself

11:08:32.281 --> 11:08:34.841
and of his delusion as to consuming live things.

11:08:35.341 --> 11:08:38.201
He said to Madame Mina as I see in your diary of yesterday

11:08:38.201 --> 11:08:40.381
that he had once had such a belief.

11:08:41.281 --> 11:08:42.681
Why do you smile, friend John?

11:08:43.881 --> 11:08:45.981
Excuse me, I said, but the answer is here.

11:08:46.781 --> 11:08:48.661
I laid my hand on the tight written matter.

11:08:49.361 --> 11:08:52.141
When Arsene and Learned Lunatic made that very statement

11:08:52.141 --> 11:08:53.661
of how he used to consume life

11:08:54.141 --> 11:08:56.861
his mouth was actually nauseous with the flies and spiders

11:08:56.861 --> 11:08:59.741
which he had eaten just before Mrs Harker entered the room.

11:09:01.821 --> 11:09:03.321
Van Helsing smiled in turn.

11:09:04.121 --> 11:09:06.641
Good, he said, your memory is true, friend John.

11:09:06.641 --> 11:09:07.801
I should have remembered.

11:09:08.401 --> 11:09:11.041
And yet it is this very obliquity of thought and memory

11:09:11.041 --> 11:09:13.341
which makes mental disease such a fascinating study.

11:09:14.061 --> 11:09:16.801
Perhaps I may gain more knowledge out of the folly of this madman

11:09:16.801 --> 11:09:18.721
than I shall from teaching of the most wise.

11:09:19.241 --> 11:09:19.841
Who knows?

11:09:21.041 --> 11:09:25.001
I went on with my work and before long was through that in hand.

11:09:25.721 --> 11:09:27.961
It seemed that the time had been very short indeed.

11:09:28.401 --> 11:09:30.221
But there was Van Helsing back in the study.

11:09:31.081 --> 11:09:33.921
Do I interrupt? he asked politely as he stood at the door.

11:09:33.921 --> 11:09:36.281
Not at all, I answered. Come in.

11:09:36.521 --> 11:09:38.041
My work is finished and I am free.

11:09:38.421 --> 11:09:39.861
I can go with you now if you like.

11:09:40.821 --> 11:09:43.001
It is needless. I have seen him.

11:09:43.781 --> 11:09:44.181
Well?

11:09:46.161 --> 11:09:48.201
I fear that he does not appraise me at much.

11:09:48.801 --> 11:09:49.881
Our interview was short.

11:09:50.381 --> 11:09:52.801
When I entered his room he was sitting on a stool in the centre

11:09:52.801 --> 11:09:54.101
with his elbows on his knees

11:09:54.101 --> 11:09:56.921
and his face was the picture of sullen discontent.

11:09:57.441 --> 11:09:59.141
I spoke to him as cheerfully as I could

11:09:59.141 --> 11:10:01.441
and with such a measure of respect as I could assume.

11:10:01.441 --> 11:10:03.741
He made no reply whatever.

11:10:04.461 --> 11:10:05.721
Don't you know me? I asked.

11:10:06.521 --> 11:10:07.561
His answer was not reassuring.

11:10:08.781 --> 11:10:09.721
I know you well enough.

11:10:09.941 --> 11:10:11.641
You are the old fool Van Helsing.

11:10:12.261 --> 11:10:13.241
I wish you would take yourself

11:10:13.241 --> 11:10:15.421
and your idiotic brain theories somewhere else.

11:10:15.841 --> 11:10:17.361
Damn all thick-headed Dutchman!

11:10:18.261 --> 11:10:19.521
Not a word more would he say

11:10:19.521 --> 11:10:21.341
but sat in his implacable sullenness

11:10:21.341 --> 11:10:24.381
as indifferent to me as though I had not been in the room at all.

11:10:25.141 --> 11:10:26.401
Thus departed for this time

11:10:26.401 --> 11:10:28.781
my chance of much learning from this so clever lunatic.

11:10:29.141 --> 11:10:30.601
So I shall go, if I may,

11:10:30.601 --> 11:10:32.081
and cheer myself with a few happy words

11:10:32.081 --> 11:10:33.441
with that sweet soul, Madame Mina.

11:10:34.601 --> 11:10:37.041
Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakably

11:10:37.041 --> 11:10:38.701
that she is no more to be pained

11:10:38.701 --> 11:10:40.781
no more to be worried with our terrible things.

11:10:41.501 --> 11:10:43.021
Though we shall much miss her help

11:10:43.021 --> 11:10:44.241
it is better so.

11:10:45.621 --> 11:10:46.741
I agree with you

11:10:46.741 --> 11:10:48.841
with all my heart, I answered earnestly

11:10:48.841 --> 11:10:51.141
for I did not want him to weaken in this matter.

11:10:51.901 --> 11:10:53.541
Mrs Harker is better out of it.

11:10:53.821 --> 11:10:55.361
Things are quite bad enough for us

11:10:55.361 --> 11:10:56.421
all men of the world

11:10:56.421 --> 11:10:58.581
and who have been in many tight places in our time

11:10:58.581 --> 11:11:00.701
but it is no place for a woman

11:11:00.701 --> 11:11:02.781
and if she had remained in touch with the affair

11:11:02.781 --> 11:11:05.941
it would in time infallibly have wrecked her.

11:11:06.781 --> 11:11:09.081
So Van Helsing has gone to confer with Mrs Harker

11:11:09.081 --> 11:11:10.061
and Harker.

11:11:10.261 --> 11:11:12.141
Quincy and Art are all out following up the clues

11:11:12.141 --> 11:11:13.021
as to the earth boxes.

11:11:13.581 --> 11:11:15.021
I shall finish my round of work

11:11:15.021 --> 11:11:16.601
and we shall meet tonight.

11:11:20.081 --> 11:11:21.541
Mina Harker's journal

11:11:22.641 --> 11:11:23.861
1st of October

11:11:25.021 --> 11:11:26.481
It is strange to me

11:11:26.481 --> 11:11:28.301
to be kept in the dark as I am today

11:11:28.301 --> 11:11:30.141
after Jonathan's full confidence

11:11:30.141 --> 11:11:31.101
for so many years

11:11:31.101 --> 11:11:33.621
to see him manifestly avoid certain matters

11:11:33.621 --> 11:11:35.661
and those are the most vital of all.

11:11:36.501 --> 11:11:37.681
This morning I slept late

11:11:37.681 --> 11:11:39.101
after the fatigues of yesterday

11:11:39.101 --> 11:11:41.721
and though Jonathan was late too he was the earlier.

11:11:42.561 --> 11:11:44.361
He spoke to me before he went out

11:11:44.361 --> 11:11:46.241
never more sweetly or tenderly

11:11:46.241 --> 11:11:47.821
but he never mentioned a word

11:11:47.821 --> 11:11:50.201
of what had happened in the visit to the Count's house

11:11:50.201 --> 11:11:52.081
and yet he must have known

11:11:52.081 --> 11:11:54.061
how terribly anxious I was.

11:11:54.061 --> 11:11:55.321
Poor dear fellow!

11:11:55.501 --> 11:11:57.221
I suppose it must have distressed him

11:11:57.221 --> 11:11:58.621
even more than it did me.

11:11:59.421 --> 11:12:00.781
They all agreed that it was best

11:12:00.781 --> 11:12:02.981
that I should not be drawn further into this awful work

11:12:02.981 --> 11:12:04.141
and I acquiesced

11:12:04.141 --> 11:12:06.701
but to think that he keeps anything from me

11:12:06.701 --> 11:12:09.081
and now I am crying like a silly fool

11:12:09.081 --> 11:12:11.421
when I know it comes from my husband's great love

11:12:11.421 --> 11:12:14.261
and from the good, good wishes of those other strong men.

11:12:15.801 --> 11:12:17.141
That has done me good.

11:12:17.901 --> 11:12:19.821
Well, some day Jonathan will tell me all

11:12:19.821 --> 11:12:21.441
and lest it should ever be

11:12:21.441 --> 11:12:22.781
that he should think for a moment

11:12:22.781 --> 11:12:24.341
that I kept anything from him

11:12:24.341 --> 11:12:26.501
I still keep my journal as usual.

11:12:27.381 --> 11:12:28.841
Then, if he is feared of my trust

11:12:28.841 --> 11:12:31.441
I shall show it to him with every thought of my heart

11:12:31.441 --> 11:12:33.441
put down for his dear eyes to read.

11:12:34.321 --> 11:12:35.601
I feel strangely sad

11:12:35.601 --> 11:12:36.861
and low-spirited today.

11:12:37.721 --> 11:12:40.061
I suppose it is the reaction from the terrible excitement.

11:12:42.301 --> 11:12:43.341
Last night I went to bed

11:12:43.341 --> 11:12:44.341
when the men had gone

11:12:44.341 --> 11:12:46.221
simply because they told me to.

11:12:46.941 --> 11:12:48.081
I didn't feel sleepy

11:12:48.081 --> 11:12:50.241
and I did feel full of devouring anxiety.

11:12:51.701 --> 11:12:53.521
I kept thinking over everything that has been

11:12:53.521 --> 11:12:55.381
ever since Jonathan came to see me in London

11:12:55.381 --> 11:12:57.541
and it all seems like a horrible tragedy

11:12:57.881 --> 11:13:00.761
with fate pressing on relentlessly to some destined end.

11:13:01.741 --> 11:13:04.501
Everything that one does seems, no matter how right it may be

11:13:04.501 --> 11:13:07.161
to bring on the very thing which is most to be deplored.

11:13:07.761 --> 11:13:09.621
If I hadn't gone to Whitby perhaps

11:13:09.621 --> 11:13:11.481
poor dear Lucy would be with us now.

11:13:12.041 --> 11:13:14.681
She hadn't taken to visiting the church out till I came

11:13:14.681 --> 11:13:17.041
and if she hadn't come there in the daytime with me

11:13:17.041 --> 11:13:18.381
she wouldn't have walked in her sleep

11:13:18.381 --> 11:13:20.581
and if she hadn't gone there at night and asleep

11:13:20.581 --> 11:13:22.941
that monster wouldn't have destroyed her as he did.

11:13:23.541 --> 11:13:26.101
Oh, why did I ever go to Whitby?

11:13:26.381 --> 11:13:27.961
There now, crying again.

11:13:28.901 --> 11:13:30.501
I wonder what has come over me today.

11:13:31.061 --> 11:13:32.441
I must hide it from Jonathan

11:13:32.441 --> 11:13:35.001
for if he knew that I had been crying twice in one morning

11:13:35.621 --> 11:13:37.641
I, who never cried on my own account

11:13:37.641 --> 11:13:39.561
and whom he has never caused to shed a tear

11:13:39.561 --> 11:13:41.981
the dear fellow would fret his heart out.

11:13:42.821 --> 11:13:44.201
I shall put a bold face on

11:13:44.201 --> 11:13:45.661
and if I do feel weepy

11:13:45.661 --> 11:13:47.241
he shall never see it.

11:13:47.861 --> 11:13:49.601
I suppose it is just one of the lessons

11:13:49.601 --> 11:13:51.221
that we poor women have to learn.

11:13:53.261 --> 11:13:56.121
I can't quite remember how I fell asleep last night.

11:13:56.661 --> 11:13:58.321
I remember hearing the sudden

11:13:58.321 --> 11:14:00.421
barking of the dogs and a lot of queer sounds

11:14:00.421 --> 11:14:02.641
like praying on a very tumultuous

11:14:02.641 --> 11:14:04.421
scale from Mr. Renfield's room

11:14:04.421 --> 11:14:06.141
which is somewhere under this.

11:14:06.841 --> 11:14:08.501
And then there was silence over everything

11:14:08.501 --> 11:14:10.021
silence so profound

11:14:10.021 --> 11:14:12.121
that it startled me and I got up

11:14:12.121 --> 11:14:13.181
and looked out of the window.

11:14:14.221 --> 11:14:15.481
All was dark and silent

11:14:15.481 --> 11:14:17.661
the black shadows thrown by the moonlight

11:14:17.661 --> 11:14:19.921
seeming full of a silent mystery of their own.

11:14:20.881 --> 11:14:22.361
Not a thing seemed to be stirring

11:14:22.361 --> 11:14:24.021
but all to be grim

11:14:24.021 --> 11:14:25.701
and fixed as death or fate

11:14:25.701 --> 11:14:27.941
so that a thin streak of white mist

11:14:27.941 --> 11:14:30.261
that crept with almost imperceptible slowness

11:14:30.261 --> 11:14:32.001
across the grass towards the house

11:14:32.001 --> 11:14:34.081
seemed to have a sentience and a vitality

11:14:34.081 --> 11:14:34.661
of its own.

11:14:35.861 --> 11:14:37.701
I think that the digression of my thoughts

11:14:37.701 --> 11:14:40.081
must have done me good, for when I got back to bed

11:14:40.081 --> 11:14:41.981
I found a lethargy creeping over me.

11:14:42.481 --> 11:14:44.681
I lay a while but could not quite sleep

11:14:44.681 --> 11:14:46.241
so I got out and looked out

11:14:46.241 --> 11:14:47.061
of the window again.

11:14:47.841 --> 11:14:50.461
The mist was spreading and was now close up to the house

11:14:50.461 --> 11:14:52.161
so that I could see it lying thick

11:14:52.161 --> 11:14:53.881
against the wall as though it was

11:14:53.881 --> 11:14:55.061
stealing up to the windows.

11:14:56.081 --> 11:14:57.901
The poor man was more loud than ever

11:14:57.901 --> 11:15:00.141
and though I could not distinguish a word he said

11:15:00.141 --> 11:15:02.241
I could in some way recognize in his

11:15:02.241 --> 11:15:04.121
tones some passionate entreaty on

11:15:04.121 --> 11:15:04.701
his part.

11:15:06.001 --> 11:15:07.421
Then there was the sound of a struggle

11:15:07.421 --> 11:15:09.961
and I knew that the attendants were dealing with him.

11:15:10.701 --> 11:15:11.681
I was so frightened

11:15:11.681 --> 11:15:13.441
that I crept into bed and pulled the clothes

11:15:13.441 --> 11:15:15.781
over my head putting my fingers in my ears.

11:15:16.761 --> 11:15:18.201
I was not then a bit sleepy

11:15:18.201 --> 11:15:19.601
at least so I thought

11:15:19.601 --> 11:15:20.981
but I must have fallen asleep

11:15:20.981 --> 11:15:23.641
for except dreams I do not remember anything

11:15:23.641 --> 11:15:25.801
until the morning when Jonathan woke me.

11:15:26.321 --> 11:15:27.801
I think that it took me an effort

11:15:27.801 --> 11:15:29.861
and a little time to realize where I was

11:15:29.861 --> 11:15:32.321
and that it was Jonathan who was bending over me.

11:15:33.221 --> 11:15:33.701
My dream

11:15:33.701 --> 11:15:35.801
was very peculiar and was almost typical

11:15:35.801 --> 11:15:37.801
of the way that waking thoughts become merged

11:15:37.801 --> 11:15:39.501
in or continued in dreams.

11:15:41.181 --> 11:15:41.861
I thought that

11:15:41.861 --> 11:15:43.921
I was asleep and waiting for Jonathan to come

11:15:43.921 --> 11:15:45.941
back. I was very anxious

11:15:45.941 --> 11:15:47.661
about him and I was powerless to act.

11:15:47.961 --> 11:15:49.901
My feet and my hands and my brain were

11:15:49.901 --> 11:15:51.861
weighted so that nothing could proceed

11:15:51.861 --> 11:15:52.901
at the usual pace

11:15:53.521 --> 11:15:55.761
and so I slept uneasily and thought.

11:15:56.781 --> 11:15:57.861
Then it began to dawn upon

11:15:57.861 --> 11:15:59.981
me that the air was heavy and dank and

11:15:59.981 --> 11:16:01.841
cold. I put back the clothes

11:16:01.841 --> 11:16:03.821
from my face and found to my surprise that all

11:16:03.821 --> 11:16:06.201
was dim around. The gaslight

11:16:06.201 --> 11:16:08.001
which I had left lit for Jonathan

11:16:08.001 --> 11:16:09.981
but turned down came only

11:16:09.981 --> 11:16:11.841
like a tiny red spark through the

11:16:11.841 --> 11:16:13.821
fog which had evidently grown thicker

11:16:13.821 --> 11:16:15.101
and poured into the room.

11:16:15.861 --> 11:16:17.801
Then it occurred to me that I had shut the

11:16:17.801 --> 11:16:19.281
window before I had come to bed.

11:16:19.941 --> 11:16:21.841
I would have got out to make certain on the point

11:16:21.841 --> 11:16:23.801
but some leaden lethargy seemed to chain

11:16:23.801 --> 11:16:25.341
my limbs and even my will.

11:16:26.221 --> 11:16:27.481
I lay still and endured.

11:16:27.781 --> 11:16:29.861
That was all. I closed

11:16:29.861 --> 11:16:31.921
my eyes but could still see through my eyelids.

11:16:31.921 --> 11:16:33.981
It is wonderful what tricks our dreams

11:16:33.981 --> 11:16:36.401
players and how conveniently we can imagine.

11:16:37.721 --> 11:16:38.081
The mist

11:16:38.081 --> 11:16:39.921
grew thicker and thicker and I could see

11:16:39.921 --> 11:16:42.061
now how it came in for I could see it

11:16:42.061 --> 11:16:44.061
like smoke or with the white energy

11:16:44.061 --> 11:16:45.941
of boiling water pouring in

11:16:45.941 --> 11:16:47.981
not through the window but through the joinings

11:16:47.981 --> 11:16:50.061
of the door. It got thicker

11:16:50.061 --> 11:16:52.301
and thicker till it seemed as if it became

11:16:52.301 --> 11:16:53.921
concentrated into a sort of pillar

11:16:53.921 --> 11:16:55.881
of cloud in the room through the top

11:16:55.881 --> 11:16:57.761
of which I could see the light of the gas

11:16:57.761 --> 11:16:59.541
shining like a red eye.

11:17:00.201 --> 11:17:02.161
Things began to whirl through my brain

11:17:02.161 --> 11:17:04.061
just as the cloudy column was now whirling

11:17:04.061 --> 11:17:06.121
in the room and through it all

11:17:06.121 --> 11:17:07.461
came the scriptural words

11:17:07.461 --> 11:17:10.021
a pillar of cloud by day and of fire

11:17:10.021 --> 11:17:10.681
by night.

11:17:11.681 --> 11:17:13.621
Was it indeed such spiritual guidance

11:17:13.621 --> 11:17:15.061
that was coming to me in my sleep?

11:17:16.441 --> 11:17:17.961
But the pillar was composed of both

11:17:17.961 --> 11:17:19.801
the day and the night guiding for the fire

11:17:19.801 --> 11:17:21.741
was in the red eye which at the thought

11:17:21.741 --> 11:17:24.001
got a new fascination for me till as I looked

11:17:24.001 --> 11:17:25.801
the fire divided and seemed

11:17:25.801 --> 11:17:28.221
to shine on me through the fog like two red eyes

11:17:28.221 --> 11:17:30.461
such as Lucy told me of in her momentary

11:17:30.461 --> 11:17:32.421
mental wandering when on the cliff

11:17:32.421 --> 11:17:34.461
the dying sunlight struck the windows

11:17:34.461 --> 11:17:35.681
of St Mary's Church.

11:17:37.041 --> 11:17:38.561
Suddenly the horror burst upon

11:17:38.561 --> 11:17:40.461
me that it was thus that Jonathan

11:17:40.461 --> 11:17:42.081
had seen those awful women

11:17:42.081 --> 11:17:44.401
growing into reality through the whirling

11:17:44.401 --> 11:17:46.401
mist in the moonlight and in my

11:17:46.401 --> 11:17:48.561
dream I must have fainted for all became

11:17:48.561 --> 11:17:49.541
black darkness.

11:17:50.081 --> 11:17:52.561
The last conscious effort which my imagination

11:17:52.561 --> 11:17:54.301
made was to show me a

11:17:54.301 --> 11:17:56.461
livid white face bending over me

11:17:56.461 --> 11:17:57.261
out of the mist.

11:17:59.941 --> 11:18:01.861
I must be careful of such dreams

11:18:02.461 --> 11:18:04.401
for they would unseat one's reason if there

11:18:04.401 --> 11:18:05.421
were too much of them.

11:18:06.661 --> 11:18:08.261
I would get Dr. Van Helsing

11:18:08.261 --> 11:18:10.341
or Dr. Seward to prescribe something for me

11:18:10.341 --> 11:18:12.481
which would make me sleep only that

11:18:12.481 --> 11:18:13.721
I fear to alarm them.

11:18:14.441 --> 11:18:16.261
Such a dream at the present time would become

11:18:16.261 --> 11:18:18.141
woven into their fears for me.

11:18:18.661 --> 11:18:20.381
Tonight I shall strive hard to sleep

11:18:20.381 --> 11:18:22.381
naturally. If I do not

11:18:22.381 --> 11:18:24.581
I shall tomorrow night get them to give me a dose

11:18:24.581 --> 11:18:26.541
of chloral that cannot hurt me for once

11:18:26.541 --> 11:18:28.781
and it will give me a good night's sleep.

11:18:30.001 --> 11:18:30.821
Last night tired me

11:18:30.821 --> 11:18:32.581
more than if I had not slept at all.

11:18:35.081 --> 11:18:36.621
Second of October, 10pm

11:18:37.921 --> 11:18:38.661
Last night

11:18:38.661 --> 11:18:40.441
I slept but did not dream.

11:18:41.301 --> 11:18:42.621
I must have slept soundly for

11:18:42.621 --> 11:18:44.601
I was not waked by Jonathan coming to bed

11:18:44.601 --> 11:18:46.641
but the sleep has not refreshed me

11:18:46.641 --> 11:18:48.601
for today I feel terribly weak

11:18:48.601 --> 11:18:49.521
and spiritless.

11:18:50.361 --> 11:18:52.281
I spent all yesterday trying to read

11:18:52.281 --> 11:18:53.901
or lying down dozing.

11:18:54.781 --> 11:18:56.501
In the afternoon Mr. Renfield

11:18:56.501 --> 11:18:58.241
asked if he might see me.

11:18:58.561 --> 11:18:59.921
Poor man he was very gentle

11:18:59.921 --> 11:19:02.301
and when I came away he kissed my hand

11:19:02.301 --> 11:19:04.261
and bade God bless me.

11:19:04.681 --> 11:19:06.161
Some way it affected me much.

11:19:07.001 --> 11:19:08.581
I am crying when I think of him.

11:19:09.461 --> 11:19:10.481
This is a new weakness

11:19:10.481 --> 11:19:11.781
of which I must be careful.

11:19:12.141 --> 11:19:14.861
Jonathan would be miserable if he knew I had been crying.

11:19:15.721 --> 11:19:16.361
He and the others

11:19:16.361 --> 11:19:17.741
were out till dinner time

11:19:17.741 --> 11:19:19.181
and they all came in tired.

11:19:20.061 --> 11:19:22.141
I did what I could to brighten them up

11:19:22.141 --> 11:19:24.281
and I suppose that the effort did me good

11:19:24.281 --> 11:19:26.341
for I forgot how tired I was.

11:19:26.861 --> 11:19:28.321
After dinner they sent me to bed

11:19:28.321 --> 11:19:30.641
and all went off to smoke together as they said

11:19:30.641 --> 11:19:32.861
but I knew that they wanted to tell each other

11:19:32.861 --> 11:19:34.881
of what had occurred to each other during the day.

11:19:35.801 --> 11:19:37.241
I could see from Jonathan's manner

11:19:37.241 --> 11:19:39.181
that he had something important to communicate.

11:19:40.301 --> 11:19:41.461
I was not so sleepy

11:19:41.461 --> 11:19:42.381
as I should have been

11:19:42.381 --> 11:19:44.261
so before they went I asked Dr. Stewart

11:19:44.261 --> 11:19:46.281
to give me a little opiate of some kind

11:19:46.281 --> 11:19:48.381
as I had not slept well the night before.

11:19:48.961 --> 11:19:51.161
He very kindly made up a sleeping draft

11:19:51.161 --> 11:19:52.381
which he gave to me

11:19:52.381 --> 11:19:54.181
telling me that it would do me no harm

11:19:54.181 --> 11:19:55.281
as it was very mild.

11:19:57.161 --> 11:19:58.241
I have taken it

11:19:58.241 --> 11:19:59.341
and am waiting for sleep

11:19:59.341 --> 11:20:00.761
which still keeps aloof.

11:20:01.781 --> 11:20:03.421
I hope I have not done wrong

11:20:03.421 --> 11:20:05.241
for as sleep begins to flirt with me

11:20:05.241 --> 11:20:06.441
a new fear comes

11:20:06.921 --> 11:20:09.521
that I may have been foolish in thus depriving myself

11:20:09.521 --> 11:20:10.601
of the power of waking.

11:20:11.821 --> 11:20:13.141
I might want it.

11:20:13.701 --> 11:20:14.781
Here comes sleep.

11:20:14.781 --> 11:20:16.941
Good night.

11:20:22.241 --> 11:20:24.341
Read in Nottingham, England

11:20:24.341 --> 11:20:27.201
on the 28th January 2006

11:20:27.201 --> 11:20:28.781
by Alex Foster

11:20:28.781 --> 11:20:32.841
www.alexfoster.me.uk

11:21:06.284 --> 11:21:07.964
Jonathan Harker's Journal

11:21:09.464 --> 11:21:11.724
1st October, Evening

11:21:13.584 --> 11:21:17.304
I found Thomas Snelling in his house at Bethnal Green,

11:21:17.664 --> 11:21:21.204
but unhappily he was not in a condition to remember anything.

11:21:22.404 --> 11:21:26.544
The very prospect of beer which my expected coming had opened to him,

11:21:26.764 --> 11:21:31.504
had proved too much, and he had begun too early on his expected debauch.

11:21:32.184 --> 11:21:37.304
I learned, however, from his wife, who seemed a decent poor soul,

11:21:37.964 --> 11:21:40.244
that he was only the assistant of Smollett,

11:21:41.144 --> 11:21:43.804
who of the two mates was the responsible person.

11:21:44.884 --> 11:21:49.824
So off I drove to Walworth, and found Mr. Joseph Smollett at home,

11:21:50.044 --> 11:21:54.364
and in his shirt sleeves, taking a late tea out of a saucer.

11:21:54.824 --> 11:22:00.404
He is a decent, intelligent fellow, distinctly a good, reliable type of workman,

11:22:00.844 --> 11:22:02.624
and with a headpiece of his own.

11:22:03.524 --> 11:22:06.184
He remembered all about the incident of the boxes,

11:22:06.924 --> 11:22:08.884
and from a wonderful dog-eared notebook,

11:22:09.164 --> 11:22:13.124
which he produced from some mysterious receptacle about the seat of his trousers,

11:22:14.004 --> 11:22:18.264
and which had hieroglyphical entries in thick half-obliterated pencil,

11:22:19.124 --> 11:22:21.344
he gave me the destinations of the boxes.

11:22:22.204 --> 11:22:26.044
There were, he said, six in the card-load which he took from Carfax,

11:22:26.044 --> 11:22:30.164
and left at 197 Chickson Street, Mile End, New Town,

11:22:30.884 --> 11:22:34.384
and another six which he deposited at Jamaica Lane, Bermondsey.

11:22:35.684 --> 11:22:40.384
If, then, the Count meant to scatter these ghastly refuges of his over London,

11:22:40.944 --> 11:22:43.444
these places were chosen as the first of delivery,

11:22:44.144 --> 11:22:46.424
so that later he might distribute more fully.

11:22:47.684 --> 11:22:51.344
The systematic manner in which this was done made me think that he could not mean

11:22:51.344 --> 11:22:53.744
to confine himself to two sides of London.

11:22:54.504 --> 11:22:57.864
He was now fixed on the Far East on the Northern Shore,

11:22:58.104 --> 11:23:00.784
on the East of the Southern Shore, and on the South.

11:23:01.744 --> 11:23:05.884
The North and West were surely never meant to be left out of his diabolical scheme,

11:23:06.504 --> 11:23:11.324
let alone the city itself, and the very heart of fashionable London in the South West and West.

11:23:12.504 --> 11:23:15.184
I went back to Smollett, and asked him if he could tell us

11:23:15.184 --> 11:23:17.584
if any other boxes had been taken from Carfax.

11:23:18.444 --> 11:23:19.304
He replied,

11:23:19.804 --> 11:23:22.544
Well, Governor, you've treated me very handsome.

11:23:23.244 --> 11:23:25.104
I had given him half a sovereign.

11:23:25.844 --> 11:23:27.404
And I'll tell you all I know.

11:23:28.304 --> 11:23:32.344
I heard a man by the name of Bloxham say four nights ago in the Aire and Ounce,

11:23:32.624 --> 11:23:37.864
in Pinchard Alley, as how he and his mate had had a rare dusty job in an old house at Perfleet.

11:23:38.744 --> 11:23:40.864
There ain't many such jobs as this here,

11:23:41.144 --> 11:23:44.144
and I'm thinking that maybe Sam Bloxham could tell you summat.

11:23:45.024 --> 11:23:47.384
I asked if he could tell me where to find him.

11:23:47.384 --> 11:23:52.484
I told him that if he could get me the address it would be worth another half sovereign to him.

11:23:53.544 --> 11:23:56.204
So he gulped down the rest of his tea and stood up,

11:23:56.384 --> 11:23:59.104
saying that he was going to begin the search then and there.

11:23:59.804 --> 11:24:01.584
At the door he stopped and said,

11:24:01.804 --> 11:24:05.164
Look here, Governor, there ain't no cent in mere keeping you here.

11:24:05.964 --> 11:24:08.464
I may find Sam soon, or I mayn't.

11:24:08.904 --> 11:24:12.744
But anyhow, he ain't like to be in a way to tell you much to-night.

11:24:13.804 --> 11:24:16.204
Sam is a rare one when he starts on the booze.

11:24:16.944 --> 11:24:21.404
If you can give me an envelope with a stamp on it, and put your address on it,

11:24:21.704 --> 11:24:24.684
I'll find out where Sam is to be found and post at you to-night.

11:24:25.944 --> 11:24:29.924
But you'd better be up after him soon in the morning, ever mind the booze the night afore.

11:24:31.224 --> 11:24:32.504
This was all practical.

11:24:33.364 --> 11:24:37.124
So one of the children went off with a penny to buy an envelope and a sheet of paper,

11:24:37.464 --> 11:24:38.744
and to keep the change.

11:24:39.844 --> 11:24:42.984
When she came back I addressed the envelope and stamped it,

11:24:42.984 --> 11:24:46.944
and when Smollett had again faithfully promised to post the address when found,

11:24:47.084 --> 11:24:48.344
I took my way to home.

11:24:49.324 --> 11:24:50.844
We're on the track anyhow.

11:24:51.824 --> 11:24:54.824
I am tired to-night, and I want to sleep.

11:24:56.044 --> 11:24:58.884
Mina is fast asleep, and looks a little too pale.

11:25:00.104 --> 11:25:02.144
Her eyes look as though she had been crying.

11:25:03.324 --> 11:25:06.404
Poor dear, I've no doubt it frets her to be kept in the dark.

11:25:07.384 --> 11:25:10.344
And it may make her doubly anxious about me and the others.

11:25:11.344 --> 11:25:13.284
But it is best as it is.

11:25:14.984 --> 11:25:19.504
It is better to be disappointed and worried in such a way now than to have her nerve broken.

11:25:20.624 --> 11:25:24.484
The doctors were quite right to insist on her being kept out of this dreadful business.

11:25:25.784 --> 11:25:30.144
I must be firm, for on me this particular burden of silence must rest.

11:25:31.584 --> 11:25:35.704
I shall not ever enter on the subject with her under any circumstances.

11:25:36.844 --> 11:25:43.004
Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for she herself has become reticent on the subject,

11:25:43.704 --> 11:25:48.504
and has not spoken of the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.

11:25:51.244 --> 11:25:57.044
Second October. Evening. A long and trying and exciting day.

11:25:58.384 --> 11:26:02.784
By the first post I got my directed envelope with a dirty scrap of paper enclosed,

11:26:02.784 --> 11:26:06.324
on which was written with a carpenter's pencil in a sprawling hand,

11:26:07.084 --> 11:26:15.104
Sam Bloxham, Corcoran's, 4 Poters Court, Bartle Street, Walworth. Ask for the dip height.

11:26:16.724 --> 11:26:19.784
I got the letter in bed and rose without waking Mina.

11:26:20.764 --> 11:26:24.064
She looked heavy and sleepy and pale and far from well.

11:26:24.904 --> 11:26:29.864
I determined not to wake her, but that when I should return from this new search

11:26:29.864 --> 11:26:32.344
I would arrange for her going back to Exeter.

11:26:33.364 --> 11:26:38.764
I think she would be happier in our own home with her daily tasks to interest her,

11:26:39.044 --> 11:26:41.264
than in being here amongst us and in ignorance.

11:26:42.704 --> 11:26:46.964
I only saw Dr Seward for a moment and told him where I was off to,

11:26:47.584 --> 11:26:51.484
promising to come back and tell the rest so soon as I should have found out anything.

11:26:53.204 --> 11:26:57.064
I drove to Walworth and found, with some difficulty, Potter's Court.

11:26:58.124 --> 11:27:03.104
Mr Smollett's spelling misled me, as I asked for Poters Court instead of Potter's Court.

11:27:04.204 --> 11:27:09.024
However, when I had found the court I had no difficulty in discovering Corcoran's lodging

11:27:09.024 --> 11:27:15.784
house. When I asked the man who came to the door for the dip height, he shook his head and said,

11:27:16.444 --> 11:27:22.324
I don't know him. There ain't no such person here. I never heard of him in all my blooming days.

11:27:23.104 --> 11:27:26.404
Don't believe there ain't nobody of that kind living here or anywheres.

11:27:27.464 --> 11:27:32.204
I took out Smollett's letter, and as I read it, it seemed to me that the lesson of the spelling of

11:27:32.204 --> 11:27:36.704
the name of the court might guide me. What are you? I asked.

11:27:37.864 --> 11:27:42.864
I'm the deputy, he answered. I saw at once that I was on the right track.

11:27:44.284 --> 11:27:50.044
Phonetic spelling had again misled me. A half-crowned tip put the deputy's knowledge at my

11:27:50.044 --> 11:27:55.644
disposal, and I learned that Mr Bloxham, who had slept off the remains of his beer on the previous

11:27:55.644 --> 11:28:01.684
night at Corcoran's, had left for his work at Poplar at five o'clock that morning. He could not

11:28:01.684 --> 11:28:07.224
tell me where the place of work was situated, but he had a vague idea that it was some kind of a

11:28:07.224 --> 11:28:14.344
newfangled warress, and with this slender clue I had to start for Poplar. It was twelve o'clock

11:28:14.344 --> 11:28:19.564
before I got any satisfactory hint of such a building, and this I got at a coffee shop,

11:28:19.844 --> 11:28:25.564
where some workmen were having their dinner. One of them suggested that there was being erected

11:28:25.564 --> 11:28:32.244
cross Angel Street a new cold storage building, and as this suited the condition of a newfangled

11:28:32.244 --> 11:28:39.464
warress, I at once drove to it. An interview with a surly gatekeeper and a surlier foreman,

11:28:40.184 --> 11:28:45.204
both of whom were appeased with the coin of the realm, put me on the track of Bloxham.

11:28:46.844 --> 11:28:51.984
He was sent for on my suggestion that I was willing to pay his day's wages to his foreman

11:28:51.984 --> 11:28:55.124
for the privilege of asking him a few questions on a private matter.

11:28:56.484 --> 11:29:02.224
He was a smart enough fellow, though rough of speech and bearing. When I had promised to pay

11:29:02.224 --> 11:29:07.224
for his information and given him an earnest, he told me that he had made two journeys between

11:29:07.224 --> 11:29:13.604
Carfax and a house in Piccadilly, and had taken from this house to the latter nine great boxes,

11:29:14.424 --> 11:29:19.484
main heavy ones, with a horse and cart hired by him for this purpose.

11:29:20.724 --> 11:29:25.804
I asked him if he could tell me the number of the house in Piccadilly, to which he replied,

11:29:26.524 --> 11:29:32.504
Well, Governor, I forgets the number, but it was only a few door from a big white church,

11:29:32.784 --> 11:29:38.944
or something of the kind, not long built. It was a dusty old house, too, though nothing to the

11:29:38.944 --> 11:29:44.824
dustiness of the house we took the blooming boxes from. How did you get in if both houses were empty?

11:29:45.704 --> 11:29:51.424
There was the old party that engaged me awaiting at the house at Purfleet. He helped me to lift the

11:29:51.424 --> 11:29:56.564
boxes and put them in the dray, cursed me, but he was the strongest chap I ever struck, and him an

11:29:56.564 --> 11:30:00.444
old fellow with a white moustache, one that thin you would think he couldn't throw a shadow.

11:30:01.384 --> 11:30:07.504
How this phrase thrilled through me! Why, he took up his end of the boxes like they was pounds of

11:30:07.504 --> 11:30:12.604
tea, and me a puffin' and a blowin' afore I could upend mine anyhow, and I'm no chicken neither.

11:30:13.204 --> 11:30:16.864
How did you get into the house in Piccadilly? I asked.

11:30:17.644 --> 11:30:22.424
He was there, too. He must have started off and got there afore me, for when I rung the bell

11:30:22.424 --> 11:30:26.204
he came and opened the door himself, and helped me carry the boxes into the hall.

11:30:27.124 --> 11:30:29.384
The whole nine? I asked.

11:30:30.524 --> 11:30:33.764
Yes, there was five in the first load and four in the second.

11:30:34.544 --> 11:30:37.864
It was main dry work, and I don't so well remember how I got home.

11:30:38.184 --> 11:30:41.424
I interrupted him. Were the boxes left in the hall?

11:30:42.244 --> 11:30:45.164
Yes, it was a big hall, and there was nothing else in it.

11:30:46.264 --> 11:30:50.344
I made one more attempt to further matters. You didn't have any key?

11:30:51.104 --> 11:30:55.384
Never used no key nor nothing. The old gent, he opened the door himself,

11:30:55.464 --> 11:31:00.164
and shut it again when I drove off. I don't remember the last time, but that was the beer.

11:31:01.324 --> 11:31:03.304
And you can't remember the number of the house?

11:31:04.284 --> 11:31:07.884
No, sir. But you needn't have no difficulty about that.

11:31:08.624 --> 11:31:13.484
It's iron with a stone front with a bow on it, and I steps up to the door.

11:31:13.884 --> 11:31:17.684
I know them steps, having had to carry the boxes up with three loafers that come round

11:31:17.684 --> 11:31:22.224
to earn a copper. The old gent gave them shillings, and they seeing they got so much,

11:31:22.284 --> 11:31:26.004
they wanted more. But he took one of them by the shoulder and was like to throw him

11:31:26.004 --> 11:31:28.424
down the steps till the lot of them went away cussing.

11:31:29.544 --> 11:31:32.464
I thought that with this description I could find the house.

11:31:33.144 --> 11:31:36.704
So having paid my friend for his information, I started off for Piccadilly.

11:31:37.424 --> 11:31:42.464
I had gained a new painful experience. The Count could, it was evident,

11:31:42.844 --> 11:31:48.684
handle the earth boxes himself. If so, time was precious. For now that he had achieved

11:31:48.684 --> 11:31:55.144
a certain amount of distribution, he could, by choosing his own time, complete the task unobserved.

11:31:56.564 --> 11:32:00.104
At Piccadilly Circus I discharged my cab and walked westward.

11:32:01.184 --> 11:32:05.544
Beyond the junior constitutional, I came across the house described and was satisfied that this

11:32:05.544 --> 11:32:10.824
was the next of the layers arranged by Dracula. The house looked as though it had been long

11:32:10.824 --> 11:32:17.144
untenanted. The windows were encrusted with dust and the shutters were up. All the framework was

11:32:17.144 --> 11:32:23.564
black with time, and from the iron the paint had mostly scaled away. It was evident that up to

11:32:23.564 --> 11:32:29.504
lately there had been a large notice board in front of the balcony. It had, however, been roughly

11:32:29.504 --> 11:32:33.284
torn away, the uprights which had supported it still remaining.

11:32:34.684 --> 11:32:39.384
Behind the rails of the balcony, I saw there were some loose boards whose raw edges looked

11:32:39.384 --> 11:32:44.424
white. I would have given a good deal to have been able to see the notice board intact,

11:32:45.104 --> 11:32:48.644
as it would, perhaps, have given some clue to the ownership of the house.

11:32:49.944 --> 11:32:53.904
I remembered my experience of the investigation and purchase of Carfax,

11:32:54.264 --> 11:32:58.644
and I could not but feel that if I could find the former owner there might be some means

11:32:58.644 --> 11:33:04.784
discovered of gaining access to the house. There was at present nothing to be learned

11:33:04.784 --> 11:33:09.744
from the Piccadilly side, and nothing could be done, so I went around the back to see if

11:33:09.744 --> 11:33:15.384
anything could be gathered from this quarter. The mews were active, the Piccadilly houses being

11:33:15.384 --> 11:33:21.224
mostly in occupation. I asked one or two of the grooms and helpers whom I saw around if

11:33:21.224 --> 11:33:25.924
they could tell me anything about the empty house. One of them said that he heard it had

11:33:25.924 --> 11:33:32.544
lately been taken, but he couldn't say from whom. He told me, however, that up to very

11:33:32.544 --> 11:33:38.884
lately there had been a notice board of For Sale up, and that perhaps Mitchell, Sons and Candy,

11:33:38.984 --> 11:33:43.624
the house agents, could tell me something, as he thought he remembered seeing the name of that firm

11:33:43.624 --> 11:33:49.944
on the board. I did not wish to seem too eager or to let my informant know or guess too much,

11:33:49.944 --> 11:33:53.524
so thanking him in the usual manner I strolled away.

11:33:54.964 --> 11:34:00.804
It was now growing dusk, and the autumn night was closing in, so I did not lose any time.

11:34:01.344 --> 11:34:05.504
Having learned the address of Mitchell, Sons and Candy from a directory at the Barclay,

11:34:05.844 --> 11:34:12.084
I was soon at their office in Sackville Street. The gentleman who saw me was particularly suave

11:34:12.084 --> 11:34:18.824
in manner, but uncommunicative in equal proportion. Having once told me that the Piccadilly house,

11:34:18.824 --> 11:34:24.704
which throughout our interview he called a mansion, was sold, he considered my business

11:34:24.704 --> 11:34:30.544
as concluded. When I asked who had purchased it, he opened his eyes a thought wider,

11:34:31.284 --> 11:34:33.484
and paused a few seconds before replying,

11:34:34.364 --> 11:34:36.304
It is sold, sir.

11:34:37.924 --> 11:34:43.424
Pardon me, I said, with equal politeness, but I have a special reason for wishing to know who

11:34:43.424 --> 11:34:48.864
purchased it. Again he paused longer and raised his eyebrows still more.

11:34:49.624 --> 11:34:53.404
It is sold, sir, was again his laconic reply.

11:34:54.584 --> 11:34:59.004
Surely, I said, you do not mind letting me know so much.

11:34:59.924 --> 11:35:05.184
But I do mind, he answered, the affairs of their clients are absolutely safe in the

11:35:05.184 --> 11:35:10.744
hands of Mitchell, Sons and Candy. This was manifestly a prig of the first water,

11:35:10.744 --> 11:35:16.424
and there was no use arguing with him. I thought I had best meet him on his own ground,

11:35:16.784 --> 11:35:22.764
so I said, Your clients, sir, are happy in having so resolute a guardian of their confidence.

11:35:23.324 --> 11:35:31.044
I am myself a professional man. Here I handed him my card. In this instance I am not prompted

11:35:31.044 --> 11:35:37.044
by curiosity. I act on the part of Lord Godelming, who wishes to know something of the property which

11:35:37.044 --> 11:35:43.544
was, he understood, lately for sale. These words put a different complexion on affairs.

11:35:44.224 --> 11:35:50.024
He said, I would like to oblige you if I could, Mr. Harker, and especially would I like to oblige

11:35:50.024 --> 11:35:55.704
his lordship. We once carried out a small matter of renting some chambers for him when he was the

11:35:55.704 --> 11:36:01.224
Honorable Arthur Homewood. If you will let me have his lordship's address, I will consult the

11:36:01.224 --> 11:36:06.264
house on the subject, and will, in any case, communicate with his lordship by tonight's post.

11:36:07.044 --> 11:36:11.684
It will be a pleasure if we can so far deviate from our rules as to give the required information

11:36:11.684 --> 11:36:18.764
to his lordship. I wanted to secure a friend and not make an enemy, so I thanked him,

11:36:19.004 --> 11:36:25.684
gave the address at Dr. Seward's, and came away. It was now dark, and I was tired and hungry.

11:36:26.604 --> 11:36:31.424
I got a cup of tea at the aerated bread company, and came down to Purfleet by the next train.

11:36:32.104 --> 11:36:37.064
I found all the others at home. Mina was looking tired and pale,

11:36:37.484 --> 11:36:42.864
but she made a gallant effort to be bright and cheerful. It rung my heart to think that I had

11:36:42.864 --> 11:36:48.684
had to keep anything from her, and so caused her inquietude. Thank God this will be the last night

11:36:48.684 --> 11:36:53.824
of her looking on at our conferences, and feeling the sting of our not showing our confidence.

11:36:54.864 --> 11:36:59.544
It took all my courage to hold to the wise resolution of keeping her out of our grim task.

11:37:00.504 --> 11:37:06.684
She seems somehow more reconciled, or else the very subject seems to have become repugnant to her,

11:37:07.104 --> 11:37:11.004
for when any accidental illusion is made, she actually shudders.

11:37:12.484 --> 11:37:16.824
I am glad we made our resolution in time, as with such a feeling as this,

11:37:17.104 --> 11:37:19.264
our growing knowledge would be torture to her.

11:37:21.184 --> 11:37:25.064
I could not tell the others of the day's discovery till we were alone,

11:37:25.824 --> 11:37:30.824
so after dinner, followed by a little music to save appearances even amongst ourselves,

11:37:31.784 --> 11:37:34.164
I took Mina to her room and left her to go to bed.

11:37:35.164 --> 11:37:39.764
The dear girl was more affectionate with me than ever, and clung to me as though she would detain

11:37:39.764 --> 11:37:46.044
me. But there was much to be talked of, and I came away. Thank God the ceasing of telling

11:37:46.044 --> 11:37:51.444
things has made no difference between us. When I came down again, I found the others

11:37:51.444 --> 11:37:56.464
gathered round the fire in the study. In the train I had written my diary so far,

11:37:56.804 --> 11:38:01.184
and simply read it off to them as the best means of letting them get a breast of my own information.

11:38:02.884 --> 11:38:04.844
When I had finished, Van Helsing said,

11:38:05.324 --> 11:38:10.064
This has been a great day's work, friend Jonathan. Doubtless we are on the track

11:38:10.064 --> 11:38:15.404
of the missing boxes. If we find them all in that house, then our work is near the end.

11:38:16.104 --> 11:38:19.724
But if there be some missing, we must search until we find them,

11:38:19.724 --> 11:38:24.104
then surely make our final coup, and hunt the wretch to his real death.

11:38:25.364 --> 11:38:28.984
We all sat silent a while, and all at once Mr Norrish spoke.

11:38:29.904 --> 11:38:32.224
Say, how are we going to get into that house?

11:38:32.724 --> 11:38:36.064
We got into the other, answered Lord Godelman quickly.

11:38:37.084 --> 11:38:42.264
But Art, this is different. We broke house at Carfax, but we had night and a walled park

11:38:42.264 --> 11:38:46.844
to protect us. It will be a mighty different thing to commit burglary in Piccadilly,

11:38:46.844 --> 11:38:51.484
either by day or night. I confess I don't see how we are going to get in,

11:38:51.504 --> 11:38:54.344
unless that agency duck can find us a key of some sort.

11:38:55.864 --> 11:38:59.884
Lord Godelman's brows contracted, and he stood up and walked about the room.

11:39:00.884 --> 11:39:04.624
By and by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us,

11:39:05.224 --> 11:39:08.944
Quincy's head is level, this burglary business is getting serious.

11:39:09.684 --> 11:39:13.684
We got off once all right, but we have now a rare job on hand,

11:39:13.684 --> 11:39:16.104
unless we can find the Count's key basket.

11:39:17.704 --> 11:39:22.504
As nothing could well be done before morning, and as it would be at least advisable to wait

11:39:22.504 --> 11:39:27.784
till Lord Godelman should hear from Mitchell's, we decided not to take any active step before

11:39:27.784 --> 11:39:33.304
breakfast time. For a good while we sat and smoked, discussing the matter in its various

11:39:33.304 --> 11:39:38.344
lights and bearings. I took the opportunity of bringing this diary right up to the moment.

11:39:39.084 --> 11:39:46.224
I am very sleepy and shall go to bed. Just a line. Mina sleeps soundly and her breathing is

11:39:46.224 --> 11:39:52.664
regular. Her forehead is puckered up into little wrinkles, as though she thinks even in her sleep.

11:39:53.604 --> 11:39:59.844
She is still too pale, but does not look so haggard as she did this morning. Tomorrow will,

11:39:59.844 --> 11:40:06.744
I hope, mend all this. She will be herself at home in Exeter. Oh, but I am sleepy.

11:40:09.464 --> 11:40:18.104
Dr. Seward's Diary. 1st October. I am puzzled afresh about Renfield. His moods change so rapidly

11:40:18.104 --> 11:40:23.244
that I find it difficult to keep touch of them. And as they always mean something more than his

11:40:23.244 --> 11:40:29.844
own well-being, they form a more than interesting study. This morning, when I went to see him after

11:40:29.844 --> 11:40:36.864
his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny. He was, in fact,

11:40:36.864 --> 11:40:42.944
commanding destiny, subjectively. He did not really care for any of the things of mere earth.

11:40:43.444 --> 11:40:47.784
He was in the clouds and looked down on all the weaknesses and wants of us poor mortals.

11:40:49.304 --> 11:40:53.364
I thought I would improve the occasion and learn something, so I asked him,

11:40:53.844 --> 11:41:01.344
what about the flies these times? He smiled on me in quite a superior sort of way, such a smile as

11:41:01.344 --> 11:41:07.904
would have become the face of Malvolio, as he answered me. The fly, my dear sir, has one striking

11:41:07.904 --> 11:41:14.784
feature. Its wings are typical of the aerial powers of the psychic faculties. The ancients did well

11:41:14.784 --> 11:41:21.064
when they typified the soul as a butterfly. I thought I would push his analogy to its utmost

11:41:21.064 --> 11:41:29.384
logically. So I said quickly, oh, it is a soul you are after now, is it? His madness foiled his reason

11:41:29.384 --> 11:41:34.424
and a puzzled look spread over his face as, shaking his head with a decision which I had

11:41:34.424 --> 11:41:43.584
but seldom seen in him, he said, oh, no, oh, no, I want no souls. Life is all I want. Here he

11:41:43.584 --> 11:41:50.504
brightened up. I am pretty indifferent about it at present. Life is all right. I have all I want.

11:41:51.284 --> 11:41:57.764
You must get a new patient, doctor, if you wish to study zoophagy. This puzzled me a little,

11:41:57.764 --> 11:42:05.444
so I drew him on. Then you command life. You are a god, I suppose. He smiled with an ineffably benign

11:42:05.444 --> 11:42:12.144
superiority. Oh, no, far be it from me to arrogate to myself the attributes of the deity.

11:42:13.104 --> 11:42:19.064
I am not even concerned in his especially spiritual doings. If I may state my intellectual

11:42:19.064 --> 11:42:24.844
position, I am, so far as concerns things purely terrestrial, somewhat in the position which Enoch

11:42:24.844 --> 11:42:32.224
occupied spiritually. This was a poser to me. I could not at the moment recall Enoch's

11:42:32.224 --> 11:42:38.284
appositeness, so I had to ask a simple question, though I felt that by so doing I was lowering

11:42:38.284 --> 11:42:45.184
myself in the eyes of the lunatic. And why with Enoch? Because he walked with God.

11:42:46.184 --> 11:42:53.004
I could not see the analogy, but did not like to admit it, so I harked back to what he had denied.

11:42:53.604 --> 11:43:00.544
So you don't care about life, and you don't want souls. Why not? I put my question quickly

11:43:00.544 --> 11:43:07.584
and somewhat sternly, on purpose to disconcert him. The effort succeeded. For an instant he

11:43:07.584 --> 11:43:12.484
unconsciously relapsed into his old servile manner, bent low before me, and actually

11:43:12.484 --> 11:43:18.404
fawned upon me as he replied, I don't want any souls, indeed, indeed, I don't. I couldn't use

11:43:18.404 --> 11:43:25.024
them if I had them. They would be no manner of use to me. I couldn't eat them, or... He suddenly

11:43:25.024 --> 11:43:30.204
stopped, and the old cunning look spread over his face, like a wind sweep on the surface of the water.

11:43:30.944 --> 11:43:35.604
And, Doctor, as to life, what is it, after all, when you've got all you require?

11:43:36.304 --> 11:43:42.304
And you know that you will never want, that is all. I have friends, good friends, like you,

11:43:42.304 --> 11:43:46.584
Doctor Seward. This was said with a leer of inexpressible cunning.

11:43:47.284 --> 11:43:53.324
I know that I shall never lack the means of life. I think that through the cloudiness of his insanity

11:43:53.324 --> 11:43:59.104
he saw some antagonism in me, for he at once fell back on the last refuge of such as he,

11:43:59.304 --> 11:44:05.424
a dogged silence. After a short time I saw that for the present it was useless to speak to him.

11:44:06.044 --> 11:44:13.344
He was sulky, and so I came away. Later in the day he sent for me. Ordinarily I would not have

11:44:13.344 --> 11:44:18.984
come without special reason, but just at present I am so interested in him that I would gladly make

11:44:18.984 --> 11:44:26.024
an effort. Besides, I am glad to have anything to help pass the time. Harker is out, following up

11:44:26.024 --> 11:44:32.824
clues, and so are Lord Godelming and Quincy. Van Helsing sits in my study, pouring over the record

11:44:32.824 --> 11:44:38.004
prepared by the Harkers. He seems to think that by accurate knowledge of all details he will light

11:44:38.004 --> 11:44:44.784
upon some clue. He does not wish to be disturbed in the work without cause. I would have taken him

11:44:44.784 --> 11:44:50.064
with me to see the patient. Only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go

11:44:50.064 --> 11:44:56.804
again. There was also another reason. Renfield might not speak so freely before a third person

11:44:56.804 --> 11:45:03.604
as when he and I were alone. I found him sitting in the middle of the floor on his stool,

11:45:03.984 --> 11:45:07.664
a pose which is generally indicative of some mental energy on his part.

11:45:08.724 --> 11:45:12.724
When I came in he said at once, as though the question had been waiting on his lips,

11:45:13.504 --> 11:45:19.764
what about souls? It was evident then that my surmise had been correct.

11:45:20.804 --> 11:45:24.424
Unconscious celebration was doing its work, even with the lunatic.

11:45:25.604 --> 11:45:32.844
I determined to have the matter out. What about them yourself? I asked. He did not reply for a

11:45:32.844 --> 11:45:38.464
moment, but looked all around him, and up and down, as though he expected to find some inspiration

11:45:38.464 --> 11:45:46.324
for an answer. I don't want any souls, he said in a feeble apologetic way. The matter seemed

11:45:46.324 --> 11:45:53.004
praying on his mind, and so I determined to use it. To be cruel only to be kind. So I said,

11:45:53.684 --> 11:46:00.444
you like life and you want life? Oh yes, but that is all right, you needn't worry about that.

11:46:01.064 --> 11:46:08.024
But, I asked, how are we to get the life without getting the soul also? This seemed to puzzle him,

11:46:08.464 --> 11:46:14.364
so I followed it up. A nice time you'll have some time when you're flying out there with the souls

11:46:14.364 --> 11:46:19.044
of thousands of flies and spiders and birds and cats buzzing and twittering and moaning all around

11:46:19.044 --> 11:46:25.784
you. You've got their lives, you know, and you must put up with their souls. Something seemed to

11:46:25.784 --> 11:46:31.424
affect his imagination, for he put his fingers to his ears and shut his eyes, screwing them up

11:46:31.424 --> 11:46:36.944
tightly just as a small boy does when his face is being soaked. There was something pathetic in it

11:46:36.944 --> 11:46:44.244
that touched me. It also gave me a lesson, for it seemed that before me was a child, only a child,

11:46:44.364 --> 11:46:50.064
though the features were worn and the stubble on the jaws was white. It was evident that he was

11:46:50.064 --> 11:46:55.544
undergoing some process of mental disturbance, and knowing how his past moods had interpreted

11:46:55.544 --> 11:47:00.464
things seemingly foreign to himself, I thought I would enter into his mind as well as I could

11:47:00.464 --> 11:47:07.704
and go with him. The first step was to restore confidence, so I asked him, speaking pretty loud

11:47:07.704 --> 11:47:12.264
so that he would hear me through his closed ears, would you like some sugar to get your

11:47:12.264 --> 11:47:18.064
eyes around again? He seemed to wake up all at once and shook his head. With a laugh he replied,

11:47:18.564 --> 11:47:25.484
not much, flies are poor things after all. After a pause, he added, but I don't want their souls

11:47:25.484 --> 11:47:32.344
buzzing round me all the same, or spiders, I went on. Blow spiders, what's the use of spiders?

11:47:33.024 --> 11:47:41.484
There isn't anything in them to eat, or he stopped suddenly as though reminded of a

11:47:41.484 --> 11:47:45.784
second time he has suddenly stopped at the word drink. What does it mean?

11:47:48.484 --> 11:47:53.064
Renfield seemed himself aware of having made a lapse, for he hurried on as though to distract

11:47:53.064 --> 11:47:59.864
my attention from it. I don't take any stock at all in such matters. Rats and mice and such small

11:47:59.864 --> 11:48:06.064
deer, as Shakespeare has it, chicken feed of the larder, they might be called. I'm past all that

11:48:06.064 --> 11:48:11.464
sort of nonsense. You might as well ask a man to eat molecules with a pair of chopsticks, as to

11:48:11.464 --> 11:48:18.164
try to interest me about the less carnivora, when I know of what is before me. I see, I said,

11:48:18.364 --> 11:48:23.664
you want big things that you can make your teeth meet in. How would you like to breakfast on an

11:48:23.664 --> 11:48:29.764
elephant? What ridiculous nonsense you are talking! He was getting too wide awake, so I thought I would

11:48:29.764 --> 11:48:37.284
press him hard. I wonder, I said, reflectively, what an elephant's soul is like. The effect I

11:48:37.284 --> 11:48:41.744
desired was obtained, for he at once fell from his high horse and became a child again.

11:48:42.604 --> 11:48:48.724
I don't want an elephant's soul, or any soul at all, he said. For a few moments he sat despondently.

11:48:50.204 --> 11:48:54.564
Suddenly he jumped to his feet, with his eyes blazing and all the signs of intense cerebral

11:48:54.564 --> 11:49:00.784
excitement. To hell with you and your souls, he shouted. Why do you plague me about souls?

11:49:00.924 --> 11:49:05.184
Haven't I got enough to worry and pain to distract me already without thinking of souls?

11:49:05.824 --> 11:49:09.644
He looked so hostile that I thought he was in for another homicidal fit,

11:49:09.744 --> 11:49:15.784
so I blew my whistle. The instant, however, that I did so, he became calm and said apologetically,

11:49:16.644 --> 11:49:22.684
forgive me, doctor, I forgot myself. You do not need any help. I am so worried in my mind that

11:49:22.684 --> 11:49:28.524
I am apt to be irritable. If you only knew the problem I have to face, and that I am working out,

11:49:28.884 --> 11:49:34.284
you would pity and tolerate and pardon me. Pray do not put me in a straight waistcoat.

11:49:34.924 --> 11:49:40.624
I want to think, and I cannot think freely when my body is confined. I am sure you will understand.

11:49:41.924 --> 11:49:47.124
He had, evidently, self-control. So when the attendants came, I told them not to mind,

11:49:47.244 --> 11:49:53.144
and they withdrew. Renfield watched them go. When the door was closed, he said,

11:49:53.224 --> 11:49:59.524
with considerable dignity and sweetness, Dr. Seward, you have been very considerate towards me.

11:50:00.384 --> 11:50:03.804
Believe me that I am very, very grateful to you.

11:50:06.184 --> 11:50:12.364
I thought it well to leave him in this mood, and so I came away. There is certainly something to

11:50:12.364 --> 11:50:17.744
ponder over in this man's state. Several points seem to make what the American interviewer calls

11:50:17.744 --> 11:50:25.284
a story, if one could only get them in proper order. Here they are. Will not mention drinking.

11:50:25.944 --> 11:50:32.324
Fears the thought of being burdened with the soul of anything. Has no dread of wanting life

11:50:32.324 --> 11:50:39.644
in the future. Despises the meaner forms of life altogether, though he dreads being haunted by their

11:50:39.644 --> 11:50:46.944
souls. Logically, all these things point one way. He has assurance of some kind that he will acquire

11:50:46.944 --> 11:50:54.524
some higher life. He dreads the consequence, the burden of a soul. Then it is a human life he looks

11:50:54.524 --> 11:51:02.404
to. And the assurance? Merciful God, the count has been to him, and there is some new scheme of

11:51:02.404 --> 11:51:10.224
terror afoot. Later, I went after my round to Van Helsing and told him of my suspicion.

11:51:11.144 --> 11:51:16.084
He grew very grave, and after thinking the matter over for a while, he asked me to take him to

11:51:16.084 --> 11:51:22.824
Renfield. I did so. As we came to the door, we heard the lunatic within singing gaily,

11:51:23.324 --> 11:51:30.024
as he used to do in the time which now seems so long ago. When we entered, we saw with amazement

11:51:30.024 --> 11:51:35.424
that he had spread out his sugar as of old. The flies, lethargic with the autumn, were beginning

11:51:35.424 --> 11:51:41.044
to buzz into the room. We tried to make him talk of the subject of our previous conversation,

11:51:41.204 --> 11:51:47.224
but he would not attend. He went on with his singing, just as though we had not been present.

11:51:47.884 --> 11:51:54.064
He had got a scrap of paper and was folding it into a notebook. We had to come away as

11:51:54.064 --> 11:52:01.784
ignorant as we went in. His is a curious case indeed. We must watch him tonight.

11:52:05.584 --> 11:52:16.304
Letter, Mitchell, Sons and Candy, to Lord Godelming. 1st October. My Lord! We are at all times

11:52:16.304 --> 11:52:22.124
only too happy to meet your wishes. We beg, with regard to the desire of your lordship,

11:52:22.404 --> 11:52:27.724
expressed by Mr Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale

11:52:27.724 --> 11:52:35.844
and purchase of No. 347 Piccadilly. The original vendors are the executors of the late Mr Archibald

11:52:35.844 --> 11:52:42.684
Winter Suffield. The purchaser is a foreign nobleman, Count de Ville, who affected the

11:52:42.684 --> 11:52:47.604
purchase himself, paying the purchase money in notes, over the counter, if your lordship

11:52:47.604 --> 11:52:53.264
will pardon us using so vulgar an expression. Beyond this, we know nothing whatever of him.

11:52:53.864 --> 11:52:58.404
We are, my Lord, your lordship's humble servants, Mitchell, Sons and Candy.

11:53:01.224 --> 11:53:08.144
Dr Seward's Diary. 2nd October. I placed a man in the corridor last night, and told him to make

11:53:08.144 --> 11:53:12.964
an accurate note of any sound he might hear from Renfield's room, and gave him instructions that

11:53:12.964 --> 11:53:18.964
if there should be anything strange he was to call me. After dinner, when we had all gathered round

11:53:18.964 --> 11:53:24.704
the fire in the study, Mrs Harker having gone to bed, we discussed the attempts and discoveries

11:53:24.704 --> 11:53:30.924
of the day. Harker was the only one who had any result, and we are in great hopes that his clue

11:53:30.924 --> 11:53:36.564
may be an important one. Before going to bed, I went round to the patient's room and looked

11:53:36.564 --> 11:53:43.724
in through the observation trap. He was sleeping soundly. His heart rose and fell with regular

11:53:43.724 --> 11:53:49.764
respiration. This morning the man on duty reported to me that a little after midnight he was restless

11:53:49.764 --> 11:53:55.844
and kept saying his prayers somewhat loudly. I asked him if that was all. He replied that it

11:53:55.844 --> 11:54:01.144
was all he heard. There was something about his manner so suspicious that I asked him point blank

11:54:01.144 --> 11:54:06.464
if he had been asleep. He denied sleep, but admitted to having dozed for a while.

11:54:07.184 --> 11:54:10.484
It is too bad that men cannot be trusted unless they are watched.

11:54:12.464 --> 11:54:17.764
Today Harker is out following up his clue, and Art and Quincy are looking after horses.

11:54:19.544 --> 11:54:22.684
Godelming thinks that it would be well to have horses always in readiness,

11:54:23.764 --> 11:54:27.244
for when we get the information which we seek there will be no time to lose.

11:54:28.104 --> 11:54:34.204
We must sterilize all the imported earth between sunrise and sunset. We shall thus catch the count

11:54:34.204 --> 11:54:39.804
at his weakest, and without a refuge to fly to. Van Helsing is off to the British Museum,

11:54:40.364 --> 11:54:45.904
looking up some authorities on ancient medicine. The old physicians took account of things which

11:54:45.904 --> 11:54:51.144
their followers do not accept, and the professor is searching for witch and demon cures which may

11:54:51.144 --> 11:54:57.224
be useful to us later. I sometimes think we must be all mad and that we shall wake to sanity in

11:54:57.224 --> 11:55:05.944
straight waistcoats. Later we have met again. We seem at last to be on the track, and our work

11:55:05.944 --> 11:55:11.724
of tomorrow may be the beginning of the end. I wonder if Renfield's quiet has anything to do

11:55:11.724 --> 11:55:17.244
with this. His moods have so followed the doings of the count that the coming destruction of the

11:55:17.244 --> 11:55:23.564
monster may be carried to him some subtle way. If we could only get some hint as to what passed

11:55:23.564 --> 11:55:28.604
in his mind between the time of my argument with him today and his resumption of fly-catching,

11:55:29.424 --> 11:55:34.364
it might afford us a valuable clue. He is now seemingly quiet for a spell.

11:55:35.444 --> 11:55:41.124
Is he? That wild yell seemed to come from his room. The attendant came bursting into my room

11:55:41.124 --> 11:55:45.864
and told me that Renfield had somehow met with some accident. He had heard him yell,

11:55:46.044 --> 11:55:51.004
and when he went to him found him lying on his face on the floor, all covered with blood.

11:55:51.004 --> 11:55:52.984
I must go at once.

11:56:37.256 --> 11:56:41.436
Let me put down with exactness all that happened, as well as I can remember,

11:56:41.576 --> 11:56:46.236
since last I made an entry. Not a detail that I can recall must be forgotten,

11:56:46.536 --> 11:56:52.176
in whole calmness I must proceed. When I came to Renfield's room I found him lying on the floor,

11:56:52.256 --> 11:56:57.376
on his left side, in a glittering pool of blood. When I went to move him it became at once apparent

11:56:57.376 --> 11:57:02.456
that he had received some terrible injuries. There seemed none of the unity of purpose between the

11:57:02.456 --> 11:57:09.436
which marks even lethargic sanity. As the face was exposed I could see that it was horribly bruised,

11:57:09.616 --> 11:57:14.336
as though it had been beaten against the floor. Indeed, it was from the face wounds that the pool

11:57:14.336 --> 11:57:20.716
of blood originated. The attendant who was kneeling beside the body said to me as we turned him over,

11:57:21.176 --> 11:57:26.196
I think, sir, his back is broken. See, both his right arm and leg and the whole side of his face

11:57:26.196 --> 11:57:31.196
are paralyzed. How such a thing could have happened puzzled the attendant beyond measure.

11:57:31.196 --> 11:57:35.056
He seemed quite bewildered and his brows were gathered in as he said,

11:57:35.516 --> 11:57:40.316
I can't understand the two things. He could mark his face like that by beating his own head on the

11:57:40.316 --> 11:57:45.156
floor. I saw a young woman do it once at the Eversfield Asylum before anyone could lay hands

11:57:45.156 --> 11:57:50.156
on her. And I suppose he might have broken his neck by falling out of bed if he got in an awkward

11:57:50.156 --> 11:57:55.976
kink. But for the life of me I can't imagine how the two things occurred. If his back was broke

11:57:55.976 --> 11:58:00.176
he couldn't beat his head. And if his face was like that before the fall out of bed there would

11:58:00.176 --> 11:58:06.656
be marks on it. I said to him, go to Dr. Van Helsing and ask him to kindly come here at once.

11:58:06.856 --> 11:58:12.776
I want him without an instant's delay. The man ran off and within a few minutes the

11:58:12.776 --> 11:58:17.276
professor in his dressing gown and slippers appeared. When he saw Renfield on the ground

11:58:17.276 --> 11:58:22.536
he looked keenly at him a moment then turned to me. I think he recognized my thought in my eyes

11:58:22.536 --> 11:58:28.216
for he said very quietly manifestly for the ears of the attendant. Ah, a sad accident.

11:58:28.776 --> 11:58:33.616
He will need very careful watching and much attention. I shall stay with you myself,

11:58:33.836 --> 11:58:38.696
but I shall first dress myself. If you will remain I shall in a few minutes join you.

11:58:39.776 --> 11:58:44.396
The patient was now breathing stertoriously and it was easy to see that he had suffered some

11:58:44.396 --> 11:58:50.076
terrible injury. Van Helsing returned with extraordinary celerity bearing with him a

11:58:50.076 --> 11:58:55.596
surgical case. He had evidently been thinking and had his mind made up for almost before he looked

11:58:55.596 --> 11:59:01.216
the patient he whispered to me, send the attendant away. We must be alone with him when he becomes

11:59:01.216 --> 11:59:07.616
conscious after the operation. I said, I think that will do now Simmons. We have done all that

11:59:07.616 --> 11:59:12.636
we can at present. You had better go your round and Dr. Van Helsing will operate. Let me know

11:59:12.636 --> 11:59:19.116
instantly if there be anything unusual anywhere. The man withdrew and we went into a strict

11:59:19.116 --> 11:59:25.196
examination of the patient. The wounds of the face were superficial. The real injury was at

11:59:25.196 --> 11:59:32.096
the pressed fracture of the skull extending right up through the motor area. The professor thought a

11:59:32.096 --> 11:59:37.476
moment and said, we must reduce the pressure and get back to normal conditions as far as can be.

11:59:38.096 --> 11:59:43.716
The rapidity of the suffusion shows the terrible nature of his injury. The whole motor area seems

11:59:43.716 --> 11:59:53.256
affected. The suffusion of the brain will increase quickly so he must cleft in at once or it may be

11:59:53.256 --> 11:59:58.616
tapping at the door. I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without Arthur and

11:59:58.616 --> 12:00:04.376
Quincy in pajamas and slippers. The former spoke, I heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell

12:00:04.376 --> 12:00:09.756
him of an accident. So I woke Quincy or rather called for him as he was not asleep. Things are

12:00:09.756 --> 12:00:15.096
moving too quickly and too strangely for sound sleep for any of us these times. I've been thinking

12:00:15.096 --> 12:00:19.736
that tomorrow night we'll not see things as they have been. We'll have to look back and forward a

12:00:19.736 --> 12:00:25.516
little more than we have done. May we come in? I nodded and held the door open till they had entered

12:00:25.516 --> 12:00:30.836
then I closed it again. When Quincy saw the attitude and state of the patient and noted the

12:00:30.836 --> 12:00:36.356
horrible pool on the floor he said softly, my God, what has happened to him? Poor, poor devil.

12:00:37.456 --> 12:00:43.036
I told him briefly and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation

12:00:43.036 --> 12:00:48.236
for a short time at all events. He went at once and sat down on the edge of the bed with

12:00:48.236 --> 12:00:53.856
a dollaming beside him. We all watched in patience. We shall wait, said Van Helsing,

12:00:54.196 --> 12:00:58.396
just long enough to fix the best spot for roughening so that we may most quickly and

12:00:58.396 --> 12:01:02.436
perfectly remove the blood clot for it is evident that the hemorrhage is increasing.

12:01:03.916 --> 12:01:09.156
The minutes during which we waited passed with fearful slowness. I had a horrible sinking in my

12:01:09.156 --> 12:01:13.976
heart and from Van Helsing's face I gathered that he felt some fear or apprehension as to what was

12:01:13.976 --> 12:01:19.176
to come. I dreaded the words Renfield might speak. I was positively afraid to think.

12:01:19.836 --> 12:01:24.496
But the conviction of what was coming was on me as I have read of men who have heard the death watch.

12:01:25.136 --> 12:01:29.816
The poor man's breathing came in uncertain gasps. Each instant he seemed as though he would open

12:01:29.816 --> 12:01:34.616
his eyes and speak but then would follow a prolonged stertorous breath and he would relapse

12:01:34.616 --> 12:01:40.776
into a more fixed insensibility. Inured as I was to sickbeds and death the suspense grew and grew

12:01:40.776 --> 12:01:45.296
upon me. I could almost hear the beating of my own heart and the blood surging through my

12:01:45.296 --> 12:01:51.776
temple sounded like blows from a hammer. Silence finally became agonizing. I looked at my companions

12:01:51.776 --> 12:01:56.436
one after another and saw from their flushed faces and damp brows that they were enduring equal

12:01:56.436 --> 12:02:01.856
torture. There was a nervous suspense over us all as though overhead some dread bell would

12:02:01.856 --> 12:02:08.796
peel out powerfully when we should least expect it. At last there came a time when it was evident

12:02:08.796 --> 12:02:13.916
the patient was sinking fast. He might die at any moment. I looked up at the professor and

12:02:13.916 --> 12:02:19.296
caught his eyes fixed on mine. His face was sternly sad as he spoke. That is no time to lose.

12:02:19.776 --> 12:02:23.516
His words may be worth many lives. I have been thinking so as I stood here.

12:02:23.776 --> 12:02:27.936
It may be there is a soul at stake. We shall operate just above the ear.

12:02:29.376 --> 12:02:34.196
Without another word he made the operation. For a few moments the breathing continued to be

12:02:34.196 --> 12:02:39.156
then there came a breath so prolonged that it seemed as though it would tear open his chest.

12:02:39.636 --> 12:02:44.676
Suddenly his eyes opened and became fixed in a wild helpless stare. This was continued for a

12:02:44.676 --> 12:02:49.516
few moments then it was softened into a glad surprise and from his lips came a sigh of relief.

12:02:50.216 --> 12:02:56.556
He moved convulsively and as he did so said I'll be quiet doctor tell them to take off the straight

12:02:56.556 --> 12:03:02.056
waistcoat. I have had a terrible dream and it has left me so weak that I cannot move.

12:03:02.056 --> 12:03:06.276
What's wrong with my face? It feels all swollen and it smarts dreadfully.

12:03:07.436 --> 12:03:11.516
He tried to turn his head but even with the effort his eyes seemed to grow glassy again so

12:03:11.516 --> 12:03:18.596
I gently put it back. Then Van Helsing said in a quiet gray voice. Tell us your dream Mr. Renfield.

12:03:20.296 --> 12:03:23.896
As he heard the voice his face brightened through its mutilation and he said.

12:03:24.596 --> 12:03:30.916
That is Dr. Van Helsing. How good it is of you to be here. Give me some water. My lips are dry

12:03:30.916 --> 12:03:37.316
and I shall try to tell you. I dreamed. He stopped and seemed fainting. I called quietly to Quincy.

12:03:37.456 --> 12:03:42.416
The brandy. It is in my study. Quick. He flew and returned to the glass. The decanter of brandy

12:03:42.416 --> 12:03:47.936
and a carafe of water. We moistened the parts lips and the patient quickly revived. It seemed

12:03:47.936 --> 12:03:52.296
however that his poor injured brain had been working in the interval for when he was quite

12:03:52.296 --> 12:03:56.836
conscious he looked at me piercingly with an agonized confusion which I shall never forget

12:03:56.836 --> 12:04:03.656
and said I must not deceive myself it was no dream but all a grim reality

12:04:04.236 --> 12:04:09.096
then his eyes roved around the room as they caught sight of the two figures sitting patiently on the

12:04:09.096 --> 12:04:15.136
edge of the bed he went on if I were not sure already I would know from them for an instant

12:04:15.136 --> 12:04:20.396
his eyes closed not with pain or sleep but voluntarily as though he were bringing all his

12:04:20.396 --> 12:04:25.896
faculties to bear when he opened them he said hurriedly and with more energy than he had yet

12:04:25.896 --> 12:04:31.596
displayed quick doctor quick I am dying I feel that I have but a few minutes and then I must go

12:04:31.596 --> 12:04:37.896
back to death or worse wet my lips with brandy again I have something that I must say before I

12:04:37.896 --> 12:04:44.536
die or before my crushed brain dies anyhow thank you it was that night after you left me when I

12:04:44.536 --> 12:04:54.276
implored you to let me go away I couldn't speak then for I felt my tongue was tied but I was as

12:04:54.276 --> 12:05:00.056
despair for a long time after you left me it seemed hours then there came a sudden peace to

12:05:00.056 --> 12:05:05.136
me my brain seemed to become cool again and I realized where I was I heard the dogs bark

12:05:05.136 --> 12:05:12.396
behind our house but not where he was as he spoke Van Helsing's eyes never blinked but his hand came

12:05:12.396 --> 12:05:18.296
out and met mine and gripped it hard he did not however betray himself he nodded slightly and said

12:05:18.296 --> 12:05:20.236
gone in a low voice

12:05:22.356 --> 12:05:28.056
Renfield proceeded he came up to the window in the mist as I had seen him often before but he

12:05:28.056 --> 12:05:33.116
was solid then not a ghost and his eyes were fierce like a man's when angry he was laughing

12:05:33.116 --> 12:05:37.536
with his red mouth the sharp white teeth glinted in the moonlight when he turned to look back over

12:05:37.536 --> 12:05:42.556
the belt of trees to where the dogs were barking I wouldn't ask him to come in at first though I knew

12:05:42.556 --> 12:05:48.816
he wanted to just as he had wanted all along then he began promising me things not in words but by

12:05:48.816 --> 12:05:56.756
doing them he was interrupted by a word from the professor how by making them happen just as he

12:05:56.756 --> 12:06:02.196
used to send in the flies when the sun was shining great big fat ones with steel and sapphire on their

12:06:02.196 --> 12:06:08.236
wings and big moths in the night with skull and crossbones on their backs Van Helsing nodded to

12:06:08.236 --> 12:06:13.256
him and he whispered to me unconsciously the acarantia atropos of the sphinges what you call

12:06:13.256 --> 12:06:20.996
the death's head moth the patient went on without stopping then he began to whisper rats rats rats

12:06:20.996 --> 12:06:27.216
hundreds thousands millions of them and everyone in life and dogs to eat them and cats too all

12:06:27.216 --> 12:06:32.896
lives all red blood with years of life in it and not merely buzzing flies I laughed at him for I

12:06:32.896 --> 12:06:38.536
wanted to see what he could do then the dogs howled away beyond the dark trees in his house

12:06:38.536 --> 12:06:44.076
he beckoned me to the window I got up and looked out and he raised his hands and seemed to call out

12:06:44.076 --> 12:06:49.736
without using any words a dark mass spread over the grass coming on like the shape of a flame of

12:06:49.736 --> 12:06:55.396
fire and then he moved the mist to the right and left and I could see that there were thousands of

12:06:55.396 --> 12:07:01.096
rats with their eyes blazing red like his only smaller he held up his hand and they all stopped

12:07:01.096 --> 12:07:06.756
and I thought he seemed to be saying all these lies will I give you I am many more and greater

12:07:06.756 --> 12:07:12.836
through countless ages if you will fall down and worship me and then a red cloud like the color of

12:07:12.836 --> 12:07:17.696
blood seemed to close over my eyes and before I knew what I was doing I found myself opening

12:07:17.696 --> 12:07:24.456
the sash and saying to him come in lord and master the rats were all gone but he slid into the room

12:07:24.456 --> 12:07:30.096
through the sash though it was only open an inch wide just as the moon herself has often come in

12:07:30.096 --> 12:07:37.396
the tiniest crack and it stood before me in all her size and splendor his voice was weaker so I

12:07:37.396 --> 12:07:42.096
moistened his lips with the brandy again and he continued but it seemed as though his memory had

12:07:42.096 --> 12:07:47.296
